<HEADER>
A5249 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      07-18 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    NEW&AMP;NOTABLE BOOK REVIES(a) 
 &HT;    (RESENDING: Moving in ``E'' and ``L'' categories) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By ANNE STEPHENSON(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new books:
</P>
<P>
   ``THE SOUL OF A CHEF''
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Ruhlman
</P>
<P>
   (Viking, $26.95)
</P>
<P>
   That pizza from Uncle Sam's looked mighty good to us after we
finished reading about the pressure and politics behind the making
of great food. In the first part of this book, Ruhlman, who wrote
on the same subject in (beginitalic)The Making of a
Chef(enditalic), investigates the grueling certified master chef
exam at the Culinary Institute of America (where one participant
was berated for his ``knife skills'' after a slice of duck terrine
turned up wider at one end than at the other). Part two moves to
the kitchen of the personable Michael Symon of Cleveland's Lola
Bistro and part three to California's French Laundry, opened by
Thomas Keller (who had no formal culinary training) in 1994 and
three years later called ``the most exciting restaurant in
America'' by Ruth Reichl of the (beginitalic)New York
Times(enditalic). The Keller chapters are the best, showing both
the chef's severe perfectionism and the relentless stress under
which he and his staff create extraordinary meals.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE UNWANTED GAZE''
</P>
<P>
   By Jeffrey Rosen
</P>
<P>
   (Random House, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   Rosen, legal affairs editor of the (beginitalic)New
Republic(enditalic), takes a disturbing look at the legal and
social changes that ``have undermined our ability to control how
much information about ourselves is communicated to others.'' If
that sounds harmless, consider this: E-mail, even deleted, is
really a permanent record that can be retrieved by employers or
prosecutors at any future time. Kenneth Starr was able to confront
Monica Lewinsky with love letters written on her computer but never
sent to Bill Clinton, and later he was able to subpoena receipts of
Lewinsky's book purchases for 1995. Rosen also offers the
controversial suggestion that Clinton's alleged actions with Paula
Jones in that infamous Little Rock, Ark., hotel room did not
constitute sexual harassment but an invasion of her privacy. He
makes a complex subject fascinating by showing us how vulnerable we
all are. His message: Pay attention. It could happen to you.
</P>
<P>
   ``WERE YOU ALWAYS AN ITALIAN?''
</P>
<P>
   By Maria Laurino
</P>
<P>
   (Norton, $23.95)
</P>
<P>
   When Mario Cuomo graduated from law school and tied for first
place in his class, the dean suggested that he change his name in
order to get a job on Wall Street. ``Can you imagine me as Mark
Conrad?'' Cuomo asked Laurino, and then he posed the question that
became her book's title, establishing between them a bond of ethnic
ambivalence. Yes, she once wanted to change her name to Laurin, to
free her of her Italian identity. And, no, she could not imagine
him as Mark Conrad. A warning: This is no warm and fuzzy book of
Italian jokes and anecdotes, with some references to
(beginitalic)The Godfather (enditalic)thrown in for good measure.
With intelligence and honesty, Laurino discusses her family, her
self-image, the contradictory effects of her ethnicity (she winces
at books and documentaries on ``the Italian-American experience,''
yet is quick to romanticize her own history) and the fierce ties
that hold her to a heritage she does not completely understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``A GATHERING OF SPIES''
</P>
<P>
   By John Altman
</P>
<P>
   (Putnam, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the reference to Cary Grant and Carole Lombard on the
first page, but this book has the feel of one of those great old
movies about World War II. If you were to compare it to another
novel, it would be Ken Follett's (beginitalic)Eye of the
Needle(enditalic). Unlike Follett's Henry Faber, however, Altman's
spy is a woman. Katarina Heinrich has murdered a friend, assumed
her identity and married her employer, plodding Princeton scientist
Richard Carter. In true old-movie tradition, Richard is invited to
work on the bomb project at Los Alamos, N.M., and his stunned wife
goes along, planning her next move on behalf of Germany. Meanwhile,
British authorities recruit aging professor Harry Winterbotham to
spy for them, and Harry sees an opportunity to rescue his Jewish
wife, who was caught in Poland during Hitler's invasion. Are you
taking notes? Good, because there's more. It's all easy,
old-fashioned fun. Just bring the popcorn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 0005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
