<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5253 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLA     07-18 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON FINDS LINE-DRIVE SWING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Garret Anderson's four hits Sunday against the San
Diego Padres were a season high, but more notable than the number
of hits was the type of hits they were. Singles. All four, with no
home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has a career-high 26 homers this season for the Anaheim
Angels, but his average has been in the .240 range most of the
season, considerably below his .300 lifetime average going into the
season. The four hits Sunday raised his average to .256, the
highest it had been since April 24 (.260).
</P>
<P>
   Is the line-drive hitting Anderson back?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's been back for a while,'' hitting coach Mickey
Hatcher said. ``He admitted to himself he was trying to do too much
and was guessing instead of seeing the ball and reacting.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher said Anderson finally got frustrated enough recently to
sit in manager Mike Scioscia's office with Scioscia and Hatcher and
discuss his problems. During the meeting, Scioscia and Hatcher let
Anderson do all the talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a new contract (four years, $20 million) and he was
putting too much pressure on himself,'' Hatcher said. ``He sat back
and evaluated himself. . . . He needs to trust himself. He's got
great hands and is a great hitter. Mike and I always tell him at
the end of the year you're going to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher said he expects to see Anderson's average get back to
normal but not at the expense of his home run total.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'll hit more home runs,'' Hatcher said. ``He's not
getting himself out. He's giving himself a chance to be aggressive
in certain situations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to take what they give me,'' Anderson said.
``(Sunday) the pitches were down in the zone and I did what I had
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Salmon hurting: Right fielder Tim Salmon was not in the
starting lineup Monday night because of an inflamed left shoulder.
His shoulder has been bothering him for the past couple of weeks,
but he irritated it Sunday afternoon trying to make a sliding catch
of Kevin Nicholson's double.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon drove to Orange County on Monday afternoon to have the
shoulder examined by Dr. Lewis Yocum.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon's status is day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Pitcher Kent Mercker, trying to come back from
a cerebral hemorrhage suffered May 11, threw a bullpen workout
Monday and had ``good velocity,'' according to Scioscia, but ``it's
still like spring training for him.'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Scott Schoeneweis will make his second rehab start
Wednesday for Triple-A Edmonton. Schoeneweis, recovering from a
strained rib-cage muscle, will need to make at least one more rehab
start following Wednesday's before he will rejoin the rotation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
