<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5254 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-COPYRIGHT-AZR &LR;      07-18 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPYRIGHT-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-SLUG-COPYRIGHT-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    COPYRIGHTS: ENTERTAINMENT INDUSTRY AT CROSSROADS ON NET(a) 
 &HT;    (With ``COPYSIDE'' sidebar) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By MONTY PHAN(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Xerox, Memorex, Betamax , Napster?
</P>
<P>
   If the company behind the file-sharing software wants some
comfort, it could consider its multitude of lawsuits a sort of
badge of honor. After all, like the copy machine, recordable
audiotape and the VCR, Napster makes information sharing easier.
It's just that a lot of that shared information happens to be
copyrighted.
</P>
<P>
   So, the entertainment industry has turned to lawsuits. Trouble
is, Napster has created the potential for millions of people to
break the law, and even if it's shut down, there are similar
programs out there that would gladly take its place. So, the
industry is left with some scenarios:
</P>
<P>
   Adapt to the new technology - Traditionally, this has taken the
entertainment industry the longest to do. The most famous example
is Hollywood's lawsuit to ban Sony's Betamax, the VCR's precursor.
Sony won, and the movie industry went on to make billions off
videotape sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time a new product is introduced, it seems the
entertainment industry has fought it,'' says Mike Blevins, a
spokesman for the Home Recording Rights Coalition in Washington,
D.C. ``It's mind-boggling when you consider how different our lives
might be if the VCR weren't here today.''
</P>
<P>
   Figure out ways to discourage the making of illegal copies -
This could be done by either making encryption so complicated that
it's not worth the time to hack, or by providing content in an
equally easy, yet legal, way.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people are getting easy access to a good product at a fair
price with no hassles in getting that product, then the vast
majority of people will choose legal content,'' says Geordie
Wilson, consumer-products manager for the Windows Media Player.
</P>
<P>
   Hope the ambiguity of current digital copyright law swings in
favor of the copyright holder - So far, it has.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is the high-water mark for programs like
Napster,'' says Jonathan Zittrain, executive director of the
Berkman Center for Internet and Society at Harvard Law School.
``It's not going to be a free-for-all years from now. Those who are
gnashing their teeth and saying, `God, the only way I'm going to
get on the Internet is if I'm giving stuff away,' I think it's
going to be a very different landscape soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Ian Clarke, a 23-year-old e-commerce consultant from London,
sees it differently.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1999, he completed work on Freenet, a file-sharing
program designed to give its users anonymity. Ideally, it would be
used in such countries as China or Saudi Arabia, where free speech
is prohibited. The program, however, is blind to the type of
information shared, meaning that copyrighted material could be
traded as easily as recipes.
</P>
<P>
   In Clarke's world, all information eventually will be free,
effectively nullifying the entire concept of copyright.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that as communications technology improves, it will
become increasingly difficult to restrict the sharing of
information,'' he says. ``Freenet makes it extra-difficult, if not
impossible, to restrict the sharing of information.''
</P>
<P>
   Realistically, that's far from happening, and the entertainment
industry is doing everything it can to make sure it doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1998, the recording industry and technology
companies teamed up to form the Secure Digital Music Initiative to
devise a framework for the playing, storing and distribution of
material. Meanwhile, lawsuits, many involving interpretations of
1998's Digital Millennium Copyright Act, continue to shape the law.
</P>
<P>
   If history repeats itself, then this is merely the industry's
growing pains. That's the belief of Leonardo Chiariglione, the
Italian engineer who in 1988 helped form the Moving Picture Experts
Group, a team of international experts in audio and video. The
group created a standard for compressing large audio files, called
MPEG-1, Layer 3, or MP3, the popularity of which has led to the
trading of digital music and, eventually, Napster's success.
</P>
<P>
   So, the recording industry turned to Chiariglione for help,
asking him to head the Secure Digital Music Initiative.
</P>
<P>
   As he puts it, ``New technologies, new possibilities, new
threats and new technologies to cope with the threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiariglione said he sees that threat spreading to movies,
electronic books and video games.
</P>
<P>
   In film, that's happening already. A compression format called
DivX - sharing the name of the failed Circuit City plan for
pay-per-view DVDs - that combines elements of MPEG technology has
steadily gained popularity on the Web. For now, the factors
limiting DivX - besides the fact that much of the content is in
violation of copyright laws - are that files are about 100 times
larger than MP3s, the selection of films is minimal and its success
depends on whether people want to watch movies on their computers.
</P>
<P>
   But, as the success of MP3s has shown, the market for
downloadable content is there. Although the music industry has to
play catch-up, film companies and book publishers have some time to
prepare. That's where the burgeoning field of digital-rights
management comes in.
</P>
<P>
   As an example of how such companies work, in June the
digital-rights management firm Reciprocal offered a secure download
of the trailer for Adam Sandler's upcoming film (beginitalic)Little
Nicky(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   Users download the trailer from the film's Web site. Upon the
first viewing, a users must connect to Reciprocal's Web site and
enter his or her e-mail address and ZIP code, after which the user
will receive a certificate that's stored on his or her computer.
</P>
<P>
   The file can be traded with other users, but each subsequent
person must apply for the certificate upon the initial viewing. The
(beginitalic)Little Nicky (enditalic)trailer is free; in the case
of, say, a new Britney Spears single, a person could have to pay
for the file before listening to it the first time; each other
person to whom the file was sent also would have to pay. That
defeats the notion of one person paying for the song and putting it
on Napster for everyone else to have.
</P>
<P>
   The key is making it simple. The more complicated the process,
the less likely a person is to go through it. But the less secure
the process, the less likely a company will be to make content
available.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a balance that has yet to be achieved in the
marketplace,'' says Larry Miller, president of Reciprocal's music
division. ``Content providers have to be confident enough to make
it available for consumers to enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other side, you have to make it seamless. You don't
want the technical solution to override the consumer's need to make
it a seamless, maybe even fun, experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
