<SLUG> BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMARKABLE RUNYAN HAS SYDNEY IN SIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ The night before the final of the women's
1,500 meters, Marla Runyan was lying in bed when her boyfriend,
Matt, realized she probably wasn't fast asleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were there in complete silence, and he asked what I was
doing. I said, `I just ran the race three times in my head, and I
got third place two out of the three times,' '' Runyan said.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, Runyan walked up to her place at the starting
line at Hornet Stadium, drew a breath, and 4:06.44 later, she
indeed came in third, winning a trip to Sydney behind Regina Jacobs
and Suzy Favor Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   For Runyan, like so many elite athletes, visualization is
everything. For Runyan, who is legally blind, visualization really
(begin italic) is (end italic) everything.
</P>
<P>
   Runyan, 31, has dealt with a degenerative eye disease since age
9. A strict interpretation of Stargardt's Disease would say that
Runyan's world, seen through clouded retinas, has been reduced to a
blur of shapes and colors.
</P>
<P>
   That is a ridiculously limited interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really think as much about my vision as the media
does. And I don't think my competitors do, either,'' Runyan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my personality is _ I'm just an athlete. My vision is
a circumstance that just happened. I never said I wanted to be a
legally blind Olympian. I just said: `I want to be on the Olympic
team. Me, Marla.'''
</P>
<P>
   As frustrating as it may be to constantly be reminded of her
so-called disability, Runyan is incredibly generous in answering
questions, without a whiff of impatience in dealing with the
attention.
</P>
<P>
   She perfectly walks the line between dismissing the 30/200
vision she uses to get around and evidencing what it takes to
overcome the so-called disability.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result of what I've achieved, I can't tell you the number
of letters I've gotten from parents, children and teenagers who
have the same or similar condition. It makes me feel good to affect
people in a positive way,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Runyan has steadfastly refused to be boxed in by any definition,
which is how her talents found an outlet as a high jumper at San
Diego State.
</P>
<P>
   Later, she turned to the heptathlon _ memorizing the number of
steps between each hurdle.
</P>
<P>
   She was ranked 10th nationally before the 1996 Olympic Trials,
but instead competed in the World Paralympic Games, winning four
gold medals as she overwhelmed her opponents.
</P>
<P>
   It was time to find a better outlet. So she turned to middle
distance running _ a move that indicates Runyan's tenacity.
</P>
<P>
   After clocking the world record for the 800 meters during a
heptathlon, Runyan tried to talk her way into the 800 during the
1998 Prefontaine Classic in Eugene, Ore. The race director said no,
since she had not met the sub-2:00 qualifying time. Instead, she
worked her way to an entry in the 1,500.
</P>
<P>
   By July 1998, she had won the Pan American Games.In August, she
finished fourth at the World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   She has since moved to Eugene, where she is ensconced in a
network of runners and supporters. Runyan said she is just
beginning to explore the 1,500, the 5,000 and possibly the 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   By now, there's nothing to stop her _ except the other injuries
that hamper elite runners in their quest.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, what really put these Olympic Trials in doubt was the
injury she sustained June 9. While running on a trail near her
home, she had to jump out of the way of a kid on a bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   On the track, Runyan has learned to steer wide in turns, careful
to avoid collisions, even though this tactic can cost her time.
</P>
<P>
   She distinguishes her fellow racers by memorizing who has a
ponytail or who is blonde.
</P>
<P>
   It can be harder to prepare for real-world mishaps. The
near-miss caused her to strain the band of tendons that run from
her hip to her knee.
</P>
<P>
   In pain, she couldn't jog, let alone train. She spent two weeks
in Colorado Springs, Colo., for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   She flew home and told her parents she wasn't going to run in
the Trials. Then, on the plane home to Eugene, she decided to go
for it, even though her coach, Mike Manley, would barely let her
run a serious warm-up before the 1,500 final.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a remarkable woman,'' Manley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would have destroyed most other athletes. She has a
tremendous physical gift, but she has the mental strength to
overcome problems and focus on what she needs to do to get where
she wants.''
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to be overwhelmed this Olympic season by the wondrous
talent of Michael Johnson or Marion Jones. These once-in-a-lifetime
superstars are the king and queen of American track.
</P>
<P>
   But there are others in the kingdom, and Marla Runyan's ticket
to Sydney can be credited to her awesome resolve. Watching her run,
you get a sense of her triumph.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
