<HEADER>
A5260 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-JAILCAM-AZR &LR;      07-18 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAILCAM-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-JAILCAM-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    ARPAIO TAKES JAIL REALITY TO WEB SITE(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By MIKE MC CLOY AND JUDI VILLA(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The public's hunger for ``reality-based programming'' has
brought us (beginitalic)Cops, Rescue 911 (enditalic)and
(beginitalic)America's Funniest Home Videos.
</P>
<P>
   (enditalic)Combine them, film it in Phoenix, and you'd have
something that could be called (beginitalic)Joe's Jail,
24/7.(enditalic)
</P>
<P>
   Which - without the name - is coming to the Internet courtesy of
Maricopa County Sheriff Joe Arpaio.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Monday, all the drama and mayhem of 300 people being
booked daily will be available for public viewing with just a click
on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be educational,'' Arpaio said. ``It'll be a deterrent.
Maybe those guys who get busted on Van Buren Street (for soliciting
prostitutes) can wave to their wives.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is amused.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a problem with that,'' said Eleanor Eisenberg,
executive director of the Arizona Civil Liberties Union. ``Sheriff
Joe often seems to forget that a lot of people in his care haven't
been convicted of a crime. Putting them on the Internet for all the
world to see is an invasion of privacy that is not warranted.''
</P>
<P>
   Even people who are convicted deserve better, Eisenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who are convicted have the human right to be treated
with some sense of human dignity, but we don't seem to want that to
happen,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Arpaio said the public should be allowed to see what
happens inside the jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the difference if you take a picture right away and put
it in the newspaper or put it over the Internet?'' Arpaio said.
``There really is no difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Viewers who visit www.mcso.org will be warned that anything can
happen as two color cameras follow inmates through booking and down
a hallway to the bowels of the Madison Street Jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be scary if I'm supposed to have the worst
jail in the United States,'' the sheriff said. ``What if the
inmates give me the finger all the time? What if they take their
pants down?''
</P>
<P>
   The site is believed to be the first in the country to take
viewers live inside a jail.
</P>
<P>
   However, county Supervisor Don Stapley said that, without
including inmates' vulgar and deranged screams or the odor of
unwashed vagrants and vomiting drunks, the sheriff's $2,000
investment of taxpayer money on Web cameras will not offer much
reality to viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to be able to show much,'' he said, noting
that the jail intake center has many hallways and alcoves where
incoming inmates are sent for physical and psychological
evaluations, background checks and assignment to various security
levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would question the utility of this kind of expenditure,''
Stapley said. ``But I'll have to withhold judgment until I
understand what they intend to show.''
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio said he wants to overcome the negative image created by
the jailhouse death of inmate Scott Norberg in a restraint chair in
1996. Norberg's family settled a wrongful death suit against
Maricopa County for $8million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody says we killed Norberg,'' Arpaio said. ``People
think inmates are getting the hell beat out of them. I'm getting
tired of all these allegations. Now everybody can see.''
</P>
<P>
   Reach the reporters at Mike.McCloy(a)ArizonaRepublic.com or
(602) 444-8111, and at Judi.Villa(a)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-8048.
</P>
</TEXT>
