<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABOARD THE GOOD SHIP EXCESS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If Larry Ellison ever breaks out of his rut as
No. 3 richest being in the solar system (behind God and Bill Gates,
not necessarily in that order), maybe he'll buy a bigger boat.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Ellison will paddle along in his 192-foot power
boat, Izanami, which he moors at Sausalito.
</P>
<P>
   Or does Sausalito moor at Izanami?
</P>
<P>
   The Belvedere Beachcomber says the local salts consider Larry's
tub to be the sports model of the Aegis missile cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   Izanami's monthly electric bill is $6,000, which takes skipper
Larry a good eight seconds to earn. The engines have to be kept at
160 degrees even when the ship's not in use, so air conditioning
the engine room eats up serious wattage and coinage. That and the
ship's electric can openers.
</P>
<P>
   When the boat cruises at 37 knots, it sucks up $500 worth of
diesel fuel per hour. So it uses more fuel than a Ford Exploitation
or Lincoln Fumigator.
</P>
<P>
   Nosy folks speculate that the lavish on-board entertaining of
certain Japanese investors means something big is afoot at Oracle.
</P>
<P>
   SPEAKING of SUVs, why is it that the chromiest and shiniest
vehicles on the road are the four-wheel-drive sport-utes?
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that like putting a doily on the seat of a tractor?
</P>
<P>
   LOCAL AUCTION house Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield will hold a fossil
auction next month, the star of which will be a 200
million-year-old winged reptile.
</P>
<P>
   The Icarosaurus siefkeri is expected to fetch about $300,000. So
if you're shopping for Larry Ellison's birthday, this might make a
nice chew toy for his dog.
</P>
<P>
   I'm going to wait until the fossil market is flooded with
knockoffs and the prices comes down.
</P>
<P>
   FOR RENT, a nice little two-bedroomer in Noe Valley, and the
owner was asking $1,800 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, more than 100 prospective renters showed up, each
kicking in the $100 credit-check fee that the owner was asking in
hopes of weeding out casual shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   The place finally rented for $3,000 per.
</P>
<P>
   DANGER LURKS everywhere in this city.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Kaufman sends a frightening listing from the July issue of
Bay Area Parent magazine, from the calendar of events:
</P>
<P>
   ``Storyteller and harpist Nancy Thym tells `The Stolen Bairn and
the Sidh,' the Scottish Highland tale of a woman whose baby is
stolen by fairies at the California Academy of Sciences.''
</P>
<P>
   And Tinkerbell is the  &UR; capo de tutti capos,  &LR; right?
</P>
<P>
   GET HIGH and be clean forever more.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you can become the Bathing Betty or Bill who will sit in
the bathtub that perches on the roof in front of Caldwell's Factory
Outlet on Bayshore Blvd.
</P>
<P>
   The original mannequin bathed in that tub for decades, a
semi-historical piece of roadside kitsch, but fell down and broke
in last winter's storms.
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell's is searching for a worthy native San Franciscan to
serve as the model for the next Betty.
</P>
<P>
   To apply for the job, write a letter to Caldwell's explaining
why you are best qualified. Include a snapshot, birthday suit not
required.
</P>
<P>
   THOSE CUTE new scooters, admit it, you have to have one.
</P>
<P>
   We all do. And soon we all will, and can you imagine how many
pedestrians are going to be run down by scooter people? And how
many cars are going to have to go to the body shop to have scooters
removed from their grills?
</P>
<P>
   I don't mean to represent doom &AMP;  &LR; and gloom, but if we can't
handle the current pedestrian-motorist-bicycle mix, what will be do
when a million madly zipping scooters are tossed into the formula?
</P>
<P>
   WITH A SONG on his lips and a package in his arms, Dave McCann
has brightened the mood at City Hall and Civic Center since 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Dave is the Singing UPS Man, nonstop belter-outer of Broadway
show tunes, barbershop quartet hits and whatever else hops onto the
turntable of his internal jukebox.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, next month Dave is retiring. The city will be a quieter,
duller place.
</P>
<P>
   I hereby nominate Dave for the Whirlitzer Prize.
</P>
<P>
   JURY SELECTION in federal court in Oakland, and one woman stated
her occupation as clairvoyant.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Spencer PI reports that the woman told District Judge
Claudia Wilken that she (the clairvoyant) would base her ultimate
decision not solely on evidence and testimony, but also on the
``energy fields'' of witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Sad ending to a potential only-in-the-Bay-Area story: The woman
was not seated on the jury.
</P>
<P>
   TO WHIP PAST the Golden Gate Bridge toll booths, Matt Regan says
he flashes his cell phone and presses ``car forwarding.''
</P>
<P>
   I've got ``car waiting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
