<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TV ADS IN CALIFORNIA FOR BUSH EMPHASIZING EDUCATION
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush is back on television in
California for the first time since March, with a
Republican-sponsored ad touting his record on education.
</P>
<P>
   The ad campaign, backed by the California Republican Party, is
designed to showcase the presidential candidate in the weeks
leading up to the GOP national convention in Philadelphia at the
end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the maximum number of people to see this,'' said state
Sen. Jim Brulte, R-Rancho Cucamonga, the finance chair for the
state GOP. ``We want to set the tone for the convention, where one
of the themes will be improving schools. We know during the summer
months very few voters are paying attention. Now we think people
are starting to focus on the election.''
</P>
<P>
   Brulte refused to say how much the television campaign costs or
where exactly the commercial will run, saying only that the expense
is ``significant.'' There is a version of the ad in Spanish, but
Brulte would not say if it will be aired.
</P>
<P>
   The ad buy is part of an effort by the Republican National
Committee to back Bush with so-called ``soft'' money from the party
rather than ``hard'' dollars from the Texas governor's own campaign
treasury. The single commercial will start running Tuesday in
California and 19 other states.
</P>
<P>
   The ad features a relaxed Bush talking about some of the
education programs he has promoted in Texas. About the only
difference from the flock of campaign ads that will fill the
airwaves in the fall is that the party-sponsored spot doesn't _ and
by federal election law, can't _ end by asking viewers to ``Vote
Bush for President.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy just to spend more,'' Bush says in the ad, repeating
one of his standard campaign themes. ``Now it is time to expect
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Kent Grusendorf, a state representative from Texas, told a news
conference in Sacramento Monday that the commercial emphasizes some
of the areas Bush has pushed in his own state.
</P>
<P>
   ``This personifies what George Bush stands for,'' he said. ``We
have seen minority scores improve more than any state in the
country. Bush ended social promotion and refused to believe that
some kids just couldn't read by the end of third grade.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the other improvements Grusendorf said Bush will take from
Texas to the White House if elected are: increased local control,
stricter accountability measures and alternatives for at-risk
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Texas, there has been a 37 percent increase in student
funding and a 37 percent increase in teacher pay,'' Grusendorf
said. ``I'm convinced that if Bush is elected president, he will
work tirelessly to help children receive the best possible
education.''
</P>
<P>
   Brulte said the new television ad campaign shows once again that
Bush is going to fight hard to try to win California, despite
trailing Vice President Al Gore in polls here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats want to win California on the cheap,'' he said.
``They are afraid of this candidacy, they are afraid of this
message. I assure you that when you see the size of this buy and
how widespread it is, you will see that Governor Bush is serious
about California.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is welcome to spend time and money in California, said Bob
Mulholland, a spokesman for the state Democratic Party. But before
election day, he warned, the Texas governor is going to have to
talk about subjects that are much more controversial than
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have Republicans right where we want them,'' Mulholland
said. ``They want to prove California is competitive, but in the
end we will crush them on (abortion) choice and guns.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
