<HEADER>
A5263 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-DIRT-STADIUM-SFCHRON &LR;      07-18 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIRT-STADIUM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CALIFORNIA TAXPAYERS FOOT $1 MILLION TAB FOR S.F. DIRT REMOVAL  &HT;     By GREG LUCAS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ The giant trash company that had to haul away the
lead-tainted dirt that builders of San Francisco's Pacific Bell
Park took to the wrong landfill has persuaded legislators and the
Davis administration to make taxpayers foot the $977,000 bill for
disposal.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists for Waste Management Inc., which had sales of $13
billion in 1999, has said the company was owed the money because
the state first said dirt from the stadium was not hazardous and
then reversed itself. The company was then forced to move the soil
again, this time to a more secure landfill.
</P>
<P>
   Waste Management argued that the state admitted its mistake and
should compensate the company for the costs of that error. But in
April, the state Board of Control rejected Waste Management's
claim, as it routinely does with most big-ticket items.
</P>
<P>
   That same error cost the Giants more than $2 million in
higher-than-expected disposal costs of the tainted dirt left on its
infield. The Giants received no state reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it passed muster,'' said Assemblywoman Carole Migden,
D-San Francisco, who placed the money for Waste Management in this
year's state budget. ``I first tried to ascertain if it was a
legitimate claim, and the Davis administration's view was the claim
was righteous.''
</P>
<P>
   Waste Management is a political backer of Migden's. On February
18, Migden received a $2,000 campaign contribution from the
disposal company.
</P>
<P>
   The money for Waste Management _ slipped into the budget at a
late-night hearing days before the budget was finally approved _ is
probably the last chapter in the saga of the disposal of 18,000
cubic yards of lead-laced dirt by the builders of Pacific Bell
Park.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1999, while the $319 million stadium was under
construction, the state Department of Toxic Substance Control
analyzed a mound of dirt from the site and found it not to be
hazardous.
</P>
<P>
   Some 6,000 cubic yards of the dirt was then hauled to the
Altamont landfill, which is operated by Waste Management.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after the ballpark builders got the go-ahead to dump
the dirt at Altamont, the state reversed itself, saying a more
thorough testing of the dirt proved that it contained high enough
concentrations of lead to be hazardous.
</P>
<P>
   Disposal of hazardous materials is much more rigorous and
requires the use of special landfills.
</P>
<P>
   Alameda County officials, angered that the lead-heavy dirt was
dumped in a municipal landfill, ordered Waste Management to get the
dirt out of Altamont or possibly see its license revoked.
</P>
<P>
   Waste Management was forced to gather up the tainted dirt and
truck it to a hazardous-materials dump it operates in Kettleman
Hills in Kings County.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the company requested reimbursement from the state
for the moving costs, saying the costs would never have been
incurred if it had not been for the state's error. The claim also
included $45,621 in legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   After the state Board of Control rejected the claim, Waste
Management's lobbyists went to work, trying to get the company's
money into the budget.
</P>
<P>
   The company won approval of the idea from Ed Lowry, the new
director of the toxics department, and Winston Hickox, Gov. Gray
Davis' cabinet secretary for environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a legitimate beef with the state,'' Lowry said.
``Before I became director, someone dropped the ball and mistakes
were made.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the company enlisted Migden's help.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was complete agreement,'' said Kent Stoddard, director
of government affairs for Waste Management in Sacramento. ``No one
in the administration was disputing an error was made which put us
in the very costly position of having to remove this waste (from
Altamont).''
</P>
<P>
   The money is buried on Page 332 of the 863-page budget as a
spending item for the Integrated Waste Management Board, which
regulates landfills.
</P>
<P>
   It is almost impossible to tell that the money is for Waste
Management by reading the budget item:
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the amount appropriated in this item, $977,000 shall be
used by the (board) exclusively for the remediation costs described
in the State Board of Control Claims No. G503311, for full
satisfaction and release of that claim.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the number of the Waste Management claim the State Board
of Controls already had rejected.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no attempt by the state to offer compensation to
the Giants, which bore the cost of sending 12,000 cubic yards of
the lead-laced dirt left in the ballpark's infield by train to a
dump in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a small part of the soil was hauled to Altamont. We
incurred costs in excess of $2 million,'' said Jack Bair, the
Giants' vice president and general counsel. ``This latest
development certainly came as a surprise to us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
