<HEADER>
A5264 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-CALIFIA-DEVELOPMENT-S     07-18 1680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIFIA-DEVELOPMENT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELTA PROMOTER NOW WANTS 8,500 HOMES BUILT BEFORE GIANT
THEME  PARK
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By ELIZABETH BELL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LATHROP, San Joaquin County _ A decade ago, a South African
architect came to this Interstate 5 town and dazzled residents with
visions of ``Califia'' _ an entertainment Mecca grander even than
Epcot Center _ on their very own Delta island.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the 5,800 acres of fertile farmland from which Califia
would spring is still characterized by the same cornfields,
farmworkers, potholes, heat, dust, soupy fog and floods.
</P>
<P>
   But Lathrop residents _ who pine for their own Save-Mart, or
Wal-Mart, or any mart that would save them a trip out of town for
the most basic of errands _ still believe.
</P>
<P>
   They believe in Califia's chief visionary, Norman Jarrett, and
in his plans for four world-class theme parks, three golf courses,
8,500 homes in European-style villages, a sports arena, cultural
arts center, shopping malls and offices.
</P>
<P>
   They believe in Califia despite critics' warnings that Jarrett
will never find backers for his ideas and that Lathrop will wind up
with 8,500 tract homes, freeways clogged with even more Bay Area
commuters and not a roller coaster or new job to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   That won't happen, Jarrett has sworn up and down for a decade.
But now, after struggling to find investors willing to sign on the
dotted line, he wants the city's permission to build the houses
before the theme parks.
</P>
<P>
   The naysayers are all but jumping up and down shouting, ``I told
you so.'' They worry that if the homes come first they will attract
commuters instead of retirees and employees for Califia.
</P>
<P>
   But the faithful still believe and want to accommodate Jarrett
lest they risk losing Califia altogether.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,400 of Lathrop's 3,400 registered voters have signed a
petition to put an initiative on the November ballot letting
Jarrett out of a key clause of the original development deal.
Instead of having to spend $100 million on a theme park before
breaking ground on a single house, they want to allow Jarrett to
build the houses first.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative would require developers to guarantee
``substantially equivalent'' economic development, or pay $5,000
per house into an economic development fund. It would be up the the
City Council to decide what qualifies as ``substantially
equivalent.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the $5,000, Lathrop would get $1,000 per house to use for
economic development. The rest would go to Califia to support
simultaneous commercial development on the island _ known as the
Stewart Tract _ such as business parks or shopping. Thus, Jarrett
said, the new residents would have jobs nearby and would not become
Bay Area commuters.
</P>
<P>
   By bringing in housing first, Jarrett believes the new residents
would help foot the $100 million bill for needed infrastructure,
making the project a more attractive deal for entertainment
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Situated about three miles from the rest of Lathrop, Stewart
Tract has flooded twice in 17 years and would need huge levees,
roads, a sewage treatment plant and potable water before developers
could build anything else.
</P>
<P>
   One of Califia's biggest foes, state Sen. Patrick Johnston,
D-Stockton, believes that Jarrett is leading his followers further
astray. He worries that Jarrett will try to put up thousands of
houses, then pull the plug on the rest of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should the developer be believed? A decade of promises
that a big theme park would come first have vanished because it's a
stupid idea in the first place,'' Johnston said. ``There is no
logical market for a gigantic theme park on a Delta island that is
foggy and wet in the winter and hot and windy in the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Downstream and upstream residents say the levees would cause
their land to flood during heavy rains. County health officials say
the proposed location for the sewage treatment plant could
contaminate drinking water. Farmers say Califia would destroy prime
farmland and sap the Central Valley of desperately needed water.
Environmentalists say the entire project is a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   About 20,000 new homes have been built in San Joaquin and
Stanislaus counties in the past five years, and nearly 40,000
people travel over the Altamont Pass every day for work. Traffic on
Interstate 205 is bumper to bumper every weekday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Tri-Valley area cities are also straining at the flow of traffic
and would oppose any widening of the Altamont Pass to accommodate
Central Valley commuters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would just inundate everything in the Tri-Valley area,''
said Livermore's traffic engineer, Dan Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club has sued, and other groups are poised to do the
same.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, a seemingly mild-mannered, buttoned-down businessman in
person, comes off as an unlikely crusader for a place of such
exuberance and abandon as an amusement park. He enjoys theme parks,
although he's not one for roller coasters.
</P>
<P>
   What drives him, he said, is his belief that ``master-planned
communities are better than adding to existing cities in a
sprawl-like manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Before bringing his family to the United States in 1986, Jarrett
said, he worked in an architecture firm in South Africa with his
father and had a hand in early planning of a theme park outside
Johannesburg called Gold Reef City. In America, he said, he could
think much bigger.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett's vision for Califia _ named after the queen of a
mythical paradise from 16th century Spanish literature _ has grown
over the years. It all began with an idea for an amusement park
named ``Gold Rush City,'' bringing the Wild West back to life.
</P>
<P>
   Now he talks of a number of amusement parks, with themes like
``Farm World,`' a salute to the Central Valley agriculture
industry; ``Wild Encounter,'' a majestic wildlife park with day and
nighttime safaris; ``Ingenuity,'' celebrating technology; and
``Splash Down,'' a water playground.
</P>
<P>
   His brochure shows a sports complex, three golf courses, a
cultural center drawing world-class performers, houses designed to
look like European villages, fine hotels, and a network of ferries,
airplanes and trains shuttling people to Califia.
</P>
<P>
   It appears as inappropriate in the hot Central Valley _ where
water wars dominate local politics _ as modern-day Las Vegas might
have once sounded.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not his dream will ever be built, Jarrett has enough
financial backing and government support to convince his supporters
that he is credible.
</P>
<P>
   He has already persuaded Lathrop to annex 5,800 acres and sign a
development agreement. Backed by Somerset Homes, a subsidiary of a
British land investment company, Jarrett has sunk $20 million into
the plan. And Somerset Homes' president, Allan Chapman, has a track
record. He won approval for 11,000 homes now under construction
near San Ramon.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the market for theme parks is good. U.S. park revenues
have steadily grown by about 6 percent a year for the past 20
years, according to the International Association of Amusement
Parks and Attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Theme park operators like Six Flags are capitalizing on the
demand by taking over inefficient parks such as Vallejo's Marine
World and revamping them. Disney is set to open a new theme park in
Anaheim next year, and Seagram just opened a new park in Florida.
Jarrett contends that Northern California is underserved by
amusement parks.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison Price, a Palm Springs consultant for entertainment
attractions who helped plan Disneyland in 1953, said he agrees
there is a market for a theme park in the Central Valley, although
he isn't sure it is big enough to accommodate the scale Jarrett
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Before coming to the largely industrial town of Lathrop, Jarrett
tried to sell his big dreams in Stockton, Richmond and Vacaville.
Only Lathrop bit.
</P>
<P>
   Situated near the intersection of Interstates 5 and 205, Lathrop
is home to glass and fertilizer plants, a grocery distribution
warehouse and an Army depot, but unemployment remains relatively
high, as it does throughout most of the San Joaquin Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Lathrop residents want the niceties of urban life and believe
that the tax revenues and demand created by hordes of people
flocking to Califia could deliver them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to shop in our own town, in our own city,'' said Benny
Gatto, a former mayor who is leading the drive to allow Califia to
build houses first. ``We don't have a library, we don't have a
bank, we have one doctor, we don't have a barber shop, we don't
have a grocery store except the small little mom and pop.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Jarrett predicted that he would open the first
theme park in 2001, although that now appears impossible. But he
isn't fazed by his results so far and says it would be reasonable
to spend 20 years getting a project of this magnitude off the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any doubts whatsoever,'' said Jarrett. ``I don't
panic easily; otherwise, I would probably not be doing what I'm
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lathrop Mayor Steve McKee may be the biggest skeptic on the City
Council, and he still believes it's all possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have supported this project for 10 years, and I have sold it
and I have preached it and I have enthusiastically embraced it,''
said McKee. McKee, however, isn't keen on allowing the housing
before he sees some big investors commit to the Califia dream.
(Jarrett said he has many interested investors, but they wish to
remain anonymous.)
</P>
<P>
   Many Lathrop residents, however, appear willing to give Jarrett
the benefit of the doubt. Nearly every day, residents of Lathrop
and surrounding towns stop by the Califia offices housed in a
former outlet store on the edge of I-5 to see the plans for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   By the time they've wound their way through an exhibit with
pictures of beaming people enjoying themselves in other theme
parks, most have joined the ranks of the believers.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving, they record their testimonials in a guest
comment book: ``I can't wait to see it live!'' and ``Wow! Hope it's
here soon!'' and ``Thanks to those who dare to dream!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
