r n BC-STAR-CALIFORNIA-SFCHR     07-18 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAR-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCORES EDGE UPWARD IN STATEWIDE STUDENT TESTING
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By NANETTE ASIMOV 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Test scores in reading, math and grammar once again inched
upward for most California students, a victory that carries the
promise of cash awards for many schools and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Results released Monday on the third annual Stanford 9 exam show
that, statewide, math scores rose an average of 8 points, grammar
skills 5 points, reading 3 points and spelling 7 points. Most
scores hover at or below the 50th percentile, which is the national
average.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Bay Area, scores showed similar upward trends.
The greatest gains were seen in elementary grades, where the state
has concentrated efforts to train teachers and lower class sizes.
</P>
<P>
   The exception was in the Oakland district, where students with
limited English skills were included in the testing for the first
time. Scores remained flat or dropped slightly at most grade
levels, prompting the district's new superintendent to order
remedial classes for low-performers.
</P>
<P>
   About 4.4 million California public school students in grades 2
through 11 took the multiple-choice test in the spring. Only
students in grades two through eight took the spelling test, while
only upper grades took science and social studies exams. The scores
include results for each school, district and county, as well as
statewide averages.
</P>
<P>
   `We've seen real, solid gains across every grade and subject,''
said state Superintendent Delaine Eastin, who announced the results
Monday in Sacramento. ``Some grades are better than others (but)
our investment is paying dividends.''
</P>
<P>
   That is literally true. Depending on the rate of improvement,
schools will for the first time be awarded $150 per pupil.
Teachers, too, will see awards as high as $25,000 if growth is
steep enough. The winners will be announced in November.
</P>
<P>
   The rewards will come from a pool of $677 million dollars set
aside to encourage improvement. That is far more than the cost of
the test itself, $40.6 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have challenged our schools, and our schools are rising to
the challenge,'' said Gov. Gray Davis who has steered much of the
state's budget surplus into the schools. ``But we can't afford to
rest on our laurels. We have to keep improving.''
</P>
<P>
   Although scores rose overall this year, reading performance
plunged after eighth grade and remained low throughout high school,
a trend that has continued for three years. This year, the score
dropped from 47 to 36.
</P>
<P>
   That trend also played out in many Bay Area schools, even
affluent ones that typically perform well.
</P>
<P>
   At San Ramon Valley schools, for example, eighth-graders scored
77, while ninth-graders scored 63.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our kids don't suddenly get dumb after eighth grade,'' said
Eastin, noting the drop also occurs on the Stanford 9 test in other
states. She blamed the problem on the test publisher, Harcourt
Educational Measurement of Texas and said other state schools
chiefs also believe there is something wrong with the questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just stuff and nonsense,'' responded Bob Rayborn,
Harcourt's spokesman in California. ``Ninth grade is the first year
where it's unusual to find specific courses in reading. They're
reading to learn instead of learning to read. We also know there
are larger numbers of non-English speakers in grade nine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stanford 9 is designed to compare yearly scores against a
large national sample collected some years ago, which means the
test questions are identical each year. This has led to criticism
that gains are largely due to teachers' familiarity with the test
and their improved ability to teach to its specific content.
</P>
<P>
   Education experts have also complained that the Stanford 9 does
not test students on California's academic standards. And, as a
multiple-choice test, it fails to inspire students to think
critically or test writing skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to write anything, so teachers focus on how to
identify bad sentences in a paragraph,'' said Mike Kirst, a
Stanford University education professor. ``I don't call that
teaching to the test, but you're narrowing the focus of instruction
to what's being tested on the test.''
</P>
<P>
   Eastin said she expects that an actual writing section will be
added next year. She also said that within two years, there will be
more questions that match the state's academic standards. Those
will be given increasing importance when it comes to judging which
schools have earned finanical rewards, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is not a multiple-choice exam,'' Eastin said. ``We do not
know if our children can write and problem solve.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the improved scores pleased educators around the
state, who praised the state for spending money on teacher training
and smaller class sizes.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, high scores were most evident in wealthier school
districts. Some great leaps were seen in lower-scoring districts _
although occasionally the percentage of eligible students who took
the test was low enough to raise suspicions that weaker students
had been sent on a field trip on testing day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it's not true,'' said Ritu Khanna, San Francisco's
testing director. ``It's very hard to (manipulate) scores.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Khanna plans to send a letter asking for an
explanation at schools with at least a 10 percent drop in the ratio
of students taking the test. One such school was Balboa High, where
81 percent of eligible students took the test in 1999, but only 67
percent took it this spring.
</P>
<P>
   In order for any high school to earn a reward, at least 90
percent of eligible pupils must take the test. In the lower grades,
the figure is 95 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The money is not intended to simply reward high-scoring schools,
but those that make great improvements. Some low performers in San
Francisco did leap forward _ including Harte, King and Malcolm X
elementaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so happy about those schools and how they've improved,''
Khanna said.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Bay Area districts, the economically and culturally
diverse Mount Diablo spent the last year reworking its curriculum
and materials trying to make sure students were covering state
standards by grade level, said Superintentent Gary McHenry. It also
revamped after-school and summer school programs for struggling
students.
</P>
<P>
   In that district scores generally rose by up to 4 points each of
the last three school years, though in some cases they remained the
same.
</P>
<P>
   In Oakland, three-fourths of students read below the national
average for their age, and two-thirds scored below average in math.
Hoping to reverse the trend Superintendent Dennis Chaconas said
Monday he will require all middle and high schoolers who scored
below 36 to enroll in new math and reading classes in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the district purposely didn't test nearly 9,000
students still learning English, arguing that to do so would skew
the district test results and traumatize the students.
</P>
<P>
   The Redwood City school district this year also tested more
limited English speakers, about 700 in all, said Superintendent
Ronald Crates. Many parents wanted their children to be excused
from the test, he said, but the district urged them to participate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our work has been paying off,'' Crates said. ``Even with more
tested who are basically not fluent in English, the district has
improved'' in reading, math and grammar.
</P>
<P>
   Crates attributes the rise to a new program that provides
tutoring and after-school help to every child who scored below 25.
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle Staff Writers Elizabeth Bell, Julie Lynem and
Meredith May contributed to this story.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
