   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-CLINTON (Washington) _ On what prompted President
Clinton to break his own news blackout on the Mideast peace talks
Monday and comment on the summit meeting. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-HAMPTONS-WEALTH (Southampton, N.Y.) _ Based on the frenzied
pace of speculative construction here this summer, the Hamptons
have never before been invaded by so many rich people wanting to be
wowed and demanding that it happen fast. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT8,9) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-APPLE-GROWERS (Milton, N.Y.) _ Poor weather and a number of
economic forces, from depressed apple prices to spotty insurance
coverage to consumer demand for flawless fruit, have pushed New
York's Hudson Valley apple farmers to the brink. Many are wondering
aloud whether the 10-minute hail bursts in May and June will be the
straws that finally broke them _ and in the process altering an
austere landscape of gnarled trees and open sky forever. By Lisa W.
Foderaro.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ABORTION-VEEP (Washington) _ When George W. Bush is asked
what factors he is seeking in his running-mate, he talks about
things like preparedness to be president and compatibility. But he
never mentions the one factor that several of his advisers say is
hovering over his entire selection process: abortion. By Richard L.
Berke.
</P>
<P>
   CATHOLICS-ABORTION (Undated) _ A group of Catholic priests,
Priests for Life, has launched a campaign to keep the abortion
issue up front in the election season. By Gustav Niebuhr. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-BOOKS (Undated) _ The Frommer's guide to France may be
made up of chapters and maps, but most readers know it as an
indivisible and coherent whole: a book. This fall, that book and a
few hundred others will take a new form on the Internet. They will
be sold in component parts _ chapters, maps and even paragraphs _
that can be mixed and matched. By Lisa Guernsey.
</P>
<P>
   GENERALMILLS-PILLSBURY (Minneapolis) _ They grew up side by side
on the banks of the Mississippi River, two 19th-century milling
companies that competed head to head and made this city the flour
capital of the world. Their decades-old signs still face each other
across the river in symbolic combat _``Gold Medal Flour,'' from
General Mills, on the west bank, and ``Pillsbury's Best'' on the
east. On Monday, though General Mills and Pillsbury said they were
uniting to create a food giant with more than $12 billion in annual
sales. The merger would bring together such well-known brands as
Cheerios, Wheaties, Hagen Daz, Yoplait yogurt, Hamburger Helper,
Jolly Green Giant vegetables and Pillsbury bakery items, though not
all these products will remain within the new company's stable. By
David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   LAGEAR-GREENBERGS (Undated) _ Skechers, the maker of trendy
shoes, is on a roll: It is now the third-most popular brand among
teens, company sales were up 40 percent last quarter from a year
ago, and its stock has been among the market's best performers this
year. But the Greenbergs, the family that runs Skechers, also ran
L.A. Gear, one of retailing's most explosive collapses. Some
analysts and investors are concerned with what they see as
parallels between the two companies. By Kruti Trivedi.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-INVESTMENT-CLUBS (Undated) _ While Web sites like the
Motley Fool have long provided forums for investment club members
to meet and educate themselves about how to run clubs, a new crop
of Internet companies are taking it a step further, offering
one-stop shops merging communication tools with software engines
that handle complex administrative bookkeeping functions and
compile tax returns. By Danny Hakim.
</P>
<P>
   GEN-MILLS-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ In announcing that it would
pay $10.5 billion for Pillsbury, General Mills served notice Monday
that it wants to be the king of convenience foods, an important
area for time-pressed consumers and the companies that want their
business. But Wall Street turned the tables on General Mills,
making the company time-pressed to make the deal pay off. By
Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ABC-AD-COLUMN (Pasadena, Calif.) _ ABC will begin a promotion
campaign for its fall lineup that seems intent on all but stalking
viewers, forcing them to be aware of ABC shows in almost every
waking moment of their lives _ when they withdraw cash from an ATM
machine, shop in the supermarket or use the urinal at the local bar
and grill. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-U.S.-TV (Undated) _ Two top U.S. television shows, ``Who
Wants To Be A Millionaire'' and ``Survivor,'' are 100 percent
British-made television ideas. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   WILDE-LOVER-BIOGRAPHY (Undated) _ Douglas Murray, who is ending
his second year at Magdalene College, Oxford, thinks that Lord
Douglas Alfred, the lover of Oscar Wilde, who was convicted of
``gross indecency'' and imprisoned because of his homosexual
activities, has gotten a bad rap. Murray, 20, is the author of
``Bosie,'' a new biography of Douglas. Wilde ``was not sent to
prison for Douglas,'' Murray said. ``He was prosecuted for his
relationship with rent boys,'' a British term for male prostitutes.
By Dinitia Smith.
</P>
<P>
   O'NEILL-NEW-PLAYWRIGHTS (Waterford, Conn.) _ For 35 summers the
National Playwrights Conference has been the tall ship of the
Eugene O'Neill Theater Center, giving a berth to hundreds of new
plays and new playwrights. This year there is a major difference:
James Houghton as the new artistic director. By Mel Gussow.
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL-NOVEL (Undated) _ Critic's Notebook: Ring Lardner was
not merely America's incomparable analyst of a baseball pitcher's
psyche but of much else about the America of his time and ours. By
Walter Goodman.
</P>
