   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUN-RHODEN-COLUMN (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Sports of the Times
Column on the U.S. track and field trials and the sudden surge of
trash-talking that is making runners resemble NBA players. By
William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   RUN-OLY-JENNINGS (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Gabe Jennings, the
Stanford junior who won the men's 1,500 at the Olympic track trials
on Sunday, is a Steve Prefontaine disciple with some wacky
principles of his own. By Jere Longman.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-EBAY-SALE (Undated) _ The Honus Wagner card sold for $1.1
million on Ebay in bidding that ended Saturday, the most ever for
paid this card and the second most for any sports memorabilia after
the Mark McGwire home run ball. By Richard Sandomir.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE TIMES (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PROZAC-SAFETY (Undated) _ The new book ``Prozac Backlash''
claims that the drug has more serious and more frequent side
effects than the public is aware of or than the label indicates,
but other medical experts take a much more cautious approach. By
Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT2) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LIGHTNING (Undated) _ An eight-week long experiment on
lightning and severe weather turned up some stunning surprises in
Goodland, Kan., the home of the nation's most violent
thunderstorms. By Sandra Blakeslee.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FUNGUS-HERBICIDE (Bozeman, Mont.) _ A native bioherbicide
fungus, Fusarium oxsporum, attacks coca plants, and some
researchers and politicians want to put it to work against the coca
fields of Colombia. But biologists see pros and cons. By Jim
Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HAWAII-TRASH (Undated) _ Though Hawaii's coral reefs are
healthy compared to others in the world, they are the unfortunate
host to huge quantities of trash discarded into the Pacific Ocean.
This debris, like large fishing nets, threaten the coral and
endangered animals like the monk seal, as well as the green sea
turtle and the humpback whale. By Rachel X. Weissman.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BODY-IMAGE (Baltimore) _ Most psychologists believe that
women, men and even children are feeling worse than ever about the
way they look, especially about their weight. Girl Scouts and women
attending a tour called Feast, Famine and the Female Form _
Exploring Body Image Through Art, learned of the pitfalls of
dieting and that beauty comes in all shapes and sizes. By Leslie
Berger.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MINI-HEALTHCLUBS (Undated) _ Health clubs squeezed into
places people go, are called mini-fusion workout centers and are
turning up in landromats, supermarkets, etc. Their purpose is to
make exercise more convenient for busy people. By Linda Villarosa.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MEDIA-MEDICINE (Undated) _ A look at the media and medicine,
and when it is appropriate to determine that a development is a
breakthrough. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Part 2 of the Personal Health
column on water: tap water, bottled water and water filters. By
Jane E. Brody.
</P>
