<HEADLINE>
GLOVER SIZZLES TO VICTORY IN HURDLES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ When Sandra Glover graduated from the University of
Houston in 1991, she became an elementary school teacher and her
hurdling career seemed destined for anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   After two Olympic trials in which she never threatened to make
the American team, however, Glover ran the fastest time in the
world this year in the 400-meter hurdles on Monday night, winning
in 53.33 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing fifth at the 1999 world championships, she now
becomes a favorite to win the gold medal at the 2000 Summer
Olympics in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   In the men's long jump, with the four-time Olympic champion Carl
Lewis and the world record-holder Mike Powell retired, the event
has slumped into mediocrity. Melvin Lister won on Monday night with
a jump of 27 feet 3} inches, the shortest winning jump at the
Olympic trials since 1980. Lister's jump was the only 27-foot
effort of the night. Dwight Phillips took second at 26-8{ and
Walter Davis finished third at in 26-7\.
</P>
<P>
   A day after winning the women's 1,500 meters, Regina Jacobs was
the top qualifier in the 5,000-meters preliminaries on Monday night
in 15 minutes 36.09 seconds. She has said that she used the 5,000
only for a training run and will not contest the event in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   In the women's 400-meter hurdles, Glover started in Lane 7, not
generally a prime lane, but she took control of the race on the
final curve. Her winning time was a full two-tenths of a second
ahead of the previous world best of 53.53 this year, held by the
current world champion, Nezha Bidouane of Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   Glover defeated the world record-holder, Kim Batten, who was
second in 54.70, and Tonja Buford-Bailey, who was third in 54.80.
Glover's victory was more remarkable considering that she is
coached by her husband, Don, who is a chemical engineer for
Phillips Petroleum. When he began coaching his wife six years ago,
he knew nothing about the event. By last year, however, Sandra
Glover had become the national champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do it at 22 or 23, but I'm here and I'm grateful,''
she said. ``Thirty-one years old and running strong.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Glover has taken a leave from her teaching job. She
and her husband train after he gets off work in the evening. He
will also take a leave to prepare for Sydney, he said, adding, ``I
hope I have a job when I get back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a full-time job and was training at the same time,''
Sandra Glover said. ``It was hard. After working eight hours with
4- and 5-year-olds, it was tough. ``
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference tonight, she then looked at Batten, whose
world record is 52.61 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry, Kim,'' Glover said, ``but your record is going down
this year.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
