<HEADLINE>
ANGELS BREATHE SIGH OF RELIEF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Brian Cooper was credited with the victory in the
Anaheim Angels' 3-2 win over the San Diego Padres on Monday night
before 19,930 at Qualcomm Stadium. But he couldn't have done it
without a little help from his friends.
</P>
<P>
   Four relievers _ Mark Petkovsek, Mike Holtz, Shigetoshi Hasegawa
and Troy Percival _ combined for the final 2 innings to save it for
Cooper (4-3), who allowed two runs and four hits in 6 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper was good, but the bullpen was perfect. The foursome
retired all eight batters they faced, including three by strikeout.
Percival pitched the ninth and rebounded from his blown save Sunday
to earn hit 22nd save of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels managed just enough offense off Padres starter Matt
Clement. Mo Vaughn had an RBI double in the first inning to score
Darin Erstad (2 for 4), and reserve catcher Matt Walbeck had a
two-run homer in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   It was enough, just barely. The Angels didn't have a baserunner
after Erstad singled to lead off the fifth inning. The final 15
Angels batters were retired in order.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad led off the game with a double into the right-field
corner. After Kevin Stocker sacrificed Erstad to third, Vaughn
drove him in with a double to left-center.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres matched the Angels' run in the bottom of the first
after Al Martin tripled and scored on Ryan Klesko's single.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels took a 3-1 lead in the fourth when Adam Kennedy
singled with two out and scored on Walbeck's fourth homer of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cooper settled into a groove. Following a two-out
walk to Bret Boone in the first inning, Cooper retired 10 in a row.
The streak ended when Kory DeHaan led off the fifth with a walk.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper rarely hits 90 mph on the radar gun, but he threw one of
the Angels' two complete-game shutouts this season on June 30
against Oakland. (Scott Schoeneweis has the other.) He started the
season in the minors but was called up May 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like his makeup on the mound,'' Angels manager Mike
Scioscia said. ``He has an idea what he wants to do. He's fearless
out there. If somebody digs out a sinker for a base hit, he's not
afraid to throw it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``When guys like that show that kind of makeup, they're ready
for the challenge. You don't know if they'll be successful, but
they're ready for the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper faced a challenge in the sixth inning after Klesko's
one-out double. Phil Nevin followed with an RBI single to center,
but Boone flied to right for the second out, Wiki Gonzalez grounded
out to third and the Angels still held a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper batted for himself in the top of the seventh, grounding
out, but ran out of gas in the bottom of the inning. He walked the
No. 8 hitter, Kevin Nicholson, with one out, then walked
pinch-hitter Dave Magadan and was replaced by reliever Petkovsek.
</P>
<P>
   Petkovsek got Eric Owens on a liner to third for the second out,
before Scioscia went to his bullpen again. Holtz entered the game
and faced Joe Vitiello, who ended the inning when he grounded into
a force play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
