<HEADLINE>
BROKEN RIGHT THUMB PUTS HUNDLEY ON DL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ Todd Hundley's injury-marred season took another
hit Monday when the Los Angeles Dodgers catcher was placed on the
15-day disabled list with a broken right thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley could be back in less than a week since the DL is
retroactive to July 9, when he took a foul tip off the thumb in
Seattle. Hundley, who also missed a month with a strained rib-cage
muscle, aggravated the thumb throwing before Sunday's series opener
against Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pain was tremendous,'' said Hundley, whose thumb is
wrapped but not in a cast. ``I could not grip the ball. Hitting is
fine, but throwing is impossible. I could have come down from the
side, but that didn't help the throws. We're fortunate that we have
good depth at catcher. Chad (Kreuter) has been great all year and
Paul (LoDuca) has been outstanding when he's been in there.''
</P>
<P>
   LoDuca, who will catch former Albuquerque teammate Mike Judd
today, is batting just .214, but he has called good games, thrown
out baserunners and added a spark. But there is no substitute for
Hundley's offense. He has played just 46 of the Dodgers' 91 games
but has 17 homers, 43 RBI and a 316 average.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think he will be fine in a week, but this is something that
had to be done,'' said dugout coach Jim Tracy, who is serving as
manager while Davey Johnson is out with an irregular heartbeat.
``It's tough not having his bat in there, but with 70-odd games
left, we need to make sure he is 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Brown will start: Kevin Brown tested his tender right
shoulder by throwing for 15 minutes off a bullpen mound before
Monday's game and declared himself ready to start Wednesday against
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on,'' said Brown, who left Saturday's start with a
slight muscle strain in his shoulder. ``Now, we'll see if I am on.
I did not feel any discomfort in the area that gave me trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's workout session actually lasted 25 minutes with time out
to evaluate his performance with pitching coach Claude Osteen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is such a perfectionist, we went over a bunch of different
things. That is one of the things that makes him so special. Most
guys will just go out to the bullpen and see how hard they can
throw it. When they reach a certain number they're done. Brownie is
different. He makes sure all his pitches are working the way he
wants them before he is ready to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   __ A start for Judd: Judd, the one-time top prospect, is
replacing left-hander Carlos Perez, who began serving a five-game
suspension on Sunday for his involvement in the May 16 Wrigley
Field brawl.
</P>
<P>
   Judd, 25, once was considered such a valuable member of the
organization he was protected during the 1997 expansion draft after
making just 12 starts above Single-A. Injuries and inconsistency
stalled his progress and he now is in his third season splitting
time between Triple-A Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it is just one start and then I go back,'' said Judd,
4-4 with a 4.74 ERA in 16 starts for the Dukes. ``I feel I've been
pitching well, especially lately. It is always good to be here and
show what I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Quick hits: Not surprisingly, Gary Sheffield was named
National League Player of the Week after batting .412 (5 for 12)
with four homers and six RBI. Sheffield homered in three
consecutive games, including his 30th on Friday, the fastest player
to reach that total in L.A. Dodger history. He also had a .588
on-base percentage. . . . The Dodgers have a decision to make after
Judd is returned to the minors. Utility player F.P. Santangelo
begins his five-day suspension Friday, meaning they could bring up
a position player or activate Gregg Olson, who has made just two
appearances all season because of a right-forearm strain. . . .
Brian Giles' third-inning homer off Darren Dreifort was the 100th
of his career.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
