<SLUG> BC-DNC-FUNDS-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTY SUPERVISORS TO VOTE ON CONVENTION FUNDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY ANDERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Boosting the bill taxpayers will have to pay for
the Democratic National Convention, the county Board of Supervisors
will vote Tuesday on a motion to spend an additional $1.59 million
to help the Los Angeles Police Department and convention planners.
</P>
<P>
   About one-third of the money would pay for buses for convention
delegates, with the rest being used to pay for overtime for
deputies to provide security on the buses and respond to LAPD
requests for help during the Aug. 14-17 convention.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by the supervisors, more than $1 million would be
spent to pay overtime to 300 sheriff's deputies to protect
delegates as they ride tour buses to and from their hotels
throughout the county, said sheriff's Capt. Michael Kenyon.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the funds would pay for 100 to 200 support personnel and
as many field booking teams as needed to transport people to jail
after mass arrests.
</P>
<P>
   About $500,000 would go to the Los Angeles Convention and
Visitors Bureau to charter 286 tour buses on 38 different routes.
</P>
<P>
   If the LAPD responds in full force to quell as many as 50,000
protesters expected during the convention, the extra $1.59 million
could bring the total local law enforcement tab to more than $11
million, said taxpayer advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've created a monster with this convention,'' said Kris
Vosburgh, executive director of the Howard Jarvis Taxpayers
Association. ``It's getting to the point where taxpayers would be
better off if we would pay the Democrats to go away.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear how the supervisors will vote on the issue. While
the board's two Republican members are opposed, three of the five
supervisors are Democrats _ Gloria Molina, Zev Yaroslavsky and
Yvonne Brathwaite Burke. But Yaroslavsky and Burke did not return
phone calls seeking comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In a March 14 letter, Los Angeles Police Chief Bernard C. Parks
requested Sheriff Lee Baca's help in the event of ``major civil
unrest.''
</P>
<P>
   Board of Supervisors Chairwoman Molina added the motion to
Tuesday's agenda late Friday to pay the $1.59 million at Baca's
request.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sheriff Baca is particularly concerned about the incidents
that occurred after the Lakers (NBA championship victory) game and
the World Trade Conference in Seattle so that the county is
prepared for whatever may occur,'' said Miguel Santana, Molina's
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traffic downtown is especially bad right now. And to minimize
that impact, they felt it would be helpful to provide $500,000 to
the Los Angeles city Convention and Visitors Bureau to provide
transportation to the convention,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   LAPD Lt. Horace Frank said Parks did not request the use of
private security guards, who might have cost less, because ``we are
talking about the security of our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank said armed sheriff's deputies will be needed for ``an
event as historic as this, where you will have the president and
vice president of the United States and not to mention hundreds of
delegates.''
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Michael D. Antonovich called Molina's motion an
attempt to ``steamroll $1.586 million ... to the Democrat
convention.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This left-wing maneuver _ breaking county policy of private
organizations paying their own way _ is reckless,'' Antonovich
said. ``The Tournament of Roses Parade contracts with the county
and pays for sheriff's services. It brings in hundreds of thousands
of people and creates a greater boost to the county treasury than
the convention will.''
</P>
<P>
   Knabe said he intends to introduce a motion Tuesday that would
require the city of Los Angeles to reimburse the county for the
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't support the $500,000 for the visitors bureau,'' Knabe
said. ``As it relates to the Sheriff's Department, I don't mind
setting aside some money if there is a way for us to get
reimbursed.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jimenez, spokesman for the visitors bureau, said the
$500,000 will cover the gap between the $2 million the city paid to
provide shuttle service for delegates and the $2.6 million price.
</P>
<P>
   He said delegates will be staying in 79 different hotels
throughout the county and that 26 percent will be at hotels outside
the city of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because those locations in Los Angeles County are farther away
from the Staples Center, that 26 percent is about 40percent of the
cost,'' Jimenez said. ``The people staying outside the city
constitute about $1 million in cost. So what the county is
providing is about half of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Vosburgh said the county was drawn into the fray by the
``ill-considered decisions of the city,'' which agreed with the DNC
officials to pay for police protection services.
</P>
<P>
   ``The additional money for the sheriff's deputies can be
justified somewhat because obviously the convention and associated
activities have the potential to put lives and property at risk,''
he said. ``I think where we firmly draw the line is in providing an
additional half-million dollars to the visitors bureau.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   ``Why this rush to subsidize the activities of a private
political party? The city first promises to host the convention at
no expense, solicits the Democrats to come here, breaks its
promises to city residents and then subsidizes the convention with
an additional $4 million over and above the costs of additional
security measures,'' Vosburgh said.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Austin, spokesman for L.A. Convention 2000, said it's normal
for government entities outside the host city to pay for political
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   He said the city of Philadelphia, where the Republican National
Convention will be held July 31-Aug. 3, is paying $14 million for
the event, and that the state of Pennsylvania is spending $7
million for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The neighboring state of New Jersey is paying $3 million,'' he
said. ``New Jersey isn't kicking in $3 million to a city in a
neighboring state because nice people live in that city, but
because it's an extremely good investment. That's why this
convention is a great investment for the citizens of Los Angeles,
as well as the citizens of Los Angeles County.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Stephen Yagman, who last Friday went to federal court
and asked for an injunction to force the return of funds the city
paid for the convention, said he intends to ask his clients _ a
group of city taxpayers _ what they intend to do about this latest
action.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is that gifts of public funds are being made for
private purposes,'' Yagman said. ``The group I represent believes
that to be both unconstitutional and wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anybody who votes for something like that is corrupt.
What's shocking is that the people at the city who did this and
what the county may do seem to have no shame.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
