<HEADLINE>
BIG NIGHT FOR DREIFORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Davey Johnson didn't have cable TV in his hospital
room, but no doubt he had Darren Dreifort on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers manager spent a second night Monday
undergoing treatment for an irregular heartbeat and through his
doctors learned his erratic right-hander withstood a sloppy start
to defeat the Pittsburgh Pirates 9-6 at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was eager to be with the crowd of 25,261 and is expected
to be back in uniform by the end of the homestand. More
importantly,Dreifort retired 11 of the final 12 Pirates he faced to
win for just the second time since May 12.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Terry Adams didn't make it easy, allowing three runs in
the eighth inning after taking over for Dreifort, including a
two-run homer by Kevin Young.
</P>
<P>
   But Gary Sheffield countered with a two-run homer of his own in
the bottom of the eighth, giving the Dodgers (47-44) their
second-straight victory under interim manager Jim Tracy and keeping
them five games back of division-leading Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just keeping the seat warm,'' said Tracy, who managed
seven years in the minors for the Montreal organization. ``Nothing
go Davey being gone. I have learned so much from him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tracy's troops took it to the Pirates, who started
right-hander Bronson Arroyo (0-2, 9.33 ERA). Make that 0-3.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Elster had a two-run double in the second and Jim Leyritz
added a two-run single in the seventh that blew the game open. St
right-fielder Shawn Green even brought the crowd to its feet when
he was thrown out trying to stretch a third-inning triple into an
inside-the-park home run.
</P>
<P>
   But this night belonged to Dreifort (5-7), who even drove in the
eventual winning run when he was struck on the left toe by a pitch
from left-hander Chris Peters with the bases loaded in the sixth.
It scored Eric Karros, who reached on an error by shortstop Pat
Meares.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort allowed four hits and three runs in seven innings,
walked just two and struck out eight.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort entered the game winless in his past six starts after
pitching a two-hit shutout more than two months ago against the fi
Cardinals in St. Louis. But he followed it by allowing six runs in
just 4 innings against the lowly Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   In that game Dreifort also tweaked his right knee sliding. After
beginning the season 3-1 with a 2.59 ERA, he entered Monday's game
1-6 with a 7.03 ERA in his next 10 starts.
</P>
<P>
   High pitch counts have hurt and Monday was no different. He
threw 96 through the first six innings and was gone after seven
even though he blew through the Pirates at the end.
</P>
<P>
   But at least he had a lead.
</P>
<P>
   After walking the last four batters he faced July 5 at San
Diego, Dreifort walked the first two Pirates. When he retired No. 3
hitter Wil Cordero on a fielder's choice, a mock cheer went up in
the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But the boos returned when Brian Giles followed with an RBI
double to right.
</P>
<P>
   When the Dodgers scored three runs in the second, Dreifort
performed another old trick _ giving back the lead. Giles tied the
game in the third on a two-run homer to left-center.
</P>
<P>
   Although Johnson pleaded with the Dodgers to let him return to
the field, team internist Michael Mellman insisted the manager
remain under observation a second night at Centinela Hospital
Medical Center in Inglewood.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson takes medication for high blood pressure and missed one
game in 1996 with an irregular heart beat when he managed
Baltimore. He successfully underwent a second day of tests Monday
and was examined by cardiologist Phillip Frankel.
</P>
<P>
   Mellman, however, said Johnson probably would not return to the
club until the end of the home stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wishes and Davey's wishes are somewhat different,'' Mellman
said with a smile. ``He is very anxious to leave. I have to block
his door.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
