A5285 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RUN-TRACK-LADN-(SLANG     07-18 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-TRACK-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOVER RACES TO HEAD OF CLASS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL OBERJUERGE  
 c.2000 San Bernardino Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Sydney, say g'day to America's fastest schoolmarm.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Glover won the women's 400-meter hurdles Monday to stamp
herself the favorite in the event in the upcoming Summer Games. A
late-bloomer at 31, Glover defeated world-record holder Kim Batten
with a time of 53.33 seconds in the U.S. Olympic Track and Field
Trials at Sacramento State.
</P>
<P>
   After thanking God repeatedly for giving her the strength to win
in a personal-best time, Glover blurted, ``Sorry, Kim, but your
record is going down this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Batten, somewhat taken aback, said: ``I've had it for six years.
I'd like to see somebody take it down. Go for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Seilala Sua won a battle of UCLA Bruins in the women's discus by
defeating Suzy Powell. Sua threw 216 feet, 2 inches and Powell
threw 211-10. Kristin Kuehl qualified third at 202-7.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin Lister won a lackluster long-jump competition with the
only 27-foot leap.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1999, Glover trained under her husband's tutelage when she
wasn't teaching school in Houston. She taught preschool for three
years and second grade for two more. After a breakthrough year in
1999, she was able to put teaching on hold indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Glover will be absent from class, at least until after the
Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   Tonja Buford-Bailey rallied to finish third. She and Batten have
the two fastest times in history (52.61 and 52.62, in 1995), and
they won bronze and silver, respectively, at the 1996 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Batten took off the 1999 season to nurse a toe injury.
Buford-Bailey missed two years to be a full-time mother to her
20-month-old child. Both expect to be sharper for the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Lister led long-jump qualifying with a leap of 27-3 inches. No
one else managed 27 feet in an event dominated for decades by Yanks
such as Bob Beamon, Carl Lewis and Mike Powell. Now, Cuba is the
long-jump power, with Ivan Pedroso the most prominent of the lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm the one to beat'' at Sydney, Lister said. ``I know
I can beat Pedroso. I'm a good jumper just waiting to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Lister, fourth at the NCAA meet for Arkansas last spring,
finished ahead of Dwight Phillips (26-8) and Barton (Kan.)
Community College student Walter Davis (26-7), who was only two
inches and change over the Olympic qualifying standard.
</P>
<P>
   The trio easily is the youngest and most anonymous group of
American long jumpers ever sent to an Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Howard was an angry fourth after claiming his best jump
was improperly measured by officials, who then raked the landing
pit before he could appeal. ``It cost me second place,'' Howard
said. As a replay was shown he said, ``Look America, there's the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   In other events Monday:
</P>
<P>
   __ Lynda Blutreich won the women's javelin competition with a
throw of 191-2, gaining the only guaranteed U.S. berth at the
Sydney Games. None of the top three finishers met the Olympic
qualifying standard of 196-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our sport is kind of looked down upon and we don't get much
respect,'' said Blutreich, who went to North Carolina on a softball
scholarship. ``You have to earn respect, too, and I hope the crop
of throwers coming up can push the sport along.''
</P>
<P>
   Runners-up Kim Kreiner and Emily Carlsten have until Sept. 11 to
meet the qualifying standard.
</P>
<P>
   __ Elizabeth Jackson set an American record in the women's
3,000-meter steeplechase, and the memory of that will have to keep
her warm during the Sydney Games, because the steeplechase is one
of the few track events the women don't run in the Olympics.
Jackson's time was 9:57.20.
</P>
<P>
   __ American record-holder Bob Kennedy qualified for the final of
the 5,000-meter run. Kennedy skipped the 10,000 on Friday because
of lingering injuries.
</P>
<P>
   __ Women's 1,500-meter winner Regina Jacobs advanced to the
5,000 final with the best qualifying time, 15 minutes, 36 seconds.
Also qualifying was 10,000-meter winner Deena Drossin of Agoura, at
15:37.52.
</P>
<P>
   Marla Runyon, the legally blind runner who qualified in the
1,500 on Sunday, was entered in the 5,000 but chose not to run.
</P>
<P>
   No competition is scheduled today or Wednesday. Activity resumes
Thursday morning, with the first events of the decathlon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
