<HEADLINE>
MARINERS SNAKE-BIT BY ARIZONA ROOKIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The good news for the Mariners is that interleague
play ends Tuesday night, and they've been able to maintain most of
their lead in the AL West while having to play without major-league
RBIs leader Edgar Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona rookie Geraldo Guzman managed to get sneak the baseball
from his hand to catcher Damian Miller's glove without too much
interference from Mariner bats Monday night in pitching the
Diamondbacks to a 7-0 win.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' first five games after the All-Star break have
been on the road in National League parks, where the designated
hitter is believed to be as barbaric as the Inquisition.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, where the DH is something akin to motherhood and
apple pie in the form of Martinez, it's tough to go cold turkey. In
these first five games, three of which have been losses, the
Mariners are hitting just .226. The Mariners had just five hits,
only four off Guzman in eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners need Martinez. And Martinez needs to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really wanting this stretch to be over,'' Martinez said
after grounding out as a pinch-hitter in the ninth inning. That was
just his third at-bat in these five games. He's hoping to get three
at-bats in five innings Tuesday night against Arizona left-handed
starter Brian Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``A week is a long time to sit out,'' Martinez said. ``I want to
play, not sit. ``It's been a long week. But now it's over. Now I
can go out and play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners, who have the same three-game lead in the West that
they had at the All-Star break, are delighted to be getting him
back. They'd like to have both Martinez and injured shortstop Alex
Rodriguez both back, but if they can only get one at a time,
they'll take it. Rodriguez isn't eligible to come off the DL until
July 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, we've missed both of those guys,'' center fielder Mike
Cameron said. ``Getting Edgar back will be a very big help. We'd
like to have Alex, too, but that's not going to happen right now.''
</P>
<P>
   With Martinez returning, the expectation is that the Mariners
will somehow automatically become a better offensive team. That
could happen, but it won't be just because of Martinez. If the rest
of the lineup doesn't hit, Martinez won't be able to shoulder the
load alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing in NL parks was fun for a while, but it's going to be
great to have Edgar back,'' manager Lou Piniella said. ``We keep
talking about Alex and Edgar, and we do need them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth of it is, though, that we need a few of these other
guys to hit, too. That's the reality of the situation. You need to
distribute your offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Guzman, the Mariners did no such thing. John Mabry, in
his third straight start, had two hits. Starting pitcher John
Halama had his first hit of the season, and that was the end of the
offense for Seattle for seven innings. David Bell singled in the
eighth. With Greg Swindell finishing up for Guzman, Jay Buhner
doubled in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guzman did a nice job,'' left fielder Rickey Henderson said.
``He had a nice cutter and worked the outside of the plate. But
we've got to hit better. It will be great to have Edgar back. He's
a big part of the offense. But we've all got to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Guzman, mostly unknown except to baseball insiders, was making
just his second big-league start. It only seemed as if he'd been
doing this all his life. In his major-league debut against Houston
on July 6, Guzman gave up four hits and walked one in eight innings
in beating the Astros at hitter-friendly Enron Field. Before that,
Guzman was 4-1 with a 1.42 ERA in six starts for Class AAA Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   He made his share of mistakes. He opened both the first and
second innings by walking the first batter he faced. And he opened
the third by giving up a hit to the opposing pitcher, Halama,
almost as much of a no-no. But he came back to keep Seattle off the
scoreboard inning after inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had trouble picking up the ball against him,'' Cameron said.
``I don't think he was anything special.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither was Halama, making his first start since July 5.
Although he didn't walk anyone, Halama's pitch location was
sporadic, and he got too many pitches up where hitters thrive. Jay
Bell hurt Halama with hits his first three times up, including a
run-scoring triple in the third inning and a single in the fourth
that accounted for another run, capping a three-run rally that put
the game firmly in Arizona's grip.
</P>
<P>
   ``John didn't locate his pitches all that well,'' Piniella said.
``But he got into the seventh inning. He should be sharper the next
time.''
</P>
<P>
   So should the Mariners' offense, now that Martinez is part of
the equation again.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 0217EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
