<HEADLINE>
ANGELS BREATHE A SIGH OF RELIEF
</HEADLINE>
 ... WRITETHROUGH (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Brian Cooper was credited with the victory in the
Anaheim Angels' 3-2 win over the San Diego Padres on Monday night
before 19,930 at Qualcomm Stadium. But he couldn't have done it
without a little help from his friends.
</P>
<P>
   Four relievers _ Mark Petkovsek, Mike Holtz, Shigetoshi Hasegawa
and Troy Percival _ combined for the final 2 innings to save it for
Cooper (4-3), who allowed two runs and four hits in 6 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper was good, but the bullpen was perfect. The four retired
all eight batters they faced, including three by strikeout.
Percival pitched the ninth and rebounded from his blown save Sunday
to earn hit 22nd save of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels managed just enough offense off Padres starter Matt
Clement (9-8). Mo Vaughn had an RBI double in the first inning to
score Darin Erstad (2 for 4), and reserve catcher Matt Walbeck had
a two-run homer in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   It was enough, just barely. The Angels didn't have a baserunner
after Erstad singled to lead off the fifth. The final 15 Angels
batters were retired in order.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Angels bullpen was shutting down the Padres as well,
the offense wasn't needed after the fourth inning. It was nothing
new. The bullpen has an ERA of 1.98 over the past 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any team at the top of their division wouldn't be there
without a solid bullpen,'' said Percival, who hit 97 mph on the
radar gun. ``They've been great. Especially when every one of the
guys, except (Mike) Fyhrie, has struggled for a solid two or three
weeks, and every one has battled out of it. Now if we can get the
closer going, we'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Self-deprecating humor aside, Percival was a completely
different pitcher than he was one day earlier when he blew a 5-4
lead in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sharper for sure,'' Percival said. ``I knew my fastball
was good tonight. Yesterday I didn't have a good feel for it.
Yesterday I had a bad approach. It's just a matter of getting out
there and trusting my stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys have been there and sometimes they get lost in the
shuffle,'' Angels manager Mike Scioscia said of the bullpen.
``There's a lot of focus on blown saves with Percival, but that's
not what it's about at all.... These guys are on the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper retired 10 Padres hitters in a row during one stretch
between the first and fifth innings and didn't allow a hit in
innings 2-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found my tempo and got to where I was throwing strikes and
they were putting the ball in play,'' Cooper said. ``Usually the
first inning is the toughest for me. When I do get into the middle
innings, I feel extremely confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, though, didn't have his best stuff Monday. At least
that's what his catcher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``His breaking ball wasn't there, he didn't locate his fastball,
his changeup was mediocre and his slider was nonexistent,'' Walbeck
said. ``But he had a huge heart. He literally willed outs out
there. I'm a firm believer if you have a huge heart, you can get
away with mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper appeared to run out of gas in the seventh, when he walked
two consecutive hitters with one out. Scioscia went to his bullpen
and it bailed out Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   ``He walked those two guys in the seventh and I thought his
command was wavering a bit,'' Scioscia said. ``I didn't want to
wait to see if he would get it back. But he battled the whole way
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Petkovsek replaced Cooper with two on and one out in the seventh
and got Eric Owens on a liner to third for the second out. Scioscia
then went to Holtz, who got Joe Vitiello to end the inning on a
force play. The Padres didn't have another baserunner the rest of
the way.
</P>
</TEXT>
