<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    ... WRITETHROUGH 
FINE NIGHT FOR DREIFORT
</HEADLINE>
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Davey Johnson didn't have cable-TV in his hospital
room, but no doubt he had Darren Dreifort on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers manager spent a second night Monday
undergoing treatment for an irregular heartbeat and through his
doctors learned his erratic right-hander withstood a sloppy start
to defeat the Pittsburgh Pirates 9-6 at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was eager to be with the crowd of 25,261 and is expected
to be back in uniform by the end of the homestand. Perhaps more
importantly, Dreifort retired 11 of the final 12 Pirates he faced
to win for just the second time since May 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw a lot of things tonight that make this a great team,''
interim manager Jim Tracy said. ``But (Dreifort) really did the job
and we need that. He just got better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   Relief pitcher Terry Adams didn't make it easy when he took over
for Dreifort and allowed three runs in the eighth, including a
two-run homer by Kevin Young.
</P>
<P>
   But Gary Sheffield, National League Player of the Week,
countered with a two-run homer of his own in the bottom of the
inning, his 32nd and Jeff Shaw pitched the final 1 innings for his
first save since June 18.
</P>
<P>
   Add it up and the victory was the Dodgers' (47-44) second
straight under Tracy and kept them five games back of
division-leading Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see the smile on my face,'' said Shaw, who has been
battling arm problems. ``There a lot of good things all around. I
swear Sheff is the Player of the Week every week. And getting a
game like that out of (Dreifort) is a good sign for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracy's troops took it to the Pirates and moved into third place
in the West after Colorado split a doubleheader with Oakland.
Pittsburgh might have known there could be trouble starting
right-hander Bronson Arroyo (0-2, 9.33 ERA). Make that 0-3.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Elster had a two-run double in the second and Jim Leyritz
added a two-run single in the seventh that blew the game open.
Struggling right-fielder Shawn Green even brought the crowd to its
feet when he was thrown out trying to stretch a third-inning triple
into an inside-the-park home run.
</P>
<P>
   But this night belonged to Dreifort (5-7), who even drove in the
eventual winning run when he was struck on the left toe by a pitch
from left-hander Chris Peters with the bases loaded in the sixth.
It scored Eric Karros, who reached on an error by shortstop Pat
Meares.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort allowed four hits and three runs in seven innings,
walked just two and struck out eight. He even gave the Dodgers the
lead for good when he took a pitch off his left foot with the bases
loaded in the sixth. It was the first victory by a Dodgers starter
not named Kevin Brown since June 18.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort entered the game winless in his past six starts after
pitching a two-hit shutout more than two months ago against the
first-place Cardinals in St. Louis. But he followed it by allowing
six runs in just 4 innings against the lowly Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Monday didn't start out well. After the Dodgers scored three
runs in the second, Dreifort gave back the lead. Brian Giles tied
the game in the third on a two-run homer to left-center.
</P>
<P>
   Although Johnson pleaded with the Dodgers to let him return to
the field, team internist Michael Mellman insisted the manager
remain under observation a second night at Centinela Hospital
Medical Center in Inglewood.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson takes medication for high blood pressure and missed one
game in 1996 with an irregular heartbeat when he managed Baltimore.
He successfully underwent a second day of tests Monday and was
examined by cardiologist Phillip Frankel.
</P>
<P>
   Mellman, however, said Johnson probably would not rejoin the
club until the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wishes and Davey's wishes are somewhat different,'' Mellman
said with a smile. ``He is very anxious to leave. I have to block
his door.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
