<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5348 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-ROUNDUP-BOS &LR;      07-18 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-ROUNDUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROTTEN APPLE NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Bill Hunzeker, the most important new-product rollout at
this week's MacWorld trade show in New York won't be a faster
microchip or an upgraded operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hunzeker makes computer mice. And he's fidgeting with
eagerness to see if the rumors are true that Apple Computer Inc. is
finally going to change the design of the mice it ships with its
Macintosh computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job hinges on what the hell Apple does next week,''
Hunzeker, a product manager for Contour Design Inc. of Salem, N.H.,
says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Contour Design is a maker of ``aftermarket'' computer mice for
people who've worn out their original mice or just don't like them.
The Mac's mouse has been a gold mine for Contour.
</P>
<P>
   Despite rave reviews for the performance and beauty of newer
Macintosh computers, many users have railed against the mice that
come with them. The current design resembles a hockey puck, and
critics have called it clumsy and hard to use. That's fine with
Contour Design. It's sold thousands of its UniMouse replacement
units, styled more like traditional computer mice.
</P>
<P>
   If Apple finally abandons its present mouse, says Hunzeker,
sales of the UniMouse will likely plummet. ``I would expect I will
lose a good chunk of the mouse business,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Hunzeker notes that apart from its unpopularity, the old mouse
may not work well with Mac OS X, the new operating system set for
release next year. OS X is based on a variant of the high-powered
Unix operating system, and Unix computers normally use mice with
two or three buttons. The Mac has always used a one-button mouse.
Hunzeker's betting that the move to OS X will force Apple to adopt
a new mouse design with two buttons, and probably a more
comfortable feel as well.
</P>
<P>
   The mouse isn't Hunzeker's only worry. His company also makes a
special stand for holding Apple's popular iMac computers. When
Apple upgraded the iMac last year, the new models no longer fit on
the old stands. Now Hunzeker's hearing that future iMacs will have
17-inch monitors instead of today's 15-inch displays. Once again,
Contour's stands will have to be upgraded.
</P>
<P>
   And because of Apple's penchant for secrecy, Hunzeker can't get
the information he needs to start redesigning his products. ``We
can't prepare for it,'' he says, ``because we haven't seen the
prototype.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he will, this week. Then again, maybe not. An Apple
spokesman flatly refused to provide a sneak peek of this week's
design news. Hunzeker will just have to fly to New York and keep
his fingers crossed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The success of Apple's colorful iMac computer certainly got the
attention of rival PC makers. They've served up a number of gaudy,
sleek machines designed to appeal to the sort of people who see a
computer as a fashion statement.
</P>
<P>
   Only it turns out there aren't as many such people as the
companies thought _ at least not in the United States. Last week,
Compaq Computer Corp. announced that it was pulling its Presario
3500 home PC from the American market, where it's been languishing.
</P>
<P>
   The Presario 3500 featured a lean and shapely casing and a
fashionable flat-panel display screen, done up in a dark, rich
shade of blue. It also featured an exalted price of $1,999.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a product that was originally created for the Asian
market,'' says Compaq spokeswoman Cherry Harris. But it was decided
that American customers might embrace the 3500 at Christmastime,
when they might be willing to spend considerably more than usual
for a PC. Not so; the pricey machines gathered dust as consumers
continued to opt for machines that were equally capable, but much
less costly.
</P>
<P>
   ``US consumers are a little more cost-conscious,'' Harris
admits. But she adds that the Presario 3500 still sells well in
Asia, and Compaq will continue to market it there.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq isn't the only PC maker to discover the market for
cool-looking machines is smaller than expected. Dell Computer Corp.
recently abandoned its sleek WebPC product line, introduced in
November. ``This has proven to be a very good experiment for us,''
says Dell spokesman Bob Kaufman. He says elements of WebPC's design
will be in future Dell products.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kaufman conceded that sales of the WebPC didn't meet
expectations. ``We have many customers who really liked and bought
and embraced Web PC,'' he says. Too bad there weren't quite enough
of them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5349 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-ASIANS-ART-BOS &LR;      07-18 1634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-ASIANS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIANS TAKING THE LEAD IN HIGH-TECH INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. _ If there was an Ironman competition for
starting the most companies, Wu Fu Chen would be a contender.
</P>
<P>
   Chen, 50, looks nothing like your average Ironman. He walks with
a slight stoop, peers through thick spectacles and sports a black
plastic digital watch. The walls in his office have none of the
usual executive's trophies, diplomas, or photos of himself with
famous people. In fact, they are completely bare.
</P>
<P>
   But don't let looks fool you. In the world of data networking,
Chen is regarded as an entrepreneur par excellence. Having founded
a dozen technology companies in the past 14 years, including
Cascade Communications, Chen has amassed a gold-medal reputation
among venture capitalists, as well as a sizable fortune. He is
estimated to be worth several hundred million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for the son of a poor farmer from Taiwan whose family
had to borrow money for Chen's plane ticket to the United States in
1974.
</P>
<P>
   But Chen is just one of a growing number of Asian entrepreneurs
turbo-charging Silicon Valley's technology engine. Between 1995 and
1998, nearly three in 10 companies started in the Valley had Asian
founders, a study by the University of California at Berkeley
found. The numbers include Asian-Americans as well as immigrants.
Asians account for about 17 percent of Silicon Valley's population
in San Mateo and Santa Clara counties, according to 1990 US Census
Bureau data.
</P>
<P>
   ``When locals here claim that Silicon Valley is built on ICs,
they're not referring to the integrated circuit, but to Indian and
Chinese engineers,'' said Anna Lee Saxenian, a Berkeley professor
and author of the study on Asian immigrants in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a whole bunch of companies started by Asians,'' said
Venky Harinarayan, a 32-year-old entrepreneur from India who
founded Jungle.com, an e-commerce software company that was sold to
Amazon.com in 1998 for $180 million. ``It's amazing how many there
are. The harder question is: Why?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer to that question has particular relevance today as
Congress debates whether to expand the number of visas given to
skilled workers to alleviate the nation's dire shortage of
technology workers.
</P>
<P>
   To battle critics, proponents of immigration are arguing that
entrepreneurial immigrants create jobs rather than take away work
from natives. In addition, immigrants are starting to develop
business ties back to their homelands, fostering trade and creating
a situation in which a brain drain to the United States is yielding
to ``brain circulation.''
</P>
<P>
   Asian immigration to Silicon Valley, and to other American
technology centers from Boston to Seattle, can be traced in part to
past US immigration policy, which in 1990 was liberalized to nearly
triple the number of visas granted to skilled workers. The result
is that one-third of all scientists in Silicon Valley are
foreign-born, and that two-thirds of these are Asian, according to
Saxenian's study.
</P>
<P>
   While Asians are typically defined as people from China, Taiwan,
Hong Kong, India, Pakistan, and other South and Southeast Asian
countries, the vast majority of Asian engineers are Chinese and
Indian, Saxenian found. In 1998, Indian and Chinese engineers were
senior executives at one-quarter of Silicon Valley's new technology
companies. These businesses accounted for more than $16.8 billion
in sales and 58,282 jobs that year, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of America's newcomers, the Asians are more prone to
risk-taking than the average person, some say. Others say that, in
order to gain entry into the United States, immigrants must exhibit
some level of skill or education, making them more likely to be
entrepreneurial. Still others cite social reinforcements such as a
myriad of ethnic professional associations that immigrant groups
build up to support themselves and one another in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``For immigrants, it's about survival,'' said Pauline Lo Alker,
chief executive and cofounder of Amplify.net, her sixth start-up
since 1964. Lo Alker is also president of the Asian American
Manufacturers Association and is starting up HongKongSV.com (the SV
stands for Silicon Valley).
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a people business,'' she said. ``To survive, you have
to meet the right people. These organizations are about
facilitating that.''
</P>
<P>
   Another hotly debated theory about why the Asians succeed
involves the glass ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until recently, there has been a bit of a glass ceiling that
dictated that Asians were better employed as engineers,'' said
William P. Tai, a venture capitalist who began his career as a
microprocessor designer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marketing and management were performed by white Americans.
That forced a sense of community among Asians who believed that, in
order to advance, they needed to strike out and form their own
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People saw us as good techies, not necessarily good
businesspeople,'' said Suhas Patil, founder of Cirrus Logic and a
former professor of electrical engineering at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   But John Chen of Sybase disputes the glass-ceiling notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't buy that,'' he said. ``I have never bumped into a
glass ceiling.''
</P>
<P>
   Saxenian believes there is truth in both points of view. In her
study, she found little disparity between white and Asian engineers
in pay, but Asians were less likely to be employed as managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is consistent with the findings of other researchers who
document greater disparities in managerial representation and
upward mobility than in wage levels between Asian and white
engineers with comparable skills and education,'' Saxenian wrote.
Her study quotes an Asian entrepreneur who said Asians were seen as
``good work horses, not race horses.''
</P>
<P>
   Some say the abundance of Asian entrepreneurs is related to
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asians are a very entrepreneurial people,'' said Chih T.
Cheung, a 29-year-old born in Fuzhou, China, who got his
undergraduate, master's in business administration, and law degrees
from Harvard University and is chief executive of HelloAsia.com in
Redwood City, Calif. ``There's a saying in China _ it is better to
be the head of a rooster than the tail of an ox. That means it's
always better to be your own boss.''
</P>
<P>
   For Indians in Silicon Valley, part of the answer may be traced
back to India itself. There, the highly competitive India Institute
of Technology, with campuses across the country, has cranked out
thousands of English-speaking, technologically astute graduates who
come to the United States seeking graduate education and then stay
on to start companies. Graduates of IIT have even formed an alumni
network in Silicon Valley, with similar groups in Boston and
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the Indians who come here are engineers from IIT,''
said Srini Anumolu, founder of eLance in Sunnyvale, Calif., and,
like Harinarayan and Patil, an IIT graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the explanation, it is sure to be complicated by the
fact that Asian engineers aren't a monolithic force. Among the east
Asians are those from mainland China, Taiwan, Hong Kong, and other
countries. South Asians come from India, Pakistan, Sri Lanka, and
Bangladesh. Some bring to the United States old nationalistic
grudges, others don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have specialized groups like the Chinese Software
Professionals Association or the Chinese American Semiconductor
Professionals Association,'' said John Chen, chief executive of
Sybase Inc. in Emeryville, Calif. ``There are groups tied to
geographies within Asia. Others are tied to technical areas. Some
have a political agenda, others a scientific agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we very organized?'' Chen asked rhetorically. ``If you
line them up along special interests, then, yes. But, together, we
don't speak with one common voice, one common vision. And we need
to.''
</P>
<P>
   With so many Asians in America starting up companies, one would
be tempted to argue that there has been a brain drain of talent
from Asian countries. To some extent, that is true. But their
success in America has benefits, too, as Asians reach back to their
home countries to do business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Research suggests that the `brain drain' may be leading to
`brain circulation,' '' said Saxenian.
</P>
<P>
   Examples of this abound. Chueng's HelloAsia sells Web commerce
tools to companies in Singapore, China, Hong Kong, Japan, South
Korea, and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our attitude is that Asia has 6 billion sets of eyeballs,''
Cheung said. ``We think that's a very big market for us. Asia is
where the US was three years ago, so there's a lot of opportunity
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Tai, a second-generation Taiwanese, started a company in Hong
Kong called iAsiaWorks, which earlier this year acquired AT&AMP;T's
Hong Kong Internet operations. It is now a $6-billion-a-year
Internet infrastructure company.
</P>
<P>
   Kanwal Rheki, president of the Indus Entrepreneur, an
association for South Asian entrepreneurs, and Patil of Cirrus
Logic regularly return to India. There they conduct seminars on
entrepreneurship and lobby the Indian government for reforms that
make it easier for people to start their own businesses in India
rather than having to go to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Still, entrepreneurs say Silicon Valley remains uniquely suited
to breeding Horatio Alger legends.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is a meritocratic society,'' Patil said. ``This is a
country where I can come here, and with sole enthusiasm, I can make
it my own country. There's no other place in the world like that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1042EDT &QL; 
