<HEADER>
A5350 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-BROADBAND-BOS &LR;      07-18 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-BROADBAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBUGGING BROADBAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM, Mass. _ People who have switched from dial-up Internet
access with America Online to a broadband Net connection may rave
about how much they love the speed.
</P>
<P>
   But when was the last time you ever heard of someone needing to
have AOL send a truck to their house 12 times to make their service
work?
</P>
<P>
   For all the convenience and benefits of the high-speed,
always-on Net connections offered by services such as Verizon/Bell
Atlantic digital subscriber line access and AT&AMP;T Broadband's
RoadRunner, signing up is never as easy as popping one of those AOL
disks from the Sunday paper into your computer.
</P>
<P>
   However, if Abraham Gutman and the company he started here two
years ago, Emperative Inc., succeed in their mission, broadband Net
access will be almost as easy to install as AOL. And you may never
need to spend hours on hold with technical support or have an
installer perform surgery on your home computer to get you up and
running.
</P>
<P>
   Gutman, an immigrant from Colombia, led efforts at AT&AMP;T
predecessor Continental Cablevision to roll out the area's first
cable modem service. Now he has developed a complex software
package allowing DSL and cable modem services to allow people to
sign themselves up for service.
</P>
<P>
   Already in tests at three big carriers, including RoadRunner's
Minneapolis franchise, the Emperative ProvEn system has drawn more
than $24 million in venture funding, including a key investment
from Continental, founder and industry legend Amos B. Hostetter Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conservatively, you'll see these things deployed in 18 to 24
months, probably first on the cable side rather than the DSL
side,'' Gutman said. That's because figuring out whose phone line
can support DSL remains a lot more complex than adding a cable
modem customer. Licensing the software starts at $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it might work:
</P>
<P>
   You go to Circuit City or CompUSA and buy a cable or DSL modem,
take it home, and plug it in your computer and cable plug or phone
jack. (You can buy a Verizon DSL modem this way today, but you
still need to talk to someone on the phone to get service.)
</P>
<P>
   Once the modem is installed, the network automatically records
its 14-digit identification code and displays a signup page on your
computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   You pick what service you want, register how you want to pay for
it, and select how many e-mail accounts you want and whether you
want a family home page or other options.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if you don't have a cable outlet in the room where
you want your computer, you would still need to have a cable guy
come tack up a new line first. And for DSL, you would still have to
live somewhere close enough to a phone company central office
equipped for DSL _ and on a street without any phone-line anomalies
_ to allow the Emperative system to work.
</P>
<P>
   But if you already had the right connections in place, you could
have, voila, broadband in minutes, without ever having to schedule
an installation appointment within the dreaded ``two-hour window.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Self-provisioning'' for broadband is considered nothing short
of a Holy Grail for cable and phone companies. They are already
finding that projections of an America with 35 or 40 million
broadband homes on line by 2005 are crashing into the reality that
many installations still require intense on-site work by
technicians and repeat visits to fix bugs.
</P>
<P>
   Once you move to a ``self-provisioning'' world in broadband,
some interesting possibilities open up, such as ordering a new
e-mail account, or switching your ISP. Even more interesting is the
idea that you could determine how much bandwidth, or
telecommunications access, you need at a given time.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the typical cable modem customer is offered ``up to'' 1.5
megabits per second, all the time, for $40 or $50 a month. The
basic Verizon DSL package comes with 640 kilobits. But that is far
more than most people ever need to do things like Web surfing or
reading and sending e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   What if you could go online to order a service costing $20 a
month for an everyday speed of 300 kilobits per second and pay for
higher capacity only when you actually use it? Or buy ``bursting
minutes'' each month, similar to long-distance phone service, for
those occasions when you are downloading a movie or video game off
the Net?
</P>
<P>
   And once broadband became as easy to get as dial-up access
today, and maybe as cheap, you might find you had enough friends
and relatives with high-speed access to do things like making video
calls to them over your computer or trading home videos (and
pirated music albums) over the Net like e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   In aiming for automated broadband ordering, Emperative has
plenty of competition among ``integrators,'' including arms of many
of the accounting and consulting giants, that help companies make
different computer systems talk to each other. Gutman maintains
Emperative's system is far more flexible.
</P>
<P>
   Mid-America phone giant SBC Communications has also made a big
push into trying to make DSL easier to get, including a $60-a-month
plan where you buy a DSL-ready computer and the access. As it moves
into the Greater Boston market this autumn, SBC may offer this plan
locally, too.
</P>
<P>
   Gutman has had a colorful life, once running a South American
conglomerate whose three divisions included a cable TV system in
Argentina, a salmon farm in Chile, and a fresh-cut flower business.
After Continental bought half of the Argentine cable company,
Gutman became involved as a top consultant advising Continental on
its HighwayOne cable modem service.
</P>
<P>
   ``For broadband to live up to all its promise, it has to be as
easy as getting AOL,'' Gutman said. ``Today, it still requires a
ton of manual labor _ not because they are incompetent, but because
it has been hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are, vis a vis broadband, where the telephone business was
in 1920,'' Gutman said. ``That makes it a great time to be alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter J. Howe is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached
by e-mail at howe(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
