<HEADLINE>
EVERETT FLAP, FLAK WON'T END SOON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carl Everett probably needed a little vacation. Things were
getting a little too tense for the man Boston Globe sports
columnist Dan Shaughnessy calls ``Jurassic Carl.''
</P>
<P>
   A few more nutties by Everett and the Fourth Estate will start
getting really pesky, asking even tougher questions about anger
management and past claims of domestic abuse. The toughest problem
will be coming up with a nickname. ``Jurassic Carl'' is all right
for now, but it might have been more apt for slow-footed, ill-fated
former Celtics first-round draft choice Acie Earl.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one: The Phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   No telling how Everett will handle the onslaught. But it's
coming, and Shaughnessy and nicknames will be the least of his
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The latest meltdown by the Red Sox center fielder came Saturday
in the second inning against the Mets. Home plate umpire Ron Kulpa
ordered Everett to stand inside the batter's box, Everett
disagreed, and next thing you know, Everett is ejected. He left the
field four minutes after the ejection, but not without head-butting
Kulpa.
</P>
<P>
   ``His behavior right now is embarrassing,'' said Joe Buck, who
was working the national telecast for Fox. ``It's uncalled for and
he is 100 percent out of control. His coaches can't keep him calm.
Nobody is applauding what Carl Everett just did, and if he's trying
to find an audience in his dugout, none of (the Red Sox) are
willing to commiserate with what just took place.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Tim McCarver was equally shocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something the Red Sox cannot afford is to have one of their
best players miss time, and he is going to miss time right now,''
McCarver said after Everett head-butted the umpire. ``That's five
to 10 days right there. They've got to get him out of there. This
is an ugly scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Fox interviewed Everett about his unusual
batting stance, and the footage was aired after Everett's
explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I encourage pitchers to try and come in there,'' Everett told
Fox. ``I'll let them know I like it in. I'm closer to the plate
just because I know that the majority of the pitchers in baseball
can't hit that spot. I don't care at all. I'm not afraid of
anything. I grew out of that when I was a child.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Monday night quarterback
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boomer Esiason is back with Monday night football. But this time
it is with Westwood One/CBS Radio Sports, for which he will work
with play-by-play announcer Howard David and analyst Matt Millen
starting with the Sept. 4 game between St. Louis and Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The former All-Pro quarterback was fired from ABC last year, and
on his way out the door, he blasted the network and particularly Al
Michaels, saying the legendary announcer would prefer working in a
booth alone.
</P>
<P>
   Esiason said he is over the firing now and is looking forward to
calling at least two seasons on radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't really a spot in television at this point,''
Esiason told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Esiason readily admits that he was emotional and outspoken about
his ABC experience. He worked there for two seasons, first as part
of a three-man booth with Michaels and Dan Dierdorf and later with
only Michaels. Last month, ABC hired comedian Dennis Miller and Dan
Fouts to work with Michaels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't worry about what has transpired,'' Esiason said.
``Certainly when you get released from somewhere, you get down and
are emotional about it. I'm over it. It's like anything else, where
you get fired from someplace and they want to replace you. I've
always worn my feelings on my sleeve. It took me a while. No one
ever wants to be told they can't do a job they think they're good
at.''
</P>
<P>
   Esiason said the radio work will not be as commercialized as
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't be up against the windows of promotions and
billboards, where we have to keep our ideas short,'' he said. ``I'm
looking forward to getting into it with Millen.''
</P>
<P>
   David, who is also the Celtics' radio announcer, said he is
excited as well, and blessed to have Esiason and Millen, both of
whom are capable broadcasters and personalities.
</P>
<P>
   Millen and Esiason, who played against each other, talked about
some of their on-field discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millen was one of those guys who liked to carry on
conversations,'' Esiason said. ``I remember one time when he was
sweating and had all kinds of stuff running out his nose and he was
telling me to run the ball inside. I told him we weren't going to
do that because he couldn't catch the play outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Millen said Esiason made the game fun because he wouldn't get
rattled by trash talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boomer could handle not only the game but also the
conversations,'' Millen said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fight night
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Felix Trinidad appears on HBO Saturday at 10:45 p.m. when he
defends his welterweight title against Mamadou Thiam in a 12-round
bout at American Airlines Arena in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
