<SLUG> BC-TECH-VENTURE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAVASTORM HELPS WEB SITES TAKE HITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't go to LavaStorm with lightweight assignments.
</P>
<P>
   These guys pride themselves on tackling some of the toughest
problems on the Internet _ like writing a program to let 4 million
people log on to an interactive Web site at the same moment.
</P>
<P>
   That's more than twice as many visits as the top sites get in an
entire day.
</P>
<P>
   The Waltham, Mass. systems engineering company is the story
behind the story at sites like Monster.com, the recruiting outfit;
FamilySearch.org, the site for genealogy buffs; and GoldPocket.com,
the Web game show that gives away $1 million every Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't buy a package or a search technology to build
this architecture,'' says chief executive V. Miller Newton (that's
Virgil Miller Newton IV, if you must know) of LavaStorm. ``You had
to build this from scratch.''
</P>
<P>
   Venture investors seem to like this story. LavaStorm will
announce that it's landed $45 million in its second round of
financing, led by Oak Investment Partners of Westport, Conn.,
Intel, Lehman Brothers, and Reuters Greenhouse Fund. And its
first-round financiers from last October, the famous San Francisco
firm Hummer Winblad Venture Partners, is also in the deal.
</P>
<P>
   That's good money for a company in a crowded field. Newton
himself concedes that big consultants and firms with other
approaches are competing to help companies build systems solutions.
Hummer Winblad partner Mark Gorenberg says it's LavaStorm's focus
on highly complex jobs that's attractive. With no small bias, he
predicts they'll be ``the premier player'' in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Newton says he raised more money than he may need to get through
the next 12 to 18 months. That's because he wants to focus on
growing the company, instead of on raising money, he says.
LavaStorm has been operating on the $10 million it amassed in its
first round. And it's been hiring like gangbusters, adding 120
people in the first half of this year _ mainly engineers and
technical talent _ for a total of 170 employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us some running room,'' he says of the cash.
</P>
<P>
   Newton, 41, joined LavaStorm last year _ from a key client. He
was chief executive of Maynard's Monster.com. You might think
that's a blimp company, if you've been anywhere around Boston
lately. But it's a recruiting, job-hunting, and resume-help site
that Newton helped grow to $45 million in annual revenues in 18
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pretty wild ride,'' says the longtime marketing
executive. He hired LavaStorm _ founded in 1993 by Justin Lindsey
and a group of MIT engineers _ because Monster.com's site was
getting slow and unreliable as the number of job hunters using it
soared toward 2 million. The number now exceeds 8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Newton brings experience to the game. He got to Monster via its
parent, TMP Worldwide, a publicly traded New York marketing
company, where he'd worked for 12 years, most recently as chief of
sales and marketing. He's no techie; he relies on the engineering
gurus for that.
</P>
<P>
   If the company has made a splash with giant family-tree sites
(the Mormon Church's FamilySearch.org and a new client,
OneGreatFamily.com), a job site and a popular game show, its future
is in two broad categories, Newton predicts.
</P>
<P>
   One of LavaStorm's early successes was EdgarWatch, the online
site for accessing financial filings with the Securities and
Exchange Commission. That's translated to a big push in financial
services and banking, the boss says. And GoldPocket, which has put
money in the hands of four winners so far, is all about online
events, he says.
</P>
<P>
   The company's driving principal is not modest. Its Web site
touts systems that give clients a competitive advantage and
``disrupt the playing field forever.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Beth Healy is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached by
e-mail at bhealy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
