<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHINESE PROVINCE CRACKS DOWN ON CHEATING HUSBANDS, AND THEIR
CONCUBINES
 &HT;    (750&AMP;ADDS)
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., July 23, And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By JULIE CHAO 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ In the southern Chinese province of Guangdong, just
over the border from high-flying Hong Kong, there's a saying: If a
man doesn't keep a concubine, he's not successful.
</P>
<P>
   Well, there are a lot of successful men in Guangdong. So
successful, in fact, some men have acquired not only a second
``wife,'' they have even a third or a fourth. It's called bao ernai
in Chinese, or taking a second wife. And like the concubines of
traditional China, she gets money, gifts and usually even a house
to live in from her married lover. She often even bears him
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Guangdong, the bao ernai phenomenon has reached the point
where we can no longer ignore it,'' Cui Shuhui, an official of the
state-run All-China Women's Federation recently told the Yangcheng
Evening News, a Guangdong newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The problem has become so serious, local law enforcement could
no longer wait for China's outdated divorce laws to catch up. So
last month, four provincial law-enforcement and judicial agencies
jointly issued a legal ``opinion'' _ which they claim has the
weight of law _ that makes it easier for women to divorce husbands
who bao ernai.
</P>
<P>
   The opinion entitles the wife to half of everything her husband
has bought for his mistress, even if the item, such as a house, car
or stocks, is in the other woman's name. If the wife has no hard
evidence that her husband has been cheating, the opinion allows
police to help her obtain it.
</P>
<P>
   Local women's groups that had been demanding something be done
to protect the financial interests of wives are over-joyed. Since
the legal opinion was announced, the phones at local offices of the
All-China Women's Federation, which operates at all levels of
government, have been ringing off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   The Yangcheng Evening News called the opinion a ``huge bomb.''
One reporter wrote that in two days of interviewing women, the
phrase he heard most often was: ``I was so excited I couldn't sleep
all night.''
</P>
<P>
   The Guangdong opinion comes just as the communist National
People's Congress, China's legislature, is in the midst of debating
a badly-needed revision of the marriage law. Chinese society has
seen huge changes since the law was last updated in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Divorce rates have more than tripled; domestic violence has
increased; and marriages now are based more on individuals'
feelings rather than the old standard of political or familial
ties. The current law gives few guidelines on how to handle issues
such as support payments, splitting assets and custody of children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision to amend the law comes at a time when Chinese
society is increasingly troubled by such social problems as
proliferating concubinage and worsening family violence,'' said
Xinhua, the official Chinese news agency.
</P>
<P>
   The divorce rate was just 3 percent in 1980 but has climbed to
13 percent. In large cities, such as Beijing and Shanghai, it is
well over 25 percent. A 1998 survey in Shanghai found that 36
percent of divorces were due to incompatibility and 22 percent to
extramarital affairs, according to Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Prof.t foreign businessmen who are taking second wives,'' said
Hu Kanghsang, an official of the National People's Congress
Standing Committee who is working on the marriage law revision.
``It also includes domestic factory heads, executives, private
businessmen, even party cadres. This phenomenon seriously goes
against socialist morality and customs . . . and seriously impacts
social stability and family planning.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Although concubines are most common in Guangdong, they exist in
other prosperous regions also. In Shanghai it's called ``keeping a
golden canary,'' that is, a lovely, frail creature who lives in a
cage and comes out only when you take it out. In Beijing, she's
called a ``little honey.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a status symbol,'' said Liu Donghua, a lawyer at the
Center for Women's Law Studies &AMP; Legal Services of Beijing
University. ``Men think, 'Everyone else is doing it,' so they just
copy.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 60 percent of cases at the non-profit law center are
for divorce. Of those, almost one-fifth involve extra-marital
relations. To be sure, cases of adulterous women are numerous also
but are vastly outnumbered by philandering husbands. Some men even
bring their mistresses home, Liu said, forcing wife and concubine
to live under one roof.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the Guangdong opinion doesn't go far enough. Liu, for
example, believes that not only should the husband be made to pay
compensation, so should the other woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The third party has to take responsibility for destroying a
family,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Other legal experts in China believe that would be allowing the
law to go too far into the moral realm. Even allowing police to
help gather evidence of adultery, as the Guangdong opinion does,
opens personal lives up to dangerous abuses of police power, says
sociologist Li Yinhe, a researcher at the state-run Chinese Academy
of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Such disputes have been dividing feminists since a revision of
the marriage law was first proposed in 1995. Passage this year is
unlikely, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   (Julie Chao's E-mail address is: juliec(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
