<P>
   &UR; Tuesday, July 18, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Wednesday.
If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PELICAN-REVIVAL (Point Lobos State Reserve, Calif.) _ The
endangered California brown pelican hasn't nested along the
shoreline of Carmel Bay for more than 30 years. Yet things may be
changing. Hundreds of brown pelicans are swarming around the point
and its little offshore rock islands, raising hope that the
remarkable seabird knocked back by the pesticide DDT will once
again return to mate, build nests and hatch young in Central
California. By JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ According to some technopundits, the
future of computing is in the palm of your hand. Hand-held
computing devices, they argue, will soon supplant the PC as the
primary way people communicate and access the Internet. I've long
been a skeptic of this point of view. Hand-helds are cool for
retrieving information, but frustrating for storing and massaging
it. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-AIRPLANE (San Antonio) _ Sino Swearingen Aircraft Co. has
unveiled the first completed model of its SJ30-2 jet, taking a
major step toward becoming the first start-up company to bring a
business jet to market in 40 years. If certified by the Federal
Aviation Administration, the San Antonio company's six-passenger,
$5 million plane will be the first business jet sold by a start-up
since the Learjet was introduced in the early 1960s. By SANFORD
NOWLIN.
</P>
<P>
   LAWYERS-MERGE (San Francisco) _ Old-line San Francisco law giant
Pillsbury Madison &AMP; Sutro is girding its 126-year-old practice for
the new economy by agreeing to join forces with the old-line New
York-based law firm of Winthrop Stimson Putnam &AMP; Roberts, both
firms announced. By DEMIAN BULWA.
</P>
<P>
   WEB-FINANCES (San Francisco) _ Now that banks, credit card
providers, brokerages and other financial companies have succeeded
in getting customers to move their business online, the money
business is betting the next most popular service will be Web sites
that allow customers to consolidate all their financial
transactions in one place. By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN.
</P>
<P>
   CAREER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ I love asking job applicants,
``What's your favorite Web site?'' It's mostly a throwaway
question, but what I like about it is that the best answers are
honest ones, not rehearsed ones. What am I looking for? A pilot
light, some sign that the person in front of me is enthused about
something on Earth other than the particular job I'm offering. By
DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-NEW-SHOWS (Pasadena, Calif.) _ After the networks spent a
year freaking out _ first over the surprise success of ``Who Wants
to Be Millionaire,'' then the ``Survivor'' reality phenomenon _
they neglected to take care of one teeny, bottom-of-the-pile task:
developing a really good show for next year. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   KID-BAND (Lake George, N.Y.) _ Dylan and Chelsea Wilcox, 12 and
14 respectively, went to a park to play _ in a different sense of
the word. The siblings, who live in White Creek, N.Y., are the
principal members of the band GreayStar, which recently signed a
seven-album deal with Epic Records. By MIKE HESS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DICTIONARY-SLANG (Undated) _ Slang is increasingly becoming part
of common language. In the 2000 edition of the Random House
Webster's College Dictionary, there 303 new words appearing for the
first time among the 200,000-plus definitions. The majority of the
new words come from slang: my bad! (my mistake) 24/7 (continually,
constantly) and candy (someone or something that is excellent,
pleasing or pleasurable). By KRISTEN MACK.
</P>
<P>
   FLORAL-FROGS (Albany, N.Y.) _ In addition to being functional,
floral frogs have also become very collectible. Some people collect
artistic figural frogs, which are shaped like animals or have a
statue rising out of the center. Bathing beauty flower frogs (of
women in swimsuits) were made in Germany in the 1920s. English
Glass frogs produced in the 1920s and '30s were Britain's answer to
American Depression Glass. By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PROVINCETOWN (Provincetown, Mass.) _ The summer season is now at
full bore in Provincetown and will not slow down until
mid-September. At the northern tip of the Outer Cape, this town is
renowned for its art galleries, cafes, nightclubs, clever
landscaped alleys, colorful cottages and guests houses and
family-friendly/gay-friendly attitude. By WILLIAM M. DOWD.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-WOMEN-DISCUS (Sacramento, Calif.) _ There is an elegance to
the women's discus throw that often gets lost in the swirl of
activity in most track meets. At the U.S. Olympic Track &AMP; Field
Trials, UCLA's Seilala Sua threw a near American record throw of
216 feet, 2 inches. By JOHN CRUMPACKER.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NINERS (Stockton, Calif.) _ When John Milem was a Marine
recruit, his drill instructor at Parris Island (S.C.) would make
the young man get on his knees. Then the sergeant would stand on
Milem's footlocker. All this so the DI could look down on him.
Milem is a 6-foot-9, 290-pound defensive end in 49ers training
camp, a tough former barroom bouncer who looks like your average
Marine _ only bigger and stronger. By BRUCE ADAMS.
</P>
<P>
   POLO-CLUB (Saratoga Springs, N.Y.) _ The new owner of Saratoga
Polo Club is investing $1.5 million in improvements and charging
significantly more for memberships to raise Saratoga polo to a
world-class level. ``We're hoping to attract the best teams in the
country, as well as from abroad,'' said polo pioneer William
Ylvisaker, former chairman of the U.S. Polo Association. By DENNIS
YUSKO.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ If you're of a certain age, you
probably remember your first flight on an airliner as fondly as I
do. Getting there was more than half the fun, and unlike ocean
liners, you got there quickly with no boring shuffleboard. By ROB
MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The subject has replaced all
others in my circle of friends and acquaintances. Finances, kids,
spouses, partners, religion and politics all take a backseat to
Topic A: Forgetting. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-DEATH (San Francisco) _ On Friday, a Miami jury gave its
verdict in a class action suit against the tobacco industry, the
first to go to trial: a $145 billion judgment for the plaintiffs.
At last I'd have someone to blame for my father's youthful death
three decades ago. By LYSSA FRIEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   LITERARY-WARS (San Francisco) _ In the art of betrayal, writers
have it made. Instead of going to jail for assault and battery,
they get to splatter blood all over the page, which then becomes
the hot item of the week to read, followed by TV appearances which
enhance the stature of the writer. Best of all, the writer gets
paid for the hit job. By BOB ARMSTRONG.
</P>
