<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 11:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5380 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-MONEY-TALK0719-COX     07-18 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TALK0719-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Broker's just a click away
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ James Olsen of Atlanta shifted his investment
portfolio to an online broker five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He was an early bird. At the present, 16 million Americans have
established Internet accounts to manage at least a portion of their
investments.
</P>
<P>
   That's one of every 12 adults in the country, and the ratio is
changing fast. Online brokers opened 2.5 million new accounts in
the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   At Fidelity alone, assets in online accounts went from $170
billion in May 1999 to $300 billion in May 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first it was just an interesting thing,'' the 32-year-old
Olsen said, ``but then I found out it was a useful tool.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy accessibility is a major reason why people start investing
through Internet accounts. ``I can check my portfolio at 10 o'clock
at night,'' said Olsen. He also uses his Fidelity account to gather
information about potential investments, as well as for buying and
selling.
</P>
<P>
   Low transaction costs are another attraction. A number of online
brokerages charge only $5 for each trade. A few are lower than
that, and two offer free trades.
</P>
<P>
   Price-cutting by the earliest online brokers drew such a crowd
of investors that it compelled full-service brokers to join the
game, at more-or-less competitive prices.
</P>
<P>
   One warning is in order: Online investing is a mechanism for
buying and selling securities. It doesn't make an investor wise or
well-informed, and it certainly will not make you effortlessly
rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do not have the knowledge and the time and discipline
to do your research, to know what you're buying, then this is not
for you,'' said Kyle Flynn, a certified financial planner.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential problem: Easy trading can lead to frequent,
ill-considered decisions. ``It's the same thing as opening the
refrigerator, seeing the apple pie and not being able to resist
it,'' said Carol Hartz, an investor and an officer of Atlanta's
chapter of the American Association of Individual Investors. ``If
you know you're going to be tempted, it's a good thing to stay away
from.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by economists at the University of California at
Davis reported the results of 1,607 investors who switched to
online brokers. Before the switch, their returns beat the market by
an average of 2 percent. Online, they made 3 percent less than the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Note also that online investing has its particular problems. On
heavy trading days _ including days when the market takes a header
_ investors routinely find they can't get through to their brokers
or can't get trades executed quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Getting a real person to answer the phone can also be difficult.
Ironically, the rapid growth of online investing has made it hard
for brokerages to hire enough employees to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission reported 3,313 complaints
about broker dealers in the year ended last September. On the one
hand, that's three times as many complaints as the year before. On
the other hand, that's 3,313 complaints out of about 11 million
accounts last September.
</P>
<P>
   For tips on protecting yourself, go to
www.sec.gov/consumer/jneton.htm. While you're there, check out the
link to the Federal Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some things to keep in mind if you're shopping for an
online broker:
</P>
<P>
   Check the broker's performance at making trades.
</P>
<P>
   ``If their systems get bogged down and don't process your orders
quickly, that can hurt you,'' said Dan Dubay, a certified financial
planner and a principal in PPA Advisory Services in Roswell.
</P>
<P>
   The accompanying chart shows Web sites that can help you check
out this and other factors.
</P>
<P>
   Ask what research capacity the broker will supply.
</P>
<P>
   Dubay advises asking whether the broker will give you access to
outside research reports as well as its own.
</P>
<P>
   Decide exactly what services you need.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 175 online brokers now, according to some
counts. As competition increases, consumers get access to more
varied services. Some offer advice as well as research. Some will
provide access to professional advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Hartz said she picked Schwab not because of its transaction
prices but for the services it offers. She was attracted by free
switching among numerous mutual funds and consolidated statements,
as well as other things.
</P>
<P>
   Consider keeping one foot in the real world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find that people usually do some things online and other
things offline,'' said Tracey Curvey, Fidelity's executive vice
president for online investments. ``Most people still like talking
to a phone representative or walking into an investment center.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask about the broker's insurance.
</P>
<P>
   You're looking for protection in case the brokerage goes under,
said Dubay. In general, he suggested sticking with major
brokerages.
</P>
<P>
   The largest online brokers, ranked by assets at the end of 1999,
are Schwab, ETrade, TD Waterhouse, Fidelity, Datek, Ameritrade, DLJ
Direct, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, Cybercorp and Suretrade. The
list was prepared by U.S. Bancorp Piper Jaffray.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget investment costs.
</P>
<P>
   This is not overwhelmingly important for people who invest for
the long term, rather than trading for quick profits.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Dubay points out, a broker might have competitive prices
on large transactions but relatively high charges for buying 100 or
200 shares. ``You need to compare pricing on whatever kind of
transactions you're doing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Test drive the broker's Web site. If it's hard to use, you
probably won't want to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
