</P>
<P>
   Decide exactly what services you need.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 175 online brokers now, according to some
counts. As competition increases, consumers get access to more
varied services. Some offer advice as well as research. Some will
provide access to professional advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Hartz said she picked Schwab not because of its transaction
prices but for the services it offers. She was attracted by free
switching among numerous mutual funds and consolidated statements,
as well as other things.
</P>
<P>
   Consider keeping one foot in the real world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find that people usually do some things online and other
things offline,'' said Tracey Curvey, Fidelity's executive vice
president for online investments. ``Most people still like talking
to a phone representative or walking into an investment center.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask about the broker's insurance.
</P>
<P>
   You're looking for protection in case the brokerage goes under,
said Dubay. In general, he suggested sticking with major
brokerages.
</P>
<P>
   The largest online brokers, ranked by assets at the end of 1999,
are Schwab, ETrade, TD Waterhouse, Fidelity, Datek, Ameritrade, DLJ
Direct, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, Cybercorp and Suretrade. The
list was prepared by U.S. Bancorp Piper Jaffray.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget investment costs.
</P>
<P>
   This is not overwhelmingly important for people who invest for
the long term, rather than trading for quick profits.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Dubay points out, a broker might have competitive prices
on large transactions but relatively high charges for buying 100 or
200 shares. ``You need to compare pricing on whatever kind of
transactions you're doing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Test drive the broker's Web site. If it's hard to use, you
probably won't want to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
