<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5383 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0719-CO     07-18 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0719-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A magic fern brings the past to the present
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ The biggest asparagus fern I've ever seen
lived in a gigantic terra cotta pot on my grandmother's front porch
in Jacksonville. For as many years as I knew her, which were too
few I'm thinking now, that fern welcomed visitors to the row of
rocking chairs she shared with friends and family. It even had a
name _ Bessie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Has anyone fed Bessie this morning?'' Grandmother would ask
over grits and eggs. We all were expected to lend a hand in
Bessie's care and feeding _ even first time visitors were
instructed. ``Egg water's in the pantry,'' she'd say pointing
toward the small room between the dining room and the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Mrs. Parker stored her magic fern formula, the
``tea'' that grew Bessie to such gargantuan proportions that
perfect strangers would step up onto the porch to admire her and
ask Grandmother how she did it. She liked that. She was happy to
share her secret which was nothing more than a crock filled with
egg shells, coffee grounds, and enough water for steeping. That's
what did it _ that's what kept Bessie green and springy when her
kin on porches up and down Herschel Street lorida summertime.
</P>
<P>
   Feeding Bessie could have been my full-time job since I was the
only grandchild until I was seven and my cousin Malcolm was born,
but I was afraid of the pantry because a house spider the size of a
salad plate lived in there _ unmolested. Mrs. Parker had kind of
taken a fancy to the bug. She'd even named him _ Junior.
</P>
<P>
   Junior was protected like he was some kind of an endangered
species _ which he definitely was not because I'd seen his brothers
and sisters around _ and even Grandmother's house cats knew better
than to take a passing swipe at the family bug.
</P>
<P>
   Only once did I forget and walk through Junior's condo _ and I
saw his arachnid-y eyeballs watching me. After that, if I wanted a
between-meal handout, I went out the front door, down the sandy
drive to the back of the house, around the corner past the wash
house, and up the steps to the latticed kitchen porch. Grandmother
thought I was pretty silly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won't hurt you,'' she'd remind me, her patience wearing
thin at my childish histrionics. I didn't know how to tell her that
I wasn't afraid of being bitten, I just didn't want to be uglied to
death.
</P>
<P>
   Afternoons, after I'd been cleaned up from the day's play, Mrs.
Parker would invite me to join the grownups on the porch for iced
tea. While the big folks rocked and fanned themselves with
cardboard fans on a stick from Seashole's funeral home, I'd sit on
the floor next to the fern, running my hand along the branches,
feeling the soft needles against my palm.
</P>
<P>
   Grandmother promised that when I grew up and married and had a
porch of my own, she'd give me Bessie to keep. Sometimes I'd think
about that on the long summer evenings after I'd been tucked in
between the seersucker summer sheets on the upstairs sleeping porch
off Grandaddy's room. I didn't know who, but I knew I had to marry
someone, if Bessie was to be mine.
</P>
<P>
   Long before I was of marrying age, Bessie, Junior, the house on
Herschel Street, and Grandmother Parker were gone. I wish I had
known them all better.
</P>
<P>
   Now I have a house _ an old house with a front porch swing and
rockers, and an asparagus fern in a green pot over in the corner,
out of the sun. I'm thinking about brewing up some ``tea'' for it,
but I know there'll never be another gloriously perfect Bessie.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail to: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
