<HEADER>
A5405 &Cx1f; tab-z
u t BC-ALL-AROUND-PHILADELPH     07-18 2109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALL-AROUND-PHILADELPHIA-TRAVEL-DOING-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S DOING IN PHILADELPHIA  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color slides and B&AMP;W map available.) 
 FROM THE NEW YORK TIMES 
 By LAURA MANSNERUS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    Philadelphia has done everything it could think of for the
45,000 visitors expected at the Republican National Convention: its
landmark architecture is polished, its streetscapes groomed, its
hotels gleaming with restored marble and brass and stocked with
concierges.
 &HT;    But the convention is brief (July 31 through Aug. 3) and the
summer is long, making for many more weeks of prime tourism in the
nation's original convention city.
 &HT;    When you're inviting the whole country, it's good to have a city
full of walking opportunities. While the convention site, the First
Union Center, is in deep South Philadelphia, the restaurants,
shopping and historic sites are clustered in mercifully compact
Center City, a 15-minute subway or cab ride away.
 &HT;    There, in the two-mile stretch between rivers, the spines of
skyscrapers give way quickly to narrow, leafy residential streets
that make life easy for walkers, if not for traffic. A tourist
could spend a day just inspecting the courtyards and mews,
especially plentiful in the old neighborhoods east of Broad Street.
 &HT;    Philadelphia in summer is still the hot, placid city where
street life means corner taverns with open doors and row-house
stoops occupied by supervising grandparents. But with the dizzying
revival of Center City, another public life _ the kind involving
theater tickets and cell phones _ brings people out.
 &HT;    High summer is also the time to set sandals to the streets
around Independence Hall and see where the delegates to the First
and Second Continental Congresses sweltered. Or to explore the cool
halls of museums that have given their all to this summer's
exhibitions. Or to visit the rivers: the Delaware, with its night
life on the piers, and the more sedate Schuylkill, where the grassy
banks invite picnics and jogging.
 EVENTS  
 &HT;    The city will greet the convention on its eve, July 30, with a
parade of 59 lighted boats at 9 p.m. and fireworks along the
Delaware. Penn's Landing and the New Jersey State Aquarium in
Camden are prime viewing spots. Information: (800) 770-5883.
 &HT;    You don't have to be a GOP delegate to get into PoliticalFest,
described as a world's fair of politics. It will have historical
and interactive (want to read from a teleprompter?) exhibits at the
Pennsylvania Convention Center, 12th and Arch Streets, July 26
through Aug. 3. Admission: $10 and $5 for students, ages 4 to 11
and 65 and older; (215) 686-0350.
 &HT;    And at the Atwater Kent Museum, 15 South Seventh St., the
exhibit ``Vote: Campaign Choices/Presidential Voices'' is showing
two centuries of campaign memorabilia until Nov. 26. Admission to
the Atwater Kent, Philadelphia's history museum, is $3, $2 for ages
55 and older and $1.50 for children 3 to 12. Information: (215)
922-3031.
 &HT;    The African American Museum in Philadelphia, 701 Arch St., (215)
574-0380, is celebrating the blues all summer. In addition to a
photography exhibition, through Sept. 3, the museum plans outdoor
lunch concerts on Wednesdays in July and August, with hip-hop,
zydeco and classical music represented, too. A second exhibit,
through Sept. 17, celebrates Paul Robeson. Admission: $6, $4 for
students, those aged 55 and older and the handicapped.
 &HT;    ``Andy Warhol: Social Observer'' is at the museum of the
Pennsylvania Academy of Fine Arts, Broad and Cherry Streets, (215)
972-7600, through Sept. 21. The show, including paintings of
Presidents Reagan and Nixon, Chairman Mao and Lenin, is the first
major exhibition of Warhol's work since 1988. Admission is $8, $7
for students and ages 60 and up, and $5 for ages 5 to 18.
 &HT;    On the streets or in the galleries, plastic cups of wine in
hand, people gather in Old City, just northeast of the Liberty
Bell, on First Fridays. This month, an extra Friday, July 28, will
accommodate convention visitors at the sprawling open house. About
40 art galleries, on Second and Third Streets, will open from 5
till 9 p.m. For information, call (215) 625-9200 or (800) 555-5191.
 &HT;    It's not Wrigley Field, but Veterans Stadium does have real
baseball, and it's next to the First Union Center. No matter what
they say about Philadelphia fans, the Vet is a friendly place. The
Phillies are home July 25 to July 30 (Chicago and Los Angeles),
Aug. 7 to Aug. 16 (San Diego, Houston and Arizona) and Aug. 25 to
Aug. 30 (San Francisco and Colorado). Tickets, $7 to $22.50;
information, (215) 463-1000.
 SIGHTSEEING  
 &HT;    In a city that never runs out of material, the Foundation for
Architecture leads walking tours of about two hours five days a
week _ Saturday and Sunday at 2 p.m., and Tuesday, Wednesday and
Thursday evenings at 6.
 &HT;    A dozen offerings during the convention include ``20th Century
Unlimited,'' around Center Square, and ``Littlest Streets,'' along
the old, once-bohemian residential alleys of Washington Square
West. Adults $7, students $6; (215) 569-3187.
 &HT;    A different thread of history is on view at the hulking Eastern
State Penitentiary, 22nd Street and Fairmount Avenue. Eastern
State, one of the nation's first penitentiaries, opened in 1829 and
was home to Al Capone and Willie Sutton. The gothic stone monster
was only recently rescued from decades of decay and opened for
tours of Capone's specially furnished cell and other exhibits on
Wednesdays through Sundays from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. in summer. The
fee is $7, $5 for students and ages 55 and up, and $3 for under 17.
Information, (215) 236-3300.
 &HT;    Walkers naturally seek out Society Hill, the core of
Philadelphia's original civic life and of its downtown revival 30
years ago. It's a genteel quarter, red brick from the sidewalks up,
encompassing Independence National Historic Park and dotted with
courtyards and churchyards, with many Georgian and Federal
buildings. But at its southern edge, South Street booms at night
with bars and quirky shops.
 &HT;    Across Society Hill's northern boundary, Market Street, is Old
City, which 20 years ago was a disused quarter of small, abandoned
garment factories with a few luncheonettes and a string of
restaurant-supply stores. The area is now packed with galleries,
coffeehouses, restaurants and clubs.
 &HT;    Runners can always put on shorts and head up the Benjamin
Franklin Parkway from Center City to the Philadelphia Museum of
Art. A jogging and bike path continues another four miles along the
Schuylkill, where the sights _ bridges, scullers, masses of willows
_ are pretty much as Thomas Eakins painted them more than 100 years
ago.
 WHERE TO STAY  
 &HT;    Philadelphia is booked for convention week, but the building
binge has ensured a tourists' market for most other weeks of the
summer and fall. To find out about hotel packages, including
tickets to cultural events, call a visitors' information number:
(888) 467-4452.
 &HT;    The Sheraton Society Hill, Second and Walnut Streets, has a
quiet, established niche in the historic district. Like its
surroundings, the low-rise red-brick hotel is Colonial (except for
the swimming pool) and sedate. The 365 traditional rooms and suites
range from $155 to $270 for a double. Reservations, (215) 238-6000,
fax (215) 238-6652.
 &HT;    A block from the convention center, Loews, 1200 Market St.,
(215) 627-1200, fax (215) 231-7305, is an Art Deco creation in an
old bank building (check out the vault doors). The 583 rooms are
pure 1930s luxe. A standard double is $175 to $240.
 &HT;    Just off Rittenhouse Square, the Sofitel, a part of the French
hotel chain, recently opened at 120 South 17th St., on a pleasingly
unreconstructed block of tiny shops. The hotel, by contrast, is all
modern and smooth, its 306 rooms furnished in gleaming woods and
geometric prints. Doubles, $189; (215) 569-8300, fax (215)
569-1492.
 &HT;    Budget: The Hawthorn Suites, 1100 Vine St., (215) 829-8300, fax
(215) 829-8104, is crisp and new, if a bit spare. Each of the 294
suites, at $149 to $159 (sometimes less on weekends), has
refrigerator, microwave and wet bar, making life easier for
families. At the northern edge of Center City, the hotel towers
over the convention center and Chinatown.
 &HT;    Luxury: The Park Hyatt Philadelphia at the Bellevue, Broad and
Walnut Streets, is rich in detail and history, a match for the
Academy of Music on the next corner of the theater district. With
just 172 rooms, including suites, it has a ballroom, a
conservatory, a rooftop rose garden and such amenities as a day
spa. Doubles start at $275; (215) 893-1234, fax (215) 732-8518.
 &HT;    Rittenhouse Bed and Breakfast, 1715 Rittenhouse Square, (215)
545-1755, fax (215) 545-1750, is as elegant as the neighboring
square, formal from its facade to its nightly shoeshine service.
Some of the 10 individually decorated rooms, all with baths, have
fireplaces and whirlpools. Rates are $220 to $340 and include full
breakfast.
 WHERE TO EAT  
 &HT;    An anchor of Center City's restaurant row, Susanna Foo, 1512
Walnut St., (215) 545-2666, has done Asian fusion elegantly for
years. Under silk lanterns, diners can make their way from Chinese
soups and delicate dumplings to emphatically French desserts
(apricot tart with almond ice cream, for one). Dinner for two
people with wine, about $125.
 &HT;    Fishmarket, 122 South 18th St., (215) 569-9080, offers seafood
in a town house with just enough painted wood to feel like a crab
house. In fact, for the summer, the Fishmarket is making a big
production of crabs. Take a stool at the glistening raw bar at
happy hour and enjoy oysters for $1 each. Dinner for two, with a
bottle of wine, about $120. Closed Sunday.
 &HT;    Le Bar Lyonnais, 1523 Walnut St., (215) 567-1000, is the
downstairs wing of Le Bec-Fin, the French restaurant that has been
on national best-of lists for years. The bar offers many lighter
Bec-Fin standards like the galette de crabe and vichyssoise au
caviar at considerably lower prices. The atmosphere is rich, dark
and close -- it seats about 30. No reservations. Dinner for two
with drinks, about $100. Closed Sunday.
 &HT;    On the other side of Rittenhouse Square, Audrey Claire, (215)
731-1222, opens its wide windows at the corner of 20th and Spruce
Streets to a neighborhood of brownstones and small shops. The fare
is Mediterranean _ Audrey Claire is known for its grilled
flatbreads _ and simple. Outdoor tables available. No reservations
on Friday and Saturday. Bring your own wine. Dinner for two, about
$60. Closed Monday.
 &HT;    Effie's, at 1127 Pine St. on Antique Row, (215) 592-8333, is a
tiny Greek restaurant in a row house with a tiny, inviting garden.
Effie's has fresh fish every day, usually served whole, brushed
with lemon and olive oil and grilled. Bring your own wine. Dinner
for two, under $40.
 &HT;    For those who cannot leave town without a cheesesteak, the pure
South Philadelphia version is available at Pat's King of Steaks,
(215) 468-1546, or Geno's, (215) 389-0659, competing cholesterol
palaces at the intersection of Passyunk, South Ninth and Wharton
Streets.
 &HT;    And for South Philly pizza, try Marra's, 1734 East Passyunk
Ave., (215) 463-9249, now in its third generation. Wear a tank top
and bring $5 to $10 a person (that includes the beer).
 &HT;    A note about Pennsylvania dining: Most restaurants have liquor
licenses, but if you must bring your own, plan. Wine and liquor are
sold only in state stores, which are sparse, poorly stocked and
expensive. They are also not open late or on Sunday. 
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Laura Mansnerus, a reporter on the metropolitan staff of The
Times, lives in Philadelphia.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Laura Mansnerus 
