<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING AROUND: APRIL IN PARIS? WHY NOT?  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color slide included.) 
 By EVERETT POTTER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    Autumn may be the most delightful time to visit Paris, Rome and
many other European destinations. After all, most of the tourists
have gone home, museums have shorter lines and the weather can be
the best of the year.
 &HT;    Hotel prices, however, may not be that much lower than they are
in July and August because September and October are becoming
increasingly popular months to travel. But come late October,
prices do indeed fall.
 &HT;    For those considering a European getaway this autumn, here are
some planning tools.
 AIRFARES &AMP; PACKAGES  
 &HT;    Those who simply want a good, cheap airfare should look to
Expedia.com (www.expedia.com), Travelocity.com
(www.travelocity.com) and LowestFare.com (www.lowestfare.com),
which offer fare finders for thrifty travelers.
 &HT;    Another way to save money is with package deals that include
round-trip airfare, accommodations and transfers _ all for a single
price. Major American and European air carriers offer various
packages to Europe, but two carriers with extensive offerings are
British Airways (Holiday Desk, 75-20 Astoria Blvd., Jackson
Heights, NY 11370; 877-428-2228; www.britishairways.com) and
American Airlines (P.O. Box 619688, DFW Airport, Texas 75261;
800-882-8880; www.aa.com).
 &HT;    Package prices are fixed, and they're frequently available with
as little as seven days' advance notice. The best ones offer a
range of hotel choices, satisfying both budget-minded travelers and
those who want to splash out a little.
 ESCORTED TOURS  
 &HT;    For a single price, escorted tours provide airfare, hotel
accommodations, transfers, transportation as well as most meals,
sightseeing, baggage handling and taxes.
 &HT;    Fortunately, most tour companies no longer try to cram seven
countries into seven days. The smarter ones are tailoring their
trips to people who were brought up traveling independently.
 &HT;    The price can be right, because an escorted tour almost always
costs less than pricing components separately and it comes with the
added benefit of service.
 &HT;    Dozens of companies offer such tours to France, Spain and
virtually every country in Western and Eastern Europe. Travelers
can narrow their search by contacting the United States Tour
Operator Association (342 Madison Ave., Suite 1522, New York, NY
10173; 212-599-6599; www.ustoa.com).
 TRAINS  
 &HT;    Getting around Europe by train is easy. And the easiest way to
research European rail schedules and prices is to contact Rail
Europe (44 South Broadway, White Plains, NY 10601; 800-4-EURAIL;
www.raileurope.com), which also includes Brit Rail.
 &HT;    With a little work, smart travelers can determine whether it's
cheaper to buy point-to-point tickets or to go for a railpass _ or
perhaps decide that a rental car might be even cheaper if there are
enough people traveling together.
 &HT;    A basic Eurailpass costs $554 and provides 15 consecutive days
of unlimited first-class travel in the 17 member countries:
Austria, Belgium, Denmark, Finland, France, Germany, Greece,
Hungary, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, Netherlands, Norway, Portugal,
Spain, Sweden and Switzerland.
 &HT;    But Rail Europe offers an array of regional and national passes,
in both first- and second-class versions. Many passes also come in
flexi-pass versions, since many travelers won't travel on every day
of their vacation.
 &HT;    A German Flexipass, for example, permits four days of travel in
a one-month period, for $252 in first class and $174 in second.
 &HT;    There are also passes that save two travelers money, like the
Swiss Saver Flexipass. It's $198 in first class and $132 in second
class, per person, for two travelers. They get three days of travel
within one month. Single travelers pay $234 and $156, respectively,
for these same passes.
 &HT;    Regional passes, such as the Europass, link France, Germany,
Italy, Spain and Switzerland. Rail Europe also offers a variety of
Eurostar tickets, for travel on the high-speed train between
Brussels, London and Paris.
 RENTALS  
 &HT;    Renting a European house or apartment for a week or more is
often an affordable way to go. That's true for a London apartment,
a Swiss chalet or a French villa.
 &HT;    Most renters will find that they get more space for their money,
even in a studio apartment, than at a comparable hotel.
 &HT;    Small homes and larger villas are suitable for families or
couples traveling together. In fact, when families or couples pool
their finances, renting can be a true cost-saver.
 &HT;    When looking for a rental, choose a property by location as well
as size and amenities. These companies offer a wide range of
European rentals:
 &HT;     The French Experience  (370 Lexington Ave., Suite 812, New
York, NY 10017; 212-986-3800; www.frenchexperience.com) has long
specialized in ``gites,'' rural vacation homes throughout the
French countryside.
 &HT;     Homes Away  (34 Park Road, Toronto M4W 2N4, Ontario, Canada;
800-374-6637; www.homesaway.com) has a handful of upscale rentals
in the most desirable areas of France and Italy.
 &HT;     The Landmark Trust  (707 Kipling Road, Dummerston, VT 05301;
802-254-6868; www.landmarktrust.co.uk) has a selection of unusual
rentals in period buildings throughout the British Isles.
 &HT;     Paris Sejours Reservations  (875 N. Michigan Ave., Suite 3214,
Chicago, IL 60611; 312-587-7707; www.PSRyourhomeinParis.com)
focuses on Paris apartments, from studios on up.
 &HT;     The Parker Company  (Seaport Landing, 152 Lynnway, Lynn, MA
01902; 800-280-2811; www.parkercompany.com) specializes in Italy.
 &HT;     WIMCO  (P.O. Box 1461, Newport, RI 02840; 800-932-3222;
www.wimcovillas.com) offers rentals in England, France, Ireland,
Italy and Scotland.
 ---- 
 c.2000 Everett Potter 
