<P>
   Editors at publications outside the United States may find the
following stories from the New York Times News Service for
 &UR; WEDNESDAY, July 19,  &LR; of particular interest:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' news category)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Thurmont, Md.) _ Developments in the Mideast
peace talks at Camp David. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-CHINA-DEFENSE (Washington) _ John Holum, a top U.S. arms
negotiator, has conceded that China's fears of the U.S. missile
defense system are not unfounded. This and other comments
illustrate the administration's problems with the issue. By Elaine
Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-RUSSIA-DEFENSE (Beijing) _ The presidents of China and
Russia, meeting in Beijing on Tuesday, warned the United States of
``grave'' security consequences if it goes ahead with a missile
defense system. By Craig S. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ Rivalry between the two top
pro-Moscow Chechen officials degenerated into armed confrontation
Tuesday, forcing the Russian military to step in. By Michael R.
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BRIEFS (Undated) _ World news in brief.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNITED STATES &LR;  _ General
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   ARIZ-JAIL-PRIVACY (Dateline to come) _ Maricopa County Sheriff
Joe Arpaio, who gained national attention for dressing prisoners in
pink underwear and dispatching chain gangs in old-style striped
uniforms, is installing video cameras to show inmates being booked
over the Internet. ``It'll be educational,'' he says. It will be an
invasion of privacy, says the American Civil Liberties Union. By
Don Terry.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-PRIDE (Houston) _ For months now, Vice President Al Gore
and other national Democrats have pounded away at George W. Bush's
record in Texas, reciting a litany of unflattering statistics while
all but equating the state with Outer Mongolia. Not surprisingly,
Texans, a prideful lot, have taken offense. The criticism seems to
be scratching at deep psychological territory, reinforcing the
belief held by many Texans that outsiders still regard the state as
a hothouse of violence and ignorance and pickup trucks. By Jim
Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   NY-GENETICS-PROTEST (Cold Spring Harbor, N.Y.) _ Vandals mowed
down a cornfield last week that the late geneticist Barbara
McClintock started in the 1940s to do the Nobel-winning research
that laid the groundwork for today's genome work. It sets
experiments back only a few weeks, but officials at the Cold Spring
Harbor Lab see it as a disturbing, and misguided, outbreak of
anti-genetics protest. By Michael Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SAKS-RENOVATE (New York) _ Saks Fifth Avenue's five-year,
$100 million renovation will turn the entire store into selling
space; it will culminate with the restoration of a ``grand
boulevard'' layout to the currently cluttered main floor. (Byline
to come)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNITED STATES &LR;  _ Washington
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `w' category)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHCARE-GOVT (Washington) _ The debate over Medicare and the
cost of prescription drugs comes down to an old philosophical
division between the Republicans and Democrats: How big a role
should the government play in providing health care? How much
should be left to the private sector? By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `f' news category)
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-WINE-MANAGE (Aniane, France) _ America is famous for its
corporate marketing. Think Coke and McDonald's. France is famous
for its fine wines. Think Chateau Yquem and Chateau LaTour. Now,
imagine a U.S. marketing juggernaut like the Robert Mondavi Winery
traipsing into a French village that prides itself on its ancient
vintages. Such a Yankee intrusion just might arouse a firestorm of
opposition from locals, and indeed, that is exactly what has
happened. (Byline to come)
</P>
<P>
   TOURDEFRANCE-MARKETING (Courchevel, France) _ On the marketing
convoy of vehicles that precedes the Tour de France, where 40
advertisers ranging from Credit Lyonnais to makers of pork pate
spend millions to give away products to spectators. By Samuel Abt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `e' news category or as indicated)
</P>
<P>
   BOLSHOI-DANCERS (New York) _ Svetlana Lunkina and Maria
Alexandrova are the darlings of ballet critics in Russia and in
England. They have a faunlike delicacy that suggests they might
break if touched. But as the two young Bolshoi Ballet stars talked
in New York, it quickly became apparent that underneath that
fragility lay strong wills and even stronger senses of self. By
Jennifer Dunning.
</P>
<P>
   NY-HARLEM-GALLERY (New York) _ In the fall of 1998, Christian
Haye, a New York poet and art critic, opened a gallery of
contemporary art. He called it The Project and presented an
impressive lineup of artists from the Americas, Europe, Africa and
Asia. But if prime location is everything for a start-up venture,
there was a potential handicap. The gallery wasn't situated within
Manhattan's carefully defined downtown art geography. It was in a
former disco on West 126th Street in Harlem. But Haye has turned
being out-of-the-way into a mark of distinction. By Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   KAISER-KENNEDY-CENTER (Undated) _ Michael Kaiser, the American
who helped rescue London's Royal Opera House from its the financial
crisis and internal feuding, is to be named Wednesday as president
of the Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. By Irvin Molotsky.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-OPERA-FESTIVAL (Aix-en-Provence) The Aix-en-Provence
music festival hopes to broaden its reach. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   JAMES-DEAN-FILM (Undated) _ For years, film studios have toyed
with projects about James Dean but were locked in a Catch-22:
studios would finance the movie only with a star _ or at least a
name actor. But these actors shied away from playing the 1950s
icon. Now, a film, called ``James Dean: An Invented Life,'' is in
production in Los Angeles, and will be shown next year. By Bernard
Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   PAPERS-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Readers of Andre Aciman's earlier
work will not be surprised by the rapture over the personal past in
his new book of essays, ``False Papers: Essays on Exile and
Memory.'' In ``Out of Egypt,'' Aciman searched his memory for the
city of Alexandria, Egypt, where he spent his childhood, and this
new book is a sort of sequel to the earlier one. Reviewed by
Richard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (Undated) _ Wine Talk Column: On the San Francisco
International Wine Competition, which featured wines from 16
countries and 22 U.S. states. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `d' category)
</P>
<P>
   COOKING-LAVENDER (New York) _ In Provence, lavender is used
mostly for its fragrance. But in New York, far from the capital of
this redolent crop, a strange thing happened when farmers started
selling lavender. People started cooking with it. By Florence
Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `d' category)
</P>
<P>
   RESERVATIONS-LIES (New York) _ During the last year or so,
restaurateurs all over the city say that lying about reservations
that have supposedly been made has spiraled out of control. People
want what they want when they want it, and, well, if they didn't
plan in advance, they're just going to show up and demand it. By
Alex Witchel.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `d' category)
</P>
