<P>
   &UR; HIGH STAKES, HIGHER OBSTACLES FACE CAMP DAVID SUMMITEERS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POWWOW-CAMP-DAVID-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Deadline after deadline has slipped by since Israeli
Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat,
under U.S. President Bill Clinton's benevolent eye, signed their
declaration of peace on the White House lawn in September 1993. But
America's electoral calendar is compelling. Clinton is at the tail
end of his presidency. This, above all else, has dictated the
timing of the crucial summit between Clinton, Arafat and Israel's
current prime minister, Ehud Barak, at Camp David, giving it sudden
now-or-never urgency. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (775 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EVEN IN AFRICA, THE AIDS SCOURGE CAN BE CONQUERED &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AIDS'N'AFRICA-ECONOMIST-525&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ It is hard to absorb the full reality. So far, the
global AIDS epidemic is thought to have killed 19 million people.
That is almost twice as many as died in the First World War. It has
infected another 34 million. Within the next few years, AIDS will
have killed nearly as many as the Second World War _ mostly on the
African continent. And the epidemic shows no signs of abating. AIDS
in poor countries will not go away so long as their leaders do not
take a lead in fighting against it. And Africa's rulers, with one
or two shining exceptions, have not yet done so. Some have simply
ignored the problem, and available remedies _ to deadly effect. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 125-word optional trim; total uncut is 1,125 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE WEST MUST NOT BE OUTWITTED BY MILOSEVIC AGAIN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MENACING-MILOSEVIC-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Slobodan Milosevic, whose downfall as Yugoslav
president seemed imminent just last year when his troops were
driven out of Kosovo by NATO forces, is in fact tightening and
perpetuating his grip on power. Worse, he has lost none of the
malign ingenuity that has always been his hallmark. He still knows
how to exacerbate crises that might otherwise be settled
peacefully. And despite being indicted for war crimes, he hopes the
West will turn to him, as it has before, as the only person who can
resolve a conflict that he has himself stirred up. This time, the
West must do better. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (700 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AL GORE'S POLITICAL SCHIZOPHRENIA &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASS-WARRIOR-GORE-ECONOMIST-625&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ For most of this campaign, Vice President Al Gore
has been suffering from multiple personality disorder. He can be an
alpha male, a caring environmentalist or an international
statesman, depending on the time of day. Scornful Republicans ask
when the real Al Gore will please stand up. The answer may be: now.
Over the past week, a new, retooled model candidate has been
road-tested. With this version, Gore may at last have settled on
something he can take to the voters in November. It may even work. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Two optional trims, totaling 150; total uncut is 1,050) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA: LIFE, LIBERTY, AND THE PURSUIT OF COSMETIC SURGERY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NIPS'N'BUCKS-AMERICA-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ One way to test the buoyancy of Nasdaq is to observe
the blouses and trousers of America. With their investment accounts
swelling, Americans have been laying out more money than ever for
tucks, lifts, implants, peels, injections and assorted
``augmentations.'' According to the American Society of Plastic
Surgeons (ASPS), the number of cosmetic surgical procedures grew
almost as quickly as the Dow _ from 413,000 in 1992 to over 1
million in 1998. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (500 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAN BUSH BREAK BLACKS' FAUSTIAN PACT WITH DEMOCRATIC PARTY? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GOP-BLACK-MAGIC-ECONOMIST-550&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ ``Most black people don't think alike. Most black
people just vote alike,'' says J.C. Watts, a black Republican
congressman from Oklahoma. Republicans consistently get a mere 10
percent of the black vote, plus or minus 5 percent, according to a
black think-tank in Washington. This is not just bad news for
Governor George W. Bush; it is bad news for America's blacks.
Although their long identification with the Democratic Party has
allowed some black leaders to emerge, it has been, for the most
part, a Faustian bargain. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Two optional trims, totaling 225; total uncut is 1,175) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PENTAGON MISSES THE TETHERED CHICKEN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MISSILE-FIASCO-US-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ As technical failures go, this one could hardly have
been more humiliating. Before conducting the third test of its
``mini-Star Wars'' system intended to smash up enemy warheads in
space, the Pentagon had given careful warnings that the whole
project was a ``high-risk'' one. In fact, barely a feather flew.
The missile test of July 7 suffered a failure so fundamental that
it did not even figure among the various ``high-risk'' scenarios
the Pentagon had worried about. It was, in short, a bit like
hitting a tethered chicken. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (400 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUIPS, QUIRKS AND QUOTES FROM THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN-TRAIL-MIX-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political, Humor Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (425 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AMERICAS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEXICO'S ONCE-RULING PARTY FACES SHOCK OF OPPOSITION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRI-EXTINCT?-MEXICO-ECONOMIST-750&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ After ruling Mexico since 1929, the Institutional
Revolutionary Party (PRI), stunned by its historic defeat in the
July 2 presidential election, now faces a daunting, unprecedented
task: it must not only find new leaders, but a new identity and
methods to sustain it in opposition. Its ability _ or failure _ to
reinvent itself will be important to the stability of
President-elect Vicente Fox's Mexico. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story can stand in 750 words; 1,125 uncut)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EUROPE &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ITALY'S `GENETICALLY MUTATING' PRISON POPULATION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JAILS-ITALY-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MILAN _ ``The prison population has been genetically mutating,''
says Giancarlo Caselli, the man in charge of keeping Italy's
criminals behind bars. He is not referring to some scientific
experiment under way in such prisons as Milan's San Vittore or
Rome's Regina Coeli, but to changes in the social and criminal
make-up within the country's 257 jails. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (450 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MCDONALD'S: TODAY BURGERS, TOMORROW...? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MCCRAZY-MCDONALD'S-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It sounds McCrazy. In an arguably unrivalled example
of corporate paranoia, McDonald's, a giant hamburger chain, has
forced a tiny health-care company based in Switzerland and calling
itself McWellness to change its name. Why would McDonald's bother
with a loss-making small fry employing only 45 people? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (450 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LABORS LOST: AMERICA'S `FREE AGENT' WORK FORCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WORKER-TURNOVER-ECONOMIST-300&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two floor assistants in Home Depot, a hardware
superstore, are chatting. ``Is there anyone left from our
orientation class other than us?'' one asks the other. ``Uh, let me
think. Nope, just you and me.'' They shake their heads, wondering
why they, alone in a group of 15 who joined only eight months
earlier, are still there. Maybe only suckers stick around in jobs
like theirs. These are words and thoughts that strike terror across
America. Today nearly a quarter of working Americans clock in each
day in businesses where the average tenure is less than a year _
often far less. The ``free agent'' movement that is spurring
white-collar workers to shun corporate career paths is trickling
down to blue-collar workers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Two optional trims, totaling 300; total uncut is 1,250) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
