<HEADER>
A5490 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-MENACING-MILOSEVIC-EC     07-18 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENACING-MILOSEVIC-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEST MUST NOT BE OUTWITTED BY MILOSEVIC AGAIN  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 700-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   For anyone who hopes that European history is coasting towards a
happy, democratic ending, the latest news from the Balkans must
come as a shock.
</P>
<P>
   Slobodan Milosevic, whose downfall as Yugoslav president seemed
imminent last year when his troops were driven out of Kosovo, is
tightening and perpetuating his grip on power. Worse, he has lost
none of the malign ingenuity that has always been his hallmark.
</P>
<P>
   He still knows how to exacerbate crises that might otherwise be
settled peacefully. And despite being indicted for war crimes, he
hopes the West will turn to him, as it has before, as the only
person who can resolve a conflict that he has himself stirred up.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the West must do better.
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional changes rushed through the Yugoslav
legislature this month are a textbook example of the Milosevic
method. The amendments were designed to make life intolerable for
Montenegro, Serbia's reluctant partner in the Yugoslav federation.
</P>
<P>
   The aim was to reduce Montenegro's say in federal affairs and
thus to bounce Milo Djukanovic, the Montenegrin leader, into a
referendum on independence _ which might in turn trigger a civil
war in which Serbia could ``intervene'' without seeming to fire
first.
</P>
<P>
   For people whose purpose is served by fratricide, Montenegro
provides uniquely promising material. Like Northern Ireland, it is
a small, clannish territory whose well-armed populace is deeply,
and about evenly, divided over questions of political and cultural
identity _ which anyway have no clear-cut or rational answer.
</P>
<P>
   About a third of Montenegrins firmly support independence; a
third want no loosening of the ties with Serbia; the remainder are
in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   If at some time in the future, a clear majority of Montenegrins
were to vote for independence, and the republic came under attack
from Serbia, NATO would have little choice but to rally to the
smaller republic's aid. That is a political reality of which
Milosevic should be reminded as clearly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   It would, however, be vastly preferable if the slide towards
confrontation could be halted at an earlier stage. Given the
reluctance of western governments to face the messiness of ground
warfare in mountainous terrain, military aid to Montenegro would
presumably take the form of air support.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever such a policy achieved, it would not be able _ on past
evidence _ to prevent retaliatory killings on a horrific scale in
Montenegro's highlands, and it might well exacerbate them.
</P>
<P>
   In some circumstances, a storming NATO intervention would seem
less bad than doing nothing; but everything possible should be done
to stop such circumstances arising.
</P>
<P>
   How can the risk be reduced? Hitherto, western policy has aimed,
sensibly enough, at calming the political atmosphere through modest
economic aid and quiet security help for Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Though it has cushioned the effects of Serbia's blockade, this
aid has not so far been effective enough to convince a clear
majority of Montenegrins that their interests are served by
pro-western policies.
</P>
<P>
   With the Djukanovic government keeping a tight hold on the
economy, some citizens suspect their leader of using the standoff
with Serbia for his own political purposes _ and they blame the
West for abetting him.
</P>
<P>
   A worse problem is that in Serbia, too, people doubt whether the
West really would help them economically if they ousted Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of concentrating on fanfare diplomacy, like the Balkan
summit France wants to convene, West European governments should be
looking for ways to show their good faith to skeptics in both
Serbia and Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   They should swiftly act, as the European Commission suggests, to
open their markets to exports from Montenegro and other south
Balkan countries. And the EU's leaders should endorse, loudly and
clearly, the commission's proposal to set aside a substantial sum
for the reconstruction of a post-Milosevic Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic, meanwhile, should be urged to open up his economy to
the sort of legal, private-sector activity that gives people a
stake in peace.
</P>
<P>
   He should also be told to deal generously with his compatriots
who feel culturally Serbian, embarrassed though some may be by
Serbia's government. If he matches Milosevic's cunning, he might
yet turn this crisis into an opportunity to ease Montenegro's
internal wounds. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1302EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
