r k BC-MISSILE-FIASCO-US-ECO     07-18 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-FIASCO-US-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON MISSES THE TETHERED CHICKEN  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 400-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   As technical failures go, this one could hardly have been more
humiliating. Before conducting the third test of its ``mini-Star
Wars'' system intended to smash up enemy warheads in space, the
Pentagon had given careful warnings that the whole project was a
``high-risk'' one.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics, meanwhile, had questioned the honesty of the test,
arguing that it was far too easy.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast with a real-life onslaught by a rogue state, the
designers of the intercepting missile would know the time and
source of the incoming missile; they would also know all about the
single, crude decoy that would be released at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   It was, in short, a bit like hitting a tethered chicken.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, barely a feather flew. The missile test on July 7
suffered a failure so fundamental that it did not even figure among
the various ``high-risk'' scenarios the Pentagon had worried about.
</P>
<P>
   The intercepting missile refused to separate from its booster
rocket, so no collision was attempted; and in a separate setback,
the decoy balloon did not inflate.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's Ballistic Missile Defense Organization (BMDO) is
still at an early stage in its program of 19 tests. But the
experiment was a politically sensitive one on both sides of the
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   President Bill Clinton has said its outcome will help him to
decide whether to launch an anti-missile program before his
presidency ends. If he does so, that would have momentous
diplomatic consequences. In particular it might mean breaking out
of the Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty, which the Russians and
Chinese hold dear.
</P>
<P>
   From this perspective, you might have imagined that the failure
would be greeted with relief by the Clinton administration. In
fact, the test weakens its diplomatic leverage with the Russians _
and reduces the chances that they will accept America's proposed
amendments to the ABM treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, Clinton and, particularly, Al Gore will remain exposed to
Republican allegations that the administration has not pursued
anti-missile defenses with sufficient zeal.
</P>
<P>
   Military analysts are asking questions not just about the
competence of the BMDO and its contractors, but about the concept
itself. Richard Garwin, a missile-defense expert, thinks the test
adds weight to the view that the missiles should be intercepted
soon after they are launched, not in space.
</P>
<P>
   You don't want the chicken to get too far off the ground. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1302EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
