r k BC-NIPS'N'BUCKS-AMERICA-     07-18 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIPS'N'BUCKS-AMERICA-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USA: LIFE, LIBERTY AND THE PURSUIT OF COSMETIC SURGERY  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 500-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   CHICAGO _ One way to test the buoyancy of Nasdaq is to observe
the blouses and trousers of America. With their investment accounts
swelling, Americans have been laying out more money than ever for
tucks, lifts, implants, peels, injections and assorted
``augmentations.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the American Society of Plastic Surgeons (ASPS),
the number of cosmetic surgical procedures grew almost as quickly
as the Dow _ from 413,000 in 1992 to over 1 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Procedures are within the grasp of everyday folks,'' says Dr.
Lin Puckett, a practitioner who is also the ASPS's president.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, given the complaints about the bubble economy, the
most common body upgrade is liposuction, a surgical procedure in
which fat is suctioned from beneath the skin with a vacuum machine.
Doctors performed over 170,000 liposuction procedures in 1998, more
than three times as many as in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Bigger breasts are also in demand now that safer saline implants
have replaced silicone. The number of breast-augmentation surgeries
increased 306 percent between 1992 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   After these, the most common procedures are eyelid surgery (up
102 percent over the same period), facelifts (up 77 percent), and
chemical peels (up 246 percent).
</P>
<P>
   No part of the body is beyond improvement. There are buttock
lifts, chin augmentations, anti-wrinkle injections and even cheek
implants.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are women the only ones seeking technological assistance.
Men account for roughly 10 percent of all cosmetic procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Such vanity is not risk-free. The husband of a prominent Chicago
socialite died earlier this year after cosmetic facial surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration has just approved saline breast
implants for continued use, but it notes that the devices have a
high failure rate; roughly one in six women require a second
surgical procedure within three years of receiving the implants.
</P>
<P>
   Such surgery is not covered by health insurance. The average
breast augmentation costs over $3,000; a buttock lift is slightly
more. Liposuction fees average $1,900 per ``site.''
</P>
<P>
   The work is lucrative for doctors; since patients pay up front,
there is no haggling with HMOs over paperwork or reimbursement
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Plastic surgeons have traditionally done America's
body-sculpting, but dermatologists, ophthalmologists and other
doctors are expanding their cosmetic offerings and advertising
aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet teems with proselytizers for neat buns, boobs and
chins. People are bombarded by radio advertisements that begin, ``I
used to be self-conscious about my appearance...''
</P>
<P>
   The until-recently booming stock market is not the only reason
for all this nipping and tucking. Another factor is the demographic
bulge. The baby-boomers are reaching the age where assorted body
parts are feeling (and worse, showing) the effects of time and
gravity.
</P>
<P>
   One of the largest segments of the market is ``facial
rejuvenation.'' The typical patient, says Dr. Puckett, is from
``married middle-class America.''
</P>
<P>
   The urge to flirt with eternal youth for such folk is strong.
But can it survive another plunge in the Nasdaq? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
