<HEADLINE>
QUIPS, QUIRKS AND QUOTES FROM THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Political, Humor Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 425-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   &UR; WISH OF THE WEEK (1): &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to be a better dancer.'' (Al Gore, Washington Post,
July 6) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WISH OF THE WEEK (2): &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish reporters would ask me more about what's in my head and
less about what's between my legs.'' (Karen Kerin, the first openly
transgender candidate for Congress, who is running against Bernie
Sanders in Vermont, Newsweek, July 17) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SNACK OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's a candidate or a cookie, aesthetic appeal and
trustworthiness of ingredients are paramount.'' (America Chews, a
cookie company selling shortbread images of Al Gore and George W.
Bush, reporting that Bush cookies are outselling Gore's by 2 to 1,
Los Angeles Times, July 9) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BLUSH-MAKERS OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   On July 10, a Salon.com quiz about the presidential candidates
included a reminder that, as a congressional candidate in 1978,
George W. Bush opposed the Equal-Rights Amendment (granting equal
rights to women) and claimed to have done active duty in the armed
forces; and Gore, in 1976, opposed gun control and called
homosexuality ``abnormal.'' (Salon.com, July 10) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PIGGY BANK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' House campaign committee had $37.4 million in
hand at the end of June _ seven times as much as they had in 1996
and $15.2 million more than the House Republicans, who have a
slender six-seat majority. (Federal Election Commission) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PARTY ON: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In the space of one week in August, Los Angeles will host seven
separate political get-togethers. The Democratic Party and the
Reform Party are the most conventional (so to speak). Among the
unconventional are the People's Convention (a gathering of
progressive groups), the Mothers' Convention (welfare reform), the
North American Anarchist Conference (anarchy), the Shadow
Convention (satire and celebrities), the Youth Convention and the
Homeless Convention (no hotel rooms left). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BLAH OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Renewing America's purpose. Together.'' (Republican National
Convention 2000) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANGEL CHILD (1): &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to be in this interview if you're going to
start talking like that. George will call and he'll be furious.''
(Former President George Bush, chiding his wife, Barbara, for
criticizing Gore, New York Times, July 8) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANGEL CHILD (2): &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard my peers written off by the pundits as a generation
too involved with itself to be bothered with public life. I take
this charge personally.'' (Karenna Gore Schiff, 26, who is helping
her father's campaign, Newsweek, July 17) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
