<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 13:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5496 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-PRI-EXTINCT?-MEXICO-E     07-18 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRI-EXTINCT?-MEXICO-ECONOMIST-750&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S ONCE-RULING PARTY FACES SHOCK OF OPPOSITION  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (NOTE: Story can stand in 750 words; 1,125 uncut)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (NOTE: THIS STORY CAN STAND ALONE IN 750 WORDS; TOTAL UNCUT IS
1,125.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ ``Would you mind opening the boot (trunk)?'' The
guards at the vehicle entrance to the massive, ugly complex of
offices that are the headquarters of the Institutional
Revolutionary Party (PRI) were never especially security-conscious.
But after the party's historic defeat at the hands of Vicente Fox
in the presidential election on July 2, they have become so.
</P>
<P>
   Not because they worry about what visitors may bring into the
PRI's offices. Rather, they are making sure that nobody takes
anything away. The risk of staff sneaking off with office
equipment, however, is the most trivial of the PRI's problems.
</P>
<P>
   After ruling Mexico since 1929, the party faces an unprecedented
task: it must not only find new leaders, but a new identity and
methods to sustain it in opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Since the PRI will retain a big presence in Congress and state
government, its ability _ or failure _ to reinvent itself will be
important to the stability of Fox's Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The new president will not be sworn in until Dec. 1. But already
the battle over the PRI's future has broken out.
</P>
<P>
   The party's disconcerted state was summed up last week when
Dulce Maria Sauri, the PRI's chairwoman, and other party officials
offered to resign, only to backtrack hours later.
</P>
<P>
   For several days, the PRI's traditional facade of public unity
has been punctured by open sniping and squabbling. Many of the
PRI's lower ranks blame their defeat on President Ernesto Zedillo.
Others point the finger at their uninspiring presidential
candidate, Francisco Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the PRI's ills lie deeply in its political genes. Born
as the National Revolutionary Party, it was an attempt to provide
stability by uniting under a single banner hundreds of factions,
interest groups and small political parties thrown up by Mexico's
1910-17 revolution.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, and for many years, it was extraordinarily
successful. Yet its traditional strengths have become weaknesses:
the division between party and state was blurred and the PRI had no
clear ideology save that of power.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did each president impose his own policies on the PRI,
but he acted as the party's supreme arbiter, choosing its top
officials, while balancing and holding together an elaborate web of
interests to ensure the system's perpetuity.
</P>
<P>
   So the first problem the PRI must confront is the vacuum created
by its loss of the presidency. But that is likely to overlap with
the policy battle.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo and his two predecessors each pursued broadly liberal
economic policies which challenged corporatist traditions, and hurt
interest-groups such as labor and farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI's most obvious divide is between the ``technocrats'' who
came to dominate central government, and the traditionalist
``dinosaurs,'' who include many state governors. Labastida is in
fact an intermediate figure between the two groups.
</P>
<P>
   But defeat tars with a broad brush. Labastida and his campaign
team, who included a few ``dinosaurs,'' as well as Zedillo and his
cabinet, are now equally discredited.
</P>
<P>
   And defeat has tarnished Zedillo's ``neo-liberal'' policies too.
These gave Mexico macroeconomic stability and new growth, but
increased the rich-poor gap and landed taxpayers with an expensive
bank bailout.
</P>
<P>
   A more reflective analysis would note that the PRI was defeated
from its right, not its left, and that Fox might turn out to be as
``neo-liberal'' as Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   But the PRI's mood is rebellious. ``Many people are angry with
Zedillo and have stopped obeying him,'' says Ernesto Ramirez, a
young civil servant who has spent 14 years as a PRI activist, and
calls himself a ``babysaur.''
</P>
<P>
   If the dinosaurs are now in a strong position, it is partly
because without the presidency the PRI's most powerful officials
will be its state governors and the bosses of the big pro-PRI trade
unions, such as those of the oil workers, telephone workers,
electricians and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even more important, to get all the PRI's factions to
support Labastida's campaign, many old-timers were offered places
on the party's congressional lists.
</P>
<P>
   Though he lost, they did not: the PRI will no longer have an
absolute majority in the Senate, but it will still be the largest
single party in both houses of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   That could make it hard for Fox to cut the deals he will need in
the legislature, if the PRI stays united. Will it? The first test
will come in internal elections, to be held probably in November. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 750, OR CONTINUE TO 1,125) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At a meeting with Zedillo on July 11, the PRI's state governors
agreed that Sauri should stay on as party chairman to prepare these
elections _ but with an advisory committee of the party's former
chairmen to help her.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the rest of the PRI's executive resigned the next day.
</P>
<P>
   A dissident group of seven state governors, led by Roberto
Madrazo from the southeastern state of Tabasco, want a new election
for the PRI's 300-member national council, and not just for the
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo is tipped by some as the PRI's likely new leader. He was
Labastida's main challenger in last year's primary for the PRI's
presidential candidacy, which brought him national prominence and a
campaign network.
</P>
<P>
   Activists such as Ramirez are already being invited to meetings
organized to push his bid for the leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of Madrazo at the helm worries many. Though he is
relatively young and talks of modernizing and democratizing the
party, his record speaks of a return to the old methods: his
election to the governorship in 1994 was so dogged by accusations
of overspending that Zedillo tried, but failed, to make him step
down.
</P>
<P>
   But in October Madrazo's own state elects a new governor. Should
the PRI lose, as it may, his credibility will suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins the PRI leadership will have to try to keep the
party together while working out a new set of policies, and seeking
new sources of funds. Without the patronage of central government,
and the largesse that flowed from it, many supporters may drift
away.
</P>
<P>
   Having relied in the past on the vote in rural areas, the party
has to make a special effort to attract young and middle-class
voters _ not something the dinosaurs are obviously well-placed to
do.
</P>
<P>
   More important than any new ideology, therefore, could be the
party's performance where it still has power.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it can't achieve good government at the municipal and state
level, it doesn't have a future,'' says Javier Trevino, a former
adviser to Labastida. ``That's what the old-timers don't want to
see.'' But that also gives Fox some leverage with which to gain
legislative allies. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
