<HEADER>
A5499 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-JAILS-ITALY-ECONOMIST     07-18 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAILS-ITALY-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALY'S `GENETICALLY MUTATING' PRISON POPULATION  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 450-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   MILAN _ ``The prison population has been genetically mutating,''
says Giancarlo Caselli, the man in charge of keeping Italy's
criminals behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   He is not referring to some scientific experiment under way in
such prisons as Milan's San Vittore or Rome's Regina Coeli, but to
changes in the social and criminal make-up within the country's 257
jails.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, nearly all inmates were Italian, and the range of
their crimes was wide. Today, out of 52,000 inside, 14,000 are
foreigners. One-third are there because of drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Caselli is one of many who would like an amnesty; otherwise, he
fears, tensions may snap. It would be the 20th big release since
1947.
</P>
<P>
   Most people who support the current, rather shaky, coalition
government of the center-left broadly favor the idea of a new
amnesty; so does the Catholic church.
</P>
<P>
   When Pope John Paul visited Regina Coeli on July 9, he appealed
_ to the cheers of inmates _ for ``a gesture of clemency.'' A week
before, in the hope of hastening their release, prisoners in
several jails had rioted. Disturbances have been reported in as
many as 52 Italian prisons in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The government has dithered, while making several proposals _
for new prisons, for more magistrates to make the wheels of justice
turn faster, for foreign criminals to be kicked out of Italy.
</P>
<P>
   But ministers are wary of suggesting another amnesty, because
the opinion polls suggest that six out of ten Italians are against
the idea.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition, which is riding high, is not keen to help the
government out. Amnesties must be approved by a majority of
two-thirds in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Still, almost everyone agrees that something must be done. Italy
does not have a particularly large prison population, compared with
other countries, but its prisons are old and overcrowded.
</P>
<P>
   They are supposed to hold up to 43,000 people _ 9,000 fewer than
now. San Vittore, which has 1,800 inmates, is designed for 800;
half its inmates are foreign.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, an amnesty would be only a stopgap. Judicial
sloth, unless special steps are taken, will continue to be a major
offender.
</P>
<P>
   Half of Italy's inmates are on remand, waiting to be tried. In
Naples alone, some 578,000 cases are pending. Of the 9 million or
so new cases that crop up every year, many are minor and should not
carry a jail sentence. Judges lack proper staff and computers.
</P>
<P>
   The whole process is so lengthy that more genuine villains now
get off by statute of limitation; almost all sentences of less than
two years are automatically suspended. In that sense, an informal
amnesty is taking place already. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1303EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
