r e BC-TV-NEW-SHOWS-HNS &LR;      07-18 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NEW-SHOWS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     OLD TV SEASON WASN'T SO BAD AFTER ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ After the networks spent a year freaking out
_ first over the surprise success of ``Who Wants to Be
Millionaire,'' then the ``Survivor'' reality phenomenon _ they
neglected to take care of one teeny, bottom-of-the-pile task:
developing a really good show for next year.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from what has been seen so far at the gathering of the
nation's television critics _ and it could change before the fall
debuts _ there are no new shows worth getting jazzed about. Indeed,
the 2000-2001 television season (which won't start in earnest until
October, because of the Summer Olympics) only makes us appreciate
the quality of last fall's slate.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, there were close to a half-dozen new shows to get
excited about. ``Action,'' ``Freaks and Geeks,'' ``Now and Again''
were three very good pilots that didn't even make it to a second
season. (No, I didn't forget about all the other garbage that came
out last year.)
</P>
<P>
   This year, after mining and extrapolating and heaping globs of
wishful thinking, the best you can come up with is two or three.
</P>
<P>
   Most of NBC's fall lineup appears to be a disaster waiting to
happen. The pilot for the new sitcom from Michael Richards (Kramer
on ``Seinfeld'') was reportedly so bad that it was never allowed
within an area code of critics. ``Ed'' (facing tough competition on
Sunday night) appears solid, and the newspaper drama ``Deadline''
is an unknown quantity because the pilot has yet to be released,
but the rest of the new schedule is so weak, officials better
introduce a new slogan: ``We Were No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC has only four new shows to roll out; Regis Philbin,
apparently, can handle the other 19.5 hours of prime time.
``Gideon's Crossing,'' thanks to the presence of Andre Braugher and
Ruben Blades, exudes potential. Geena Davis' sitcom, cleverly
titled ``Geena,'' does not and wouldn't, even if you added Lucille
Ball, Jerry Seinfeld, Sid Caesar and Carol Burnett to the cast.
</P>
<P>
   And ``The Trouble With Normal''? Well, let me save for another
day my rant on that piece of ... art.
</P>
<P>
   CBS's dramas look slick, but nothing jumps out as a must-see,
although ``Bette,'' from Bette Midler, has some very amusing
moments.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Fox, still trying to find a successor for ``The
X-Files'' even as it desperately holds on to its dramatic flagship;
its slate of dark dramas makes the movie ``Seven'' look like a
knee-slapping farce. One important caveat here: Critics have yet to
see Fox's David E. Kelley teaching drama ``Boston Public.''
</P>
<P>
   The WB has yet to present a must-see pilot, although the
behind-the-scenes spoof ``Grosse Point'' has a chance to be a funny
send-up of ``Beverly Hills 90210.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, UPN has ``Freedom,'' a drama set in a future America
ruled by a military dictatorship; it should be the top-ranked show
in secluded compounds across northern Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for the warnings: Pilots can be tinkered, retooled,
refurbished, recast and reshot before airing, and sometimes shows
develop into something much stronger than the initial episodes
suggest.
</P>
<P>
   Another important point: Television critics, individually and
collectively, sometimes make bad calls on shows. If you went back a
few years, I'll bet no more than a few out of the 200 in attendance
thought ``Providence'' would be a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, let's not forget that we still have some broadcast
heavyweights returning: ``The Simpsons,'' ``ER,'' ``Frasier,''
``The Practice,'' ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' and ``Friends,'' as
well as new classics from last season like ``The West Wing'' and
``Malcolm in the Middle.''
</P>
<P>
   All is not lost.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not all that much to get excited about.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
