<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORAL-FROGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FROGS GIVE FLORAL DISPLAYS A LIFT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Many floral design specialists will tell you that
the frog is the secret of floral arranging.
</P>
<P>
   To a horticulturalist, the word frog conjures the image of a
tool that supports the stems of flowers and keeps them in a desired
shape.
</P>
<P>
   They can be made from glass, china, concrete, pottery, ceramic,
metal or wire that provides support and stability.
</P>
<P>
   Customarily, dark frogs are used in dark vases and clear or
light colored ones in light vases, so that they seem to disappear
in water.
</P>
<P>
   Floral frogs are also known by other names, such as a flower
brick, holder, block or arranger. Kenzan is the Japanese word for
flower arranging frogs (or pins).
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being functional, frogs have also become very
collectible.
</P>
<P>
   Some people collect artistic figural frogs, which are shaped
like animals or have a statue rising out of the center. Bathing
beauty flower frogs (of women in swimsuits) were made in Germany in
the 1920s. English Glass frogs produced in the 1920s and '30s were
Britain's answer to American Depression Glass.
</P>
<P>
   Some frogs may also be used as candleholders, paperweights or
purely as a display collection.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, commercial florists switched from floral frogs,
which date to the 14th century, to water absorbing single-use foam
blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Other options for anchoring a cut arrangement are clear or
colored marbles, small pebbles, florists' tape crisscrossed across
the top of the container to form a grid, or a supple twig, curled
and forced into the vase. A piece of crumpled chicken wire tucked
into the vase or taped across the top will also do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Frogs made by glass manufacturers may cost hundreds of dollars
today, but the average price for a new glass, metal or wire frog
ranges from $3 for a small round plain needle frog to $30 or more.
Frogs made between 1910 and '40 are currently very collectible.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity-owned frogs may often cost more, as in the case of
those owned by the late Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis. Her floral
frogs and a couple of metal containers sold at auction for $4,025
in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
