<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5523 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-KIDS-BAND-HNS &LR;      07-18 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-BAND-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     YOUNG MUSICAL SENSATIONS INK SEVEN-ALBUM CONTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Note optional trim)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MIKE HESS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE GEORGE, N.Y. _ Dylan Wilcox and sister Chelsea stood 30
feet from a busy, jungle-gym-equipped playground at Shepard Park
last week as climbing, rambunctious children filled the air with
cheers of happiness.
</P>
<P>
   Dylan, 12, and Chelsea, 14, went to Shepard Park to play, too _
but in a different sense of the word. The siblings, who live in
White Creek, N.Y., are the principal members of the band GreayStar,
which recently signed a seven-album deal with Epic Records.
</P>
<P>
   Chelsea, the lead vocalist, has the stage presence of an angry
Gwen Stefani, and Dylan is a guitar phenom. While comparisons to
Jimi Hendrix are still a stretch, Dylan already has skills that
many 20- or 30-year-olds only dream about.
</P>
<P>
   During GreayStar's two-hour set in Shepard Park in this upstate
New York village, the band rocked the perpetually growing crowd
with hard-driving, post-punk tunes, all of them originals. At the
beginning of the performance, most of those in the park carried on
with typical summertime activities, more interested in their ice
cream and the day's last rays than some unknown local band. But by
the end of the night a parkful of GreayStar converts buzzed about
Dylan's scorching guitar licks.
</P>
<P>
   Their father and band manager, Jay Wilcox, has been involved in
music all of his life, and is amazed at Dylan's abilities. ``Just
imagine what he'll be able to do when he's 16!''
</P>
<P>
   Dylan started playing the guitar at age 6 but had been watching
his father play and clapping along since he was 2.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilcox children were noticed by Randy Cantor, a music
producer who worked on Ricky Martin's ``Livin' La Vida Loca,'' when
they played at the Philadelphia Music Conference in January. Cantor
was at the conference to discuss Latin music, but his priorities
quickly shifted. Like many in attendance, Jay Wilcox said, Cantor
was impressed by the talent of the Wilcox kids _ so much so that he
immediately called Peter Robinson, Epic Records' senior vice
president of A&AMP;R (artist and repertoire).
</P>
<P>
   ``They both have a lot of potential,'' Robinson said of the
Wilcoxes, adding, ``Dylan is a very musical young guy. He has a
great feel for music.''
</P>
<P>
   Known for signing The Dave Matthews Band while working for RCA
Records, Robinson spoke with the band after the Philadelphia show,
and set up an appointment to travel to their home _ a nearly
four-hour trip from his Manhattan office _ in early February. Wowed
by that living-room performance, Robinson took GreayStar to an
audition for Epic bigwigs on Valentine's Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilcox kids again impressed seen-it-all record executives,
Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   During the audition, Dylan showed his musical savvy by
improvising in the middle of a song he'd never before played.
``He's always changing music as he goes along,'' said his father.
``Nobody knows it except for a few of us, but he just makes up a
lot along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Wilcoxes now live in White Creek, where they have an
in-house studio in which they practice for up to four hours a day.
Jay Wilcox writes most of the lyrics, and works with Dylan on
composing the guitar and rhythm elements of GreayStar's songs.
</P>
<P>
   The band's drummer, 17-year-old Nick Callonnec, is awed by
Dylan's tremendous knowledge and talent. ``He blows my mind away,''
said Callonnec. ``He's 12 years old, and playing lead guitar!''
</P>
<P>
   Callonnec was connected to GreayStar by his father, Roger
Callonnec, who became Dylan's guitar teacher after Jay Wilcox could
no longer keep up with the boy. Roger Callonnec occasionally fills
in on bass guitar with the band, when regular bass player Kevin
Martindale is unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   Dylan was surrounded by music his whole life, having been
influenced by his father's '70s favorites, but it wasn't until
hearing one popular '90s punk band that he was inspired to make
music his main priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once Green Day started, Dylan's life changed,'' Jay Wilcox
said. Dylan's other influences range from Hendrix to Tom Morello of
Rage Against The Machine.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Wilcox has said the contract with Epic is in the
mid-five-figure range, but he declined to discuss it in detail.
Like most contracts today, the seven albums are not guaranteed.
Instead, the deal allows Epic the option to pursue more recordings
if the company believes the Wilcoxes have hit potential.
</P>
<P>
   This summer will be used for development of Dylan and Chelsea as
performers (the contract covers only them, not the rest of
GreayStar's members). The two spend the beginning of each week
rehearsing and recording in New York City with studio musicians
chosen for them by Epic. Robinson said he hopes the band, which is
also working on a video, will have four singles done by September.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the first set in Shepard Park, Dylan played so
ferociously that his guitar strap (which covers nearly his entire
back with its width) came off, and he almost dropped the
instrument.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you see how I caught the guitar?'' he said excitedly.
``That was awesome!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
