<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5525 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-DICTIONARY-SLANG-HNS &LR;      07-18 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DICTIONARY-SLANG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WANT TO BE A HIP? EDGY DICTIONARY OFFERS COOL CANDY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Note optional trim)  
 &HT;     (With DICTIONARY-SLANG-WORDS)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KRISTEN MACK  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Slang is increasingly becoming part of common language. It is
unavoidable, whether on television or out of the mouths of teens.
In the 2000 edition of the Random House Webster's College
Dictionary, released this week, there are 303 new words appearing
for the first time among the 200,000-plus definitions.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the new words come from slang. Among them war:
my bad! (my mistake) 24/7 (continually, constantly) and candy
(someone or something that is excellent, pleasing or pleasurable).
How long they will be current is another question.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is always hard to know what the staying power of slang
is,'' said George Aaron Broadwell, director of the program in
linguistics and cognitive science at the State University of New
York at Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Lexicographers, the people who put the dictionary together, have
to balance the needs of several different audiences. One audience
consists of linguists and non-native speakers of English.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two groups will want a source that faithfully documents
every word that is commonly in use in spoken English, regardless of
whether the word is `proper' or not,'' Broadwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Someone learning English needs to be able to find ``arm candy''
in the dictionary, because he or she won't be able to figure it out
otherwise, according to Broadwell.
</P>
<P>
   But lexicographers must also consider the audience of people who
are concerned with the correct usage of English. They tend to
regard the fact that a word is in the dictionary as evidence that
it is in fact a correct and accepted part of the language.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two groups come into conflict with new words and slang
where it may take a commonly used word some time before it becomes
accepted or regarded as correct,'' Broadwell said. ``Some words and
phrases have been around for decades, while others seem to last
only a few months.''
</P>
<P>
   In the vernacular, there is recent evidence of slang being
overused to the point of saturation, bordering on lame. So if you
have used the phrases ``you go, girl,'' or ``talk to the hand ...''
frequently in the last year, you may want to stop. Don't mean to
dis, but it's wack. Even though both of those words have made it
into the dictionary, if you want to be considered up-to-date,
refrain now from using them.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are those words that surpass trendiness and
come into common usage, like chill, cool or awesome.
</P>
<P>
   But for every word that makes it, there are probably two that
never quite stick. For instance, in 1997, Random House added
Macarena, a then-popular dance craze and song, to the dictionary.
But it faded, and didn't have the perennial appeal of say, the
tango, so it was taken out in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   No word is written in stone. If it's dying out or played out, it
can be easily snatched out from a dictionary. Just as easily
though, it can be put back in. Capris and cargo pants were recently
re-inserted because they have come back into fashion.
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes a word will have been around for decades before it
makes it into the dictionary. The word Ebonics, or black English,
has around for about 30 years, but just made it in the dictionary a
couple years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The dating of a word is difficult, according to Carol Braham,
the Random House senior editor in charge of the day-to-day
development of the dictionary. Braham searches on-line databases
and old slang dictionaries to find the history of a word.
</P>
<P>
   When adding words, Random House studies semantics and
morphology, and how words change in meaning and form over time.
</P>
<P>
   Take the word bad. Michael Jackson released an album titled,
``Bad'' (Epic), in 1987. Starting then, we began to take the word
less literally. And, in 1989, LL Cool J coined the phrase, ``Not
bad meaning bad, but bad meaning good,'' in his song, ``I'm Bad''
(Def Jam).
</P>
<P>
   Edgy, which most of us think of as nervous and jittery, has a
new definition this year, referring to something that's innovative
and cutting edge.
</P>
<P>
   Dis is a shortened form of the word disrespect. Dis came into
usage between 1980 and 1985 _ for most entries Random House
includes the dates, parenthetically. Words such as typewrite,
lifestyle and roundtrip started off as two words, and then became
hyphenated, before eventually evolving into one word. It's the
natural process of word formation, according to Braham.
</P>
<P>
   Jiggy, which means ``wonderful and exciting, especially because
stylish,'' made it into the dictionary this year after its frequent
rotation on radios across America in Will Smith's song, ``Gettin'
Jiggy Wit It'' (Sony).
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't make it up, but he popularized it,'' Braham said.
</P>
<P>
   In general, a lexicographer will want some evidence that a word
is being widely used, and it is not just the jargon of some
restricted group. Evidence might include use in national
publications, frequency of use on the Internet, in songs,
advertisements or conversations. Random House contends that new
words can come from wherever language happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our editors are always scanning these sources, and many people
also send us new words or meanings in the mail,'' said Wendalyn
Nichols, the editorial director of Random House Reference.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New technology and slang are the biggest sources of new words.
Each year, Braham creates a list of words for inclusion, along with
their citations. She searches files, databases and the Internet to
determine how frequently words are used, their range of uses, and
even their variant spellings.
</P>
<P>
   In any given year, more than 1,000 new words are considered for
placement in the dictionary. Words with staying power are the most
likely to succeed. The number of words that make it in varies each
year. In the latest edition, there are the 303 new entries
definitions of old words.
</P>
<P>
   A dictionary is a living record of language, it's not static,
according to Braham, who said that words are not invented in the
dictionary, just recorded.
</P>
<P>
   While Broadwell says lexicographers are making a judgment call
and probably err on the side of including most words, Braham says
neither she nor the rest of the selection committee is making an
ethical decision when putting words in the dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't make a judgment as to whether it's nice or has any
good value or is even correct,'' Braham said. ``If it's used and
used widely, then I put it in.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the terms Driving While Black and racial profiling
were included in the dictionary. Braham said they were added
because they have been in the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing that we're making up,'' Braham said. ``We don't
create the language, we just record it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
