r l BC-DICTIONARY-SLANG-WORD     07-18 0164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DICTIONARY-SLANG-WORDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PEEPS ARE THIRSTY TO FLOSS BLING-BLING ICE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (With: DICTIONARY-SLANG)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A glossary of new slang, with some words and definitions that
haven't made it into dictionaries just yet:
</P>
<P>
   Ball _ (derived from ballplayer) to be successful
</P>
<P>
   (Be) Easy _ see you later
</P>
<P>
   Bling-bling _ anything that's new or shiny
</P>
<P>
   Ends _ money
</P>
<P>
   Floss _ to show off or brag about new stuff
</P>
<P>
   Hater _ someone who is covetous of your belongings or lifestyle
</P>
<P>
   Ice _ diamonds set in platinum
</P>
<P>
   Jump-off or pop-off _ starting time for a party or other event
</P>
<P>
   Mad _ anything to its extreme
</P>
<P>
   Peeps _ abbreviation of people, in reference to close friends
and family
</P>
<P>
   Thirsty _ to really want something
</P>
<P>
   Tight _ something nice, or to be broke
</P>
<P>
   To death _ anything to its extreme; e.g., ``That shirt is tight
to death.'' (see ``mad'')
</P>
<P>
   Whip _ car
</P>
</TEXT>
