<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-HILLARY-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY IS NOT AN ANTI-SEMITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tuesday, July 18, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's ROEPER COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the ROEPER COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can say a lot of things about Hillary Clinton, but the
allegations that she's anti-Semitic sound like a big crock of
rotten politics to me.
</P>
<P>
   That said, I find her denial hard to fathom.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, ``State of a Union: Inside the Complex Marriage of
Bill and Hillary Clinton'' by former National Enquirer scribe Jerry
Oppenheimer, will land on bookstore shelves with the resounding
thud of an ``event book'' _ a publication that has the media
chirping in advance. In this case it's because of a report Matt
Drudge (Matt!) that was picked up by everyone: the claim that in
1974, Mrs. Clinton called one of her husband's campaign aides a
``f------ Jew bastard'' on the night Clinton lost a congressional
race.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Mrs. Clinton was calling a news conference to deny the
report and her husband was phoning the New York Daily News from the
Camp David Middle East peace summit to say his wife has ``never,
ever uttered an ethnic or racial slur against anybody, ever,'' the
gecko-like Dick Morris was offering his own unique brand of slimy
innuendo on Fox News.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Hillary is an anti-Semite, but I do think she
has, in my dealings with her, she's always had a consciousness that
she's talking to somebody who's Jewish,'' said Morris, who went on
to tell anecdotes about Mrs. Clinton supposedly making jokes to him
about eating pork and saying things like, ``Money, that's all you
people care about is money.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. It's always difficult to believe someone who has just
crawled out from under a rock in order to appear on a cable news
channel.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to say for sure whether Hillary Clinton spat out
an anti-Semitic insult more than a quarter-century ago, unless we
hear from some Nixon-inspired operator who was lingering nearby
with a tape recorder, but I choose to believe her word over the
claim of the book's author, a former National Enquirer reporter _
especially in light of the fact that the putative target of Mrs.
Clinton's ire is not Jewish. (His paternal grandmother was Jewish.)
</P>
<P>
   But in issuing her denial, Mrs. Clinton made some claims that I
find even more unfathomable than the allegations against her.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, I may have called someone a name, but I have
never used ethnic, racial, anti-Semitic, bigoted, discriminatory,
prejudiced accusations against anybody,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never done it. I've never thought it.''
</P>
<P>
   Never thought it? Wow. I always figured that even the likes of
Gandhi and Mother Teresa had their moments of internal weakness in
which they experienced prejudiced thoughts, even as they were
performing heroic feats of almost incomprehensible self-sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Hillary Clinton says she's never uttered a bigoted
statement, never thought an prejudiced thought.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about the senate, she oughta be campaigning for
sainthood.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of New York politicians _ and sorry for that mild
whiplash of a segue _ I just came across a surprising appearance by
moral crusader Rudy Giuliani in the latest issue of a steamy,
boundary-stretching publication.
</P>
<P>
   A grinning Giuliani is interviewed in the ``Back to School''
edition of A&AMP;F quarterly, the pseudo-catalog from Abercrombie &AMP;
Fitch that is so risque it costs $6 an issue and is delivered in
kid-discouraging shrink wrap.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy G. even allowed himself to be photographed at City Hall for
the piece, wearing an A&AMP;F hat.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the revelation that Giuliani used to go out in New
York in a disguise of sunglasses or a hat but would be recognized
anyway, there's nothing terribly eyebrow-raising about the cheeky
Q-and-A _ other than its very presence in the catalog.
</P>
<P>
   After all, this is the same Mayor Giuliani who has fought to
have ``objectionable'' art removed from city museums, who has
cleaned up Times Square, who has crusaded against Calvin Klein's
provocative billboards. And now he shows up just a few pages away
from these images:
</P>
<P>
   _ A group of young people in Rudy's beloved Times Square,
including four young men wearing boxers, their pants around their
ankles.
</P>
<P>
   _ A preppie-looking gal stuffing dollar bills into the G-strong
of a tattoeed, male exotic dancer.
</P>
<P>
   _ A gay couple sharing a fond moment in a dorm room.
</P>
<P>
   _ Young men frolicking in a fountain, the way young men will do
when they're frolicking in a fountain. One such muffin has his
pants around his knees, revealing his bare behind.
</P>
<P>
   Nice to know Giuliani has become so ... tolerant.
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the co-host of ``Ebert &AMP; Roeper &AMP; the
Movies.'')
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
