<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5542 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-WHAT-LIES-PREVIEW-LAD     07-18 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHAT-LIES-PREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL `WHAT LIES BENEATH' THRILL AUDIENCES?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use after July 21, 2000, by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
You've probably seen either the commercial or trailer for ``What
Lies Beneath.'' Michelle Pfeiffer, wearing a slinky red dress,
straddles Harrison Ford, telling him breathlessly, ``I think she's
starting to suspect something.'' Ford, befuddled, asks, ``Who?''
Pfeiffer, throaty: ``Your (ITAL)wife(END ITAL).''
</P>
<P>
   Great moment. The only problem is that _ like so many movie
trailers today _ the spot spoils a major plot point in the film.
Namely: Harrison Ford's character has had an affair with a woman
who's now haunting his house and, during this particular scene,
inhabiting the body of his wife, played by Pfeiffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``To do our art we need people to go see our movies,'' explains
the film's director Robert Zemeckis, a man who knows a thing or two
about box-office hits with ``Forrest Gump'' and the ``Back to the
Future'' movies on his resume.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a perfect world, you wouldn't have to show a scene like
that in the trailer. But that's not the world we live in. I equate
it to McDonald's. People go to the movies, and they like to know
exactly what they're going to see before they see it. Nobody wants
to be surprised anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   And that puts Zemeckis at cross purposes with his audience since
``What Lies Beneath'' is a psychological thriller that aims to keep
its audience guessing through numerous plot twists, red herrings
and misdirections. Ford and Pfeiffer play a long-married couple
whose lives begin to unravel after her daughter (by a previous
marriage) goes off to college. A not-so-friendly ghost has taken up
residence in their New England home, and it's soon clear that the
spirit is a scorned woman from Ford's past. Spookiness ensues.
</P>
<P>
   Producer Jack Rapke calls the film the type of movie Alfred
Hitchcock would make if he had access to modern technology;
co-producer and frequent Zemeckis collaborator Steve Starkey
welcomes any and all comparisons to last summer's breakout mystery
hit ``The Sixth Sense.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Sixth Sense'' didn't tell audiences the significance
of Haley Joel Osment's penchant for seeing dead people. Moviegoers
had to discover it for themselves, a fact that helped fuel the
film's enormous box-office success. The marketing folks at
DreamWorks have already tipped Zemeckis' hand with their campaign
for ``What Lies Beneath.'' Not that the director is complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we gave nothing away, we would run the risk of it looking
like Harrison and Michelle were in some domestic movie,'' Zemeckis
says of the trailer, which he calls a ``beautiful piece of
marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It can't look boring. The trailer has to deliver some of the
movie's promise. Good God, the film is going to be opening in 2,400
theaters or something like that. (Actually, it's closer to 2,700.)
That's a lot of people who are going to have to go see the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   The trailer, Zemeckis adds, is the least of his worries when it
comes to audience expectations. What really bothers Zemeckis is
what lies beneath moviegoers' collective consciousness _ 100 years
of cinema.
</P>
<P>
   ``Audiences today are aware of the conventions of the genre
quite simply because they've seen so many of these movies,''
Zemeckis says. ``They're savvy. So what works best is to
acknowledge the past, put in little winks and nods, and then
contribute what you have to say. And hopefully you can somehow stay
ahead of what the audience is thinking because they're usually 20
minutes ahead of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone familiar (and probably some with only a passing
acquaintance) with Hitchcock's body of work will know what Zemeckis
is thinking while watching ``What Lies Beneath.'' The film moves
from ``Rear Window'' to ``Vertigo'' to ``Psycho'' _ with plenty of
``Suspicion'' thrown in _ before calling it a day with a ``Fatal
Attraction.'' Composer Alan Silvestri's score apes Bernard
Herrmann's work with Hitchcock, making the homage complete.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Zemeckis brings his own trademark blend of
storytelling and special effects into the mix, but with all the
``winks and nods,'' it's difficult sometimes to hear what Zemeckis
has to say, particularly over Silvestri's jolting musical cues.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK,'' Zemeckis says. ``I consider it standing on the
shoulders of giants. Hitchcock wrote the language of this genre.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford, who has said on many occasions that he doesn't like
watching old movies, respectfully disagrees with his director.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never scared by Hitchcock; I never believed his
characters that much,'' Ford says. ``What's scary about this movie
is the reality of the characters and the complexity of their
relationship. And that kind of maturity is refreshing in a climate
where most scary stories involve long knives and ladies that take
showers.''
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer didn't have to take any showers in the movie, but she
does spend an inordinate amount of time in water, which led to some
serious skin wrinkling and occasional bouts of claustrophobia. (``I
certainly was plenty clean for a few days there,'' she jokes.)
</P>
<P>
   The actress appreciates film history a bit more than her
co-star, citing vampire movies, Hitchcock's ``The Birds'' and the
1956 demonic kid flick ``The Bad Seed'' as her early favorites of
the thriller genre.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never made one of these primarily because they stopped
making them for a long time,'' Pfeiffer says. ``The thriller genre
turned into slasher movies. And I'm just not into gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither is Zemeckis, who shot ``What Lies Beneath'' during a
break from making ``Castaway,'' the Tom Hanks survivor movie set
for release this December. (Hanks needed the hiatus to add a beard
and shed some weight.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The really twisted psychological aspects of the genre are
what's most fun,'' Zemeckis says. ``The less you show, the spookier
it is because you leave it all up to the audience's imagination.
And the audience loves that because you're reaching down into the
primitive part of the brain that loves fear and craves that
adrenaline fix.''
</P>
<P>
   All that fearmongering gave Zemeckis an energy boost himself,
particularly on the heels of working on the serious ``Castaway.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like going from realism to opera,'' Zemeckis says. ``I
love thrillers because they're director-heavy. They're all about
technique and style. It's a genre of film that is all film. It's
like a high-performance car. We don't use them for our practical,
everyday driving, but they're cool to take out every now and
again.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
