<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPOS ARE IN EXPERT HANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To the baseball fan(s) in Montreal, he is the gerant. To his
Spanish-speaking players, he is the dirigente. To you, me, and
Lenny Webster, he is the manager.
</P>
<P>
   In all three languages, his authority and stature supercede his
title. Felipe Alou is not just the skipper of the Montreal Expos.
He is the public face of the beleaguered franchise, the man whose
blood, toil, and tears and have flowed through this organization
longer than anyone else in the team's history.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos have been in business for 32 seasons and Felipe Alou
has been a member for 26 of them. He played 19 games for the team
in 1973 and became a coach in 1976. He has been there ever since,
managing 12 years in the minor league system before being elevated
to the head job in 1992 when the brass needed someone to replace
Tom Runnels 37 games into the season.
</P>
<P>
   So that means he is in his eighth full season as the gerant.
That's a long time for anyone to remain in a manager's job in this
turbulent day and age, and it leads us to one inescapable
conclusion: He must know what he's doing.
</P>
<P>
   There are many, in fact, who maintain that there is no gerant,
dirigente, or manager who can touch him and that what he has done
with the Expos during his nearly nine years in charge is just shy
of miraculous. These folks say that the greatest personal
managerial injustice of our time was the 1994 work stoppage,
because that was going to be Felipe's moment. His team was 74-40
when the strike began, and had the postseason begun right then and
there, his Expos would have been the favorites.
</P>
<P>
   No team has suffered more in the wake of that disastrous strike
than the Expos, whose city has turned against them and whose
financial situation has never been the same. How could this
scenario not be frustrating for such a good baseball man?
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to put '94 and 2000 in the same bag,'' he says with a
shrug. ``What can you do? We had a team that, if it wasn't
dismantled in 1994, who would have beaten us in 1995? Instead, we
were in last place the next year with different players.''
</P>
<P>
   The players on that '94 team were good, some of them even on a
par with their manager, which is to say, pretty damn good. For
Felipe Alou, along with Juan Marichal, brother Mateo, Rico Carty,
and, a little later, his brother Jesus, was in the original wave of
Dominican players who have reshaped the landscape of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were always good Dominican players,'' he says, alluding
to such legendary figures as Ventura Escalante, who died in a plane
crash before ever getting a shot at the Bigs.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but the first ones we saw were his group of stars, the
ones who came of age in the late '50s and early '60s. But no one
ever foresaw such a Dominican takeover of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't see that far ahead,'' smiles Alou, who had a
17-year major league career. ``We were just concerned about
ourselves. But I am telling you that talent was there. We won the
Pan-Am Games in Mexico City by defeating the Americans. I will
never forget the score: 10-4.''
</P>
<P>
   Felipe Alou has had a career. He played alongside Willie Mays,
and let's not forget the day San Francisco finished a game with an
All-Alou outfield. He played in a World Series (1962). He hit .300
three times, finishing with a career average of .286. He led the
National League in hits twice and runs once.
</P>
<P>
   But he is proudest of his arm. He signed as a pitcher/outfielder
and he threw the javelin, discus, and hammer in college. He is not
at all shy about saying that he could throw, although he admits
that Vladimir Guerrero's arm is even better.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers the day his winter league manager was fired and he
was asked to take his place because he was the only legit major
leaguer on the team. `` `You're the man,' they said. I said, `Wha?
Me?' '' He was 24 years old.
</P>
<P>
   So that's how it began, this love affair with managing. He has
had ample opportunity to study his craft, having played for, among
others, Bill Rigney, Tom ``Clancy'' Sheehan, Alvin Dark, Bobby
Bragan, Dick Williams, Gene Mauch, Del Crandall, John McNamara, and
Ralph Houk. Repeat: among others.
</P>
<P>
   Bragan made a particular impression on him, and Houk makes two.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were both real good with players,'' he explains. ``I
learned from them that if you're only going to tell a guy half a
truth, don't say anything. I think players appreciate that more
than anything else. And I've learned not to promise anything,
because there's always a boss or two on top of you. You say
something to someone, and two hours later some higher person says
something different.''
</P>
<P>
   Dark and Williams were two more intriguing pieces of managerial
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dark,'' says Felipe, ``was very similar when he was young to
Williams when he was old.''
</P>
<P>
   After 26 years, he most definitely bleeds bleu, blanc, et rouge.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this franchise leaves, I would consider that a setback to
the city of Montreal,'' he says. ``The sad thing is that this is
not something that started last year. No one has been able to stop
this decline that can lead to the loss of the franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   He identifies closely, having married a French-Canadian and
having two children born in the city. He may not speak much French,
but he understands it very well.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd better not say anything in front of me, because I
understand everything,'' he laughs.
</P>
<P>
   He has seen the town rock to the sport he loves, and it
frustrates him that the situation has broken down the way it has.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my 26th year with the franchise,'' he says. ``I've
always kind of wondered why a ballpark was not built. Now it's a
race with the clock. But why wasn't something done 20 years ago? Or
25 years ago?''
</P>
<P>
   His own clock is ticking. He turned 65 in May and it's very
likely that the 1994 team represented his best chance at managing
in a World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't,'' he says, ``I have no complaints. I played in a
World Series. It would only be frustrating to me if I committed a
mistake _ a managerial mistake _ that prevented my team from
getting to the World Series. That would be frustrating. That would
be painful.''
</P>
<P>
   Take this to the savings and loan institution of your choice:
That's a fictional pain he will never have to share. If the Expos
ever again even sniff at a title, it will not be despite this
extraordinary man. It will be because of him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail at
ryan(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
