<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5551 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-SURVIVOR-BOS &LR;      07-18 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURVIVOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SURVIVOR' THEORY ON NET UNDERSCORES POP PHENOMENON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're talking about it at water coolers, debating it on
bulletin boards. They're searching for the answer everywhere _
hacking Web sites, scouring computer code, analyzing television
footage. Everyone wants to be the first to know who will emerge
victorious at the end of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   No, we're not talking about the bid for vice president _ Did
someone say election? We're talking about ``Survivor,'' the CBS
reality program (Wednesday at 8 p.m.) that critics originally
dismissed as the end of Western civilization but that is actually
bringing people together to share a common pop cultural obsession.
Who will survive the rats _ both literal and figurative?
</P>
<P>
   There hasn't been this much popular attention to a TV
cliffhanger since the nation wondered who shot J.R. on ``Dallas''
in 1980 or who killed Laura Palmer on ``Twin Peaks'' in 1990. There
is, of course, nothing new about conspiracy theories and pop
culture. But today, there is one difference to the rampant
speculation about ``Survivor'': It's called the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone stood around the water cooler and speculated about
who shot J.R., and it was intense,'' recalls cultural critic Steven
Stark. ``But with the Internet, the water cooler is a heck of a lot
bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   And today, conspiracy theories run deeper, spread more quickly,
and involve more high-tech espionage. Over the weekend, a Canadian
college student claimed to have discovered the winner of the show
by cracking into files supposedly not available to the public on
the CBS ``Survivor'' Web site (see end of story for details). The
student, Corrie Sloot of Ontario, found image files of the 16
contestants; all of the photos were marked with a red X, except
one. He immediately announced his shocking revelation on the
popular fan site, www.survivorsucks.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in North America always open their Christmas presents
before Christmas,'' Sloot said in an interview by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the show has given CBS a nice little Christmas in
July; last week, almost 25 million people watched the top-ranked
show.
</P>
<P>
   Sloot's announcement set off a wave of further speculation that
the discovery was a red herring planted by CBS. Earlier in the
show's run, one of the contestants who had already been kicked off
the show dropped a hint that the winner was Gretchen Cody, a former
Air Force survival instructor. That theory was nixed last week,
when Cody was voted off the show.
</P>
<P>
   Is the Sloot's discovery just another false clue?
</P>
<P>
   ``CBS will neither confirm nor deny any report about the future
results of `Survivor' and instead will continue letting the press
run inaccurate information,'' said Dana McClintock, vice president
of communications.
</P>
<P>
   Is this a brilliant marketing coup or a dumb mistake by some
unwitting Web designer? CBS isn't talking.
</P>
<P>
   But Paul Sims, the Dallas-based programmer who runs
survivorsucks.com, says he doubts CBS is planting false leads.
``It's like this monster that keeps growing based on a kernel of
truth,'' says Sims, whose site received 250,000 hits last week. (In
an ironic note, Monday Sims was asked to shut down another fan site
for another CBS reality show, ``Big Brother,'' by its producers,
despite the fact that his ``Survivor'' site is feeding a media
frenzy.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, computer security experts say such a mistake breaks
the basic rule of Web design. ``It's common knowledge that you
never put anything out on the Web that you don't need to have out
there, especially with something top secret,'' says Weld Pond, a
research scientist at the Cambridge-based computer security firm,
At Stake.
</P>
<P>
   Some enterprising students at MIT weren't convinced that Sloot's
X theory was legit, so they did some sleuthing and discovered
another series of photographs of all 16 contestants on another
section of the Web site; all 16 were shown with a red X. The kids
at MIT didn't really care about the show until the rumors emerged
about the Web site: ``That kind of thing excites people on this
campus,'' said Satwik Seshasai, chairman of MIT's student newspaper
and one of the students who sought to disprove the rumor.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, you can't buy the kind of publicity ``Survivor'' is
generating. ``If you had 15 minutes to spend, would you prefer
listening to the drab packaged rhetoric of both Gore (and) Bush or
getting a chance to see who's going to win (a million) bucks?''
asks Democratic political consultant Michael Goldman, who expresses
disdain for ``Survivor'' but admits he will probably watch the
final show. ``What do you get with Bush and Gore? It's just blah,
you know?'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In the '70s, we had the Watergate trials, in the '80s we had
``Dallas,'' and now we have a desert isle. And there are some who
say that this particular pop cultural phenomenon isn't necessarily
a bad thing since it brings together a fragmented, divided nation.
``Television used to be a social glue, and that has changed in the
late 20th century,'' says Robert Thompson, professor of film and
television at Syracuse University. ``This show, and `Who Wants to
Be a Millionaire,' remind me of the '50s, because everyone can sit
around and watch it, young, old, rich, and poor.''
</P>
<P>
   And the show itself, Thompson points out, is quite clean-cut,
despite its initial promise of all the fun that comes with scantily
clad strangers marooned in the tropics. But that innocence could
change: After the show debuted in Sweden, some particants contended
that other contestants smuggled alcohol and tobacco onto the
island, allegedly with the help of the producers. And some fans of
the show think CBS is sure to cook up something fishy in upcoming
episodes. Could it be that there is yet another conspiracy brewing?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SPOILER: Read no further if you don't want to know Sloot's
theory of the alleged winner, however dubious. He suggests that the
victor is Gervase Peterson, a youth basketball coach
distinguishable as the only contestant on the island who can't
swim.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
