<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-STORK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CLEARHEADED LOOK AT THE STORK CLUB'S GLORY DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
STORK CLUB 
America's Most Famous Nightspot and the Lost World of Cafe Society 
By Ralph Blumenthal 
Little, Brown, 296 pp., illustrated, $25.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Ralph Blumenthal's ``Stork Club,'' a marvelous evocation of
New York night life from the Depression through the mid-'60s, you
can practically smell the secondhand smoke from Walter Winchell's
cigarette and hear the tinkle of ice in Ernest Hemingway's scotch
and water.
</P>
<P>
   The Stork Club, under the savvy management of Oklahoma-born
Sherman Billingsley, became a worldwide symbol of America's cafe
society. At various times, the duke and duchess of Windsor sat near
Alfred Hitchcock while he discussed ``The Wrong Man'' with Henry
Fonda. Congressman John F. Kennedy smiled over drinks with the
vivacious Jacqueline Bouvier not far from where FBI chief J. Edgar
Hoover was meeting and greeting with his ominipresent pal Clyde
Tolson. Joltin' Joe and Jock Whitney and Bogie and Bacall. Gene
Tunney and Hank Greenberg and Lana Turner. In short, a
name-droppers' paradise suitable for an Al Hirschfeld drawing.
</P>
<P>
   While Billingsley's reputation rests on his convivial
countenance as the club's official greeter, this book's value is in
recounting Billingsley's backdoor dealings, and sometimes double
dealings, with politicians and gangsters.
</P>
<P>
   There are also the matters of race and class. It was no
coincidence that most of the famous smiling out from the publicity
photographs were white and wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most highly publicized incidents in the club's
history, international star Josephine Baker waited for her dinner
for more than an hour. When it didn't arrive, she called her
lawyer, Walter White, executive secretary for the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   The club weakly claimed she ordered a filet mignon that wasn't
on the menu and quickly tried to make amends. But it was too late.
NAACP counsel Thurgood Marshall advised her to picket the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not intend to take such treatment quietly, '' Baker told
the New York Post. ``I have no intention of suffering deliberate
humiliation without striking back.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Stork Club habitue Hoover, after receiving a request
from the NAACP to investigate the matter, responded with the
following scribble: ``No answer required. I don't consider this any
of my business.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the picket line outside the Stork Club included cast
members from ``Guys and Dolls'' and ``South Pacific'' along with
Ruth James, Duke Ellington's sister. Eventually, Sugar Ray Robinson
and other Billingsley pals came to his defense, and excuses were
made that everyone must wait for service. But the fact remains that
most of the black faces at the Stork Club were congregated in the
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   And these incidents are precisely what makes Blumenthal's book
so superior to ``Welcome to the Stork Club,'' a purported Sherman
Billingsley memoir penned by former maitre d' Mearl L. Allen,
published in 1980. While Blumenthal is clearly enchanted with the
comings and goings at the club _ as a social history of the years
from Prohibition through the Vietnam War _ he's not a romantic.
He's not trying to create a nostalgic view of Billingsley's reign
but a clearheaded, concise account of how power among organized
crime, Hollywood celebrities, New York politicians, and the wealthy
came together over an oversize black-and-white ashtray and a couple
of martinis.
</P>
<P>
   In 1959, Blumenthal notes, a Philadelphia Inquirer columnist
wrote what amounted to the Stork Club's obituary: ``The E. 53rd St.
club is now less like a debutante than a movie star of the 1930s
who once was aloof but now is eager to chat with anyone who
recognizes her. She has aged but not gracefully.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
