<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5560 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-BIKE-BOS &LR;      07-18 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BIKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW CANCER SPURRED A BIKING STAR'S BIG WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
IT'S NOT ABOUT THE BIKE 
My Journey Back to Life 
By Lance Armstrong with Sally Jenkins 
Putname, 288 pp., $24.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bicycle is a grand metaphor for life. It is freedom but also
control. It is a parent who has held a child in arm's-length safety
for a young lifetime letting go _ go! _ and pushing the precious
human cargo free, without benefit of training wheels. The young
rider is under her own power, wobbling at first, now steady, the
tears gone, the smile triumphant. It is all there, the bond between
parent and child spinning into trust on a warm summer's day.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Armstrong, the Texan who this week is trying to repeat
last year's victory in the Tour de France, rides this metaphor for
all it is worth in his remarkable autobiography. His life has been
a ride over countless mountain ranges, figurative and literal.
Winning the Tour de France, with its many 100-mile-plus days and
alpine passages, was the easy part, to hear Armstrong tell it.
</P>
<P>
   As the title of Armstrong's book says, ``It's Not About the
Bike.'' Armstrong, as even many casual sports fans know by now, was
a brash up-and-coming US star of the European racing circuit when
he discovered in 1996 that he had testicular cancer. For months, he
ignored the pain, thinking it was the price of pounding in the
saddle. Then the pain transformed itself into terror; a testicle
grew three times its normal size and he began coughing up blood.
Finally, he went to his doctor. Armstrong's failure to deal earlier
with the symptoms of this rare form of cancer enabled the disease
to speed through his body and affect his brain, ultimately
requiring a horrific combination of brain surgery and chemotherapy.
By the end of his treatment, Armstrong was so weak he couldn't ride
his bike for months. Any thought that he could participate in a
bike race _ or even a neighborhood jaunt _ seemed far-fetched.
</P>
<P>
   As Armstrong knows well, relatively few Americans would be
interested in his story if it were merely a tale of how he won the
Tour de France. It has been nearly a century since bicycle racing
was the most popular sport in the United States. While the
three-week race through France is one of the world's most-watched
sporting spectacles, there is nothing remotely comparable to it in
this country, and most mainstream media here give bicycle racing
short shrift. It has taken a human story of tragedy and triumph to
give the sport the attention it deserves in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong and his skilled co-author, sports journalist Sally
Jenkins, put this elegantly in perspective. ``I left my house on
October 2, 1996, as one person and came home another,'' Armstrong
writes.
</P>
<P>
   That was cancer day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that cancer was the best thing that ever happened
to me,'' Armstrong writes. ``I don't know why I got the illness,
but it did wonders for me, and I wouldn't want to walk away from
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong was just a scrawny 7-year-old when he got his first
``serious'' bike, an ugly brown Schwinn Mag Scrambler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why does a kid love a bike?'' Armstrong writes. ``It's
liberation and independence.''
</P>
<P>
   Independence turned out to be a valuable commodity. Armstrong
never met his biological father, whom he refers to acidly as the
``DNA donor'' and ``my so-called father.'' He is similarly
disparaging about the man who adopted him and married and divorced
his mother. He says his own name, Armstrong, means nothing to him.
A hero of the book is Lance's mother, who was 17 years old when
Lance was born and raised him mostly as a single mother.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's story of his treatment and recovery in Indianapolis
is the heart of the book. Doctors and nurses are heroes. His former
French racing team, which tried to renegotiate Armstrong's contract
after learning of his cancer, is the villain. Shortly after being
declared cancer-free, Lance got married; his wife, Kristin,
eventually went through a painful but successful process of
in-vitro fertilization to have a child.
</P>
<P>
   In unexpected ways, the cancer treatment helped Armstrong win
the Tour de France as a rider for the team sponsored by the US
Postal Service. The treatment led to a dramatic weight loss and
reshaped Armstrong's muscular structure, making it easier for him
to climb the highest mountains. He was forced to make his technique
more efficient, pedaling in an easier gear at a higher speed. By
the time Armstrong recovered from his cancer treatment, he was like
the kid on a new bike again, craving the freedom. That is the
inspiration of this book, to feel again the joy of the ride, and of
life itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
