<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVE WAS HERE AND NOW IT'S GONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Diana Ross must be flipping her weave.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of dismal ticket sales and half-empty venues, the
plug was finally pulled last week on the whole sputtering mess that
was the ``Return to Love'' tour starring Diana Ross and Those Two
Women Who Were Supremes But Weren't The Supremes.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't supposed to be like this.
</P>
<P>
   Back in April, when Ross announced that she would be launching a
30-city summer tour with Scherrie Payne and Lynda Laurence, she
tried to pitch the concerts as something a rung or two below a
reunion, since Ross, who left the group in 1969, had never sung a
single note with either Payne or Laurence. Said Ross at the time,
``I decided to do this again for the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, the fans wanted nothing to do with it, and now Ross is at
a loss, wondering where did our love go. The show couldn't even
sell out in Michigan, where three Detroit high school chums first
joined their voices and became the Supremes more than 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement last week, Ross said she was ``severely
disappointed'' with the cancellation of the tour's remaining dates.
``I promised our fans that I would be there for them. . . . I would
sing the same if there were 10 people in the audience or 10,000. I
love the music and the fans, and I will find a way to reconnect
with them as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ross may well mean that. But if she were so interested in
connecting with her fans, she would have given them what they've
been wanting for 30 years _ a real Supremes reunion with cofounder
Mary Wilson and Cindy Birdsong, who replaced original Supreme
Florence Ballard in 1967. More than just icons, they've been the
evergreen template for every girlgroup since _ from the Emotions to
TLC to Destiny's Child.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I'm sure Payne and Laurence are very nice and talented
women, two of the eight who, between 1959 and 1977, donned the
uniform of killer pumps, fancy dresses, and heavy eyeliner as the
Supremes. But they are not the Supremes most of us grew up with,
not the women who, along with Ross, first gave life to such
Holland-Dozier-Holland gems as ``Stop! In the Name of Love,''
``Love is Like an Itching in My Heart,'' and ``Baby Love.'' Given
that she was joining Payne and Laurence, Ross said, ``I never even
considered it a reunion tour'' _ and that was fine because neither
did we.
</P>
<P>
   For while Ross may be the voice of the Supremes, Wilson is its
heart and soul. It was Wilson who kept the group going after Ross's
departure, and with Jean Terrell taking over lead-singing duties,
the Supremes enjoyed such hits as ``Up the Ladder to the Roof,''
``Stoned Love,'' ``Everybody's Got the Right to Love,'' ``Floy
Joy,'' and ``Nathan Jones.'' The Supremes have existed without
Ross, but never, in an appreciable way, without Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Ross assumed that she alone was worth the price of
admission, and believed it didn't really matter who cooed those
``oooohs,'' ``think it overs,'' and ``baby, babys'' next to her.
But ultimately, it mattered mightily when the top ticket price was
a stunning $250 to see what amounted to Ross and a couple of backup
singers.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? If this had truly been a Diana Ross and the Supremes
reunion, instead of ``Suprememania'' starring Diana Ross, folks
might have been willing to pay those prices, instead of stamping
the ``Return to Love'' tour ``return to sender.'' It would have
been a thrill to see Ross, Wilson, and Birdsong together again,
finally breathing life into the long-unfulfilled promise of their
hit ``Someday We'll Be Together.''
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, I saw Ross in concert, and for all her diva
overkill, there was something electric about hearing her sing
classic tunes from the Supremes' 1960s heyday. How couldn't there
be? Songs like ``You Can't Hurry Love,'' ``Back in My Arms Again,''
``The Happening,'' and ``Love Child'' are like old friends whose
presence never fails to bring joy. Many of us were warbling these
songs into hairbrush microphones before we even knew what love or
heartbreak were, and can't recall a time when they weren't a part
of our lives.
</P>
<P>
   But alas, Ross and Wilson, who with Ballard (she died in 1976)
first formed the group as teenagers living in Detroit's Brewster
projects, couldn't come to terms on money. Wilson said she was
``insulted'' by a $3 million offer out of an overall talent budget
of $15 to $20 million. (Birdsong must have been insulted three
times over _ she was offered less than $1 million.)
</P>
<P>
   Ross claimed that she wished Wilson could have joined the tour,
but added, ``When I decided to do the tour, I thought the music was
more important than the individuals.'' Perhaps. But the true
Supremes have always been more than just the hired help. Without
them, the tour's been aborted, and somewhere out there, Mary, Cindy
_ and yes, Florence, too _ are having the last laugh.
</P>
<P>
   All those years ago, Ross once sang ``You Can't Hurry Love'';
now, perhaps, she understands that, as far as her fans are
concerned, you can't take it for granted either.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Renee Graham covers the pop scene for The Bosto Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
