<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART TECHNOLOGY GROUP IS PROVING IT PAYS TO STAY FLEXIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a lot to be said for flexibility when you know your
world will change every six months but don't have a clue exactly
what the future will demand.
</P>
<P>
   That idea has been rumbling around one corner of the Internet
stock market this month. Debate surrounding it may say a lot about
what works in the competition for business customers on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The big winner of the moment: Art Technology Group Inc. of
Cambridge, Mass., whose stock has jumped by more than 25 percent in
less than two weeks and set an all-time high six days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Art Technology Group counts itself among a handful of software
companies that can transform electronic commerce Web sites from
another form of mass marketing to vehicles for personalized
connections with customers.
</P>
<P>
   As a customer you may never notice the software at work. It can
recognize you upon entering a Web site, recall your past activities
there, react to what you are doing at that moment, figure out what
items might be cross-sold to you, and keep in contact later through
e-mail promotions and other communications. All that is known as
``closing the loop'' in e-commerce parlance, helping a company
forge and hold onto relationships with customers.
</P>
<P>
   Practically every commercial site on the Internet uses the kinds
of software products sold by these companies or will soon. In the
business-to-business Internet world, that's a pretty good growth
story.
</P>
<P>
   The rumbles were felt two weeks ago when American Airlines hired
Art Technology Group to work on its Web site, replacing competitor
and industry leader Broadvision Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The dollars involved were never disclosed and almost beside the
point. The deal was news because it seemed to back up a strategy
the smaller Art Technology Group has pursued from its earliest
days.
</P>
<P>
   Though Broadvision has been serving its customers longer and
offered high-quality software, it sells products that are more
difficult to intregrate with other computer systems inside a
company and even other, related customer software. Broadvision
became an early star in its world on the quality of its packaged
application software, or ``packaged apps,'' and stands above its
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Art Technology Group built its Dynamo product line using Java
software that could mesh easily with other types of computer
systems and adapt with relative ease to new situations that
required additional software or other changes.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines was just one of hundreds of corporate clients
at Broadvision. But it was a flagship relationship Broadvision had
often promoted itself, involving the operation of a complex and
active Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the American Airlines win is a watershed kind of thing
but it's not signficant in and of itself,'' said Jeet Singh, the
chief execuitve of Art Technology Group. ``What the world is
watching is the decision-making that went into it and a much more
significant change in thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly investors were wondering if there might be at least some
truth to that.
</P>
<P>
   Broadvision shares lost about a third of their value within four
days of the American Airlines announcement. Bad news came in a
batch: the next day Broadvision said it wouldn't supply software to
Walmart.com while Art Technology Group played up the fact that an
early version of Kmart Corp.'s BlueLight.com would use its Dynamo
products.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is rapidly moving to one of open architecture,''
said analyst Steven Frankel of Adams, Harkness &AMP; Hill in Boston. It
would be easy to declare the recent advances of Art Technology
Group as evidence that open architecture, software and systems that
make possible a maximum amount of computer interaction, will win
out in business-to-business Internet competition.
</P>
<P>
   Corporations, after all, have the technical skills and
complicated circumstances that seem to demand it.
</P>
<P>
   But that's too simple, said analyst David Smith of Loomis Sayles
&AMP; Co. He said Art Technology Group would not be racking up
impressive client scores without a related business strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Art Technology Group has spent serious time and money
to train hundreds, perhaps thousands, of people at other consulting
companies who are paid by Web-site operators to select and install
software systems.
</P>
<P>
   Without that growing army, Smith said, there would be no
commercial movement to open systems. And even today, it's not
entirely clear who or what will win.
</P>
<P>
   The one sure thing: It's nearly impossible to stay on top for
long without a serious challenge. Just like their customers, Art
Technology Group and competitors will have to deal with a
competitive world that demands endless change.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
