<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5568 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-POP-GIRLFANS-BO     07-18 1369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-POP-GIRLFANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEMALE FANS SAY THEY'RE IN IT FOR THE CATHARSIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Picture the typical rap-metal or hardcore rock fan and you're
likely to come up with a variation on this theme: young,
pugnacious, and male, hurling his shirtless frame to gargantuan
beats in unison with hordes of oafish frat boys, radical skate
kids, and raging teens.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the brief ascent of the riot grrrl movement in the
cultural consciousness last decade, hard, angry music is largely
perceived as a testosterone-saturated affair, for performers and
fans alike. Especially now, with misogyny a prominent theme among
chart-topping artists such as Eminem, Limp Bizkit, and Kid Rock,
the genre seems skewed toward a particularly vicious sort of
masculinity.
</P>
<P>
   That's why it's startling to see the growing ranks of female
fans of hardcore music. Contrary to popular opinion, not every
adolescent heart is aflutter for the Backstreet Boys and 'N Sync.
Girls from the suburbs and girls from the city, girls who live in
tiny hamlets overseas and in Midwestern trailer parks, are
dedicated followers of the new crop of coarse, venomous rockers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seems to be a growing passion among females for this
type of music,'' says Amy Doyle, director of music programming for
MTV. ``We think that `TRL' (`Total Request Live'), our audience
empowerment show, may be contributing. The girls started out
calling in for the pop groups, while the males were voting for Limp
Bizkit and Kid Rock. They ended up being exposed to music they
might not have sought out. Females are buying it in droves now. It
seems very clear that when Eminem is selling over 5 million CDs in
six weeks, it's not just males buying it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're taking all their hate inside, all that's
happened, and releasing it in the best way,'' says 16-year-old
Kelly O'Connell of Boston, who counts among her favorite musicians
Slipknot, Korn, Marilyn Manson, and Insane Clown Posse. ``Take
Slipknot's `Wait and Bleed,' '' says O'Connell. ``With the words, I
feel the hate rise up in me, and I'm putting the hate out by
listening to it. When I get in a fight with my mom, I'll turn on a
CD and listen to all the weird stuff they sing about, and it calms
me down. Slow music doesn't help me, it makes me madder.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Not just a guy thing &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Historically, pummeling death-metal drums, shrieking feedback,
and horror-show samples _ Slipknot's stock in trade _ haven't held
much appeal for young females. Neither has Limp Bizkit's brand of
sledgehammer misogyny, though frontman Fred Durst and company are
dealing in essentially the same currency heavy-metal gods and
rappers have for years. The difference is that young women are
beginning to embrace it with open arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the women he knew treated him badly,'' says Stephanie
Finelli, 16, who lives in Manchester, Conn., of Durst-penned tunes
such as ``Stuck.'' In the song _ which Durst often dedicates in
concert ``to all the girls'' _ he sings ``Psycho female blowin' up
the phone line/You need to tighten that screw, it's been loose for
a long time/You make a dash for my cash/it's your (expletive) that
I'm blasting. . . . Why, why, why you gotta dig in my business you
(expletive) whore?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Limp Bizkit,'' Finelli says. ``The beat really appeals
to me. I occasionally listen to the words. But I don't take it
personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course Durst is a veritable Osmond Brother when compared with
Eminem, whose unbridled venom toward women, gays, most of his
colleagues in music, his wife, and his mother sets a new standard
for violent and hateful lyrics. As the best-selling pop artist in
the country, Eminem is a lightning rod for debate about issues
ranging from censorship and artistic accountability to the decline
of polite society and American youth's taste for mean-spirited
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   For Jenny Hawkins, Eminem represents something much simpler.
``My parents hate rap. Sometimes I play my Eminem records to rebel
against them when I feel angry,'' says 15-year-old Hawkins, echoing
a form of teenage insurrection as old as rock itself. Hawkins lives
in the small English village of Huntley (we met in an Eminem chat
room and conversed via e-mail); she doesn't always like her
isolated country life, but next to Eminem's, she says, hers seems
tolerable. ``I play songs like `Rock Bottom' when I'm depressed, to
prove to myself that my life isn't so bad after all.''
</P>
<P>
   Catharsis, in some form or another, comes up in every
conversation with young female fans of angry music. ``They're
letting out their frustration, and I do too, at the same time,''
says 15-year-old Jesica Corbo, a Korn devotee who lives in Dedham,
Mass. Nikki Vanwasshnova, a 21-year-old veteran of hardcore music
fandom who lives in Ypsilanti, Mich., observes that ``they have
problems with something that happened in their lives, and they're
pissed. It's a way of dealing with pain in their own creative way.
That's how I judge a band.'' Kelly O'Connell points out that ``when
you have anger inside, you don't have to take it out on someone
else. It's like the band does it for you.''
</P>
<P>
   While girls, traditionally, have been allowed a certain measure
of angst-ridden growing pains, the real vitriol has always been
accorded to the male gender. Girls brood; boys act out. In one
sense, the emergence of young females fans into the hardcore music
arena signals a leveling of the playing field. The girls aren't
just tagging along with their boyfriends anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to a lot of shows, and the first place my eyes are drawn
to is the mosh pit,'' says Jamie Roberts, director of publicity for
Roadrunner Records, home to Slipknot, Type O Negative, Coal
Chamber, and Machinehead, among others. ``There are an increasing
number of girls in there. I'd never seen girls in the pit before
recently.'' It is, Roberts believes, a step in the right direction.
``I get the sense that the girls know that they can do whatever
boys are doing. It's not a girls' thing or a boys' thing. Hard rock
and metal is really the kids' music now. It's their mode of
rebellion, and it's a pretty safe one.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Will there be a price? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Statistically speaking, aggressive music is a relatively
risk-free way of blowing off steam. But one has to wonder, as
today's artists push the boundaries of savage imagery and
hate-filled verbiage to new extremes _ and children consume it by
the tens of millions _ if there's a price to be paid that can't be
measured in numbers of injuries or arrests. Will a generation
weaned on violence-drenched entertainment be further desensitized
by the music _ arguably one of the most potent forces in a young
person's life?
</P>
<P>
   According to the girls, neither they nor their friends _ male
and female alike _ have trouble differentiating between the fantasy
world of a song and the reality of living humane and civil lives.
The music, they agree, actually helps them to avoid engaging in
antisocial behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone's dumb and depressed, if they're unstable, then
it's different,'' says Vanwasshnova. ``It's like anything else,
something on TV, that could make them snap. But if you have a grip
on yourself, it's a way to deal with feelings instead of going out
and doing something real.''
</P>
<P>
   Says MTV's Doyle: ``We've certainly talked about lyrical
content, and our research shows the reason that females like these
artists is they're coming from a point of honesty about issues
they've been faced with. Like the topic or not, it's real to the
artist, and that's how the fans are taking it.''
</P>
<P>
   The main thing, all agree, is not the literal meaning of a
lyric, but rather the feeling of a song _ conveyed not simply in
words but in the visceral language of screaming guitars and
jackhammer drums, jittery turntables and shredded voices. As
Hawkins points out: ``We all swear at people when we're angry. We
all say we'll kill someone who's annoyed us. But we don't mean
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about the emotion behind it,'' Vanwasshnova says,
summing up what all of these young women have been saying in myriad
ways. ``It's about what you can release.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5570 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-ANGER-BOS &LR;      07-18 1744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ANGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BANDS SAY THEY'RE SIMPLY VENTING, HONESTLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Last of two parts)
</P>
<P>
   The aggressive music and fiery climax of Woodstock '99 were the
tip-off. The world is not a pretty place to a new era of rock acts
that use anger as their primary motivation. Call it scary, call it
therapy, call it niche marketing, but high-decibel screaming is
shaking the charts and selling in the millions like never before.
</P>
<P>
   Turn on today's rock radio and brace yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rage is bliss!'' sings the band Slipknot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already told you _ stop pushing me!'' shrieks Dope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get away from me, stay the (expletive) away from me!'' barks
Kittie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get up, come on down with the sickness!'' bellows Disturbed.
</P>
<P>
   Road rage. Air rage. And, now, airwave rage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge demand for angry music right now. A lot more
angry bands are being signed, because that's what the marketplace
dictates,'' says Jason Wyner, vice president with Artemis Records,
which is having success with Kittie, an all-female metal group from
London, Ontario, that performs such tersely titled rants as
``Spit,'' ``Suck,'' and ``Choke.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, we've seen bands like the Clash and Rage Against
the Machine channel their anger into their political leanings,''
says Oedipus, program director of Boston rock station WBCN. ``But
now, a lot of music is anger for the sake of anger.''
</P>
<P>
   Hot and angry chart acts like Korn and Limp Bizkit have broken
the doors down _ and a new wave is rushing in. Many of the young
venom-spewing rockers are headed toward Boston on the Vans Warped
Tour at Suffolk Downs on Thursday, the Tattoo the Earth Festival at
Suffolk Downs on Saturday, and the Ozzfest at the Tweeter Center
July 29 and 30.
</P>
<P>
   Some wear their mantle of anger as if it's a badge of courage.
``You will never meet a band that is more full of anger than us,''
says Slipknot cofounder/percussionist Shawn Crahan, who describes
his Des Moines-based group as ``nine lunatics in masks and boiler
suits.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Anger is an energy &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I play drums because a psychiatrist told me I needed to vent
some anger,'' says Crahan, adding, ``My job is to wake everybody
up. I'm stripping away all the labels. You're no better than me,
you don't breathe my air, and you don't make my decisions. Too many
people don't have the courage anymore to change the world. Our
world has become nothing but a herd of cattle. And I'm in front of
them in the biggest tree, looking down. I'm not going to be
trampled.''
</P>
<P>
   Slipknot's self-titled debut album, which has gone platinum (1
million sold), is a slamming mix of larynx-scarring vocals,
shredding guitars, punk-laced rhythms, and anxiety-inducing noises
made by clanging on metal objects and weaving in the roar of
electrical saws.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can duplicate the 'Knot,'' says Crahan, who had his
``fair share of problems'' growing up, but is now married with
three children and says ``I will never cheat on my wife and will
never make this a dysfunctional family.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some observers wonder what these musicians can complain
about _ after all, the economy has been thriving and there's no
cause like the Vietnam War to protest about _ Disturbed's singer,
Dave Draiman, says such critics need to wake up.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can delude themselves because the economy is great, or
because there's no war involving American soldiers,'' Draiman says.
``But there's so much more wrong with the world than there was 10
or 20 years ago. The world keeps going in a downward spiral. Not
everything is about the economy. I have three friends who died of
AIDS, and there are children getting killed in gangland crossfires,
and people with SUVs, a condo, and a $50,000-a-year job who are
still killing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anything wrong with this anger kick in
music. There's a lot to be angry about,'' says Draiman, who was
expelled from five boarding schools in his youth, once for setting
a principal's van on fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family is conversative, religious types,'' he adds. ``They
had planned for me to be a very different person than I am today.
They tried to mold me into the stereotypical child they wanted.
That's why they shipped me around to boarding schools.''
</P>
<P>
   The experiment failed. Draiman finished high school in Chicago,
then went to Los Angeles to play in a band called the Foreskins.
That led to an audition with Disturbed _ and he passed by grabbing
the microphone and venting uncontrollably. He now sometimes comes
onstage in a cage or an electric chair, symbolizing the
imprisonment he feels is his assigned role in society.
</P>
<P>
   Disturbed's fascinating metal-core song ``Down With the
Sickness'' has become a rock hit and paints sickness as an
appropriate response to being labeled a black sheep. ``Madness is
the gift that has been given to me,'' Draiman sings. Another song,
``Violence Fetish,'' is about how people have a natural tendency
toward violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's undeniable,'' he says. ``They watch football games and
boxing matches and see movies about gladiators. But instead of
focusing on it in a negative way, we use music to allow you to get
immersed in a sea of people and let loose. It's better to let it
loose that way than walking a high school corridor with a gun under
your coat.''
</P>
<P>
   That image summons memories of the Columbine High School
shootings in Colorado last year. It was an event that resonated for
every parent, indeed for every grown-up wondering what to make of
the rage in rock music. It's also the incident that inspired Papa
Roach's song ``Dead Cell.'' Says Roach's singer, Coby Dick: ``Maybe
those kids who did it were dead cells. Maybe it's because the media
and their families pushed them that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Papa Roach's impressive debut CD, ``Infest,'' has climbed to No.
9 on the Billboard charts, propelled by the hit, ``Last Resort,''
about contemplating suicide. ``It's about a roommate I had who
finally found God, and for him, that was awesome. He got on with
his life and got better,'' says Dick.
</P>
<P>
   The product of a divorced family, Dick sings another song,
``Broken Home,'' with the bitter line: ``I'm stuck in between my
parents.'' His mother remarried and he hated his stepfather at
first, but ``now he's one of the greatest people to come into my
life.'' Still, Dick, whose band is from Vacaville, Calif., sports a
tattoo of a burning house, suggesting how the pain still cuts deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can store these things in the back of my head, then when I'm
40, have a nervous breakdown because I never got them out,'' he
says. ``Or I can vent them, so I don't keep them inside. Men have a
tough time expressing their emotions, but music is the way to do it
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   In total agreement is Edsel Dope, singer for the band Dope, a
punk act also influenced by old-school Motley Crue-style metal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see the pain in our faces and in the faces of the kids
who are singing back at you,'' he says. ``These emotions have got
to come out. Not everybody is good at sitting down with their
family and talking about it. But sitting in a dark room listening
to music, or going to a show with thousands of other people, is a
way to get it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Edsel Dope grew up in South Florida, and his parents divorced
when he was 4 years old. He had a ``white trash background,'' he
says, then moved to Las Vegas, where he handled customer service
for a phone sex company. He later moved to New York to sell drugs,
which is how his band (founded with his brother, Simon) was first
financed. He also had some run-ins with the police, which led to
the viciously angry tunes ``Pig Society'' and ``America the
Pitiful,'' which are on Dope's new album, ``Felons and
Revolutionaries.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really angry that they could take people who just smoke
pot and throw them in prisons with violent criminals. That's what
really started to screw with my head,'' he says. He won't talk
about whether that prison experience is a personal memory, but on
Dope's CD jacket, the band members are pictured inside prison
cells. &QL; 
 &QL; 
It's just an expression &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unleashing anger, for whatever reason, is the result of
``feeling oppressed and victimized,'' according to Dr. Michael
Rater, medical director of the adolescent residential treatment
center at the Harvard-affiliated McLean Hospital in Belmont, Mass.
He also cites a ``new level of vulgarity'' in some of today's rock,
which he sees as an outgrowth of the anger expressed in an earlier
generation by punk bands such as the Sex Pistols and Dead Kennedys.
</P>
<P>
   Rater, who has spent time analyzing Korn lyrics with patients at
his center, notes how ``all of this anger gets channeled fairly
quickly into marketable niches where it can be enjoyed without huge
societal impact.'' For that matter, he adds, ``If you're
functioning well, to be able to blow off steam is probably kind of
fun. It's self-affirming to do that.'' He sees the positive side of
the phenomenon and even notes how the ``physicality'' of the mosh
pits that form at many rock concerts ``can be attractive'' to young
people in search of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about Rage Against the Machine's famed anti-authority
chant of ``(Expletive) you, I won't do what you tell me!'' Rater
calmly explains: ``Is that really much different from (Bob Dylan's)
`I ain't gonna work on Maggie's farm no more'?''
</P>
<P>
   One group whose members don't come from dysfunctional
backgrounds is Kittie. The group consists of women who led ``fairly
normal lives,'' says singer Morgan Lander. She always loved
hard-rock music _ from Van Halen and AC/DC to Tool and Helmet _ and
steered that way when she realized the power of her voice. ``My
early voice sounded like a raccoon getting hit by a hammer, but
then it developed,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Kittie's musicians are still in their teens and advertise
themselves as the hard-rock alternative to frilly teen pop stars
like Britney Spears. Kittie, known as the ``anti-Britney,'' hasn't
had it easy, however, because the group is competing in the
predominantly male genre of heavy metal. One of their songs,
``Raven,'' was inspired by a death threat received from a male band
against whom they competed in an Ontario talent contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our songs are all about not letting anyone hold you down,''
says Kittie's Lander. ``We're not trying to be preachers, but we're
not going to be pushed around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
