<HEADLINE>
SHEEN'S IMAGE ADDS NEW SPIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, CALIF. _ Michael J. Fox, the now-departed star of
``Spin City,'' has projected a clean-cut, wholesome aura throughout
his career, remaining the boy next door even as he neared 40.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Sheen, who is replacing Fox this fall as the new deputy
mayor on the ABC sitcom, has a somewhat . . . different image.
Sheen became tabloid fodder in the mid-1990s amid revelations that
he ran up a tab of $53,000 with prostitutes working for Hollywood
madam Heidi Fleiss.
</P>
<P>
   So the obvious question hanging over the upcoming fifth season
of ``Spin City'' is: Will viewers accept the brooding Sheen in a
role designed for the sunny Fox?
</P>
<P>
   ``America likes a guy that's been down and is trying to get
up,'' executive producer Gary David Goldberg said hopefully. ``Look
at Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than run from Sheen's bad-boy image, Goldberg has opted
to play off it by creating for Sheen a character, Charlie Owen,
whose checkered past made him a gossip-column fixture. ``Fun finds
me,'' the character says ruefully. Sheen said Monday that he
envisions playing the role as a way to dispel his reputation by
proving ``I can laugh at myself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To ignore the reality of the lifestyle I led for a time _ a
long time _ would be a disservice,'' said Sheen. Not that he wants
``Spin City'' to mirror his life too closely. Some parts of his
past, he admitted, ``really have no place on network television.''
</P>
<P>
   Even apart from image questions, Sheen faces a major challenge
in trying to fill Fox's shoes and cross from films into series
television for the first time. One of the obstacles is his own
father, Martin Sheen, a star of NBC's acclaimed drama ``The West
Wing,'' which will air opposite ``Spin City.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The shows are so different, it's almost like people looking in
their video stores and deciding whether to watch ``Apocalypse
(Now)'' or `Major League,'' Sheen said, alluding to the somber war
epic starring his father and a goofy baseball comedy starring
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Father and son have discussed the unusual competition facing
them, and Sheen the elder has made a cocky prediction to Sheen the
younger. ``He says he's going to watch (`Spin City') tumble down in
the ratings as he stomps us with both feet,'' said Charlie Sheen.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Spin City'' is billed as an ensemble comedy, the reality
is that it was built around Fox. When Fox, who has Parkinson's
disease, announced he was leaving the sitcom to devote his energies
to battling and raising public awareness of the disease,
``Everyone's first instinct was to end the show, frankly,''
Goldberg said. But Fox urged that the show continue.
</P>
<P>
   It is rare for a show to survive the departure of the leading
character, although Goldberg pointed out that ``Cheers'' flourished
even after Shelley Long left, and that ``MASH'' withstood major
cast changes. Heather Locklear, who joined the ``Spin City'' cast
last year, is returning, and Goldberg said the supporting cast will
find their parts beefed up.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Fox has offered some reassuring words to his
successor, according to Sheen: ``He said `Don't worry. They'll
still tune in.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
