<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5578 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-VT-COLLEGE-SPORTS-BOS     07-18 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VT-COLLEGE-SPORTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERMONT COLLEGE CAUGHT IN SPORTS FUROR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every year, hundreds of students at Champlain College throng to
Memorial Auditorium for the Great Northern Shoot-out. It's a rare
chance to show school spirit. But in two years, the rousing
season-opening basketball tournament will cease to exist.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the Champlain Beavers, long a powerhouse in
junior college sports, won't be around to host the games. Last
month, after students left for the summer, the small
career-oriented college in Burlington, Vt., eliminated all varsity
sports _ one of the few private, four-year colleges ever to take
such a step.
</P>
<P>
   The decision had nothing to do with financial problems, school
officials said. Abolishing varsity sports, they argue, is an
innovative way to free up resources for intramural sports, in
essence slashing top-notch basketball and soccer programs so more
students can take part in everything from kayaking to rock
climbing.
</P>
<P>
   Now, supporters of the varsity teams are reeling, saying that
the end of Beaver sports will hurt school morale and alumni
relations as well. They accuse the administration of disregarding
student support for the teams and defying the recommendation of a
special commission.
</P>
<P>
   And for some of the athletes and coaches, the end of varsity
sports is devastating. Bob Tipson, coach of the men's basketball
team for the last 33 years, who has the eighth best record in
National Junior College Athletic Association history, says the
decision will rip the heart out of the college.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel like you let some people down,'' Tipson lamented,
wondering, ``Was there something else I could have said? Was there
something else I could have done? It's not just the alums, it's the
ones that I haven't coached. The ones who will never get a chance.
It's really just sad.''
</P>
<P>
   In defending the college's decision, which takes effect in the
2002-2003 school year, Champlain president Roger Perry said the
administration spent much of the past year consulting students and
faculty. After surveys and meetings indicated a lackluster interest
in the varsity sports program compared with intramural sports, he
said, the trustees decided it would be better to spend the $500,000
annual varsity budget on a multimillion-dollar facility to increase
students' access to sports, including snowboarding and sailing.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, he said, is to quadruple the number of students on
campus involved in sports, so they're more likely to play than
watch. Now, only about 50 students participate on the three varsity
sports teams _ men's basketball and men's and women's soccer.
Champlain has 1,380 full-time students and 1,105 part-timers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were spending a lot of money for only a few students,''
Perry said. ``This was essentially a business decision. People say
universities don't know how to make priorities and choices. Well,
that's what we're doing. We want more inclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics say the administration is miscalculating the value
of the varsity sports program. Support from alumni might diminish,
they argue, while school spirit will wane, and nearly $1 million in
tuition money from student athletes will vanish.
</P>
<P>
   Janine Fagan, a 23-year-old center-forward on the women's soccer
team who moved from England to play for Champlain, scoffs at any
suggestion that students aren't interested in varsity sports.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever she goes, she said, people always admire that she plays
for Champlain, which won the NCJAA women's soccer national
championships in 1994 and 1998. The men's basketball team,
meanwhile, has been a top contender for the title five times in the
last decade and the men's soccer team took regional titles in the
1995 and 1997 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's devastating to think that a school with such a high
reputation for its sports program is going to end it all,'' Fagan
said. ``To carry the name on your shirt and your shoulder is very
important. This is like cutting off your nose to spite your face.
And in the long run, I think this could be the downfall of
Champlain.''
</P>
<P>
   The initial questions about the longevity of the varsity sports
program arose in the college's marketing department. Champlain
first began offering four-year bachelor's degrees in 1991. Now,
nearly 90 percent of the students seek such diplomas. The problem,
marketing officials said, is that each time a team wins a
high-profile game, the media mention they're competing against
junior colleges. That, Perry and other school officials say, gives
prospective students the wrong impression.
</P>
<P>
   The image problem sparked interest across the campus in the
Beavers joining a four-year athletic association, such as the
National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics. Perry and
trustees said it was simply too expensive for the college, which
has an operating budget of about $25 million, to maintain the
varsity program and launch a serious intramural program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is a series of tradeoffs,'' he said. ``Dollars have to
follow priorities. It's like a family budget. I would love a boat,
an airplane, and a Lexus. But we can't have it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Collins, chairman of the college's board of trustees,
insisted the decision serves the college's best interests. ``The
college and the student body has changed,'' he said. ``The best
information we have shows this is what students want. And one of
the reasons Champlain is healthy is because it makes difficult,
soul-searching decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics from students to professors argue the administration
misread student surveys in deciding they didn't care about varsity
sports. For example, a Champlain survey cites 43.5 percent of
students saying the varsity sports program doesn't interest them at
all. But that means 56.5 percent of the students are interested,
the critics note.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was always a lot of school spirit here, and a lot of
people rallied around the teams,'' said Elizabeth Hartwick, a
21-year-old senior who signed a petition with hundreds of other
students in favor of keeping the varsity teams. ``Our name was
athletics. That's what we were. Now it's gone, and I'm wondering
what's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   So is David Mona, an assistant professor of accounting who has
taught at Champlain for 15 years. Like others at Champlain, he
doesn't understand how the trustees made the leap from considering
moving the teams to another league to eliminating them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The natural decision would have been to take the sports teams
out of a junior league and put (them) in a four-year sports
league,'' he said. ``That would be the capstone for the transition.
But I just can't understand this. We're financially healthy enough
to do both. Is this for the sake of being unique?''
</P>
<P>
   Now, after years of coaching at Champlain, both Tipson and Sue
Rand, the college's athletic director and women's soccer coach, are
mulling a future neither ever expected.
</P>
<P>
   Tipson, who has been at Champlain since studying there as an
undergraduate, and Rand, who has worked in the athletic department
for 18 years and has turned down several job offers, are both
dusting off their resumes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had planned to spend the rest of my career here,'' Rand
said. ``But that's minor in the greater scheme. We have a history
and legacy of successful athletic programs. They're a large part of
the overall college experience. The students are going to miss
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1402EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5580 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-TIPS-BOS &LR;      07-18 0200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TIPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Driving Mr. Albert'' by Michael Paterniti (Dial Press,
$18.95). In a tale that sounds like fiction but happens to be true,
a writer recounts his cross-country adventures with an aged doctor
who's the keeper of Einstein's brain. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Name of the World'' by Denis Johnson (Harper
</P>
<P>
   Collins, $23). In this moving novel, a college professor,
shocked almost beyond functioning by the death of his family,
slowly climbs back toward understanding the quizzical meaning of
life. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Obedient Father'' by Akhil Sharma (Farrar, Straus &AMP;
Giroux, $23). A novel about the dark side of politics in India, and
the even darker side of the man at the story's core. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Circus Fire'' by Stewart O'Nan (Doubleday, $24.95). A top
fiction writer shifts his attention to examining the 1944 big-top
fire in Hartford that took more than 160 lives and changed
thousands of others. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``From Dawn to Decadence'' by Jacques Barzun (HarperCollins,
$36). A magisterial survey of the West's past 500 years, as
readable as it is learned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
