   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CELL-PHONES (Washington) _ In an effort to assuage growing
concerns about health risks associated with cellular phones,
manufacturers next month will begin disclosing the level of
microwave radiation emanating from each new phone sold. The action
is designed to assure customers that radiation from the devices
does not exceed government limits. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   PATENT-COLUMBIA (Washington) _ The Senate is expected to kill a
measure to extend a lucrative patent on a biotechnology process
held by Columbia University. The university, which sells the
process to drug companies, estimates that the 15-month extension
would be worth $70 million to $150 million. But the extension and
others like it have recently come under fire as giveaways to
special interests. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ This is the way Congress and the
White House work these days. With much fanfare, the Republicans
pass something they know President Clinton will veto. Then they
either quietly modify it to get the president's okay or they let
him veto it. The idea is not to build a record but to build an
issue. Playing this game, the House recently voted to kill
AmeriCorps, Clinton's pet project to encourage volunteer national
service. The GOP did it just to get Clinton's goat. By MARIANNE
MEANS.
</P>
