<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !! ``American Pimp'' Hardly the searching look at the sex
industry it could have been, this documentary by Allen and Albert
Hughes interviews pimps uncritically, accepting their fast-talking
testimony at face value, emphasizing the pimps' colorful,
entertaining side, downplaying the exploitation of women on which
their prosperity rests. (Unrated)
</P>
<P>
   (FU) ! 1/2 ``But I'm a Cheerleader'' Lame satire of homophobia,
painted in Day-Glo colors, as a teen perceived as lesbian is sent
to a heterosexual boot camp to be ``cured.'' Natasha Lyonne, as the
cheerleader, and Clea DuVall, as the smoldering camper she falls
for, turn in good performances (most notably in a tender lovemaking
scene), but the rest of this flimsy film crashes and burns around
them. (R)
</P>
<P>
   !! 1/2 ``X-Men'' It could have been more than a big-screen
version of the popular comic series, but it isn't. Dark, handsome
visuals that might have resonated provocatively with themes of
bigotry and alienation settle instead for slick good mutant-bad
mutant stuff, with Patrick Stewart as the good mutants' guru and
Ian McKellen as his opposite number. Hugh Jackman, as the pained,
steel-clawed Wolverine, comes off best among the action figures.
(PG-13)
</P>
</TEXT>
