<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5583 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-COLLINS-BOS &LR;      07-18 1662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENYA'S ELEPHANTS SURE OFFER A LOT TO LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEWA DOWNS, Kenya _ The view from the swimming pool, which hangs
on the lip of the Isiola Valley, is, shall we say, elephantine.
Across the gap, on the faded green and ecru slope, there are so
many dark gray elephants wandering about that they could hire out
as symbolic extras at the forthcoming GOP convention.
</P>
<P>
   Call it Republican Ridge, although that might offend the
resident mammoths since they're smarter than most of us. Maybe
because they've been around longer. They're also more peaceful.
That's not to say they don't get riled or aren't troublesome.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can be mischievous,'' Phil West says. ``They're why you
didn't have any water in your room this morning. They like to tear
up the water pipes, but we'll have them fixed soon. Those guys can
be a bother, but we love them.''
</P>
<P>
   Who wouldn't? So, who needs a shower? Just jump in the pool.
Float on your back and gaze over at the ``ellies,'' as Phil calls
them. Phil, whom I call ``Mwalimu'' (``teacher,'' in Swahili),
delights in imparting items of his vast comprehension of the
African bush. He's the head guide at Lewa Downs, a mellowing-out
refuge in the wilds of Kenya's Highlands where life moves at a
satisfyingly pachydermic pace. A family lineup of ellies in transit
reminds you of a slow freight, and sometimes the whistle _ a
trumpeting _ sounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be deceived by their size, and that shuffling gait,''
Phil says. ``They can hustle if they need to. If you've annoyed
them and they are in a mind to trample you _ well, you can't outrun
them. But you can walk with them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can,'' I say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can. Believe me. We'll drive over there, then leave the car
and walk.''
</P>
<P>
   A walk with Mwalimu, the ambulatory professor in khakis whose
classroom today covers several miles of lonely, uneven terrain, a
lot of it dense bush, is always enlightening. Or a drive.
</P>
<P>
   The day before had offered a good one across the silvery
grassland of Simba Ridge in an open car. On surprising a couple of
ugly dukelings _ two bull rhinos _ duking it out with horny head
butts in a clearing, the driver, Peter Munoro, said it was all
about dating rights. He nodded toward the prize, an interested
party poking her double-pronged head out of the scrub.
</P>
<P>
   Not far away was a panorama that could have been a tribute to
the National Basketball Association: two teams of five giraffes
accompanied by a couple of zebras. Somebody had forgotten a ball.
Should the zebras have volunteered to referee for the pugnacious
rhinos?
</P>
<P>
   These were reticulated giraffes with distinctive body patterns.
Their terra cotta-hued hides seemed the work of wall-building
masons who've separated the large blocks with white lines of
mortar.
</P>
<P>
   Farther along, dipping into a ravine, we encountered the scarce
antelope that obsessed Ernest Hemingway, the hunter: a male greater
kudu of at least 500 pounds, light gray and topped by elegant
high-spiraling horns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eureka!'' I whispered, remembering a solid, fruitless week of
driving and tramping through Tanzania 35 years ago, searching for
kudus. Apparently inheriting his father's fixation, Dr. Greg
Hemingway, the leader of that hunting safari, was haunted by an
Ahabian desire to bag one for himself. Many tracks and reported
sightings _ but no cigar. Not even a glimmer.
</P>
<P>
   Belatedly here was a big daddy that Papa H. would have coveted.
Shortly, in the brush, appeared three bareheaded females.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was it worth the wait?'' said New Yorker Royce Battlemans,
watching with her husband, David.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gosh, yes. Three queens and a king _ a kudu flush.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't bet on it happening again,'' said another rider, Angela
Bromley-Martin from England. She and her husband, David, have been
around the African blocks a few times.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't bet against anything happening since each day's
sights and experiences are so varied.
</P>
<P>
   After a few miles came the word ``Cheetahs!'' from Peter at the
wheel. He stopped the car and turned off the engine.
</P>
<P>
   Angela smiled, ``Now behold this scene. Mind you, we're all
voyeurs.'' Ahead, a male ostrich, a dandy in formal plumage, black
and white, was coming on to a dowdy-looking female in gruel gray.
Rocking and rolling in the courtship dance, jiggling spindly
scarlet legs and neck, he waved his white wings seductively, and
impressively enough. As they got it on discreetly, the lovers had
the full attention of arrayed peeping toms across the savannah: us,
a cheetah quartet, five Grant's gazelles (their bachelor horns
twinkling in the sun), a giraffe, six female impalas, an oryx, two
hyenas. Transfixed. Sex sells.
</P>
<P>
   Only the cheetahs' sleek, spotted faces and overreaching,
twitching tails were visible in a thicket. They looked like
See-no-evil, Speak-no-evil, Hear-no-evil and Can-do-evil. Looking
like candidates for positions in an antelope harem, the impalas had
arrived, leaping high, gliding smoothly, perhaps dreaming, ``Some
day he'll come along _ the ram I love.''
</P>
<P>
   But everything seemed to stop until the ostriches parted.
</P>
<P>
   Today starts early. We're out of the car before breakfast, and
the quest is elephants. Mwalimu Phil lugs his .458 Winchester, for
emergency use only. Hunting in Kenya has been taboo for almost 25
years. ``You're safe in a car, and the animals look fairly
harmless. But you shouldn't underrate them,'' he says. ``Remember
they are wild, so I take a gun when we walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next year we hope to offer six-day walking safaris, tenting at
night away from the lodge. You won't cover the area a car or van
could, and you may not see as many animals. But being on the ground
with them is the best, the genuine safari experience.''
</P>
<P>
   We're on the ground all right, my friend Aurelio and I trudging
a hillside with Phil. We pause often for him to describe sights
that aren't sights at all to aliens, easily overlooked until he
singles them out and lectures. ``Matabele ants down there. See?''
He says the 2-inch creatures are ``savages. They'll eat anything.
They break in and raid termite mounds. If they can get a crowd
together they can take out an antelope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's what we call a diet tree, the boscia. You grind up the
bark, add to tea or milk, and it dissipates hunger. Knobwood bark
there. Make it into tea that cures flu.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're walking through an outdoor pharmacy. See that plant, the
rhus natalensis. If you're weary, chew the stems and it'll keep you
awake. Make a tea out of the bark of this tree, the acacia
tortillis, and it'll fix a sore throat. Pick those desert dates,
boil them down to stop a cold. It's said the leaves from the
bossier tree can be used to alleviate epilepsy. There's so much
natural medicine out here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, whoa, right here. Danger. This fruit is a Sodom apple.
Poison for us. But ellies like to eat them to ease indigestion.
Elephants have a terrible digestive system. They have to eat
massive amounts, and don't use much of it. They eliminate most of
it, 60 percent, as you can see. Piles of it. They have awful table
manners. Look at all these trees they've knocked over so they can
get at the leaves.''
</P>
<P>
   We've descended into a lugga, a dry riverbed, and Phil seems to
be more attentive. There's thick cover on the left, a good hideout
for buffalo. ``Stay close behind me now. We don't want any of them
charging out.''
</P>
<P>
   But then all mastadonic hell breaks loose.
</P>
<P>
   Elephants are showing up everywhere, like relatives and
creditors when you hit the lottery. Left . . . right . . . front .
. . back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow, a lot of them,'' says Phil.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what Custer said about the Indians,'' says Aurelio.
</P>
<P>
   On a ledge above us a young bull appears to be weeping. Phil
says, ``He's in musth _ you know, heat, love crazy. The fluid
flowing from the temporal gland near his eye tells us that. He
could be edgy, excitable. We want to move away from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Retreating farther along the lugga, we find a stretch of granite
that is tiered and resembles a section of a Grecian amphitheater.
It would be nice to sit here and take in the elly show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not now. We have to keep moving. We don't want to be
surrounded.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, we are. Looming like gigantic dusky boulders, are
they closing in? I think of MacBeth and Birnham Wood. Adrenaline is
pumping. Over on the right a nervous cow, guarding her calf, flaps
blanket ears _ not a good sign. Mom accompanies that signal by
bellowing, ``Wah-owwww!'' This is not cheering.
</P>
<P>
   Phil remains cool as we walk one way, then another. ``Evasive
action. We have to be sure not to invade their comfort zone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What about my comfort zone?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're careful not to get behind any of them. They want to be
dominant, keep us in view. Fine. We want them to see us, realize we
mean no harm.'' Mwalimu knows what he's doing. We have just about
maneuvered to an opening but the protective mother, about 30 yards
distant, begins to advance our way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom, we come in peace,'' I mumble. ``Phil, why don't you call
a taxi.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good idea,'' he says, laughing and pulling out a walkie-talkie
to direct a driver to a spot he thinks the car and we can reach.
</P>
<P>
   Mom takes another giant step . . . reconsiders and turns around.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly a chorus line of female zebras rumbles through, a chain
gang tripping the light fantastic, breaking the tension. The ellies
are spreading out, going about their business.
</P>
<P>
   The field clear, we start walking to the spot where the driver,
Kilai Munyori, is waiting. He takes us to a shady grove and cooks
breakfast for other guests who've been riding horseback.
</P>
<P>
   Fried eggs and sausage taste very good. Phil raises a cup of
coffee, ``Here's to your digestion. May it be better than an
ellie's.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while I wasn't so sure. It seems a good time for a swim
and another look at elephants without taking evasive action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1406EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
