<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5584 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MEDIA-CULTURE-BOS &LR;      07-18 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-CULTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY CAN'T THE MEDIA STOP OVERRATING MEDIA EVENTS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oh what a difference a year makes. Just about this time last
summer, the media world was atwitter with expectations about Tina
Brown's new Talk magazine.
</P>
<P>
   In a carefully staged rollout, ``the queen of buzz'' _ as Brown
had become known during stops at Vanity Fair and The New Yorker _
previewed her first issue to a chosen few reporters, daintily
thumbing through the pages as if they were printed on gold leaf.
Talk's coming-out party at the Statue of Liberty attracted an array
of partygoers _ from Henry Kissinger to Madonna _ on the glitterati
A-list. Of Talk's launch, The (London) Independent gushed: ``the
media event of the year, if not the decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the headlines are different. ``Is Talk making a last
stand?'' The New York Post asked recently. In a particularly
pungent piece, Toronto's National Post called Brown and Hillary
Clinton former ``power babes,'' who'd been reduced to ``humbled,
sweaty working women with struggling start-ups.''
</P>
<P>
   The August issue of Talk _ with a cover shot of Elizabeth Hurley
kittenishly gnawing on some shiny jewelry _ epitomizes the
magazine's nagging identity problem. Part celebrity fanzine (the
Hurley story), part serious journalism (revisiting a 43-year-old
race crime in Alabama), and part Johnny-come-too-lately (excerpts
from screenwriter Joe Eszterhas's new book based on the
beaten-to-death Monica Lewinsky scandal), the magazine never found
a niche. Despite all the early hype, has anyone ever heard a real
person utter a syllable about Talk at the water cooler?
</P>
<P>
   So why did it take the big media mandarins a while to figure out
what the public intuitively sensed about Talk?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the audience in a lot of ways is a lot more
sophisticated than we give them credit for,'' says J. Max Robins,
senior editor at TV Guide.
</P>
<P>
   True, but there's something else at play. While influential
journalists create megahype and hyperbuzz about magazines like
``Talk,'' movies like ``The Insider,'' TV shows like ``Action'' and
Web sites like Inside.com, the public's response is often a
collective yawn. Observers say that's because there's a pop-culture
chasm between big media and the populace that mirrors the famous
``Beltway disconnect'' between political journalists who
hyperventilated over the Lewinsky story for a year and the
scandal-weary citizenry.
</P>
<P>
   The common thread here is media self-absorption. The Lewinsky
story generated so much coverage because it reinvigorated a
Washington press corps that had been rendered increasingly
irrelevant by the public's diminishing interest in politics. It's
not surprising, then, that the objects of the most lavish media
hype tend to come from the media.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Lichter, president of the Center for Media and Public
Affairs, refers to this phenomenon as the ``Buzzway.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
The way of buzz &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing fascinates the media more than the media,'' says
Lichter. ``There's always been a buzz production industry and I
think it's gotten more automated. Hype moves faster and it cuts
across more media lines.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about a culture of narcissism,'' adds media
critic Jon Katz. ``I think the media has become one of the most
disconnected elites in American life.''
</P>
<P>
   In the world of entertainment television, two recent ``Buzzway''
favorites were given their last rites by viewers. ``Sports Night,''
a comedy featuring clever, fast-talking journalists at an ESPN-like
network, was canceled by ABC. ``Action,'' a Fox comedy about the
outrageous inner workings of Hollywood (kind of ``Get Shorty''
without a protagonist), crashed and burned commercially.
</P>
<P>
   ``To this day, I think (``Action'') was really a funny show. It
was really edgy,'' says Robins. ``But it turned out to be too
inside-the-business to get the kind of audience you need to sustain
a network show.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant Gumbel's 1999 return to early morning news on CBS's ``The
Early Show'' was a media event huge enough to generate a New York
Times Magazine piece. Gumbel's story line was similar to Brown's:
Could the longtime ``Today'' anchor replicate his success at a new
network?
</P>
<P>
   The public couldn't have cared less. Ratings for ``The Early
Show'' were lousy until recently, when CBS managed to piggyback on
the success of its red-hot ``Survivor'' show by working it into the
morning-show format. (Perhaps Dawn Wells, the perky Mary Ann on
``Gilligan's Island'' who recently appeared on the show to discuss
``Survivor'' from her unique perspective, has as much to do with
the improving numbers as Gumbel.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Meet the press movie &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 movie that captivated the journalism world was ``The
Insider,'' a tale of how corporate pressure almost forced ``60
Minutes'' to spike an interview with a tobacco industry
whistleblower. This saga of network news intrigue and the hard
feelings between ``60 Minutes'' star Mike Wallace and the
filmmakers fascinated journalists and bored everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Insider'' is ``one of those classic media brawls that
media critics have an orgasm over. But the public doesn't give a
hoot,'' said Katz at the time. He was right. Though the film
garnered an Oscar nomination for best picture, it was far from
box-office boffo.
</P>
<P>
   On the radio dial, talk host Don Imus's proclivity to chat up
members of the chattering classes, such as Tim Russert and Dan
Rather, has rewarded him with heaps of big-media attention. Several
years ago, Time named him one of the 25 most influential Americans,
and in the July issue of George magazine he's one of a handful of
luminaries selected as the nation's ``New Patriots.''
</P>
<P>
   But Imus's numbers have never matched his hype. In Boston, where
he toils for new FM talk station WTKK, the latest ratings have his
morning show in 15th place. It is the happily incorrigible Howard
Stern, the subject of journalistic disdain, who dominates the
ratings in his time slot.
</P>
<P>
   In cyberspace, mediacentric Web sites such as Slate.com
(slate.msn.com) and the new Inside.com (www.inside.com) are all but
doomed, says Katz. The sites ``that are not successful are about
media themselves,'' he says. ``The central conceit . . . is the
idea that the media is inherently fascinating,'' but the Internet
ethos is all about openness and full access, not about restricting
content to insiders in the know.
</P>
<P>
   Lichter says the media establishment's tastes don't match the
public's because its members belong to an elite class that tends to
``share a perspective, a sensibility that diverges from middle
America. . . . It's more cultural than political.'' Several years
ago, the Center for Media and Public Affairs commissioned a poll
that asked 3,000 Americans whether they thought most journalists
shared their beliefs or values. More than half the respondents _ 53
percent _ said no.
</P>
<P>
   From the tizzy over Talk to the ruckus over ``Action,'' that
sure seems to be true when it comes to stoking the pop-culture hype
machine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1407EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
