<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5594 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-18 1300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER ENJOYMENT, BOTH NEAR AND FAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summer is a time to be festive. So, check out these fun
happenings.
</P>
<P>
   In Yarmouth, Maine, they say clam is king, and next weekend
they'll hold the 35th annual Clam Festival. Featured will be the
Medieval Festival of Cortona, Italy. The group of 20 players will
lead the parade at 6 p.m. Friday with flag performers, crossbow
champions, and musicians in medieval costumes. On Sunday afternoon,
the group will hold a crossbow tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The festival will offer music ranging from a popular Maine trio,
the Devonsquare, to the outrageous ditties of The Wicked Good Band.
There also will be a craft show, races, and the Maine State Clam
Shucking Championship.
</P>
<P>
   And, there will be lots of clams _ fried, stuffed, and cakes _
along with lobsters, oysters, shrimp, chicken, and more. For a
complete listing of events, call 207-846-3984 or visit
www.yarmouthmaine.org/clamfest.
</P>
<P>
   Head to Newport, R.I., for the 17th annual Black Ships Festival,
the city's annual Japanese-American celebration, July 20-23. More
than 50 events include a kite festival, a tea ceremony, a festival
of drums, and workshops. For information, call the festival hot
line at 401-846-2720.
</P>
<P>
   Key West, Fla., is holding its 20th annual Hemingway Days
Festival Wednesday through Sunday. There will be a Papa Hemingway
Look-Alike Contest to celebrate his birthday Friday, a marlin
tournament, a street fair, an offbeat Running of the Bulls, a
twilight party on the grounds of his former home, and an all-day,
all-night party at Sloppy Joe's Bar Wednesday. For information,
call 800-LAST KEY.
</P>
<P>
   And, in Asheville, N.C., the 34th annual Shindig on the Green is
offered Saturdays through Sept. 2 at the City/County Plaza
downtown. This celebration of traditional mountain dances and music
is free. It, however, will not be held Aug. 5 when the Mountain
Dance and Folk Festival takes place or July 29 during Bele Chere,
North Carolina's largest street festival. For information, call
800-280-0005 or visit www.ashevillechamber.org/music.htm.
</P>
