<HEADER>
A5598 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-18 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAINING A DEGREE, LOSING A PREPOSITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jane Holden's recent e-mail was just the latest in a steady
trickle of inquiries about a disappearing preposition. ``Since
moving to the Boston area I have often noted that the word graduate
is used with a direct object,'' she writes _ as in ``he never
graduated college.'' Everywhere else, the phrase was graduated from
college, and Holden wonders if the from-free variant is a regional
quirk or a ``newer, hipper version.''
</P>
<P>
   Previous correspondents have posed the same question, sometimes
more forcefully. ``I was taught that a school graduates its
students and that colloquially and informally we may say that a
student graduated from a school,'' wrote Michael Malamut last fall,
wondering why the from was suddenly evaporating. For once, there is
a simple answer: To graduate college may be gaining ground, but it
has no defenders I can discover in the world of usage commentary.
Graduate from, however, is acceptable everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   But of course there's more to the story. Half a century ago,
when I graduated college was elbowing its way into spoken English,
the language honchos were fighting a different battle over
graduate: whether it was properly used in the active voice at all.
During the first few centuries of graduation ceremonies, students
were graduated, passively, from their institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The first recorded instance of the student doing the graduating,
rather than having it done to him, dates to 1807 _ but the zealous
usagists of the later 19th-century language pounced on that form,
denouncing it loudly and sternly enough that Malamut's teacher,
among others, believed them. She graduated from college, however,
was eventually accepted as standard (not merely colloquial).
</P>
<P>
   Is she graduated college coasting in with the same ease? Well,
it is appearing more often in print than it did 25 years ago, and a
quick survey suggests that Holden's suspicion may be justified:
Newspapers in the Northeast seem more receptive to graduated
college. Sometimes it's in a quotation, but it also shows up in the
prose of well-educated writers, and not just the younger ones.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, other verbs have gone through more radical
transformations: Once upon a time a woman was delivered of a baby,
as in ``set free.'' Bergen and Cornelia Evans, in their 1957
Dictionary of Contemporary American Usage, approve of the still
controversial graduate from, but they won't budge on the
obstetrical question. ``Although it would seem that birth sets the
baby free even more than it does the mother, this hasn't been the
opinion of people old enough to talk about the matter. . . . it is
the mother, and not the child, who is delivered,'' they write. A
stork could always deliver a baby, but only in the past few decades
have we agreed that physicians and taxi drivers can deliver babies,
not just deliver mothers of babies.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's diagnose, still the subject of a mini-controversy
over whether it can be applied to a person. Although general usage
accepts ``My dog was diagnosed with obsessive-compulsive
disorder,'' a few people have insisted that only a disease, not a
person (or a dog) can be diagnosed. However, since this rule adds
nothing but excess verbiage _ ``He diagnosed my dog's affliction as
obsessive-compulsive disorder'' would be the approved form _ it's
had trouble attracting support among sensible people.
</P>
<P>
   And prepositions are just as variable as verbs _ arbitrary,
regional, inexplicable. We insist (so far) on graduating from
college, but some of us babysit for a child, while others babysit
the children and babysit for the parents, or whoever's paying. Some
dictionaries go one way, some the other _ though I have a hunch
that the disappearing for, like the fading from after graduate, is
a Northeastern phenomenon. (Babysit for was what they said in last
week's rerun of ``The West Wing,'' so it's surely not obsolete.)
</P>
<P>
   Stranger things have happened, languagewise, than dropping a
preposition; if our descendants still go to school in 2050, it may
be fine for them to say they've graduated college. But if you use
the phrase today, be warned: Some people will think you don't yet
deserve that degree.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Word appears alternate weeks throught the summer. Jan
Freeman's e-mail address is freeman(at)globe.com; write to her at
The Boston Globe, PO Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
