<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5601 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-SUPERCOMPUTER-ART     07-18 1562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SUPERCOMPUTER-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNLEASHING A SUPERCOMPUTER ON THE HUMAN GENOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAJA MISHRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The reigning ``world's fastest computer'' sits inside a lab just
east of San Francisco, a hockey-rink-sized machine named ASCI White
that spends its days simulating nuclear bomb blasts for the
goverment. This powerhouse can do 3.8 trillion calculations in a
single second, the equivalent of 50,000 desktop computers running
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   But, in a lab just north of New York City, such staggering
numbers get little more than a dismissive yawn. There, computer
architects for IBM are building the ``Next Big Thing'' in the world
of supercomputers. Blue Gene, designed to explore the intricacies
of human genetics, is expected to be 500 times faster than its West
Coast rival, also made by IBM.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our machine will make (ASCI White) look like a Palm Pilot,''
said Blue Gene's chief architect, Monty Denneau, referring to a
popular brand of pocket-sized electronic planners.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Gene is the most fantastic entry in the furiously growing
field of bioinformatics, where computing and biology merge to
unravel the genetic secrets at the heart of life. Already,
high-speed computers have been instrumental in mapping the 3
billion chemical letters in the human genome, the equivalent of a
100,000-page run-on sentence that contains all the operating
instructions for a human being.
</P>
<P>
   Computers will play an equally large role in deciphering the
sentence, specialists say. And understanding, in detail, how the
genetic process works will take Herculean computing power _ thus
Blue Gene.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to providing computer firepower for gene
exploration, the $100 million Blue Gene project is further proof
that post-genome medical research has taken a privileged place at
the top of the scientific heap. In years past, supercomputers were
primarily made for physics research, such as ASCI White's nuclear
simulations or showy demonstrations, such as Deep Blue's chess
games against top human opponents. Now, the DNA inside our cells
appears to be the target of choice.
</P>
<P>
   Denneau's team plans to run Blue Gene 24 hours a day for an
entire year to solve just one problem: How does a single protein
molecule form? Though it may sound esoteric, the question is
actually at the center of life because protein forms much of the
body and the chemicals that run it. DNA may be life's instructions,
but it's tens of thousands of different proteins that do all the
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of nature's most complex processes. And a very
important one,'' said Denneau, a former philosophy student and
accidental computer architect.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the goal of the DNA revolution is to understand and
manipulate what proteins do, paving the way for new medicines and
treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Modern genomics would not exist without the recent leaps in
computing power. Mapping the genome was, more than anything, a
computing problem. It took an army of computers working for both
the government's Human Genome Project and the private Celera
Genomics to decipher and string together the millions of A's, C's,
G's and T's in the genetic code. Figuring out what they mean will
take even more silicon prowess.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of bioinformatics companies have emerged in the last year
to help researchers process, compare and analyze all the data
streaming from the genome mapping teams. Creating gene-based cures
for cancer, brain diseases and numerous other illnesses hinges on
this computer work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The human genome accomplishment is the product of a confluence
of biology, chemistry and computing,'' said Tony White, chief
executive officer of PE Corp., the parent company of Maryland-based
Celera.
</P>
<P>
   PE Biosystems Group created high-powered genome mapping
computers that _ when paired with robots that sequence genes _
allowed the once-unfathomable task to be completed in a few years.
The Human Genome Project, something of a competitor to Celera and
PE Corp., even bought some.
</P>
<P>
   Still, until now, the race for the world's fastest computer has
centered on the federal government's nuclear blast simulation
project, Accelerated Strategic Computing Initiative or ASCI.
</P>
<P>
   Intel upped the ante last year when it produced ASCI Red, which
broke the barrier of 1 trillion calculations per second. ASCI
White, formally unveiled earlier this month, is IBM's reply with a
speed of 3.8 trillion calculations per second. Blue Gene will do
one quadrillion calculations per second. (Translation: That's a one
followed by 15 zeros.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, there's a bit of competition. You want to beat the next
guy,'' Denneau said.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Gene's ancestor, Deep Blue, captured headlines in 1997 by
beating world chess champion, Garry Kasparov, at his own game.
Chess has its obvious complexity: All the different pieces moving
on an ever-changing board. But protein creation, with more than
30,000 atoms pushing on one another to give it shape, humbles the
64-square chess board.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the growing army of gene-hunting and drug development
companies don't need the supercomputer's help to go forward. But,
once Blue Gene solves its protein problem, researchers will be able
to visualize, at a very basic level, how life is created through
the interaction of DNA and protein.
</P>
<P>
   ``To understand how the body works, we're going to have to
understand how protein works,'' said Dr. Joel Habener, director of
molecular endocrinology at Massachusetts General Hospital, who
researches the genetic roots of diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   To simulate the birth of a protein, Blue Gene begins with
ultrafast processors capable of 1 billion operations per second.
Thirty-two of these will be crammed on a single computer chip; 64
of these chips will be put on one computer board. And Blue Gene
will come to life when 512 of these boards, with more than a
million chips, are linked.
</P>
<P>
   The supercomputer's genius lies in the novel and efficient way
all these chips will talk to each other. The communications system
is so powerful, it could download the entire contents of the
Internet, every Web page and e-mail, in a second. And, once Blue
Gene starts on the protein problem, the chips will have much to
talk about.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works: DNA is made of chemical bases _ adenine,
cytosine, guanine and thymine _ which researchers commonly refer to
by their initials, A, C, G and T. They are fed into each cell's
protein-making organ. For every three letters in, one amino acid
comes out. Three more, and another amino acid forms, until there is
a long chain of connected amino acids. This chain is protein, and
it's eventually cut loose to do its work.
</P>
<P>
   But the work a protein does depends on the amino acids it's made
of and what it looks like. The chain isn't long and straight. It's
all twisted like a crumpled ribbon. Blue Gene's task is to figure
out the shape of this crumpled atomic ribbon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem,'' Denneau said, ``is all these atoms are exerting
force on all the other atoms.''
</P>
<P>
   The average protein consists of about 300 amino acids, and some
have more than 1,000, making it an almost infinitely complex
molecule. There are more possible forms for a single average-sized
protein than there are atoms in the entire universe. (Translation _
a lot.)
</P>
<P>
   The twisted, folded shape of each protein determines how it
functions. Proteins bind with each other, causing crucial chemical
reactions and the creation of body tissue. They fit together like
lock and key. If a protein is folded incorrectly, because of a
single defect in the gene code, it may not fit into its proper
lock, depriving the body of an important function. This is how many
diseases are caused.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of research today is trial and error,'' said Habener of
MGH. ``If we knew the exact structure of a protein, we could
eliminate a lot of the guesswork.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue Gene was born in the intellectually fecund hallways of
IBM's research labs in Yorktown Heights, N.Y., where physicists and
biologists roam next to computer scientists _ with the
bean-counting business types off in another building. The idea of a
protein-modeling supercomputer was first raised in a chance hallway
encounter between a biologist and Denneau.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know who you'll run into,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the IBM lab has created numerous bomb simulators.
Then there was the supercomputer that confirmed the weight of the
proton, one of the tiny particles that make up matter. It took
seven years, then the computer was mothballed.
</P>
<P>
   More often, however, in the process of designing these computing
behemoths, researchers develop practical money-making technologies.
</P>
<P>
   With the intellectual heavy lifting for Blue Gene mostly done,
Denneau and his crew are already contemplating the next challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone told me just a few months ago, we're going to
understand all the metabolic pathways in a cell. We might try to
model the cell. That would be staggering,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one computer that continues to humble these
scientists _ the human brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe someday we'll model human intelligence,'' Denneau said.
``But right now we're just specks of sand in that regard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1413EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
