<HEADLINE>
WHAT MAKES YOUR SKIN DARKEN WHEN YOU USE TANNING CREAMS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. How do artificial tanning products work? Are they just paint,
or what?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  T. P., Boston
</P>
<P>
   A. There are several ways to simulate a tan without actually
exposing your skin to dangerous ultraviolet light. You can take
pills containing carotene and carotene-like compounds that will
lend your skin a bit of color, though you tend to come out looking
more orange than tanned. Some creams do contain dyes that simply
stain your skin. The most popular and effective tanning products
are creams containing dihydroxyacetone, a simple sugar that is
nontoxic, and that binds to amino acids in proteins in your skin to
form colored compounds called melanoidins.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction between sugars and proteins is called the Maillard
reaction, after a Frenchman who first described it in 1912. The
same reaction contributes to many of the interesting brown colors
in food, from the skin of a Christmas turkey to the golden brown
color of beer.
</P>
<P>
   It is important to note that the browning you get from a pill or
a tube of cream is not likely to protect you much from the sun, so
you still need to stay in the shade and use sun-block.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail your questions to drknowledge(at)globe.com; or send fax to:
617-929-9263, or a letter to Dr. Knowledge, The Boston Globe,
Health/Science Section, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107. Please include
your initials and hometown. Selected questions of general interest
will be answered.
</P>
</TEXT>
