<HEADLINE>
IN JERUSALEM, ENMITIES YIELDING TO A FRAGILE HOPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The spirit of reconciliation seems buried under the
weight of the Old City's ancient stones, which retain the scorching
summer heat here as the Jewish, Christian, and Muslim faithful
throng to their holy sites.
</P>
<P>
   But in the cool, antiseptic environs of the maternity ward at
Haddasah Hospital on Mount Scopus, the cries of newborns seemed to
awaken hope Monday that a solution can be found on the future of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   In a city sharply divided by culture, politics, and religion,
and which both Palestinians and Israelis insist on as their
capital, the Hadassah maternity ward is one of few places where the
two sides seem intimately bound together, in this case by the joy
of birth. And to those here Monday the possibility that the
negotiators at Camp David could make a breakthrough on Jerusalem
did seem possible, even necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should be locked in a room and kept there until there is
an agreement, because what we have here is not a life,'' said Gary
Hughes, 40, an immigrant to Israel from England.
</P>
<P>
   He looked exhausted after helping his wife, Margolit, deliver
their daughter, Maya, who he boasted was ``our first ``sabra,'' the
Hebrew word for the tough little cactus that is used to describe
Jewish children born in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be an agreement, or there is no future for any
of these babies, whether they're Israeli or Palestinian,'' he said,
as Israeli and Palestinian women in pink bathrobes wheeled newborns
to and from the nursery.
</P>
<P>
   Hanadi Mustafa, 25, a Palestinian woman from the nearby village
of Isawiya, was cradling her new baby girl, who did not yet have a
name: ``There is a way for the leaders to agree, God willing. There
are extremists on both sides, but most people just want a better
future.''
</P>
<P>
   In the next two days, perhaps even before these mothers and
their newborns go home, the fate of Jerusalem could be determined.
</P>
<P>
   At Camp David, the Palestinian and Israeli leaders were said to
be working hard Monday on a series of proposals that could resolve
the rival claims to Jerusalem. The Israelis reportedly summoned
Reuven Merhav, a specialist on Jerusalem issues, from Israel. He
was expected to help map out a proposal to grant Palestinians rule
of East Jerusalem in exchange for grafting surrounding West Bank
settlements onto West Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   West Jerusalem is today predominantly Jewish. East Jerusalem and
the Old City, which were captured by Israel from Jordan in 1967,
are mainly Palestinian.
</P>
<P>
   In practical terms, the two sides live in deeply divided
communities. West Jerusalem is a modern city of secular and
religious Israelis who live amid shopping malls, clean boulevards,
parks with green grass, McDonald's restaurants, Blockbuster Video
stores, and Tower Records.
</P>
<P>
   East Jerusalem is a different story. Israeli police and army
units patrol intensively. But residents say municipal services in
Palestinian areas are badly neglected, while the Israeli government
pumps millions of dollars into expanding and improving Jewish
settlements around Palestinian neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the Palestinian areas of East Jerusalem are
already under the de facto control of Yasser Arafat's Palestinian
Authority. Palestinian plainclothes police work the streets and the
school curriculum is set by Palestinian educators. Palestinians
vote for their parliament and have their own representatives in the
Palestinian Legislative Council.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Seidemann, a Jerusalem lawyer and longtime peace
activist, said that at the Camp David negotiations, ``the point is
not to create something new, but to tell the truth about something
that already exists.''
</P>
<P>
   But Israel has long maintained that Jerusalem is its ``eternal
and indivisible'' capital, and the more hardline opposition, made
up largely of religious Jewish parties, is pressuring Prime
Minister Barak not to allow a divided city.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians claim that East Jerusalem was taken from them
during the 1967 war and, according to UN resolutions, must be
returned. They say East Jerusalem and the Old City are the rightful
place for the capital of an independent state that Arafat has vowed
to declare this fall, with or without an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   And so the two leaders at the Camp David summit, hosted by
President Clinton, are struggling to find a way to share control of
a city coveted through the ages.
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem could make or break a peace deal at Camp David. An
agreement on Jerusalem could end 52 years of Arab-Israeli conflict
and open the way for other tough issues to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Failure to agree on Jerusalem could undermine diligent efforts
on other fronts, and possibly reignite violence. Other issues
include the final borders between Israel and those parts of the
West Bank that will fall under Palestinian rule, as well as the
fate of 3 million Palestinian refugees uprooted by wars in 1948 and
1967.
</P>
<P>
   To understand just how powerfully emotional is the battle for
Jerusalem, enter Damascus Gate and walk the cobblestones of El Wad
Street in the Old City, with its Ottoman-era walls and its ancient
warren of streets and alleys.
</P>
<P>
   The narrow, winding street is a melange of smells of spice and
Turkish coffee and a mix of sounds of the Muslim call to prayer, of
church bells, of the crackling of Israeli soldiers' radios, and
blaring Arab pop music.
</P>
<P>
   El Wad skirts the ``Via Dolorosa'' where Jesus is believed to
have carried the cross, then winds its way to the entrance to the
plaza of the Western Wall, the holiest site in Judaism and all that
remains of the Second Temple destroyed by Romans in the year 70
A.D. It also leads to the passage that brings Muslims to the Dome
of the Rock, where tradition holds that the prophet Mohammed
ascended to heaven. Muslims call the raised 35-acre space where the
golden dome shimmers by the name al-Haram al Sharif. Jews call it
the Temple Mount, and under it are the remains of the destroyed
temples.
</P>
<P>
   Chaim Yishai, 24, a Jewish settler with a knitted kippah on his
head and a pistol strapped to his waist, rushed for prayers at the
Western Wall Monday, saying, ``Just open the Bible and read, this
city was always Jewish. For 2,000 years we dreamed of returning,
and we prayed. Why should we give an inch, and why should we give
up the dream of rebuilding the Temple?''
</P>
<P>
   Along the same path, Hassan Abu Zneid, 40, was heading to his
job as a guard at the Dome of the Rock. ``If the Jews ever try to
lay a finger on our mosque, there will be war,'' he warned. ``This
is a place for all three religions, but East Jerusalem and the Old
City are Palestinian. It must be under Palestinian rule or there
will be violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Minister of Justice Yossi Beilen, an architect of the
1993 Israeli-Palestinian accord at Oslo, said a solution on the
future of Jerusalem, which may be the most intractable problem the
two sides face, could open the door to solving all other issues.
</P>
<P>
   That, analysts here suggest, is why Clinton has pushed Barak and
Arafat to begin the negotiations with the Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we solve Jerusalem, we can show we can solve the other
problems,'' said Beilen in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem's mayor, Ehud Olmert, a member of the conservative
opposition Likud Party, vehemently disagrees, and he joined some
150,000 demonstrators in Tel Aviv to make their point clear to
Barak, who faces a domestic political crisis upon his return, with
or without an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerusalem is the heart of Jewish existence,'' said Olmert.
``It is not a heart to Muslims or to Christians.''
</P>
<P>
   Illustrating with maps of Jewish and Palestinian populations in
the east and west sides of the city as he spoke in his office,
Olmert dismissed proposals for shared rule of Jerusalem as ``not a
solution, but a prescription for almost endless conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a half-mile down the road, across what was the ``no man's
land'' separating the two sides of Jerusalem between the wars of
1948 and 1967, is Orient House in East Jerusalem, which has become
the focal point for the Palestinian leadership and administration.
Faisal Husseini, the Palestinian official responsible for Jerusalem
affairs, held a town meeting last week, where Muslim and Christian
clerics and community leaders gathered to express the intense
feeling in the streets that there can be no peace without
Palestinian control of East Jerusalem as it existed before the 1967
war.
</P>
<P>
   That is ``clearly what is called for in Resolution 242,'' said
Husseini, referring to the UN Security council's action. The
Israeli-Palestinian ``Declaration of Principles'' signed on the
White House lawn on Sept. 13, 1993, he went on, says that ``the
negotiations on permanent status will lead to the implementation of
Security Council Resolution 242,'' approved in 1967 and ordered the
withdrawal of Israeli troops from occupied territories.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the emotion on both sides, the Israeli-funded Hadassah
Hospital that is among the more advanced medical care facilities in
the world, stands as a practical, modern reality, perhaps even a
model of coexistence in which it seems possible to see Palestinians
and Israelis learning to live together.
</P>
<P>
   The staff is mostly Israeli, but there are Palestinian doctors
and nurses as well. The patients are a mix, people struggling with
illness and rejoicing in birth in side-by-side beds.
</P>
<P>
   George Moshe, 60, an Iranian-born Jew who works as a security
guard in the Israeli parliament and became a grandfather Monday,
spoke there with the wisdom of age: ``When my daughter was born, we
hoped she would never go to the army. Now she has a baby, and we
find ourselves hoping again. Every generation wants it to be better
for the next, and we hope our leaders know that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
