   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of WEDNESDAY, July
19.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE AND ENTERTAINMENT
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `e' category)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BOLSHOI-DANCERS (New York) _ Svetlana Lunkina and Maria
Alexandrova are the darlings of ballet critics in Russia and in
England. They have a faunlike delicacy that suggests they might
break if touched. But as the two young Bolshoi Ballet stars talked
in New York, it quickly became apparent that underneath that
fragility lay strong wills and even stronger senses of self. By
Jennifer Dunning.
</P>
<P>
   NY-HARLEM-GALLERY (New York) _ In the fall of 1998, Christian
Haye, a New York poet and art critic, opened a gallery of
contemporary art. He called it The Project and presented an
impressive lineup of artists from the Americas, Europe, Africa and
Asia. But if prime location is everything for a start-up venture,
there was a potential handicap. The gallery wasn't situated within
Manhattan's carefully defined downtown art geography. It was in a
former disco on West 126th Street in Harlem. But Haye has turned
being out-of-the-way into a mark of distinction. By Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   KAISER-KENNEDY-CENTER (Undated) _ Michael Kaiser, the American
who helped rescue London's Royal Opera House from its financial
crisis and internal feuding, is to be named Wednesday as president
of the Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. By Irvin Molotsky.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-OPERA-FESTIVAL (Aix-en-Provence) _ Things have been going
well for the international opera festival of Aix-en-Provence since
it underwent a management shake-up in 1998. This year's festival,
which runs through July 28, includes four new productions and a
repeat from 1999 presented by big-name conductors and directors,
while its sold-out houses visibly sparkle with European elites. By
Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   JAMES-DEAN-FILM (Undated) _ For years, film studios have toyed
with projects about James Dean but were locked in a Catch-22:
studios would only finance the movie with a star _ or at least a
name actor. But these actors shied away from playing the 1950s
icon. Now, a film, called ``James Dean: An Invented Life,'' is in
production in Los Angeles, and will be shown next year. By Bernard
Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   PAPERS-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Readers of Andre Aciman's earlier
work will not be surprised by the rapture over the personal past in
his new book of essays, ``False Papers: Essays on Exile and
Memory.'' In ``Out of Egypt,'' Aciman searched his memory for the
city of Alexandria, Egypt, where he spent his childhood, and this
new book is a sort of sequel to the earlier one. Reviewed by
Richard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   MISSISSIPPI-TV-REVIEW (Undated) _ Almost every-other Wednesday
night at 11, through the end of the year, weather disaster buffs
can have a nightcap of typhoons, hurricanes, avalanches and floods.
The History Channel series begins Wednesday with ``Mississippi:
River out of Control,'' about the terrible flood of 1927 that
killed between 500 and 1,000 people and left almost 1 million more
homeless. By Julie Salamon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `d' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RESERVATION-LIES (New York) _ During the last year or so,
restaurateurs all over the city say that lying about reservations
has spiraled out of control. People want what they want when they
want it, and well, if they didn't plan in advance, they're just
going to show up and demand it. By Alex Witchel.
</P>
<P>
   COOKING-LAVENDER (New York) _ In Provence, lavender is used
mostly for its fragrance. But in New York, far from the capital of
this redolent crop, a strange thing happened when farmers started
selling lavender. People started cooking with it. By Florence
Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   MEAT-LABELS (Undated) _ Nutrition labeling is mandatory for
virtually every food but fresh meat and poultry, because those
products are regulated by the Department of Agriculture. Meat and
poultry producers may soon have to provide the same nutritional
information as other food producers. By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   GARLIC-FARMERS (Undated) _ Ray Bradley, one of about 20 farmers
selling new garlic at New York City's Greenmarkets, came to farming
through haute cuisine's back door, as a chef in some of the city's
top restaurants. By Deborah Baldwin.
</P>
<P>
   OLIVE-OILS (Undated) _ In a world awash in olive oil, it is hard
to imagine a new one that could merit singling out. But several
olive oils, and one innovative grapeseed oil, are worthy of the
attention of the serious cook. By Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   SORBET (Undated) _ A good sorbet should taste like an extraction
of its main flavor, and nothing else. There are almost no
limitations on flavors; they can be summer fruits like peaches,
blackberries and nectarines, or spices, chocolate, herbs or
spirits. Some chefs have recently taken to making almost-ice-cream
sorbets with fromage blanc, sour cream or even goat cheese. All of
them are able to stand out without compromise. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (New York) _ The column: Cooking basil-crusted loin
of lamb with Michel Richard, the chef and owner of Citronelle in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: On cooking sorrel
chicken. By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (Undated) _ The weekly wine column: On the San
Francisco International Wine Competition, which featured wines from
16 countries and 22 U.S. states.By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   TASTINGS (Undated) _ The column: On Beaujolais. By Erik Asimov.
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `s' category)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN (St. Andrews, Scotland) _ Sports of the
Times column on the British Open and the memory of Old Tom Morris.
By Dave Anderson.
