<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-SUMMIT _ THURMONT, Md. _ With time running down before
President Clinton is scheduled to leave for a G8 summit in Japan,
final status peace talks between Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators took on a palpable sense of urgency
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday. A news blackout remained over the talks at nearby Camp
David, but a White House spokesman said the two sides were down to
the nitty-gritty issues. Meanwhile, an Arab American group released
a poll of likely U.S. voters showing
</P>
<P>
   that a majority favor establishing a Palestinian state anbd
divided Jerusalem. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Expected to move by 4 p.m. (ET) on the NYT Wire in both
</P>
<P>
   International/Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   INTERIOR _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate approved a %15.5 billion
Interior spending bill that has $23 million earmarked for
Everglades restoration. In a related action, the Senate Energy and
Natural Resources Committee voted to allocate part of the royalties
from offshore drilling to conservation activities. (Lipman and
O'Dell, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   OFFSHORE-DRILLING _ WASHINGTON _ Senate Energy and Natural
Resources Committee meets to mark up legislation that would
allocate part of the royalties from offshore drilling to
conservation activities. (O'Dell, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL-ABORTION _ Anti-choice zealots in the U.S. House of
Representatives are at it again. Last year, they blackmailed
President Clinton into including an amendment barring aid to
international family planning organizations in a United Nations
funding bill. Last week GOP conservatives killed a bipartisan
amendment to remove the so called `` gag rule'' from the annual
foreign aid bill. (The Atlanta Constitution). 10.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Ads on overhead luggage bins of airliners are
just one more way for advertisers to get in your face every waking
moment. (Teepen, Cox News Service). MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Howard Kleinberg says that if the tax codes
are ever re-written, consideration should be give to the ``trickle
up'' theory. Kleinberg says that the principal of this theory is
that helping the little guy in turn helps wealthier taxpayers.
(Kleinberg, Cox News Service). MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ The biggest asparagus fern
I've ever seen lived in a gigantic terra cotta pot on my
grandmother's front porch in Jacksonville. For as many years as I
knew her, which were too few I'm thinking now, that fern welcomed
visitors to the row of rocking chairs she shared with friends and
family. It even had a name _ Bessie. (Schuett, Cox News Service)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ John Young is on vacation. His column will resume
shortly.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   GAPAC-ANALYSTS _ Georgia Pacific briefs analysts after
yesterday's merger announcement. which was greeted with a lot of
questions. (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Story will be based on 5 p.m. meeting in New York.
</P>
<P>
   RENTAL _ Aaron Rents is buying a furniture plant in Texas and
expanding another in South Georgia as it continues adding stores.
Chairman Charles Loudermilk, who's in his mid-70s, says he isn't
ready to retire but has four potential successors in line at the
Atlanta based furniture rental company. (DeGross, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CCE-EARN _ Coca-Cola Enterprises reported today that net income
in the second quarter rose to $122 million, or 29 cents a share,
beating Wall Street estimates by a penny. (Unger, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HEADHUNTER _HeadHunter.com announces a merger that will make it
second largest job site on the web after Monster.com, also
announces 2Q earnings. (Brister, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ Personal finance advice. This week: Online brokers.
(Ezell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WHEELS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET WHEELS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   Art includes three color photographs
</P>
<P>
   COXNET WHEELS 0715: 2000 ISUZU RODEO _ Although the 2000 Isuzu
Rodeo is a quite civilized sport-utility vehicle, it will issue
reminders that Isuzu is a truck manufacturer and not a carmaker.
The ride is noticeably trucklike, and not even Isuzu's Intelligent
Suspension Control system (ISC) prevents that. (DeVault, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes a 3-column color photo of the
2000 Isuzu Rodeo and a 2-column color photo of the SUV's interior.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   AT A GLANCE _ Fact box previewing the 2000 Isuzu Rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   THE MECHANIC _ Hoses must endure tough conditions to survive.
Hoses come in many shapes and sizes, yet all have one thing in
common: They are expected to perform their jobs in an environment
that typically exceeds 200 degrees. (Carter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). Includes 1-column color photograph of
columnist.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPICS-SYDNEY _ SYDNEY, Australia _ It's Friday night, and the
musky aroma of Australian manhood saturates the Oaks, a pub on the
north side of Sydney Harbour that's as big as a Wal-Mart. Mobs of
men are standing around talking rugby over schooners of beer. Some
are furiously working the slot machines everyone calls ``pokies.''
Others are charring slabs of meat on a barbecue pit out in the
courtyard. There's something odd about the round table by the door.
Not only does it include several women _ eating pizza no less _ but
some of their accents sound rather alien. ``I remember when I left
Atlanta,'' one of them says, ``my mover asked, `What's the deal
with Sydney? It seems like we've been moving everyone to Sydney.'''
The deal with Sydney, of course, is the Olympics. Four years ago
tonight, Muhammad Ali lit the caldron that signaled Atlanta's star
turn on the world stage. For some Atlantans, it wasn't enough. At
least 200 veterans of the 1996 Games have moved on to Australia to
be part of the first Olympics of the new millennium. (Auchmutey,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 34.
</P>
<P>
   RACE _ A question of race. In a different time and a different
place a young teacher answered a student's question _ would she
teach if black students were admitted to their all-white school? _
and unwittingly stoked a national fire. ``I said I'd teach any
student.'' (Kalajian, Palm beach Post). 70. WITH ART.
</P>
<P>
   FOODWINE-COLUMN _ A swirl here, a sip there . . . (Fisher,
Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is Mark Fisher's wine column.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTSTVTOUR_ PASADENA Calif. _ Garry Shandling is
sure to shake up the Emmys when he is the host this September. Also
talks about Kirk Cameron on being a father, obscure stats on ``Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire'' and ABCs new series. (Thompson, Palm
Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   TVCOLUMN _From L.A. Will lede with chat with Charlie Sheen,
who's replacing Michael J. Fox on ``Sp Andrews today after spending
a week in Ireland working on his game. Woods understands what's at
stake when the British Open begins on Thursday: He can become the
fifth golfer to win the career Grand Slam. (Sheeley, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-BROPEN-TIGER _ ST. ANDREWS, SCOTLAND _ Main story on Tiger
Woods trying to join exclusive Grand Slam club. It will include
