<TEXT>
<P>
   Entertainment and culture stories from The N.Y. Times News
Service for Wednesday, July 19.
</P>
<P>
   BOLSHOI-DANCERS (New York) _ Svetlana Lunkina and Maria
Alexandrova are the darlings of ballet critics in Russia and in
England. They have a faunlike delicacy that suggests they might
break if touched. But as the two young Bolshoi Ballet stars talked
in New York, it quickly became apparent that underneath that
fragility lay strong wills and even stronger senses of self. By
Jennifer Dunning.
</P>
<P>
   NY-HARLEM-GALLERY (New York) _ In the fall of 1998, Christian
Haye, a New York poet and art critic, opened a gallery of
contemporary art. He called it The Project and presented an
impressive lineup of artists from the Americas, Europe, Africa and
Asia. But if prime location is everything for a start-up venture,
there was a potential handicap. The gallery wasn't situated within
Manhattan's carefully defined downtown art geography. It was in a
former disco on West 126th Street in Harlem. But Haye has turned
being out-of-the-way into a mark of distinction. By Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   KAISER-KENNEDY-CENTER (Undated) _ Michael Kaiser, the American
who helped rescue London's Royal Opera House from its financial
crisis and internal feuding, is to be named Wednesday as president
of the Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. By Irvin Molotsky.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-OPERA-FESTIVAL (Aix-en-Provence) _ Things have been going
well for the international opera festival of Aix-en-Provence since
it underwent a management shake-up in 1998. This year's festival,
which runs through July 28, includes four new productions and a
repeat from 1999 presented by big-name conductors and directors,
while its sold-out houses visibly sparkle with European elites. By
Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   JAMES-DEAN-FILM (Undated) _ For years, film studios have toyed
with projects about James Dean but were locked in a Catch-22:
studios would finance the movie only with a star _ or at least a
name actor. But these actors shied away from playing the 1950s
icon. Now, a film, called ``James Dean: An Invented Life,'' is in
production in Los Angeles, and will be shown next year. By Bernard
Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   PAPERS-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Readers of Andre Aciman's earlier
work will not be surprised by this rapture over the personal past
in his new book of essays, ``False Papers: Essays on Exile and
Memory.'' In ``Out of Egypt,'' Aciman searched his memory for the
city of Alexandria, Egypt, where he spent his childhood, and this
new book is a sort of sequel to the earlier one. Reviewed by
Richard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   MISSISSIPPI-TV-REVIEW (Undated) _ Almost every-other Wednesday
night at 11, through the end of the year, weather disaster buffs
can have a nightcap of typhoons, hurricanes, avalanches and floods.
The History Channel series begins Wednesday with ``Mississippi:
River out of Control,'' about the terrible flood of 1927 that
killed between 500 and 1,000 people and left almost 1 million more
homeless. By Julie Salamon.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at
888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927. And be sure to look for other
entertainment stories from our partners: The Boston Globe, Cox News
Service, Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona
Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles
Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
