<SLUG> BC-DINING-NYT-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Food and dining stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Wednesday, July 19:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RESERVATION-LIES (New York) _ During the last year or so,
restaurateurs all over the city say that lying about reservations
has spiraled out of control. People want what they want when they
want it, and, well, if they didn't plan in advance, they're just
going to show up and demand it. By Alex Witchel.
</P>
<P>
   COOKING-LAVENDER (New York) _ In Provence, lavender is used
mostly for its fragrance. But in New York, far from the capital of
this redolent crop, a strange thing happened when farmers started
selling lavender. People started cooking with it. By Florence
Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   MEAT-LABELS (Undated) _ Nutrition labeling is mandatory for
virtually every food but fresh meat and poultry because those
products are regulated by the Department of Agriculture. Meat and
poultry producers may soon have to provide the same nutritional
information as other food producers. By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   GARLIC-FARMERS (Undated) _ Ray Bradley, one of about 20 farmers
selling new garlic at New York City's Greenmarkets, came to farming
through haute cuisine's back door, as a chef in some of the city's
top restaurants. By Deborah Baldwin.
</P>
<P>
   OLIVE-OILS (Undated) _ In a world awash in olive oil, it is hard
to imagine a new one that could merit singling out. But several
olive oils, and one innovative grapeseed oil, are worthy of the
attention of the serious cook. By Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   SORBET (Undated) _ A good sorbet should taste like an extraction
of its main flavor, and nothing else. There are almost no
limitations on flavors; they can be summer fruits like peaches,
blackberries and nectarines, or spices, chocolate, herbs or
spirits. Some chefs have recently taken to making almost-ice-cream
sorbets with fromage blanc, sour cream or even goat cheese. All of
them are able to stand out without compromise. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (New York) _ The column: Cooking basil-crusted loin
of lamb with Michel Richard, the chef and owner of Citronelle in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: On cooking sorrel
chicken. By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (Undated) _ The weekly wine column: On the San
Francisco International Wine Competition, which featured wines from
16 countries and 22 U.S. states.By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   TASTINGS (Undated) _ The column: On Beaujolais. By Erik Asimov.
</P>
<P>
   We expect to move all Dining Section stories by early evening
with a ``d'' category code, unless otherwise indicated.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at
888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927. And be sure to look for other stories
from our partners: The Boston Globe, Cox News Service, Hearst
Newspapers, The Arizona Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle and
Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
