<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HAND-HELD COMPUTERS MAKE A COLORFUL DEBUT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to some technopundits, the future of computing is in
the palm of your hand. Hand-held computing devices, they argue,
will soon supplant the PC as the primary way people communicate and
access the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   I've long been a skeptic of this point of view. Hand-helds are
cool for retrieving information, but frustrating for storing and
massaging it.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise that the most common way for putting data into
a so-called palmtop is by first attaching it to a PC, then using
software to manage the transfer.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at two devices that are cool to have on hand _ pun
intended:
</P>
<P>
   Palm IIIc _ $449, Palm Computing. Fans of the Palm brand of
hand-held computers have been dying for a color model for years.
The folks at Palm Computing have held off, though, because color -
while pretty - adds expense and robs battery life.
</P>
<P>
   But they couldn't delay much longer, because Microsoft and its
hardware partners have been aggressive about offering color
versions of their Windows CE and now Pocket Windows hand-helds.
Finally, Palm junkies can get what they need in semi-glorious
color.
</P>
<P>
   I say semi-glorious because the Palm IIIc is somewhat
underwhelming, a kind of technological anti-climax. Color on the
Palm operating system is not that impressive - in fact, it's about
one step up from the kind of hues you find on Nintendo's Color
GameBoy.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm IIIc comes with eight 8 megabytes of memory, which can
hold 10,000 addresses or 3,000 appointments. It has all the
standard applications found in other Palm units - a date book,
to-do list, contacts, an expense application, e-mail, a calculator
and more. It's just slightly thicker than the regular Palm III, and
much thicker than the cool, ultra-slim Palm V.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other Palms, it does not use replaceable AAA batteries.
Instead, it has built-in lithium ion batteries that give an average
of about two weeks' service on a full charge. The cradle that you
use to synchronize the Palm IIIc with data on your PC or Macintosh
charges the batteries.
</P>
<P>
   If you're good about dropping it into the cradle every few days,
you'll probably never get a low-battery warning.
</P>
<P>
   The software that handles the transfer and synchronization of
data is excellent, and can get calendar and contact information
from a variety of key programs, including Outlook and Act! On the
PC, it connects via serial port, and an optional USB kits allows it
to hook up to USB-equipped Macs.
</P>
<P>
   While it's nice to finally have color on the Palm, I'm not sure
it's worth the added cost. The Palm IIIxe, which has comparable
specifications, is $200 less. I'd rather save the cash and look up
phone numbers in black and white.
</P>
<P>
   iPaq Pocket PC _ $499, Compaq Computer Corp. Like the Palm IIIc,
this hand-held device isn't cheap. But it's just about as
cool-looking as it gets, and its use of color is much more
effective than that of the Palm.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq, playing off the buzz its iPaq business PC has gotten,
named its newest hand-held after the stylish desktop. It even has
designed the Pocket PC so it looks a little like the iPaq when
dropped into its synchronization and charging cradle.
</P>
<P>
   The iPaq Pocket PC comes in a brushed-chrome case that's
significantly heavier than the Palm IIIc _ you'll definitely know
it's there if you drop it into a shirt pocket. It comes with 32 MB
of system memory.
</P>
<P>
   It uses Microsoft's Windows for Pocket PC operating system,
which is a much-improved version of the original Windows CE
software found in earlier hand-helds. It takes a very different
approach from the Palm OS, which strives for simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   Windows for Pocket PC is very much like its namesake _ it has a
little bit of everything, from slimmed-down versions of Word and
Excel to a simplified version of Internet Explorer. The opening
screen, which resembles the Today screen from Outlook, shows your
upcoming appointments and unread e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   There's even a voice recorder, an MP3 player and movie viewer.
While the sound isn't stellar and the images are a little grainy,
it raises all kinds of possibilities. How about Napster for Pocket
PC?
</P>
<P>
   I really like the color screen on the iPaq Pocket PC. It's much
better than earlier Compaq color hand-helds, and definitely more
impressive than the Palm IIIc. The Windows operating system also
makes better use of color.
</P>
<P>
   But it does have a price. I got about four days' worth of
battery power on a single charge, which isn't bad, considering how
bright the screen can get. As with the Palm, conscientiously
dropping it regularly into the charging cradle renders battery life
a non-issue.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't care much for Microsoft's synchronization software,
ActiveSync, which pales in comparison with the Palm software.
However, the Pocket PC does connect to a Windows computer using the
USB port, which makes for fast transfers.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Palm and the iPaq come with modules that let you get
e-mail and wirelessly surf the Web. The iPaq has an interesting way
of accepting add-ons - they come in the form of a jacket that wraps
around it. This adds quite a bit of thickness and weight, however.
</P>
<P>
   The Compaq device is more expensive than the Palm, but frankly
you get more for your money. The display is better and the iPaq has
more built-in functions. If color is crucial to you when
considering a hand-held, this is the better choice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
