</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     USEFUL WEB SITES CAN GIVE YOUR CAREER A BOOST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I love asking job applicants, ``What's your
favorite Web site?''
</P>
<P>
   It's mostly a throwaway question, but what I like about it is
that the best answers are honest ones, not rehearsed ones. After
all, no book can give you the ``right'' answer to that question; it
all depends on what the interviewer is looking for.
</P>
<P>
   So what am I looking for? A pilot light, some sign that the
person in front of me is enthused about something on Earth other
than the particular job I'm offering. And that the person has been
curious enough to experiment with the Internet, even if it's not a
job requirement.
</P>
<P>
   There is no right answer, just a wrong one: ``I've never used
the Internet.'' OK. I'll keep you in mind the next time I'm
choosing people for ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of the most crucial skills any worker can have are
curiosity, initiative and adaptability. If you have never used the
Internet, that is strike one, strike two and strike three.
</P>
<P>
   If candidates say they have tried the Internet for several
things but simply hate it, that's fine. But at least you ought to
know what's out there to see if it could enrich your life.
</P>
<P>
   What follows are my 20 favorite sites that are at least loosely
career-related. (Note the word ``favorite.'' This is not a
comprehensive list of the best career sites out there, which would
have required months of staring at Web pages. My mind is perfectly
capable of going numb on its own, thank you. It doesn't need the
Internet's help.)
</P>
<P>
   Here they are, in no particular order:
</P>
<P>
   Careerjournal.com _ A nice collection of career-related stories,
columns and other materials from the Wall Street Journal. You'll
find a lot of great advice here.
</P>
<P>
   Vault.com and wetfeet.com _ These two sites have plenty of
information on what it's like to work for particular companies or
in particular industries. They survey rank-and-file workers to help
in their company profiles, which cost a little money but are well
worth it once you've narrowed your focus to a few companies.
</P>
<P>
   Hoovers.com _ If you are looking at large companies, you can
find a lot of financial information here, as well as information on
competitors. It might give you background information that helps in
job interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Google.com and ask.com _ My two favorite Internet search
engines. New and unusual Web sites pop up all the time, and these
can help you discover other career sites, research projects or
pursue your hobbies.
</P>
<P>
   Rileyguide.com _ This points you toward many career Web sites,
not just for job hunting but for things like salary surveys and
career management.
</P>
<P>
   Careerzone.com _ If you are at a career crossroads, this has
several assessment tools that might help.
</P>
<P>
   Monster.com _ Tons of job listings, as you probably know, but
Monster also has decent career advice and is more comprehensive
than many of the job-posting sites.
</P>
<P>
   Cooljobs.com _ This has a lot of offbeat listings that are worth
exploring, if only to only to open your eyes to possibilities.
Among the categories during a recent check: juggling, explosives
and gaming.
</P>
<P>
   Recruitersonline.com _ Many recruiters from around the world are
listed here.
</P>
<P>
   Resumeblaster.com _ This pay service will e-mail your resume to
thousands of recruiters. As with all job-hunting sites, consider
this a supplement to your other efforts, not a miracle cure.
Old-fashioned networking still is the best way to find and land a
job.
</P>
<P>
   Jobstar.org _ The best part of this site, by far, is that it has
lots of salary information. Whether you are applying for a job or
trying to get a raise, this can help you find out what others in
your industry are earning.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it doesn't make my list because it's so new, I'd
also check salary.com, which has a Salary Wizard calculator that
can let you compare salaries for specific types of jobs in various
areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Paycheckcity.com _ This offers calculators to help you figure
things like your take-home pay and the value of your stock options.
</P>
<P>
   Fool.com _ This Motley Fool site offers solid financial advice,
including a section called Fool's School that covers a lot of the
basics. It also explains what you should consider before investing
in individual stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Money.com _ A lot of other financial basics, including advice on
retirement and effective methods of saving.
</P>
<P>
   Don't discount the importance of understanding personal finance
for your career. If you manage your money well, you might be able
to retire early or take a lower-paying job that offers more
satisfaction or start your own business.
</P>
<P>
   Distancelearn.about.com _ If you need to build career skills,
and it's hard to find anything locally that fits into your
schedule, this site can be a huge help. It has links to all sorts
of programs you can study at home or over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   CEOexpress.com and britannica.com _ Two terrific reference
sites. CEOExpress has links to dozens of publications, and
Britannica includes its on-line encyclopedia.
</P>
<P>
   Darwinawards.com _ A guilty pleasure, certainly. If you're the
sensitive type, by all means pass on this site, which has all sorts
of morbid tales of human stupidity. But if you've ever made a
mistake at work _ and we all have _ this will help to put it in
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
