<SLUG> BC-LAWYERS-MERGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EAST, WEST COAST LAW FIRMS TO MERGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DEMIAN BULWA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Pillsbury Madison &AMP; Sutro, an old-line law firm
in San Francisco, is girding its 126-year-old practice for the new
economy by agreeing to join forces with a New York-based law firm.
</P>
<P>
   Pillsbury, with 596 lawyers and a reputation for intellectual
property law, plans to merge with Winthrop Stimson Putnam &AMP;
Roberts, which has 265 attorneys and specializes in utility, energy
and aviation finance, officials from both firms announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The merger, which must be approved by partners from both firms
and is set to be completed by year's end, continues an industrywide
consolidation trend, creating a firm with 12 national offices and
four more abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to provide the resources to guide (clients) through
globalization,'' Pillsbury managing partner Marina Park said
Monday. ``For example, we don't have an aircraft leasing legal
team, and Winthrop does. And before, if we had a client that wanted
to do a large project overseas, they might go to a New York firm
for financing. It's one-stop shopping now.''
</P>
<P>
   The technology and globalization boom has brought big changes to
law firms, which have to compete harder for more demanding clients,
especially in the fast-paced Silicon Valley. Some law practices
have responded by trying to beef up their national and
international reach and offering a wider range of specialties under
one umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   Long known as a firm for West Coast blue-chip companies like
Chevron and Bank of America, Pillsbury in recent years has added
several emerging high-tech clients, including Vodafone AirTouch,
the world's largest mobile telecommunications company, and
support.com, which provides customer service software to Internet
companies.
</P>
<P>
   After years of well-documented troubles with boosting profits
and retaining lawyers, Pillsbury is in the midst of a five-year
overhaul of its operations after the appointments in January 1999
of Park and Chairwoman Mary Cranston.
</P>
<P>
   The primary goal of that strategic plan: Either expand to New
York and other key markets, or merge with a firm that already was
there, Park said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our vision is a firm with global resources that's positioned
to provide services to clients who are going global,'' Park said.
``We wanted to be able to work in the high-end capital and finance
markets, which really mandates a presence in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Park said that although many partners had left Pillsbury in the
past year and a half, ``the vast majority left out of mutual
agreement'' after discussions about the firm's direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were never in financial trouble,'' she said. ``We were in
spiritual trouble because we weren't moving, and everyone was
moving quickly around us.''
</P>
<P>
   The new firm, to be called Pillsbury Winthrop, would be headed
by Cranston, 53, who was recently named one of the nation's 100
most influential attorneys by the National Law Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Based on American Lawyer magazine's 1999 ranking of U.S. law
firms, Pillsbury Winthrop would rank 18th in gross revenues, the
firm said.
</P>
<P>
   Pillsbury has 198 lawyers in San Francisco, 81 in Palo Alto and
18 in Sacramento. It also has offices in Los Angeles, Orange
County, San Diego, northern San Diego County, New York, northern
Virginia, Washington, D.C., and Tokyo. Winthrop is in New York,
Stamford, Conn., Washington, D.C., Palm Beach, Fla., London, Tokyo,
Singapore and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could not be more pleased to be joining forces with
Pillsbury and to be creating one of the few national law firms with
real corporate and litigation depth in New York,'' said Winthrop
Chairman John Pritchard, who will be vice chair of the combined
practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
