<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-FINANCES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WEB BUSINESSES KEEN ON ONE-STOP BILL PAYMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Now that banks, credit card providers,
brokerages and other financial companies have succeeded in getting
some customers to move their business on line, the money business
is betting the next most popular service will be Web sites that
allow customers to consolidate all their financial transactions in
one place.
</P>
<P>
   Since millions of Americans have begun doing at least some
banking through the Internet, the next logical step, they say, is
to combine banking, credit card, brokerage, insurance and even
mortgage servicing on one site, which the industry calls an
aggregator.
</P>
<P>
   Though industry insiders and observers say the trend is only
about 6 months old, several Internet service and content providers
and individual companies have begun to provide such services, among
them America Online and Microsoft's MSN Money Central.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies, such as Yodlee.com, have begun to provide the
service on a stand-alone basis. Among banks, Chase has led the pack
into the aggregating arena, planning to launch its own version of
the service _ with Yodlee as the backbone _ in mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   Other banks, including Citibank and Bank One, have retained
Corillian, a Beaverton, Ore., company that designs software that
enables the banks to provide aggregating service on their own Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web is uniquely suited for personal finance,'' said Chris
Jolley, product manager for MSN's MoneyCentral. ``I don't know too
many people who say, `I can't wait to write out a check _ or
balance my checkbook.'''
</P>
<P>
   Not all banks are happy about the idea, variously saying the
service infringes on copyrights or threatens the safety of consumer
data. Charlotte, N.C.-based First Union bank briefly sued Secure
Commerce Services, which operates an aggregating site called
Paytrust, in March for alleged violations of the Computer Fraud and
Abuse Act. The suit accused the company of ``screen scraping,''
that is, taking information off the bank's Web site without
permission.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was later withdrawn, but First Union now has strict
controls and rules governing aggregator access to its data. It also
requires that aggregators provide full disclosures to consumers
about the risks of sharing account information with a third party.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly 24 million investors now managing their money on
line and 21 million households expected to begin using on-line
bill-paying services, according to varying research groups, banks
see potential in sites that combine those services and others.
</P>
<P>
   Though most sites and companies decline to release numbers of
actual registered users, Stephen Franco, an analyst with US Bancorp
Piper Jaffray, predicted the number of consumers who use such
services will rise from about 800,000 this year to 4 million by
2002.
</P>
<P>
   Most sites offer some combination of on-line bill payment
service, bank and credit card account balance information, and
brokerage account access. MSN MoneyCentral and America Online,
favorites with some industry observers, offer users access to
search engines to find investments tailored to their interests as
well as equity analysis and chat, insurance and mortgage
information, financial planning tools and articles, and the latest
business news.
</P>
<P>
   MoneyCentral also offers a ticker that can be customized to
present news and quotes on stocks in a user's particular portfolio.
Once a customer organizes his money, Yodlee.com provides links to
sites where he can spend it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
