<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AIRPLANE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     U.S.-TAIWAN VENTURE UNVEILS NEW BUSINESS JET 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (ATTN: W.Va.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SANFORD NOWLIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTIONO _ Sino Swearingen Aircraft Co. has unveiled the
first completed model of its SJ30-2 jet, taking a major step toward
becoming the first start-up company to bring a business jet to
market in 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   If certified by the Federal Aviation Administration, the San
Antonio company's six-passenger, $5 million plane will be the first
business jet sold by a start-up since the Learjet was introduced in
the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do our job right, we should be able to keep building
this airplane for the next 30 to 35 years,'' Sino Swearingen chief
executive Jack Braly told a crowd of more than 700 employees and
aerospace industry officials at the unveiling ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The new plane was rolled out of a hangar at the company's
headquarters at San Antonio International Airport amid pulsing
music, a waft of smoke and strobes of multicolored lights.
</P>
<P>
   Sino Swearingen, a joint venture between Swearingen Aircraft of
San Antonio and Sino Aerospace Investment of Taiwan, has so far
spent $250 million developing the SJ30-2, which is its only
product. The company employs about 400 people in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The company has 164 orders for the twin-engine SJ30-2, which it
says can fly faster and for longer distances than other jets in its
price range.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the plane can fly coast-to-coast without refueling,
something only jets in the $12 million-or-more price range are
capable of doing, the company says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this will be a trend-setting airplane,'' said aviation
designer Ed Swearingen, who formed the company in 1995 and is a
Sino Swearingen board member. ``This will change the way people
build airplanes.''
</P>
<P>
   Most start-up companies that have tried to bring a new business
jet to market have run out of money before getting FAA
certification for their planes, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a new jet from the drawing board to the assembly line
costs hundreds of millions of dollars and takes years of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It remains a difficult market to break into,'' said Paul
Nisbet, president of Newport, R.I.-based JSA Research Inc. ``The
certification process is a really big barrier for small firms.''
</P>
<P>
   Swearingen still needs to flight-test the SJ30-2 before it can
get FAA certification and begin large-scale manufacturing of the
plane. The flight-testing process is expected to take at least
another year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a lot of work to do,'' Braly said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the attendees at the rollout ceremony was Sen. John D.
Rockefeller IV, D-W.Va., whose home state houses Sino Swearingen's
main manufacturing facility.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to convince Sino Swearingen to locate its plant in
West Virginia, the state invested some $4 million in the company
and built infrastructure improvements at its plant, located in the
city of Martinsburg.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
