<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5680 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     07-18 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENGLISH, THE INTERNATIONAL LANGUAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Foreign travel offers some unique challenges, not the least of
which is translating the local signs.
</P>
<P>
   These head-scratchers were brought to my attention by the
Vancouver English Centre:
</P>
<P>
   On the door of a Moscow hotel room: ``If this is your first
visit to the USSR, you are welcome to it.''
</P>
<P>
   With excessive generosity of this sort, it's no wonder the
Soviet Union collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   From a Japanese information booklet about using a hotel air
conditioner: ``Cooles and Heates: If you want just condition of
warm in your room, please control yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   What if you control yourself and your room is still too cooles?
Clearly, this information booklet is not as detailed as it should
be.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisement for donkey rides in Thailand: ``Would you like to
ride on your own ass?''
</P>
<P>
   That's probably what would happen if I attempted to climb aboard
an unwilling donkey.
</P>
<P>
   In a Paris hotel elevator: ``Please leave your values at the
front desk.''
</P>
<P>
   This sort of casual immorality may be OK for the French, but I
prefer to keep my values in my pants pocket where they belong.
</P>
<P>
   On the menu of a Polish hotel: ``Salad a firm's own make; limpid
red beet soup with cheesy dumplings in the form of a finger;
roasted duck let loose; beef rashers beaten up in the country
people's fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like that kitchen is a pretty violent place. I am curious
about the roasted duck let loose, however. Do you have to catch it
before you can eat it, and if so, wouldn't that seem to indicate
it's a trifle underdone? Kind of makes you hope there's a
McDonald's close by.
</P>
<P>
   From a brochure of a car rental firm in Tokyo: ``When passenger
of foot heave in sight, tootle the horn. Trumpet him melodiously at
first, but if he still obstacles your passage then tootle him with
vigor.''
</P>
<P>
   Way too complicated. The Japanese should treat passengers of
foot the way we do in Florida: Run 'em down, then tootle the horn.
</P>
<P>
   Two signs from a Majorcan shop: ``English well talking. Here
speeching American.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, so that's it! George W. is speaking Majorcan!
</P>
<P>
   In a Belgrade hotel elevator: ``To move the cabin, push button
for wishing floor. If the cabin should enter more persons, each one
should press a number of wishing floor. Driving is then going
alphabetically by national order.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like it might take days to go from floor to floor in
Belgrade elevators. By the time they got around to driving
alphabetically by national order, you'd be wishing you'd taken the
stairs.
</P>
<P>
   In a Copenhagen airline ticket office: ``We take your bags and
send them in all directions.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't need to go to Copenhagen for that; you can receive
that sort of treatment right here in the states.
</P>
<P>
   In a Norwegian cocktail lounge: ``Ladies are requested not to
have children at the bar.''
</P>
<P>
   A sound policy. They should try to have them on Belgrade
elevators where, due to the general pandemonium, no one would
notice.
</P>
<P>
   In an Acapulco hotel: ``The manager has personally passed all
the water served here.''
</P>
<P>
   I guess that would explain the lack of ice cubes.
</P>
<P>
   On the menu of a Swiss restaurant: ``Our wines leave you nothing
to hope for.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I don't know about that. I'm still very curious about the
roasted duck let loose.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1522EDT &QL; 
