<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5695 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-PELICAN-REVIVAL-HNS &LR;      07-18 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PELICAN-REVIVAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GLIMMER OF HOPE FOR REVIVAL OF CALIFORNIA'S BROWN PELICAN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JANE KAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   POINT LOBOS STATE RESERVE, Calif. _ Jutting out from the rocky
shoreline south of Carmel Bay is a popular bird-watching peninsula
called Pelican Point.
</P>
<P>
   Yet its namesake, the endangered California brown pelican,
hasn't nested here for more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   This year, things may be changing. Hundreds of brown pelicans
are swarming around the point and its little offshore rock islands,
raising hope that the remarkable seabird threatened by the
insecticide DDT will once again return to mate, build nests and
hatch young in Central California.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 birds swirl overhead, fishing and preening on the
rocks in the state reserve, three times as many as in previous
years, Point Lobos State Reserve rangers report.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly for scientists, the pelicans are courting.
They're nuzzling necks, rubbing bills, trading sticks, bobbing
heads and flapping wings as they face one another, and even
experimenting with mating tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been doing the dance, but that's all they're
doing,'' said Chuck Bancroft, a Point Lobos State Reserve ranger
for the past 19 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe within the next couple of years, we'll get lucky, and
they can start nesting here again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bird Island, the largest of the guano-encrusted rocks offshore
from the reserve 3 miles south of Carmel and 120 miles south of San
Francisco, has been documented as the northernmost nesting ground
of the California brown pelican.
</P>
<P>
   Sparse, early research shows the presence of nests and young on
Bird Island in the late 1920s through the 1950s. The last chicks
were seen in 1959, and the last nests in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 60,000 mating pairs of pelicans left in the world
breed, nest and hatch young in Baja California, Mexico. The Channel
Islands of Anacapa and Santa Barbara, with up to 7,000 pairs of
California brown pelicans, are the only permanent nesting rookeries
in California.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of brown pelicans are leaving these nesting
areas to migrate to southern British Columbia for feeding and
roosting. But they are not nesting, which involves producing young.
</P>
<P>
   On schedule, some of the giant birds, which grow to 4 feet tall
and weigh 11 pounds, are stopping in San Francisco Bay, following
the anchovies, sardines, mackerel, smelt and grunion.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the pelicans left months earlier, arriving at Bird
Island when breeding was still going strong in the Channel Islands
and Baja. They are so numerous here that visitors to the state
reserve can sit for hours on the shore, watching with binoculars as
the birds return from fishing. The flapping of their strong,
6-foot-wide wings sends down soft, feathery sounds.
</P>
<P>
   The pelicans glide back to the rocks with bills jutted, landing
with splayed legs. Nestled in rock crevices, they preen and doze,
hunching down and turning their big bills onto their backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Point Lobos is the perfect place to see birds. You can stand
on the point and look across,'' said Dan Anderson, a professor of
wildlife biology at the University of California at Davis and one
of the country's foremost brown pelican researchers.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the raucous calls of the western gull and the
croaks of the nesting dark-brown Brandt's cormorants, with which
they split the territory, the pelicans utter hardly a sound.
</P>
<P>
   For 30 years, UC-Davis scientists have published dozens of
papers on the effects of contaminants, food supply, commercial
fishing and oil spills on brown pelicans.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson and others are cautious about whether the big numbers
and courtship activities mean the advent of nests at Point Lobos.
Sometimes, Anderson said, pelicans are ``just playing house.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Long, acting chairman of the California Academy of
Sciences' Department of Ornithology and Mammalogy, agrees. At the
Farallon Islands, where pelicans visit to feed, yet don't nest, he
sees similar behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oftentimes, it's not that they're breeding, but the young,
inexperienced birds will practice their courtship with one
another,'' he said. ``They may be going through the motions at Bird
Island.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Anderson and Long haven't seen the birds at Bird Island,
relying on an assessment by the respected Alan Baldridge, librarian
emeritus of Stanford University's Hopkins Marine Station in Pacific
Grove. Baldridge wrote a definitive 1973 paper on past nesting at
Bird Island, and visited the site in May. He confirmed the typical
posturing of breeding and ``some amateurish attempts at
copulation.''
</P>
<P>
   After closely examining their coloration, Baldridge concluded
the birds were immature, probably 3 years old, a year short of
breeding age.
</P>
<P>
   ``The birds didn't have the Cabernet-colored pouches and yellow
on the crown feathers,'' Baldridge said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we think is if the conditions are the same next year, if
some of the same birds return, we might have a resumption of
nesting at this site, the northern edge of the known nesting
range,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nesting or not, ``it's a very good sign,'' Baldridge said. ``I
think when you have a population that's doing very well, they tend
to push the boundaries of their range. If they're not doing well,
they tend to retreat to a core.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a fantastic thing for a state reserve if they
returned to breed like they were breeding in the 1920s through the
1950s.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hopes are buoyed by an influx over the last decade at the
protected and more isolated Ano Nuevo State Reserve, 25 miles south
of San Francisco. Rangers report some rookie courtship behavior in
the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   Pelicans are about 10 million years old. The California brown
pelican is about 2 million years old. Since people started counting
pelicans in the late 1800s instead of shooting them, records show
they have been loyal to the Channel Islands. There they build what
look like crow nests, some big, some insignificant, sitting on the
ground or in trees, usually within sight of water.
</P>
<P>
   Skilled divers, they speed down at 40 mph from 100 feet in the
air to scoop schools of fish in their throat pouches. Sometimes
they glide just above the waves, braking in mid-air when they spy
food. Ornithologists think the way they crash into the water stuns
the fish.
</P>
<P>
   Pelicans lay three eggs a season, staying in pairs until the
young fledge. Then, the parents leave the colony as individuals.
They recognize one another almost immediately the next season at
the same nesting ground, and may link up again if they successfully
produced young the year before.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1950s, the National Audubon Society's Christmas Count
began to record a decline in the number of brown pelicans. Later
studies would find an increase in DDT residues in California marine
phytoplankton beginning in that period.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, former U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service biologist Rachel
Carson shocked the nation with her landmark book, ``Silent
Spring.'' She warned how the widespread use of pesticides was
killing birds and other wildlife and harming humans. In a chapter
called ``And No Birds Sing,'' she reported studies and field
accounts of DDT's disruption of reproduction.
</P>
<P>
   In later studies, scientists tied the decline of nesting at Bird
Island in 1966 to the wider damage caused by the insecticide and
other chemicals. In California, brown pelicans, peregrine falcons,
bald eagles and double-crested cormorants were virtually wiped out.
</P>
</TEXT>
