<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIVE-OILS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OILS LIKE THESE DON'T JUST GROW ON TREES 
</HEADLINE>
   By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a world awash in olive oil, it is hard to imagine a new one
that could merit singling out. But several olive oils, and one
innovative grapeseed oil, are worthy of the attention of the
serious cook. None are cheap, so they are probably not for dishes
in which a supermarket brand will do. But if you have a wardrobe of
olive oils for different purposes, you might consider some of
these.
</P>
<P>
   For one of them, you'll need your freezer. It's Novizio, an
extra virgin olive oil from the Antinori wine family of Tuscany and
Martini Bernardi, an olive oil producer, also of Tuscany. Along
with 100 other oils, it was introduced last week at the Fancy Food
trade show in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The oil, pressed in Tuscany from green olives grown in Apulia,
is flash frozen as soon as it is bottled. The purpose of the
unusual process, said Alessia Antinori, a daughter of Piero
Antinori, the winery owner, is to ``make very fresh olive oil
available all year.'' The oil has a lively freshness and is
extremely fragrant, with floral notes and a peppery aftertaste.
</P>
<P>
   Novizio must be thawed before its first use (this can take
several hours, so plan ahead) but if stored in a cool dark place,
it is supposed to retain its vibrant qualities and brilliant green
color for a month. After that, these qualities will begin to
diminish, but it still will be an excellent oil. Do not try to
refreeze it once it has been thawed. (One complaint is that the
bottle has a standard wine cork, which makes resealing difficult.)
</P>
<P>
   Freshness is critical to the quality of olive oil. Better oils
have a harvest date listed on their labels, and should be used
within a year, preferably six months of purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Whether consumers will be willing to pay the higher price for
the extra freshness promised by Novizio remains to be seen. This
oil has such a fresh taste that it would be delicious drizzled on
ripe tomatoes or over grilled wild striped bass.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Dean &AMP; DeLuca, 560 Broadway (Prince Street), and Grace's
Marketplace, 1237 Third Ave. (71st Street), are expected to have
the oil by the end of the month, with an 8.7-ounce bottle priced at
around $15 and a 17.5-ounce bottle at $25.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Another oil, named the best new product at the show, is ruby
grapefruit olive oil by O, a company in San Rafael, Calif., whose
citrus-flavored organic extra virgin oils are made by crushing the
whole fruit and olives together. The company already makes olive
oils blended with blood oranges, Tahitian limes and Meyer lemons.
The newest oil is rich, with hints of tart and sweet. Because pink
grapefruit is such a splendid complement for sweet seafood like
shrimp, scallops and red snapper, this oil would provide a lovely
finishing touch to the preparation, or could dress a salad served
alongside. It will be available in specialty shops next month for
about $18 an 8.8-ounce bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Supremo, of Hayward, Calif., also has a line of flavored organic
extra virgin olive oils, which it makes by infusing the oils with
citrus peels. They have piquant notes of lemon, lime and orange
zest, making them good for dishes like cold tomato soup, but they
are less complex than O's oils. A 6.4-ounce bottle will sell for
$10 next month.
</P>
<P>
   Another citrus oil is the Meyer lemon extra virgin olive oil
made by Da Vero in Healdsburg, Calif. This oil is made like O's, by
crushing the fruit and olives together. It tastes more of olives
than fruit, and the citrus adds only a subtle, pleasantly bitter
presence. It's tailor-made for steamed or grilled asparagus, or to
trace over sheep's milk cheese. The oil, in a 12.7-ounce bottle, is
sold for $20, plus shipping, by Katz and Co. in Napa, Calif.: (800)
676-7176.
</P>
<P>
   A more unusual newcomer is Salute Sante's cold-pressed extra
virgin grapeseed oil, which is made from grapeseeds that have not
been allowed to ferment after the grapes are pressed for wine.
Unlike typical grapeseed oils, which are pale and fairly neutral
tasting, this one, made by Food &AMP; Vine in Napa, is greenish and
somewhat more viscous and has a sweet, floral aroma and a mellow,
slightly fruity taste. It is also unfiltered, which gives it the
richer color, yet it's not cloudy with sediment. Like most
grapeseed oils, it does not solidify when refrigerated, so you
don't get clumps in your salad dressing or marinade, which you
might if you used olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a jewel-box oil, in a dark bottle with gold leaf on
the label, which costs $30 for eight ounces (www.grapeseedoil.com);
it will be in stores this fall. So use it sparingly, as a seasoning
for salmon poached in white wine, in a sauce for leeks vinaigrette
or on a tender salad scattered with walnuts and pears.
</P>
<P>
   In this age of specialization, Food &AMP; Vine is now developing
varietal grapeseed oils. First on the list is chardonnay, so the
oil can match your glass of wine.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
