<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5705 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TVTOUR19-COX     07-18 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVTOUR19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shandling is certain to shake up Emmy telecast
 &HT;    By Kevin Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Jon Cryer is starring on a new sitcom. Garry
Shandling isn't. That tells you everything you need to know about
the intelligence of network programmers.
</P>
<P>
   But the forever-wincing comic will be back in the spotlight in
September when he hosts the 52nd Annual Emmy Awards. Shandling
admits, however, that he's not up to speed on current shows. ``I
have to catch up on all my TV,'' he told TV writers at the annual
fall TV press tour. ``I thought ``Malcolm in the Middle'' was an
episode of ``Oz.''
</P>
<P>
   Shandling knows a little bit about the Emmys, though. He earned
four consecutive acting nominations for his brilliant role on HBO's
``The Larry Sanders Show.'' The only time he won, however, was in
1998, for writing. ``Since I started as a writer and consider
myself a writer, it was the most meaningful Emmy I could've
gotten,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Shandling hopes to shake up the often-staid Emmy format. For
starters, he doesn't want to give out awards. ``Just give me the
whole three hours,'' he cracks.
</P>
<P>
   That's really not a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   Seriously, Shandling would like to see more pre-taped packages.
Those segments, he says, could be about the new voting process
(judges can now view tapes from home instead of gathering in a
hotel during a 48-hour period) or where stars keep their Emmys.
``Maybe we can open it up a little bit,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But will Shandling feel comfortable performing for such a large
audience? While his HBO series was a critical favorite, only about
32 people saw it each week in the relatively small cable universe.
``I was lonely not being in front of 50 million people,'' Shandling
says. ``I need to be in front of 50 million people. I wish we could
all go to therapy together.''
</P>
<P>
   Cameron happy to be father of four children
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Cameron's handsome yet boyish face hasn't changed much. The
inviting smile and precious dimples could still make young girls
swoon the way they did in the '80s. Yes, there are a few crinkly
lines around his eyes. But that's to be expected. After all, the
29-year-old actor, who played budding con man Mike Seaver for seven
seasons on ABC's ``Growing Pains,'' is the father of four kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy,'' cracks Alan Thicke, Cameron's TV dad, ``has turned
into a fathering machine.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a bit hard, though, to picture Cameron as a dad. When I
think of Kirk Cameron _ and I assure you that doesn't happen too
often _ I remember a scrawny kid whose voice was cracking. No,
puberty isn't always a pretty sight.
</P>
<P>
   So, what's it like being a young father?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great,'' says Cameron, who's married to ``Growing Pains
`` co-star Chelsea Noble. ``When I'm on my deathbed, and I'm
looking back on (my life) and say, `What am I really glad I did?'
I'll say, `I'm glad I had kids.' Being a dad is awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing Pains `` fans will probably think ABC's decision to
air a reunion movie is pretty awesome, too. In the film, the
Seavers gather one more time when Jason (Thicke) asks his grown
kids to return home to run Maggie's (Joanna Kerns) campaign for
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Obscure statistics
</P>
<P>
   Nothing bores a TV critic more than a network suit spouting
self-serving research statistics. Oddly, that's how ABC chose to
begin its Sunday presentation. Needless to say, while Larry Hyams,
ABC's vice president of prime time audience analysis, took 10
minutes telling us how great ABC is, I spent most of that time
doodling and wondering what Heather Locklear was going to wear
during her chat with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Hyams, however, caught my attention when he began throwing out
really obscure statistics about ``Who Wants To Be A Millionaire.''
For instance, I'll bet you didn't know that when ``Millionaire's''
audience is ranked by state, Florida comes in a dismal 47th with a
7.7 rating in the key 18-to-49 age demographic. Hawaii ranks first
with a 13.2 rating. Six percent of the people who watch Reege live
in a mobile home. Fancy that! Forty-nine percent own dogs.
Thirty-three percent have cats. And a whopping 83 percent drive a
good, old-fashioned domestic vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ABC plans only four new shows
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, ABC is rolling out only four new series this fall. I
say luckily because none of the shows _ including ``Gideon's
Crossing,'' Andre Braugher's medical drama _ looks promising. In
fact, the dismal sitcom ``The Trouble With Normal `` could be the
season's first casualty. But ABC would have you believe that
debuting a mere four shows is a good thing. ``It will allow us to
be so effective and target in our on-air promotion and marketing,''
says Stu Bloomberg, co-chairman of ABC Entertainment Television
Group. ``We see it as a plus.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, you gotta love network spin.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg producing documentary lauding WWII camermen
</P>
<P>
   ABC announced Steven Spielberg will executive-produce a two-hour
documentary celebrating the motion picture combat cameramen who
served on the front lines of World War II. ``Shooting Wars'' is
scheduled to air Dec. 7 and will be hosted by Tom Hanks (''Saving
Private Ryan''). ``Time'' magazine film critic Richard Schickel
will write, produce and direct the documentary. ``Shooting Wars''
draws on more than 600 hours of rare archival footage as well as 25
exclusive interviews with combat photographers.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE OF THE WEEK (SO FAR): ``We're dead.'' Dick Van Dyke on
``Diagnosis Murder's'' chances against ``ER `` in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Thompson can be reached at kevinthompson(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
