<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5706 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-WINE-COLUMN19-COX     07-18 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taste of wine column
 &HT;    A frank take on an industry ploy
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SWIRL HERE, A SIP
</P>
<P>
   there ...
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mike Frank _ the irascible, always opinionated proprietor of
Arrow Wine and Spirits' Far Hills Avenue store in Kettering _ is
obviously out to steal my job. Frank has begun writing a regular
column for the ActiveDayton.com Web site that includes the Dayton
Daily News as a partner. Here's an excerpt from Frank's inaugural
piece, in which he explains why his column is titled ``I don't know
anything about wine, but...'':
</P>
<P>
   ``The title comes from something I've heard time and again at
our store. People will wander in with a sheepish look on their
faces because they've been intimidated by the foolish way the wine
industry markets its product. Instead of making wine approachable
the industry has surrounded it with an air of mystery and intrigue.
That is a shame because wine is a food product we humans have been
happily drinking for thousands of years.''
</P>
<P>
   You go, Mike.
</P>
<P>
   Point your browser to www.activedayton.com/entertainment/dining
to read the rest.
</P>
<P>
   The ActiveDayton site also features a wine forum
www.activedayton.com/entertainment/forumschat/wine.html) and
listings of upcoming events.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Sixth Annual Vintage Ohio Wine Festival will be Aug. 4-5
at Lake Farmpark in Kirtland, in Lake County east of Cleveland.
Advance tickets are $13 for adults, $8 for nondrinkers or
designated drivers and $3 for children. For more information about
the event, call (800) 227-6972 or check the Web site at
www.ohiowines.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wine of the week, in the ``gloriously red'' category: 1998 Les
Baux de Provence Mas de Gourgonnier, $10.99: It's a positive sign
when, after pouring red wine into a glass, even the bubbles that
show up around the rim are dark purple. That's when you know you're
holding a glass of concentrated, highly extracted, palate-coating,
teeth-staining, attention-grabbing wine. This blend of
Rhone-varietal grapes, produced organically in the south of France,
has everything that big-red lovers would want; those who like
lighter-style merlots and gamays might want to skip this one. To my
tastes, it's among the best wines in its price range I've tasted.
Serve it with a slight chill with anything off the grill. Note:
some wine shops still have earlier vintages of this wine on the
shelf, which are quite good as well, but the enthusiasm of these
tasting notes apply only to the '98.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wine of the week, in the ``chill-fully white'' category: 1999
Protocolo, $5.99: A tasty, quaffable white at a nice price. I led a
wine-tasting a few weeks ago for some folks in the local
mortgage-banking business, and this Spanish white _ the least
expensive of the four wines we sampled _ was a hit. Made from
relatively obscure white grape varieties (90 percent arien, 10
percent viura), the wine is dry but not bracingly so. Sip a short
glass before dinner, and you'll find yourself pouring a refill.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Contact Mark Fisher at markfisher(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
