<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5716 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PAPERS-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     07-18 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAPERS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FALSE PAPERS': ABSENCES THAT MADE A HEART GROW FONDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Someone once said that nostalgia was the most beautiful word in
the language, in any language. Like the cruelest month, it mixes
memory and desire, but what is it exactly that we remember, and
what do we desire? In his beguiling new book of essays, ``False
Papers,'' Andre Aciman gives these questions deep, lyrical and
melancholy reflection, melancholy because nostalgia in this
rumination is connected to the quest to make sense out of a life,
even though ``we know there is no sense to be made.''
</P>
<P>
   Readers of Aciman's earlier work will not be surprised by this
rapture over the personal past. In his exquisitely wrought ``Out of
Egypt,'' in which he searched his memory for the city of
Alexandria, Egypt, where he spent his childhood, his evocation is
poignant and affecting because most of what he describes of life
there has vanished, along with the Greeks and the Jews who gave
Alexandria much of its vitality. This new book is a sort of sequel
to the earlier one. It shows the same refined sensibility, this
author's remarkable intellectual penetration and his gift for
language.
</P>
<P>
   It is a sequel to ``Out of Egypt'' thematically as well, with
Aciman dryly, wittily, urbanely examining the various meanings of a
life lived in permanent exile, thoroughly cut off from the smells
and colors of the past.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the essays in ``False Papers'' Aciman credits Marcel
Proust with ``a vision that gave memory and introspection an
aesthetic scope and magnitude no author had conferred on either
before.'' The same cannot be said of Aciman for the simple reason
that the Proust of ``Remembrance of Things Past'' came before him.
Reading these essays, with their almost languid appreciation for
the nuances and subtleties of consciousness, one feels that if
Proust had not existed, Aciman would have invented him.
</P>
<P>
   He begins with an account of a return trip to Alexandria, which
Aciman's Jewish family was forced to leave in the mid-1960s during
the nationalist presidency of Gamal Abdel Nasser. He quickly
realizes, as he visits the few vestiges that remain of the vibrant,
cosmopolitan city that is no more, that he is not experiencing the
powerful emotions that he anticipated his return trip would bring.
In a sentence that sums up the themes of this book, he writes:
``This is how I always travel: not so as to experience anything at
the time of my tour, but to plot the itinerary of a possible return
trip. This, it occurs to me, is also how I live.''
</P>
<P>
   There is enough rue in that remark for it to leak off the page,
but it is rue that contains an entire psychology of emotion. There
is a secondhand quality to all experience, including the experience
of remembering. We are usually kept from the ecstasy we anticipate
by a layer of consciousness that separates us from it. So in
Alexandria Aciman goes through certain motions _ looking at the old
neighborhood, revisiting the beach where he used to spend his
summers, cleaning his grandfather's gravestone _ without really
feeling much of anything, even as he remains aware that as soon as
he returns to New York, he will begin longing for Alexandria again.
</P>
<P>
   Aciman evokes a similar sort of disconnect as he ruminates on
other subjects: the sea glimpsed through trees on the Rome-to-Paris
train, the tiny park on the Upper West Side of Manhattan where he
used to go to dream he was in Paris or Rome, an unrequited love of
his student days.
</P>
<P>
   In each instance he draws out the idea that somehow experience
itself is less meaningful than the anticipation of it or the memory
of it or even the pure imagination of it. Others have had similar
thoughts. As Roger Shattuck points out in his recent book,
``Proust's Way,'' the young Marcel of Proust's novel observes his
first kiss with his beloved Albertine so closely that it becomes
like an object examined in a glass case, more analyzed than felt.
In Aciman's case the disconnect is given its particular character
by his identity as an exile.
</P>
<P>
   ``An exile is not just someone who has lost his home; he is
someone who can't find another, who can't think of another,'' he
writes in a marvelous disquisition on his little park in New York.
He remembers having been a young man in Rome dreaming of New York,
and now he is in New York longing for Rome and, at the same time,
knowing that he will not satisfy his longing by going there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I yearn for Rome when I am finally standing where I longed
to stand when I was once a young man in Rome?'' he wonders. The
question is rhetorical, but it leads Aciman to disclose the mystery
of his little park in New York, which is that it is not a stand-in
for Rome or Paris or any place he has visited as an adult. It is
Alexandria but not the real Alexandria; it is the Alexandria of
imagination ``that is perhaps more in me than it ever was out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean that one spends one's life attempting to
recapture the sites of one's childhood?
</P>
<P>
   It might mean that, but Aciman is more Proustian than Freudian
in these essays. He visits Illiers, the French town where Proust
spent his childhood summers and that became Combray in his great
novel. Aciman is struck by how ordinary the Proust house is, and he
realizes that Proust's powerful love for Combray and his
description of the place as rather grand parallel his own feelings
about Alexandria. They explain the mystery of what we long for when
we are nostalgic and in that sense nicely limn the delicate
meandering of Aciman's finely tuned mind: ``Illiers itself was
simply a place where the young Proust dreamed of a better life to
come,'' he writes. ``But, because the dream never came true, he had
learned to love instead the place where the dream was born.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FALSE PAPERS
</P>
<P>
   By Andre Aciman
</P>
<P>
   182 pages. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1603EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
