<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5717 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-GARLIC-FARMER-2TAKES-     07-18 1439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARLIC-FARMER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINGTIME IN JULY FOR CRUNCHY, YOUNG GARLIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Conn., Fla., Mass., Calif., Germany)  (Editors: A 350-word recipe for Garlic Pudding Souffle appears at
end of story.) 
 By DEBORAH BALDWIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hot day, hard time getting out of the city. By the time we got
to New Paltz, N.Y., the sun was halfway down, and Ray Bradley, a
modest farmer with a big-city resume, had already been at work 11
hours.
</P>
<P>
   At the distant end of a long, skinny plot of raggedy green
stalks, Bradley was a Coppertone blur in a stained T-shirt and
baseball cap. He was overseeing three field hands and half a dozen
city slickers who had driven hours for the privilege of a great day
in the country: the July 1 garlic harvest at the Bradley Farm.
</P>
<P>
   Picking garlic is slow work: you have to bend and yank the bulbs
one by one out of the cakey soil. Every so often, the pickers
gathered their smelly bundles and moved toward Bradley's truck, a
1984 heap with so much soil on the floor you could probably throw
down a few kernels and raise corn. By sundown the back of the truck
was buried in light-bulb-white garlic heads so fresh that it seemed
a shame to eat them.
</P>
<P>
   Garlic is available year-round, but the season for young garlic
is terribly short, only a few weeks in spring and early summer.
During that time, growers like Bradley rush to farmers' markets and
restaurants with crates of naked-looking new bulbs, soil still
clinging to their roots and stalks, their nearly skinless, barely
formed cloves as crunchy as apples.
</P>
<P>
   For some customers, it is a thrill simply to see garlic that is
not in a cardboard container. Others are charmed by garlic nipped
before it has reached adulthood and conveying spring in all its
senses. For the time-pressed cook, new garlic has a more practical
payoff: there is no need to remove annoying raspy skins, as with
mature garlic. You can slice and saute an entire head like an
onion. Its flavor can be mild or strong, but either way, garlic is
an excellent candidate for poaching in soups, roasting with meats
and pureeing for mashed potatoes, aioli and the like.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, one of about 20 farmers selling new garlic at New York
City's Greenmarkets, came to farming through haute cuisine's back
door, as a chef in some of the city's top restaurants. He is a
Connecticut native whose father grew garlic, and whose mother
refused to cook with it. Bradley, 47, studied forestry and logged
in Maine and Oregon. But he had always been interested in cooking
and, in the late 1970s, became a kitchen grunt, peeling carrots for
a chef who circulated between Clearwater, Fla., and Cape Cod, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Next, he moved to New York, where he perfected his skills
cooking alongside his childhood friend David Bouley at restaurants
like Le Cirque and Montrachet. When Bouley opened a restaurant of
his own in 1987, Bradley served as sous-chef. He also helped hammer
the place together, Bouley recalled last week, as he scuttled
between his current restaurants, Danube and Bouley Bakery.
</P>
<P>
   For Bradley, the gourmet grind proved as tough as carting timber
out of the Cascades, and in 1993 he decided to get into the less
heated business of providing the provisions. He tried being a
middle man, tracking down hard-to-get ingredients for name
kitchens. Then he began growing the goods himself, renting seven
flood-prone acres in the Hudson River Valley on the Wallkill River
near New Paltz, where farmers have tilled the loamy soil since the
1670s. He chose organic methods, mainly because he had no stomach
for chemistry. The trick, he figured, was to find crops that would
thrive in his inexperienced care.
</P>
<P>
   Garlic, it turned out, is a survivor. Raised organically, garlic
``is smaller, but it tastes great and lasts longer,'' Bradley said.
Within three years, he was specializing in a variety called German
porcelain, which comes from the branch of the garlic family known
as hard-neck because the bulb has a stiff central stem.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Bradley plants cloves from the biggest bulbs culled
the previous year. (If he sells down his stocks, he buys seed from
Charles Bishop, a friend and fellow Greenmarket purveyor.) Come
spring, the cloves send up long green shoots, which curl like a
pig's tail. Garlic farmers chop them off to discourage the plants
from concentrating on flower production. More important, the shoots
yield a by-crop called scapes, which make a nice side dish sauteed
in butter or olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   The scapes, which are mild and look like Asian string beans,
have a surprisingly long shelf life, and Bradley and Bishop sell
them all summer, along with tons of garlic.
</P>
<P>
   By September, the garlic has lost weight and begun to resemble
the dried garlic sold in stores.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, word of Bradley's garlic harvest has gotten
around, and a couple of carloads of amateur garlic hounds arrive in
time to help, pocketing a few pounds for personal use and praying
that the former chef will offer them dinner. Last year, he put out
roasted lamb marinated in garlic and olive oil, a dish he likes to
garnish with fresh garlic chips, or croutons. (Thinly slice some
new garlic, and fry in butter and olive oil until crisp.) He also
likes to separate new cloves and sprinkle them with olive oil,
baking them in a moderate oven until they begin to soften, then
caramelizing them in a saute pan with a bit of olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer, Bradley works the farm until sundown before
Greenmarket days and heads for the city at about 3 a.m. In the
co-pilot seat is a 120-pound Labrador named Grizzly.
</P>
<P>
   Some shoppers seemed perplexed by a table piled with garlic so
new that it was still attached to its umbilical stems. Others made
beelines to Bradley's signature impulse item: homemade garlic dog
biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   There were those, like John Policastro, the chef at the nearby
Garden Cafe, who had other things in mind. Policastro makes a
seasonal soup using Bradley's bulbs and early fingerling potatoes,
garnishing it with scape-flecked creme fraiche. Anna Klinger, the
chef at Al Di La in Brooklyn, makes soup out of Bradley's garlic,
with chicken stock and little else, and she grills Bradley's scapes
and serves them in a fresh garlic dressing made with anchovies,
chili pepper and olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   New garlic is old hat in Berkeley, Calif., where Chez Panisse
and its adjoining cafe celebrate Bastille Day every July with an
all-garlic menu. Fresh garlic is ``usually sweeter, without an
acrid taste,'' Russell Moore, one of the chefs, said, estimating
that 450 guests went through 70 to 80 pounds of it last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   New England is still catching up with Northern California, but
``10 years ago, garlic got very popular,'' said Bishop, 57, a
former aerospace engineer who dedicates three acres of his
Susquehanna Valley farm near the Pennsylvania line to garlic. He
credits a September garlic festival in Saugerties, N.Y., with
stimulating interest in fresh garlic. No one knows how much is
harvested in New York State annually, but Bishop thinks he will
pull four tons this year, selling three and holding back the rest
for seed stock.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he started harvesting the first of four varieties, a
no-name soft-neck with a possibly Alsatian provenance, which he
brought from Germany eight years ago. His other varieties include
the German porcelain, which he describes as ``beautifully
impressive,'' with a strong flavor and a high sugar content.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is sweeter when you bake it,'' he said. (Wrap a head in
foil with a bit of vinaigrette and push it around the periphery of
a hot Weber grill until it begins to collapse.)
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, despite his culinary background, prefers even simpler
preparations. ``Just slice up the fresh garlic and saute it in
butter until it caramelizes,'' he said. ``It goes great on steak.''
</P>
<P>
   For side dishes he suggested, ``Chop up some scapes and saute
them, and add them to mashed potatoes.'' Another idea: ``Cut a
baguette down the middle, open it up and put some olive oil on it.
Broil it. Add minced garlic, salt and pepper, Parmesan. Close it
up, wrap it in foil and bake it.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time we loaded the car and left New Paltz, we had enough
new garlic to keep ourselves in garlic bread for months. We pointed
the car south and drove until we got to a busy crosstown street. We
double-parked, hopped out and opened the trunk, which reeked. A man
driving by leaned out the window _ a real New Yorker, who wants you
to know he doesn't miss a thing _ and yelled: ``Hey! Is that fresh
garlic?''
</P>
<P>
   We took it upstairs and started cooking. &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   NEW GARLIC PUDDING SOUFFLE  &QL; 
Adapted from ``Chez Panisse Cafe Cookbook'' by Alice Waters
(HarperCollins, 1999) &QL; 
Time: 1 hour 30 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons ({ stick) butter, more for greasing ramekins
</P>
<P>
   \ cup flour
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups milk, slightly warmed
</P>
<P>
   Salt and fresh-ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 sprigs fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   { pound new garlic, sliced, about 1 cup (see note)
</P>
<P>
   Pinch cayenne
</P>
<P>
   { cup grated Gruyere cheese
</P>
<P>
   3 large eggs, separated
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup heavy cream.
</P>
<P>
   1. Melt 3 tablespoons butter in pan over medium-low heat. Stir
in flour, and cook for a few minutes; do not brown. Add milk a
little at a time, whisking to keep mixture smooth. Add { teaspoon
salt and thyme. Reduce heat to very low, and simmer until sauce is
medium-thick, about 20 minutes. Stir frequently to prevent
sticking. Remove from heat, and discard thyme. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Melt remaining butter over medium heat. Add onion, and saute
until translucent. Add new garlic, 1 teaspoon salt and \ cup water.
Reduce heat to low. Simmer until garlic is soft and water has
nearly evaporated, about 10 minutes. Cool, then puree in a food
processor. Stir puree into sauce. Add cayenne, Gruyere and black
pepper to taste. Mix well, and adjust seasonings; sauce should be
highly seasoned. Lightly beat egg yolks, and add to sauce. Mix
well.
</P>
<P>
   3. Heat oven to 400 degrees. Butter six 1-cup ramekins. Beat egg
whites until they form soft peaks, then fold into sauce. Fill
ramekins, and place in a deep baking dish. Pour hot water to
halfway up sides of ramekins. Bake until souffles are golden brown
on top, about 20 minutes. Remove from water bath. Cool, then
unmold, placing in a shallow baking dish, top side up. Souffles can
be held at room temperature for a few hours.
</P>
<P>
   4. Heat oven to 425 degrees. Pour cream over souffles. Bake
until cream bubbles and souffles are puffed, 6 to 8 minutes. Serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: For cup of garlic, } cup sliced leeks, \ cup chopped
scallions and 3 chopped garlic cloves may be substituted.
</P>
</TEXT>
