<SLUG> BC-INTERIOR19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATE APPROVES INTERIOR BILL WITH EVERGLADES FUNDING
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate overwhelmingly passed a $15.5 billion
Interior Department spending bill Tuesday that includes $25 million
for Everglades-related projects.
</P>
<P>
   The 97-2 vote sets up a conference with the House, which passed
a $14.6 billion version of the bill last month.
</P>
<P>
   The bill includes $12 million to assist the state of Florida in
purchasing property near Everglades National Park to act as a
restoration buffer. The Clinton administration had requested $47
million.
</P>
<P>
   It also includes $9 million for construction projects to modify
the water system within the park. The administration had sought $12
million.
</P>
<P>
   Closely tied to the Everglades project, the bill allocated $2
million for land acquisition for Big Cypress National Park and
another $2 million for land acquisition for the Archie Carr
National Wildlife Refuge.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Adams, director of governmental affairs for the National
Audubon Society, said he expects the Everglades will receive more
money before Congress approves a final version of the Interior
spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``These numbers are not good, but I think at the end of the day
we will have higher levels of funding, consistent with previous
appropriations,'' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress has kept (Everglades spending) low to force the
administration to bargain for it, and they will have to give
something,'' Adams said. ``There is a bit of politics being played,
but we've been in about the same place the last couple of years and
the administration has been able to go in there and get them to
agree to higher funding.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has warned he may veto the bill because it does not
include enough money for various park projects or for Indian and
cultural programs.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the final vote, the Senate voted 50-49 to reject
a bid to block Clinton from designating any additional lands as
national monuments.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton already has declared 2 million Western acres as national
monuments under a 1906 law giving him power to act without the
consent of Congress. Opponents worry that he may use that power to
declare all or part of Alaska's Arctic National Wildlife Refuge as
a new monument, making it off-limits to oil companies who want to
drill there.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
