<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVCOLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Younger Sheen ready to give it a 'Spin'
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Charlie Sheen seems calm for a guy facing an
uphill climb this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is he replacing the irreplaceable Michael J. Fox on
ABC's ``Spin City,'' but he also has to take on his father,
Martin's, hit series ``The West Wing'' to do it. The two shows will
go head-to head Wednesday nights, forcing viewers to choose between
Sheens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, the shows are so totally different, it's like choosing
between 'Apocalypse Now' and 'Major League,''' Charlie said.
</P>
<P>
   Any words of encouragement from Papa?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hah! He says he's going to watch us topple and plummet in the
ratings,'' Sheen said with a grin.
</P>
<P>
   Father and son _ in fact the whole Sheen-Estevez acting clan _
are getting along fine these days after Charlie's wild years of
drug addiction that nearly tore apart the family. After several
rehab stints and brushes with the law, Martin had his son arrested
two years ago, and Charlie, 34, has been clean and sober since.
</P>
<P>
   Art will imitate life when Sheen debuts as Charlie Owen, the new
deputy mayor on ``Spin City.'' The character, according to creator
Gary David Goldberg, is ``a bad boy who's a good guy.'' The new
guy's career was tarnished by incidents that bumped him from the
political pages to the gossip columns in New York papers. Too close
to home?
</P>
<P>
   ``To ignore the reality of the lifestyle I led for a long time
would be a disservice to the show _ and to the comedic
possibilities,'' Sheen said. ``Being able to laugh at myself seems
like a good way to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   How much of Sheen's past will be re-created?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain things that can be portrayed in good
taste,'' Sheen said. ``Others really have no place on network
television.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheen is no stranger to comedy. After starting off in serious
films such as ``Platoon'' and ``Wall Street,'' he went for all-out
yucks in ``Major League'' and ``Hot Shots.'' But his stone-faced
comedy is light years from the fast-paced, pratfall style of
Michael J. Fox, a beloved TV figure for whom ``Spin City'' was
written. Fox, of course, left to spend more time with his family as
he battles Parkinson's disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first instinct was to end the show,'' Goldberg said. ``It
was Mike's idea to continue. We definitely would not have gone
forward without his blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   Other shows, notably ``Cheers'' and ``Law &AMP; Order,'' have
survived changes in leads, but such moves are risky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we have a leg up because we have a strong ensemble,
but we have no way of knowing what level of the audience's emotion
was drained by Mike's departure,'' Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox owns an interest in the show and may participate as a
consultant. Whether he will return for guest spots is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever he wants to contribute, we'd be happy to accept,''
Goldberg said. ``He's a guy who always feels obligated, and I don't
want him to feel obligated.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheen has talked with Fox several times since landing the role.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he felt he was leaving his baby behind with a very
trusted guardian,'' Sheen said. ``That was a nice shot in the
arm.''
</P>
<P>
   No questions, please
</P>
<P>
   ABC entertainment chief Stu Bloomberg called a news conference
and then refused to answer questions. Always tight-lipped with the
press, he responded to tepid programming questions a half-dozen
times by saying, ``I don't want to talk about that right now.''
Then when? After the press tour?
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg also insisted his network is not jumping on the
reality bandwagon _ even though ABC has three such programs in
development. Matt Damon and Ben Affleck are conspiring to produce
``The Runner,'' which will send contestants across country as they
try to avoid being detected by viewers. Also on the drawing board
are ``The Mole,'' which will have contestants competing in a group
that will include an infiltrator trying to sabotage them, and ``Go
New York,'' an inside peek at an Internet publication.
</P>
<P>
   On the scene ...
</P>
<P>
   Spandex is alive and tightly wrapped around the stars and
wannabe stars who attended ABC's press tour party Monday at the
Ritz-Carlton in Pasadena. In the land that defies gravity, there's
no such thing as too tight. Everybody wears a size zero.
</P>
<P>
   Geena Davis, the ``Thelma &AMP; Louise'' movie star who has a sitcom
this fall, was sausage-wrapped in black. Ditto the entire cast of
``General Hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   A notable exception was Kathy Kinney, who plays acid-tongued
Mimi on ``The Drew Carey Show.'' She wore a sensibly full dress in
pale lavender. Without her blinding blue-green eyeshadow and
big-hair horrible sense of entitlement and a disgusting smirk,''
said Maher, holding court near a bar. ``But Gore is ultimately less
human. He could be an android for all I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, ABC announced it will launch a new
promotional campaign for ``Norm'' that will feature talking video
screens in selected major-market urinals. The text cannot be
repeated in a family newspaper, but suffice it to say there is word
play on ABC's yellow trademark.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he thought of the campaign, ``Norm'' executive
producer Bruce Helford said, ``Sometimes the low road is less
congested.'' Let's hope.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
