<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESERVATIONS-LIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GOOD EVENING,' THEY LIED 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The original author of ``Thou Shalt Not Lie'' never
anticipated Nobu. Or Pastis. Or Cafe des Artistes.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the lying is about reservations, like ``I made it
a month ago'' (often heard at Joe Allen, which accepts them only a
week in advance) or ``My secretary set it up this morning'' (often
heard at Nobu, which its manager politely terms ``usually
impossible'').
</P>
<P>
   During the last year or so, restaurateurs all over the city say,
lying has spiraled out of control. People want what they want when
they want it, and, well, if they didn't plan in advance, they're
just going to show up and demand it. And they're not only looking
for something as modest as a table for two. Parties of 12 are
walking in the door unannounced, brandishing a major sense of
entitlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens in an economic boom,'' said Clark Wolf, a
restaurant consultant based in Manhattan. ``When all the really big
Hamptons estates are sold, New Yorkers need another place to
compete.''
</P>
<P>
   And it really is a competition, with top restaurants like Babbo
and Nobu booking one month in advance, and many more accepting
reservations no more than a week ahead. Of course, for some people,
it's sport to show up unannounced and see what they can get away
with. When they cheat and win, the thrill is complete. Then again,
there are others who are simply lazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just forgot to call and do it,'' one liar told me.
</P>
<P>
   She appeared anyway with a friend after the theater one night at
Joe Allen, insisting she had called. She was seated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lying happens several times an evening,'' said Sara Collins, a
manager and maitre d'hotel at Nobu. ``We have a very good
reservations system, and inherent in the system are controls about
who's telling the truth. Oftentimes, a group of eight will stand in
front of me and in the thick of it they can't answer the right
questions. The ones who are lying always come in ready to fight.
They think they can intimidate us, and since I'm a woman they think
I'll ultimately buckle and be afraid of them.''
</P>
<P>
   She sighed. ``They think it's a great thing to brag that they
just walked into Nobu and got a table, because the restaurant has
become a cult thing, if you will. People know how difficult it is
to get in here.''
</P>
<P>
   You might think that a really smart liar would take a different
tack and try to charm the staff, rather than alienate it. (Charming
liars who are willing to wait get better treatment than their nasty
counterparts, restaurateurs admit.) But the ones who start off
nasty, they say, are dead giveaways.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the name is not in the book and the people are not the
least bit polite, all signs point to guilty,'' said Mike Cetta, the
owner of Sparks Steakhouse. ``Though you've got to play it by ear.
The good news is we have 684 seats. If we have a table, we'll seat
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Some liars reveal themselves more quickly than others. Jenifer
Lang, the managing director of Cafe des Artistes, who is married to
its owner, George Lang, recalled: ``A couple came in once without a
reservation and they were very loud, saying, `Jenifer and George
Lang are really close friends of ours.' George and I were standing
right there in front of them.'' She laughed. ``It happens a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephane Gerbier, the general manager at Pastis, has had similar
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ultimate line is, `I'm a friend of Keith's,''' he said,
referring to the restaurant's owner, Keith McNally. ``Much of our
staff has worked with Keith in the past, so they tend to know his
friends.'' He sighed. ``But we're trained to be agreeable. It's not
a kick for a us to find a liar.''
</P>
<P>
   Another way some people lie their way through a restaurant's
door is to skip playing pals with the owner and go for the big
time: using real celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week, someone called who said he was coming in with Tom
Cruise and they wanted to be served late,'' Lang said. ``They
preordered their dinner and we made special arrangements to stay
open. They showed up an hour late and came in without him.''
</P>
<P>
   Did anyone say anything? ``No, we're in the hospitality
business,'' she said philosophically. ``We also had Howard Stern
last week. He was a 75-year-old man who came in with his wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Della Femina, who owns Della Femina in New York and East
Hampton, had an even more unnerving experience. ``I called Alison's
by the Beach to make a reservation last week,'' he said, ``and I
said who I was and the woman asked, `Are you  &UR; really? &LR; ' It turned
out that a few weeks ago someone called and said it was me with a
party of eight, and even though the restaurant was really booked,
they spent an hour reconfiguring everything. Then in walks a short
fat guy with lots of hair.''
</P>
<P>
   Della Femina is notoriously bald.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, a stunt like that will work only once, though
for some, once is enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people feel restaurants are fair game, and when
they're in the Hamptons they're even more fair game,'' Della Femina
said. He recalled an incident that his staff named the Happy
Birthday Barbara Scam, which was a reservation for a birthday
dinner for 12 on a Saturday night in the middle of the summer. The
group requested a custom birthday cake, which the restaurant
special-ordered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three or four days later,'' Della Femina said, ``the baker
called to say that Laundry had put in an order for a cake for 12,
East Hampton Point ordered a cake for 12 and Nick &AMP; Toni's ordered
a cake for 12. These people were going to literally stiff one of
us. We stopped our order that day and the people never showed up.
Later, we found that they had also tried booking at the Palm that
night but had been turned down. I'm not even sure where they wound
up. But that's beyond being cynical.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Also hovering in the beyond-cynical category, said Tom
Piscitello, a maitre d'hotel at Babbo, is the new rash of
self-styled concierges. ``That's what they call themselves, but
what they do is broker tables for money,'' he said. ``They learn a
restaurant's booking system, secure tables and sell them to other
people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard all of the stories people can come up with,'' he
went on. ``There are no new ones.'' One of the ways the Babbo staff
weeds out storytellers is to assign reservation numbers. But
Piscitello stressed: ``We try to bend over backwards to accommodate
people. If someone wants to eat here, they will. They'll just
wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Fair enough, if a liar's got the time and inclination. But at
theater district restaurants, for example, the schedule is not as
flexible, since the dinner hour begins at around 10 p.m. or later.
(Pre-theater lying has a very low glamour quotient: after the show
is when the actors tend to eat and bring their famous friends with
them.)
</P>
<P>
   Angus McIndoe, a maitre d'hotel at Joe Allen, says he can expect
an influx of up to 20 people at one time at 11 on a Saturday night.
``What bothers me most is when people come in then and lie,'' he
said. ``They try to intimidate the staff while they hold up
everyone else who did things honestly. The people who do it feel
it's OK to do it. But I can never say, `Are you lying?' to a
customer, and I can't insinuate that because there is always a .01
percent chance that we've made a mistake. So, I tell them, if we
have a table, you'll get it. We treat them like a walk-in.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a restaurant like Joe Allen, which is a traditional
hangout for people in show business, is not the best place for a
liar to stage a scene. As McIndoe said: ``If it is a Saturday night
at 11 o'clock and a celebrity regular comes in, I'm going to seat
him first. I'm not going to make Al Pacino wait at the bar for a
table.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's the whole point, isn't it? Because after all the lies
have been tried _ the lies on the phone and the lies at the door _
at the end of the day, one thing is clear. He really is Al Pacino.
And you're not. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
