u s BC-OLY-BATTEN-NYTR &LR;      07-18 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BATTEN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTEN ISN'T FINISHED JUST YET 
</HEADLINE>
   By LOWELL COHN   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ It must be a pleasure when everyone says
you're washed up, and you know that's a bunch of baloney.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Batten was supposed to be washed up, but that was a lie.
Maybe you never heard of her. She's one of those people who
suddenly become news during an Olympic year when the world pays
attention to track and field. Batten's story is important because
she was once a great hurdler, and then she wasn't a great hurdler,
and now she's trying to be a great hurdler all over again.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't come in first in the finals of the women's 400-meter
hurdles at the Olympic Trials on Monday night. Coming in first
would have been too unbelievable. But she came in second and
qualified for the Olympics. And that itself is something of a
miracle.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for you to learn a few things about Batten. She's the
world record holder in the 400-meter hurdles. She set the world
record in 1995, which in the life of a hurdler, is a long time ago.
</P>
<P>
   How she set the world record is interesting. First of all, she
won the U.S. championships a few weeks after recovering from an
emergency appendectomy. So we're dealing here with a tough cookie.
After that, she set the world record in Goteborg, Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   After that she started to feel pain in the big toe of her right
foot, which she refers to as her ``great'' toe. For a while the
pain didn't matter. She went to the Atlanta Olympics in 1996 and
finished second.
</P>
<P>
   Then everything went to hell. Her great toe hurt so badly she
couldn't rise up on her toes. A regular person would just learn to
walk flat-footed. No big deal. In a hurdler, it's athletic death.
After 1996, Batten's career was a slow decline to no career.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in the U.S. championships, she fell at the eighth
hurdle, and failed to finish the race. And then she just walked
away from track disillusioned and bored. Sorry. Thanks for the
memories.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that wasn't the entire story. She tried to make her toe
feel better. She traveled around the country in search of a cure.
She tested different shoes. She consulted doctors who told her she
had a bone chip, or that her toe was broken, or that they just
couldn't figure out the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, out of desperation, she saw a chiropractor in
Tallahassee, Fla. It's not that she believed in chiropractors, but
she had nothing to lose. This chiropractor did stuff to her toe
that Batten didn't even understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked out of there almost laughing to myself,'' Batten said
after Monday's race. ``This is like voodoo. But it worked. After a
day and a half, 75 percent of the pain was gone. Now, there's no
pain. I don't know what this woman's doing. I know she took the
pain away.''
</P>
<P>
   Just in time, too. Batten has been training for about a month,
which is almost like no training. She's not what runners call
meet-sharp. And that's a bad thing in one of the toughest track
events on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The 400-meter hurdles will rip out your guts. The event combines
the 400 meters, which is the most challenging sprint, with an
obstacle course. Even the best competitors are hurting at the end.
They're struggling and lurching, and none of them looks stylish
struggling across the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   But Batten's lack of preparation also gives her hope. She has
two months before the Olympics, and she's certain to improve. And
that means she's a threat to win the whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Sandra Glover thinks so. Glover came in first Monday.
</P>
<P>
   When they had brought the first three finishers to an interview
room, Glover, who has the severe, sour look of someone who's spent
the last 24 hours sucking on a lemon, announced to Batten in front
of the media, ``Sorry, Kim, but your record is going down.''
</P>
<P>
   Batten almost fell off the podium in surprise. Later, Batten
spoke about Glover.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Sandra, I'll have my own few words to say,'' Batten said.
``I'm not going to be nice to her any more. We're not sprinters,
but I understand the sprinter mentality. I'll make my few words to
her very stern. Now, I'm mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Batten didn't know when she made her comeback and
fixed her great toe, that she'd jump right into the middle of a
controversy. What happens next should be fun.
</P>
<P>
   (Lowell Cohn writes for The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.,
which is a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.
This article was distributed by The New York Times News Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
