<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE VACATION BUG BITES, BE WARY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
 By MONICA ANDERSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This has been one strange summer so far.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, I wake up wondering what odd and fascinating thing
will occur next. Even the most mundane activities have taken
unexpected twists. For instance, I pulled into a gas station the
other day because my fuel gauge was on ``D.''
</P>
<P>
   I had been running low on gas for several days but I kept
forgetting to stop at the service station. This irritates my
husband tremendously but I never, well, hardly ever _ OK, most of
the time I don't run out of gas.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I told my son to hop out and fill 'er up with the
cheapest unleaded on the rack. Slowly but surely he got out and
started filling 'er up. A short while later I glanced in the side
mirror and started screaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop! Stop! For goodness sakes, take your hand off the pump!''
</P>
<P>
   My son was so startled that he almost dropped the hose.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's wrong, Mom?'' he said. ``It's not even full yet. You
said to fill itup.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, that thing is on $30. I have outfits that didn't cost
$30.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're going on vacation,'' he protested.
</P>
<P>
   Grabbing my credit card from his hand, I said, ``Our plans have
changed. We were going to Pensacola but now we're just going to
drive until we run out of gas.''
</P>
<P>
   My youngest boy piped in, ``Mom, we could be anywhere when we
run out of gas. What if it's a boring little town?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you'd better bring something to play with,'' I suggested
as we merged into the traffic. ``And roll those windows down, I'm
turning the air off.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen hours later we pulled into Pensacola, and I tell you
those beautiful white beaches were worth the heat exhaustion
suffered from having those windows rolled down. We were staying at
a total dump but the hotel was on the beach and our room was by the
pool. My husband slept the first day we were there because he drove
most of the way and he was exhausted. I drove all the way to Dallas
_ from Arlington (maybe 20 miles)_ but then I got cramps in my
legs.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, we rented chairs and an umbrella and spent the day
on the beach. I only moved far enough to reach into the cooler, but
the kids rolled in and out of water like little chocolate waves. I
kept warning them to stay in my sight and not to swim out by the
reefs because there were no lifeguards on duty.
</P>
<P>
   My baby boy listened to me but Junior has a more curious spirit.
Before I could stop him, he was snorkeling way out in the bay. The
water was shallow but it still made me nervous to have him out of
arm's reach. Well, my intuition was right. At first, I ignored the
shouts and screams echoing through the air, but when I looked up
and saw everyone exiting the water like a scene from ``Jaws,'' I
was on my feet.
</P>
<P>
   I listened more closely to hear what the commotion was about and
I finally deciphered the word ``SHARK!'' The surfers, the tubers
and the swimmers were all hastily making their way to the sandy
beaches. Everyone but my son was coming to shore.
</P>
<P>
   My husband and I were yelling and screaming at him to get out of
the water. At one point, he raised his head out of the water and
waved at us. Then he went right back under the water. As my husband
started wading into the water to retrieve our child, the shark swam
by. It looked 8 feet long to me but they tell me it was just a baby
shark. Whatever. It wasn't my baby.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I have always maintained that I would fight a lion over my
children but I must confess that I did not put a toe into that
salty water. I left it up to Dad to rescue junior, which he did
with valor.
</P>
<P>
   When we asked our son why he didn't swim to shore when he heard
all of the people screaming, he said, ``I thought they were yelling
for some guy named Mark.''
</P>
<P>
   Strange. Very strange.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is an Arlington, Texas, wife, mother
and dentist, 548-5564. Write in care of the Star-Telegram at 1111
W. Abram St., Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
