<HEADER>
A5734 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINE-TALK-NYT     07-18 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR INEXPENSIVE UPSTARTS, A DAY OF GLORY
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Calif., Mo.) By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last month, I flew to California to be a judge at the San
Francisco International Wine Competition. The event attracted wines
from 16 countries and 22 states in this country, many of them
places one normally thinks of as sources of good wine.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, when the final results were faxed to all 42 of
us _ importers, distributors, sommeliers, wine writers _ who had
been judges, what particularly interested me, aside from the fact
that we got through a record 2,783 wines, was the number of
moderately priced wines that did well.
</P>
<P>
   Against wines costing $100 and more, the best white was judged
to be a 1999 sauvignon blanc from New Zealand's Giesen Wine Estate
listed at $13. The best red was a tie: the 1997 Joseph Phelps
Insignia, a cabernet-based blend that lists at $120, and the 1997
Storrs Winery BXR Red Table wine, at $32.
</P>
<P>
   Among the eight best-of-variety winners were four wines priced
at $10 or less, including a sprightly Italian, a 1998 Montepulciano
d'Abruzzo from Dario d'Angelo at $5. There are restaurants in New
York that get four times that for a bottle of water.
</P>
<P>
   Let me explain about those 2,783 wines. Accepted wisdom holds
that no one can taste that many wines over a weekend and come away
with a coherent assessment. The accepted wisdom is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, that total can be broken down into 10 groups of about
280 wines, a not insignificant number but hardly daunting to a team
of seasoned judges. Spread over several days and divided into
groups of five or six varieties _ cabernet, merlot, pinot noir,
zinfandel and so on _ it becomes a rigorous but hardly onerous
exercise. In practice, the sizes of the groups varies widely; there
are might be hundreds of chardonnays but only a few lembergers or
scheurebes.
</P>
<P>
   Good wine judges work fast, sniffing, tasting and spitting, all
the while scribbling cryptic notes only they understand. Many wines
are never tasted; they are eliminated by smell. The best panels
usually include two or three people who have previously worked
together; in discussing each flight of wines, they understand each
other's remarks, which can be almost as cryptic as their notes.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco competition awards double gold, gold, silver,
and bronze medals. To receive a double gold, a wine must get a gold
meal from the panel that judges it in its own variety group, and
then another gold from the entire group of 42 judges, who compare
it with all the other gold medal winners.
</P>
<P>
   There were 35 double golds, or just over 1 percent of the wines
entered. There were 85 single golds, 327 silvers and 835 bronzes.
Seem like a lot of medals? It is. But wineries enter these
competitions to win medals; no medals, no entries. And the San
Francisco International is one of the roughest competitions. In
half-hearted defense of such largesse it can be said that wines in
general have improved considerably in recent years. What better
proof of that than the fact that so many relatively unknown wines
ended up in the winners' circle along with the thoroughbreds.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: Both the best merlot and the best syrah in the show
cost $8. What's more, both were from the same Australian winery,
Stonehaven Vineyards. The merlot was a 1999; the shiraz, a 1998. Of
course, in that part of the world, syrah is called shiraz.
</P>
<P>
   Other bests included, for riesling, a 1999 halbtrocken
(half-dry) from the Prinz von Hessen, from the Rheingau in Germany,
at $11; and for cabernet sauvignon, a 1997 Amberhill from Raymond
Vineyard in California at $10.
</P>
<P>
   It was especially heartening to see gold medals awarded to
nontraditional wines and nontraditional wine-producing regions.
They included a 1999 steinberg from the Stone Hill Winery in
Hermann, Mo., ($9) and a 1999 seyval blanc from another Missouri
producer, the St. James Winery in St. James ($10).
</P>
<P>
   A gold medal for Willie Frank's 1999 riesling from the
Konstantin Frank winery in the Finger Lakes ($10) strengthens my
feeling that one day, New York state could become the ultimate
source of fine rieslings in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the winners carried bargain basement prices. The best
dessert wine, a double gold winner, was a 1998 riesling icewine
from Jackson-Triggs Vintners in the Okanagan Valley in British
Columbia ($46). The best chardonnay was a 1998 single vineyard wine
from Mirassou Vineyards in Monterey County at $24; the best malbec,
a 1997 Alexander Valley wine from Geyser Peak in Sonoma at $20; the
best sparkling wine, a Gloria Ferrer 1992 brut from Freixenet in
the Carneros section of Sonoma at $22.
</P>
<P>
   Among the winners, there was a noticeable lack of famous names,
either from this country or certainly from France. If Anthony Dias
Blue, the wine and spirits editor of Bon Appetit Magazine, who runs
the San Francisco competition, persists in turning up low-priced
winners he may frighten off the powerhouse wine producers who can
ill afford to have a pack of upstarts ruffle their promotional
feathers.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the results of the competition would seem to
show that, shorn of their carefully constructed mystiques, their
beautiful labels and clever marketing, many expensive wines are
really not that much superior to their less-expensive rivals. Maybe
the veritas really is in the vino.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
