r k BC-EDITORIAL-ABORTION     07-18 0344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ABORTION </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Veto aid bill with abortion 'gag rule'
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Anti-choice zealots in the U.S. House of
Representatives are at it again. Last week, on a vote of 221-206,
GOP conservatives killed a bipartisan effort to remove the
so-called ``gag rule,'' which bars mention of abortion by
international family planning organizations, from the annual
foreign aid bill. In effect, the provision bars those groups from
accepting much-needed U.S. aid.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 600,000 women around the world died from
pregnancy-related complications and lack of proper medical care. In
part because of lack of money, family-planning organizations in
Africa and Asia that offer birth control and prenatal care never
reached these women, some of whom are young teenagers. In effect,
Washington politicians are trading the lives of women and children
for political gain, while piously proclaiming themselves the
protectors of human life. What they are really protecting is the
GOP's far-right flank.
</P>
<P>
   Of Georgia's nine Republicans in Congress, only U.S. Rep. Johnny
Isakson was willing to stand up for women's reproductive health _
for the universal right of women to choose when to bear children
and how many to bear. Along with Georgia Democratic Reps. Cynthia
McKinney and John Lewis, Isakson voted in favor of an amendment
that would have stripped the gag rule out of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton threatened previously to veto the House
foreign-aid bill because it contains $1.8 billion less than he
requested for debt relief, economic and military assistance, AIDs
and health programs. The Senate version doesn't contain the onerous
anti-choice provision, but it shortchanges debt relief to an even
greater extent than the House bill. The president should exercise
his veto power if the gag rule isn't dropped and the funding
enhanced in upcoming budget negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   This editorial appeared in the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
