<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I WROTE THIS COLUMN ON MY PALM PDA
</HEADLINE>
  By LONNIE BROWN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the recent PC Expo, personal digital assistants were all the
rage _ with interest partly fueled by Microsoft's new PocketPC
operating system designed for PDAs with color screens and big
memory capacity.
</P>
<P>
   The real workhorses, however, are the Palm PDAs and and their
new siblings, the Visor from Handspring. The Palms have been around
for several years, and although the lower-end models lack color
screens, they still have crisp black-and-white displays, lots of
memory, and can provide weeks of service on two AAA batteries. They
also have a lower price: between $150 to $250 for basic models that
lack wireless capabilities, but will fulfill the needs of many
users.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm personal information managers are good for finding and
storing all sorts of information. A little larger than a deck of
playing cards _ but no thicker _ one can fit in a shirt pocket or
small purse. They hold addresses, telephone numbers, a to-do list,
and random information.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a memo function. And using it, and a small,
portable keyboard that the Palm plugs directly into, I was able to
write this entire column. The finished product was transferred from
the Palm to the office desktop computer using Palm's
synchronization cradle (which backs up all the information in the
Palm to a hard disk). Once in the office computer, the text was
transferred to the newspaper's word processor where it was then
turned into print.
</P>
<P>
   GoType! Pro from LandWare Inc. was the keyboard used. It has 62
keys and six function keys. The function keys are used just like
the function keys on the Palm to bring up the datebook, address
book, to-do list and search capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The keyboard is about a foot long (about twice the length of a
Palm IIIx) and about four inches wide (slightly wider than the
Palm). The Palm plugs into the keyboard, so the screen of the Palm
becomes a word-processing monitor. On either end of the keyboard is
a small holder for the Palm's pointing stylus, which must be used
occasionally _ mainly to highlight a choice on the Palm screen that
might not be available through pressing keys.
</P>
<P>
   Without the keyboard, I could have entered this review
letter-by-letter in the Palm. But that's no fun. The Palm's
graffiti (its term for the letter-making symbols) is easy enough
for entering small amounts of information. But it would take a
considerable amount of time to enter this much into the Palm using
the hand recognition method.
</P>
<P>
   But I can type nearly as fast on the GoType! keyboard as I can
on a full-size keyboard. There's no delay in getting the letters on
the Palm's screen and the time a key is pressed. The keyboard has
no batteries of its own. It uses the Palm's power, and it doesn't
seem to create any drain on the batteries.
</P>
<P>
   The keyboard also has a serial connector on its side, so it can
be used as a cradle for the Palm to synchronize the Palm with a
desktop computer. If you need two cradles _ one for home, one for
office _ it's an advantage worth considering.
</P>
<P>
   The keyboard comes with TakeNote, a word-processing program that
simplifies note taking with the keyboard, and WordSleuth, a
thesaurus program.
</P>
<P>
   The GoType! Pro keyboard is $70. Last week, LandWare had ``open
box'' keyboards that had been returned and refurbished for $45. For
information: www.landware.com.
</P>
<P>
   Palm's version of the keyboard is far different from the one
developed by LandWare. Its four hinged sections fold up to about
the size of the Palm organizer itself _ slightly larger than a
3-by-5-inch index card. Unfolded, it is the same size as a
full-size keyboard _ big enough to touch-type on, small enough to
fit on an airline tray. The keyboard sells for about $99.
</P>
<P>
   For information: www.palm.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor of The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla. He can be reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. The
Ledger is a member of the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
