<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRENQUE WINS FINAL ALPS SEGMENT OF TOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORZINE, France _ Richard Virenque _ ``Ree-shar'' to nearly
every adolescent in France _ finally gave his fans something
concrete to celebrate Tuesday.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The French star has shone less brightly through the first 15
daily stages in this 21-stage, 87th Tour de France. But on the last
of three days in the Alps on Tuesday, he powered away on the final
climb, negotiated a tricky curve that wiped out his one companion
and easily finished first. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the Polti team and five-time winner of the king of
the mountains jersey in the Tour, Virenque credited the return of a
hot sun for his victory. Not that hot, actually _ temperatures atop
the last of five climbs barely reached 68 degrees Fahrenheit _ but
at least this was no longer the Tour of Frigid France, as it has
been since the start on July 1. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I like hot weather,'' Virenque said. ``I like the sun. I ride
best in hot weather.'' While the forecast until Sunday, when the
tour finishes in Paris, is for continuing sun and heat, there are
only small hills left to climb and he seems destined not to win a
sixth climbing jersey, tying the record. He ranks third in that
category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, though, he fulfills another goal: In fifth place
overall, he is the highest-ranking Frenchman behind the continuing
leader, Lance Armstrong, the defending champion and chief of the
U.S. Postal Service team. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong did not have a good day. ``The hardest day of my life
on a bike,'' he called it after he finished eighth, 2 minutes, one
second behind the winner. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem was a `fringale,' '' he explained, using the
French word for a sudden loss of energy.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't eat enough and on the last climb had no energy,'' he
said. On the narrow alpine road, his team car could not get to him
to supply nourishment and he had no teammate with him to drop back
and fetch it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong started that climb, the 11.8-kilometer Joux Plane,
with an average grade of a steep 8.5 percent, in fine position just
behind an early breakaway that was leading the stage. He was about
a third of the way up, riding with Virenque and Jan Ullrich, the
German in second place, when he began to fall back. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His face strained and his pedaling uneasy for the first time in
this Tour, Armstrong continued to lose ground. Soon he was a minute
behind his two former companions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to limit my losses,'' he reported afterward. ``I
told myself to just stay in control and don't panic.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mission accomplished. His lead over Ullrich, who finished
second, shrunk two minutes to a still-safe 5:37. The German, the
leader of the Telekom team, gained a minute over the third-place
rider, Joseba Beloki, a Spaniard with Festina, who is now 6:38
behind Armstrong. In fourth place is Roberto Heras, a Spaniard with
Kelme and the rider who crashed into a barrier on a curve into the
resort of Morzine as he battled Virenque for the victory. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Frenchman is fifth, 7:36 behind, with Christophe Moreau, a
Frenchman with Festina, sixth, 8:22 behind.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Virenque was timed in 5 hours, 32 minutes and 20 seconds for the
196.5-kilometer (122-mile) 16th stage from Courchevel, a speed of
35 kilometers an hour. Ullrich was 24 seconds slower, with Heras
third, 27 seconds behind the winner. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The major wipeout of the day was Marco Pantani, the fine Italian
climber and leader of the Mercatone Uno team, who won the Tour in
1998. A day after he and Armstrong bickered about the race, Pantani
attacked on the first of the day's climbs, far earlier than he
usually does. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He built a lead of nearly two minutes, as if he was determined
to show Armstrong who was really boss, then fell apart. By the
final climb, he was at the tail end of the main group. Soon he was
going uphill at the speed of somebody bicycling to the grocery. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pantani finished in 38th place, 13:44 behind the winner, and
fell from sixth overall to 14th. Like Virenque, he has run out of
mountains.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1644EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
