<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5740 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SORBET-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      07-18 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SORBET-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ESSENCE OF SUMMER, SAVORED WITH A SPOON 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: recipes at end of article)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On nearly every dessert menu, sorbets are listed in
the very same way, in the very same place: ``assorted sorbets,'' at
the bottom, as if they were an afterthought or a compromise for
diners who don't want to commit to a whole dessert. The listing is
as appealing and nondescript as ``mixed green salad.''
</P>
<P>
   For many New York restaurants, it is an exercise in deceit.
Sorbet, in the hands of a good pastry chef, can be the most
thrilling flavor in a meal, and can be one of those culinary
miracles that actually improves on nature.
</P>
<P>
   Take the cantaloupe. Its flesh is pureed smooth, its flavor is
intensified so that it is more nectar than juice. Then, it is
chilled and churned so that it has the creaminess of caramel. It
becomes cantaloupe that is as refreshing as an iced drink, as
powerful as a shot of whiskey.
</P>
<P>
   It is what you hope to get from a melon bought at the store and
never really find, even at the Greenmarket. The transformation is
simple _ puree, season and freeze _ but what is captured is the
essence of the fruit and the palate of the cook in a way that no
other dessert can.
</P>
<P>
   A good sorbet should taste like an extraction of its main
flavor, and nothing else. It should be more gutsy than ice cream,
and more pure. There is no custard to compete with. Its substance
is formed by the main flavor, some sweetening and a little water.
There are almost no limitations on flavors; they can be summer
fruits like peaches, blackberries and nectarines, or spices,
chocolate, herbs or spirits. Some chefs have recently taken to
making almost-ice-cream sorbets with fromage blanc, sour cream or
even goat cheese. All of them are able to stand out without
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   If you were to ask about the ``assorted sorbets'' at Lespinasse,
the response would be startling. On a recent day, they had jasmine,
red hibiscus, litchi, fromage frais, apricot and orange-nepitella.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds more like a botanical garden inventory. But it's not
that chefs like Chris Broberg at Lespinasse are forcing
inventiveness. Sorbets are an ideal way for a flavor to express
itself, and they know it.
</P>
<P>
   Sono serves a cantaloupe sorbet but infuses it with an unusual
partner: star anise. Where the melon might droop, the anise picks
up. Where the anise might overwhelm, the cantaloupe dilutes it. As
an ice cream, it would have lacked poignancy.
</P>
<P>
   A fromage blanc-lemon grass sorbet at Vong strikes a similarly
surprising balance. The fromage blanc is tangy and blunt; the lemon
grass rounds out the edges and showers it with a floral, herbal
aroma that lingers in your mouth. At Eleven Madison Park, a
strawberry-moscato sorbet manages to eliminate the tartness of the
fruit and the cloyingness of the wine.
</P>
<P>
   Single flavors can be almost shocking in their purity. A
grapefruit sorbet at Brasserie tastes as though you're biting into
a very cold, perfectly ripened grapefruit without anything _ not
even a grain of sugar _ to distract you.
</P>
<P>
   But there are plenty of sorbets that taste more like flavored
water, or have enough sugar to give you a headache. Others,
especially those bought in the grocery store, can be gummy from
additives meant to keep them from turning icy.
</P>
<P>
   While sorbets are easy to make, they are also unforgiving.
Underripe strawberries will make a sorbet that tastes green and
bitter. Cheap sake will make a sorbet that tastes yeasty and has
the aroma of worn socks. Not exactly what most people want.
</P>
<P>
   Great ingredients are the only way around this. Wines and
spirits should be ones you would drink. Spices should be fresh.
Fruit should be in good condition and nearly overripe.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar is added for several reasons. It is a seasoning, like salt
in savory dishes. It balances acids, elevates the main flavor and,
of course, makes it a dessert. But it is also responsible for
creaminess in the texture. Without it, sorbet would be icy and
grainy.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to sweeten the main flavor without diluting it and
without making it, as contradictory as it sounds, sweet. And though
regular granulated sugar works, it must be dissolved in water first
and cooked into a syrup.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, this additional water can also dilute the
flavor, and too much sugar can oversweeten the base. Pastry chefs
tend to use a combination of sugar syrup and glucose or Trimoline.
These two are invert sugars, sweeteners in which the sucrose has
been broken down into glucose and fructose. They have a low
moisture content compared to sugar syrup and are less sweet than
granulated sugar. They also inhibit crystallization, making the
sorbet feel creamy once it's frozen rather than granular. They can
be difficult to find, but light corn syrup, also an invert sugar,
makes a good substitute.
</P>
<P>
   As with any seasoning, you must use your judgment when adding
these sweeteners. Tart blueberries, for example, may be watered
down by extra sugar syrup. So you may need to use less water in the
syrup or more corn syrup.
</P>
<P>
   In a sorbet that is more of an infusion, like the lime-rosemary
sorbet at Local, sweetness is needed to balance the acid in the
lime juice and give texture to the sorbet _ but it isn't meant to
upstage the heady scent of the rosemary.
</P>
<P>
   Sorbets made with starchy or densely textured fruits, like
papayas and bananas, do not need as much sugar for texture. At
Fressen, a pure papaya sorbet is very creamy but hardly sweetened
at all. It tastes as if you are scraping spoonfuls straight from
the fruit. For banana sorbet, Nicole Kaplan, the pastry chef at
Eleven Madison Park, actually roasts the fruit first (whole in its
skin with a few slashes so it doesn't explode) to break down its
starch.
</P>
<P>
   There is one other way _ though a less honest way _ to give
sorbet a creamy texture. You can add a lightly whipped egg white to
the sorbet in the ice cream maker, just before it finishes
churning. It makes the sorbet lighter and, some chefs claim,
creamier. But I find that it gives the sorbet a texture like that
of the head on a beer. It is full, light and annoyingly foamy.
</P>
<P>
   Once a sorbet base is mixed _ it is usually quite liquid _ it
should be tasted and adjusted much like a soup would be. Many fruit
sorbets, like jams and jellies, benefit from a splash of citrus
juice, which sharpens their flavor. In sorbets made with cream,
buttermilk or fromage blanc, you can add a pinch of salt.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the sorbet should be a little too intensely
flavored, because once it goes into the machine, it will change.
The machine whips air into the mixture and diminishes its flavor.
</P>
<P>
   When making sorbet at home, the biggest problem is usually the
ice cream maker. Many home models are rudimentary. They either
don't churn the sorbet enough or don't get cold enough, forcing you
to call it quits before the mixture is properly churned. Later, you
are left with a hard mass that you have to chip like a block of
ice.
</P>
<P>
   To get around this, it's best to chill the sorbet liquid before
adding it to the machine. This way, it doesn't warm up the freezing
container at the beginning. If the sorbet contains alcohol, which
acts as an antifreeze, you can pour it into a deep pan and light it
(carefully!) with a match to burn off the alcohol before adding it
to the sorbet mixture.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sorbets swirl around the container in the machine unchanged for
most of the churning, then turn slushy and eventually thick just at
the very end. Checking up on it during the first 20 minutes is
discouraging if nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   It's best to make small batches, so that you know it will freeze
quickly enough for your machine to whip it up well at the end. (It
should be thick and almost elastic-looking by the time it's done
churning.)
</P>
<P>
   But there is another reason to make small batches. You don't
want the sorbet to last too long. In good restaurants, sorbet is
made every day. Some even melt down the batch made in the morning,
readjust its flavor and then rechurn it before dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Sorbet is like any fresh fruit. Its flavor is fleeting. Its
texture is fragile. Its moment of intense purity is brief. You
should embrace it at its pinnacle, or not at all.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. RECIPES FOLLOW)
</P>
<P>
   ROSEMARY-LIME SORBET
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Local
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes, plus chilling and churning time  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   } cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 cups half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped rosemary
</P>
<P>
   \ cup light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 3 limes.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a large sauce pan, combine sugar, half-and-half, rosemary
and corn syrup. Whisk lightly and bring to a boil, making sure
mixture does not boil over, then strain into a bowl. Let cool, then
chill in refrigerator. Remove from refrigerator and slowly whisk in
lime juice. If mixture shows signs of curdling, whisk harder or
transfer to a blender.
</P>
<P>
   2. Pour mixture into an ice cream maker and follow
manufacturer's instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 1 quart.
</P>
<P>
   FROMAGE BLANC-LEMON GRASS SORBET
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Vong
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes, plus overnight chilling and churning time  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   } cup plus 2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   1 stalk lemon grass, smashed
</P>
<P>
   22/3 cups fromage blanc.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a large saucepan, combine sugar, corn syrup, lemon grass
and 2 cups water. Bring to a boil, then remove from heat and let
cool. Cover and chill in refrigerator overnight.
</P>
<P>
   2. Strain liquid through a fine sieve. Stir fromage blanc into
liquid. Taste and adjust sweetness if necessary. Pour into an ice
cream maker and follow manufacturer's instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 1 quart.
</P>
<P>
   STRAWBERRY-MOSCATO SORBET
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Eleven Madison Park
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes, plus chilling and churning time  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup very ripe strawberries, quartered
</P>
<P>
   1 cup moscato wine
</P>
<P>
   { cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup plus 2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons corn syrup.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a food processor, puree strawberries. Add moscato, orange
juice, sugar, corn syrup and 1{ cups water. Puree. Strain through a
fine sieve. Taste, adding sugar if necessary. Chill in
refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   2. Stir mixture, then pour into an ice cream maker and follow
manufacturer's instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 1 quart.
</P>
<P>
   CANTALOUPE-STAR ANISE SORBET  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Sono &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes, plus resting and churning time  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 very ripe cantaloupes, peeled, seeded and cut into large
chunks
</P>
<P>
   12 pieces star anise
</P>
<P>
   } cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   \ cup light corn syrup.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a food processor, puree cantaloupe until smooth. This
should yield at least 4 cups. In a large saucepan, combine 4 cups
cantaloupe puree, star anise, sugar, corn syrup and 1 cup water.
Place over medium-low heat and stir just until sugar is dissolved.
Remove from heat and let rest for at least 2 hours at room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   2. Strain through a fine sieve, pressing out as much juice as
possible. Pour liquid into an ice cream maker and follow
manufacturer's instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 1{ quarts.
</P>
</TEXT>
