<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5747 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-TOYS-R-FUN-2TAKES-TEX     07-18 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYS-R-FUN-2TAKES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECIALIZED PLAYTHINGS HELP KIDS WITH SPECIAL NEEDS LEARN (AND HAVE
FUN)
</HEADLINE>
  ATTN: Ill. 
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
 By JAVONNA MAY-MONS 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All kids love toys, but not all toys love all kids.
</P>
<P>
   Which is too bad. Toys are a great way for children to develop
skills essential to reasoning, self-esteem, movement and
socializing. And, of course, toys R fun.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, when Congress passed the Americans with
Disabilities Act mandating equal access to employment, public and
commercial facilities and healthcare, our legislators didn't add
any provisions about play toys. But the act did signal a sea change
in the way Americans thought about people with special needs.
</P>
<P>
   And soon, toy companies and retailers responded.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Toys R Us, the nation's No. 1 retail toy store, joined
forces with a nonprofit group called the National Lekotek Center to
create the ``Toys 'R' Us Toy Guide for DifferentlyAbled Kids!''
</P>
<P>
   Lekotek, a 40-year-old nonprofit group based in Evanston, Ill.,
is dedicated to engaging special-needs children in play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guide promotes the philosophy that play, laughter, fun and
toys should be universally enjoyed by every child _ including
children with special needs,'' says Beth Boosalis Davis, executive
director of the center. ``It minimizes the guesswork in selecting
appropriate toys, increases the potential for more fun and learning
opportunities, and builds on what a child can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Toys R Us sought Lekotek's help in creating the catalog because
of the center's special services: providing play sessions and toy
lending libraries for infants through 8-year-olds. The Lekotek
(loosely translated as ``play library'') concept was launched in
Sweden in the early 1960s by parents of disabled children who
banded together to share hard-to-find adapted toys. In 1980, the
first American Lekotek was launched in Evanston. Today, the
company's more than 60 nationwide play centers welcome children
with a wide range of disabilities such as Down syndrome, cerebral
palsy, sight or hearing loss, mental retardation, and chronic
conditions including HIV/AIDS and cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The toy guide itself includes playthings for children with a
range of disabilities. Toys are selected on the basis of how they
meet developmental skill criteria, including: auditory, creativity,
fine motor, gross motor, language, self esteem, social, tactile,
thinking and visual skills. Although these guidelines for
playthings may seem appropriate for any child, they are extremely
important for disabled children, who are oftentimes late in
developing motor and social skills. Each entry in the guide
includes a picture of the toy and an explanation of which
developmental skills the toy helps the child with. For example, a
little boy in a wheelchair is shown wearing the Tech-Link Aviator
500, an electronic headset, which is said to promote social skills,
language and creativity.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Paweni, Lekotek marketing manager, explains a few of the
benefits this toy offers disabled children: ``It's good for speech
and language disorders because you're practicing how to
communicate. For the hearing impairments you can eliminate external
noise and increase the volume.''
</P>
<P>
   Before being accepted into the guide, toys must go through
thorough and rigorous trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our play experts review the toys and indicate what type of
disabilities it would work for,'' Paweni says. ``And they also
observe children and families playing with them. And we get
feedback from parents.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar collaboration took place between the American Toy
Institute _ a facet of the Toy Manufacturers of America that
solicits, collects and raises funds for children's charities _ and
the American Foundation for the Blind in 1993 when TMA President
David Miller proposed the idea. Each year the ATI and AFB issue the
``Guide to Toys for Children Who Are Blind or Visually Impaired.''
The guide features commercially available toys and games
appropriate for children of all ages who are blind or have low
vision or special needs.
</P>
<P>
   Again, children play an integral role in selecting the featured
toys. The AFB's guide's input comes from three special-needs
schools in the New York area that allow 75 to 100 children to
participate in the toy trials.
</P>
<P>
   David Miller ``came to the American Foundation for the Blind and
organized the testing of toys by blind children,'' said Elizabeth
Neal, AFB communications specialist. ``So basically our
organization set up appointments with schools for blind or visually
impaired children and brought in toys and had the kids play with
them. We took their assessment and made selections from that.''
</P>
<P>
   As attention to the play needs of special-needs children has
grown, new sources for toys have appeared on the market. One of the
most notable recent additions is Life's Little Helpers. The
company, which is based in Deerfield, Fla., is a branch of
Diabetic.com, a site dedicated to the medical needs of diabetics.
Life's Little Helpers has a print catalog and an online catalog
full of all sorts of products aimed at disabled people of all ages
_ including kids. Toys include everything from phones with both
Braille and large numbers to a Braille version of the popular board
game Battleship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of Braille items,'' said Gabrielle Ohayon,
director of new business. Ohayon said that people with diabetes
sometimes suffer from vision and walking problems. Life's Little
Helpers offers items to make their lives easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, we have a whistling football or volleyball that
people who are visually challenged can actually play (with) and
hear the ball whistle and guide themselves accordingly.''
(MORE) (A listing of 10 special toys for special-needs kids, and
tips for buying, both of which can run as separates.).
</P>
<P>
   Ten special toys for special-needs kids (unless otherwise noted,
all can be found at major toy retailers; prices are approximate):
</P>
<P>
   1. Peaceful Planet Soothing Sounds Bear
</P>
<P>
   With a gentle nudge or hug, this bear makes the sounds of
nature. Birds, crickets and babbling brooks lull kids to sleep
while giving them something soft to snuggle. A glowing sun on the
bear's chest creates a soft, comforting night light. The sounds
continue for about two minutes before the toy needs another hug.
This soft, cushy bear is great for children with visual impairments
because it gives them something solid to hold and makes soft
sounds, providing night-time comfort. $14.99.
</P>
<P>
   2. Leap Frog Explorer
</P>
<P>
   This globe from Leap Frog is a great educational tool. Touching
the NearTouch Magic Pen to any country gives the country's name. By
touching the country again, the child can learn facts such as the
country's population, capital and currency. Touching two countries
will give you the distance between the two. The globe features a
game called ``Eureka!,'' in which the globe gives a country's name
and the player has 45 seconds to find it. The globe has three
difficulty levels. In addition to that, the volume is adjustable _
a plus for hearing-impaired children. $99. (Life's Little Helpers
carries a similar toy called Geosafari Talking Globe Junior,
$99.95)
</P>
<P>
   3. Beeping foam balls
</P>
<P>
   Most children love playing with balls, and these soft foam,
beeping balls ensure that blind or visually impaired children won't
be left out. They are extremely safe to use and easy to find by
following the high-pitched beeping sound, which can also be turned
off. Available in soccer ball, Nerf football and 63/8-inch-diameter
round ball. Life's Little Helpers, $39.95
</P>
<P>
   4. Roller 2 in-line skates
</P>
<P>
   The popular sport of in-line skating can help with mastery of
gross motor skills, which is especially important for
developmentally delayed children. The boot is designed to be used
with shoes and has a sturdy, built-up ankle support. Parents can
choose from three settings: locked, forward only or freewheeling.
Adjustable wheel space allows the skates to move from a broad to a
narrow base. Skates can be adjusted to fit infant size 8 to
children's size 2. $19.99.
</P>
<P>
   5. Song Magic Banjo
</P>
<P>
   Barney's Song Magic Banjo provides musical, two-handed play for
kids who can hold onto the banjo. Although the banjo doesn't have
strings, a child has but to ``strum'' through its center for music
to play. Press the large button on its neck to select from eight
familiar songs or eight instrument sounds. The banjo can be held in
any position, ensuring that a child can use just one arm arm or a
leg to play. This toy is great for hearing-impaired children and
promotes fine motor skills and thinking. $24.99.
</P>
<P>
   6. Happy Stack
</P>
<P>
   Bright colorful tubes and zany happy faces make this
stack-'em-up game a favorite with babies. For developmentally
delayed kids, Happy Stack promotes fine motor skills by prompting
babies to use eye-hand coordination and two hands cooperatively to
stack the plastic pieces. The tubes may be stacked in any order
your child pleases. The peekaboo heads on each piece eliminate the
pole that many children have difficulty reaching over when placing
the tubes. The peekaboo heads also serve as a natural handle,
allowing kids to better manipulate the pieces. $7.99
</P>
<P>
   7. Frontier Fort Lincoln Logs
</P>
<P>
   Building this log cabin promotes fine motor skills and
creativity. The play set contains wooden logs, ladder, figures and
instructions for creating different layouts, including multiple
buildings complete with plastic roofs, doors and windows. Children
can let their imagination run wild and practice language skills by
telling a story while building. $19.99
</P>
<P>
   8. Braille alphabet blocks
</P>
<P>
   Classic wood blocks embossed with letters and corresponding
Braille cells can help blind or visually impaired children learn
their alphabet. The 27 colorful blocks include realistic animal
drawings, letters and numbers on the other sides. Life's Little
Helpers, $27.95
</P>
<P>
   9. Chinese checkers
</P>
<P>
   Chinese checkers introduces the concept of competition. Children
will learn how to play against opponents without trying to
purposely set them back. Simple instructions keep youngsters who
aren't yet reading from feeling frustrated. This game promotes fine
motor skills, social skills and thinking. $2.99.
</P>
<P>
   10. Vortex Power Bat
</P>
<P>
   The people who brought us Koosh balls are responsible for the
Vortex Power Bat, a lightweight bat and plastic ball. The bat has
an easy-to-grasp, textured handle and a large hitting surface. The
ball is a bright fluorescent orange, making it easy to see and
find. Children can practice gross motor skills and increase their
self-esteem with a home run. $19.99. ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Shopping for special-needs kids
</P>
<P>
   The National Lekotek Center offers 10 tips to keep in mind when
buying toys for children with disabilities:
</P>
<P>
   1. Multisensory appeal
</P>
<P>
   Does the toy respond with lights, sounds or movement to engage
the child? Are there contrasting colors? Does it have a scent? Is
there texture?
</P>
<P>
   2. Method of activation
</P>
<P>
   Will the toy provide a challenge without frustration? What is
the force required to activate? What are the number and complexity
of steps required to activate?
</P>
<P>
   3. Where the toy will be used
</P>
<P>
   Will the toy be easy to store? Is there space in the home? Can
the toy be used when the child is in a variety of positions, such
as lying on his or her side or in a wheelchair?
</P>
<P>
   4. Opportunities for success
</P>
<P>
   Can play be open-ended with no definite right or wrong way? Is
the toy adaptable to the child's individual style, ability and
pace?
</P>
<P>
   5. Current popularity
</P>
<P>
   Is it a toy that will help the child with disabilities feel like
``any other kid?'' Does it tie in with other forms of
entertainment, such as books and art sets, that promote other forms
of play?
</P>
<P>
   6. Self-expression
</P>
<P>
   Does the toy allow for creativity, uniqueness and choice-making?
Will it give the child experience with a variety of mediums?
</P>
<P>
   7. Adjustability
</P>
<P>
   Does it have adjustable height, sound volume, speed and level of
difficulty?
</P>
<P>
   8. Child's individual characteristics
</P>
<P>
   Does the toy provide activities that reflect the child's
interest and age?
</P>
<P>
   9. Safety and durability
</P>
<P>
   Consider the child's size and strength. Is the toy
moisture-resistant? Can it be washed and cleaned?
</P>
<P>
   10. Potential for interaction
</P>
<P>
   Will the child be an active participant during use? Will the toy
encourage social engagement?
Source: National Lekotek Center
SOURCES
</P>
<P>
   To get a free copy of the ``Toys R Us Toy Guide for
DifferentlyAbled Kids!,' call (800) 366-PLAY.
</P>
<P>
   Additional information about Lekotek and its services is
available at www.lekotek.org.
</P>
<P>
   The American Foundation for the Blind provides free copies of
its ``Guide to Toys for Children Who Are Blind or Visually
Impaired'' in full-color print or audiocassette. Call (800)
232-5463. The guide is also posted on the AFB's Web site,
www.afb.org and the ATI's Web site, www.toy-tma.org.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on Life's Little Helpers, call (877)
AHELPER or visit www.lifeslittlehelpers.com.
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
