<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WRITERS' BLOC 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB ARMSTRONG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Internal bleeding and liver failure caused Allan
Bloom's death in 1992, according to his obituary. The conservative
critic and author of ``The Closing of the American Mind'' comes to
life again, then dies of AIDS as a character in Saul Bellow's new
novel, ``Ravelstein.''
</P>
<P>
   Bellow and Bloom were close friends, but Bellow has been accused
by numerous critics of outing Bloom and betraying his friendship.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Paul Theroux wrote a book on his mentor and close
friend V.S. Naipaul. No disturbing outing here, but Theroux paints
an unflattering portrait of Naipaul as an insufferable lout with a
``sour mouth'' and ``cheated eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Literary feuds are commonplace, but usually among writers who
knife each other at a distance and were never buddies. Like Mary
McCarthy's famous _ or infamous _ denunciation of Lillian Hellman:
``Every word she writes is a lie, including `and' and `the.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the art of betrayal, writers have it made. Instead of going
to jail for assault and battery, they get to splatter blood all
over the page, which then becomes the hot item of the week to read,
followed by television appearances which enhance the stature of the
writer.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, the writer gets paid for the hit job.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not trying to come off high and mighty here. Quite the
opposite. I can't get enough of these betrayals. I recall trembling
with excitement when I spotted a review of a book by Norman
Podhoretz, a heavyweight in Manhattan intellectual circles for more
than 50 years. The title alone had me running to the bookstore:
``Ex-Friends.''
</P>
<P>
   I was not disappointed. Podhoretz blasts away at Lionel
Trilling, Lillian Hellman and Mary McCarthy, Allen Ginsberg, Norman
Mailer, Hannah Arendt, Hans J. Morgenthau and other literary lights
with whom he shared highballs and lofty ideas until his own views
shifted from left to right in the late '60s.
</P>
<P>
   When somebody does the switcheroo in politics, too often the
fallout is personal. Although I enjoy reading about writers doing
each other in, it is sad when differences of opinion keep them
apart. What another critic said about Bloom's ``The Closing of the
American Mind'' is a perfect retort to the writer who turns on a
friend for the ``wrong'' politics: What we really have here is the
closing of AN American mind.
</P>
<P>
   I don't believe all those with bright minds and sharp pens have
mean hearts, but you have to wonder if these writers are capable of
true friendship. I suspect what is taking place in these bondings
is cheap office politics in a refined setting.
</P>
<P>
   Writers use each other as stepping stones, a mutual aid society
to get on the inside track. The meaningful conversation at the
party where One Must Be Seen provides not only intellectual
stimulation, but access to the movers and shakers at the party.
(Strange too, these distinguished writers sucking up to each other
in the Friendly First Stage, and then writing amusing anecdotes
about has-beens and hangers-on and sycophants circling around
important people at the party.)
</P>
<P>
   In ``Ex-Friends,'' Podhoretz tells us he turned down an
invitation to Norman Mailer's 75th birthday party because the
author ``had so bitterly disappointed my literary expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   I can't read Podhoretz's mind, but I'm tempted to say every word
in that quote is a lie.
</P>
<P>
   But the quote speaks volumes. He wants us to know he got an
invitation many would covet. Better yet, he gets to tell us he
doesn't need it and for good measure can shove it back down
Mailer's throat.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, he's letting us know he's a man of high principles
who doesn't need to suck up to Mailer.
</P>
<P>
   With friends like Podhoretz . . .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
