<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5751 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-18 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SORRY, IT WAS A SENIOR MOMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The subject has replaced all others in my circle
of friends and acquaintances. Finances, kids, spouses, partners,
religion and politics all take a backseat to Topic A:
</P>
<P>
   Forgetting.
</P>
<P>
   Put two or more people of my age group _ baby boomers _
together, and the embarrassing, mystifying, sad stories abound. One
by one, each woman or man steps forward to recount her or his
latest ``senior moment'' _ a colossal memory or attention lapse.
</P>
<P>
   Always, the confessions are accompanied by a bewildered shaking
of the head, as if the teller were describing something that was
visited upon her or him.
</P>
<P>
   Like an alien inhabitation.
</P>
<P>
   Always, one confession inspires another:
</P>
<P>
   ``You think THAT'S bad, let me tell you what I did . . .''
</P>
<P>
   And almost always, someone pipes up with a well-meaning but
totally unsuccessful attempt at consolation:
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you think it's just because we live in such distracting,
stressful times? Because we just have too much in our heads?''
</P>
<P>
   No, it is because we are getting older, and getting older means
never having to say, ``You can count on me; I'll remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Legions of experts work on various drugs, programs, exercises,
supplements and voodoo dances that might help millions of us
mitigate the unraveling of our brains.
</P>
<P>
   They suggest we ``make lists.''
</P>
<P>
   I make lists, then forget to check them. Or forget where I put
the lists.
</P>
<P>
   Now that I have a computer, I could put the lists there. But a
recent experience while on vacation scared me off of that. I tried
to sign on as a ``guest'' on AOL at my parents' house, but I had
forgotten my password.
</P>
<P>
   AOL's help line gave me a temporary password to get me into my
own e-mail, but _ without my real password _ I couldn't access my
personal address book.
</P>
<P>
   What good is e-mail without one's e-mail address book? Like I'm
expected to remember e-mail addresses when I can't even remember my
own password?
</P>
<P>
   Another memory expert suggests that we can better remember or
focus on things if we can ``incorporate them into a story.''
</P>
<P>
   I write ``stories'' for a living. Just last week, I wrote
``Julie Christy'' in a column when I meant to write ``June
Christy.'' Alas, both are blonds, but Julie Christie is a film
actress and June Christy was a singer with Stan Kenton's band.
</P>
<P>
   Last month I wrote that I started working at this newspaper in
1975, when I clearly knew that I began in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of good it does me to incorporate information into
stories.
</P>
<P>
   But, as I mentioned a few paragraphs back _ remember? _ I know
I'm not alone.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Gingko biloba, an herbal supplement that is rumored to
aid memory but has never been proven to do so, now top $250 million
a year in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Health food store shelves are stocked with products with names
like ``Deep Thought'' and ``Brain Gum.'' Bookstores carry titles
like ``Why Can't I Remember? Reversing Normal Memory Loss.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, an entrepreneur is launching a chain of ``memory
centers,'' hoping to become the Fantastic Sam's of short-term
recall.
</P>
<P>
   All of which makes me feel better. When it comes to forgetting,
misery does love company.
</P>
<P>
   Like the New England professor not long ago who apologized
profusely for not calling me back at the appointed time of our
interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so sorry,'' she said, ``These days I have Swiss cheese for
brains.''
</P>
<P>
   I so liked that image (and remembered it) that I have used it
several times since, as my own excuse, or to bring some small
amount of comfort to someone similarly afflicted.
</P>
<P>
   Take my friend Jackie.
</P>
<P>
   After listening to me describe a humbling incident involving a
neighbor's garage door, Jackie delivered the official ``senior
moment'' preface:
</P>
<P>
   ``You think THAT'S bad . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Then she told of a horrific realization she had as she stood
near the copying machine in her office with a plate of food (her
lunch) in one hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just about to turn the plate over on the Xerox machine
when something in me said, `Wait! This is wrong.' I almost Xeroxed
my lunch!''
</P>
<P>
   Swiss cheese indeed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1701EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5752 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-TOBACCO-DEATH-HNS &LR;      07-18 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-DEATH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NO SMOKING GUN IN THIS ASHTRAY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LYSSA FRIEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ On Friday, a Miami jury gave its verdict in a
class-action suit against the tobacco industry, the first to go to
trial: a $145 billion judgment for the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   Representing more than 300,000 smokers, attorneys sued five
cigarette makers, claiming they ruined the lives of their sick and
addicted customers.
</P>
<P>
   If only I could cash in on the big winnings. At last I'd have
someone to blame for my father's youthful death three decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Dad's cigarettes were part of family life. He woke up, showered,
looped his tie and inhaled the day's first Alpine while gulping
coffee and reading the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   You could map Dad's movements by his trail of menthol stubs.
</P>
<P>
   A glass ashtray overflowed next to the newspaper on his
nightstand. Embers dropped from the ceramic dish, contoured with
cigarette-nesting concavities, beside the paperbacks on his reading
table. Dad filled a beanbag ashtray in the breakfast nook and
another in the bathroom. Filters tumbled from the pullout
compartment of his Mercury and spilled onto the bench seat.
</P>
<P>
   When my mother carried home sacks of groceries, gallons of milk
nestled against cartons of cigarettes. When I helped her with
housework, I followed her from room to room, emptying ashtrays and
dusting ash from tabletops.
</P>
<P>
   My father's bathroom noises _ the shower, the electric razor _
would have seemed incomplete without the clearing of his throat and
the hacking cough.
</P>
<P>
   Dad noticed those first warnings on cigarette packs and the
early stop-smoking ads in the Times. When his talk radio station
waged a quit smoking campaign, he joined. For a month or two it was
as if spring windows had been thrown open through the house,
cleansing the odor of smoke from clothing and bed linens.
</P>
<P>
   But soon he restarted. My best sixth grade friend destroyed her
father's Marlboros by stashing them in the freezer. I admired her
activism, but I knew if I threw Dad's out, he'd buy more. My father
would change when he was ready, not when I pressured him to.
Besides, other fathers had heart attacks, not mine.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, an ambulance whisked Dad to the emergency room. I
imagine now a nurse pushing against his chest, another injecting
medication into his vein, a doctor shouting orders. And I picture
my mother sobbing in the waiting room as my father waved his last
goodbye in a curling wisp.
</P>
<P>
   After he died, Mom shipped Dad's ties to Goodwill and his
paperbacks to the library. But it was when his Alpines were tossed
out, followed by his ashtrays, that I palpated his absence.
</P>
<P>
   I sat next to his reading table and rubbed my thumbnail against
the place where his ceramic ashtray once sat. All that remained was
a black streak burned permanently into the veneer. It marked the
place where, while he dozed, his cigarette had rolled carelessly
onto the oak surface.
</P>
<P>
   During adolescence I railed against the father who abandoned me,
against the mother who erased his presence by throwing his remnants
in the trash and against companies like Philip Morris and R.J.
Reynolds Tobacco Co., whom I believed to be manufacturers of
murder.
</P>
<P>
   And now that I've reached adulthood, I could organize a
Miami-like class-action lawsuit in California. I could hold the
cigarette makers responsible for blowing loss through my young
being like smoke curling from a lit tip.
</P>
<P>
   But I won't. Let the Florida plaintiffs amass their fortunes.
Adulthood has taught me that no one is untouched by death.
</P>
<P>
   Dad's death is a fact of my life. Holding a cigarette maker
accountable neither restores Dad's life nor changes the trajectory
of mine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1702EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5754 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-18 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     METAL DECTORS SET TO `STUN' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If you are of a certain age, you probably
remember your first flight on an airliner as fondly as I do.
Getting there was more than half the fun, and unlike ocean liners,
you got there quickly with no boring shuffleboard.
</P>
<P>
   To put it in terms kids might understand today, airliners were
limos in the sky, and passengers dressed accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   In that fading golden summer of 1964, I was 18 and took my first
flight from Boston to Miami, and then on to San Salvador, Guatemala
City and Tegucigalpa. The stewardesses treated my friends and me
like the young princes we thought we were. The pilots even got off
with us for an hour at the San Salvador airport and we all played
slot machines together.
</P>
<P>
   Luxury and intimacy, that's what airlines gave you then. Now we
get intimacy of the unwanted kind, and airliners are Trailways
buses with wings. We're crammed up against beefy guys in sandals
and shorts. We're forced to wait at metal detectors and in lounges
where lounging is impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Our privacy is invaded, as agents ask impertinent questions
like, ``Did you pack your bags yourself?'' and ``Have your bags
been out of your sight?''
</P>
<P>
   In the last few months I've flown cross country about 10 times,
and I have to stop myself from answering, ``I left it for a couple
of hours at militia headquarters.''
</P>
<P>
   No jokes allowed. You're in the high security world of flying,
and you should feel insecure. You'll be slammed up against the wall
and thrown in the clink for not taking terrorism seriously enough.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that airports and airlines are the ones taking people
hostage, millions a day. Forget the fact that planes get knocked
out of the skies over America not by bombs in carry-on bags, but
because of bad wiring, stripped tail stabilizer screws and ground
crews who pack oxygen canisters with old tires.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, we're treated like criminals and have to walk
repeatedly through metal detectors set between ``navel ring'' and
``surgical pin,'' while our luggage is being X-rayed by
minimum-wage employees who meet two job qualifications:
humorlessness and a supple wrist for thrusting electronic wands
into intimate places.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the city of San Francisco has required its
Cleveland-based security contractor to pay a minimum of $9 an hour
to airport security guards. Presumably this will lead to more
professional wandsmanship and more sophisticated senses of
humorlessness.
</P>
<P>
   It's amazing the stuff that does or doesn't get through the
X-ray machine. The last time I flew out of Boston back to San
Francisco, I brought a duffel bag full of antique glass and a
nautical clock. The bags went right though the X-ray machine. I
suppose terrorists use solid state these days instead of wind-up
clocks, and can't afford to use Sandwich glass as shrapnel.
</P>
<P>
   Before a flight a few months ago, a security guard opened a
drawer filled with objects taken from passengers. Among them was a
toy gun that was very obviously a toy, but confiscating it was
understandable.
</P>
<P>
   People who let their kids take toy guns onto planes should have
their kids confiscated. In fact, all kids under the age of 8 should
be confiscated before flights.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the stuff the security guards confiscate is ridiculous.
There in the drawer was a Swiss Army knife, a small one that didn't
even have the deadly assault corkscrew. As if someone would say,
``Take me to Cuba or I'll start auguring, filing and toothpicking
passengers.''
</P>
<P>
   When was the last time a plane was hijacked in this country at
all? And many planes deserve to be hijacked. ``Get me off this
taxiway and take me to my destination.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, a security guard at San Francisco spotted an object
that looked like a pistol as it went through the X-ray machine.
Actually, it dawned on the security guard a little late that the
object might have been a Glock (or a Super Squirter), and the bag
was gone by the time the alert was sounded.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in the terminal had to be evacuated, and then
readmitted, after being more carefully inspected and wanded. Like
lots of things in America, it was in the name of security. Why is
it we don't feel secure?
</P>
<P>
   The political-military-industrial complex is terrorizing us into
believing there are terrorists everywhere, even though a report
published in the Wall Street Journal showed only 58 Americans
killed by ``international terrorists'' in the last five years
compared to 400 killed between 1983 and 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Terrorists lately have tended to be homegrown, and preferred
rental trucks as delivery systems. But our leaders are still
defending against skyjackers. Now they want the military to operate
against terrorists in our cities, as well as in outer space to keep
us safe from pee-wee ``rogue states,'' recently renamed ``states of
concern.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm in a state of concern. Whenever I travel, I face long lines
at beeping machines, interminable delays in the terminal, and all
those guys with hairy legs in shorts and sandals. No amount of
officious ``security'' will stop a guy who really wants to blow up
my plane.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that will save me is that when it happens,
chances are I'll still be waiting in a stupor in the lounge,
terrorized by a Mr. and Mrs. T's Bloody Mary.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
