<SLUG> BC-FBN-NINERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NINERS DRAFTEE HAS ESPRIT DE CORPS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRUCE ADAMS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKTON, Calif. _ When John Milem was a Marine recruit, his
drill instructor at Parris Island in South Carolina would make the
young man get on his knees. Then the sergeant would stand on
Milem's footlocker. All this so the DI could look down on him.
</P>
<P>
   Milem is a 6-foot-9, 290-pound defensive end in San Francisco
49ers training camp, a tough former barroom bouncer who looks like
the typical Marine _ only bigger and stronger.
</P>
<P>
   He was a physical mismatch for his whippet-like DI, who wasn't
much more than 5-feet tall. Milem is in more natural surroundings
on the practice fields of the University of the Pacific, where he
is just one more oversized NFL rookie defensive lineman. Of course,
most rookies aren't 25 years old and coming into the league with
just two years of Division II experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a lot of looks from colleges when I came out of high
school,'' Milem said. ``I didn't feel I was ready. I was a young
kid, a wild kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Milem decided he needed discipline, so he tried the Marine
Corps. Did it work? ``Yes sir.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Marine Corps he had a job as a bouncer at a bar in
Charlotte, N.C. One night an old friend who was playing football at
tiny Division II Lenoir-Rhyne came into the bar. He suggested Milem
go out for the team.
</P>
<P>
   Big, strong and fast (he's been timed at a sub-4.7 40), Milem
started every game his freshman year, sat out his sophomore year
with a shoulder injury, then started every game again his junior
year. Then he left school for the NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers, desperate for defensive linemen, selected the
unheralded Milem in the fifth round. The line will be the subject
of a rebuilding job at camp and coaches hope to utilize Milem's
speed, quick feet and pass-rushing skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a world of potential,'' said defensive coordinator
Jim Mora.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being 25 years old could work to his advantage,'' coach Steve
Mariucci said. ``Hopefully he's not overwhelmed by this. He's
mature.''
</P>
<P>
   Many rookies come into the league with five years (including a
redshirt season) at big Division I football schools. Mora, noting
``everybody can't come from Ohio State or Michigan,'' said he is
not overly concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something he'll be able to overcome quickly because he's
smart,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Milem said while he lacks the experience of having played for a
big-time football program, he did survive ``a lot of ground
pounding'' on 25-mile marches and ``standing in the woods three
weeks at a time'' in the Marines.
</P>
<P>
   He also dismisses the age difference, saying he is as fresh as
any rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not that old in football,'' he said. ``I wasn't in
Division I five years getting pounded.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
