<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN19CX-COX- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RESENDING TO CHANGE FCC IN 2ND GRAF TO FAA
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Ads in airliners just don't fly
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a move afoot to plaster ads on the overhead luggage bins
in airliners and it's hard to imagine that carriers that have
degraded air travel into flying steerage will pass up a new
opportunity to turn a buck.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration is mulling the idea, and
Advent AirAds says only one small line, Vanguard, has committed so
far, but just you wait. If the FAA goes along, it won't be long
before the major airlines cite -- with reluctance, they will say --
competitive pressures as forcing them into the placard racket.
</P>
<P>
   The ads would complete the process of making airliners
distinguishable only by their altitude from buses.
</P>
<P>
   And would add to the process by which advertisers are contriving
to get in your face every waking moment of your life.
</P>
<P>
   Time was when communities took pride in their municipal
facilities. The auditorium, arena or theater wore either its
community's name or memorialized admired figures of its civic
adventure. Now we have stadia whose monikers are auctioned to
corporate vainglory, without any thought to local relevance, their
identities as fungible as the deracinated teams that play in them.
</P>
<P>
   Just imagine the loss to history if the Roman Coliseum had come
down to us as, instead, Mueller's Pasta Bowl. Or the Parisians had
built, not Notre Dame but Peugeot Tumbrils Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   This is actually, really true: the leading mayoral candidate in
Atlanta wants the city to can the sentimentality and let the
highest commercial bidder brand the city's airport, currently
Hartsfield International, named for the visionary mayor who made
Atlanta the hub-de-la-hub of air travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to Budweiser International Airport. Please take the
Dulcolax moving sidewalks to the Philip Morris, AOL, Fuji Film and
Pepsi concourses.''
</P>
<P>
   Public TV and radio used to offer sanctuary from incessant
commercial drumming, but their discreet credit lines for
public-spirited supporters have metamorphosed, like one of those
out-of-control bugs in a horror movie, into de facto commercials
different from the networks' only by being, as yet, a shade more
mannerly.
</P>
<P>
   In some cities, advertisers are paying private motorists to
paste ads on their cars. Expect the practice to spread.
</P>
<P>
   A Russian space rocket recently went up bearing the new logo for
Pizza Hut. (The logo was being launched. Get it?)
</P>
<P>
   Movie theaters hit you for tickets, charge you Pentagon prices
for soft drinks and popcorn and then make you sit through
commercials before you even get to the previews _ which are, of
course, more commercials.
</P>
<P>
   The conversion of airliners into advertising tubes would, I
suppose, add only a small abuse, but why stop there? Couldn't the
stewardesses, between the safety and drink-cart drills, read
commercials over the P.A.?
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: This column was brought to you by MERWIN MERKIN _ Furrier
To The Movie Stars' Pets. Remember, when one coat isn't enough for
your cat or dog, THINK MERKIN! Now, with stores in more cites than
not.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He is based in
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
