<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLO-CLUB-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POLO CLUB BOSS HOPES TO LURE MORE SPECTATORS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DENNIS YUSKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ The new owner of Saratoga Polo Club is
investing $1.5 million in improvements and charging significantly
more for memberships to raise Saratoga polo to a world-class level.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping to attract the best teams in the country, as well
as from abroad,'' said polo pioneer William Ylvisaker, former
chairman of the U.S. Polo Association.
</P>
<P>
   In return, watching and playing local tournament polo at the
greens suddenly became more expensive: Membership fees have risen
by as much as 66 percent in some cases and additional family member
passes have tripled in price this year.
</P>
<P>
   But members say the price increase will be worth it if the club
rises to Ylvisaker's standards as promised.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fee structure was an issue to some people,'' said Gene
Gass, who renewed his Players Membership for the seventh year
despite the jump in prices. Gass, who plays on one of the local
teams at the club, said tournament entry fees doubled this season
from last year.
</P>
<P>
   Since Ylvisaker purchased the club from BMHD Inc. in December,
he has hired Memo Gracida, whom he calls the best polo player in
the world, to direct the club and has negotiated a 65-acre-lease
arrangement with nearby Skidmore College that will bring the number
of playing surfaces to seven next year.
</P>
<P>
   Ylvisaker, a business magnate and the founder of Florida's Palm
Beach Polo and Country Club, hopes the additional fields and
soon-to-be-opened clubhouse that contains a 90-seat restaurant will
pay off in increased spectator interest and bring another top-notch
equestrian sport to the city.
</P>
<P>
   The new clubhouse is due to be completed by the end of this
month. It will offer food, beverages, meeting rooms and, for the
first time in the club's long history, restrooms.
</P>
<P>
   That's good news to Ronald Friske, 59, a Saratoga Springs
resident and polo fan, who has been paying the general admission
price to watch matches for the past 15 years and was one of the
only fans present at Wednesday's match _ the start of the club's
102nd season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be nice to have somewhere to go once the rains come,''
Friske said.
</P>
<P>
   Polo is played between eight players, four to a squad. Players
ride horses and try to hit a ball through a goal with mallets.
</P>
<P>
   Matches are played on a 300-by-160-yard field. The game is
divided into six periods of seven minutes each and typically lasts
up to two hours, Ylvisaker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the `20-goal level' (best players), this is one of the four
or five top places for polo at this time of the year,'' said the
club's new manager, Tony Coppola.
</P>
<P>
   Ylvisaker explains the price increases by pointing out that this
season will offer more matches with higher-quality players, and
general admission prices have not changed _ staying at the $5 per
person or $15 per carload price.
</P>
<P>
   ``In dollar amounts, yes, they are more, but there are so many
additional benefits,'' including the competitive 20-goal
tournaments in July and August that feature all-star international
players, Ylvisaker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to attract anybody. A lot of people think it's
exclusive, but it really isn't. It's very much open to the public.
People ask me, `Can I come?' I say, `Of course.' Years back, the
sport may have been known as exclusive, but that's really not the
case anymore,'' Ylvisaker said.
</P>
<P>
   The club's annual corporate membership fee, which admits six,
has increased from $600 to $1,000. Annual family membership at the
club, which admits two adults and children 16 and under and
includes six free guest passes, has increased from $290 to $380
(with additional family member passes jumping from $50 to $180),
and single membership fees increased by $45 to $260.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
