<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5777 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-FASHION-TARGET-ART-BO     07-18 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-TARGET-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 A MOVING TARGET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos are being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ That there were men in chic white suits wearing Gucci
flip-flops and pink-lensed sunglasses in the audience at a fashion
show was not surprising. But this fall collection, on display at
the Chelsea Piers last week, belonged to Target, the
Minneapolis-based department store with a reputation for selling
all things middle America, from outdoor grills to boxer shorts.
</P>
<P>
   So the relative hipness of the event was all the more
remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   The 38-year-old retailer, with a superstore in every major
American city except New York, is conducting a major Northeast
expansion spree. At the same time, the company has launched a campy
branding campaign, using lighthearted '60s music and a
red-and-white bull's-eye logo designed to lure a new spectrum of
buyers to its huge stores.
</P>
<P>
   John Remington, the company's vice president for special events,
opened this show by declaring that the retailer is ``on a mission
to democratize fashion'' by making clothing designers and trends
accessible and affordable.
</P>
<P>
   While Target has succeeded in winning over fans for its home
furnishings from such designers as Starck and Michael Graves _ both
of whom are new to the store, with Stark poised to roll out a full
line next year _ its fashion offerings have had less impact.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what the Chelsea show was all about: Creating a buzz,
encouraging fashionistas _ some of whom cheekily call the store
Tar-ZHAY _ to appreciate the store's clothing in a more glamorous
light, and showcasing the company's self-effacing approach and
quirky marketing linking household commodities to clothing. To wit:
one model wore pants covered with the Ziploc baggie logo. Target
sells the Ziplocs, not the pants, which drew the loudest applause
of the 10-minute show.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we try to do is include models who are kind of like our
guests. Some are older. Some are younger,'' said Target spokeswoman
Carolyn Brookter. ``This year, even as we look at our fashion, it
runs the gamut from New Age western to luxury, with leather. And
then there's the woman who's on the go: travel fashion. That tends
sometimes to be an older'' market.
</P>
<P>
   A blondish-gray-haired female model just past middle age also
got some clapping for standing out as an unusual specimen amid her
lithe colleagues as she strode out in a khaki skirt and vest, cut
just the right way so as not to be frumpy. But pausing before a
relatively small bank of photographers, the younger models who
circled the oversized bull's-eye-shaped stage seemed almost
embarrassed to be there.
</P>
<P>
   The only color in the room came from the clothes and those
red-and-white concentric circles in the center of the floor.
Everything else in the cavernous showroom was black: the walls, the
ceiling, and the folding chairs for 600.
</P>
<P>
   The show's first round consisted of black and gray nylon pants
and vests boasting an urban/high-tech feel, with lots of pockets,
which were paired with clingy ribbed turtleneck and zip-front
sweaters. A pale blue scarf of stuffed nylon drew murmurs from the
appreciative crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The next grouping featured a hippie theme, with tie-dye shirts,
knit hats, and knee-length rayon print skirts. In the midst of the
parade came the unexpected _ a skirt with an all-over Meow Mix logo
and a matching kerchief on the model's head. The skirt and scarf
were made just for the show, with a wink to fall's emphasis on
animal prints and to Target's pet department.
</P>
<P>
   A sharp-jawed male model looked slick in his black flat-front
pants and silky T-shirt, which sported an all-over print of Mr.
Clean's face; household supplies, you see, are another selling
point for the store.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the Western motif: denim cropped jeans and
skirts, chambray jackets, cowboy hats, and suede bags with fringe,
as well as animal-print accessories and snake skin-style pants.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, the crowd applauded, then bolted for the exits
in a mad dash to secure cabs. In the crush, one man said in a stage
whisper to a friend, ``There was some interesting stuff. But
nothing I'd buy myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the show ended abruptly, the buildup began two hours
earlier with a themed cocktail party just outside the event room.
</P>
<P>
   Waiters dressed in white shirts, black pants, and aprons covered
in the Meow Mix, Cheer, and Puffs logos, as they collected party
detritus on silver platters and doled out delicacies on sleek black
servers. The floral arrangements contained white ``flowers'' made
of tissue (Puffs, to be exact).
</P>
<P>
   The crowd, meanwhile, was reading the fine print on a Pop-art
installation billed as Warhol-esque. In one instance, instead of
using tomato soup cans, an artist assembled boxes of dry cat food
(yes, Meow Mix) to create a ``cat space mobile.''
</P>
<P>
   Large, target-shaped cushions were strewn here and there in the
room so the weary could rest their stiletto-pained feet. Outside,
on the deck overlooking the East River, sat a Jolly Rancher-shaped
cushion, wrapped in plastic just like the hard candies sold at the
store. Tie-in: the Western-inspired denim clothing and cowboy hats.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the red-haired woman whose accessories included a
pet Pomeranian and a Louis Vuitton bag. She _ and her dog _ mingled
over cocktails. But both actually stayed to see the fashions, as
did Sasha Charnin Morrison, fashion market director at Allure
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that each category was pretty strong,'' Morrison
said of the clothes. ``I think it's stuff that you want.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
