<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-JENNINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JENNINGS ONE OF A KIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ It doesn't help that Gabe Jennings shares a
Jan. 25 birthday with Steve Prefontaine, who was America's greatest
distance runner when he died in a car crash in 1975 at the age of
24. But even without that eerie coincidence the comparisons still
would be made: the shaggy hair, the nonconformity, the guts with
which he runs, the potential for greatness.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't get carried away, warns Vin Lananna, his coach at
Stanford, who is beginning to find the topic a bit tiresome. ``Gabe
Jennings is Gabe Jennings,'' he said this week, ``and I'm not sure
there are others like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennings, who just six weeks ago claimed the outdoor NCAA 1,500
meter crown as a junior, Sunday became the first collegiate runner
since Jim Ryun in 1968 to win at 1,500 meters in the US Olympic
Trials when he ran it in 3 minutes 35.90 seconds, the fastest time
by an American this year.
</P>
<P>
   As he ran, dozens of friends and family members in the bleachers
coming off the backstretch provided the external accompaniment,
pounding drums meant to activate the internal beat Jennings, a
music major and drum player at Stanford, must feel to perform his
best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our heart's always pumping and our lungs are always heaving,''
said Jennings in an explanation typical of his unconventionality.
``It's when you're aware of it that the magic can happen. When I'm
not in that zone, I have a bad race; usually I don't hear rhythms
and if I do they're not in synch or the melodies I hear are
dissonant.''
</P>
<P>
   Known to climb into the stands at Stanford after finishing his
race to drum for the rest of the runners, Jennings has been heeding
his own beat since childhood, spent in a remote California town
called Forks of Salmon. There, his family used a battery to
generate electricity when they needed it, used firewood for heat,
ate straight out of their garden, and maintained their own water
line. ``It was definitely a rugged lifestyle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But still not as primitive as the mythmakers would have it. ``We
actually did have plumbing,'' said Jennings, despite plentiful
reports to the contrary. ``I think it's funny. People razz me about
it, raised by the coyotes.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was 13, he moved with his parents and sister to Madison,
Wis., so his father, Jim, could study ancient philosophy at the
University of Wisconsin. It was at Madison East High School that
Jennings discovered running, winning nine state titles, before
moving on to Stanford, where his teammates include Jonathon Riley
of Brookline, Mass., Andy Powell of North Easton, Mass., and
Michael Stember, who finished second to Jennings at the NCAAs and
third here.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one really knows what sort of plane Gabe exists on except
that it works for him,'' said Stember. ``We all do our best to turn
it into positive energy for the team. Sometimes that's a bit
difficult, but because he is entertaining to everybody it often
gets turned into a really fun show to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Lananna, for whom Jennings this spring helped win Stanford's
first NCAA championship in 66 years, said he sees his role as
providing perspective. ``I try to make sure (race) decisions are
made with his head, and not just gut or emotion,'' he explained,
while not trying to curb Jennings's instincts to run from heart,
often making the kind of early move he did here just 600 meters
into the race. ``With Gabe, his strength is his passion and the
excitement in everything he does.''
</P>
<P>
   The young man in the smock-like shirt and soft clogs who fed off
cosmic energy as ``the moon kept getting fuller and the air kept
getting fresher'' with the biggest race of his life approaching;
who said he knew he would win when he awoke from his afternoon
visualization session to notice that his foot was tapping,
nonetheless refuses to classify himself as a free spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to overthink my image or my lifestyle and just act
it, or be it,'' he said. ``My motto is to really live in the
moment.''
</P>
<P>
   That moment will soon be on the Olympic stage. There is no fear
in Jennings's deep brown eyes when he says: ``I'm just 21 years old
now, but I'm ready to start racing the big guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken, just once, like a typical runner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
