<SLUG> BC-TV-TOUR-URINALS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABC'S LATEST PEE-R CAMPAIGN A NEW LOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Is there honor among TV critics? Not in the
men's room.
</P>
<P>
   Several promotional posters placed above urinals in a
Ritz-Carlton hotel restroom in Pasadena went missing Monday soon
after they were installed to tie in with a news conference on ABC's
fall marketing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The high-tech ``billboards'' use CD-ROMs to communicate with men
as they answer nature's call. The voice of comedian Norm Macdonald,
star of the ABC series ``Norm,'' offers a number of observations,
such as, ``Oh, my God! Look at the size of that thing!'' and
``You're a mover and shaker and so am I. `Norm' moves to Fridays
this fall.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, quickly dubbed ``must-pee TV'' by critical
consensus, will initially target men's rooms in New York and Los
Angeles, but other markets may follow.
</P>
<P>
   Defending the ads, Mike Benson, senior vice president of
advertising and promotion for ABC, said, ``It's not that we'll go
anywhere, but we feel that they are appropriate, effective pieces
in our own voice and style that fit our attitude, and we figured
that this was the perfect place to advertise `Norm.'''
</P>
<P>
   No one copped to removing the signs, but maybe we should be
grateful for the pre-emptive strike.
</P>
<P>
   Forget all the ``Survivor'' and ``Big Brother'' clones the
networks are rushing into production to catch the ``reality'' wave.
The next big thing could very well be ``BattleBots'' on Comedy
Central.
</P>
<P>
   Picture ``WWF Smackdown!'' minus the sweaty guys and the folding
chairs. Toss in some futuristic-looking appliances with heavy
armament, and you've got ``BattleBots.''
</P>
<P>
   The cool thing about it is that it's not contrived reality.
There really are people who travel the robot-competition circuit,
trying to prove their homemade automatons _ some resembling
lawnmowers, others favoring the vacuum-cleaner-on-steroids look,
still others tending toward the mad scientist's gizmo with claws _
are superior in a world-domination, annihilate-the-other-guy sort
of way.
</P>
<P>
   Tentatively scheduled to debut in late August, the series' first
episodes will feature bouts taped last month in San Francisco.
Jason and Randy Sklar, twin brothers with a mind for comedy (MTV's
``Apartment 2F''), will host the show with ``Baywatch'' alumna
Donna D'Errico. Seattle's own Bill Nye (the science guy) will serve
as technical expert, offering insight during weigh-ins and
providing vital statistics on each competitor.
</P>
<P>
   The Sklars, who like to finish each other's sentences, point out
that there is nothing fake about robot rasslin'.
</P>
<P>
   Here's Randy: ``We can say without hyperbole ... ''
</P>
<P>
   And now Jason: `` ... that there is no greater drama in all of
sport.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1727EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5788 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0719-C     07-18 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0719-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TIRED, TENSE MIDEAST NEGOTIATORS, CLINTON TALKING AROUND THE
CLOCK
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ President Clinton pressed Mideast negotiators
Tuesday in around-the-clock deadline diplomacy at nearby Camp
David, aiming to secure a peace treaty before his long-scheduled
departure for Japan on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak until nearly
4:30 a.m. (ET) Tuesday, as U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and National Security Adviser Samuel Berger held forth
into the pre-dawn hours with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   After a few hours of sleep, the negotiators were back at it for
talks expected to continue late into the night Tuesday, and White
House spokesman Joe Lockhart said aides were set to stage a signing
ceremony ``on a moment's notice,'' if an agreement were reached.
</P>
<P>
   As a week of talks drifted through their last scheduled day,
however, the outcome of negotiations remained in doubt, as Clinton
weighed whether to delay his take-off another day to buy more time
for a shot at peace in one of the most contentious regions in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The late nights and looming deadline were taking a toll on
negotiators, Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People understand that there is not an open-ended or unlimited
amount of time,'' he told reporters at a daily news briefing.
``They're tired, but they're staying at it.''
</P>
<P>
   In one sign that Clinton might put off his departure, the White
House delayed until Wednesday the press flight for reporters
covering Clinton's trip to Japan. The press charter had been
scheduled to leave the Washington area Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is due in Tokyo Thursday afternoon for a bilateral
meeting with Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials won't say the meeting is non-essential,
but it's no secret that the agenda is light.
</P>
<P>
   Logistically, Clinton could postpone the meeting with Mori,
leave Washington Thursday morning and still arrive in Okinawa _ the
southernmost island in the Japanese archipelago _ in time for the
main event of his trip: the annual summit of the leaders of the
so-called Group of Seven richest nations, plus Russia.
</P>
<P>
   That could get him 24 hours of overtime to try to wrestle a
peace treaty out of the Camp David talks.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations are centered on the core issues in the
52-year-old Palestinian-Israeli dispute. Those include the question
of Palestinian statehood, the future of Jerusalem, territory and
security, and the fate of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of a strict news blackout agreed to by all
negotiating parties before the talks began, Lockhart, or his
deputies, have provided the sole official window into the talks for
roughly 300 members of the international media gathered in this
town of 4,400 to cover the summit.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart has refused to discuss the substance of the talks and
has provided little information about the atmospherics or the
negotiating process itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can assume that I know lots of stuff,'' he told reporters
Tuesday, ``and I'm not telling you.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Washington-based Arab American Institute released
the results of a nationwide poll Tuesday that showed a majority of
American voters support the Palestinians' right to an independent
state.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 890 likely voters, conducted by New York-based
Zogby International July 14-17, showed 66 percent favored a
Palestinian state as well as 63 percent agreeing with Clinton's
handling of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   The poll had a margin of error of +/-3.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   (Cox Newspapers Washington correspondent Lisa Michals
contributed to this report. Her E-mail address is:
lmichals(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
