<HEADLINE>
SNEAD TAKES A VERY SWEET SWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ There was some milling around at the
first tee when the older gentleman in the sweatshirt sort of took
matters into his own hands and put the peg in the ground.
</P>
<P>
   With a swing that has lost none of its rhythm over the course of
seven decades, he rifled a perfect drive into the bright blue
Scottish sky, though he didn't bother to follow its flight. Truth
is, he couldn't have seen it had he tried. Further truth is, he
knew exactly where it would be, anyway: dead center, because the
swing is still true even if the eyes aren't.
</P>
<P>
   So Sam Snead, 88 and as colorful as ever, simply settled into
the passenger side of a golf cart and, with very little fanfare,
accepted a ride out to prepare for his next shot.
</P>
<P>
   Kids looking for autographs were more concerned with Tiger Woods
sightings, and some of today's professionals were too deep in their
preparation routine as they came down the 18th to pay attention to
the man in the trademark straw hat, but none of that fazed Slammin'
Sammy, who has returned to St. Andrews _ site of this year's
British Open, which begins Thursday _ to pay his respects one last
time to the birthplace of golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy being here and I will always cherish this course for
the rest of my life,'' said Snead, who accepted an invitation to
help usher this course _ and this tournament _ into a new century.
He will take part in a special Past Champions Challenge Wednesday,
with 22 former British Open champions playing a four-hole
exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   It is a perfect fit, because beyond the fact that Snead is the
oldest living former champion, his only participation in this
tournament resulted in victory, right here at St. Andrews in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Snead being Snead, his first impression of the
historic layout prompted a most infamous exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came along beside the golf course and it did not look like
it was in very good shape,'' said Snead, recounting a story that
has been altered and embellished throughout the years, though it
has not lost any of its charm. ``I heard that they used sheep to
cut (the grass), so I finally said to a guy sitting beside me,
`What abandoned golf course is that?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Showing off a pretty good Scottish brogue, Snead laughed
heartily when he remembered the man's outrage: ``I will have you
know it is St. Andrews.''
</P>
<P>
   But Snead discounts the legend that he had disdain for the Old
Course.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a whole lot of shot-making to do a good score,'' he
said of his 290 total that was four shots clear of Bobby Locke and
Johnny Bulla. ``But it is a course where every time you play it you
respect it more.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Ben Hogan (who triumphed at Carnoustie in 1953), Snead was
1 for 1 in the British Open, but typical of that era, it was not a
great windfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cost me $2,000 to come over here in '46,'' said Snead. ``I
won the tournament and got $600. They said, `You coming back to
defend?' And I said, `You're kidding.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Many years later, after he won the British Seniors Championship,
Snead received a check for $460. ``Is this my tipping money?'' he
asked. Told that it was indeed his prize money, Snead laughed. ``I
said, `Don't call me, I'll call you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Many years later, and for an enitrely different reason, they did
call and Snead did say yes. Monday, he played two holes going out
(Nos. 1-2) and two coming in (Nos. 17-18), which is what
Wednesday's competition will be. The sweetest swinger the game ever
has known is many years removed from trying to kid himself into
believing he can still play, but he made the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``With my sight, I can't see a ball land 50 yards, so you know I
have no business even hitting the golf ball,'' said Snead.
</P>
<P>
   He just wants to enjoy this moment, show off the golden swing
that even today makes the pros stop and take note, and leave on
good terms with St. Andrews.
</P>
</TEXT>
