<HEADLINE>
IT'S ANNE VS. EMILY ON PEI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Look out, Anne of Green Gables: There's a new girl in town, and
her name is Emily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emily,'' a musical about a troubled Prince Edward Island girl,
is drawing crowds at the Confederation Centre of the Arts in the
island capital of Charlottetown. And ``Emily of New Moon'' is an
award-winning television series that can now be seen in the United
States on some cable/satellite channels such as Movieplex.
</P>
<P>
   Both the musical and TV show are based upon a trio of novels by
Lucy Maud Montgomery, who also wrote ``Anne of Green Gables,'' a
book that will forever be associated with the late author's beloved
Prince Edward Island. For years, souvenirs of red-haired, pigtailed
Anne have saturated the island, and the Green Gables homestead is
something of a shrine. But nowadays mementos of dark-haired Emily
have wended their way into PEI souvenir shops _ even the one at
Green Gables. When the TV series began filming on the island, it
was a major topic of conversation. A cartoon in a local newspaper
went so far as to depict Anne on a psychiatrist's couch, lamenting,
``It's Emily this and Emily that!'' This summer, the ``Emily''
musical will play for its second year at the Confederation Centre,
and the acclaimed ``Anne of Green Gables'' will enter its 36th
season, making it Canada's longest-running musical.
</P>
<P>
   While both the Anne and the Emily stories concern an orphaned
girl growing up on the island in the early years of the 20th
century, the tales are hardly the same. For one thing, the first
Emily book was written about 15 years after ``Anne of Green
Gables,'' is more autobiographical, and reflects Montgomery's
increasing maturity. If ``Anne'' is a story told in pastels,
``Emily'' is related in richer, occasionally darker hues, making
for more compelling drama. While the Anne musical bubbles brightly
from the start, Emily's begins with the death of her father and her
upbringing by a stern, outwardly cold aunt. All is not gloom,
though: There is a lot of hope and humor _ and good songs, too.
</P>
<P>
   But if musicals about the plight of young island girls don't
call out to you, fret not: All summer long, Prince Edward Island is
a festival of plays, concerts, dinner theater, jazz, blues, art and
museum exhibits, and Highland and Celtic music and gatherings.
Under the auspices of the Confederation Centre alone are such
productions as the laugh-a-lot musical ``Forever Plaid''; the
ultra-energetic ``Barachois,'' with Acadian music, dancing, and
comedy; ``the Conjuror's Suite,'' a re-creation of an old-time
magic show; ``Celidh on the Road,'' featuring Celtic music, song,
and dance; ``Somewhere in the World,'' a rousing _ and free _
outdoor musical salute to Canada; and ``Drill Queens Comedy,''
featuring sketches, impersonations, and satirical melodies. Why,
one sketch even has a slightly tipsy Anne confronting Emily: ``For
36 seasons, I've owned this town. . . . And now, when I look in the
rear-view mirror, who do I see? You!''
</P>
<P>
   (For more information or a booklet about Confederation Centre
productions, as well as the center's extensive art gallery, call
800-565-0278, visit www.confederationcentre.com, or e-mail
shastelo(at)confederationcentre.com. For information about a lot of
other entertainment and everything else about the island whose
beauty L.M. Montgomery described so lovingly, call 888-PEI-PLAY or
visit www.peiplay.com.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Prince Edward Island is shaped like (a) a dagger,
(b) a crescent, (c) a figure-eight, or (d) a pair of pigtails?
(Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: PEI may be the island of Anne of Green Gables, but
there's a restaurant/bike-rental shop in the town of St. Peters
called Anne of Red Doors. The building is a former fire station _
thus the red doors _ and the proprietor is named Anne. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``The fairest land 'tis possible to see'' _ explorer
Jacques Cartier, after his first view of the reds and greens of
Prince Edward Island from his ship in 1534. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Snappy slogan: A message on a Prince Edward Island T-shirt reads,
``Boil a Tourist, Save a Lobster.'' (Lobster suppers are one of the
island's big draws.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sound familiar? On PEI, you can find communities named Alaska,
Arlington, Albany, New Haven, Cambridge, Newton, and Springfield. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The flavor is locked in: An early 20th-century county jail in
Longworth, Prince Edward Island, is now a pizza palace. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? A crescent. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHOOPS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The answer to last week's Travel Trivia question was woefully
incomplete. In addition to Rhode Island having a one-word state
motto (Hope), as we mentioned, these states also have one-word
mottoes: California (Eureka), Maine (``Dirigo,'' meaning ``I
lead''), New York (Excelsior), Texas (Friendship), Utah (Industry),
Washington (``Al-ki,'' an Indian word meaning ``by and by''), and
Wisconsin (Forward). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We thank Massachusetts readers Rick Brown of Manomet, Ozan Gurel
of Cambridge, Michael Wood of Arlington, Richard Bass of Rockport,
Adele Purvis of Bedford and Ken Polay of Mendon; Faithful Reader of
Cyberspace; John Di Pietro of Pownal, Maine; Richard McCarthy of
Windham, N.H.; John Borsden of the Charlotte Observer; and
anonymous letter writers. &QL; 
 &QL; 
