<HEADLINE>
YOUR TALL SHIPS DREAMS CAN COME TRUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the hundreds of thousands of people who toured the Tall
Ships as they visited the East Coast (continuing on to Maine, and
then Halifax, Nova Scotia, before crossing the Atlantic), interest
in the vessels is high. For many, the event has sparked a dream to
sail aboard one.
</P>
<P>
   That dream can be a reality. A sailing vacation is an option
many are taking.
</P>
<P>
   Along the Maine coast there are windjammers galore, some listed
as national treasures. In the Caribbean, Windjammer Barefoot
Cruises has a fleet that sails regularly to interesting and
off-the-beaten-path islands.
</P>
<P>
   Star Clipper offers the Royal Clipper, the world's largest true
sailing ship. Windstar Cruises has three computer-operated sailing
vessels that sail the world. Even Club Med has a sailing outpost.
</P>
<P>
   Heading to Maine for a one- to four-day sail among the beautiful
islands of Penobscot Bay will give you a feel for what it's like.
North End Shipyard Schooners offers two vessels, the American Eagle
and Schooner Heritage. Windjammer Cruises has a fleet of 13 vessels
that sail from Rockland and Camden, Maine. These are all genuine
sailing vessels, cruising primarily in the Penobscot Bay area,
which is filled with islands. The American Eagle has auxiliary
power and is able to cruise farther to take part in the Gloucester
Schooner Race in September. Most of the sailings are for three or
four days, with a few up to seven days.
</P>
<P>
   For information, call Windjammer at 800-807-WIND or visit
www.sailmainecoast.com; for the North End fleet, call 800-648-4544
or visit www.midcoast.com/-schooner.
</P>
<P>
   Windjammer Barefoot is as casual as you'd expect from a company
that uses ``barefoot'' in its name. There are no crowds (just
64-124 passengers), no regimen, but there are land-based
eco-adventures. Its sailings are all six days in beautiful
Caribbean waters. For information, call 800-327-2601.
</P>
<P>
   For a real sailing adventure that touches on ports in Europe,
the Mediterranean, Southeast Asia, and the Caribbean, Star Clippers
(800-442-0551) can't be beat. The company's Star Clipper and Star
Flyer are based on the great clipper ships that once were built in
Boston. The new Royal Clipper is inspired by the Preussen of the
Flying P Lines, which from 1902-1910 dominated the sea lanes of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Windstar Cruises (800-258-7245) offers sailngs in the Caribbean,
Europe, Belize, and Costa Rica. The vessels offer a luxurious
computer-operated sailing experience. Club Med 2 (800-CLUB MED)
brings the fun of a Club Med village to sea, also on a vessel with
computer-equipped sails. It home ports in winter in Martinique.
</P>
<P>
   One of the newest sailing adventures is aboard the luxurious
three-masted Barquentine, the Lili Marleen. This genuine sailing
vessel carries just 50 passengers in modern comfort (it was built
in 1994). The Lili Marleen sails year round on seven-night cruises
from Dubai. For information, call Peter Deilmann Ocean Cruises at
800-348-8287.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Foliage cruise
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Regal Cruises will offer a 12-night foliage cruise from New York
on Sept. 17, calling on New England and Canadian ports. The
900-passenger Regal Empress will visit Newport, R.I.; Bar Harbor,
Maine; Quebec City, Quebec; Halifax, Nova Scotia; Charlottetown,
Prince Edward Island; and Corner Brook, Newfoundland. For
information, call 800-270-7245.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Free activities
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Royal Caribbean is now offering rock climbing, miniature golf,
and ice skating free on its Voyager of the Seas, the world's
largest cruise ship. There was a charge for those activities when
the ship first began sailing.
</P>
<P>
   The free policy will be extended to the Explorer of the Seas,
sister ship to the Voyager, when it begins sailing on Oct. 28.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grand Voyages
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From Hong Kong and Vietnam to Fiji and Samoa and from the
islands of New Zealand to the Hawaiian Islands, the all-suite Seven
Seas Navigator will offer grand voyages during its inaugural
season. By combining two or more shorter cruises to create a Grand
Voyage of 21 to 58 nights, Radisson Seven Seas Cruises will offer
guests special combination fares, free upgrades to business or
first-class air, or extra savings from Oct. 3-Dec. 2. In addition,
those who secure their deposit with a credit card when booking
receive a shipboard credit of $1,000 per cabin ($500 a person). The
490-passenger Navigator will offer six cruises ranging from nine to
20 nights that can be built into a Grand Voyage.
</P>
<P>
   For information, call Radisson Seven Seas Cruises at
800-477-7500.
</P>
</TEXT>
