<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5794 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-18 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CONGRESS-WHITE HOUSE GAMESMANSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress and the White House maneuver like dancing
crabs these days, scuttling sideways instead of marching forward in
a direct manner.
</P>
<P>
   In this pre-convention season, the idea is to get us to listen
to what they say, not watch what they do. The emphasis is on
building issues, not a record of real achievement.
</P>
<P>
   This inevitably leads to devious public behavior. Take the
recent passage of a measure to eliminate the estate tax.
</P>
<P>
   With great fanfare, the Republicans rammed through the measure
even though they knew President Clinton had vowed to veto it. They
didn't even consider a compromise put forward by the Democrats that
would have greatly reduced the tax, wiping out the most
controversial aspects but falling short of giving the ultra-rich a
free pass altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans were going for a confrontation rather than
legislative results. They may temporarily end up with nothing,
hoping for a Bush presidency and a veto-free second go-around on
the issue next year.
</P>
<P>
   The game is being played with AmeriCorps as well. This is
Clinton's pet project, an initiative he sees as his domestic
version of President John Kennedy's famous Peace Corps. The
Republicans have been out to get it from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   The House just voted to defund (translation: kill) it. The
Senate, which is slightly more friendly terrain, may or may not
rescue it.
</P>
<P>
   But in any case the president has promised to veto the vast,
$83.8 billion Veterans Administration-Housing and Urban Development
appropriations bill, in which the small AmeriCorps budget is
buried, if the agency does not get additional funding. You can bet
the House-Senate conference will quietly give him some of what he
wants here.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has asked for $534 million for AmeriCorps, up from its
present $353 million budget. Think about it. We are talking here
about a mere drop in the federal budget ocean. And the Republicans
are trying to make it an example of wild-eyed Democratic spending!
</P>
<P>
   The House also gave similar, longer-established programs funded
through the Labor-Health and Human Services appropriations bill the
cold shoulder. It approved the same level of funds as last year,
but no increase. The programs are the former ACTION agency, now
called Senior Service Corps, and the former VISTA, now called
AmeriCorps-VISTA.
</P>
<P>
   There too a veto threat suggests that _ surprise! _ more funding
will show up in the bill's final version.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have no real reason to dump on AmeriCorps except
to get Clinton's goat. The flimsy excuse is that the money can be
better used for tax cuts and lowering the national debt. But a
better move would be to slash really big-ticket items favored by
the GOP, such as unnecessary aircraft carriers and missile defense
systems that don't work.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans love to wield the budget-cutting knife only when the
programs are important to the administration and not to their own
constituents.
</P>
<P>
   AmeriCorps is vulnerable because it is relatively small, new and
not very visible. It has not gripped the public imagination as the
Peace Corps did in the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton envisioned the program as extending our tradition of
citizen service to young people by encouraging them to volunteer to
help their fellow Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last six years, AmeriCorps members have taught, tutored
and mentored needy and non-English speaking pupils; run
after-school recreational programs and removed trash from
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Members, usually between 18 and 24, receive a living allowance
and, after a year of service, a lump sum of nearly $5,000 to help
pay for higher education or vocational training. Many of the local
programs are run by church coalitions and other religious agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, once called AmeriCorps a ``Great
Society-style boondoggle.'' But when he saw it in action in his
home state, he began to support it.
</P>
<P>
   So what's not to like in AmeriCorps? It isn't expensive. Insofar
as is known, it is scandal-free. It does good works, and it helps
to send kids to college.
</P>
<P>
   What's not to like, from the GOP point of view, is that it is
something nice dreamed up by that ogre Bill Clinton. That means it
has to be stamped out before voters get the incredible notion that
Clinton isn't all bad after all.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
