<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5799 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-TOUR19-COX     07-18 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Armstrong miscalculates, runs out of energy on final mountain
stage
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORZINE, France - Defending champion Lance Armstrong felt so
energetic early in the Tour de France's16th stage Tuesday that he
blew past the area where team workers were handing out
carbohydrate-loaded energy drinks and sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   He shouldn't have.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong was within sight of a stage win when his strength
evaporated on the 5,500-foot Col de Joux-Plane, the last imposing
summit on the tour, and he was left behind by Germany's Jan Ullrich
and eventual winner Richard Virenque.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong finished eighth, 2 minutes and 1 second behind
Virenque. But Armstrong lost valuable time to Ullrich, who moved to
within 5:37 of the defending champion in the overall standings with
five stages remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was the hardest day of my life on a bike. I knew I was
in trouble,'' Armstrong said. ``I just tried to stay calm and be
conservative. In a situation and crisis like that, you can't panic.
I'm happy to be finished with the Alps.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Postal Service team director Johan Bruyneel said Armstrong
could have lost more time to Ullrich, but yielded only 1:51.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we lost to Ullrich was really a good outcome under the
circumstances,'' Bruyneel said. ``Lance had a hunger crisis. It
comes all of a sudden. When it happens, you have to relax and try
as hard as possible. It's just a thing that happens. He'll be OK.
He's perfect. He just ran out of fuel.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruyneel said Armstrong ate well Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his problems, Armstrong does not appear to be in danger
of losing the leader's yellow jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was probably the final day that riders could make up
huge gaps in time, although the Tour does not end until Sunday in
Paris. Ullrich finished second Tuesday, 24 seconds behind Virenque.
</P>
<P>
   Of the final five stages, four are better suited for sprinters.
The fifth, a time trial in Fribourg, Germany, on Friday, fits the
styles of Armstrong and Ullrich. Armstrong, who assumed the
leader's yellow jersey after the 10th stage, won all three time
trials during his 1999 Tour championship.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, other riders knew that Tuesday was the final day to
make up significant chunks of time on the leader.
</P>
<P>
   Marco Pantani, who has drawn the ire of Armstrong for his
comments to the European press, attacked from the beginning of the
stage.
</P>
<P>
   Pantani, winner of two mountain stages, took a huge gamble,
hoping that he could maintain a torrid pace through the Alps and
narrow the gap between himself and Armstrong. He started the day in
seventh place overall, 9:03 behind Armstrong and finished the
afternoon in 14th, 20:46 behind.
</P>
<P>
   Pantani's energy evaporated at the midway point of the 129-mile
stage, and he lost touch with the main riders. He finished 38th on
the same mountain he dominated in his 1998 Tour victory.
</P>
<P>
   Virenque, the second Frenchman to claim a Tour stage this year,
said Pantani's hefty pace came much too soon. ``No one could keep
up that pace,'' Virenque said. ``He attacked too far from the
end.''
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Suzanne Halliburton at
shalliburton(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
