<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELL-PHONES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CELL PHONES TO CARRY RADIATION LABELS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an effort to reassure cell phone users, the cell
phone industry announced Tuesday that new cell phones will carry
labels describing how much microwave radiation they emit.
</P>
<P>
   Jo-Anne Basile, vice president for the Cellular
Telecommunications Industry Association _ the main cell phone trade
group _ said consumers will start to see the radiation labels on
new phones in the next six months.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's announcement comes amid growing health concerns
that cellular phones might be linked to diseases because a phone's
antenna emits microwave radiation and is typically held close to
the user's head.
</P>
<P>
   Over 95 million Americans use cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   The cellular phone industry steadfastly maintains that the
devices are safe and that the amount of radiation absorbed into a
user's head is far below dangerous levels.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission has set a maximum level of
radiation of 1.6 watts per kilogram of body tissue. CTIA says cell
phones don't exceed that limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of science shows that there are no adverse
health effects from the use of wireless phones,'' Basile said.
Still, the industry decided to publicize the radiation levels
because ``it's clear that there is increased interest in this
information,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientific studies have questioned the safety of the
devices. For example, two industry-sponsored health studies have
warned of possible damage to humans from cell phone radiation.
</P>
<P>
   This past May, a British government commission concluded that
children should be dissuaded from using cell phones until science
can conclusively determine whether absorbing radiation into the
head is safe.
</P>
<P>
   The British panel said there is no evidence that cell phones
cause harm but that it could not rule out the possibility that
future research might discover a link between disease and cell
phone use.
</P>
<P>
   The British report recommended that cell phone makers disclose
the radiation levels.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the industry action, a label on the outside packaging
of each new phone will state that this particular phone has been
tested by the manufacturer and meets government safety guidelines.
Inside the package, manufacturers will provide the specific
radiation measurement for the model and explain how the phones were
tested, Basile said.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's announcement was criticized by Dr. George Carlo,
a Washington, D.C.-based epidemiologist and lawyer who headed an
industry-sponsored cell phone safety project from 1993 until last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Carlo said the information being released by the manufacturers
would do little to help consumers determine if the phones are safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The information is industry-generated data, it's not objective
in any way and can't be relied upon,'' Carlo said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, said Carlo, the radiation information does not
allow a consumer to make a judgment about whether one 10-minute
call is better or worse than 10 one-minute calls, he said. ``It
does not tell you what the cumulative effect of cell phone use
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlo added that releasing radiation information protects the
industry more than it protects consumers. ``I believe it's an
inoculation against future liability,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration, which is responsible for
regulating cell phones, has begun questioning whether the federal
safety limit fully protects consumers. The ceiling is focused on
protecting a user from phones that actually destroy cells by
heating them, the ``thermal'' effect. This limit may not protect
against ``any non-thermal effects of chronic exposure,'' the agency
said.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to settle the safety question, the FDA announced
last month that it would collaborate with the CTIA on new studies
to be conducted over the next several years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be contacted at 202-298-6920 or via e-mail:
eric(at)hearstdc.com
</P>
