<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5817 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OLY-WOMEN-DISCUS-HNS &LR;      07-18 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WOMEN-DISCUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DISCUS: THE ELEGANT SPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ There is an elegance to the women's discus
throw that often gets lost in the swirl of activity in most track
meets.
</P>
<P>
   Swirling was at a minimum Monday night on a quiet fourth day of
the U.S. Olympic Track &AMP; Field Trials. That, in turn, afforded a
good view of the women's discus competition.
</P>
<P>
   It was an excellent competition, too, won by UCLA's Seilala Sua
on her first attempt with a near American record throw of 216 feet,
2 inches. As it was, it was the longest throw by an American in 14
years, since Carol Cady of Stanford established the record of
216-10 in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Modesto native and UCLA grad Suzy Powell had a more consistent
series than Sua and uncorked an effort of 211-10 on her last throw
to finish second and land a spot on her second Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   In third was Kris Kuehl of Windom, Minn., who threw 202-7 to
make her first Olympic team at 29.
</P>
<P>
   With two women over 210 feet and another over 200, it's a good
group the United States will send to Sydney in September. All three
are good technicians in the ring as they spin around the 8-foot
circle and release the disc with a smooth slinging motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a good crew here,'' said Kuehl, whose name is
pronounced ``keel.'' ``We can do some damage in Sydney. I'm looking
forward to it. We've got a good pool of talent here. We're building
our presence and hopefully we can get some medals.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Sua, 22, and Powell, 23, intend to do in Sydney. To
accomplish that, they will have to be throwing in excess of 220
feet in two months. With a best of 212-10 last year, Sua ranked No.
6 in the world in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be in better shape then,'' Sua said. ``I'm looking to
medal, hopefully a gold. I'm just really excited. I can't believe I
threw 216 today. I shouldn't put limits on myself.''
</P>
<P>
   After Sua won the NCAA championship in June for the fourth
straight year, her coach, Art Venegas, encouraged her to get in
better shape for the Olympic trials. Maybe ``encouraged'' wasn't
exactly what he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My coach said to lose weight, that I was too fat,'' said Sua,
who is 6-1 1/2 and 240 pounds. ``So I lost a couple pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Venegas' admonition had anything to do with Sua's
performance Monday night at Hornet Stadium is debatable. But what
she did on the first round definitely put pressure on the rest of
the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was planning on getting a good throw early,'' Sua said.
``I'm really happy with myself. I just wanted to get a good throw
early and make them chase it. When it came off my hand I knew it
would be a good one. When it hit, I was amazed. It was cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Sua said she wasn't thinking about Cady's record, though. She
was simply happy with the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing,'' Sua said. ``I can't believe I made the Olympic
team, representing the USA.''
</P>
<P>
   For Powell, it's her second time representing the USA. At 5-10
1/2 and 155 pounds, Powell is more svelte than her former UCLA
teammate. She relies on quickness in the ring and a slingshot arm
to propel her discus.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a big throw like that early, it puts a lot of pressure
on us,'' Powell said. ``It's a healthy rivalry. It helps both of us
. . . I definitely think I have the capability of being a medal
contender. My training tells me I am throwing the distances that
have historically been in that range.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the more competitive women's discus, the women's
javelin was won by Lynda Blutreich on her first throw with an
effort of 191 feet, 2 inches. Since no American, including
Blutreich, has made the Olympic qualifying standard for the event,
she will be the only U.S. women's javelinist in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be nice to have some company,'' said Blutreich, an
assistant track coach at Duke. ``We have some great talent coming
up. We need to get the women's javelin going.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Kreiner was second at 187-2, with Emily Carlsten third with
a throw of 186-11.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four women's throws events in track and field, the
javelin is by far the worst among Americans. The event has
seriously regressed since the days of Kate Schmidt and Karen Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just that all the other events are (contested) in high
school, so there's no feeder system (for the javelin),'' Blutreich
said. ``The development is just not there. Only 13 states, I think,
throw it in high school, maybe less than that. The javelin is
something you have to start when you're really young.''
</P>
<P>
   Blutreich, 28, first picked up the javelin when she was 18 after
swimming, playing basketball and throwing the shot when she was
younger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a hard transition for me,'' she said. ``It's
different than throwing a ball. I have a gun (for an arm). I'm just
trying hard to use it. You've got to be explosive, you need to be
quick, you need to be in good shape, because the javelin is really
hard on your body. If you do it wrong it hurts even more.''
</P>
<P>
   And watching American women try to throw the javelin hurts even
more than that. In comparison, the discus is downright sublime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1753EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
