<HEADER>
A5825 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-RENTAL19-COX     07-18 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENTAL19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aaron Rents planning major facility expansion in Texas, Georgia
 &HT;    By Renee DeGross
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Aaron Rents, the nation's third-largest rent-to-own
furniture retailer, is buying a manufacturing plant in Texas and
expanding another in South Georgia as it continues adding stores.
</P>
<P>
   Founder R. Charles Loudermilk said Tuesday the furniture rental
and rent-to-own company paid $3 million for a 150,000 square-foot
facility near Houston in Sugar Land, Texas. Plans call for more
than doubling the size and using it as a distribution plant and to
manufacture upholstered furniture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas is our largest state for business,'' Loudermilk said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cairo, Ga., facility will expand by another 100,000 square
feet, adding up to 100 workers, Loudermilk said. Construction will
begin in about two months.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion will help the company, which has 11 plants, open
80 new stores this year. Most are franchise locations.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Rents has 176 franchise stores, with another 120 planned
over the next few years. The company began franchising Aaron rental
purchase stores in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had 33 consecutive quarters of record revenues without a
blip,'' Loudermilk said.
</P>
<P>
   Sales over the past eight years have increased from $226.9
million to $437.4 million. Profit last year was $25.6 million, up
from $21.5 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Aaron Rents hasn't attracted much notice on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a high-flying company,'' Loudermilk said.
``Investors are looking to make a bit hit. But when the Internet
craze levels out and the legitimate players work to the top, the
investing public will look at staple businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Loudermilk founded the company with his mother, Addie, in 1955.
Now in his early 70s, Loudermilk said he isn't ready to retire, but
added he has four potential successors in line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're in good hands if something happens to me,'' said
Loudermilk. ``But I'm not retiring so long as I'm having fun and
have my health.
</P>
<P>
   Loudermilk named, in alphabetical order for fairness, the
company's four top executives as possible candidates for the
company's top position: Ken Butler, Gil Danielson, Robert ``Robin''
Loudermilk, his son; and Ed Quinones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some say my son would take it over,'' Loudermilk said. ``But I
would only do it if he wanted the job, and would do the job. Here
we let cream rise to the top and create an atmosphere that's free
flowing.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron's business has three segments: office rental, household
short-term rental, and lease to own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept is proven,'' said John Baugh, an analyst with
First Union Securities. ``It's mostly for customers that can't
qualify for credit and it's a rental transaction with an option to
own at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron also rents furniture, appliances and electronics,
including big-screen televisions.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
