<SLUG> BC-TV-NBC-REALITY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC WILL FOLLOW OTHERS INTO THE REALITY FRAY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
PASADENA _ NBC executives surprised reporters with an unlikely mea
culpa for not diving into the reality-TV trend more quickly,
despite the critical caning of CBS's ``Big Brother'' and overall
bland ratings for such programming outside of ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' and ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Reality programming is definitely here,'' Scott Sassa,
president of NBC West Coast, declared Tuesday during the
semi-annual TV press tour. ``This is not a fad; it's a trend that's
going to be around for a while. The line of what is acceptable has
definitely been blurred. It's a moving target defined by public
tastes and public sentiment. We weren't as aggressive as we should
have been in pursuring that type of programming.''
</P>
<P>
   Sassa conceded that the network's success in traditional
fictional programming and its adherence to a concrete, less fluid
schedule than competitors CBS, ABC and Fox contributed to NBC's
flat-footed response to reality TV's explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our success in story form hurts us in (developing reality
shows),'' he said. ``Because of our stability, we're more
vulnerable because we have none of those shows.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC was second in the network ratings for the much sought-after
18-49 viewer demographic behind ABC, whose success can be planted
squarely on ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   Reality programming will likely pop up on NBC next summer,
despite the added costs of generating original programming during
the season when viewers are watching the networks the least.
</P>
<P>
   ``One smart thing about placing them in summer is that they're
against competition that's not as great,'' Sassa said, admitting
that due to the fact that such programs have such short shelf lives
_ they can't really be repeated or syndicated _ their ostensibly
lower price tag is misleading.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tricky field _ one of the trepidations is that you
don't want to inhibit the brand of quality we've established with
NBC over the years,'' Sassa said.
</P>
<P>
   Garth Ancier, president of NBC Entertainment, added, ``We can't
ignore this as something that's going to go away. The public spoke,
and they want these shows. The challenge is not just chasing a
clone (of ``Survivor'' or ``Millionaire''). We're trying to find
the next genre of this programming that will have some life. We've
heard every variation of putting people on a bus or train or
whatever and have them kicked off one by one. Nothing we've seen so
far is something we're happy announcing (as being in
development).''
</P>
<P>
   Sassa suggested that criticisms that series such as ``Big
Brother'' have debased network airwaves are ``not a good thing or
bad thing. It is what it is. Public sentiment and morals have
changed. I'm not comfortable making value judgments of other
people's programming.''
</P>
<P>
   In other news, Sassa dismissed published rumors that he would
soon be fired (Allison Janney of ``The West Wing'' and Megan
Mullally of ``Will &AMP; Grace'' mocked the rumors in a sketch
introducing Sassa to the press conference).
</P>
<P>
   Ancier also tried to quell rumors that ``The Michael Richards
Show,'' featuring the former ``Seinfeld'' star as a bumbling
private detective, was in creative turmoil. NBC scrapped the
original pilot and has added William Devane, ``Saturday Night
Live's'' Tim Meadows and Amy Farrington to the cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that we had the right idea (in the pilot), and the
right executive producers and star, but that we had not fleshed out
the concept enough,'' Ancier explained.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, he was on his own with these bits of physical humor.
Scripts past the pilot are promising. We've hired onto the staff
someone who writes detective stories to make it more workable.''
</P>
<P>
   Other cast additions announced by Ancier included feature film
actors Tom Conti, Lili Taylor, Hope Davis and Bebe Neuwirth to the
cast of ``Deadline,'' starring Oliver Platt as an investigative
journalist. Paul F. Tomplins of ``Mr. Show'' will join the cast of
``DAG,'' starring David Alan Grier as the First Lady's bodyguard,
and Oscar-winner Dianne Wiest will join ``Law &AMP; Order.'' Also,
Ancier announced that ``Tucker,'' a new family comedy, would air
Mondays at 8:30 p.m. and ``3rd Rock from the Sun'' would return to
Tuesdays at 8:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Ancier also announced that Steven Spielberg's fictional drama
about the Marines, ``Semper Fi,'' was expected to be a midseason
replacement series, though he admitted, ``We're looking for a show
runner to run it. It's a pretty ambitious show _ we'll be filming
all over the world, and you need a show runner willing to commit
his life to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Other midseason replacements: the comedies ``Three Sisters,''
``Go Fish,'' ``Dog Days,'' about talking dogs, and an untitled
series starring Tony winner Kristen Chenoweth, and two possible
dramas, ``News from the Edge'' and ``This Life.'' And Ancier
announced a new comedy in development for fall 2001, from Drew
Carey and Bruce Helford, inspired by an episode of ``The Drew Carey
Show'' broadcast live and incorporating material both scripted and
improvised. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
