<HEADER>
A5843 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-MEAT-LABELS-NYT &LR;      07-18 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEAT-LABELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READING THE FINE PRINT ON THAT FAT PIECE OF MEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just weeks ago, it seemed that meat and poultry
producers were finally going to have to provide the same nutrition
information on fresh cuts of meat that shoppers can find on a can
of peas or a box of crackers. President Clinton said so in a radio
address on May 27.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what the president said: ``This summer the federal
government will propose that packaged meat and poultry sold in
stores must come with nutrition labels. This is just plain common
sense. Shoppers value the fact that when they pick up a box of
cereal or a frozen meal, they can check the nutrition labels and
see how many calories or grams of saturated fat these foods
contain. That's the same kind of information that ought to be put
on every package of ground beef. Currently fewer than 60 percent of
retailers do so, because nutrition labeling of meat is voluntary.
It's time we make it mandatory.''
</P>
<P>
   That seemingly straightforward statement is anything but. It's
possible that the nutritional information will appear not on
packages but just at the meat counter.
</P>
<P>
   Nutrition labeling is mandatory for virtually every packaged
food, but not for meat and poultry, which is regulated by the
Department of Agriculture. All other foods are regulated by the
Food and Drug Administration, which since 1994 has required
nutrition labeling on packages.
</P>
<P>
   The Agriculture Department's regulations are voluntary and allow
stores to put nutrition information on placards or in brochures
near packages as long as at least 60 percent of the fresh meat is
labeled.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has spent time at a supermarket meat counter knows
that nutrition labeling is hard to find. Although pork and poultry
processors have started including nutrition information, beef
processors have not, and neither have supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Agriculture Department has indicated it does not plan to
force meat producers to put information on packages. In the Federal
Register of April 24, it said: ``The agency is proposing to require
that nutrition information be provided for these products either on
their label or at their point of purchase.''
</P>
<P>
   The department said last week that it would have no comment on
its tentative proposal. But it has obviously signaled what it
intends to do.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, ``We'd like to give the voluntary approach one more
try,'' said Sarah Lilygren of the American Meat Institute, a trade
association. After all, who wants to face the fact that an
eight-ounce porterhouse steak has 740 calories and 50 grams of fat?
</P>
<P>
   Karen Brown, a senior vice president of the Food Marketing
Institute, a supermarket trade association, said that she would
have no comment until a final proposal was issued. She noted that
some supermarkets, including Wegman's, a 58-store chain in upstate
New York, do label meat.
</P>
<P>
   That was news to Jane Andrews, a Wegman's spokeswoman. She said
the company favors labeling but labels only its ground meat because
it is difficult to provide accurate nutrition information on meat
cut at the stores.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Agriculture Department is expected to retain a
voluntary approach for most meat, it will make an exception for
ground meats, requiring that they carry nutrition labels. Labels
will still be able to say ``70 percent lean,'' ``80 percent lean,''
and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the Food and Drug Administration and the Agriculture
Department both ruled that a product could use the ``X percent
fat-free'' claim only if it was low fat (less than 10 percent) to
begin with. ``X percent fat-free'' and ``X percent lean'' are the
same.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, the Agriculture Department proposed a special
exemption allowing the ``percent lean'' claim even when the ground
meat was not low fat, as long as nutrition information was
available on the package or at the meat counter.
</P>
<P>
   There was heated opposition from health professionals, who
contended that such labeling confused and misled shoppers. But the
Agriculture Department is now proposing to make the loophole
permanent.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews said a combination of ``X percent lean'' and nutrition
information is exactly what consumers requested in focus groups,
adding, ``After we put the nutrition labeling and the `percent
lean' on the ground products, consumers changed what they bought
and started reducing fat.'' Labeling on the packages is preferable,
she said, because ``it's easier to read, and it's clear.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1812EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
