<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, July 19, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Humidity waned across the northern Middle Atlantic States on
Tuesday in the wake of a cool front. Wednesday, newly arrived dry
air will encourage the development of rain as moist air arriving
from the south is forced to rise over dense dry air.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, areas of steady rain will dampen the region
stretching from the upper Ohio River Valley to Pennsylvania,
Maryland, northern Virginia, northern West Virginia, and southwest
and south-central New York. With rain falling into dry air,
temperatures will drop dramatically below seasonal levels. Rain
will spread east toward the Middle Atlantic coast.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, thunderstorms, some approaching severe levels,
will erupt over parts of southern Virginia, the southern Delmarva
Peninsula and North Carolina as a jet stream disturbance lifts
humid air.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: A CHILL FROM HEAT
</P>
<P>
   On Monday afternoon, 100-degree heat at Austin, Texas, set the
stage for record chill at night. By dawn Tuesday, readings had
fallen to 69 degrees, tying the record low for the date. During the
day Monday, intense heating of the very dry ground around Austin
caused blobs of hot air to rise several thousand feet above the
surface before warm air aloft (associated with a ridge of high
pressure) halted the ascent. In compensation, drier air sank to the
ground. With less water vapor near the surface, nighttime
temperatures fell to lower levels. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
