``marriage penalty'' bill Tuesday that would provide $248 billion
in tax relief over 10 years, a centerpiece of the Republican drive
for election-year tax cuts. By Richard W. Stevenson. (Summary from
wires) With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `w' category)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Thurmont, Md.) _ The White House painted a
picture Tuesday of little sleep and unwavering intensity inside the
gates of Camp David, describing scenes of President Clinton
negotiating until dawn with Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel and
then, after a catnap, meeting with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
five hours later. Informally, officials were suggesting that
Clinton's artificial deadline of 9 a.m. Wednesday, when he is
scheduled to leave for Japan, could be stretched by as much as 21
hours, an element of information that added to a steadily building
drama. By Jane Perlez. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   REFORM-BUCHANAN (Undated) _ At the urging of the Pat Buchanan
campaign, the Reform Party national committee has scheduled a
meeting the day before the party's August convention that could
lead to the final takeover of the party by the former conservative
commentator. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `p' category)
</P>
<P>
   ADOPTED-MONKEY (New York) _ The saga of Cookie Flikshtein has
stirred tumultuous feelings on both sides of the fight. To the
Flikshtein family and an outraged army of their neighbors, Cookie
is a beloved _ albeit simian _ member of the family. She may be a
monkey, they admit, but she has adjusted enough to the human
condition to spend most evenings eating Rocky Road ice cream and
watching the nightly news. The state agrees that Cookie is no
ordinary primate, but not because of her human characteristics. She
is a Diana monkey, an endangered species. As such, she deserves
special care, and the state, after a protracted court battle, has
successfully argued that Cookie should be taken from the Flikshtein
home and placed in a special animal rescue program at the Detroit
Zoo. By Alan Feuer. With photos NYT5, 6.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-DAMS (Pioneer, Calif.) _ The future of the Pacific Gas and
Electric hydropower system, a complex of 174 dams on 17 river
systems that is the largest privately held collection of dams in
the world, is at stake under current plans for its pieces to be
auctioned off to the highest bidder by sometime next year. That
specter had prompted a coalition of environmental groups and
outdoorsmen to demand that any sale be tied to arrangements
intended to ease the toll being inflicted on California's rivers.
By Douglas Jehl. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
