<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIKAILA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIKAILA AIMS TO BREAK THE BLOND TEEN POP-STAR MOLD 
 (ACCOMPANIES POPMUSIC-FERMAN-COLUMN)
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
 By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeff Fenster knows talent _ or at least a dollar sign _ when he
sees it.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-based talent scout and executive vice president of
A&AMP;R (artist and repertoire) for the Island/Def Jam label is the man
responsible for signing teen-pop unstoppables Backstreet Boys and
Britney Spears to Jive Records, where he used to work.
</P>
<P>
   Since he joined Island/Def Jam a year ago, he has signed only
one artist, but he insists she's going to be a big one: Mikaila
Enriquez, a 13-year-old singer from North Richland Hills, Texas, a
Fort Worth suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Island/Def Jam is poising Mikaila _ who, trendily, goes by her
first name only (it's pronounced Mah-KAY-la) _ for major success by
giving her the opening slot on Spears' current tour (which rolls
into Smirnoff Music Centre in Dallas on Wednesday night), sending
her across the country to pop radio stations for interviews and
spending a ton of time, energy and money on her self-titled debut,
which is set to come out January 2001.
</P>
<P>
   It's something she's been preparing for all of her young life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been singing since I was 3, since I could talk,'' Mikaila
said, calling from a hotel room in New York, where she's been
rehearsing for her tour with Britney. ``Wherever, family reunions,
school, church.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, with Britney, stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're gonna do the same thing that we did with Britney,''
Fenster said. ``We're gonna put her out there and keep her out
there. This isn't something you do with every artist, but when it's
someone this special, you kind of want to let the world know that
you're coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Mikaila is the latest in a long line of attractive, post-Britney
teen female singers to be groomed for the pop-music spotlight _ and
the third from Texas, right behind Jessica Simpson from Plano and
Angela Via from San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   What makes her different is her age. At 13, Mikaila is the
youngest pop singer to get a major label deal. But in spite of the
music industry's current Lolita-like love affair with blond teen
girls _ as well as the arrival of Billy Gilman, the much-touted,
12-year-old male country singer _ Fenster surely must fear that
Mikaila's age will handicap her in an industry known for its
cutthroat competition, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the answer is `no,' '' Fenster says. ``It's an old
cliche, but from our standpoint, age ain't nothing but a number.
Besides, she's a teen artist and her initial audience will be
teens. She is a member of who her audience is. That's where they
start, with their peers. If they're the real deal, they grow and
appeal to an even broader audience.''
</P>
<P>
   To Mikaila's credit, she hardly seems like a 13-year-old.
Makeup, platform shoes and sexy clothing at least superficially
bump up her maturity a few years, but it's not just her looks that
belie her age. She is quick-witted and sagacious far beyond her
years.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if she feels like the label is looking to cash in on
the cute-girl trend rather than her talent, she answers astutely.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're always going to be looking at the money side,'' she
says, ``But they haven't forced me to do anything I haven't wanted
to do. That's why I went with them. A lot of new artists get pushed
in directions they don't want to go, or get lost among other
artists on that label. It's sad.''
</P>
<P>
   A native of Edmond, Okla., Mikaila moved to North Texas with her
family when she was 9. There, she attended Spring Garden Elementary
School in Bedford; she had already been singing for six years.
</P>
<P>
   Mikaila's family eventually took her musical aspirations
seriously and helped her build a career, enrolling her in vocal and
dance classes. Singing in churches led to singing at sporting
events. Sporting events led to lawyers' offices. Finally, the
family hired entertainment attorney Larry Rudolph, who just so
happened to be Britney Spears' manager.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Mikaila says, the phone would not stop ringing.
``We went to New York and, in one day, visited five different
record labels,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   After signing with Island/Def Jam, Mikaila began work on her
self-titled debut.
</P>
<P>
   And it will be this album, Mikaila says, that will make her
stand apart from all the other teen singers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My music is a lot different than everyone else's,'' she says.
``It has more of an R&AMP;B flavor to it. It's not the usual thing you
hear on the radio. Plus, I know I'm gonna stand out 'cause I have
brown hair.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
