r s BC-GLF-BROPEN-WOODS19     07-18 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BROPEN-WOODS19 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Odds are nearly 2-1 Woods will win British Open on Woods
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland - It will take a serious wager to make
substantial money on Tiger Woods here this week.
</P>
<P>
   On the brick-hard fairways of the Old Course, his odds for the
129th British Open resemble those usually associated with
thoroughbreds.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Tuesday about the lopsided 2-1 favorite's role, Woods
corrected to the right odds, 15-8. Then he discouraged people from
betting. ``Well, maybe five quid here and there,'' Woods said. ``I
probably wouldn't put any more than that. It's bad odds.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not. When you win a U.S. Open by 15 shots, anything is
possible. Add his 15-stroke victory at the U.S. Open to his 12-shot
victory in the 1997 Masters, and the pressure shifts to those being
embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   Woods seems comfortable as the favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you, it is nice to have an opportunity to
complete the (career) slam at St. Andrews,'' he said, ``but, then
again, if my career goes as long as I hope it will go, I think I
might have a few more opportunities. And that's something you have
to keep in the back of your mind. I know one thing. When it's time
to play on Thursday, I couldn't care less about the slam.''
</P>
<P>
   He played the Old Course about 7 a.m. Tuesday with Mark
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara and Mark Calcavecchia. He was wearing his black
ensemble, including a turtleneck to fight the morning cool. With
his mother, Tida, following the group, Woods hit tee shots and lies
in several bunkers, trying to gather new information about the Old
Course, which can differ by the moment. He has played at St.
Andrews twice, as an amateur in 1995 and in the Dunhill Cup two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   His length off the tee is expected to serve him well. Depending
on weather conditions, O'Meara said, Woods could drive as many as
eight of the par-4s; seven are under 400 yards. The ball is running
so fast on the fairways that all of the long hitters should have
opportunities for eagles.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Woods spoke about a bunker downwind on the 464-yard
4th hole, about 350 yards from the tee. He was 15 yards short of
the bunker on Tuesday with a poorly hit 3-wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the wind blows,'' Woods said, ``you can see guys hitting
the ball over 400, no problem. That won't be hard to do. . . . I'm
not the only one saying this, but it's weird to have the fairways
faster than the greens.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Faldo envisions 450-yard bombs from Woods. Lee Trevino, who
knows something about getting maximum yardage from low-trajectory
shots in a British Open, figures at least six par-4s are driveable
by Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to make some mistakes trying to hit it so far,''
Trevino said, ``but I'll tell you, he's going to make a lot of
birdies, too.''
</P>
<P>
   He could be in line to break the Open Championship record of
18-under, set by Faldo in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've watched those tapes (of 1990), and the pins were not
tucked,'' Tiger said. ``They were toward the middle of the greens,
because they were protecting against the big wind. . . . If you
looked at the scores in '90, it wasn't just Nick. He only won by
four. There were other guys on 14-under. . . . The pins were
accessible, and the golf course was to be had.''
</P>
<P>
   Masters champion Vijay Singh has suggested that players who
concern themselves too much with what Woods is doing this week
``are already in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods said he doubts that many players will be that poorly
focused. ``They need to take care of their own business,'' he said.
``I'm going to try and take care of mine, so I can be there Sunday
with a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
