<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: Mr. Poppy trimmed your hair while
filling your head with stories
 &HT;    (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By David C. Keller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Special to Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Sunday morning, it was St. John's Lutheran Church.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday and Saturday nights, it was one of the five taverns in
town or the American Legion Hall.
</P>
<P>
   But on Saturday morning the gathering place of society in Union,
Ill., a small farm town of 300, was Mr. Poppy's barbershop.
</P>
<P>
   When we first moved to town, Mr. Poppy had a regular shop with
three chairs in a converted garage and a little gas heater that
barely kept the shop warm in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time he ``retired'' at the age of 85, he had grown
tired of keeping up such a big place and moved his shop into his
home.
</P>
<P>
   His living room was the waiting room, and he set up his barber
chair and equipment in the dining room. A tiny kitchen and bedroom
made up the rest of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Before coming to Union, our haircuts were generally given by my
mom in our basement. But, now my dad decided my brothers and I were
old enough to go to a regular barber.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Poppy charged 25 cents for a haircut, which was a bargain
even for the early '60s. He said he didn't want to make too much
money or his Social Security would be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Dad would always give us $1, though, and told us we'd better not
bring back any change. Mr. Poppy would often protest that it was
just too much of a tip for a 25-cent haircut.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Poppy never seemed to be in a hurry even if half a dozen
shaggy farmers filled his tiny waiting area. He would cut a little,
then stop and talk for a few minutes, then cut a little more. As a
result, a haircut usually took an hour to complete.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Poppy had only one kind of haircut -- short on top and no
sideburns. This was definitely not a cool haircut for a teenager of
that era.
</P>
<P>
   But the main reason most people went to Mr. Poppy's shop was for
the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Poppy was a fount of information about Union and its
citizens, having lived there his entire 89 years and barbered its
residents for most of that time.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but his lady friend was the postmistress of Union
and knew everything about everybody, which she gladly passed along
to him:
</P>
<P>
   Art Moellering bought that 80 acres out on River Road and
intended to put in soybeans ... Some new people from Chicago
acquired the old Wayne place ... The Baumans just got a load of sod
delivered to their house ...
</P>
<P>
   The one topic that both young and old enjoyed most was
reminiscing.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Poppy would hold us spellbound with accounts of how Union
was the last town east of the Mississippi to go dry before
Prohibition and how trainloads of drinkers would travel to Union
from Chicago to fill their jugs with whiskey.
</P>
<P>
   I always came away from Mr. Poppy's barbershop with my head
shorn of its sideburns but filled with wonderful stories.
</P>
<P>
   (David C. Keller lives in Greensboro, N.C.)
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915; email, jmurray(at)txucom.net. If your article
is used, you will receive $25. For other Dreamsville stories, visit
http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
