<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5863 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-POL-TICKER19-COX     07-18 2032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gephardt says he doesn't want to be Gore's running mate
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt says he doesn't want to be
Al Gore's running mate this fall _ but he wouldn't rule out
accepting the second slot. Democratic officials have said in recent
days that Gephardt was one of several potential running mates on
Gore's list. But Gephardt says he expects to be busy helping the
party recapture Congress. ``I think I've been clear; I don't know
how you can be more clear,'' the Missourian said in his first
public comments since word surfaced that he and Gore held an
unannounced meeting recently. ABC News quoted a Gephardt adviser as
saying it is ``very, very unlikely'' that Gephardt will be on the
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   A PUSH FOR VICTIMS' RIGHTS
</P>
<P>
   Criticized for halfhearted support of a victims' rights
resolution in the Senate, Al Gore wrapped the proposed
constitutional amendment into his presidential campaign with an
appearance in Memphis today at the side of crime victims. Gore
listened _ nodding and ``mmm-hmmm-ing'' sympathetically _ as seven
victims told their stories. One told of having her rapist watch her
as she testified at his parole hearing. Another _ held hostage and
raped repeatedly for five days by three men _ pleaded to be
notified when they're paroled. Gore promised that, under his
proposed amendment, there would be victim notification of paroles
or escapes.
</P>
<P>
   ON TIPTOES IN ILLINOIS
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush went to Illinois Tuesday in an attempt to strike
a delicate balance between winning votes in a key battleground
state and aligning himself too closely with a politically
beleaguered governor who chairs his state campaign. Bush's first
visit to Illinois came amid concerns in his camp over Gov. George
Ryan. Asked recently in jest whether Ryan, who has imposed a
moratorium on the death penalty in Illinois, was ever on the list
to be considered as a potential running mate, ``Oh pleeease,'' Bush
responded, his mouth turning into a grin.
</P>
<P>
   CAROLINE KENNEDY ON THE BILL
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Kennedy, the only surviving member of the slain
president's immediate family, will address the Democratic
convention. Mark Fabiani said the time and topic have not been
decided. Caroline's brother, John F. Kennedy Jr., addressed the
convention in 1988 to wild cheers as he recounted the legacy of his
father and introduced his uncle, Massachusetts Sen. Edward Kennedy.
Caroline Kennedy has been careful about her turns in the political
spotlight. In 1992, she declined to serve as Democratic convention
chairwoman.
</P>
<P>
   AS QUICK AS YOU CAN SAY JACK ROBINSON
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts' highest court ruled that Republican Jack E.
Robinson gathered enough valid voter signatures and should be
allowed to make his long shot challenge of Sen. Edward Kennedy.
``We won,'' said Robinson, who was disavowed by his own party after
embarrassing details about his past were revealed. The State Ballot
Law Commission had ruled in favor of challenges to 129 signatures
by the secretary of state's office and the state Democratic Party,
making him 14 signatures shy of the 10,000 needed. Today's court
decision overturned that ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ANY TIME LEFT FOR COMMERCIALS?
</P>
<P>
   CBS, which had considered cutting back prime-time coverage of
the two conventions to just two nights, now says it will have at
least some live coverage on all four nights of each gathering. ABC
also changed its plans, adding an hour of coverage on the first
night of both conventions. The expanded coverage assures that
President Clinton's speech will be broadcast live on the two
networks. The extra hour for the Republicans will help equalize
coverage and allow the showing of retired Gen. Colin Powell's
speech.
</P>
<P>
   SOME SHRINKAGE IN THE POLLS
</P>
<P>
   Three new polls indicate that George W. Bush's lead over Al Gore
is narrowing. A CBS News survey (4 percentage point margin of
error) shows Bush leading Gore 43-41 percent, down from his 47-39
edge in May. A Zogby poll (3 percentage point error margin) has
Bush holding a 45-41percent lead, compared to a 47-39 edge a month
ago. And a USA Today/CNN Gallup poll (4 percentage point error
margin) has Bush leading Gore 45-43 percent, compared to 50-to-41 a
week ago.
</P>
<P>
   RECORDS ARE MADE TO BE BROKEN
</P>
<P>
   It's only July and already the hard-fought congressional contest
in the Los Angeles suburbs between Rep. James Rogan (R-Calif.) and
Democratic state Sen. Adam Schiff is on the verge of becoming the
most expensive House race in American history. With about $7.5
million raised so far, they seem certain to surpass the $8 million
record set in Georgia in the 1996 contest between then-Speaker Newt
Gingrich and his Democratic challenger, Michael Coles. Rogan was
one of the House impeachment managers in the case against President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   GOOD SHOT IN THE ARM NEEDED
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic National Committee warning that traveling in Texas
may be hazardous to your health _ intended as a slap at George W.
Bush _ brought a stern warning from a Houston health official about
injecting politics into public safety. ``Public health is too
serious an issue to politicize, especially the health of our
children,'' said Kathy Barton of the Houston health department. The
nation's fourth largest city, according to the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention, is ripe for an epidemic because only 67
percent of its children are vaccinated.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T TREAD ON THEIR STATE
</P>
<P>
   A group headed by a Texas magazine publisher says it'll work to
ensure the state is treated fairly as its Republican governor runs
for the presidency. The Proud of Texas Committee was formed by
Texas Monthly publisher Michael Levy. Members include Democratic
State Board of Education member Will Davis, Texas Tech University
Health Sciences Center president David Smith and ex-state Rep. Mark
Stiles, a Democrat from Beaumont. All four have contributed to
George W. Bush's campaign. Texas Democratic Chair Molly Beth
Malcolm said that's proof the group is not independent.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK OUT AL, HERE COMES NADER
</P>
<P>
   The Green Party is striking some fear into the hearts of
Michigan Democrats by pushing to get Ralph Nader onto Michigan's
ballot. By Thursday's deadline, Green Party supporters plan to turn
in more than 50,000 petition signatures. At least 30,272 signatures
must be valid for the party to qualify for the November ballot.
``The ones that sign ... are just so happy to have a viable
alternative'' to Bush and Gore, said the Geen Party's Craig Harvey.
A recent statewide poll showed Nader taking votes away from Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   SUING FOR SPOT AT DEBATES
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party presidential hopeful Pat Buchanan's campaign said
today he'll soon file suit against the commission organizing
presidential candidate debates to be included in the contests.
Buchanan, running for the Reform Party nomination against nuclear
physicist John Hagelin, petitioned the Federal Election Commission
for inclusion in the debates. A 20-day period for the FEC to take
action was to expire today, apparently without any response.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERTRAIL OF CAMPAIGN DONATIONS
</P>
<P>
   It's now much easier for Texans, or anyone else, to follow the
money. Starting today, political campaign finance reports filed
electronically with the Texas Ethics Commission were going posted
on the Internet (www.ethics.state.tx.us), making them more widely
available. Texas joined a group of about 20 states that mandate
electronic disclosure of contributions and expenses by candidates
and lawmakers. Watchdog groups hailed the online database's debut
as a victory for open government.
</P>
<P>
   PROTESTERS AS SUPERHEROS
</P>
<P>
   The Berkeley-based Ruckus Society is hosting a training camp
this week to teach activists elaborate civil disobedience tactics
for the demonstrations planned outside the Aug. 14-17 convention in
downtown Los Angeles. Atop the Santa Monica Mountains, about 150
activists are learning how to be like Superman. They're practicing
ways to scale tall buildings to hang massive protest banners,
linking arms to form nearly unbreakable human blockades, and
learning how to move faster than a speeding tear gas canister.
</P>
<P>
   PROTESTERS AS PUPPETS
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators at the Republican convention in Philadelphia will
perform impromptu street theater as colorful political puppets
while wearing papier-mache masks of Uncle Sam or ``corporate fat
cats.'' Some of the most elaborate puppets will appear in the Unity
2000 march, expected to draw up to 20,000 demonstrators on July 30
the day before the convention opens. Dozens of activists plan to
dress up as rats, cockroaches and ants in a ``Parade of
Pestilence'' on July 31 _ representing ``dirty government.''
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC NEPHEW OUT THERE STUMPING
</P>
<P>
   George Prescott Bush, son of Florida Gov. Jeb Bush and his
Mexican-born wife, Columba, was in Atlanta speaking at the Plaza La
Fiesta, a Latino marketplace, before attending a reception with
young professionals at a swank Buckhead-area jazz club. A day
earlier Bush, who will enter the University of Texas Law School
next month, spoke to the Young Hispanic Republican Association in
Arlingon, Va. He said his uncle is working to appeal to Hispanic
and other minority voters who have historically been written off as
sure votes for Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   OLD RIVAL GOES TO BAT FOR BAUER
</P>
<P>
   ``It's payback time for Sen. John McCain,'' the National Journal
reports. No, he hasn't set out to settle an old score. Rather, he's
asking about 80,000 of his contributors to send checks to a former
rival for the Republican nomination, conservative activist Gary
Bauer, to help him retire his campaign debt. The publication said
that McCain, in a letter to mail donors (not the thousands who gave
through the Internet), noted that Bauer was ``willing to put his
neck on the line for us'' when he endorsed McCain's candidacy after
withdrawing from the race.
</P>
<P>
   CAN YOU KEEP THE NAMES STRAIGHT?
</P>
<P>
   K.B. Forbes rejoined Pat Buchanan, becoming a spokesman for his
campaign after a stint representing unsuccessful Republican
candidate Steve Forbes. K.B. Forbes was Buchanan's deputy press
secretary in 1996 and a regional press secretary based in
California in 1992. Then he became Steve Forbes' traveling press
secretary. In his new role, K.B. Forbes will be Buchanan's
communications director. The Forbeses are not related, and K.B.
says he remains a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   A LOT MORE WHERE THAT CAME FROM
</P>
<P>
   Jon Corzine, who spent a record $36.7 million to win the
Democratic primary in New Jersey for U.S. Senate, filed to sell $41
million worth of stock in Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., which he once
headed. A campaign spokesman said Corzine wanted to diversify his
investment portfolio.The candidate has lent his campaign $33
million so far. The stock sale is expected to take place in a
public offering in about two weeks. Corzine will still own about 4
million shares of Goldman Sachs, worth about $400 million at
current value of about $1000 a share.
</P>
<P>
   WOULD HILLARY HAVE DONE THIS?
</P>
<P>
   Tipper Gore's ginger snaps are going cookie-to-cookie against
Laura Bush's Texas governor's mansion cowboy cookies in Family
Circle's third cook-off between the presidential candidates' wives.
You can try out the recipes and cast your vote by sending a
postcard to Family Circle Cookie Cook-Off, c/o Grand Central
Station Post Office, P.O. Box 4663, New York, NY 10163. It must be
postmarked by Aug. 1. The winner will be revealed in an upcoming
issue.
</P>
<P>
   NOW WIFE'S TURN TO TAKE THE STAGE
</P>
<P>
   Donna Hanover, who pulled out of a turn in ``The Vagina
Monologues'' after estranged hubby Rudy Giuliani was diagnosed with
prostate cancer and quit the New York Senate race, has signed on
for a stint running from Oct.10-Nov. 5. Hanover will be one of the
three female stars who read the monologues, which involve
everything from rape in Bosnia to sex on Long Island. Hanover: ``
Personal and family considerations make this fall a better time
than the previous dates.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
