<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5867 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-DRUGCO-DISTRUST-NEWHO     07-18 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGCO-DISTRUST-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG INDUSTRY LIKELY TO REMAIN UNDER FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Tuesday, July 18, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By ED SILVERMAN and ROBERT COHEN  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite churning out effective medicines in recent years, the
bitter debate over a prescription-drug benefit for seniors and the
cost of AIDS drugs in poor countries has turned the nation's
pharmaceutical industry into a high-profile whipping boy.
</P>
<P>
   To an extent, the heated rhetoric labeling drug makers as price
gougers and profiteers reflects election-year politics. Vice
President Al Gore is the most visible example, accusing the
``powerful'' industry of ``special-interest schemes'' to keep
prices high.
</P>
<P>
   But a growing number of politicians, consumer advocates and
health-care experts say the harsh statements reflect a growing
distrust that may keep pharmaceutical companies on the defensive
well beyond the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``This industry is in a tough situation. It's very clear it's
not well liked. The challenge is to remain competitive without
alienating consumers,'' said Laura Ries, a corporate-image
consultant. ``But there's no easy answer and so the problem isn't
going to go away.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first time drug makers have been lambasted. They
were vilified during the Clinton administration's failure to
overhaul the health care system in 1994. And AIDS activists have
regularly heckled and picketed pharmaceutical companies.
</P>
<P>
   As drug makers see it, they're misunderstood. They argue
research funding, which climbed from $15.2 billion in 1995 to $26.4
billion last year, would be hurt by some proposals for making drugs
more affordable here and abroad. And while they have a duty to
patients, they say, they also have a responsibility to
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the industry needs to be relentlessly and continuously
positive and open about the benefits our medicines provide,'' said
Alan Holmer, president of the Pharmaceutical Research and
Manufacturers of America, the industry's trade group. ``I know it
sounds Pollyanish, but this is what we'll do and, principally, all
we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, prices for prescription drugs continue to rise.
Last year, the average cost of a prescription drug jumped 9.6
percent, according to Express Scripts Inc., a pharmacy benefits
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Another study by Families USA, a health-care advocacy group,
found the average cost of the 50 drugs most used by the elderly --
one-third of whom lack drug coverage -- rose almost 4 percent last
year, outpacing the 2.2 percent inflation rate. At the same time,
consumer advocates have pointed to drastically lower drug prices in
Canada and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the industry is spending billions of dollars
promoting new and expensive pills for impotence, dieting and
baldness -- life-style, not life-saving medicines.
</P>
<P>
   According to IMS Health, a market researcher, industry
promotional spending rose 11 percent in 1999 to $13.9 billion. This
included $1.8 billion for direct advertisements to consumers, a 40
percent increase from 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Drug makers also have come under attack for trying to block poor
African governments from allowing local companies to make cheaper
generic versions of expensive AIDS drugs or even import them from
Brazil or India where U.S. patents aren't protected. And plans by
some drug makers to offer steep discounts has prompted cries for
price reductions in this country.
</P>
<P>
   All of this has occurred as the drug industry has consistently
racked up impressive profits -- year-to-year earnings growth
reported by most drug makers has regularly exceeded 10 percent.
Some companies recorded earnings gains above 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the heavy promotional spending, expensive lobbying
battles over AIDS drugs and the Medicare drug benefit, and
legislative efforts to extend patents on big-selling drugs convey
the sense that the companies put profits ahead of patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through it all, the drug industry keeps saying they're
interested in public health,'' said Larry Sasich of Public Citizen,
a consumer advocacy group. ``But they're really just a business
like any other.''
</P>
<P>
   Public Citizen this month issued a report criticizing the
industry for spending $236 million to lobby Washington between 1997
and 1999, and giving an estimated $13.8 million in political
contributions for the 2000 election year cycle to influence
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Drug makers respond that they have a right to make their
positions heard and argue that rising prices reflect the rapidly
increasing cost of developing each new medicine, a figure that now
stands at about $500 million. They say such outlays require them to
develop and aggressively promote any drug that will provide high
returns and attract investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pharmaceutical companies are not philanthropic
organizations,'' said Ralph Larsen, chief executive at Johnson &AMP;
Johnson in New Brunswick, N.J. ``Yes, we have to find a way to make
drugs more affordable for people who can't afford them. But if
companies went out and slashed prices for everything, research
would dry up. And like it or not, this is expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, pharmaceutical companies maintain the White
House's Medicare proposal -- which relies on government, not
private insurers, to administer a drug benefit to seniors -- would
lead to price controls, stifling revenue needed to pay for
research. They prefer a Republican plan that relies on a federally
subsidized drug benefit provided by the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Republican pollster Whit Ayres said the attacks on the industry
by Gore and the Democrats represent a predictable ploy to appeal to
seniors and bolster its chances in the fall elections, rather than
work with the GOP to pass legislation in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is having difficulty consolidating the Democratic base
behind his candidacy and whenever that happens, Democrats start
engaging in anti-rich, anti-business class warfare to gin up the
troops,'' said Ayres.
</P>
<P>
   But some observers say the industry has gone overboard and
created some of its own problems, pointing to an organization
called Citizens for Better Medicare. Ron Pollack, director of
Families USA, called the organization a ``deceptive'' front
operation for the drug industry that has spent more than $30
million on advertising to oppose the Democrats' Medicare plan.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Ryan, who heads Citizens for Better Medicare, complained his
group has been ``demonized,'' and said it is fighting for
comprehensive Medicare reform that includes a drug benefit free of
government price controls.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Silverman is a staff writer and Robert Cohen is Washington
correspondent for The Star-Ledger of Newark, N.J.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
