<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEEDY FAIRWAYS MAKING BRITISH OPEN FIELD CAUTIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ Christy O'Connor Jr. would be next on
the first tee, so as he waited for Tom Lehman and Duffy Waldorf to
hit, there was time for some practice putting.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Connor wasn't on the practice green; he was right there on
a portion of the first tee, rolling putts toward the six holes that
had been cut. Mike Weir, who would tee off after O'Connor, was
doing the same thing, and you couldn't find a player in the field
of 156 who would tell you it didn't make sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greens are running 10 on the stimp, the fairways 12,''
said Lehman, whose view is universally shared by his colleagues
here for the 129th British Open at historic St. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   Firm and fast? How about firmest and fastest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is weird to have the fairways faster than the greens,''
said Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is going to be very, very fast,'' said Jack Nicklaus.
``They have cut the fairways to nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is seriously dry,'' said Nick Faldo. ``It is a different
style of golf. You have to really start thinking bump and run. The
fairways are very tight.''
</P>
<P>
   Fairways? How about runways?
</P>
<P>
   It is generally believed that Woods has the ability to drive at
least four of the par-4s here, but over the last two days, when
conditions were out of the ordinary for this cherished venue _ that
is, warm and windless _ great length was not limited to Woods.
There is, after all, the presence of John Daly, who reportedly
drove the 412-yard sixth hole.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, that would open eyes, but already this week there have
been so many stories of golf balls rolling wild distances that
nothing is hard to believe.
</P>
<P>
   There was Jeff Sluman, tossing balls on the practice range only
to see them roll a hundred yards.
</P>
<P>
   There was Fred Couples driving on the closing hole, his ball
rolling through the Valley of Sin, up and through the green, and
out-of-bounds on a hole that measures 357 yards.
</P>
<P>
   There was Colin Montgomerie reaching the 312-yard 12th hole, and
Woods doing likewise, with a ``cut driver back into the wind,'' no
less.
</P>
<P>
   There were Darren Clarke and Paul McGinley having easy
approaches into the usually-feared Road Hole, the demanding par-4
17th that measures 455 yards.
</P>
<P>
   And there was Woods, of all people, acting amazed at how far he
had hit a shot. It was at the 464-yard fourth hole, a drive down
the left side with the wind ``coming down off the right.'' He
pulled it slightly, but it stayed in the fairway and rolled and
rolled and rolled. Nice, said Woods, ``but it was only 15 yards
away from a huge bunker that only comes into play downwind right to
left.''
</P>
<P>
   The bunkers at St. Andrews are to be avoided at all cost, but
with the ground so hard, Woods now knows the bunker on No. 4 _ even
if it is 350 yards away _ is within range for him, and not just
with the wind at his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of neat to pick up new little things,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Players, said Faldo, best pick up a lot of new little tricks if
they are to navigate their way around St. Andrews this week,
because unless conditions change dramatically, they won't be flying
their wedges and 9-irons at pins and making them stop on a dime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite often, the shot is just feel,'' said Faldo, who was 18
under when he won the British Open here in 1990, a week when
conditions were somewhat similar. ``There is a lot of putting from
around the greens, short of the greens, off the greens, that sort
of thing. Very much along the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   That has players scrambling to figure out which 14 clubs to put
into their bags.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the guys are talking about changing some of their
wedges,'' said Woods. ``They want to try and go for a little less
bounce, get the blade underneath the ball for a bit. You have to
tinker with things.''
</P>
<P>
   The added distance, said Woods, is not necessarily a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the fairways being as fast as they are,'' he said, ``you
need to position your golf ball off the tee because the ball will
run, and if you keep it on the left too much, there are pots
(bunkers) on the holes that you share the fairway with that you can
run right into and still have to pitch out.''
</P>
<P>
   Personally, he'd like an old staple _ the wind _ to make an
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it blows because I think that's the tradition of the
British Open,'' said Woods, who is trying to complete the career
grand slam. ``I think any time the wind blows on any golf course,
it distinguishes the players who are playing well a lot faster and
more dramatically than when it is calm.''
</P>
<P>
   Be careful what you wish for, say longtime observers, because
conditions at St. Andrews can change in the time it takes one of
Woods's drives to travel 400 yards. Because of that, Vijay Singh
said, he wasn't spending any time worrying about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys who are not used to dry and fast conditions have just
got to get used to it right now,'' said Singh, the Masters champ.
``Otherwise, they're not going to contend.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of contention _ but a long way down the fairway, it seems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
