<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5873 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-CYC-TOUR-BOS &LR;      07-18 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG STRUGGLES UP MOUNTAIN, STILL HOLDS OVERALL LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORZINE, France _ The French sense of hyperbole must be rubbing
off on American Lance Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was the hardest day of my life on a bicycle,'' he said
after Tuesday's 16th stage in the Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
   He sounded an awful lot like the television commentators who
exclaim ``Lance is suffering!'' or ``It looks like Marco Pantani is
pedaling backwards!'' if it looks as though a cyclist is having
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong might have suffered as he made his way up the final
mountain, and his overall lead did slip a little. But he finished
eighth in a stage that Frenchman Richard Virenque won in 5 hours 32
minutes 20 seconds, and still holds the overall lead, with a 5
1/2-minute margin.
</P>
<P>
   Italian Pantani and Colombian Santiago Botero went down in a
fall less than 3 miles into the 118-mile stage. But that was the
last of Pantani's troubles, as he and Botero made it back to the
pack, and Pantani proceeded to move to the front and lead the group
over the next three climbs.
</P>
<P>
   But as the roads wound north in the Alps and the cyclists hit
the final climb _ the highest category in the tour _ the mountains
started to take their toll.
</P>
<P>
   Pantani dropped back first, and Armstrong tried to keep up with
Virenque and Spaniard Roberto Heras. But he was obviously
struggling as he stood up in his saddle and grimaced. Other riders
went by him, most notably Jan Ullrich, who is in second place
overall.
</P>
<P>
   Heras and Virenque were headed for a neck-and-neck sprint to the
finish until the Spainard made a too-wide turn in the last mile and
crashed into a metal barrier holding the crowd back. While he sat
waiting for the team car to rush him a new bike, Ullrich cruised
into second place behind Virenque.
</P>
<P>
   Ullrich gained a couple minutes on Armstrong but Pantani dropped
more than 20 minutes back, to 14th place overall.
</P>
<P>
   Virenque, 29, has finished on the podium twice, with a third in
1995 and a second in 1997. In addition, he won the red-and-white
polka-dot jersey as best mountain climber five times, including
last year, when he finished eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Virenque fell out of favor with many cyclists two years
ago when the Festina team he was on was expelled because of drug
violations. All of its racers but three _ including Virenque _
admitted to drug use.
</P>
<P>
   But Virenque is undeniably a crowd favorite, as polka-dot signs
proclaiming ``Allez, Richard!'' line the course every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was glad to have good weather,'' said Virenque of the sunny
day with temperatures in the 60s. ``I felt really good on the rest
day Tuesday, and I told my teammates beforehand that I was going to
have a good day. And I could see Armstrong wasn't at his best on
the last descent.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong agreed he had a sluggish day.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, he said, was that he rode past the designated ``feed
zone'' halfway through the race where riders grab sacks of food and
drink, and opted not to take any time to slow down and snack, as
most riders do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't eat enough, and had no energy,'' he said. ``I knew I
was in trouble, so I stayed regular and rode pretty conservatively.
In a situation like that, it's better to not panic and stay in
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just happy to be finished with the Alps.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Tour announced Tuesday that it will cut back on the number
of vehicles it allows on the course in front of the riders. The
number of media, team, sponsor, and publicity cars has been cut
back by several hundred. ``We were going to do it for the 2001 race
anyway,'' said Tour spokeswoman Sophie del Rizzo, who acknowledged
that the move was expedited after last week's accident, in which a
car killed a spectator . . . Tyler Hamilton, of Marblehead, Mass.,
continues to move up in the overall standings. He is now in 28th
place, the highest-ranking American behind Armstrong . . .
Wednesday's stage crosses into Switzerland and finishes in
Lausanne.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
