</P>
<P>
   NET-ENVELOPES _This story takes a look at how the envelope
manufacturing industry, particularly two local companies _ Atlantic
Envelope Co. and World Envelope Manufacturing Inc. _ is responding
to the Internet its impact on their bottom lines since consumers
and businesses are moving toward paperless transactions. While the
need for envelopes won't be going away entirely, manufacturers say
they will have to adapt _ i.e., make the envolpes they produce more
technology inclusive as way of remaining competitive. Even the U.S.
Post Office is jumping on the Internet bandwagon, pushing its own
bill paying service and other web-based initiatives to stave off
possible revunue losses from this medium. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DAYTRADING _ Day trading is still apparently pulling them in in
Atlanta. No stats on trading are available, but six firms are doing
business in the city. The state of Georgia continues its
investigation of the industry, which has been hit with a number of
complaints by the Securities and Exchange Commission and the
regulatory arm of the National Association of Securities Dealers.
(McNaughton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ALSO-RAN _ When you take a new position, it's in your best
interest to know who else wanted the job -- particularly if the
losing candidates are still there, working for you or with you.
We'll explore what you need to find out about who you beat out, and
we'll provide strategies for working with them in the days ahead.
(Mallory, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   UPSAIR _ A subsidiary of UPS is testing a new technology that,
proponents say, can drastically reduce or even eliminate mid-air
and runway collisions. The experimental system known as ADS-B (for
Automatic Dependent Surveillance - Broadcast) also promises to
unclog aerial gridlock by allowing planes to safely fly closer
together and takeoff and land at shorter intervals. UPS will begin
equipping its own planes with ADS-B this year, and others including
FedEx, Airborne and DHL are likely to follow by the end of 2002
when all cargo planes will be required to carry collision avoidance
equipment. (Hirschman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DIGITIAL-MUSIC _ Advance story on digital download conference in
NYC mondy and tuesday. Bottom line: the record companies are still
holding out, but the Internet industry is reading and to go with a
variety of products and services that involve the best of napster
in a format that will generate revenue. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   SYDNEY _Sydney _ In going from Georgia to Australia, then, the
Olympics have gone from one British penal experiment to another.
This odd kinship of outcasts dawned on me as I was sitting at a
cafe beside Sydney Cove, the aquamarine inlet that sets off the
heart of the city like a jade pendant. Ferry boats were churning
through the whitecaps of crisscrossing wakes. On one side of the
cove, the Opera House roof loomed like the upturned prows of a
dozen giant rowboats. On the other side, blue Australian flags
streamed in the breeze atop the long steel arch of the Harbour
Bridge. It's hard to imagine now, but this postcard spot was where
the First Fleet landed in 1788 with a thousand convicts and
sailors. Ten thousand miles from home, they struggled and almost
starved yet somehow managed to transform their bitter exile into a
city and nation that will soon command the world's attention.
(Auchmutey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
