<HEADER>
A5876 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      07-18 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAW SAYS STEEL PLATE IN HAND WON'T SLOW HIM UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ His first contact with Bill Belichick was in 1996,
when he was a carefree kid just trying to get better as a football
player and make it to the Pro Bowl. Having accomplished that,
bigger things began happening to Patriots cornerback Ty Law.
</P>
<P>
   He became a megamillionaire last August when the Patriots opened
the vault and dumped a $14 million signing bonus and $50 million in
salary over seven years on his doorstep. He joined the ranks of
fatherhood this offseason, and proudly displays his little girl,
Tya, who waits for him after a grueling day of practice at training
camp.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other firsts, as well. For the first time in his
career, he suffered a serious injury last season. He broke his hand
Dec. 5 in a victory over the Dallas Cowboys, then played a week in
a cast before being placed on injured reserve, ending his season
for good on Dec. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Law revealed two things Tuesday: He played all of last season
with a fractured toe and he will play this season with screws and a
steel plate in his right hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have to play with a plate and screws all year,''
said Law. ``It's a case of feeling arthritic pain every now and
then, but it's nothing I can't handle. Basically fine. The
flexibility isn't all the way there because I have a plate and
screws in there. But I'm ready to roll in the Ty Law style of
football.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that he established himself as one of the top
cornerbacks in the game two years ago; thus, the huge contract. Law
remains bold, brash, and confident, and his experience will make up
for anything he might have lost as a result of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm 70-75 percent, I feel I'm better than a lot of people
at 100 percent, so I'm not going to go out there and complain about
an injury,'' he said. ``I don't make excuses about anything. It was
just getting out there and playing. It was a little injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of his injuries, Law said, he worked with legendary
track coach Bob Kersee in the offseason but curtailed some things
because he needed to rest his body.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, he's meeting up with Belichick again, but this
time Belichick is head coach, not an assistant. Law thought he knew
Belichick well, and even lobbied for him after Pete Carroll was
fired. But Belichick, like Law, has gone through some changes in
the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was going to be a little more simplified,'' said
Law. ``He sure put in a lot more stuff. It's coming along. I'm
working hard. It's going to take time.''
</P>
<P>
   Law is set at the left corner spot, but since his rookie season,
seven other cornerbacks have played on the opposite side. With
Steve Israel gone to New Orleans via free agency, Law will have an
eighth new man to get used to. Currently the top contender is
former Brown and 49er Antonio Langham, who has been working with
the first unit in practice. What Law does know is that Belichick
will throw everything and the kitchen sink at the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be a little bit of everything,'' said Law. ``He's basic
on first down, and on second and third down we'll have some fun. On
third down we're sending the house, but there'll be someone
blitzing all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Law said Belichick has brought Football 101 to training camp.
Some of the defensive assistants are coaching basic tackling
skills. Six years into his professional career, Law said, that has
been a big adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all professionals now,'' said Law. ``This is my sixth
season and you're showing me tackling drills? It's kind of hard.
You haven't paid that much attention to smaller things, but Coach
Belichick is the type to bring us back down to reality. We're going
out there right now in shoulder pads and we're out there running
and doing drills. He's got a bus for guys who don't make the
conditioning. It's something you desperately need.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you want to tackle Coach Belichick once in a while.
He's changed a lot over the years. With four years gone, he's made
up new defenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Law said he never met anyone who spends more time on the finer
details of the game than Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll show some film, and when he sees a bad play, he'll play
it over and over 20 times until you know what you did wrong,'' said
Law. ``He always makes sure you know you're not too big for your
britches. He's amazing that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watch film, but there comes a time when you have to leave it
alone. It's like studying the playbook. You look at it over and
over and over. I swear he takes it to the toilet with him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots hope he takes it to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the changes, Law feels he has a handle on what Belichick
expects. Learning that will be the toughest thing for players who
aren't used to Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll have to figure it out in a hurry because they'll be on
the next plane home,'' said Law. ``It's all a matter of time. We're
getting better and better. He was upset at first because some guys
were out of shape, but we'll pay for it in the long run because
we'll be out there longer until we get it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Law didn't make the Pro Bowl last year, and he wants to return.
He wants to be part of the best secondary in football, the best
defense on earth, the best team in professional football. He'll
have to do it being a little older, with a little more to care for,
and perhaps in a little more pain.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``These should be the best years of my career
coming up. A lot of us have been together and gone through things
together. Now we'd like to see some good things. That's all we're
thinking about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
