<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5877 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-HEADHUNTER19-COX     07-18 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEADHUNTER19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shareholders to consider Headhunter's acquisition of
CareerMosaic
 &HT;    By Kathy Brister
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Shareholders of Headhunter.net will decide today on a
deal likely to put the company at No. 2 in the national online job
market.
</P>
<P>
   The approval of Headhunter's purchase of Palo Alto, Calif.,
competitor CareerMosaic, would position the Norcross company behind
online job site, Monster.com, according to industry estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholder balloting comes a day after Headhunter.net Inc.
reported second-quarter revenues six times greater than the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the acquisition, announced in April, Headhunter
will pay $110 million in stock for CareerMosaic, owned by New
York-based advertising giant Omnicom. Headquarters of the merged
company will remain in Norcross.
</P>
<P>
   Headhunter's purchase of CareerMosaic would add more than
100,000 resumes to its bank of about 548,000. It also would add
CareerMosaic's Fortune 100 customer base to the 8,000 firms _
primarily mid- to small-size companies _ that now pay to post jobs
on Headhunter's site.
</P>
<P>
   And Headhunter would gain access to about $5 million in cash and
a $10 million line of credit now held by CareerMosaic. That's
important to the company, which last quarter added 27 sales people
in an effort to ramp up sales and marketing. It now employs about
300 nationwide, including about 150 in Atlanta, and will gain
another 50 workers through the CareerMosaic deal.
</P>
<P>
   But Headhunter's access to capital also is important to Wall
Street, said Robert Fontana, an analyst with Wachovia Securities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The investment community is concerned about Internet companies
burning lots of cash,'' he said, noting by his estimates Headhunter
now has enough money to fuel its growth until third quarter 2001.
At that time, Fontana estimates, Headhunter should begin operating
in the black.
</P>
<P>
   In earnings released Tuesday, Headhunter reported a net loss of
$4.17 million on revenues of $9.8 million in the second quarter,
ended June 30. In second quarter 1999, the company reported a loss
of $2.6 million on revenues of $1.6 million. Per-share loss for the
second quarter of 2000 was 38 cents, compared to a loss of $1.17
per share in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Fontana said Headhunter's quarterly report beat all of
Wachovia's estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Headhunter Chief Executive Officer Bob Montgomery said merging
with CareerMosaic is likely to add to the bottom line because the
companies attracted different corporate clients and different
job-seekers. He estimates there is only a 10 to 12 percent overlap
in resumes posted on the two companies' sites.
</P>
<P>
   Headhunter's shareholder vote comes during a week marked by
consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Knight Ridder Inc. and Tribune Co. said they will buy
online job sites CareerBuilder Inc. and CareerPath.com Inc. The
purchase would link the Internet companies with 45 local daily and
national newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue for online job sites is expected to grow from $1.2
billion to $8.2 billion in the next five years, according to
Forrester Research, a Cambridge, Mass., technology research firm.
</P>
<P>
   This week's online job site consolidations mirror what's
happening across the entire e-commerce marketplace, said Ellen
Julian, an analyst with Framington, Mass., technology-research firm
IDC.
</P>
<P>
   The mergers will cause a ``reshuffle in the leadership grid,''
leaving top players in good positions as both job-seekers and
companies narrow their online career site choices to those with the
highest numbers of job postings, resumes and site visits, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
