<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SENATE KILLS PATENT EXTENSION FOR COLUMBIA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate on Tuesday killed a proposal that would
have extended a lucrative biotechnology patent for Columbia
University after critics complained that it was ``a
special-interest giveaway.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., who led the fight against the
patent extension, said it would have raised prescription drug
prices for people with debilitating diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Senate leaders stripped the measure from the pending must-pass
agriculture appropriations bill, according to Ed Amorosi, a
spokesman for Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., who had sponsored the patent
proposal. The leaders concluded that the controversial measure
would slow Senate consideration of the appropriations measure.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed patent extension could have enabled Columbia _
Gregg's alma mater _ to net $70 million to $150 million over the
next 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia's 17-year-long patent covering a key manufacturing
process for specific proteins in new drugs expires Aug. 15. The
process has been used to make 14 widely sold drugs and has netted
the university $280 million from biotech companies that manufacture
the drugs. The companies have paid a 1 percent royalty annually.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg said his amendment would grant Columbia and other
nonprofit research institutions the same right that drug companies
have to ask the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office for patent
extensions to compensate for delays in initial approval by the Food
and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Under existing law, Columbia wasn't able to apply for an
extension because its patent was for a process, not an FDA-approved
drug. University officials argued the school was entitled to an
extension because Columbia received no royalties for five years
while drug companies licensed to use its patent awaited FDA
approval for specific drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg said it is only fair that the law allow inventors of
processes to apply for patent extensions just like inventors of
drugs. He also argued that Columbia's research would benefit
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a university that uses the money for research, does not
generate profits and which allows anybody to use the process,''
Gregg said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., has also fought for
Columbia's patent extension and said he doesn't want research to
dry up at a premier institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great research institution,'' Moynihan said. ``(The
patent) would be legitimately extended for just a little while and
all the money goes to research.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics including Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., said it
would ``impose unacceptable increases in the price of prescription
drugs'' by delaying the sale of cheaper generic versions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unfair and unjust enrichment,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a special-interest giveaway.''
</P>
<P>
   Durbin has slammed Columbia's efforts to get a patent extension,
calling it the ``greening of the ivory tower.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People are shedding crocodile tears about the high cost of
prescription drugs and they're turning around and trying to give a
windfall to Columbia University,'' Durbin said.
</P>
<P>
   Durbin said an extension for Columbia would raise prices for
people with serious diseases such as breast cancer, multiple
sclerosis, heart and stroke problems and hemophilia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't how we should fund universities,'' said Sen. Jim M.
Jeffords, R-Vt.
</P>
<P>
   Other congressional efforts to extend patents for pharmaceutical
companies also appear dead this year.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin G. Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the Senate Judiciary
Chairman, was caught in a firestorm of criticism last month when
his staff floated legislation that would have allowed
Schering-Plough Corp. to seek a three-year extension of its patent
for Claritin through the Federal Court of Claims.
</P>
<P>
   The measure provoked outrage from consumer groups because it
would have automatically granted the patent extension while the
court considered it, which could take months or years.
</P>
<P>
   But Hatch now says he has ``no plans'' to slip the
Schering-Plough proposal through on a spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said all the major drug companies have come looking for
patent extensions to compensate for excessive time lost during
regulatory review at the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they can make a case for expanded patent life,'' Hatch
said. ``They deserve to make a case.''
</P>
<P>
   For four years Schering-Plough has sought legislation that would
allow it to seek a three-year extension of its patent. Supporters
have tried to add it to one of the must-pass spending bills, but
have backed off under criticism that it could cost consumers up to
$7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of like Dracula,'' said Sen. Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt.
``Every time I think it's dead, someone trips over the coffin and
it pops up again. But I have a lot of stakes. I'll kill this. I
think we start a terrible precedent if we start doing patent
extensions on appropriations bills.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL; (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address judy(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
