<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHOLESTEROL-YOUNG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY BACKS EARLIER CHOLESTEROL TESTING IN MEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Men should begin taking aggressive steps as early as their 20s
to reduce high cholesterol levels and thereby lower their risk of
fatal heart disease, according to new information from studies of
81,000 young men who were followed for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, concern about elevated cholesterol has been focused
mainly on middle-aged people since increasing age raises their
heart disease risk. Only a few small studies previously linked high
cholesterol early in life to heart disease later on.
</P>
<P>
   But now, researchers at the Northwestern University School of
Medicine in Chicago, analyzing three large studies, report that
relatively young men with high cholesterol (240 milligrams per
deciliter or above) were 2 to 3 1/2 times more likely to die from
heart disease than those whose levels were below 200.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, cholesterol levels ``are an important risk factor
throughout life'' and should be reduced in people as young as 20,
said Dr. Jeremiah Stamler, a preventive medicine specialist at
Northwestern's medical school.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he said, abnormally high cholesterol in young men
actually increased their risk of heart disease more sharply than it
did in middle-aged men.
</P>
<P>
   The effect was so marked that, in the studies, men with
cholesterol levels below 200 lived 4 to 9 years longer than those
whose levels exceeded 240.
</P>
<P>
   The data showed that 2/3 of the heart deaths among those in the
study occurred in the 1/3 of the men who had high cholesterol when
they were young adults, said Stamler, lead author of the report in
the current issue of the Journal of the American Medical Society.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important paper because it provides strong evidence
for the value of early detection'' of high cholesterol, said Dr.
Sidney Smith, former president of the American Heart Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are understandable concerns about about the cost of
screening young individuals, and (questions about) the benefits of
treating a younger population,'' added Smith, chief of cardiology
at the University of North Carolina. The new report, he said,
``suggests the benefits will be there.''
</P>
<P>
   The report is based on analyzing three long-term studies in
which younger men were followed for as long as 34 years. One
included 11,017 men in 84 Chicago companies; the second involved
1,609 men employed by the Peoples Gas Company; the third comprised
69,025 men from the multicenter MRFIT (Multiple Risk Factor
Intervention Trial) study.
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial accompanying the JAMA report, Dr. Scott Grundy
of the Univeristy fo Texas Southwestern Medical Center at Dallas
noted that the new findings reinforce earlier suggestions that
cholesterol-lowering should begin earlier in life.
</P>
<P>
   It is, he said, ``a necessary first step in the effort to reduce
the risk of (coronary heart disease) in the one-third of young
adults who have total cholesterol levels higher than 200''
milliliters per deciliter.
</P>
<P>
   The American Heart Association already recommends that
cholesterol readings be made every five years beginning at age 20,
Nevertheless, Grundy said, the opportunity to get such early
screening is often missed because busy doctors can't take time to
counsel young, healthy patients about reducing their cholesterol,
which can be done through diet modification and also by taking
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In truth, financial incentives are few and, in general,
long-term prevention is not attractive to managed care,'' wrote
Grundy.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter Libby, chief of cardiovascular medicine at Brigham and
Women's Hospital, said the study reinforces the potential value of
a ``more aggressive stance'' in attacking high cholesterol
relatively early in life.
</P>
<P>
   He echoed Grundy's concern about too little emphasis on
prevention in the health care system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prevention is under-rewarded,'' he said. ``HMO's have little
incentive to prevent illnesses that may occur in a 10 to 20 year
span, when the average length of time a member is with a health
care plan is under five years.''
</P>
<P>
   At Harvard Pilgrim Health Care, Massachusetts' largest HMO,
cholesterol screening is done according to guidelines based on
recommendations by the Heart Association and other groups, said Dr.
Roberta Herman, medical director for clinical policy and programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our current recommendation is that screening begin at age 20
or the first appropriate opportunity,'' said Herman. As for
treatment, she said, HMO officials assume that ``the provider and
the member are going to work together to determine what makes
sense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
