<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5895 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f BC-STATES-BONIOR-NAT     07-18 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-BONIOR-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;   &QL;  &UR; Bonior At the Ready If Gephardt Runs With Gore &QL;   &UR; By Laura J.
Winter &QL;  &QC;  C. 2000 States News Service &QL;  &QC;  WASHINGTON (July 18) -
Heading off party dissent, Minority Whip Rep. David Bonior, D-Mt.
Clemens, is making it clear that if the Democratic Minority Leader
seeks to run as the party's vice presidential nominee, he would be
prepared to take over his party's top House leadership role.
</P>
<P>
   Reports that Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., might be asked to run
alongside Democratic presidential nominee Al Gore, prompted Bonior
and his staff to start Friday laying claim to the House party helm.
While Gephardt said Tuesday he is not seeking the vice presidency,
he did not say he would turn down the job if asked.
</P>
<P>
   Bonior's press secretary Fred Clark said calls made over the
weekend to Sunday television talk show bookers and pundits was an
effort to send a message: The Democrats will have a leadership
structure in place well before November's general election no
matter who turns out to be Gore's running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot a lot of speculation over the past few days.
As to whether Mr. Gephardt was being courted for V.P.,'' Clark
said. ``We don't know what he is going to do, but we have to
prepare for any contingency and plan for a seamless transition.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonior, however, was not available for comment. And his press
secretary steadfastly refuted any charge that the move was purely
an ambitious one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not want there to be a story out there that there would
be a leadership vacuum,'' Clark said. ``The goal is to make it
clear that we are all working together to take back the house. That
there is no tension between leaders and both of them are focussed
on taking back the house in November.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonior has been speaking with Democratic House leaders on how
best to fill leadership roles in case Gephardt had to take up other
duties, Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Once it became known that Gephardt and Gore held a secret
meeting earlier this month, speculation that the St. Louis
representative might accept a the vice presidential role began to
build. While Gephardt continued to say his focus remains on
retaking the house, there are those on Capitol Hill that say he
might just go for it, if asked.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to firmly state firmly that he would not be Gore's running
mate, Gephardt said, ``I am for Al Gore. You know that. I have
supported him from the beginning of his campaign almost, and I
think he would make a great president of this country and I hope he
wins,'' Gephardt said. ``As you know I have been very focussed on
one thing and that's winning back the majority in the House.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., has also been touted as a possible Gore
running mate. Gore is expected to announce his vice presidential
choice on August 3, the last day of the Republican National
Convention, in Philadelphia. The Democratic National Convention
will take place in Los Angeles starting August 14.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to Democrats who do not see eye-to-eye with
minority whip, said Bonior would be the most obvious choice to at
least temporarily succeed Gephardt if the need arose. The caucus,
in any event, will hold an election in January to choose its
leaders for the new Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Democrats, while adhering to the party platform, do
not have Bonior's affection for labor unions, many voting in favor
of Permanent Normal Trade Relations with China - a legislative
battle Bonior lost.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1910EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
