u i BC-IRELAND-WEST-DEVELOP-     07-18 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-WEST-DEVELOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSALS FOR DEVELOPING THE WEST OF IRELAND INCLUDE A NEW CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  By DAN BARRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KILMOVEE, Ireland _ The exact downtown location of the new city
he is proposing for this country's isolated West must remain vague,
William Thomas said, for fear of speculators. To provide a rough
idea, though, he mounted a stone wall and swept his hand in the
general direction of a curious cow and the hoof-pocked pastures
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Other details are more specific, at least on paper. The
metropolis that would rise from undesirable farmland in counties
Mayo and Roscommon would include an initial population of 100,000,
apartment complexes designed for ``maximum tranquillity,'' the
finest in hospitals and schools, and even an ice rink designed for
international competition. As for its name, Thomas said he prefers
``The City of the Sacred Heart,'' for the inspiration he receives
from his Roman Catholic faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be seen as an option right now, but it will become a
necessity,'' said Thomas of his proposal. He is a defense
consultant to the Irish and other governments, who added that he
also ``invents things.''
</P>
<P>
   For all its fantastic elements, Thomas' idea has spurred
national debate, and is being embraced by a bishop and other local
leaders. They say that poor roadways and the medieval makeup of
towns have largely prevented the western counties from enjoying the
economic boom that has Dublin, to the east, bursting in population
and prosperity. The region's only recourse, they say, may be to
start from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of a new city also taps into the West's long-held
belief that it is an Irish afterthought, a place whose greatest
export seems to be young adults forced to pursue careers elsewhere.
Every Friday night, buses return to the struggling town of
Ballaghaderreen, jammed with people who have spent the week working
in Dublin, more than three hours away.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Thomas has impeccable timing. As he promotes
his emerald city, a team of government planners is toiling away in
the Custom House in Dublin, tinkering with maps of Ireland. Their
two-year assignment: to develop a ``national spatial strategy'' to
spread the country's resources and opportunities more evenly.
</P>
<P>
   That quest is part of Ireland's plan for its future, a plan that
focuses in large part on how to spend nearly $60 billion in
development funds, some of which comes from the European Union. The
objectives are to ensure economic stability, promote education and
to share the wealth enjoyed in the eastern and southern regions of
the country with the West, the Midlands, and the counties bordering
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The greater Dublin area now accounts for about 40 percent of
Ireland's population of 3.6 million. International investment and a
plethora of high-technology jobs have sent housing prices soaring,
clogged its narrow roads and drained other regions of their
educated young. Meanwhile, the agricultural industry that
traditionally sustained the west is on the wane.
</P>
<P>
   Finian Matthews, the director of the unit working on the spatial
strategy, said these were the reasons the ``the government is eager
to create more parity and economic opportunity regardless of where
people live.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, Matthews and his team are working to identify a
few ``gatewaycommunities'' that would become regional hubs through
the investment of billions of dollars. In theory, these centers
would ease Dublin's troubles and revitalize the country's aged
towns and villages. Country roads would become highway links
between hubs; a student in remote Connemara would have the same
opportunities as one in fashionable Ballsbridge, in Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   News of the spatial strategy and the loads of money attached to
it have stoked territorial pride. Larger towns, like Sligo in
County Sligo and Athlone in County West Meath, are presenting
themselves as obvious gateways. But Matthews said no decisions had
been made; his team is still studying statistics, consulting
experts, and reconfiguring maps that he declined, for obvious
reasons, to share.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, Matthews has received a copy of Thomas' proposal, which
prominently describes itself as ``real and magnificent, and if
successful would change the way the Irish think about themselves,
forever.'' The planner recently thumbed through the proposal _ with
its drawings of wide boulevards and suggestions for a chapel in
every home _ with an expression that was somewhere between a
grimace and a grin.
</P>
<P>
   Early research suggests that the investments would best be spent
on existing towns, Matthews said diplomatically, although he added,
``We're not ruling in or out any option.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas' idea has prompted debate and reflection in the West,
where there is an average of about 20 people to each square
kilometer (0.62 mile), compared with 1,147 for each square
kilometer in Dublin. Scarred and emptied by the famine 150 years
ago, the West continues to lose its young people, and with them its
stories and its vibrancy. Only Galway, the region's one city, seems
on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Harkin, chairwoman of a nonprofit organization called the
Council for the West, said that ``using urban solutions for rural
problems is not the way to go.'' And Sheila Caulfield, a
spokeswoman for the Western Development Commission, a public agency
that aims to foster growth in the West, said that while the
commission emphasized the need to invest in small towns, the
concerns of Thomas were well-founded.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Flynn, the bishop for the Roman Catholic Diocese of
Achonry, which includes the proposed site, enthusiastically
supports the plan. Sitting in a spare and hushed office in
Ballaghaderreen, Flynn acknowledged that the idea ``does call for a
way of thinking that we haven't been accustomed to.'' But, he
added, ``I think it's salable.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, a stout man with an intense gaze, said that he chose the
30-square-mile site after considering several factors, including
the close proximity of Knock International Airport and the recent
discovery of gas fields off the coast of County Mayo. He said he
has no idea who owns the land, although he thinks the government
lays claim to a good chunk of it.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he had no intention of benefiting financially from
his idea. He is content, he said, to continue living in his small
farmhouse on the outskirts of Galway, where he writes books on
Catholicism and keeps a collection of exotic birds. ``I'm just
offering the idea to the nation,'' he said. ``More than that I
cannot do.''
</P>
<P>
   As he toured the site the other day, Thomas paused at the ruins
of Urlar Abbey, a national landmark that sits within the boundaries
of his would-be city. Studying its haunting beauty, he vowed to
keep it intact.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
