<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5904 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JAMES-DEAN-FILM-NYT &LR;      07-18 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAMES-DEAN-FILM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBEL WITHOUT A FILM BIOGRAPHY ... UNTIL NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD, July 19 _ The death of James Dean in a car crash in
1955 turned that brooding 24-year-old movie star into a tragic
legend and symbol of alienation and hurt among teen-agers in the
1950s and 1960s. But while other icons of the era, like Elvis
Presley and Marilyn Monroe, have been grist for a steady stream of
novels, biographies and movies, Dean has, surprisingly, been
somewhat ignored, especially in films. It's not for a lack of
trying.
</P>
<P>
   For years filmmakers have toyed with projects about James Dean
but were locked in a Catch-22: studios would only finance the movie
with a star, or at least a name actor. But these actors shied away
from playing the 1950s icon.
</P>
<P>
   The playwright Israel Horovitz, who had worked on a James Dean
screenplay for years, recalled that the actor Ethan Hawke had told
him: ``If you do a James Dean imitation, they'll kill you. If you
don't do a James Dean imitation, they'll kill you. There's no way I
can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   It is, however, being done, with Horovitz's script, for the TNT
network. The film, ``James Dean: An Invented Life,'' is now in
production in Los Angeles. It will be shown next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``His legend has not been treated with appropriate respect,''
said Mark Rydell, 70, the film's director, whose credits include
``The Rose'' and ``On Golden Pond'' and who was a friend of Dean's
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   To play Dean, Rydell and Bill Gerber, the movie's executive
producer, selected James Franco, a little-known, 22-year-old
television actor from Palo Alto, Calif. More than 500 actors
auditioned for the part, sent tapes or were interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Rydell said he had cast Franco almost as soon as he saw the
actor, who bears a resemblance to Dean, and spoke to him at length.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met Mark Rydell, and he was like an analyst,'' Franco said.
``We were talking a long time about personal stuff: my parents and
issues I had with them and the trouble I had gotten into as a
teen-ager and why I became an actor. I read very easily, and there
was no pressure to give a kind of final performance. Afterwards he
gave me a hug and told me I had it. I was amazed.''
</P>
<P>
   Franco, who has appeared in some television films and
independent features as well as the NBC series ``Freaks and
Geeks,'' said that during his teen-age years he was often told that
he looked like Dean. ``I don't have blond hair and blue eyes, like
he did,'' said Franco. ``But they took care of that. I got
contacts, and they dyed my hair.''
</P>
<P>
   To put himself in the role, Franco told his girlfriend he was
not going to see her while making the movie and informed his
parents he would not be speaking to them. ``I took up smoking, like
Dean, and cut off most of my friends,'' he said. ``I'm doing
everything I can to approximate his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Dean's life was tormented. Horovitz and Rydell said that Dean's
three films, ``Rebel Without a Cause,'' ``East of Eden'' and
``Giant,'' were stamped by his playing characters who were, like
him, anguished, angry and lonely. Horovitz said the screenplay was,
largely, a story about Dean's hunt for a father who abandoned him
when he was 8 his mother died. ``Dean's father was a dental
technician who worked at a VA hospital in Santa Monica,'' said
Horovitz, ``and when the boy's mother died of cancer, the father
shipped the body back on a train to Fairmount, Ind., with the boy
to live with his aunt and uncle. He chased his father's affection
through his young life.''
</P>
<P>
   Years later Dean turned to directors like Elia Kazan, George
Stevens and Nicholas Ray and even executives like Jack Warner as
father figures. Just before his death Dean signed what was then an
unprecedented $1-million deal with Warner for nine films. ``He
spent his life trying to prove to his father that he wasn't
worthless,'' Rydell said.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Dean's personality and the characters he played on
screen seemed to foreshadow some of the mood of the 1960s and '70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``He appealed to the young because he understood that youth knew
some truths about the world that adults had looked away from: about
the unfriendly cities, the instinct for violence and forsaken
emotional sensibility,'' wrote David Thomson in A Biographical
Dictionary of Film (Knopf). ``Although he was vulnerable and
sensitive, he never suggested youthfulness or callowness. On the
contrary, he seemed older, sadder and more experienced than the
adults in his films.''
</P>
<P>
   Rydell put it another way: ``He was indeed the first rebel.''
Referring to ``Rebel Without a Cause,'' he declared, ``The film _
and Dean _ demonstrated that adolescents are loaded with anxiety
and torture and rage.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dean screenplay had been circulating at Warner Brothers for
nearly a decade under the aegis of Marvin Worth, producer of
``Lenny'' (1974) and ``The Rose'' (1979). Worth, who died in 1998,
came close to making the film in 1994 with Leonardo DiCaprio and
Michael Mann as director. But Mann, director of ``Heat'' and ``The
Insider,'' said that DiCaprio seemed too young at the time and
wanted to wait for a year or so.
</P>
<P>
   By that time they had each moved on to other projects. Other
directors like Des McAnuff and Marc Rocco, and actors like Stephen
Dorff got involved to one degree or another in the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing much happened,'' recalled Gerber, formerly a top
Warner executive. ``It just kind of hung around. It was just hard
to find bankable names that Warner Brothers would finance a $20
million movie with. And there were marketing problems. He died in a
highway accident in 1955. He isn't that well known by the
moviegoing public these days.''
</P>
<P>
   The project would probably have died with Worth, but Gerber
suggested it as a movie for cable television, where inclusion of a
big name star is not as important as it is for theatrical release.
TNT, owned by Time Warner Inc., is seen in about 77.5 million
homes. Julie Weitz, TNT's executive vice president of original
programming, said the story carried a certain resonance for
television viewers, especially those in their 30s and 40s.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's as hip and relatable today as he was years ago,'' said
Weitz. ``At the core of this story is a movie about a child, and he
stays a child. And that's timeless.''
</P>
<P>
   Rydell said he was friendly with Dean in the '50s when they were
struggling theater and television actors. ``He was a remarkably
charming and quirky and unpredictable fellow,'' said Rydell. ``We
were walking down Madison Avenue one Sunday after doing `Omnibus'
on CBS. He was talking to me about bullfighting, which was a
passion of his. A bus was hurtling down Madison, passing many stops
because it was so quiet. And suddenly Jimmy leapt into the street,
whipped his jacket off and did a bullfighter's pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bus literally grazed his shirt. I was horrified. He
giggled. I thought this kid would never live because he was so
reckless. And what happened a few years later was tragic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1915EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5905 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FRANCE-OPERA-FESTIVAL     07-18 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-OPERA-FESTIVAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RATING AN OPERA FESTIVAL, BY ITS CACHET AND ITS TRAVELS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN RIDING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AIX-EN-PROVENCE, France _ Europe's summer opera festivals are
often judged by the cachet of those they attract, not only the
artistic renown of the conductors, directors and performers but
also the social standing of the audiences. But there is another
less obvious gauge: which festivals stay alive during their long
off-seasons by taking their productions to other cities, perhaps
even to other festivals.
</P>
<P>
   By both measures, things have been going well for the
international opera festival of Aix-en-Provence since a management
shake-up in 1998. This year's festival, which runs through July 28,
includes four new productions and a repeat from 1999, all presented
by big-name conductors and directors, while its sold-out houses
visibly sparkle with European elites. At the same time, opera
lovers who cannot make it here are increasingly able to catch its
shows elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to make the festival known around the world,''
explained Stephane Lissner, who took over as director of the
festival three years ago with precisely that mandate. ``Many of our
productions are in demand even before they are created. What makes
Aix different, though, is that we concentrate on young singers, and
the tours give them the chance to be seen and heard by directors,
critics and audiences in other cities.''
</P>
<P>
   After Lissner's first season three productions _ Mozart's ``Don
Giovanni,'' Purcell's ``Dido and Aeneas'' and Britten's ``Curlew
River'' _ traveled widely around Western Europe. Last year it was
the turn of Mozart's ``Zauberfloete'' to tour European cities,
while Aix's version of Monteverdi's ``Coronazione di Poppea'' was
seen in Vienna (and returned here this year) and its production of
Offenbach's ``Belle Helene'' will be performed next month at the
Salzburg Festival.
</P>
<P>
   This year's productions will also carry the Aix brand name to
new arenas. Janacek's ``Makropulos Case'' is scheduled for the
Theatre de la Monnaie in Brussels this fall and may be seen in
Paris and Vienna, too. Monteverdi's ``Ritorno d'Ulisse in Patria''
and Rossini's ``Cenerentola'' will have long European tours, and
Mozart's ``Cosi Fan Tutte'' will travel to the Theatre des
Champs-Elysees in Paris in October and probably to the Lincoln
Center Festival next summer.
</P>
<P>
   Of course some features of the Aix festival remain very much
rooted in this medieval Provencal town. The European Music Academy,
created by Lissner in 1998, brings together 100 or so young singers
and instrumentalists for two months of workshops, concerts and new
opera productions (this year, ``La Cenerentola'').
</P>
<P>
   At the same time this summer's parallel program of concerts has
attracted star conductors like Pierre Boulez, Sir Simon Rattle and
William Christie as well as the rising British conductor Daniel
Harding.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is the opera program that generally stirs the most
interest, with particular attention given this year to the new
production of ``Cosi Fan Tutte,'' the first Western opera to be
tackled by Chen Shi-Zheng, the New York-based Chinese director who
took the epic Chinese opera ``The Peony Pavilion'' to last year's
Lincoln Center Festival. The production was accompanied by the
Concerto Koeln, conducted by the Belgian baroque specialist Rene
Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Cosi' is staged so often that my worry was, could I do
something different?'' Chen said after the premiere. ``I didn't
want to go through the psychoanalytical approach of Western
theater. I wanted to challenge what Western audiences think the
opera is about by playing it in a different environment. I didn't
want to make a moral statement about infidelity, but to entertain,
so it plays out like a children's game, a sort of teen-age opera.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen creates an Asian mood through Peter Pabst's set, with its
willow tree and lilies floating in pools of water, and the
kimonolike costumes for Fiordiligi (sung here by Alexandra
Deshorties) and Dorabella (Liliana Nikiteanu). Yet it is the
mischievous humor of the production that provides its appeal, with
Guglielmo (Stephan Genz) and Ferrando (Jeremy Ovenden) joking and
teasing as they test the flightiness of Fiordiligi and Dorabella
under the lighthearted guidance of Don Alfonso (Pietro Spagnoli).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Makropulos Case,'' on the other hand, is a far more somber
affair in Aix's new production by the talented young French
director Stephane Braunschweig, with Sir Simon Rattle conducting
the City of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra. This opera, which tells
the story of a century-old dispute between two Czech families,
revolves around the mysteriously old Emilia Marty. And with the
veteran German soprano Anja Silja returning to the role that she
first sang in 1972, the high drama of the story was more than
assured.
</P>
<P>
   Le Monde's music critic, Alain Lompech, went out of his way to
praise Silja's majestic domination of the stage, which, he said,
more than compensated for occasional signs of age in her voice. But
he insisted that the entire cast as well as director, designer and
conductor were ``touched by grace'' in this production. ``One
emerges from this performance not just moved,'' he added, ``but
shaken by some unforgettable scenes in which it is impossible to
separate seeing from hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cosi Fan Tutte'' and ``The Makropulos Case'' were staged in
the courtyard of the old Archbishop's Palace in Aix, and ``La
Cenerentola'' was performed outdoors in the Domaine du Grand
St.-Jean, an 18th-century chateau six miles from here that was
added to the festival's venues last year. And ``Il Ritorno d'Ulisse
in Patria'' seemed like the perfect opera for the 485-seat Theatre
du Jeu-de-Paume, an 18th-century jewel that has just had a $5
million restoration.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Noble, who heads the Royal Shakespeare Company, directed
the opera with a simplicity that well suited the intimacy of the
theater, while the Orchestre Les Arts Florissants, using period
instruments, was conducted by its founder, Christie. ``Noble has
created a spectacle of unusual depth with almost nothing,'' Renaud
Machart, another Le Monde critic, noted of the minimalist decor. At
the same time the youthful energy of the singers, notably Kresimir
Spicer as Ulisse and Marijana Mijanovic as his loyal wife,
Penelope, brought lightness to what is, after all, a long opera.
</P>
<P>
   The festival has now presented Monteverdi's three surviving
operas in successive years. But with Mozart, around whom this
festival was founded in 1948, there is of course much more to do.
Next year ``The Marriage of Figaro'' will be directed by Sir
Richard Eyre, the former head of Britain's National Theater, with
the Mahler Chamber Orchestra conducted by Marc Minkowski.
</P>
<P>
   But the 20th century will not be overlooked. In a production
directed by Luc Bondy and conducted by Harding, Britten's ``Turn of
the Screw'' will be presented in the Jeu-de-Paume.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
