u e BC-KAISER-KENNEDY-CENTER     07-18 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KAISER-KENNEDY-CENTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COVENT GARDEN CHIEF TO LEAD KENNEDY CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
   By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Michael Kaiser, the New York theater and ballet
manager who helped rescue Royal Opera House at Covent Garden in
London from a financial crisis, is about to be named president of
the Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts, a Kennedy Center
official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser, who announced last month that he was returning to the
United States, said then that he would leave Covent Garden at the
end of the 2000-01 season, but the Kennedy Center official said
Tuesday that Kaiser was scheduled to start his duties here on Feb.
1, well before the end of next season.
</P>
<P>
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said that the
appointment is to be announced formally on Wednesday after the
center's board formally votes its approval and that Kaiser would
not be available for comment until then.
</P>
<P>
   As chief executive at at Covent Garden, Kaiser virtually
eliminated the budget deficit and created a permanent endowment.
When he announced his resignation he said the decision to quit was
``the most profoundly difficult'' of his career, adding, ``But for
personal reasons it is time for me to return to my home.'' After
hearing of Kaiser's decision, Sir Colin Southgate, the Royal Opera
House's board chairman, said, ``We owe him a huge debt of
gratitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser will succeed Lawrence J. Wilker, who announced in April
that he would leave his post at the end of the year and, following
the path of many other executives these days, would join a new
Internet venture.
</P>
<P>
   Wilker's announcement came a week after Nathan Leventhal said he
would leave his job as president of Lincoln Center. That created
the unusual circumstance of the nation's two leading performing
arts centers recruiting chief operating officers at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser, the official said, told the search committee, ``I was
the world's worst board member because I was meddling all the time,
and that's when I realized it was what I wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   After he realized that he wanted to make arts administration his
career, Kaiser sold his business consulting firm and, the Kennedy
Center official said, ``started cold at the Kansas City Ballet and
worked his way up.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser was also executive director at the Alvin Ailey American
Dance Theater and American Ballet Theater, helping restore those
companies to financial health.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser, 47, told the search committee that he was a lover of the
performing arts who was raised in a performing arts family. His
grandfather was a violinist with the New York Philharmonic, and one
of his earliest memories is of spending every Saturday at the
orchestra's rehearsals.
</P>
<P>
   The presidency of the Kennedy Center is the No. 2 post, behind
the chairmanship, which puts Kaiser in day-to-day charge of the
center's operations and performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a demanding job, with 3,300 performances a year,'' said
James A. Johnson, chairman of the Kennedy Center, when Wilker's
resignation was announced. ``There are six or seven stages
operating in an evening when everything is full.''
</P>
<P>
   Leventhal's salary at Lincoln Center was $525,000 a year and
Wilker's at the Kennedy Center was $325,000. The Kennedy Center
official said that Kaiser's salary was still being discussed and
that it would be competitive with similar positions in the
performing arts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
