<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5907 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-TASTINGS-NYT &LR;      07-18 0319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAUJOLAIS, ALWAYS FRIENDLY AND READY TO PLEASE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A good bottle of Beaujolais, fruity and undemanding, bypasses
the analytical portion of the brain and heads directly to the
pleasure center. This wine is versatile with food and
thirst-quenching _ gulpable, as they say.
</P>
<P>
   Though Beaujolais enjoys its moment in the spotlight every
November, when the newly bottled nouveaus are shipped, it is, in
fact, a perfect hot-weather red.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for that is that Beaujolais tastes great lightly
chilled, about half an hour in the refrigerator before serving. And
it goes with almost anything, from burgers to fried chicken to
Indian takeout food.
</P>
<P>
   But the best thing about Beaujolais is its easy, open nature. If
Burgundy is a mysterious, inscrutable cat of a wine and Bordeaux a
beautiful thoroughbred, Beaujolais is simply a good pooch, young,
frisky and eager to please.
</P>
<P>
   Of the many breeds of Beaujolais, Georges Duboeuf is the best
known and most popular. Most Duboeuf wines are light, fruity and
stylistically consistent, though I found his 1998 Julienas to have
more depth than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Jadot, a big name in Burgundy and Beaujolais, makes wines
more muted than Duboeuf's but no less pleasing.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller producers are more idiosyncratic, a little more
expensive, but can be more exciting, making handcrafted wines that
add texture and richness without compromising the basic Beaujolais
likability.
</P>
<P>
   Clos de la Roilette from Coudert, for example, is a wine that
you may not find on every corner but rewards the hunt. The Granger,
Bertolla and Michaud, too, are worth seeking out.
</P>
<P>
   Even though these wines have more dimensions to them, they are
still light in spirit, joyous rather than weighty. You wouldn't
retire to the library to drink Beaujolais. It's for the kitchen
table, and certainly for outdoors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1923EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
