<HEADER>
A5910 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-NYT &LR;      07-18 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE PROPOSES AMENDING CONSTITUTION TO GUARANTEE VICTIMS' RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS, Tenn. _ Jodie Gaines Johnson was kidnapped, held
captive for five days without water or food and raped repeatedly by
three men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know the criminal system, I was just thrown in
there,'' Johnson said of the process that led to her captors'
conviction. ``And my perpetrators are now starting to be paroled. I
want to know when they're paroled. I have four kids, and I don't
want to be in the grocery store and run into them. I'm not that
strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was one of more than a dozen victims, relatives of
victims and law enforcement officers who told their stories Tuesday
to Vice President Al Gore as he sought to highlight a package on
crime prevention that he is proposing in his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   One key proposal is a constitutional amendment _ similar to one
that the Clinton administration opposed _ that would guarantee
victims like Johnson certain rights, among them the right to be
notified of a perpetrator's release and the right to have their own
safety considered in determining any conditional release.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Gore's proposal would give victims the right to be
heard at sentencing, the right to be included in any public
proceedings related to the crime, the right to restitution from a
convicted offender and the right to a trial without unreasonable
delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The accused criminals have all kinds of rights, and we all
understand why that is important,'' Gore said. ``But here is the
point: When those rights are enshrined in the Constitution and the
rights of victims are not, whenever the two come into any kind of a
conflict, it is not even a close contest. The victims are put in
the back seat and sometimes even ignored.''
</P>
<P>
   The amendment is part of a victim's bill of rights that Gore
proposed Tuesday. It would allow victims to leave work to attend
legal proceedings, much the way jurors are excused from work. Gore
said his measure would cost $685 million over 10 years and would be
paid for with money from the projected budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed amendment is based on legislation that the
administration had worked to defeat, in part because officials were
concerned that excessive victims' rights might interfere with fair
trials.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., who, with Sen. Dianne Feinstein,
D-Calif., has sponsored such an amendment, said in a conference
call with reporters Tuesday that Gore had ``been AWOL from this
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   The briefing by Kyl, who said he was irked that Gore was trying
to get credit for something that the administration had blocked,
was arranged by the campaign of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The senator said the administration had insisted that the rights
of criminals would never be ``subservient'' to the rights of
victims. ``They basically said that, in the case of a tie, the
defendant always had to win,'' Kyl said. ``It bothers me now that
Al Gore is trying to use this politically and in a fraudulent way,
because he's never been helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   Being tough on crime is a central piece of the New Democrat
approach to policy that Gore _ and President Clinton, for that
matter _ has long embraced. Both support the death penalty, for
example. ``I want to be a law-enforcement president,'' Gore said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee began running a television
commercial last week in 17 states that shows Gore promoting the
constitutional amendment and victims' rights. He says, among other
things, that victims should have the right to speak at the trial of
the accused.
</P>
<P>
   Kyl said that few supported this idea. He also said that his
proposed amendment, which is considered dead for the year, did not
guarantee the right of an employee to be excused from work to
attend a trial, but did guarantee that the victim could not be
excluded from a trial.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, 32 states have laws that give victims the right
to be heard, though usually at the time of sentencing and not when
a jury is considering guilt or innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Although Kyl said he had 41 other sponsors for his proposed
constitutional amendment, altering the Constitution is difficult at
best.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of new constitutional amendments say that this method
of social correction is overused as a political remedy to complex
problems and that in this case, it could easily delay trials and
interfere with plea bargains.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told the victims who were gathered by his campaign to
Rhodes College here on Tuesday that he has ``always been very
reluctant to support a constitutional amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   One constitutional amendment that he did support was the Equal
Rights Amendment, although he was not in Congress when it passed in
1972. After it failed to be ratified by the states, however, he did
vote in 1983 for the amendment to be revived.
</P>
<P>
   He also opposed one other constitutional amendment. In 1989,
when he was in the Senate, he voted for legislation to protect the
flag from desecration, but then a year later, he voted against a
constitutional amendment to protect the flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that our Founders did a great job'' Gore said Tuesday,
``but they anticipated that there would be times when we would have
to amend their handiwork, and this is one such time. I feel very
strongly about it.''
</P>
<P>
   He told the victims, ``No one should have to go through what you
went through,'' referring not only to the initial crime but also to
``what you experienced in the aftermath of the crime, entering the
criminal justice system that sometimes treated you as an
afterthought instead of as a central participant in criminal
justice system, deserving of protection, just as much as those who
are accused of having committed a crime against you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
