<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5911 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MARRIAGETAX-HNS &LR;      07-18 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARRIAGE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE APPROVES TAX RELIEF 
FOR DUAL-INCOME COUPLES 
 

</HEADLINE>
 TAX-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Republican-led Senate passed legislation
Tuesday to provide $248 billion in tax relief to dual-income
couples hit by the so-called ``marriage penalty,'' creating a
potential issue at the party conventions this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's action followed last week's House passage of
similar legislation that would provide $182 billion in relief. GOP
leaders in the Senate and House are expected to quickly hammer out
the differences.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate marriage-penalty bills would remove over
the next decade tax-code provisions that force 25 million
dual-income married couples to pay an average of $1,400 more in
federal income taxes than they would if they were single. The
difference between the two measures is that the Senate bill would
provide slightly more tax relief than would the House version for
couples in the 28 percent tax bracket.
</P>
<P>
   The unified legislation could reach President Clinton's desk in
advance of the GOP National Convention, which begins July 31 in
Philadelphia. Clinton, speaking through a spokesman Tuesday,
threatened to veto the measure unless it also contains the $250
billion in Medicare prescription drug coverage he seeks for seniors
during the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very clear that the Republicans in Congress have decided
to put aside their responsibilities and to play politics,'' said
presidential spokesman Joe Lockhart. ``They've made it very clear
that they want to get bills done timed to their convention so they
will have something to talk about at their convention. The
Democrats, on the other hand, I think have a stronger candidate so
we don't need to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's 61-38 vote to remove the marriage penalty followed
its 59-39 vote Friday to repeal the federal estate tax over the
next decade. Clinton has also vowed to veto that measure, now
headed to his desk, saying the repeal would largely benefit only
the wealthiest 2 percent of Americans who are assessed the tax.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the two repeal measures before the Democratic president
could make the proposed tax breaks major issues at the GOP's
convention July 31-Aug. 3 in Philadelphia. At the convention
Republicans are expected to formally nominate Texas Gov. George W.
Bush to be their party's presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, meanwhile, will hold their national convention Aug.
14-17 in Los Angeles, where they are expected to pick Vice
President Al Gore as their presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has praised the two measures, saying that removing estate
and marriage penalty taxes would bring fairness to the federal tax
code. ``The governor believes these are positive moves that will
benefit American families, farms and small businesses,'' said Bush
campaign spokesman Ray Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore has assailed the GOP's proposed repeals as helping
primarily the wealthy at the expense of providing ``targeted tax
relief for working families,'' his campaign said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-backed tax breaks come amid Congressional Budget
Office projections of a budget surplus of $2.17 trillion over the
next 10 years, including a $102 billion surplus next year. Citing
the surplus, Republican leaders have pressed for tax relief, while
Democrats have sought more money for health care and education.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas and the chief sponsor of the
marriage penalty repeal, said removing the tax will help working
parents in their efforts to pay doctors' bills and educate their
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is who controls the money you earn,''
Hutchison said after the vote. ``Should it be you, or should it be
the federal government? We believe it should be the hard-working
American family that keeps more of the money it earns, to spend for
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., challenged Clinton
to sign both the estate tax and marriage penalty repeals.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two bills, and especially this (marriage penalty) bill,
are a step in the right direction, allowing the people to keep a
little bit more of their hard-earned money and still leaving plenty
of (tax) money for education and defense and health research and
paying down the debt,'' Lott said at a news conference with
Hutchison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now this is going to be clear, very clear, Mr. President,''
Lott added. ``Sign it. It's the right thing to do for working
couples in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., however, accused the
Republicans of being more concerned with giving tax breaks to the
wealthy than helping the middle class.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans call their plans the death tax repeal and the love
tax repeal,'' Daschle said. ``What they are really doing is
offering a . . . tax break that disproportionately benefits the
wealthiest families at the expense of everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Daschle said the Republican proposal would not only reduce taxes
for the 25 million couples stung by the marriage penalty but give
an unfair benefit to nearly 20 million other married couples. These
couples are either unaffected by the penalty or pay less in taxes
because they file jointly and one spouse earns significantly more
than the other.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate votes to repeal estate tax and marriage penalty fell
short of the 67 affirmative votes that would be needed to override
presidential vetoes. On the marriage penalty, eight &UR;  &LR; Democrats
broke party ranks in voting for the repeal, while only
one &UR;  &LR; Republican _ George Voinovich of Ohio _ split from the GOP in
opposing the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Under the legislation, the standard deduction for married
couples would be raised to twice the deduction allowed for singles.
For tax year 2000 that would mean raising the standard deduction
from $7,350 to $8,800, an increase of nearly 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   To give a rough illustration of the marriage penalty, imagine an
unmarried police officer and a school teacher each making $30,000
per year in taxes. Individually, each would pay about $4,500 in
taxes based on a 15 percent tax bracket, leaving each with $25,500
after taxes for a combined total of $51,000.
</P>
<P>
   But, if they were married, their joint income of $60,000 would
be taxed at 28 percent, leaving them with $43,200 after taxes.
Their ``penalty'' for being married would be $7,800, the difference
between $51,000 and $43,200. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The GOP-dominated House passed its marriage penalty repeal
measure last week, 269-159, with 48 Democrats breaking party ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Tax historians are split on the origin of the marriage penalty.
Some attribute it to the unintended mathematical result of a
graduated income tax that increases with wealth. Others say it
arose from less enlightened, male-dominated Congresses that sought
to discourage wives from leaving the house by imposing an
additional tax on two-wage earner couples.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL; 
