<SLUG> BC-MA-CIGAR-LABELS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT REJECTS BAY STATE CIGAR LABEL RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH RANALLI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A federal appeals court has struck down Massachusetts'
landmark warning label regulations for cigar packaging and
advertising, ruling that they are an unconstitutional restriction
of interstate commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The news wasn't as good, however, for cigarette manufacturers,
whose arguments against advertising regulations based on free
speech grounds were all rejected. The appeals court upheld all of
the tough state restrictions on cigarette advertising, including a
total ban on ads within 1,000 feet of a school.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling by the US Court of Appeals for the First Circuit came
less than than three weeks after seven major cigar manufacturers,
accounting for 95 percent of the cigars sold in the United States,
struck a deal with the Federal Trade Commission for a
less-restrictive national warning label standard.
</P>
<P>
   The two recent developments in the battle between regulators and
the cigar industry had both sides sounding Tuesday as if they were
ready to light up a victory smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for what we did, there wouldn't be a consent
decree between the cigar industry and the FTC,'' said Greg
Connolly, head of the state Tobacco Control Program. ``We may have
lost, but overall I think the nation is better off for what
Massachusetts did.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul MacDonald, owner of the venerable David P. Ehrlich tobacco
shop in Boston, however, said the state had clearly ``overstepped''
its authority by requiring ``huge'' warning labels on both cigar
packaging and advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people in the industry do not object to warnings as long
as they are discreet and reasonable,'' MacDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   The state rules required stark, black and white warning labels
that covered 25 percent of the front surface area of a cigar packet
or box and 20 percent of a print advertisement. The agreement
between the cigar manufacturers and the federal government calls
for labels less than half that size.
</P>
<P>
   Still, anti-smoking advocates have hailed the June 26 agreement
as a breakthrough, since it is the first national warning label on
a tobacco product to warn about the effects of second-hand smoke.
</P>
<P>
   In a 58-page ruling made public Monday, the appeals court took
issue not with the size of the Massachusetts warning labels, but
the scope of the regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The justices held that the restrictions on advertising appeared
to apply to national publications like newspapers and magazines,
which would be forced to either print a special in-state edition
for Massachusetts or apply the restrictions nationally. Such a
dilemma posed an ``undue burden'' on interstate commerce, the
justices ruled.
</P>
<P>
   The court applied similar logic to the state requirement for
warning labels on cigar packaging. The way the state regulations
were written, the justices found, manufacturers would be liable for
penalties if any of their cigars were sold in Massachusetts without
the required packaging.
</P>
<P>
   That left cigar makers unconstitutionally liable for actions by
third parties, such as tobacco distributors and sellers, who might
bring unlabeled cigars in from out of state.
</P>
<P>
   The state cigar regulations never actually went into effect,
since the lower court had ordered them put on hold pending the
appeal. Most cigar packaging, however, already carries a California
warning label that has so far passed legal muster.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Connolly said the state will now push for tougher
warnings on cigarettes, and, later this week, announce the results
of a study comparing the effectiveness of American cigarette
warning labels vs. tougher Canadian ones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
