<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5917 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0719-1     07-18 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0719-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: writes thru, updates from late afternoon briefing
 &HT;    TIRED, TENSE MIDEAST NEGOTIATORS, CLINTON MAKING ONE FINAL PUSH
FOR PEACE
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ President Clinton pressed Mideast peace talks
deep into the night Tuesday in deadline diplomacy aimed at securing
an Israeli-Palestinian treaty before his scheduled departure for
Japan on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   With Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat still at odds over the core disputes dividing them,
White House officials were hopeful that threats to shut down the
talks by Wednesday morning would force the adversaries to make
their best efforts to strike an overnight deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``People know that they've got a lot of work to do,'' White
House spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters gathered in this
Catoctin Mountain hamlet five miles from Camp David, the
presidential retreat where the talks have been held since July 11.
``There isn't time to push issues aside or not deal as directly as
they can in the negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as Clinton sought to make the most of the looming deadline,
though, he was weighing whether to delay his departure another day
to buy more time for a shot at peace in one of the world's most
contentious regions.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a judgment that has to be made,'' Lockhart told
reporters, advising them to stay tuned for developments through the
night. ``I'm not sure I could describe the balancing act there.''
</P>
<P>
   In one sign that Clinton might put off his departure, the White
House delayed until Wednesday the press flight for reporters
covering the president's trip to Japan. The press charter had been
scheduled to leave the Washington area Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is due in Tokyo Thursday afternoon for a bilateral
meeting with Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials won't say the meeting is non-essential,
but it's no secret that the agenda is light.
</P>
<P>
   Logistically, Clinton could postpone the meeting with Mori,
leave Washington Thursday morning and still arrive in Okinawa _ the
southernmost island in the Japanese archipelago _ in time for the
main event of his trip: the annual summit of the leaders of the
so-called Group of Seven richest nations, plus Russia.
</P>
<P>
   That could get him 24 hours of overtime to try to wrest a peace
treaty out of the Camp David talks.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations are centered on the core issues in the
52-year-old Palestinian-Israeli dispute. Those include the question
of Palestinian statehood, the future of Jerusalem, territory and
security, and the fate of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   As negotiations intensified, Clinton met with Barak four times
between Monday night and 4:30 a.m. (ET) Tuesday. He caught a few
hours of sleep, then went into a one-hour meeting with Arafat
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said Clinton's mood has swung with the atmospherics
inside Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like all of them, you go through various emotions ranging from
moments where you see promise to moments where the only thing you
see is frustration,'' said Lockhart. In a word, though, he
described Clinton as ``determined,'' to broker a peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions between Arafat and Barak have run so high that U.S.
diplomats have kept them apart since Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In eight days of talks, Arafat and Barak have held just two
direct, one-on-one meetings, the last of which was Saturday. Since
then, they've encountered each other only informally, at a meal,
for example, with others present and seated between them.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart stressed, though, that the lack of direct talks between
Barak and Arafat doesn't mean the negotiations have stalled. Much
can be done to narrow the gaps between them, Lockhart said, by
using Clinton as an intermediary and a buffer to preserve what
diplomatic goodwill still exists between the Israeli and
Palestinian sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 52 years of debate behind them, so the atmosphere at
times has been tense,'' Lockhart said. ``But they are still working
at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lending the weight of his own schedule to the brinkmanship,
Lockhart told reporters late Tuesday ``this may be the last time''
for him to hold his twice-daily summit briefings.
</P>
<P>
   He stressed, though, that he had not yet packed his bags to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Washington, D.C.-based Arab American Institute
released the results of a nationwide poll Tuesday that showed a
majority of American voters support the Palestinians' right to an
independent state.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 890 likely voters, conducted by New York-based
Zogby International July 14-17, showed 66 percent favored a
Palestinian state as well as 63 percent agreeing with Clinton's
handling of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   The poll had a margin of error of +/-3.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   (Cox Newspapers Washington correspondent Lisa Michals
contributed to this report. Her E-mail address is:
lmichals(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
