<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S CHECHEN ALLIES TAKE TO BICKERING AMONG THEMSELVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: map is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The Chechen leaders appointed by Moscow are supposed to
help the Kremlin tighten its grip on the breakaway region. But
Tuesday they quarreled bitterly among themselves and even engaged
in a dangerous round of saber-rattling.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontation, which occurred in Gudermes, the region's
administrative capital and second-largest city, underscores the
difficulties Russia has encountered in establishing a Chechen
government that has the support of the Chechen people.
</P>
<P>
   It was also an embarrassment to President Vladimir Putin. He met
with the Chechen leaders at an air base in Mozdok, a few miles
outside Chechnya, just two weeks ago and urged that pro-Moscow
Chechen forces play more of a role in bringing order to the region,
where Russian troops have been fighting Chechen rebels since
September.
</P>
<P>
   The episode began when Bislan Gantamirov, a pro-Moscow leader of
a Chechen paramilitary unit, sent 200 of his men into Gudermes,
ostensibly to search for rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Gantamirov, a former mayor of the Chechen capital, Grozny, was
imprisoned for embezzlement before the current military campaign in
Chechnya. But he was released so that he could fight on the Russian
side.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the Russians appointed him deputy administrator in
their new Chechen government and gave him responsibility for
security as part of Moscow's effort to contend with the rebels'
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   But Gantamirov is also been a bitter rival of Akhmad Kadyrov,
the Russian-appointed administrator of Chechnya, who is based in
Gudermes. And Gantamirov's operation in Gudermes on Tuesday was
widely seen as an attempt to intimidate Kadyrov.
</P>
<P>
   Kadyrov, a former Muslim religious leader, opposed the Russians
during the 1994-96 Chechen war, when Russian troops attempting to
break a drive for Chechen independence were driven out of the
Caucasus republic. But he has cooperated with Moscow since Russian
troops returned last fall, after raids on neighboring Dagestan and
apartment bombings that the Kremlin blames on Chechen rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Kadyrov has been the target of several assassination attacks and
has been struggling to establish his authority in Chechnya since
his appointment last month.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was Kadyrov's decision to dismiss several local
officials, including some apparently loyal to Gantamirov, that
prompted Gantamirov to send his men to Gudermes. ``We are the
people who fought our way from the border with Ingushetiya to
Grozny and we won't be bossed around by Kadyrov and his gang,''
Gantamirov said.
</P>
<P>
   As tensions grew, Kadyrov made it clear that he did not welcome
Gantamirov's s troops and had certainly never endorsed their
mission to sweep the city. ``Gantamirov did not clear this
announcement with me and received no approval to carry out such an
operation,'' Kadyrov said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military became concerned, too. Russia's armed
forces are tied down coping with the rebels' guerrilla tactics. The
last thing they needed was a clash among their own allies.
</P>
<P>
   So Lt. Gen. Ivan Babichev quickly moved to keep order. The
Russians said that Gantamirov and Kadyrov would meet to try to
resolve their differences.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid a firefight, Gantamirov's men were allowed to pass
through the checkpoints on the outskirts of Gudermes. But Babichev
later warned Gantamirov's militia to leave Gudermes and suggested
they would be fired on if they did not.
</P>
<P>
   Or as he put it, Gantamirov's militia, if it did not leave
Gudermes, ``will be regarded as a rebel formation with all the
ensuing consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the only time that the performance of the pro-Moscow
Chechen military has come under question. Russian soldiers say that
Gantamirov has vastly exaggerated the importance of his unit in the
capture of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   And Gantamirov and his men were discharged from their duties by
Russian authorities this spring after the Russians complained the
Chechen militia had failed to carry out its responsibilities and
had disappeared along with their weapons. Gantamirov, however, was
recently hired after the militants unleashed a wave of bombings and
stepped up their guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Gen. Gennady Troshev, the senior Russian commander in
Chechnya, has also pointed to problems Moscow has had with
pro-Moscow Chechens, though he did not blame the men under
Gantamirov's command.
</P>
<P>
   According to Troshev, a Chechen militia unit recently captured
Shirvani Basayev, the bother of Shamyl Basayev, the Chechen
warlord. Apparently fearful that the detention would subject then
to reprisals, the Chechens then let him go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
