<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5924 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-CANCER-SUIT-BOS &LR;      07-18 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTERSUIT FILED IN CANCER TREATMENT RESEARCH CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAJA MISHRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In an escalation of a high-stakes scientific struggle,
prominent cancer researcher Dr. Judah Folkman and Children's
Hospital Tuesday countersued drug giant Abbott Laboratories Inc.
for fraud and defamation, accusing the Illinois company of
resorting to lies and threats in attempting to steal a potential
blockbuster cancer discovery.
</P>
<P>
   The scorching 47-page legal attack files in US District Court
Tuesday was a response to Abbott's May 30 lawsuit accusing
Folkman's lab of a ``conspiracy'' to falsely claim credit for
discovering a substance that could save lives by starving cancerous
tumors to death.
</P>
<P>
   The dueling lawsuits are a nasty byproduct of the
hyper-competitive world of cancer research, where a discovery of a
single molecule can be worth billions and a cure is perhaps the
most sought-after prize in all medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Tumor starving is seen as the most promising avenue of cancer
research and Folkman is its acknowledged father. He has become an
almost messianic figure among cancer patients, half a million of
whom die every year in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The ongoing trials of the cancer drugs stemming from his work
are among the most-watched in a generation. None of the current
trials are affected by the lawsuits. But Tuesday, Children's
alleged that Abbott's legal attack could slow future discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   The case ``has cast a cloud over Children's and the individual
scientists, jeopardizing their ability to obtain funding for their
research activities and forcing them to expend valuable time,
energy and resources to respond to the defamatory statements,''
stated Children's in its court filing.
</P>
<P>
   The heavily publicized Abbott lawsuit personally devastated
Folkman, said colleagues. His lawyers promised _ and delivered _ a
strongly worded response.
</P>
<P>
   The legal back-and-forth has been unusually personal for the
otherwise staid world of patent law. Tuesday's filing upped the
ante, adding a defamation of character charge to the already
complex scientific dispute, claiming Abbott devised a ``malicious
campaign to intimidate and harass'' the Children's researchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abbott sees some very valuable technology. They tried to get
it fairly and legitimately and they couldn't,'' said Children's
lead lawyer William F. Lee. ``What they've done now is threaten
unfairly the thing that's most important to Dr. Folkman and
Children's _ their reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   Abbott maintained Tuesday it was the sole discoverer of the
tumor-starving breakthrough in question and would continue to make
its case in court. It has 20 days to respond to Tuesday's
counter-suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since our proprietary intellectual property is at the heart of
our ability to fulfill our mission, we must vigorously defend our
rights to our discovery,'' said Abbott spokeswoman Ann
Fahey-Widman.
</P>
<P>
   After Abbott responds, the case will enter a phase where the
scientists can be questioned under oath and documents can be
subpoenaed, though the two sides have already exchanged significant
sheafs of information in the three years of failed negotiations
that preceded the legal clash.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy boils down to a scientific whodunit: who knew
what when?
</P>
<P>
   It centers on a protein called plasminogen found in blood.
Plasminogen is divided into five regions dubbed ``Kringles.''
</P>
<P>
   Undisputed is that Folkman's lab discovered the anti-tumor
potential of the first four Kringles, publishing its results in a
series of mid-1990s groundbreaking papers.
</P>
<P>
   Tumors thrive by creating their own blood vessels in a process
called angiogenesis, a discovery that is Folkman's signature
insight. His lab established that Kringles 1-4 could shut down the
process in mice, a finding that electrified the medical world.
</P>
<P>
   But Abbott, in its lawsuit, claims its own researcher, Dr.
Donald Davidson, is the discoverer of the anti-tumor potential of
Kringle 5. Davidson is an expert on plasminogen. According to court
documents, in early 1994 Folkman's lab requested supplies of
plasminogen from three sources: Notre Dame University,
Carnegie-Mellon University and Davidson's lab at Abbott. Abbott was
not engaged in any tumor-starving research at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott claims that, at this time, Davidson began his own Kringle
5 studies and found _ for the first time _ that properly treated
Kringle 5 had stronger anti-tumor properties than Kringles 1 to 4.
He told Folkman's lab about it and they ran off with the idea
straight to the patent office, claims Abbott.
</P>
<P>
   Children's Tuesday argued that Dr. Yihai Cao, then a researcher
in Folkman's lab, made the Kringle 5 discovery on his own. Cao was
able to draw on two decades worth of research in Folkman's lab,
noted Children's lawyers, while Davidson was a cancer research
neophyte.
</P>
<P>
   Cao published his findings in the Journal of Biological
Chemistry, sending a draft to Davidson. In a recent interview, Cao
maintained he made the discovery on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don Davidson never published his data. He never showed any of
it to me,'' said Cao. ``I know I created this idea in my brain. I
know what I was thinking, I know what I planned. I know what I
did.''
</P>
<P>
   During a recent interview at his suburban Chicago home, Davidson
said he could not elaborate on the lawsuit because Abbott placed
him under a gag order two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides sought patents on Kringle 5's cancer fighting
properties. The US Patent Office approved both. In fact, clashing
patents are not uncommon and usually settled in court. In that
regard, this case is typical. Abbott is asking that Children's
patent be rescinded; Children's is requesting the reverse.
</P>
<P>
   What is unusual is the angry rhetoric leveled by both sides,
with Abbott accusing Children's of being ``engaged in a scheme'' to
steal the discovery. Tuesday, Children's responded by alleging
Abbott's lawsuit was calculated to ``damage the good reputation''
of Children's and its scientists and ``intimidate them'' into
relinquishing credit for their work.
</P>
<P>
   Folkman's colleagues have said he is depressed by the case,
worried that a black mark will always appear next to his otherwise
brilliant resume. Cao, recently speaking from Stockholm where he is
researcher at the Karolinska Institute, said the Scandinavian
scientific community is abuzz with talk of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has upset me and my family, too. You try to help other
people and other people try to bite you back. It makes you wonder
why you do it,'' he said. ``I'm just starting my career at the age
of 40. I have a long way to go. I don't want to damage it.''
</P>
<P>
   The bitter legal fight may have years to go but the tests on the
tumor starving drugs pioneered by Folkman's lab _ called
angiogenesis inhibitors _ continue to plow ahead.
</P>
<P>
   One drug, Endostatin, is undergoing Phase 1 testing at the
Dana-Farber Cancer Institute in Boston and two centers elsewhere,
to see if it is safe to take.
</P>
<P>
   Another drug Angiostatin, is further along, having recently
started initial human testing at Thomas Jefferson University in
Philadelphia. Although the entire cancer community is intensely
interested in the outcomes, no results have yet been released.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Globe staff writer Richard Saltus contributed to this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
