<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECUADORR-MAHUAD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDICTED EX-PRESIDENT OF ECUADOR DEFENDS ACTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Deposed Ecuadorean President Jamil Mahuad, who faces
arrest warrants issued last week by his nation's top court,
defended Tuesday the decisions that sparked the charges against
him.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released by Harvard University, where he has been
teaching, Mahuad said that a three-member team of lawyers will
represent him in upcoming proceedings before Ecuador's Supreme
Court, but did not indicate whether he would return to face the
charges himself. He said would make no further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Mahuad said the decisions cited by the court were necessary to
stabilize a national banking and finance system that was rapidly
collapsing.
</P>
<P>
   Mahuad, who was ousted by Ecuador's military in January, became
a visiting fellow at Harvard University's Kennedy School of
Government in April and will remain at the school through the
summer working on projects that neither he nor the school has
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ecuador was facing its worst crisis in the last 70 years,'' he
said in the prepared statement. ``It had become the most indebted
country in Latin America in regard to its GDP (gross domestic
product). It had the worst inflation in South America. . . . The
financial system was broken.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a consequence of these problems, capital flight took $500
million out of the country in three months,'' he said, and for that
reason the government decided to freeze broad areas of the banking
sector ``to stop the bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics and the supreme court judge leading the investigation
allege that Mahuad exceeded his constitutional authority and
possibly engaged in corrupt behavior by helping banking-sector
leaders, but the former president said ``all our actions were in
good faith.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I affected the lives of many people with these
decisions,'' he said, ``but my main goal was to prevent the wealthy
people from taking money out of the country. Of course I made
mistakes, but it was very difficult to govern during such a
crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   The monetary crisis and his decision to freeze deposits were
subjects of a study group on Ecuador which he led at the Kennedy
School.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1933EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5935 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-HARLEM-GALLERY-ART     07-18 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HARLEM-GALLERY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GALLERY IN HARLEM BEATS THE ODDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 By HOLLAND CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the fall of 1998, Christian Haye, a New York poet
and art critic, opened a gallery of contemporary art in Manhattan.
He called it the Project and presented an impressive lineup of
artists from the Americas, Europe, Africa and Asia, many of them
making local solo gallery debuts. Among them was Paul Pfeiffer, who
went on to become a star of this year's Whitney Biennial and the
recipient of that museum's first $100,000 Bucksbaum Award,
currently the world's largest award for a visual artist.
</P>
<P>
   In a city where competition for attention-grabbing talent is
keen, the Project seemed to be on a winning track. But it was also
bucking serious odds, New York has hundreds of art galleries; they
open and fold all the time. Start-up backing can ensure at least
short-term survival; Haye had none. And if prime location is
everything, his venture had a major handicap. It wasn't situated
within one of Manhattan's downtown art precincts. It was in a
former disco on West 126th Street in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   Haye's solution was to turn being out of the way into a mark of
distinction. ``Everything about his gallery is a surprise,'' said
Thelma Golden, deputy director for exhibitions and programs at the
nearby Studio Museum in Harlem. ``On the block it blends into the
other buildings. Then you go inside and see the poured concrete
floors and white Sheetrock walls. He shows international artists
where you might expect to find only African-American artists. He
brings a contemporary art world sensibility, but he's also deeply
invested in the neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   What inspired Haye to open his gallery in Harlem? ``In a sense,
Chelsea,'' he said in a recent interview. He was referring to the
city's now-not-so-new commercial art center in the far West 20s, in
recent years a bleak stretch of storage buildings and garages until
its overnight transformation into what some people see as an
instant art mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be in a neighborhood with some history,'' Haye
said. ``SoHo was over. Williamsburg was already taken. Harlem was
the natural choice. The area is overly politicized and has always
been an economic battleground. But no place has more narrative than
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Art has always been part of that narrative. Legendary figures
like Aaron Douglas, Augusta Savage and Jacob Lawrence once lived in
Harlem. High-profile contemporary artists like Ghada Amer, David
Hammons and Nari Ward work in the area today. The Studio Museum,
established in 1968, has a worldwide reputation as a center for
African-American culture and is now expanding its physical plant
and its programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``My great-grandmother came from Barbados to live here many
years ago,'' said Haye, 30. ``I've done a lot of traveling, and
anywhere you go in the world people say: `You're from New York. Are
you from Harlem?' Everybody knows about it, though almost as if it
were a virtual space. They don't know what the reality of it is.''
</P>
<P>
   That reality is notably upbeat at the moment. A commercial
renovation is changing the face of 125th Street, bringing in
Starbucks and Disney and with them presumably more visitors,
including tourists. All of this may benefit the Project itself,
which in February moved to new quarters a few doors from its
original site after the ex-disco, on which Haye had a
month-to-month lease, was sold to a social services agency.
</P>
<P>
   The forced move was just one more learning experience for Haye,
with little cash and almost no experience in running a gallery.
Born in Queens County, raised on Long Island, he enrolled at New
York University when he was 16 to study comparative literature but
dropped out fast. ``I had problems with academia,'' he said.
``There's something about the power structure between students and
teachers that doesn't work for me.''
</P>
<P>
   He worked in publishing, then as a receptionist at The New York
Review of Books. ``Even when I was a teen-ager all I ever wanted to
do was sit down and read and write book reviews,'' he said. He
became briefly involved in the Nuyorican Poets Cafe in the East
Village after hearing Amiri Baraka read there, and got a job with
the Jack Tilton Gallery in SoHo, though that didn't last long. ``I
just don't play well with others,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While at Tilton, he was living in the East Village in an
apartment above the poet Steve Cannon, who had founded the literary
and art magazine Gathering of the Tribes. Haye edited two issues
and started writing about pop culture for other magazines like Bomb
and Frieze, a contemporary art journal published in London.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 exasperated by what he viewed as misguided critical
responses to black artists (and upset with the provocative ``Black
Male'' show at the Whitney, organized by Golden and which he
considered wrongheaded), he turned his attention to art criticism.
``I thought, `Well, I'm not an art critic, but I'm sick of reading
this stuff.' Then I found myself writing more and more about art,
which isn't what I set out to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He spent the next three years traveling, mostly in Europe,
networking intensively and looking at work in art fairs and
biennials as well as in institutional programs. ``I basically
opened a gallery to show artists I'd been wanting to write about,''
he said. So far, he added, no artist he has invited to show with
him has turned him down.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   After scouting around Harlem, he found the abandoned disco. With
the help of friends, he put up interior walls on the first floor
himself. He decided to use the basement as additional exhibition
space, leaving it more or less as he found it with tropical
landscapes picked out in glitter on black-painted walls.
</P>
<P>
   No one who visited the Project that year is likely to forget it.
There was no heat. And when a midwinter installation by the
Scandinavian artist team of Michael Elmgreen and Ingar Dragset
entailed knocking a hole through the wall of the building, the
inside temperature was biting.
</P>
<P>
   Usually two solo shows were on view at a time; the mix was
visually varied and conceptually unprogrammatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The early 1990s was an ideological time,'' he said. ``It was
the message, not the medium that mattered. Now the pendulum seems
to have swung the other way, and I guess I'm swinging with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Young artists like Bulent Sangar from Turkey and the Korean-born
Kim Sooja (much noticed at last year's Venice Biennale) appeared
along with maverick Americans rarely seen in New York, like the
performance artist William Pope L., who a few years ago tied
himself to the door of a midtown bank with a string of hot dogs and
handed out money, and the California-based Daniel J. Martinez,
known for the ``I can't imagine ever wanting to be white''
admission tags he designed for the 1993 Whitney Biennial.
</P>
<P>
   The final show in the space was work by Romuald Hazoume from
Benin, who arrived a month before the opening to collect local
materials for his sculptures. It was Hazoume's first visit to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The third day he was here,'' Haye recalled, ``he said to me:
`Christian, this is really strange. I've met so many people from
Benin here. And I don't have to speak English. I can just speak
French all day.' I said: `Well, this is Harlem. What do you
expect?'''
</P>
<P>
   After that show closed last July, the gallery was homeless for
several months until its reappearance at 427 West 126th Street, a
compact two-story former bar. Haye has also brought in a new
director and partner, Jenny Liu, whose background is almost as
varied as his. A Harvard Law School graduate with a background in
linguistics and psychology, she has a degree in art history from
the Institute of Fine Arts in New York and has worked as an
assistant director at 303 Gallery in Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition program continues to be lively. On view through
Aug. 27 are the sound-based installations by Nadine Robinson and
Stephen Vitiello, both of whom made strong impressions in the
``Greater New York'' exhibition at P.S. 1 this spring. (Through the
summer the gallery will officially be open only on Sundays, 12 to 6
p.m., though Haye and Liu are often on the premises and welcome
drop-in visits.)
</P>
<P>
   September will bring a show Haye describes as ``devoted mostly
to pornography,'' with work by Shu Lea Cheang and Matthias Vriens,
creative director of Gucci. Two young California artists, Art
Domantay and Kori Newkirk, will follow. Pfeiffer is being given
both floors of the gallery for a solo in November.
</P>
<P>
   The gallery has attracted some backing since it opened, but, Liu
said with a mild note of wonder, it largely supports itself through
sales, which have recently ranged from a $400 drawing to a $100,000
installation. Openings are well attended and foot traffic has
picked up.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning we got maybe two people a day,'' she said.
``Now we sometimes have 15 or 20, which is nothing at all for
Chelsea but a lot for here.''
</P>
<P>
   Liu and Haye have high hopes for the expansion of the
contemporary gallery scene in the neighborhood, which also includes
two spaces that predate the Project's arrival and share its broad
agenda: Gallery X at 23 West 129th Street and the nonprofit Gallery
M at 123 West 135th Street. ``We keep hearing rumors that other
galleries are moving up here,'' Golden said, ``and if they do it
will be because of what Christian has done. His energy is
infectious.''
</P>
<P>
   But Haye, who lives in an apartment near the Project, says he
wonders whether the mainstream downtown art world will really
follow his lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I run into people from the New York art world all the time in
Europe,'' he said. ``They can find their way to Berlin, but they
can't find their way to Harlem because it's too far away. It's not
really about the distance, though. It's about mental image. People
still ask me if it's safe here. It's so close to where a lot of
people are, but it's a different world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
