<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEPHARDT-VEEP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEPHARDT TAKES HIMSELF OFF GORE'S SHORT LIST _ SORT OF 
</HEADLINE>
  By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Democratic Leader Dick Gephardt took himself
off the list of possibilities for Vice President Al Gore's running
mate on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Or did he?
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference called to discuss tax bills, Gephardt, of
Missouri, who has been courted by the Gore camp in recent weeks,
said his priority was to stay put as the Democratic leader _ and
lead his party to retake control of the House. (And, he hopes,
become the next speaker.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said I don't want to do that,'' Gephardt said of the No.
2 job. ``And I've said I hope and believe they'll find someone to
do that other than me.''
</P>
<P>
   But, even as his aides insisted he had no interest in a spot on
the ticket, Gephardt left the door slightly ajar _ a point that was
noticed by Gore aides.
</P>
<P>
   What if the vice president put the squeeze on him, telling him
that he had to do it for the good of the party? Would Gephardt
change his mind?
</P>
<P>
   The congressman refused to answer, saying only, ``I've been as
clear as clear can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed at another point to ``say more firmly'' that he would
not join the ticket, he said, ``Well, I'm for Al Gore. You know
that. I have supported him from the beginning of this campaign,
almost. And I think he'd make a great president of this country.
And I hope that he wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt _ who had considered taking Gore on in the primaries
this year _ emphasized that his heart is on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been very focused on one thing, and that's winning back a
majority in the House,'' he said. ``I've worked very, very hard at
it, and I continue to work at it every day. And so I'm
preoccupied.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``That's the only reason that I wouldn't have a
different thought on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt's words must be examined carefully because there is a
history of vice presidential contenders insisting they do not want
the job. Sometimes they say that to appear virtuous, knowing they
will not get picked anyway. Other times, they say they do not want
it, but do not really mean it. Sometimes, of course, they may
really mean it but can be pressed into running anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Even the two Republicans who many party members say have the
most sizzle _ Colin Powell and Sen. John McCain of Ariz. _ left a
bit of maneuvering room when they ruled themselves out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a candidate for vice president,'' Powell said
recently.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said: ``I asked that I not be considered for vice
president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, voters should be reminded of what Sen. Al Gore of
Tennessee told Larry King on CNN in February of 1992: ``I have no
interest in being vice president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Daley, Gore's campaign chairman, explained the feint:
``People who say, `I have a much more important job. I'm in the
United States Senate.' Give me a break!'' Daley said in an
interview before he was plucked from Clinton's Cabinet to run the
campaign. ``This is the second most important job in the nation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
