A5943 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-CCE-EARN19-COX     07-18 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CCE-EARN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coca-Cola Enterprises reports big second-quarter profit
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Coca-Cola Enterprises reported Tuesday a big boost in
second-quarter profit, which benefited from a comparison with last
summer's product recall in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based CCE, the world's largest soft-drink bottler,
earned $122 million, or 29 cents a share. That compared with $33
million, or 8 cents a share, last year.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding one-time charges, the company beat analysts' estimates
by 2 cents a share, helping to boost its stock 94 cents Tuesday to
$18.44.
</P>
<P>
   CCE earned 30 cents a share in the second quarter, after
excluding a $12 million charge for restructuring operations in
Great Britain. That compared with 24 cents last year, not counting
the product recall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think CCE's numbers were solid in the second quarter,'' said
Andrew Conway, an analyst with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``This
was among the more challenging quarters for CCE in a long time,
because they faced pricing and margin pressure in Great Britain and
lower case sales in North America. However, the strong pricing in
North America was able to add significantly to operating
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Cash operating profit, a key measure of a bottler's performance
that excludes interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization, rose
21 percent to $696 million. CCE buys syrup or concentrate from
Coca-Cola Co. It then adds carbonated water before packaging the
beverages and distributing them to retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Case sales dropped 0.5 percent in North America, while shooting
up 15.5 percent in Europe, largely because of the comparison with
last year's recall there. In total, case sales rose 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their mission, should they choose to accept it, is to make
sure case-sales growth in the United States begins to pick up in
the last half of the year and strengthens further next year,'' said
Manny Goldman, an analyst with ING Barings. ``That's what counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Revenue rose 6 percent to $4.03 billion.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, CCE is expected to earn about 50 cents a share,
compared with 29 cents last year, excluding one-time charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we have more work ahead of us, we are successfully
establishing a more profitable foundation from which to build for
the long-term value of our shareowners,'' Chairman and Chief
Executive Summerfield Johnston Jr. said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the company has a ``below average'' recommendation
among Wall Street analysts, according to a survey by First
Call/Thomson Financial. Four analysts rate it a ``strong buy,''
three designate it as a ``buy,'' and eight classify it as a
``hold.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Co., which owns about 40 percent of CCE, is slated to
report its earnings today. Excluding one-time charges, analysts
expect it to report second-quarter earnings of 41 cents a share,
compared with 38 cents last year.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Coke has an ``average'' recommendation among
analysts, according to First Call/Thomson Financial. Eight analysts
rate the stock as a ``strong buy,'' two consider it a ``buy'' and
six designate it as a ``hold.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
