A5944 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-GLF-BROPEN-TIGER19-CO     07-18 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BROPEN-TIGER19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woods prohibitive favorite to win British Open
 &HT;    By Craig Dolch
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ Tiger Woods has won a U.S. Open by 15
shots and a Masters by 12. He has won more than half of his last 22
tournaments (12), including six in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for his latest _ and perhaps greatest _ piece of magic.
</P>
<P>
   This week he will try to become just the fifth player _ and the
youngest _ to win the career grand slam. At 24 years, 7 months,
Woods is heavily favored to win the British Open at the Old Course
and join golf's most exclusive club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I would love to have that happen,'' Woods said.
``And there's no better site for it to occur than the home of golf.
It's a very special place. Every person who has ever played the
game of golf has wanted to win an Open at St. Andrews because
that's where the game evolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Nicklaus, Gary Player, Ben Hogan and Gene Sarazen are
golf's version of the Fab Four, linked by their ability to win the
game's four most significant tournaments _ the Masters, U.S. Open,
British Open and PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   How difficult is it? Many have tried, but only those four have
succeeded. And nobody has done so since 1966.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're playing in four completely different environments,''
Player said Tuesday after playing a practice round with the other
living member of the club (Nicklaus). ``To win one major in your
life you can be pretty proud of. The odds of winning all four are
stacked against you.''
</P>
<P>
   Just consider some of the players who didn't win all four
majors: Arnold Palmer, Tom Watson, Byron Nelson, Sam Snead, Lee
Trevino Ray Floyd. Now Woods has that opportunity in just his
fourth full season as a professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be remarkable,'' said Watson, who like Palmer never
won the PGA. ``But given the way he's playing, it's not
surprising.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also not surprising that Woods again finds himself on a
parallel course with his childhood idol. When Nicklaus was 24, he
came to St. Andrews in 1964 with an opportunity to complete the
slam. Nicklaus finished second, five shots behind winner Tomy Lema,
and waited two years before he became the youngest to win all four
majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to deal with all kinds of conditions and you have
to be able to do a lot of different things,'' Nicklaus said.
``Certainly he (Woods) will, whether it be this year. This course
is certainly right down his alley.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods is listed as the prohibitive 15-8 favorite to win here,
thanks in large part to his 15-shot victory last month at the U.S.
Open at Pebble Beach. The rest of the field shoudn't be happy to
hear Woods' swing coach, Butch Harmon, say Woods is hitting the
ball better than he did at Pebble Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Woods surprised some Tuesday when he said he probably wouldn't
rate the career Grand Slam as his top achievement. Even more
surprising was the revelation he thinks winning three consecutive
U.S. Juniors is his greatest success.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would rank up there,'' Woods said of the career grand slam.
``At the top? That's hard to say because I've had a lot of
wonderful accomplishments in my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Harmon didn't buy that. ``It would mean a lot to Tiger, because
he's always rated his success by how he rates against the great
players,'' Harmon said.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of the current grand slam has evolved in the last 40
years. In 1930, for instance, many believed Bobby Jones won the
Grand Slam when he was victorious in the U.S. Open and British
Open, as well as the U.S. Amateur and the British Amateur.
</P>
<P>
   But after Palmer won the Masters and U.S. Open in 1960,
sportswriter Bob Drum first wrote about Palmer's chances of winning
the modern grand slam. The idea stuck and almost retroactively,
Sarazen and Hogan became members of the club they had earned
entrance to decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Others came so very close to joining them. Had Snead parred the
par-5 18th hole at Phildaelphia Country Club in the 1939 U.S. Open,
he would have won the career slam. Instead, he made triple-bogey
and missed the playoff by two shots. Snead also had four runner-up
finishes in the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something always seemed to happen,'' Snead said Monday. ``I
would step in a hole or someone would kick my ball.''
</P>
<P>
   His frustration was shared by Palmer and Watson. ``I freely
admit that I would have dearly loved to have won the PGA,''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer said. ``It would have been important for me to win it and
put the missing jewel in my crown. It bothers me that I didn't win
it, but it doesn't prey on my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Watson: ``I had several opportunities, but I also won some
majors I probably shouldn't have. I don't complain about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the active players, only Woods, Nick Price, Vijay Singh,
John Daly, Nick Faldo, Sandy Lyle and Mark O'Meara have won two
different majors, with Singh the most likely to make a run at the
career slam. Singh has the work ethic,
</P>
<P>
   but Player wonders if he was almost ordained to join the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is to win it, I don't think the man can take the
credit for it,'' he said. ``It's a special gift from upstairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
