<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE PROMOTES CRIME-FIGHTING PACKAGE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS, Tenn. _ Vice President Al Gore passed out hugs and
listened to the stories of crime victims Tuesday as he kicked off a
three-day trip spotlighting his planned $685 million, 10-year
crime-fighting package.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one should have to go through what you've been through,''
Gore told victims gathered at Rhodes College.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic presidential candidate first announced his Crime
Victims Bill of Rights proposal last year. It would use money from
the federal budget surplus to increase compensation for crime
victims, provide temporary housing for women trying to escape
domestic violence and crack down on hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Central to the plan is a constitutional amendment that calls for
giving victims the right to be heard during the sentencing process,
to be notified when prisoners are released and to receive
restitution from their offenders. Several states already offer
those protections, but Gore said about 60 percent of victims of
violent crimes are not notified of their right to participate in
prosecution, sentencing or corrections decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defendants have constitutional rights to protect them, and
when those rights are enshrined in the Constitution and the rights
of victims are not, whenever the two come into conflict, victims
are put in the back seat and sometimes completely ignored,'' Gore
said. ``We need to change that by having balance in the system.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Gore expanded his plan to include legislation aimed
at protecting the jobs of crime victims who need time off work to
attend trials. Modeled after the federal Family and Medical Leave
Act, Gore's plan would allow crime victims to take unpaid leave
from work without putting their jobs or promotions in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan also calls for increasing the amount of funds that
can be paid out of the federal Crime Victims Fund, encouraging
Congress to reauthorize the Violence Against Women Act, and
restoring a provision that gave victims of gender-motivated
violence the power to sue their attackers for lost earnings,
medical expenses and other damages. Gore also would offer 4,000 new
temporary housing vouchers to help provide safe housing for women
and children escaping abusive homes.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Clinton-Gore administration, which has increased the
number of police officers on the street, imposed tougher penalties
for some crimes and funded more crime prevention programs, crime
has fallen nationwide to its lowest level in 25 years. Serious
crime has decreased for eight consecutive years, and the murder
rate is now at its lowest point since 1967, Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore was immediately criticized by Republican rival George
W. Bush and Republicans lawmakers who accused the vice president of
playing election-year politics by supporting a victims' rights
amendment after the White House opposed a bipartisan victims'
rights amendment just a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jon Kyl, an Arizona Republican and a chief sponsor of the
measure, charged that Gore had been AWOL (absent without leave)
from the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exactly one year ago, Al Gore said he would lead the fight for
victims' rights, and then we didn't hear from him,'' Kyl told The
Associated Press in a conference telephone call that the Bush
campaign helped arrange.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane said the administration opposed
Kyl's legislation because of prosecutors' concerns that it would
interfere with defendants' rights to a speedy trial, giving
criminals another avenue to appeal their convictions. Lehane said
Gore's plan addresses technical problems with the previous
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   After a quick visit with Memphis police and with children
attending summer camp in Memphis, Gore spent the afternoon with
crime victims before flying to Kansas City, Mo., to greet
supporters there on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   For the second day in a row, Gore attacked Bush's Social
Security plan, warning that it would put the system into a deficit
for the first time in its 65-year history. He challenged Bush to
justify and explain the plan, which he believes will cost taxpayers
$3 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
