u e BC-MISSISSIPPI-TV-REVIEW     07-18 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSISSIPPI-TV-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MISSISSIPPI': A PENT-UP OLD MAN RIVER RUN AMOK 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By JULIE SALAMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are those people who wake up to the weather report and
those who don't. The Weather Channel thrives because so many of us
do, and the History Channel has noticed. So beginning Wednesday
night, History begins its ``Wrath of God'' series, which features
natural disasters, many of them meteorological, and all historic of
course.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every other Wednesday night at 11, through the end of the
year, weather-disaster buffs can have a nightcap of typhoons,
hurricanes, avalanches and floods. The series begins with
``Mississippi: River Out of Control,'' about the flood of 1927 that
killed 500 to 1,000 people and left almost one million more
homeless. Children of the region would grow up hearing their
parents date everything ``before the flood'' and ``after the
flood.''
</P>
<P>
   Produced and written by Ginny Weissman, this sober and
informative program offers a no-nonsense account of nature's
response to human hubris. Southern plantation owners needed to be
near the river to transport cotton, the region's big cash crop. The
levees they built to control flooding also built pressure in the
contained water after a big rain. In April 1927, there were many
big rains _ 15 inches fell on New Orleans in one 18-hour period _
and the levees burst. It was like a balloon popping, says one of
the documentary's historian-commentators, and the water poured out
like escaping air.
</P>
<P>
   We learn that at its peak the river zoomed along at 3 million
cubic feet a second, double the volume of water that cascades over
Niagara Falls. The Bible and Shakespeare describe the futility of
man trying to circumvent nature more poetically, but the History
Channel delivers good pictures. The documentary shows families
paddling boats up a town's main street, eye to eye with chimneys.
One man fashioned what could be called Noah's barge, a kind of
floating pen for his farm animals. We see the refugee tent camps
constructed after the flood, eerily prescient of the Depression
tent camps.
</P>
<P>
   Herbert Hoover, secretary of commerce under President Calvin
Coolidge, emerges cleanly for his sensitive handling of the
post-flood trauma. But there was plenty of insensitivity, even
brutality. Local police officers rounded up convicts to stuff and
pile sandbags on the levees. The convicts were joined in this
dangerous work by black farm workers, who had been ordered to the
riverfront by their employers. These workers were the first to bear
the brunt of the flood when the banks overflowed _ many drowned _
and the last to leave the refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary explains the political maneuvering that saved
New Orleans, by washing out her smaller neighbors. As the flood
moved south from Greenville, Miss., New Orleans politicians and
businessmen persuaded Louisiana's governor to divert the flood to
neighboring parishes, which were much less populated. Their deal
included payments of $20 a person for the displaced country folks.
</P>
<P>
   Much like their ancestors who gathered on hills to watch Civil
War battles, many New Orleans residents went to watch the explosion
upriver that would destroy the levees and change the Mississippi's
course. The sacrificial towns were destroyed as planned, and their
people never received the promised reparations.
</P>
<P>
   A man who was a boy then recalls going back into his home after
the flood: ``Oh, mud was everywhere _ and stink.'' But the terrible
vision of the flood also contained ``an awful beauty,'' says one
commentator, that lingers for historians, archaeologists,
memoirists, filmmakers and disaster buffs.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   MISSISSIPPI: RIVER OUT OF CONTROL
</P>
<P>
   11 p.m. ET Wednesday on History Channel
</P>
<P>
   Produced and written by Ginny Weissman. A production by Towers
Productions for the History Channel. Jonathan Towers, executive
producer; Pete Stacker, narrator. For the History Channel, Charlie
Maday, executive producer; Beth Dietrich-Segarra, supervising
producer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 1945EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
