<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5950 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-RAINY-DAYS19-TEXAS-CO     07-18 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAINY-DAYS19-TEXAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Despite flush economy, Texas has saved little for a financial
rainy day
 &HT;    By Gary Susswein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - After an unexpected recession forced Texas
lawmakers to raise taxes and cut spending in the late 1980s, former
Sen. John Leedom wondered why he and his colleagues had never saved
for rough economic times.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Republican started pushing for a rainy day fund to
help Texas survive the next recession without massive tax hikes or
spending cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Now, nearly 12 years after voters approved the idea, Texas has
just $84 million in that fund _ less than two-tenths of 1 percent
of its $49 billion yearly budget _ and critics say the state still
will be swamped by that next fiscal storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame,'' Leedom said Tuesday. ``With the size of the
state's budget, I'd say if they didn't have almost a couple hundred
million dollars in their sugar bowl, they should be ashamed of
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with mandatory deposits scheduled to go into the fund this
fall, Texas still will have just $130 million in savings _ enough
to run state government for one day.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when short-term budget overruns and Gov. George W.
Bush's presidential run are focusing national attention on the
state's budget, Texas has saved less for the future than about 40
other states in the country. And officials have rejected proposals
to build up the rainy-day savings in recent years, opting instead
to expand some programs and cut taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The appropriate time to fill it up is exactly now because the
economy is growing fast and revenues are coming in quickly,'' said
Dick Lavine of the Austin-based Center for Public Policy
Priorities. ``You can't foresee what sort of situation it would be
used for, but it would probably be for something like we had in the
late '80s,'' when an oil industry bust depleted state revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Lavine and others pointed to the paltry rainy-day fund last week
when state officials revealed $610 million in unexpected overruns
in the current budget, a figure which could be even higher
according to an internal Bush administration memo from May.
</P>
<P>
   The state can use up to $1.1 billion in unexpected surplus
revenues to cover those overruns. But if state surpluses dry up in
the future _ and they are already shrinking _ the Legislature could
be forced to cut spending to cover new overruns, the critics say.
</P>
<P>
   State officials dismiss those arguments as gloom-and-doom
predictions. They say conservative budgeting and the yearly
surpluses _ which may be shrinking but are still around _ will
prevent major fiscal crises.
</P>
<P>
   ``During Governor Bush's tenure, the state has had large
surpluses in the state treasury where the money is earning just as
much interest as it would in the contingency fund. Because of the
state's healthy fiscal status, the Legislature and Governor Bush
saw no need to transfer surplus funds,'' said Bush spokeswoman
Linda Edwards. ``Texas has this tradition of conservative revenue
estimates (which) helps in generating sizable surpluses.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not what happened in 1986 when oil prices plummeted,
state revenues shrank and the Legislature met in an emergency
session to cut spending and raise the sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   In the next statewide election in 1988, voters approved a
constitutional amendment that created the rainy-day fund to save
for the future and help Texas' bond ratings. The fund can legally
hold up to 10 percent of the state's yearly revenues and money can
only be withdrawn with at least a three-fifths vote of the
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   That account has grown from $8 million since Bush took office,
but still falls short of the original goals.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-five percent of oil and natural gas revenues in excess
of the state's revenues from 1987 are supposed to go into it. But
those tax revenues have not usually approached the level where they
were during the boom of the 1980s and have not generated much
money.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty percent of all unused revenue at the end of a budget cycle
also was supposed to be funneled into the fund. But the Legislature
usually spends unused dollars at the end of each two-year budget
cycle, Leedom said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, an array of state leaders _ including Comptroller
Carole Keeton Rylander, House Speaker Pete Laney and Senate
Economic Development chairman David Sibley _ proposed stashing
money from the state's record surplus in the fund. But lawmakers
rejected those ideas in favor of teacher pay raises, an expansion
of children's' health insurance and $1.7 billion in tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Bush supported transferring $471 million of the surplus into the
savings fund when officials said the state was legally required to
do so. But those officials were able to avoid that requirement by
allocating the money elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Rylander will put $48 million from natural gas taxes into the
rainy-day fund after the current fiscal year ends on Aug. 31 and
plans to propose another allocation next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas is a big extended family and like any good family we
need to spend wisely and invest wisely and save for a rainy day,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in most of the 45 other states with rainy-day funds
agree.
</P>
<P>
   Florida automatically allocated 1 percent of the prior year's
revenues to one of its two rainy-day funds until the state's
reserves reached 5 percent of the yearly budget. Massachusetts has
amassed $1.4 billion, also more than 5 percent of its budget, by
sending much of its yearly surplus into a fund.
</P>
<P>
   A 1999 study released by the the Center on Budget and Policy
Priorities in Washington found that Massachusetts and seven other
states have saved enough to survive a recession like the one that
hit a decade ago without raising taxes or cutting spending.
</P>
<P>
   Texas was at the opposite end of that study, one of 11 states
that would have less than 80 percent of the money needed to get
through a recession without tax hikes or spending cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is hoping for another recession,'' the study's authors
concluded, ``but it's only prudent to ask whether states have done
enough to prepare for the next one.''
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Gary Susswein at gsusswein(at)statesman.com or
445-3654.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
