<HEADER>
A5952 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-HNS &LR;      07-18 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PRAISED BY TEXAS DEMOCRAT, 
SCORNED BY OTHERS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ George W. Bush continued to draw fire from Democrats
Tuesday for budgeting shortages in his home state, but Texas'
highest-ranking Democrat praised the GOP governor for his ability
to work with the state Legislature and make the most of his office.
</P>
<P>
   Texas House Speaker Pete Laney didn't endorse Bush's
presidential bid and didn't discuss the budgetary controversy. But
he told state lawmakers from around the country that Bush has
``certainly been successful at achieving his goals'' and in
overcoming the restraints of a structurally weak office.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had asked Laney to introduce him before his speech to the
National Conference of State Legislatures. Laney's comments stood
in stark contrast to the message from other Democrats Tuesday,
including Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Before addressing crime victims at Rhodes College in Memphis,
Tenn., Gore criticized Bush's planning abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just this morning, the Houston Chronicle reported a memorandum
within the Texas state government projecting a $600 million
shortfall in the state's health care program. This apparently will
worsen an already grave budget situation, the worst in Texas in a
long, long time,'' the vice president said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the same policies that put Texas' budget surplus at
risk would threaten the federal government surplus if Bush is
elected.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democratic legislators from Texas also blasted away at
Bush over the budgeting shortfalls, which are estimated at more
than $610 million in Medicaid and a handful of other state
programs. The shortfalls threaten to eat away most of the state's
budgetary surplus.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Garnet Coleman, D-Houston, in a Gore-sponsored
conference call, said he believes the shortfall may be closer to
$750 million than the $610 million announced by legislative leaders
last week and he believes the entire surplus could be gone by the
time lawmakers meet next January.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Gonzalo Barrientos, D-Austin, accused Bush of pushing
a ``trophy tax on the backs of children and seniors, basically
mortgaging the state and people of Texas, most likely because he
was running for president.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrientos' accusation was similar to earlier Democratic
complaints that the $1.7 billion in tax cuts that Bush convinced
lawmakers to enact last year was to blame for the shortfalls. Bush
and legislative budget writers have blamed rising drug costs in the
Medicaid program and other unforeseen factors.
</P>
<P>
   Laney told the legislative conference that the Texas governor's
job is ``made more difficult by the fact that the public perception
and public expectations far exceed the constitutional authority of
the office.''
</P>
<P>
   The speaker said that a successful Texas governor had to be able
to ``persuade, to inspire, to otherwise motivate the people to take
action.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Success is determined more by personality than by power.
Governor Bush has certainly been successful at achieving his
goals,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Laney, who has no Republican re-election opposition in his West
Texas district but could lose the speakership if the GOP gains a
House majority, said that he and Bush have developed a ``close
working relationship, a relationship based on mutual respect and a
desire to serve the best interests of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And our relationship has been made much more enjoyable by the
governor's sense of humor and his ability to work with the
legislative process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who is campaigning hard to woo independent voters and
Democrats to his campaign, took up where Laney left off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of those who are used to the politics of personal
destruction may think it odd that I can stand before you and tell
you that I am a good personal friend with a Democrat speaker, and I
am,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he was ``proud of the accomplishments of our state,
accomplishments as a result of both Republicans and Democrats
coming together to put the people of our state above the interests
of party.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a Chicago news conference sponsored by the Illinois
Democratic Party, Barrientos and state Sen. Mario Gallegos,
D-Houston, said that Texas, under Bush, has fallen woefully short
of meeting the people's needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush brags about being a compassionate conservative,
but he never tells anyone about the colonias or the budget
shortfall or the $33 million that he could have spent, but didn't,
on summer nutrition programs for children,'' Gallegos said.
</P>
<P>
   Gallegos criticized Bush for not visiting the colonias, poverty
stricken communities along the Texas-Mexico border, to ``see tens
of thousands of Texas children who live without water or
electricity.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
