<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5955 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-RUN-TRIALS19-COX     07-18 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-TRIALS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech grad Adkins halts medicine intake in bid to make Olympics
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Derrick Adkins says he has no choice. It is
an Olympic year, the one in four that athletes have to be ready. It
is the summer to take risks, if it will help you get to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Adkins, the gold medalist in Atlanta, had been struggling to
regain his prowess in the 400 hurdles. So, two weeks ago, the
Georgia Tech graduate halted daily intake of the drug that helps
control his depression. He had been on Luvox since being diagnosed
with clinical depression in 1996. ``I figured this is the Olympic
trials, so I have to take a chance,'' Adkins said. ``I know the
medication is affecting me (in races), and I might as well tough it
out and see how I do without it.''
</P>
<P>
   Adkins suffered a series of ``depressive episodes'' when he went
off the drug without telling anyone in the summer of 1996. This
time, however, it's just for the Olympic trials, he says, and it's
with the blessing of his psychiatrist, Dr. Casandra Wanzo. He also
is taking a natural supplement that claims to help control
depression.
</P>
<P>
   The first two rounds in the 400 hurdles are Thursday and Friday,
with the finals Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Derrick has to feel right with it, and he thought it was the
only thing that would give him a chance,'' said his coach, Grover
Hinsdale. ``He's taking a risk of all of a sudden not being able to
sleep, which was a problem in '96, but so far he's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   His parents and older sister are here to monitor him. So far,
the only side effect has been minor headaches. In the past,
insomnia and depression were a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``When depression sets in there are warning signs,'' he said.
``I start to get irritable, like ridiculously irritated by little
things.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a risk he is willing to take. He has found that the
anti-depressant makes him feel lackadaisical, reduces his stamina
and inhibits performance in an event in which one hundredth of a
second can be the difference in making the Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   He began the season running well but was unable to break 50
seconds in his last two European races. Those times won't land him
in the finals, where a low 48-second clocking probably will earn
one of the three spots to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``My performances in Europe made my decision to stop taking (the
drug),'' Adkins said. ``Already, I've noticed a definite change in
my speed workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee my performances will be a lot better at the
trials,'' he said. ``Whether they'll be good enough to make the
Olympic team, I'm not sure. But I know I'll be close.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
