<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5966 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PHILIP-MORRIS-EARNING     07-18 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILIP-MORRIS-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILIP MORRIS PROFIT RISES 5 PERCENT ON FOOD AND CIGARETTE GAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reporting solid growth in its food and cigarette businesses,
Philip Morris said Tuesday that its second-quarter profit rose 5.5
percent, matching Wall Street expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Net income rose to $2.17 billion, or 95 cents a share, compared
with profit from operations of $2.06 billion, or 85 cents a share,
in the quarter a year earlier. Sales rose 5.2 percent, to $20.84
billion from $19.81 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The results were in line with analysts' forecasts, according to
First Call/Thomson Financial, which tracks company earnings.
</P>
<P>
   In the quarter a year earlier, the company took a $45 million
pretax charge to cover the costs of laying off employees in its
domestic tobacco business. That made net income $2.03 billion, or
84 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of cigarettes continued to fall by 1 percent to 2 percent
for the industry over all, but Philip Morris' sales in the United
States increased 3.6 percent, and its market share rose to 51
percent of cigarettes sold at retail outlets from 50.2 percent in
the quarter a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The domestic tobacco division's profits increased by 6.5
percent, the company said, because of higher prices a pack. Revenue
from domestic sales of brands like Marlboro and Merit increased
20.5 percent, to $5.7 billion from $4.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings announcement made no mention of the $145 billion
punitive-damages judgment against Philip Morris and other tobacco
makers by a Florida jury last week. Analysts expect the judgment to
be appealed for years to come and said there would be no material
effect on the companies for a long time, if ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a serious issue, but I think it's very manageable,''
said David Adelman, an analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
Another price increase on cigarettes is expected by Labor Day, with
analysts predicting 12 to 15 cents a pack.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris said sales increased in its international tobacco
and Kraft food divisions, as well. A disappointment was Miller
Brewing Co., where sales dropped by 2.9 percent but profits rose by
8.4 percent because of price increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shipments were weaker than expected, but Miller is such a
small part of their portfolio,'' said Bill Pecoriello, a tobacco
and beverage analyst for Sanford C. Bernstein. ``The profits were
in line, even though shipments were weak.''
</P>
<P>
   On the international tobacco front, Philip Morris said that its
revenue fell 1.8 percent compared with that in the period a year
earlier but that profits increased by 4.6 percent. About 62 percent
of the profits came from sales in Western Europe and Japan, where
volume rose as well. Volume slid in markets like Central and
Eastern Europe, the company said, and duty-free shipments were
lower because of the end of duty-free sales within the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
   The company's Kraft Foods division, which will get much larger
when the acquisition of Nabisco Holdings is completed at the end of
this year, turned in an impressive performance. Sales grew 3.8
percent and profits rose 5.3 percent, generally better than the
industry average. The company credited products like Capri Sun and
Tang beverages, as well as Balance Bar, an energy snack bought
earlier this year. Lunchables and Kraft cheese also showed higher
sales, while Kraft Macaroni and Cheese and Post cereals declined.
</P>
<P>
   The international food business showed lower sales, but profits
rose 5.1 percent, the company said. ``That was the business that
did the best relative to expectations,'' Adelman said. ``If you
adjust for currency impact, the profits were up 12 percent. They
are starting to see the benefits from integrating their sales force
in Europe and showing stronger execution as well as new products.''
</P>
<P>
   The combining of the Nabisco business with Kraft should go
smoothly, Adelman said, although layoffs are expected.
</P>
<P>
   The Nabisco brands include Oreo cookies, Ritz crackers and Life
Savers candy. Philip Morris agreed last month to buy the company
for $14.9 billion, or about $55 a share. It plans to spin off about
20 percent of the combined food company in a public offering next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris also said it bought back 36 million shares of its
stock at a cost of $900 million. The stock has been lagging,
largely because of tobacco litigation. Shares of Philip Morris rose
43.75 cents, to $24.0625.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
