u a BC-CHILDREN-GUNS-HNS &LR;      07-18 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDREN-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILD'S DEATH DOESN'T CHANGE 
PRO-GUN ATTITUDE OF TEXAS TOWN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARVEY RICE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIS, Texas _ The accidental death of a 3-year-old boy who
found a pistol under a mattress has done little to sway strongly
pro-gun sentiment in this Southeast Texas town of 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an old country boy and I'm a firm believer that
individuals should have the right to protect themselves,'' said
Richard Evans, 56, a machine shop owner.
</P>
<P>
   Evans' opinion was typical of Willis residents in an informal
survey following the death last week of Cory Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The boy had been playing in his mother's bedroom and found the 9
mm pistol hidden under the mattress. He was buried Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Firearms killed 84 children age 4 and younger nationwide in
1997, according to the most recently published figures from the
National Center for Health Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, unofficial figures for 1999 from the state Bureau of
Epidemiology show that firearms killed two children age 5 or
younger.
</P>
<P>
   If people age 19 and younger are included, the national figure
is 4,223 and the Texas figure is 21.
</P>
<P>
   Although saddened by Cory Smith's death, many residents of
Willis, about 50 miles north of Houston, said parents bear the
responsibility for keeping children away from guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many kids get killed with guns because of their parents or
grandparents,'' who fail to take safety precautions, Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he is a ``firm believer'' in the use of trigger
locks, and favors a law requiring them.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Stanley, 51, and his wife, Ellen, 41, disagreed, saying
they strongly oppose any sort of gun-control law, including trigger
locks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think they are trying to disarm us,'' said Stanley,
who runs an electronics shop with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hearts go out to that family,'' his wife said. ``I can't
even imagine losing a kid.'' Nevertheless, she said only parents
can prevent such accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is overwhelming antipathy in the community for
gun control, several Willis residents defied the trend. Jose Luis
Garcia, 44, a cook, said, ``I don't think guns should be kept in
the house.''
</P>
<P>
   He said gun-control measures could put an end to the market in
illegal guns.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates from both sides of the gun-control issue interpreted
Cory's death differently.
</P>
<P>
   The number of children killed each year by guns is low, said Don
Kates, criminologist and research fellow at the Pacific Research
Institute for Public Policy, a conservative think tank in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an extremely rare phenomenon,'' Kates said.
``Basically, the number of children killed each year in gun
accidents is about the same number each year killed from eating
iron tablets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is wildly exaggerated,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Brian Morton, spokesman for the Center to Prevent Handgun
Violence based in Washington, D.C., said, ``This isn't a question
of how many kids die from eating iron tablets. The question is,
`Are these deaths preventable?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, it happens a lot more than you would think,''
Morton said. ``People are leaving their guns loaded and unlocked
and kids are getting a hold of them.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 2009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0323 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5973 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-CORRUPTION-     07-18 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-CORRUPTION-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIAN OFFICIAL INVESTIGATING CORRUPTION BECOMES TARGET OF
VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ When Attorney General Marzuki Darusman
began investigating former President Suharto and his family on
charges of corruption last year, he expected strong resistance from
the elite, which benefited greatly under the strongman's rule.
</P>
<P>
   Marzuki, a reformist known for his human rights work, also
expected sharp criticism from leftist groups and student protesters
for not being more aggressive in prosecuting Suharto, who governed
Indonesia for 32 years, until he was forced to step down two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Marzuki said he never expected that his inquiry into whether
Suharto's vast fortune was amassed at public expense would make him
a target of violence, as it did on July 5, when a bomb exploded in
his office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never thought that anyone would go this far, to such an
extreme,'' Marzuki said in an interview in his heavily guarded
office. ``But this shows that we are making progress toward our
goal.''
</P>
<P>
   That goal extends far beyond punishing Suharto and his cronies
for reported abuses. The attorney general said his objective was to
restore the rule of law and a sense of equality to Indonesia, where
corruption permeated nearly every aspect of society under Suharto's
government. That is a colossal task that could cost Marzuki, who
has expressed presidential ambitions, his political career, if not
his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attorney general is one of the few politicians who is
earnestly committed to implementing democracy and establishing the
supremacy of law at great personal risk to himself,'' said Umar
Juoro, director of the Center for Information and Development
Studies, a research group. ``The broader question is how long will
this attorney general last in office, and the answer depends on the
president and Darusman's political and social connections.''
</P>
<P>
   Marzuki, 55, has emerged as perhaps the most prominent minister
of the fledging government of President Abdurrahman Wahid, who took
power in October in Indonesia's first contested presidential
election. Wahid's government has undertaken an ambitious agenda to
rebuild Indonesia, which has the world's fourth-largest population,
into a modern democracy.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But Indonesia has been plagued with political infighting and
rising sectarian violence that has killed thousands of people and
displaced hundreds of thousands more. The government has attributed
much of the unrest to political and military forces that are loyal
to Suharto and seek to destabilize the country.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The police say they believe that Suharto's sympathizers were
behind the bombing of the attorney general's office, which occurred
shortly after one of Suharto's sons had been questioned in
connection with the corruption charges. The blast destroyed part of
a building where the attorney general is compiling records for the
case. The day after the attack, the police defused a second bomb in
the building. Forensic evidence suggests that the explosives were
from the army, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the attack, Marzuki pledged to press the case, which he
plans to hand over to a court for trial sometime before Aug. 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a strong element of apprehension in this office after
the bombing incident,'' he said. ``But we've come so far that we
can't really turn around now. Our investigators feel that the case
is solid and that there's not much the opposition can do to deter
us.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Indeed, it would be hard for Marzuki to back down. When he took
office last year, the attorney general pledged that as a first step
toward restoring confidence in the government he planned aggressive
prosecutions of cases that involved high officials. In addition to
Suharto's case, Marzuki is investigating a political financing
scandal in the banking system and human rights abuses by the
military in Aceh and East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   ``These three cases are crucial, because they will go a long way
in convincing the public that this government has the legitimacy to
clean up this very messy situation,'' Marzuki said. ``At no point
in this country's history has there been greater pressure from the
public to rectify things and correct past ills.''
</P>
<P>
   Marzuki was appointed attorney general last year after having
led the National Commission on Human Rights, where he investigated
complaints against the military over kidnappings, mass killings and
rapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw case after case in which army personnel were committing
grave crimes and being allowed to go scot-free,'' Marzuki said.
``When you see these things firsthand, you don't forget them, and
something inside drives you to want to change the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Marzuki made his mark in political circles as a respected
reformer in the Golkar Party, Suharto's longtime machine. He was
instrumental in rallying party support for Wahid's election.
</P>
<P>
   The eldest son of a former diplomat, Marzuki spent his formative
years living in Mexico, Russia, and Switzerland. He said that as a
youth growing up overseas he first recognized the inequities of
Indonesian society compared with the West.
</P>
<P>
   His critics maintain that although the attorney general has
pursued high-profile cases with fanfare, he has been slow to clean
his own house. Marzuki promised to replace dozens of assistant
attorney generals and senior prosecutors who were known to be
corrupt, but many of them have kept their posts.
</P>
<P>
   J.E. Sahetapy, chairman of the National Law Commission, which
Wahid set up to chart a course for legal reform, said he would
score Marzuki's performance in office a 6.5 out of 10 points.
Sahetapy said he was deeply concerned that the attorney general had
failed to go after Suharto's accomplices in the corruption inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's only pursued the case to a certain point, because many of
his colleagues from his own party are involved,'' Sahetapy said.
``Most of the people who are now in power are involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Marzuki acknowledged that much work was left to be done. ``The
successful prosecution of these cases will only restore minimal
confidence in the system,'' he said. ``Then comes the hard point of
real reform, which will take years if not decades.''
</P>
</TEXT>
