<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MARRIAGE-PENALTY (Washington) _ The Republican-led Senate passes
legislation to provide $248 billion in tax relief to dual-income
couples hit by the so-called ``marriage penalty,'' creating a
potential issue at the Democratic and Republican party conventions
this summer. By STEVE LASH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CELL-PHONES (Washington) _ In an effort to assuage growing
concerns about health risks associated with cellular phones,
manufacturers next month will begin disclosing the level of
microwave radiation emanating from each new phone sold. The action
is designed to assure customers that radiation from the devices
does not exceed government limits. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   PATENT-COLUMBIA (Washington) _ The Senate kills a proposal that
would have extended a lucrative biotechnology patent for Columbia
University after critics complained that it was ``a
special-interest giveaway.'' Sen. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., who led
the fight against the patent extension, says it would have raised
prescription drug prices for people with debilitating diseases. By
JUDY HOLLAND. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-SPAM (Washington) _ The House considers legislation
sponsored by Rep. Gene Green, D-Texas, that would ban unsolicited
e-mail, known in Internet jargon as ``spam.'' By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PEACE-TALKS (Thurmont, Md.) _ Jerusalem becomes the topic of
negotiations as the Israeli-Palestine peace talks enter a crucial,
possibly final day before President Clinton leaves for an
international summit in Japan. Israeli officials tell reporters
that a partial deal might be worked out before Clinton departs Camp
David in rural Maryland. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   CHILDREN-GUNS (Willis, Texas) _ The death of Cody Smith, a boy
who accidentally killed himself after finding a pistol his
stepfather had stuffed between mattresses, saddened people in this
East Texas town. Although the death has not led to a groundswell of
support for gun control, those surveyed now say they are in favor
of trigger guards on weapons. By HARVEY RICE.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Memphis, Tenn.) _ Vice President Al Gore passes out hugs
and listens to the stories of crime victims as he kicks off a
three-day trip spotlighting his planned $685 million, 10-year
crime-fighting package. ``No one should have to go through what
you've been through,'' the Democratic presidential hopeful tells
victims gathered at Rhodes College. By PATTY REINERT. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Chicago) _ Texas George W. Bush draws fire from Democrats
for budget shortages in his home state, but Texas' highest-ranking
Democrat praises the Republican governor for his ability to work
with the state Legislature and make the most of his office. Texas
House Speaker Pete Laney tells state lawmakers from around the
country that Bush has ``certainly been successful at achieving his
goals'' and in overcoming the restraints of a structurally weak
office. By CLAY ROBINSON. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ This is the way Congress and the
White House work these days. With much fanfare, the Republicans
pass something they know President Clinton will veto. Then they
either quietly modify it to get the president's okay or they let
him veto it. The idea is not to build a record but to build an
issue. Playing this game, the House recently voted to kill
AmeriCorps, Clinton's pet project to encourage volunteer national
service. The GOP did it just to get Clinton's goat. By MARIANNE
MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
