<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5977 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOLSHOI-DANCERS-ART-N     07-18 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOLSHOI-DANCERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 AT 20 and 21, BOLSHOI BALLERINAS LEAP INTO STARDOM  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT3 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Svetlana Lunkina and Maria Alexandrova have a
fawnlike delicacy that suggests they might break if touched. But as
the two young Bolshoi Ballet stars talked, in a backstage
conversation on Monday that was filled with laughter and wry
opinions about art and life, it quickly became apparent that
underneath that fragility lay strong wills and stronger senses of
self.
</P>
<P>
   Lunkina, 20, will dance the title role in ``Giselle'' on
Saturday and Sunday afternoons at the New York State Theater in
Manhattan in a new production by the Bolshoi Theater director
Vladimir Vasiliev, in an engagement presented by Lincoln Center
Festival 2000. She is the youngest Bolshoi ballerina ever to tackle
the demanding role.
</P>
<P>
   Alexandrova, 21, will dance Myrtha, the queen of the ghostly,
man-hating Wilis, on Sunday afternoon to Lunkina's Giselle. And
each will perform lead roles in George Balanchine's sumptuous
pure-dance ``Symphony in C'' on Wednesday, Thursday and Friday
nights.
</P>
<P>
   The two are the darlings of ballet critics in Russia and
Britain. In a Bolshoi engagement this spring at the Kennedy Center
in Washington, Alexandrova was praised for the regal grandeur of
her dancing and for her astonishing jumps. ``I'm not satisfied with
it yet,'' she said of her jump, speaking in Russian translated by
Marina Panfilovich.
</P>
<P>
   Lunkina is new to New York, but she has been much talked about
not just for her impressive technique but also for the qualities
Vasiliev sought in his new Giselle. ``After a long gap a young girl
has now joined our company who, it seems to me, answers to the role
of Giselle,'' he told a Russian interviewer before the production's
premiere in 1997, the year Lunkina graduated from the Moscow
Academy of Dance, affiliated with the Bolshoi. ``She is beautiful,
light, graceful, sincere, feminine and what is more her technique
improves before our very eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Lunkina and Alexandrova began to dance at very young ages
in the kind of local amateur children's folk-dance clubs in which
Rudolf Nureyev got his start before going on to the academy. At age
9 Alexandrova, whose father is a state official, saw a television
documentary about the school of the Kirov Ballet, Russia's other
great international troupe, and knew that she must join the Bolshoi
school in Moscow, where she lived. ``My mother was a little
afraid,'' she recalled. ``She knew how hard and how complicated the
life of a ballerina is. But I said I would do it, and I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Alexandrova, Lunkina comes from a family that is not
involved in the arts except for her sister, Julia, who has just
graduated from the Bolshoi school. Her father prints scholarly
texts, and her mother is a former circus gymnast who understood her
older daughter's psychological makeup very well, Lunkina said,
laughing. ``I did not dream of being a ballerina,'' she said. Early
in life, she had answered a casual yes to her mother's even more
casual question, ``Would you like to dance?''
</P>
<P>
   At 12, she told her mother she wanted to leave the school. The
life of a ballerina was too hard. ``So leave,'' her mother told
her, wisely allowing her willful daughter to decide. ``Do as you
like.'' Lunkina laughed. ``My mother knew if she told me to stay, I
would never do it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about their dance heroes during training, both dancers
immediately mentioned their earliest teachers at the Bolshoi.
Alexandrova's began her training with Liudmila Kolenchenko.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all so afraid of her,'' Alexandrova said. ``And we all
adored her. She was very strict, but she loved us all.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexandrova knew that her parents adored her, too, she said.
``But here was a person who I understood, who did her best to
explain to me what I needed in order to do something in my life.
She taught us to have professional discipline. And we were small
children then, so everything was emotional for us. The graduates
seemed like gods. I think nowadays the attitude of small children
is different. But ballet was sacred for us.'' Alexandrova, who
finished her training with Sofia Golovkina, went on to win a gold
medal in the 1997 Moscow International Ballet Competition and to
create lead roles in Boris Eifman's ``Russian Hamlet'' and a
revival of Petipa's ``Pharaoh's Daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Lunkina's beloved first teacher was Natalia Savina. ``She must
have had a hard job,'' she said. ``I had a very nasty character.
But she soothed me. She told me I must and I did.'' Part of the
problem was that Lunkina loved swimming, painting and singing as
much as ballet and lost her voice for two years because of overuse.
</P>
<P>
   Another crucial person in her life was Marina Leonova, her
teacher and coach in her last years of training. Leonova brought
Lunkina to the attention of Bolshoi Ballet personnel, among them
Vasiliev and his wife, Ekaterina Maximova, the former leading
Bolshoi ballerina, who coached the awestruck teen-ager in the role
of the betrayed Giselle.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me those rehearsals with her were the most dear and most
sacred,'' Lunkina said. ``I tried to listen to every word and note
of her. ``I was so afraid I wouldn't cope. It was such a
responsibility, because I didn't think myself such a genius to
dance Giselle at 18. In any case my first Giselle was a Giselle of
my emotions exclusively. I gave every corner of myself at that
performance and only because of this was it a success. I was living
Giselle's life onstage.''
</P>
<P>
   The two ballerinas said they hoped New York audiences would see
the human beings inside their Giselle and Myrtha. And ``Symphony in
C,'' which demands such a different kind of dancing? ``They
shouldn't see how hard it is,'' Alexandrova said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh! `Symphony!''' Lunkina said with a sigh. ``I would like the
whole company, and especially myself, to show the beauty, strength
and emotions of this ballet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
