<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-OUTCOME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEGOTIATORS SEEK CONCLUSION BEFORE DEADLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ Working in a state of heightened tension as an
early morning deadline loomed, Middle East negotiators Tuesday
night raced toward conclusion, struggling to reach some form of
agreement in the hours before President Clinton's scheduled
departure for Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very crucial moment,'' Israeli immigration minister
Yuli Tamir said in a telephone interview. ``We're going back and
forth, and the negotiations are in full swing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The pace has picked up,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart
said. ``There are intense discussions, and negotiations going on
right now between the two parties. I think they understand what we
are up against here.''
</P>
<P>
   One of three outcomes seemed likely: That negotiators would
reach a full-blown agreement, that they would settle for
incremental progress, or that they would go home with none of the
core issues resolved. But details were scarce, and it appeared any
deal would have to come well after midnight, as delegates from all
sides worked virtually around the clock within confines of the
presidential compound.
</P>
<P>
   As of Tuesday evening, only one thing was clear: That talks to
end the 52-year conflict were increasingly strenuous, with Clinton
and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak meeting until 4:30 a.m. on
Monday before taking a five-hour break and starting again Tuesday.
Despite rumors about the nature of the discussions _ in particular
that Israel was considering a deal that would recognize a
Palestinian state _ White House officials refused to give details
of what was being said.
</P>
<P>
   They did, however, sound firmly committed to wrapping up before
Clinton leaves for another summit in Japan. After eight days of
news briefings, Lockhart declared that Tuesday night's would be his
last. And he said that when Clinton leaves Wednesday at around 8
a.m., ``he will have done his business here.''
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with Barak on Sunday night, Clinton met with
Palestinian leader Yassir Arafat Tuesday for about an hour,
officials said. Arafat and Barak have met face-to-face only four
times since the summit started nine days ago, and have not done so
since last week.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are four key issues: the fate of Palestinian refugees;
territory and borders; Israeli security; and control over
Jerusalem. The debates are considered so difficult that leaders
have postponed negotiating them throughout the last seven years of
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton could still postpone his trip for up to a day. He would
miss scheduled talks with the Japanese leader, but still be on time
for the summit of leading industrialized nations that begins in
Okinawa on Friday. US officials, by restating their determination
to leave, seemed to be once again sending a message to negotiators
to make final concessions in time for Clinton's departure.
</P>
<P>
   As the talks intensified, teenage Israeli settlers gathered in
protest about five miles from Camp David at the Thurmont Senior
Center, across the street from the site where US officials have
been briefing reporters for the last week. A senior member of the
Israeli opposition, Likud party member Uzi Landau, also arrived at
the site, warning journalists that the reports being leaked out of
the talks were a ``reason for grave concern.'' In the background, a
group of American Jewish campgoers chanted and played the drums in
the name of peace.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of miles away, the speaker of the Israeli Parliament,
Avraham Burg, suggested Barak might agree to the recognition of a
Palestinian state. Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has long said
he would declare an independent state on Sept. 13 if no other
compromise can be reached; Burg, who has been in frequent contact
with Barak throughout the talks, said formally recognizing a
Palestinian state could move the peace process forward, especially
since Israel may be faced with a self-self-declared state in less
than two months, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, let's not fool ourselves, OK?'' Burg said. ``If it
walks like a duck, if it talks like a duck, if it sounds like a
duck, it's a Palestinian state.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials strongly cautioned against taking such
outside musings as fact. Spokesman Lockhart, who has ridiculed
press accounts of the talks all week, said ``the batting average of
reports coming out of people who are not here has not improved.''
</P>
<P>
   Other rumors continued to surface, including one that the talks
had broken down completely, with Arafat threatening to abandon
negotiation. But veterans of past peace talks said that a tantrum
often precedes a breakthrough, and Lockhart said he had not heard
either side was planning to walk out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy it'd be a long walk. You gotta go all the way down the
mountain,'' Lockhart joked.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, in between two long meetings with Barak,
Clinton telephoned US House Speaker Dennis Hastert to give him an
update on the talks. Hastert denied Clinton talked specifically
about how much finacial assistance the United States would be
willing to contribute to a peace deal. But in interviews, Hastert,
an Illinois Republican, refused to offer a blank check.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reiterated again that if it is a large dollar number, if
there is an agreement, talk to us,'' Hastert said. ``We have to
appropriate that money. It is the job of Congress to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart responded to the remarks with caution. ``I think
everyone should just hold their fire on what they think it should
be, what they think it shouldn't be, until we've got something in
place and we can actually look at what the real needs are,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Charles M. Sennott of the Globe Staff contributed to this report
from Jerusalem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
