<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-EARNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT SAYS PROFITS ROSE 20 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Microsoft Corp. may have been battered in courts
and in the stock market this past year. But the software giant
remains a formidable money-making machine, Tuesday reporting a 20
percent increase in its annual profits.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, in an announcement after the market close, posted
profits of $9.42 billion on revenue of $22.96 billion for its
fiscal year ended June 30. Last year, the company earned $7.79
billion on $19.75 billion in revenue. For its fourth quarter, the
Redmond, Wash., company recorded profits of $2.41 billion, or 44
cents a share, on revenue of $5.8 billion, soundly beating
expectations of 42 cents a share by 27 Wall Street analysts
surveyed by Zacks Investment Research.
</P>
<P>
   For Microsoft, the earnings report comes as a welcome break from
the drumbeat of setbacks the company has experienced in its
unsuccessful attempts to fend off a U.S. Department of Justice
antitrust lawsuit and the resulting slide in the company's once
high-flying stock.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's shares rallied 31.25 cents to close at $78.50 on the
Nasdaq. That's up from a 17-month low of $61.4375 on May 26, but
still far below the company's 52-week high attained on Dec. 30 of
$117.625. In after-hours trading, the Redmond, Wash. company's
shares gained another 37.5 cents to $78.875.
</P>
<P>
   That Microsoft's shares have fared so poorly in recent months
contrasts with what many analysts consider to be a company with a
solid balance sheet and robust profits. That has left money
managers in a quandary over whether to buy, sell, or hang on to
their shares in the company.
</P>
<P>
   For now, most stock pickers have been reluctant to relinquish
their considerable holdings in Microsoft, in part due to the
company's habit of turning in financial results that beat Wall
Street's expectations every quarter since 1994. As a result, one in
every three U.S. stock mutual funds continues to hold Microsoft
shares, despite the stock's rocky performance this year, according
to figures from Morningstar, a mutual fund research company in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft projected its growth will slow in the coming fiscal
year as a result of its increased investment in research on
technology not based on the company's traditional stronghold in
personal computers, where it has a 90 percent share in the market
for operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts, Microsoft's chief financial
officer, John Connors, said it will step up spending on research
and development by 15 percent this year to about $4.4 billion on
such areas as mobile devices, home entertainment products, and
Internet-related products.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft's most anticipated initiative, the so-called
Microsoft.net project announced earlier this year, will have no
effect on revenues this year and is not expected to contribute to
the company's bottom line until the year 2002, Connors said.
</P>
<P>
   In the company's characteristically conservative manner, Connors
downplayed his company's ability to continue its winning streak. He
projected that growth in revenues would slow to 15 percent for the
fiscal year 2001, slightly lower than the 16 percent the company
reported for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Connors said 3 million licenses have been sold for Microsoft's
current flagship operating system, Windows 2000, since the product
was introduced in Feb. 17. But he ascribed a ``sluggishness'' in
sales of Windows 2000 to the fact that the product is aimed at
companies, which tend to switch operating systems far more slowly
than consumers. The consumer version of Microsoft's newest
operating system for consumers, Windows ME, is not expected to ship
until September.
</P>
<P>
   Connors made no mention of an ongoing inquiry by the U.S.
Securities Exchange Commission into Microsoft's accounting
practices. Last year, Microsoft disclosed that the SEC had launched
a probe into allegations by a former Microsoft employee that the
company manipulates its substantial cash reserves to ``smooth
over'' quarterly fluctuations in profits and assure a stable
progression in revenues.
</P>
<P>
   A Microsoft spokewoman said the SEC investigation was ``still
pending.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
