<P>
   EDs: Will move spot on the NYT wire in (i) International and (w)
Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-CULTURE _ LONDON _ Take a walk in Brixton. Four miles
from the gray postcard propriety of Westminster, Brixton is a riot
of noise and color. It pulsates with hefty bass riffs and reggae
rhythms dancing from knee-high speakers on the sidewalks outside CD
stores and appliance shops. In the borough's lively street market,
you hear the melodious sounds of Yoruba, Shona, Arabic, Spanish ?
occasionally even English. No less than Parliament House with Big
Ben and Churchill's statue, however, Brixton now is a part of the
fiber of modern London, a city rapidly being redefined by its
ethnic variety. ``Multiracial London is coming of age, and it is
this that is igniting such energy, buzz and creativity,'' wrote
Yasmin Alibhair-Brown, a columnist for the Independent newspaper
and author of ``Who Do We Think We Are: Imagining the New
Britain.'' (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
