<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5984 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH19-COX     07-18 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Survey: Some GOP delegates support pro-choice VP
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ As Gov. George W. Bush moves toward a decision on a
running mate, a survey of GOP delegates shows that nearly half
would support him if he chose someone who supports abortion rights,
according to an Associate Press poll released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 1,767 out of 2,066 GOP delegates found that 49
percent said they would support Bush if he chose a running mate
such as Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge. Twenty-two percent said they
would not back an abortion-rights supporter and 15 percent said
they didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   Those surveyed listed Ridge as their first choice followed
closely by Elizabeth Dole with Rep. John Kasich, of Ohio, retired
Gen. Colin Powell and Arizona Sen. John McCain. About half the
delegates did not respond to the questionnaire.
</P>
<P>
   Ridge, a Catholic from a key swing state, supports Roe v. Wade.
He opposes government financing for abortions and the late-term
procedure dubbed ``partial birth'' by opponents. Like Bush, he
supports parental notification for minors seeking abortions. New
Jersey Gov. Christie Todd Whitman, who has also been mentioned as a
possible running mate, infuriated members of her party when she
vetoed a measure to outlaw so-called partial birth abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Scott McClellan would not say if the survey could
bolster their chances, adding that Bush ``has been considering a
diverse group.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As he has said, he'll make a decision based on three
criteria,'' McClellan said. ``Are they ready to be president? Do
they share his conservative views? And will they be loyal.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush wound up a two-day campaign trip in Chicago Tuesday by
announcing $200 million plan to promote responsible fatherhood.
Later, in a speech before the National Conference of State
Legislatures, Bush called states ``the laboratories of change,''
and traded quips with Democratic Texas House Speaker Pete Laney,
who joined him on stage at the Navy Pier Convention Center with
Republican Lt. Gov. Rick Perry.
</P>
<P>
   Bush returned to Austin Tuesday after an evening fundraiser in
Chicago expected to raise $2.25 million. He remains in Austin today
as the political world waits to hear who he will choose as his
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by Perry and Laney at the National Conference of State
Legislatures, Bush continued portraying himself as a governor able
to reach across party lines.
</P>
<P>
   The speech, a promise to ``restore civility on the national
level,'' echoed the first address Bush made in Washington after
securing the Republican nomination during the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Bush told the audience that Washington can learn
from the Texas Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second biggest state in the union and we only meet four
months out of every two years,'' he said. ``I guess our motto is if
government doesn't meet it can't hurt you. And yet it may not be a
bad lesson for Washington, D.C. come to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In his introduction, Laney offered the audience a brief lesson
in Texas legislative history, making it clear that the governor
wields little real power, and ultimately chalking Bush's successes
up to his talent for playing well with others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being the chief executive of any state is a difficult job, but
in Texas it's made more difficult by the fact that public
perception and public expectations far exceed the constitutional
authority of the office of governor,'' Laney said. ``...Success is
determined more by personality than the exercise of power and Gov.
Bush has certainly been successful at achieving his goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush shot back with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to be on the stage with two distinguished Texans.
Well, two Texans,'' he said, going on to call Laney, ``a good man
and a good friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Laney _ a Democrat in a state where many in his party are
backing Bush _ has not said whether he will offer an endorsement.
And he wasn't eager to probe that question after his appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's appearance with Laney came on a day that another national
poll, by USA Today newspaper, shows support for Vice President Gore
creeping up while support for Bush slowly eroding.
</P>
<P>
   Of 1,063 adults surveyed, 48 percent said they would support
Bush and 46 percent said they would support Gore in a two-way race.
The poll, with a 3 percentage point margin of error, comes one week
after another USA Today Poll had Bush leading Gore 50 percent to 41
percent.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   '
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
