<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5988 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-SENATE-MARRIAGE-TAX-A     07-18 1321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-MARRIAGE-TAX-ART-880&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE APPROVES TAX CUT FOR MARRIED COUPLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate on Tuesday passed a tax cut for married
couples, taking a big step in the election-year push by Republicans
to highlight their differences with Democrats over what to do with
the federal budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 61-38, with eight Democrats joining Republicans to
approve the measure, which would reduce taxes for nearly all
married couples by $248 billion over the next 10 years. One
Republican voted against.
</P>
<P>
   A similar though somewhat smaller measure passed the House
earlier this year. Republican leaders said they would act quickly
to meld the two versions and send the legislation to President
Clinton, who said he would veto it as too costly and too tilted to
the wealthiest taxpayers at a time when the needs of lower- and
middle-income people are going unmet.
</P>
<P>
   But in an acknowledgment that tax reductions appear to be
gaining political appeal at a time of growing budget surpluses,
Clinton reiterated his willingness to negotiate a compromise under
which he would accept a tax cut for couples of the scale sought by
Republicans if Congress would accept his plan to add prescription
drug coverage to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans showed no inclination to take him up on the offer,
and said that a veto would help them make their case that Democrats
are standing in the way of popular tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed by the Senate was packaged by Republicans as a
reduction in the marriage penalty, the quirk in the tax code that
leaves many two-income couples paying a higher tax bill than they
would if they had remained single.
</P>
<P>
   But it would cut taxes for almost all married couples, whether
or not they pay a marriage penalty. The bill would not cut taxes
for single people.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said the bill was good economic and social policy
because it would help to eliminate what they see as an unfair levy
on marriage while advancing their agenda of returning as much of
the surplus as possible to taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   They said their case was only helped on Tuesday by the release
of new surplus projections by the Congressional Budget Office.
</P>
<P>
   The budget office said it now expects the surplus outside of
Social Security to total nearly $2.2 trillion over the next 10
years, assuming that government spending grows in line with
inflation. The surplus projection is about $300 billion higher than
a similar estimate made last month by the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill is the centerpiece of our efforts to reduce the tax
overpayment by American families,'' said Sen. William V. Roth Jr.,
R-Del., and chairman of the Finance Committee. ``I would ask those
who oppose this family tax relief: Just how big will America's
budget surplus have to get before America's families deserve to
receive some of their tax dollars back?''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the Republican leader, said the
new surplus projections might allow Congress to phase in some of
the provisions in the bill more quickly than planned. He said House
and Senate negotiators would consider that issue as they work to
reconcile their versions of the legislation this week.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said the bill suffered from a truth-in-advertising
problem, since it did not completely eliminate the marriage penalty
and provided a tax cut even to couples, mostly those in which only
one spouse works, who benefit from a marriage bonus _ that is, they
pay a lower tax bill because they are married than they would if
they had remained single.
</P>
<P>
   More important, Democrats said, Republicans had shown once again
that their main goal is to provide tax breaks to upper-income
people, even if doing so required gambling with the country's
economic future on the dubious proposition that the surpluses will
materialize as projected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the surplus projections are the fiscal equivalent
of the dot-com stock market,'' said Sen. Tom Daschle of South
Dakota, the Democratic leader.
</P>
<P>
   Both the House and the Senate have now passed both the tax cut
for married couples and the other main Republican tax bill this
year, the repeal of the federal estate tax. Republicans are also
pressing ahead with other tax bills, including an expansion of
individual retirement accounts and 401(k) retirement plans and a
reduction in the tax levied on some Social Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Although polls have repeatedly found that voters do not see tax
cuts as a priority, Republicans remain wedded to them ideologically
and continue to put them at the heart of their political strategy.
They say that individuals can better decide how to spend the money
than government, and that leaving budget surpluses in Washington
will lead inevitably to an increase in the size and reach of the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to do all we can in terms of allowing the American
people to keep more of their money,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats acknowledged that specific tax cuts, including the
bill passed on Tuesday, have some political appeal, and they are
increasingly offering their own tax agenda that is focused on
providing tax breaks to low- and middle- income people. But they
said the Republicans are heading for political trouble by weighting
their tax cuts heavily toward the wealthy and ignoring middle--
class concerns like the costs of college tuition and child care.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``While I strongly support targeted marriage penalty relief, the
marriage penalty bill put forth by the majority in Congress is one
part of a fiscally irresponsible, poorly targeted and regressive
tax plan,'' Clinton said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation passed on Tuesday would increase the standard
deduction for married couples filing jointly, starting next year,
so that it is twice the standard deduction for single taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   The deduction is adjusted each year for inflation. For this
year, the standard deduction for couples filing jointly is $7,350,
or 1.67 times more than the deduction for single people, which is
$4,400. Excluding any change for inflation, the legislation would
increase the deduction for couples filing jointly next year to
$8,800.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also gradually change the income levels covered
by the two lowest income tax brackets, 15 percent and 28 percent,
so that the brackets for married couples filing jointly would grow
to cover twice as much income as for single people.
</P>
<P>
   The brackets change each year to adjust for inflation. For this
year, the 15 percent bracket covers the first $26,250 of income for
single people and 1.67 times more _ $43,850 _ for couples filing
jointly. The 28 percent brackets pick up where the 15 percent
brackets end, and under current law extend to $63,550 for single
people and to 1.67 times more, $105,950, for couples filing
jointly.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would increase the size of the brackets for
couples filing jointly in steps over the next six years until they
cover twice the income levels covered by the brackets for single
people.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also give a tax break to married couples who
claim the earned income tax credit, which is a rebate for
low-income working people. And it would keep certain other tax
credits for families, including the child and dependent care
credits, from being reduced by the alternative minimum tax.
</P>
<P>
   The eight Democrats who voted for the bill were Sens. Joseph
Biden of Delaware, Robert Byrd of West Virginia, Max Cleland of
Georgia, Dianne Feinstein of California, Bob Kerrey of Nebraska,
Herb Kohl of Wisconsin, Mary Landrieu of Louisiana and Robert
Torricelli of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican who voted against the bill was Sen. George
Voinovich of Ohio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
