u a BC-TRAINS-HORNS-NYT     07-18 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAINS-HORNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLARING LOCOMOTIVE HORNS SPUR A BATTLE IN CONGRESS
</HEADLINE>
 By ERIC SCHMITT  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Never mind that House Speaker Dennis Hastert (R.,
Ill.) has been busy backing Republican election-year bills to cut
taxes and provide prescription drugs to the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, he took up the cudgels to deal with something that
really keeps his constituents up at night, tossing and turning.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare appearance as a star witness at a congressional
hearing, the speaker led a parade of critics who attacked a
proposed federal regulation that would require trains to blow their
horns at railroad crossings, a step to help avoid accidents with
cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impact of the rule on my constituents and the people of
Illinois'' cannot be overstated, Hastert told a House
Transportation and Infrastructure subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Many states have already adopted similar rules. But, in a clash
between public safety and quality of life, a squadron of
legislators and civic leaders complained on Tuesday that the
federal regulation, while well meaning, would unleash a cacophony
of klaxons in hundreds of cities, towns and hamlets along rail
lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crossings along many lines are located so closely together
that train engineers might as well tape the horn button down: there
will be simply no break in the noise,'' said Miguel d'Escoto,
deputy chief of staff to Chicago's mayor, Richard M. Daley. ``The
mental stress and strain on our residents will be unimaginable.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 400 people a year die in collisions at railroad
crossings. Half the fatalities occur at crossings already equipped
with gates and flashing lights, which drivers sometimes ignore.
</P>
<P>
   To address the hazard, Congress passed a law in 1994 mandating
that trains toot their horns as they approach rail crossings. But
it was only this January, after several delays, that the Federal
Railroad Administration published the proposed rule to carry out
the law. The proposal is now being subjected to a period of public
comment, and the railroad agency hopes to have the issue resolved
by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, 34 states and scores of local communities had
already approved their own whistle-blowing statutes, which
incorporated alternatives to the ear-splitting warnings.
</P>
<P>
   But the railroad agency questioned some of these options, citing
a 1995 study that showed crashes are 84 percent more likely to
occur at crossings where whistles are banned than at crossings
where horns routinely sound.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever there are passenger or freight trains, from Long Island
and New Jersey to San Diego, the issue of horns versus harmony has
roiled communities. But nowhere is the matter as contentious as it
is in and around Chicago, a hub of the nation's rail operations.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago transportation experts say that train whistles blaring
at 85 decibels or louder would rattle about 725,000 city residents,
with the brunt falling on poor neighborhoods near the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   And that is why Hastert, who represents Illinois' 14th
Congressional District, just west of Chicago, is involved. One of
out of every five railroad crossings in Illinois is in the
speaker's district.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert and other critics of the rule want the federal agency to
give local communities more flexibility in devising quieter means
to meet the safety standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must reserve a whistle-free option for our communities,''
Rep. Gil Gutknecht (R.-Minn.), said at the hearing on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, the railroad administration would accept as
substitutes for horn-blowing a range of safety measures, from
four-gate crossings and median barriers to photo enforcement and
closing rail crossings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many ways to skin this cat,'' said John V. Wells,
the agency's administrator. ``We are well aware that this is a
controversial issue.''
</P>
<P>
   But many of these options are costly and a drain on the coffers
of small towns. A flashing-signal system can cost $60,000, the
Transportation Department says, and a gate across one lane can cost
$15,000. An overpass can run $2 million to $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Even as states like Illinois move to replace simple
``crossbuck'' railroad crossing signs, funding to fix these most
dangerous rail-auto intersections may be siphoned away, critics
warned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposed rule could actually have the unintended
consequence of decreasing rail safety,'' Hastert said, because
states would spend so much money placating residents of populous
areas, smaller towns would not have enough financing to fix
problems at their dangerous rail crossings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public pressure to shield highly populated communities from
noise will undoubtedly overcome the need to upgrade the dangerous
crossings,'' Hastert said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 2023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
