<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0333 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5990 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r b BC-DRIVE-IN-TEX     07-18 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRIVE-IN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK TO THE FUTURE: DRIVE-IN MOVIES MAKING COMEBACK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
 By BILL HANNA 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABILENE, Texas _ The rebirth of the Town and Country Drive-In
made Henry Perez feel 20 years younger.
</P>
<P>
   As a brilliant evening sky of pinks and blues surrounded the
theater's 100-foot-screen on Saturday night, Perez extolled the
virtues of the drive-in and shared memories with his wife, Leslie.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not in a box with walls on either side,'' the
41-year-old Perez said. ``And you've got the West Texas sunset.''
</P>
<P>
   The reopening of the Town and Country 11 days ago is another
sign, enthusiasts say, of a drive-in resurgence after decades of
ever-declining numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time is right,'' said its owner, Ray Andress. ``Everybody
wants to return to the good old days, and this is as close as some
of us are going to get to that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Perezes are a perfect example. They were regulars at the
Town and Country before it closed in September 1981. This time,
they brought along two teen-age daughters and a couple of nieces.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came all the time back then _ and we watched the movie,''
Perez said, gesturing in the direction of his daughters who already
knew the lore of drive-ins as notorious make-out spots.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, two other drive-ins have flickered back to
life. In August, the Tower Drive-In in Rule, 70 miles northwest of
Abilene, which is 150 miles west of Fort Worth, returned after the
community rallied to rebuild its tornado-ravaged screen.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in 1999, Amarillo's Tascosa Drive-In also opened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fact that one opened in Abilene and another in
Amarillo is good,'' said Fort Worth native Don Sanders, who
co-authored ``Drive-In Movie Memories'' with his wife, Susan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since 1995, there have probably been 30 drive-ins reopen or
built from scratch across the country,'' said Sanders, who
maintains a drive-in Web site, www.americandrivein.com. ``I think
the tone has really changed, and we now know they're always going
to be around. There was a time when we couldn't have said that.''
</P>
<P>
   In North Texas, only two remain, Granbury's Brazos Drive-In
southwest of Fort Worth and the Graham Drive-In, northwest. Dallas'
Astro Drive-In never reopened after its concession stand burned
down in 1998. The Mansfield Drive-In in southeast Fort Worth,
Tarrant County's last outdoor theater, disappeared in the early
'90s.
</P>
<P>
   Abilene's Town and Country could easily have followed a similar
path. A fence fell down, a pond in the middle of the parking lot
became a sinkhole and one of its two screens was torn down.
</P>
<P>
   The only signs of life were the vagrants who used the concession
stand as their home and the pump jacks sucking oil from below the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a lot of work just getting open,'' said the
45-year-old Andress, who has sunk $200,000 into the Town and
Country, where he worked as a projectionist in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concession stand was condemned. We had to fight with the
oil company who owned the pump jacks'' and opposed the theater's
reopening, he said. ``But I never lost faith that we would open.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenda Thornton, his business partner and girlfriend, wasn't
always so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we did didn't make it look any better,'' Thornton
said. ``There were times I hated that place. I threw horrible
temper tantrums but finally it started looking better.''
</P>
<P>
   After the opening, Thornton's mood brightened as she greeted
customers at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   ``They show up and don't even know what's showing, and they
don't care,'' Thornton said. ``They just want to come in and take a
look.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple is promoting the theater as family entertainment in
conservative Abilene, home to three church-related universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that everybody know we're a family-type
business,'' Thornton said. ``We're in Abilene, Texas, and we got
more churches than anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   To attract a budget-conscious crowd, Andress has set concession
prices lower than his indoor competitors. At $2.25, a jumbo popcorn
costs about half what it does at an indoor theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting known as the `50-cent pickle man' for our cheap
pickles,'' Andress said. ``I want people to be able to come out and
have a hamburger or some nachos and not break the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   For those more interested in the movie, Andress is broadcasting
digital and Dolby sound into car radios. He is also thinking about
reviving recent hits like ``The Matrix'' during slower weeknights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm willing to try anything that will bring people out,'' said
Andress, former United Artists sound technician and projectionist,
warming to the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking of putting in a bandstand below the screen. I'm
thinking of putting in outdoor seats. I want to have a night for
the neighborhood who lives around the theater. I want to be known
as a promoter.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, the drive-in authority, suggested that a friendly
ambience will be as important as what's on the screen at the Town
and Country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been to the Brazos in Granbury seven or eight times and
never watched the movie,'' Sanders said. ``The last time I was
there I talked to two Elvis experts from Euless for two and a half
hours. Now I'll probably never talk to them again, but that was
fun. And that's what drive-ins are all about.''
Here's a list of drive-in theaters in Texas:
</P>
<P>
   1. Brazos Drive-In
</P>
<P>
   Granbury
</P>
<P>
   (817) 573-1311 or (817) 573-8086
</P>
<P>
   Open Friday through Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   2. Graham Drive-In, Graham
</P>
<P>
   (940) 549-8478
</P>
<P>
   3. Town and Country Drive-In, Abilene.
</P>
<P>
   (915) 677-9899
</P>
<P>
   4. Tower Drive-In Theater, Rule
</P>
<P>
   (877) 986-9373 or (940) 997-1300
</P>
<P>
   5. The Last Drive-In Picture Show, Gatesville
</P>
<P>
   (254) 865-8445.
</P>
<P>
   6. Sky-Vue Drive-In Theatre, Lamesa
</P>
<P>
   (806) 872-7004.
</P>
<P>
   7. Valley Drive-In Theatre, McAllen
</P>
