<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWBOYS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cowboys open training camp workouts with a spiffy new offense
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas - By the end of a two-hour practice
Tuesday, Troy Aikman was dripping with sweat, fatigued from
throwing deep pass after deep pass to Joey Galloway and Rocket
Ismail.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we keep throwing into the wind like this, I'm not going to
have an arm left by the end of training camp,'' the Dallas Cowboys
quarterback said on the first day of summer workouts under the
unforgiving Texas sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman threw long and intermediate passes to a group of
receivers all trying to make a positive impression.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the same offense now-departed Coach Chan Gailey ran
the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Everything is different. Blocking patterns have changed. Pass
routes have changed. Aikman now throws timing passes that were so
successful during the Super Bowl glory days. There are very few of
the short routes that ruined Gailey's regime.
</P>
<P>
   The new architect: Jack Reilly, a former Cowboys assistant and
new Cowboys offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack Reilly is a riverboat gambler,'' head coach Dave Campo
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times, I thought we were conservative in the old days. We
got set in what we could do. Jack is more unpredictable in his
play-calling, which will be a plus for us. I want to be
unpredictable.''
</P>
<P>
   Those should be refreshing words for anyone who watched the
Cowboys finish 16th in the NFL in total offense last season. After
a good start, Gailey's offense died in November and December, and
he was released after the Cowboys made an early playoff exit.
</P>
<P>
   Team owner Jerry Jones vowed that would not happen again.
</P>
<P>
   Jones made some aggressive moves this year, hiring Campo and
Reilly and bringing back offensive guru Ernie Zampese as a
consultant. He lured Galloway from Seattle to add speed to the
offense, and signed veteran tight end Jackie Harris from Tennessee
as another possible weapon.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1 priority of training camp is to revitalize the
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The object is to score points, whatever it takes,'' Reilly
said. ``If that means running the ball, fine. But we want to be
aggressive and go after people with both the running game and the
passing game.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman has praised the offense, which allows him to run designed
plays rather than being forced to improvise.
</P>
<P>
   The timing-based offense the Cowboys have employed was designed
30 years ago by former San Diego Chargers coach Don Coryell. With
Hall of Famer Dan Fouts at quarterback, the offense was wildly
successful. Other teams, including Washington and Dallas,
eventually copied the schemes. St. Louis used a similar attack in
its Super Bowl victory over Tennessee this year.
</P>
<P>
   No player appeared more excited about the offense than Harris,
who signed with the Cowboys shortly after the Titans were beaten in
the Super Bowl. In Dallas, Harris sees an opportunity to work with
a quarterback whose passing accuracy has never been debated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played in some offenses where the quarterback doesn't see
you,'' Harris said after Tuesday's practice. ``I was running down
the sideline in mini-camp, and I know Troy didn't see me, and all
of a sudden the ball was right there. The guy sees the field so
well. If you get open, you'd better be prepared to catch the ball
because he's going to find you.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo set the tone in camp by demanding an up-tempo practice.
Galloway and Ismail ensure that Dallas will have one of the fastest
receiver tandems in the league. The coach wants everyone on both
sides of the football to keep their motors running at all times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm well aware that offenses bring people into the stands,''
Campo said. ``I understand what offenses mean in this league. There
is no question that when you look throughout the league, the team
with the most points wins. I'm excited about this.''
</P>
<P>
   So is his boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team, with young talent coupled with an effective Troy
Aikman, can get it all,'' Jones said. ``I say that without
reservation.''
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Rick Cantu at rcantu(at)statesman.com or
445-3953.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
