u p BC-REFORM-BUCHANAN-NYT &LR;      07-18 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-BUCHANAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE HURDLE LEFT BEFORE BUCHANAN ASSUMES CONTROL OF REFORM PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After months of aggressive efforts to place his loyalists in key
positions on the Reform Party's national committee and as state
delegates to the party's nominating convention next month, Pat
Buchanan is poised to take full control of a party he joined less
than a year ago after abandoning his Republican roots.
</P>
<P>
   His ultimate triumph depends on what happens at a special
session of the Reform national committee, planned for Aug. 8, the
day before the party's convention opens in Long Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   There, if the final pieces fall into place, as expected, the
party's governing board will ratify a Buchanan ally as head of the
convention's credentials committee, virtually assuring that most
disputes over the seating of delegates will be resolved in
Buchanan's favor.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly. the move will mark a major turning point in
the party's brief and turbulent history, effectively ending Ross
Perot's control, power and influence over a political organization
he founded eight years ago as an alternative to Republicans and
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   It would clear Buchanan's path to the Reform Party's
presidential nomination and the $12.5 million in federal campaign
funds that goes with it.
</P>
<P>
   And it would give Buchanan, for the first time, a home for his
own well-organized, deep-rooted, right-wing political machine to
promote socially conservative causes, like opposition to abortion
rights, that Perot's Reform Party left out of the platform as too
divisive.
</P>
<P>
   While critics of Buchanan say his vision of the Reform Party
would, in effect, pick up where the Christian Coalition left off,
his mission could receive substantial lifts in the months ahead.
His efforts would no doubt be aided if Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, the all-but-named Republican nominee, chooses a vice
presidential running mate who favors abortion rights, alienating
staunchly conservative Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   And if Buchanan collects at least 5 percent of the popular vote
in the general election, the Reform Party would qualify for federal
campaign funds in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the key for Buchanan is final recognition at the
party's special session of Frank Reed as chairman of the
convention's credentials committee, a 15-member panel that decides
who are seated as convention delegates.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the panel's job is especially critical. Reflecting
the polarizing effect Buchanan has had on the party, the committee
has received 40 challenges from 26 states, the resolution of which
could affect hundreds of the 596 delegates and dozens of the 164
members of the national committee, some of whom are also delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, the party chairman in Ohio and chairman of the convention
rules committee, is considered a Buchanan supporter. But it remains
unclear just who is recognized as the head of the credentials
committee. Gerald R. Moan, the party's acting chairman since last
winter, originally appointed two people _ Dot Drew, a party
official from North Carolina and a long-time Perot supporter, and
Kelly Abt of Texas, a staunch Buchanan supporter. Later, Moan
removed Abt, replacing him with Russell J. Verney, a close
associate of Perot. But then he removed Verney and appointed Reed
as sole chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the 11-member executive committee overruled Moan,
voting to remove Reed and naming Drew as the sole chairwoman. But
Moan has not recognized the executive committee's action, leaving
the matter to be resolved at the Aug. 8 meeting.
</P>
<P>
   For the Buchanan campaign, the naming of Reed as credentials
chairman would appear to be the last component to a strategy
intended to safeguard the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's efforts to tie up all loose ends follow months of
contention within the party, largely as a result of his power play.
While his efforts to gain control of state delegations have
fortified his chances of winning the nomination, they have also
offended many party members who cherished Perot's founding
principles that focused on government reform and trade issues and
ignored social policy.
</P>
<P>
   For some time, Perot did not rule out a third run for the
presidency himself. He even tried to have the primary ballot offer
voters a third choice, that of ``no endorsement,'' which was widely
perceived as a signal to his loyalists that nominating no one was
better than the choice at hand.
</P>
<P>
   After Perot's request was denied, Buchanan was left only to
overcome John Hagelin, a physicist and obscure political figure who
has twice run for president under the banner of the Natural Law
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Some Reform leaders who are skeptical of Buchanan's motives
contend that the real reason for the Aug. 8 meeting, which was
called by 50 national committee members loyal to him, is that the
Buchanan campaign intends to orchestrate the removal of Moan and
replace him with someone who it believes would project a stronger
and more stable ruling style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us think Gerry has been more than fair to the Buchanan
campaign,'' said a senior party official who asked not to be named.
``But they don't trust him. He has not been with Pat long enough,
so no matter what he does, they're going to dump him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bay Buchanan, who serves as chief strategist for her brother's
campaign, denied that driving Moan from office was part of the
campaign strategy. Moan, she insisted, proved his value when he
removed Verney as credentials chairman and named Reed.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the convention is run in a manner that is fair to
all delegations, I don't see any need for the national committee to
interfere with any officer,'' she said. ``And there is no need to
remove him.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she and Moan both acknowledged that a number of national
committee members who are ardent Buchanan backers would feel more
comfortable with a chairman who has demonstrated unambiguous
allegiance to Buchanan and the direction he would take the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``My perception is they don't have the votes, and the sentiment
to remove me is not there,'' Moan said of any opponents, though he
conceded that his days in office might be numbered. ``I think I've
been more than fair to both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Verney predicted that if Buchanan supporters vote to
replace Moan with a chairman more closely aligned with Buchanan,
the Hagelin campaign would file for an injunction in federal court
to hold up dispensation of the federal election funds to the
Buchanan campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every judge has been appointed by a Republican or Democrat,
and the Federal Election Commission is not rushing to send out any
money,'' Verney said. ``That process could take a long time to
resolve.''
</P>
</TEXT>
