<HEADER>
A5995 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-WRESTLING-GRAPEVINE20     07-18 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-GRAPEVINE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GRAPEVINE: News, notes, gossip from the wrestling industry
 &HT;    By John Allen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Extreme Championship Wrestling's latest pay-per-view was the
organization's best this year and should help in head man Paul
Heyman's search for a new television home for the weekly show.
</P>
<P>
   The show, which was filmed before a sellout crowd of 6,000 in
Los Angeles, went back to the foul-language, over-the-top sexuality
and bloody wrestling tactics that helped put ECW on the
professional wrestling map. Here are some of the highlights:
</P>
<P>
   Best match of the night was the war between Steve Corino and
Jerry Lynn. Corino continues to look like a young Barry Windham
(from his Florida Championship Wrestling days) pouring out his
blood and putting his opponents over. The highlight of the match
occurred when Lynn used Corino's blood to write ``DIE'' on his
chest. Lynn has always been a good wrestler, but has lacked the
microphone and personality skills to get over the top. His feud
with Corino might just do that.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the spectrum was the match between Balls
Mahoney and Big Sal. It was quick and lacked any heat. Another
reason for the poor match could be that Mahoney is getting ready to
leave ECW. Since his tour of Japan, Mahoney has seen his stock
plummet. He might make the jump for West Coast rival XFW soon.
</P>
<P>
   The best promo of the night had to be Rhino's attack on the
Sandman before their match. During the attack, Rhino grabbed
Sandman's injured wife and tried to stuff her head-first down the
toilet before security stepped in.
</P>
<P>
   Rhino also had a hand in the craziest move of the night. Still
recovering from knee surgery, Spike Dudley tried to help Sandman
during his match with Rhino. For sticking his nose into the match,
Dudley was piledriven by Rhino off the ring apron, through a table
and onto the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The return of the night was Dawn Marie. She has been missing
since her wrestler Lance Storm jumped to WCW last month. She
returned as part of the announcing crew.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise of the night was Francine losing her top.
</P>
<P>
   _ ECW's next CD of entrance themes is set for release in
September. It will be ``Extreme Music Volume II: ECW Anarchy
Rulz.'' Some of the songs included are: Spike Dudley's theme song,
``Highway to Hell'' by Jesse James Dupree; New Jack's theme song,
``Natural Born Killaz'' by F.M. Racket; Steve Corino's theme song,
``Welcome Burden'' by Disturbed; and Mikey Whipwreck's theme song,
``Head'' by Static-X.
</P>
<P>
   _ The World Wrestling Federation's online auction (on wwf.com)
has had some big money sales so far. Triple H's outfit (tights,
trunks and elbow pads) from ``Summerslam '98'' went for over
$2,000; as did Stone Cold Steve Austin's autographed knee brace.
All the proceeds, which could reach into six-figures, are going to
charity.
</P>
<P>
   _ WWF fans at the recent ``Raw'' show in Albany, N.Y. got an
extra treat. After Raw went off the air, Triple H and Chris Jericho
actually started a match. After Triple H ripped off Jericho's
bandages, Jericho reversed an abdominal strech and hit a
``Lionsalt'' for the win.
</P>
<P>
   _ She didn't marry a millionaire on television, but Chyna should
have Playboy magazines selling at a record pace when her pictorial
appears in the men's magazine's November issue.
</P>
<P>
   _ More bad news for WCW. Despite claims from the announcers that
attendance at the ``Bash at the Beach'' pay-per-view was over
16,000, the official number was 4,400.
</P>
<P>
   _ More word leaking out this week that the Vince Russo-Hulk
Hogan flap at ``the Beach'' was fake. Also, reports say Hogan must
make only seven more appearences for WCW.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ric Flair's recent neck surgery went well and he could return
in about three months.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
