u w BC-ARMY-GAY-DEATH-NYT &LR;      07-18 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-GAY-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMY EXONERATES OFFICERS IN DEATH OF GAY SOLDIER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky., Mo.)   By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An Army investigation of events surrounding the
murder of a gay private by a fellow soldier at a base in Kentucky
has exonerated all officers of blame and concluded that no climate
of homophobia exists at the base, Pentagon officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Last July, Pfc. Barry Winchell, 21, was bludgeoned to death with
a baseball bat as he slept in his barracks at Fort Campbell. A
19-year-old private, Calvin Glover, was later court-martialed and
sentenced to life imprisonment for the murder. Spc. Justin R.
Fisher, 26, Winchell's roommate, was sentenced to 12{ years as part
of a plea bargain that allowed him to avoid more serious charges of
being an accomplice to the murder and helping to cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   The Army, stung by accusations that it was not punishing
harassment of gays, opened an investigation into the atmosphere at
Fort Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   The product that investigation, conducted by the Army's
inspector general, Lt. Gen. Michael Ackerman, is expected to be
released on Friday. , It states that some members of the unit in
which the killing occurred, a company within the 101st Airborne
division, held anti-gay attitudes. In particular, it singles out
Winchell's first sergeant, who has since been relieved of his
duties, of not putting an end to the harassment.
</P>
<P>
   But the report, whose conclusions were first reported by CBS
News, also concludes that the 101st Airborne does not suffer from
an unacceptable degree of homophobia, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, it described a sort of upstairs-downstairs mentality at
the base in which instances of harassment were not brought to the
attention of those in command who might have stopped it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of times when the problem never surfaced up
the chain of command,'' said one Pentagon official. ``But when the
leadership discovered the problem action was taken.''
</P>
<P>
   Winchell's mother, Patricia Kutteles, a registered nurse from
Kansas City, Mo., was quick to accuse the Army of a cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just so disappointed, really, really disappointed,'' she
said Tuesday in a telephone interview. ``It's been so devastating.
To me it seems as if the Pentagon brass and the command is more
concerned about protecting themselves than the safety of our
soldiers. The Army should face up to what is going on instead of
covering up for the command climate.''
</P>
<P>
   In the background, Wally Kutteles, her husband and Winchell's
stepfather, who served in the Korean War, chimed in, ``They're
trying to sweep it under the rug.''
</P>
<P>
   They have filed a claim against the Army under the Military
Claims Act for wrongful death and are seeking $1.4 million in
damages based on Winchell's loss of earning potential. The
Washington-based law firm of Covington &AMP; Burling is handling the
case without compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle M. Benecke, co-director of the Servicemembers Legal
Defense Network, an organization that provides legal aid to gays in
the military, also criticized the pending report.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Army report denies anti-gay harassment is a problem at
Fort Campbell, then the report does not have a shred of
credibility,'' she said. ``There is more than ample evidence of
anti-gay harassment, despite a process that foreclosed the
participation of gay soldiers. Army leaders need to deal with this
problem head on, and stop the harassment.''
</P>
<P>
   Benecke said her group interviewed 20 soldiers at Fort Campbell,
and discovered that ``anti-gay harassment and threats are as common
as the uniform.''
</P>
<P>
   She characterized the murder as a hate crime rooted in
homophobia; the Pentagon treated it as a simple case of murder of a
soldier by a soldier.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials on Tuesday defended the integrity of their
pending report. ``I'm not saying that harassment hasn't occurred,''
a Pentagon official said. ``But it is an exaggeration to think that
every gay at the base is being harassed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Army investigation coincides with a second report by a
Pentagon advisory group created by Defense Secretary William Cohen
after the Pentagon's inspector general stated last March that
harassment of servicemen perceived to be homosexuals was widespread
throughout the military. The report is supposed to serve as an
``action plan'' for each of the military services to address the
problem of harassment of gays in the military.
</P>
<P>
   Among its recommendations is the refinement of training for
service members of different ranks on how to properly carry out the
Clinton administration's policy of ``don't ask, don't tell'' which
allows gay men and lesbians to serve in the military provided they
keep their sexual orientation a secret and do not engage in
homosexual acts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The training about ``don't ask, don't tell'' is a servicewide
problem,'' said one Pentagon official. ``One class doesn't fit
every rank.''
</P>
<P>
   The Army inspector general's investigation at Fort Campbell was
requested by Maj. Gen. Robert T. Clark, who was commander of the
101st Airborne at the time of the murder, and who was reassigned to
the Pentagon and made vice director of operations for the Joint
Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   The report concludes that Clark should be not be held
responsible for the murder. In fact, it reinforces his own
statements made on the day he left his command.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not, nor has there ever been during my times here, a
climate of homophobia on post,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Glover's trial in December, soldiers testified that Winchell
had been taunted for months with name-calling, rumor-mongering and
an inquiry into his private life that was supposed to be forbidden
under military policy.
</P>
<P>
   The trial also laid bare the flaws in the Clinton
administration's ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy. Critics contend
that instead of making life easier for gays and lesbians in the
armed services, the policy leaves many to suffer in silence and
fear or leave the service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
