<HEADER>
A5997 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-GLF-WOMEN-OPEN19-COX     07-18 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WOMEN-OPEN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jordan checks out Open course, picks Webb as favorite
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GURNEE, Ill. - The Merit Club's most famous member played three
holes Tuesday with Nancy Lopez, Laura Davies and Michelle McGann,
then gave his assessment of the course for the 55th U.S. Women's
Open Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a good test for the women,'' Michael Jordan
said. ``I think it would be a good test for the men. If the wind
kicks up, it can be really, really tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan received tremendous ovations as he played in this
northern Chicago suburb, but said hitting a tee shot in front of
fans ``is a lot more intimidating than me making a free throw.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was humbled playing with three great players in a
short exhibition _ he lost a ball on the first hole _ Jordan said,
``I don't need much humbling. I know I'm a hack.''
</P>
<P>
   However, his best score here is a 69.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's three years ago when I didn't really have a job,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Now running the Washington Wizards, Jordan said he hasn't been
able to play as much golf as he'd like and is struggling with a
closed club on top that is causing a hook.
</P>
<P>
   He picked Karrie Webb as the favorite here, but ``would not rule
out Juli Inkster. This is a putter's course.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan also talked basketball, refusing to comment on the Bulls,
but praising North Carolina's decision to hire Matt Doherty as head
coach. Why not him?
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaching is not my bag,'' Jordan said. ``I don't think I have
the patience to sit down on the sidelines and yell and scream. I
like to do it at home in the confines of my own house.''
</P>
<P>
   Scheduling blues
</P>
<P>
   Inkster, the defending champion, said it was bad timing to hold
the Women's Open the same week as the British Open. ``I kind of
feel sorry for the PGA,'' she said, ``because we're going to take
their press. Maybe we'll throw them a few bones.'' All kidding
aside, Inkster said, ``I wish it wasn't up against the British
Open, but ... this is our biggest tournament of the year, and we're
just going to have to go out there and play some good golf and
bring the media to us.''
</P>
<P>
   More money is coming to them, thanks to an increase in the purse
from $1.75 million to $2.75 million, with the winner earning
$500,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a statement for women's golf and for the USGA that
they think we deserve to be playing for _ maybe not as much as the
men _ but the most we're playing for on tour,'' Inkster said.
</P>
<P>
   Practice, practice
</P>
<P>
   Davies admits that she's practicing more because of Webb (four
victories this year) and Annika Sorenstam (five victories).
</P>
<P>
   ``Because they are doing what they're doing, I'm not good enough
any more and I need to be better,'' said Davies, who added she's
been on the range more Tuesdays this year than in her career.
</P>
<P>
   But she's not practicing that much. ``Not ridiculously,'' Davies
said. ``I would never spend a day out there.'' She paused for
laughter. ``I've already become too professional.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
