<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-EARLY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans to move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, July 23,
2000. If you have questions about stories, call 888-346-9867 or
212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PAGE ONE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ARCHITECTURE-VENICE-BIENNALE (Venice) _ The Venice Biennale's
Seventh International Architecture Exhibition features the latest
strain to emerge in architecture in recent years: ``blob'' design,
produced with the aid of animation software. Biomorphic and
invertebrate, blobs look like things you would expect to see rising
from an electronic version of the primordial ooze. But a small
floating park set within the cargo hold of a rusting freight barge
is the favorite of Herbert Muschamp, the Times critic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-LECONTE (Paris) _ Patrice Leconte has averaged one feature
a year since his debut in 1975, and in the time it has taken for
``The Girl on the Bridge'' to reach the United States, he has
completed one feature _ the period piece ``The Widow of
Saint-Pierre,'' with Juliette Binoche and Daniel Auteuil _ and is
filming ``Felix et Lola'' with Charlotte Gainsbourg and Philippe
Torreton. In his spare time, he makes commercials. ``The Girl on
the Bridge,'' which opens Friday in New York, is a love story.
``All films are love stories,'' he says in an interview in Paris.
By Dave Kehr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-JARRE-FILM (Undated) _ Michael Beckerman says he is
rooting for Maurice Jarre to win an Oscar for his brilliant score
of ``Sunshine.'' Then, Beckerman says, he hopes Jarre gives it to
Schubert. To create the main musical theme, Jarre has played the
first phrase of the Schubert Fantasy in F Minor without notes 6-15,
the added a new expansive phrase. The Schubert fantasy is a
particularly compelling choice for ``Sunshine'' because the opening
suggests a Hungarian Gypsy origin, appropriate for the film set
over three generations of one family in Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ART-RIJKSMUSEUM (Amsterdam, the Netherlands)_ ``The Glory of the
Golden Age'' at the Rijksmuseum in Amsterdam celebrates the
museum's 200th anniversary and offers a reminder that the 17th
century was a special moment of creative boom in Dutch history. In
other parts of Europe, art was still reflecting the power of kings
and popes; in the Netherlands, it mirrored the emergence of a new
mercantile society. With still lifes decorating every
self-respecting home, it was an enviable time to be an artist.
Several million paintings were produced by several thousand
artists. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-COPS-RUSSIA (St. Petersburg, Russia) _ In the last two years,
St. Petersburg has become the hottest location for the hottest
trend on Russian television: gritty, tell-it-like-it-is cop shows.
The boom began in early 1998 with ``The Street of Broken
Streetlights,'' a St. Petersburg version of ``Hill Street Blues.''
Now, in its wake, half a dozen mini-series are being shot or are on
the drawing boards in St. Petersburg, starring counter-intelligence
agents, mafia dons, tough female investigators and other heroes and
villains. The choice of St. Petersburg echoes real life. In recent
years, the city has become infamous for a string of contract
killings. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   TV-BURNETT-SURVIVOR (Undated) _ Mark Burnett may not be liked by
everybody, but he has survived the entertainment world. The
40-year-old British native landed in Los Angeles in 1982, moved
from au pair work to telemarketing, insurance and credit card sales
before being inspired by a Tony Robbins motivational seminar. He
has since developed two winning entertainment vehicles in
remarkably little time by Hollywood standards. Over the last five
years MTV, ESPN and the Discovery Channel have spent $100 million,
by his estimate, on his ``Eco-Challenge Expedition Race.'' Now he
is producing ``Survivor,'' the latest in what he promises will be a
stream of adventure-related businesses and programming combining a
blend of drama and reality he calls ``dramality.'' By Alica Ault.
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   CHILDREN (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (moving in `e' category) &LR;  The following stories moved Monday,
July 23, in the `t' category.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-JERUSALEM-HOTELS (Jerusalem) _ Jerusalem is not an
ordinary city and this is not an ordinary guide to hotels there.
William Orme Jr. makes discerning recommendations in a 3,000-word
piece full of details about decor, history, service and discounts.
The hotels visited included: the Olive Tree, a Holy Land theme inn;
the American Colony, an 84-room compound developed from a
19th-century pasha's manse; and the King David, which for true
self-indulgence, he concludes, is Jerusalem's best luxury hotel. He
even recommends the hotel's promotional film in which employees
recall everything from the 1946 bombing of its west wing to the
pyramid cake they baked for Anwar Sadat in 1977. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   The Travel section also includes this package on Kids: Why Leave
Home Without Them.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRAZIL-SOCCER (Undated) _ How you play the game of soccer
does matter. So Annasue McCleave Wilson accompanied her 14-year-old
son, John, to Florianopolis, Brazil, for training sessions and
matches planned by his coach, Paulo Barreto. In between games, John
and his teammates had time for sandboarding and exchanging e-mail
addresses with Brazilian teenagers and parents had time for
enjoying lime drinks on the hotel veranda, ecological walks and
watching games played on sand as white as baby powder.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-TEENS (Undated) _ Based on first-hand experience from
five trips, Jill Abramson has advice for parents traveling with
teen-agers. In London, avoid the British Museum and Parliament, but
visit the Tower of London and war rooms because teen-agers like
gory stuff and they have seen enough World War II movies to make
Whitehall interesting. In Paris, she reports that her daughter took
in the Louvre in less than two hours, but loved going to a movie
without a chaperone. Other advice: rent a ``sweet'' car, don't
share rooms with teen-agers because vacation for them means not
being neat and finally, don't insist on little adults, be a big kid
instead.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) How young is too young for a child
to fly? It depends on whom you ask. Continental will not accept an
infant younger than 7 days. American Airlines sets a 3-day limit,
but in fact, a spokesman says the airline doesn't ``inspect''
babies. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta
recommends 6 weeks. Another expert asks if a postpartum mother is
ready for a long trip and still another says a good criteria might
be, Is this trip really necessary? By Betsy Wade. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REGULAR FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Joseph Siano answers questions about the
Grand Prix in Monaco; behind-the-scenes tours of English Cathedrals
and apartment rentals in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CUBA (Undated) _ Cuba has been off-limits for American
tourists for almost 40 years and unless President Clinton changes
his mind, the ban on United States tourist travel to Cuba is likely
to be tightened this summer. Meanwhile, travel from the United
States to Cuba increases. Edwin McDowell reports that there are
charters from New York, Miami and Los Angeles for exchange groups
and entrepreneurs take American tourists to Cuba without running
afoul of U.S. authorities.
</P>
</TEXT>
