<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6001 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ART-RIJKSMUSEUM-2TAKE     07-18 1276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-RIJKSMUSEUM-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DUTCH MOMENT OF GENIUS IN ITS FULL GLORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Japan, the Netherlands)   (For release Sunday, July 23)  
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMSTERDAM, the Netherlands _ A tiny country that over a short
period produces artists of the stature of Rembrandt, Vermeer, Frans
Hals, Jan Steen, Jacob van Ruisdael and Pieter de Hooch has good
reason to wax proud over its golden age of painting. Indeed, the
Netherlands is doing so yet again with ``The Glory of the Golden
Age,'' a ``best of'' exhibition of Dutch 17th-century art that is
being held at the Rijksmuseum here through Sept. 17 to celebrate
the museum's 200th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   The Rijksmuseum is itself, of course, a monument to the golden
age and, as such, has been able to provide around half of the items
in the show (with Rembrandt's ``Night Watch'' the pivotal work in
the exhibition, just as it is the iconic painting of the permanent
collection). For this occasion, to complement its own masterpieces,
it has also borrowed essential works from other Dutch museums as
well as from collections elsewhere in Europe and in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   In the main part of the exhibition, some 200 paintings,
sculptures and works of decorative art have been organized both
chronologically and around themes, some obvious (``Sky and Water,''
``Masters of Landscape,'' ``The Delft Light''), others more quirky
(``Whims and Drolleries,'' ``Extravagantly Decked Out,''
``Deceptively Realistic'').
</P>
<P>
   Until July 16, 96 drawings and prints were also presented in a
dimly lighted gallery on a lower floor, but their fragility
prevented their being displayed through September.
</P>
<P>
   The package is impressive: with such raw material, how could it
be otherwise? But the show's organizers have also done their bit.
By placing sculptures and decorative arts in the same area as
paintings, they underline how different art forms were flourishing
simultaneously. With the thematic hanging, they demonstrate how
many different schools of paintings were busy at the same time,
from portraiture to landscapes, from still life to genre painting.
</P>
<P>
   Yet perhaps most crucially, the show offers a salutary reminder
that, for all the renown of Rembrandt, Vermeer and their like
today, it was not artists who created the golden age. Rather, it
was a special moment in Dutch history, characterized by political
enlightenment and economic prosperity, that generated a veritable
boom in artistic creation.
</P>
<P>
   In other parts of Europe, art was still reflecting the power of
kings and popes. In the Netherlands, it mirrored the emergence of a
new kind of civil society, one largely run by and for its
Protestant mercantile burghers.
</P>
<P>
   Even more remarkably, for more than 30 years until the Treaty of
Westphalia in 1648, the Dutch Republic, as the United Provinces of
the north became known, was fighting to consolidate its
independence from Spain, which had inherited the Netherlands from
the Holy Roman Empire. Yet even during this time, its fleet was
establishing new colonies and opening new trading routes that
turned Amsterdam into an opulent port city: its population jumped
from 50,000 in 1600 to 200,000 in 1650. With prosperity came a
demand for fancier homes and art to put in them.
</P>
<P>
   Amsterdam, which drew Rembrandt from his native Leiden, was at
the center of artistic activity, but it was not alone. Haarlem,
Utrecht, Delft and Dordrecht, as well as Leiden, had important
guilds of artists, in many cases working independently of one
another. For example, in Utrecht, which remained largely Roman
Catholic, a tradition of religious paintings was kept alive by
painters who had studied Caravaggio in Rome. Elsewhere, paintings
were everywhere except churches _ in town halls, guild houses and
private homes.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, relieved of the need to paint royal portraits and biblical
scenes, many artists became unconscious chroniclers of the social
history of the era. Important burghers, with their black satin
suits and frilly lace collars, were natural subjects, but so also
were maritime battles and elegant cityscapes. Domestic interiors,
in which the nouveaux riches took special pride, were presented
with revolutionary realism, with the paintings on their walls duly
reproduced. Indeed, with still lifes decorating every
self-respecting home, it was an enviable time and place to be an
artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thousands of painters of varying talents were active during
this century, producing several million paintings altogether,'' Jan
Piet Filedt Kok writes in an introduction to this exhibition's
catalog. ``The production of decorative art _ ceramics, glass,
silver and furniture _ achieved new heights, too; only sculpture
lagged behind at first.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Glory of the Golden Age'' starts by introducing the ``New
Faces'' of Dutch portraiture through Thomas de Keyser's ``Syndics
of the Amsterdam Goldsmiths' Guild'' (on loan from the Toledo
Museum of Art in Ohio) and Hals' bucolic ``Marriage Portrait of
Isaac Massa and Beatrix van der Laen.'' This leads to the
``Extravagantly Decked Out'' section, where carefully painted
accessories, from leather gloves with gold thread, pearls and
sequins to delicate lace headwear, are both examples and symbols of
wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deceptively Realistic'' is of course dedicated to still lifes,
with Ambrosius Bosschaert's ``Bouquet of Flowers in a Vase'' of
1618 reminiscent of the tulipomania that gripped the Netherlands in
the early 17th century (until the speculative bubble burst in
1637).
</P>
<P>
   But the fascination with still lifes went far beyond flower
arrangements: with just a handful of works, the exhibition
illustrates the virtuosity of painters who took special pride in
portraying, say, cheese or fish or feathers or oysters, in each
case as a realistically as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seemingly Everyday'' is particularly interesting since it
mirrors the ambivalence that the Protestant Dutch felt about their
own affluence (``The Embarrassment of Riches,'' as Simon Schama
entitled his acclaimed book on the Dutch golden age). Painters
evidently enjoyed showing people having a good time, but they
justified this by suggesting they were warning of the perils of
decadence. ``In Luxury Beware'' by Jan Steen, for instance, shows a
party in full swing, while the bare-breasted women and drunken men
in Nicolaus Knupfer's ``Brothel Scene'' could be portrayed in the
Calvinist Netherlands only as an admonition against immorality.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent sections _ there are 23 _ underscore how, at the same
time as they kept one eye on the market, Dutch painters of the
period were also interested in exploring new techniques. For
instance, chiaroscuro _ the strong use of light and shadow _ was
initially borrowed from Caravaggio, but the Delft painters took it
further, creating a more natural sense of drama. Vermeer's mastery
of this technique can be seen here in ``The Glass of Wine,'' on
loan from the Gemaldegalerie in Berlin, and in the Rijksmuseum's
own ``Kitchen Maid.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the array of treasures proffered by the golden age,
the exhibition cannot escape the dominating presence of Rembrandt
and Hals. Three Rembrandts on loan to the Rijksmuseum _ ``The
Anatomy Lesson of Dr. Nicholas Tulp'' from the Mauritshuis in The
Hague, ``Flora'' from the Hermitage Museum in St. Petersburg and
``The Wedding of Samson'' from the Gemaldegalerie in Dresden _ show
the broad range of his techniques. Similarly, in the section called
``Militia Companies,'' paintings of citizens' military units by
other artists point up the remarkable composition of Rembrandt's
``Night Watch.'' (MORE)  &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
