<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6002 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ART-RIJKSMUSEUM-$ADV2     07-18 0243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-RIJKSMUSEUM-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
 
AMSTERDAM, the Netherlands: ``Night Watch.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The section dedicated to Rembrandt and Hals includes numerous
portraits by both men, but their styles can best be contrasted in
two large oils that hang side by side: Rembrandt's 1662
``Syndics,'' owned by the Rijksmuseum, and Hals' 1664 ``Regents of
the Old Men's Almshouse in Haarlem,'' on loan from the Frans
Halsmuseum in Haarlem. While Rembrandt's painting of five burghers
and a servant from the drapers' guild offers six detailed and
well-lighted portraits, Hals' seven regents _ dressed in black
against a black background, with only their faces, hands and white
collars immediately visible _ reveal how he achieved his effect
with a few hurried brush strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered throughout the exhibition are stone and marble
sculptures (mainly busts of worthy burghers), embroidered chairs,
wooden cabinets, glass and silver goblets and a good selection of
Delft pottery.
</P>
<P>
   Most unusual, perhaps, is an 11-foot-tall copper candelabrum
made by Joost Gerritsz in 1640 and donated that same year by the
Dutch East India Co. to Japan's shogun as part of a successful
campaign to curry favor with the Japanese ruler: from 1641 until
early in the 19th century, the Dutch enjoyed a European monopoly of
trade with Japan. The candelabrum, now permanently on display in a
complex of tombs and temples at Nikko in Japan, returned to the
Netherlands for the first time for this show.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
