<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: CHARLES DENIES WEDDING PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Prince Charles has formally denied that he intends to marry his
longtime mistress, Camilla Parker-Bowles. His office lodged a
complaint with the Press Complaints Commission over a Sunday Times
of London article that said the couple was exploring marrying in
Scotland, where the church is more open to remarriage of those who
have been divorced. ``By making this complaint, we hope it will
formally lay down, on St. James' Palace-headed notepaper, that
there is to be no wedding,'' a court official told the paper.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: CRIME ON RISE
</P>
<P>
   Crime figures for England and Wales rose 3.8 percent, with
robberies up 26.1 percent and violent crimes rising by 12.6
percent, the government reported. Home Secretary Jack Straw said
alcohol was a key contributing factor in the higher number of
street crimes, but his Conservative counterpart, Ann Widdecombe,
told the House of Commons that the blame lay with the Labor
Government and the dwindling number of police officers.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: SPENDING PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Brown, the treasury head, announced a $65 billion
three-year spending package for schools, transportation, the police
and other public services intended to throw Conservatives off
balance in the opening round of campaigning for an election next
year. Brown said the money was available because of Labor's success
in sustaining stable public finances, but the Tory treasury
spokesman, Michael Portillo, said the announcement represented old
style ``tax and spend'' tactics that would put the economy at risk.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: PRINCELY OFFER
</P>
<P>
   The man who would be Italy's crown prince offered to apologize
publicly for the wrongs committed by the Savoys in an effort to get
around a 1946 law that bans all male members of Italy's former
royal family from setting foot in the country. Emanuele Filiberto
di Savoia, 28, grandson of Italy's last king, has been lobbying to
be allowed to visit Italy, even for a short period. The Savoys
ruled Italy from 1861 to the end of Mussolini's dictatorship; the
monarchy was abolished in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA: ANWAR VERDICT DATE
</P>
<P>
   A judge said he would announce his verdict on Aug. 4 in the
sexual misconduct trial of former Deputy Prime Minister Anwar
Ibrahim. ``Now, my headache starts,'' said Judge Ariffin Jaka as he
closed the final hearing in the politically volatile case.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: TAKING SIDES
</P>
<P>
   A military spokesman admitted that members of the armed forces
have taken sides in the religious massacres that have taken
thousands of lives in the Maluku islands. The spokesman, Rear Air
Marshal Graito Usodo, said it was ``inevitable'' that soldiers
would ``act emotionally'' and disobey orders.
</P>
