<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6004 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FILM-LECONTE-$ADV23-2     07-18 1355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-LECONTE-$ADV23-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ADVENTURER WHO OPERATES OUTSIDE THE BOUNDARIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 23)  
 By DAVE KEHR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Prolific and unpredictable, Patrice Leconte is an
anomalous figure in today's French cinema.
</P>
<P>
   His films _ including the deliriously romantic ``The
Hairdresser's Husband'' (1990), the droll historical drama
``Ridicule,'' which was nominated for an Oscar in 1997, and ``The
Girl on the Bridge,'' a poetic love story with Daniel Auteuil and
Vanessa Paradis that opens on Friday in New York _ belong neither
to the grossly commercial film industry nor to the French tradition
of ``auteur'' filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   Leconte has somehow managed to transcend those narrow
categories, creating movies that have both broad, popular appeal
and a distinctive personal signature, much like the great Hollywood
filmmakers of the studio era.
</P>
<P>
   Like those studio filmmakers, he seems to be in almost constant
motion. He has averaged one feature a year since his debut in 1975,
and in the time it has taken for ``The Girl on the Bridge'' to
reach the United States, he has completed one feature _ the period
piece ``The Widow of Saint-Pierre,'' with Juliette Binoche and
Daniel Auteuil _ and is well into the filming of another, ``Felix
et Lola,'' with Charlotte Gainsbourg and Philippe Torreton. In his
spare time, he makes television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``After `The Widow of Saint-Pierre,' I said to myself, I've
worked a lot, I've worked well, and I want to stop a little. I want
to breathe, to rest, to look at the clouds, to travel, I don't know
what. I want to take a year or two, just to dream. And all of my
friends and my family said, `He'll never stop.' I said, `You'll
see.' Then I realized that even when a film is exhausting, when it
weighs very heavily on your shoulders, you can still recover in a
week or two. And I realized above all that what I liked most in the
world was making movies. So I said, forget what I said. It's stupid
to stop doing what you love to do.''
</P>
<P>
   A small, wiry man with close-cropped hair and large eyes framed
by large, rose-tinted glasses, Leconte spoke on a recent Saturday
morning in his office, a sun-filled former painter's studio here on
the Boulevard du Montparnasse.
</P>
<P>
   ``My origins are very simple,'' he said. ``I'm not Parisian. I
lived in Provence. My father had nothing to do with the movies. He
was a doctor. But he was a cinephile. Without doing it on purpose,
he gave me his passion. I used his amateur camera to make little
things in eight-millimeter. One fine day I said to my parents, I
want to make movies. So in 1967 I went up to Paris and took film
courses at what was then the national film school,'' IDHEC.
</P>
<P>
   After making a number of short films, Leconte graduated to
features with the comic thriller ``The Toilets Were Locked From the
Inside,'' which found him in constant conflict with his more
seasoned star, Jean Rochefort. ``It wasn't a very good film,''
Leconte said, ``and it was a commercial failure. But the second
film, `Les Bronzes,' was a huge hit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Les Bronzes'' (``The Tanned Ones'') represented the film debut
of the members of the Splendid troupe, an improvisational cafe
theater that was then the rage of Paris. The group included Michel
Blanc, Thierry Lhermitte, Gerard Jugnot, Christian Clavier and
Josiane Balasko _ all of whom have gone on to become stars in
France.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their story is amazing,'' Leconte said. ``They had all been in
the same high school class, the same students in the same
classroom. You realize? Afterward, they stayed together, they did
the Splendid, and now they're all stars. In the same class, at 15
years old, there was Lhermitte, Clavier, Jugnot, Blanc _ it's
unimaginable. I'll bet their teachers remember.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Les Bronzes,'' based on a play the troupe had created,
satirized a collection of average Frenchmen on vacation in a Club
Med-style resort. Drawing on a sketch-style humor, it launched a
new trend in French comedy, much as ``Saturday Night Live'' had in
the United States, and generated a series of sequels (``Les Bronzes
Go Skiing,'' 1979) and follow-ups (``Come to My Place, I Live at my
Girlfriend's,'' 1980; ``Keep Moving, There's Nothing to See,''
1982) that established Leconte as the foremost director of comedy
in France.
</P>
<P>
   But he was restless. With ``The Specialists'' (1984), he tried a
caper film; with ``Tandem'' (1986), a more naturalistic,
sentimental comedy. But no one was prepared for ``Monsieur Hire''
when it had its premiere at the 1988 Cannes International Film
Festival. A moody, perverse, passionate film about a mousy tailor (
Blanc) who spies on his beautiful neighbor (Sandrine Bonnaire), the
film was just as surprising as if John Belushi had suddenly (and
successfully) taken up Dostoyevsky.
</P>
<P>
   ```Tandem' changed a lot of things for me,'' Leconte said. ``But
`Monsieur Hire' was, no doubt, the first real evident change in
register, in style. When I made it, people asked me constantly if
I'd changed _ what had changed in me to make something so
different. But actually nothing had changed. This is the best
comparison: you like the movies, you go often to the movies, but
when you go, sometimes you see comedies, sometimes you see dramas
or adventures _ you go to see everything, if you like the movies.
And so, if when you're a spectator, you like a lot of different
things, why can't you, as a director, make a lot of different
things? It's all cinema.''
</P>
<P>
   From ``Monsieur Hire'' on, Leconte developed an adventurous,
highly emotional style that broke many of the fundamental rules of
the commercial cinema while continuing to function within it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monsieur Hire'' and ``The Hairdresser's Husband'' both take
place in dreamlike worlds that seem to exist outside any particular
time or locale; ``Ridicule'' bends the rules of the period film by
introducing subtly disorienting, anachronistic touches; ``The Girl
on the Bridge'' combines old-fashioned, classically lighted
black-and-white images with a freedom of camera movement that
shatters any sense of nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the protagonists of ``Girl'' _ Auteuil plays a
professional knife thrower and Paradis is the girl he saves from
suicide to become his professional target _ can chat casually with
each other across time and space, so do Leconte's films push to
transcend specific epochs and physical settings. Like the American
master Frank Borzage (``Seventh Heaven,'' 1927), Leconte believes
in the power of emotion to rise above the petty limitations of
reality. For him, love knows no boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``What pleased me a lot about `The Girl on the Bridge' was that
it was a love story but that it was above all a story of desire,''
he said. ``The two characters feel that, above their heads,
something very strong is hovering, and a spark would be enough to
get them to fall in each other's arms. But this spark only comes at
the very end. The challenge is to build that desire for an hour and
a half, until at the end it finally happens.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All films are love stories,'' said Leconte, and it is true
that a powerful, almost swooning sense of romantic redemption runs
through his best films. But he remains capable of following a
romance like ``The Hairdresser's Husband'' with a black comedy like
``Tango'' (1992), or ``Ridicule'' with a big-star romp like ``One
Chance Out of Two'' (1998) starring Alain Delon and Jean-Paul
Belmondo (which was not released in the United States).
</P>
<P>
   For Leconte, changing registers is ``the only solution for me to
stay alive, not to go to sleep, to frighten myself, to put myself
in question, to never take the same road twice.'' He continued: ``I
want to astonish myself. I want to do things that I don't know how
to do. If you make the same film all your life, if you take the
same route movie after movie, you're more likely to go around in
circles. Me, when I go in one direction, then in another, then in
another, I tell myself, well, I have less risk of repeating myself.
The only cure for facileness is to be completely new each time. It
works for me. (MORE)  &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something in France that has done a lot of harm to the
cinema, the notion of the `cinema d'auteur.' You in the U.S. have a
great advantage over us, because there the notion of auteur cinema
doesn't really exist. There are writers and there are directors,
and they aren't necessarily the same person. In France, if you make
a film you haven't written, you don't get much respect. But I've
always thought there aren't just directors who can write great
stories _ there are screenwriters for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Writers aren't paid very well in France, and that's a problem.
When I made `Ridicule,' it was a script that was proposed to me. I
loved it, and I said, `We'll shoot this, we won't change a comma,
it's magnificent.' But before they offered it to me, the producers
had offered it to four other directors, big people, and they all
said, `No thanks, I only shoot what I write.' And they said no to a
very good script. It's idiotic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The author is also the director, of course. If you give a good
script to three different directors, you'll have three different
films. It's the director plus the writer plus the actor plus the
producer _ it takes the whole thing, you have to be many, you have
to be surrounded by people with lots of talent and you have to have
a little bit yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``For `The Girl on the Bridge,' I didn't write the script. The
scenarist, Serge Frydman, is a young guy in his '40s who likes
writing scripts. He doesn't want to be a director; he's a
screenwriter. The two of us together, drinking a lot of coffee,
invented the story of `The Girl,' but I never picked up a pen to
write anything. Afterward, I said, `OK, we've talked enough about
it, go write it.' And he wrote it by himself. When you shoot a film
you haven't written, you have a much more objective point of view.
You want to make a movie worthy of the screenplay, and I find that
very motivating.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't aspire to be good at everything,'' Leconte concluded.
``But I do aspire to stay awake.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
