u f BC-AETNA-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      07-18 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AETNA-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AETNA SAYS HEALTH CARE COSTS WILL CAUSE IT TO MISS EARNINGS
FORECASTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MILT FREUDENHEIM     
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aetna Inc., the nation's biggest health insurance company, said
Tuesday that it would not meet second-quarter earnings forecasts
because its health care costs were rising faster than expected.
Surprised investors drove down Aetna's stock price.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said the announcement raised questions about
Aetna's plans to reorganize and sell its nonhealth units to the ING
Group of the Netherlands. Final agreement on the sale of Aetna's
international and financial services units still has not been
reached, people close to the deal said.
</P>
<P>
   Although ING was not directly concerned with the results in
Aetna's main health business, some analysts said the earnings
announcement could give ING a psychological advantage in the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna said its second-quarter earnings would be 85 to 95 cents a
share, well below analysts' estimates of $1.20 a share, according
to First Call/Thomson Financial, which tracks company earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The company said medical costs in its core commercial health
maintenance organizations rose 10 percent to 12 percent in the
second quarter as members spent more time in hospitals, emergency
rooms, outpatient surgery centers and doctors' offices. It promised
to provide more information on the problems when it reports
quarterly earnings on Aug. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Aetna dropped $9.25, or 13.7 percent, to $57.375
before rebounding to close at $59.6875, down $6.9375. The stock had
declined $4.0625 on Monday after speculation that a sale to ING
would be completed failed to materialize over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ING and Aetna have not commented except to confirm that talks
are under way.
</P>
<P>
   Most health insurance stocks also dropped on the Big Board
Tuesday. Cigna declined $3.4365 to $98.0625. UnitedHealth Group
lost $3.6875 to $83.25. But Wellpoint Health Networks Inc. gained
$2.1875, to $85.0625.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the problems faced by Aetna, based in Hartford,
were unique as it struggles to integrate acquired companies, soften
its aggressive culture and replace several departing senior health
insurance executives.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna has said that it is searching for a new chief executive to
run its health plan business, which it intends to spin off as a
separate company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's really minding the store,'' said Roberta Goodman, a
health care analyst at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   William S. McKeever, an analyst at PaineWebber Securities, said
Aetna faced ``more challenges than anyone else in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Costs were also rising in its money-losing Prudential Health
Care unit and Medicare HMO's. Aetna said recently that it would
close unprofitable Medicare HMO's with 355,000 members in 11 states
next year.
</P>
<P>
   William H. Donaldson, who took over as chief executive in
February, said Aetna was ``very disappointed with this increase''
in costs. He said operations would be tightened to increase
efficiency and fix or exit markets and products that do not meet
financial and strategic goals.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna plans to start raising health care premiums for a minority
of customers whose contracts open for change in the fourth quarter.
Contracts for most big employers started on Jan. 1 and for many
municipalities on July 1.
</P>
<P>
   James A. Lane, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney, said the
announcement had damaged the confidence that investors had placed
in Donaldson, a former Wall Street banker.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Donaldson had said earlier that annual earnings
would exceed $4.80 a share this year, Lane said his ``credibility
is now defunct, at least for the short term.'' Lane lowered his own
2000 earnings estimate to $3.75 a share from $4.95.
</P>
<P>
   Herbert A. Denton, an investment manager who is president of
Providence Capital Inc., said the earnings report was ``a huge pie
in the face to investors.'' He said that ``in retrospect, Aetna
might have been well advised to conclude a deal in June, ahead of
the earnings report.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives ING and other would-be acquirers of Aetna's financial
services a psychological edge,'' Denton said.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman at Merrill Lynch said Aetna had reported in a Securities
and Exchange Commission filing that it had underestimated its costs
in the second half of 1999, which may have led to misjudgments
about this year's costs. HMO's typically project costs and set
their rates for the year during the preceding summer. But the
companies do not begin to learn their actual costs until the next
June or July.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the costs might have swelled after Donaldson made
clear he wanted to improve relations with doctors, hospitals,
patients and consumers, who want flexibility to decide on their
care. Like other health insurers, Aetna faces a host of lawsuits
filed by plaintiff's lawyers who hope to bring class actions on
behalf of patients and doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna had angered doctors by forcing them to choose between
accepting low-paying, tightly controlled HMO patients or giving up
all Aetna patients.
</P>
<P>
   But Joyce Oberdorf, a spokeswoman for Aetna, said that the
operating changes intended to placate doctors that Donaldson had
announced in Texas, Connecticut and Virginia were not reflected in
the second-quarter earnings. They did not begin until this month.
</P>
<P>
   She added that the company's intention was to eliminate policies
that ``may be perceived as obstacles or may create hassles'' with
providers of health care ``and do not add to Aetna's ability to
monitor quality of care and control costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Lane at Salomon said the problems with earnings could complicate
negotiations to sell the financial and international units. ``The
company could have a hard time obtaining lender and creditor
approval for debt restructuring necessary to consummate significant
divestitures in light of the operational trends in its largest
health business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the ING-Aetna negotiations have said that Aetna
is seeking to transfer $2.75 billion of long-term debt to ING as
part of a $7.75 billion deal for the nonhealth units.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
