<SLUG> BC-CPT-GAMES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT NEW GAMES FOR YOUR PC
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
 By MALCOLM MAYHEW
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the Next Generation video-game war raging among Sega
Dreamcast, Nintendo 64 and Sony PlayStation, the PC often gets
overlooked as an outlet for equally great vid-games. Here's a look
at four of the best new PC titles:
</P>
<P>
   Chicken Run Fun Pack (Activision, all ages): Two games, a screen
saver, a clock, a CD player and clips from the movie _ this thing's
packed with cool stuff.
</P>
<P>
   The first game, ``Run Chicken Run,'' is a direct lift from the
movie: Players must help the chicks escape from the barn before
they wind up Kentucky Fried. Problem is, the farmyard is scattered
with holes in which the chicks can get trapped. Players must find
boards, cover the holes and lead as many winged ones as possible to
safety before time runs out.
</P>
<P>
   The second game, ``Spring Chicken,'' picks up where the first
one left off. Now that the chicks have escaped from the barn,
players must launch them _ via a trampoline _ over a fence to
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Dark Reign 2 (Activision, ages 13 and up): Yes, it's another
run-and-shoot futuristic action game, but it's a good one.
</P>
<P>
   This one's a cut above the rest because players have so many
options: They can play as one of two teams (the rich guys or the
ragtag outfit) or corral a bunch of friends for the dizzying
multiplayer mode.
</P>
<P>
   There doesn't seem to be much of an object here, just blow up
your opponents and capture their areas. It's pleasingly simple in
other ways, too, from the easy-to-learn controls to the
understandable, and exquisitely detailed, playing fields. The
characters look pretty cool, kind of a cross between the guys in
Dune and Blade Runner.
</P>
<P>
   Parents beware: There's a lot of blood and violence, hence the
13 and up rating.
</P>
<P>
   The Settlers III: Ultimate Collection (Blue Byte, all ages): To
hype its upcoming The Settlers IV, Blue Byte has repackaged the
third game in its empire-building/defending/destroying series with
bonus games. The object remains the same, though: Choose an empire,
from Egyptian, Roman and Asian, build it up from scratch, then wipe
out the empires. The bonus CDs include new maps, warriors,
buildings and missions.
</P>
<P>
   Pajama Sam's One-Stop Fun Shop (Humongous Entertainment, ages
3-8): Man, Pajama Sam's got more games than Mario. The latest title
hosted by the green critter is designed to get young ones
interested in art. Using virtual art tools, kids can create and
color their own pictures and storybooks. Best of all, there's no
mess to clean up.
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
