<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6009 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TV-COPS-RUSSIA-ART-$A     07-18 1485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-COPS-RUSSIA-ART-$ADV23-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S VENUE OF CHOICE FOR COPS AND ROBBERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Russia)   For release Sunday, July 23)  
 &HT;    (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ In Soviet days, filmmakers came to this
graceful city looking for a backdrop for historical dramas with men
in top hats and ladies smothered in furs dashing along snowy
streets in horse-drawn sleighs.
</P>
<P>
   Not any more. In the last two years, St. Petersburg has become
the hottest location for the hottest trend on Russian television:
gritty, tell-it-like-it-is cop shows and their many spinoffs,
coming to Russian screens this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Forget palaces and carriages, balls and picnics. Now the stories
are set in the city's dank courtyards and dingy stairwells,
featuring bloodied corpses, distraught prostitutes and cynical hit
men _ familiar stuff for Russian television viewers who for the
last 10 years have been treated to a steady stream of of contract
killings, war and violence on their nightly news shows.
</P>
<P>
   The boom began in early 1998 with ``The Street of Broken
Streetlights,'' a St. Petersburg version of ``Hill Street Blues,''
starring a group of four likable, slightly goofy cops, earnest
versions of the old ``wild and crazy guys'' on ``Saturday Night
Live.'' Nicknamed ``Menty,'' the Russian slang word for cops, the
show is now about to enter its third season, and its 58th episode.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they are kicking down doors to communal apartments or
careening down the embankments by the city's famous canals in their
boxy little Lada cars, toasting witnesses with a shot of vodka or
joshing with informers on Nevsky Prospekt, the foursome have
bumbled their way to stardom. Fans stop them on the streets in
Siberia and Odessa, and buy videos of the show in Brighton Beach
and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in their wake, half a dozen mini-series are being shot or
are on the drawing boards in St. Petersburg, starring
counter-intelligence agents, mafia dons, tough female investigators
and other heroes and villains in Russia's newly recast obsession
with the struggle between good and evil.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big mistake for these past years to think that people
don't heed heroes, when heroes are a natural part of the human
story,'' said Ada Staviskaya, whose Panaroma studio is producing
two new heroines for television. In ``Secrets of the
Investigation,'' the star is a deputy prosecutor and a ``seeker of
truth,'' to quote the press release for the season's new shows,
while ``Hunt for Cinderella'' stars a mysterious and ultimately
beautiful woman who undergoes plastic surgery, suffers from amnesia
and emerges as a Russian version of ``La Femme Nikita.''
</P>
<P>
   Also coming up is a second season of ``Agent of National
Security,'' offering ``a no-nonsense street-smart guy'' and ``a
seeker of justice in an unjust world.'' With two more series in the
development stages (including ``Baron,'' portraying a prodigy
Jewish violinist who later presents himself as a local Gypsy king),
Media-MOST, Russia's largest private media company, which owns both
the TNT network and NTV, a national channel, has taken the lead in
the Petersburg mini-series boom, although ORT, its arch-rival,
weighed in last winter with its own Petersburg action series,
``Killing Power.''
</P>
<P>
   One exception to the contemporary motif is ``Empire,'' a 12-part
series due to be broadcast in October on ORT, which takes a step
back in time and re-enacts _ again in St. Petersburg _ a string of
history-making ``hits'' or terrorist attacks that took place during
the final decades of the Romanov empire.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of St. Petersburg as a venue has an echo in real
life. In recent years, the city has become known as Russia's crime
capital, made infamous by a string of contract killings, including
the shooting death, in the winter of 1998, of Galina Starovoitova,
a leading reform democrat, and two murders, in broad daylight on
Nevsky Prospekt, of top-ranking city officials, one by a sniper's
bullet and the other by a bomb neatly placed on a car roof.
</P>
<P>
   Local police and politicians hotly dispute this reputation,
noting _ accurately _ that Moscow and its surrounding region are at
the top of national crime charts. But perceptions linger, and the
spate of TV shows have only further enhanced the cloud over the
city's image.
</P>
<P>
   For Mikhail Piotrovsky, the director of the Hermitage State
Museum, the last straw was a show earlier this year with the
unnuanced title of ``Bandit Petersburg,'' which even featured
skulduggery at Russia's most venerable museum. ``Of course, when
every day the words `Bandit Petersburg' are flashed on the screen,
it is not going to please anyone in Petersburg,'' he said during a
TV interview. ``And when they drag in the Hermitage, then they are
really going too far.''
</P>
<P>
   The interviewer, after thanking Piotrovsky for appearing on her
prime-time show, couldn't help but note that ``Bandit Petersburg''
was coming up next.
</P>
<P>
   Like many trend-setting programs, ``Broken Streetlights'' _ the
brainchild of Sergei Skvartsov, now general director of the TV
division of Media-MOST _ took a long time reaching the screen. Its
success, when it finally went on the air, was its appeal to a
market that, after years of splurging on imported goods, had
developed a craving for local, down-home fare.
</P>
<P>
   ``When American films burst onto Russian screens in the early
1990's, Russian viewers soon found that the American way of life
was something very, very far away from their own,'' said Aleksandr
Kapitsa, the veteran producer of ``Broken Streetlights.'' ``But our
guys are familiar, they are the guy next door, your neighbor on the
trolley bus, your brother, your son. They are charming and they are
recognizable, with no pretensions, just trying to do their jobs in
bad conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   The conditions are familiar. Shot entirely on location, the
series uses the back building of a police station on Vasily Island
as its own ``headquarters,'' where it can shoot only on weekends,
when the real cops in the Lost and Stolen Documents Division have
their days off. The authenticity is unmistakable, from the broken
windowpanes to the dusty piles of documents, the naked lightbulbs
and the chipped concrete.
</P>
<P>
   This shabbiness is part of the charm people associate with
``Peter,'' the Russian nickname for the former imperial capital,
which, in contrast to the flash and bustle of Moscow, has preserved
not only its czarist-era beauty but also the slow pace and
grunginess of its recent Soviet past.
</P>
<P>
   ``One man called from Israel,'' said Aleksei Nilov, a
36-year-old actor who plays one of the four main roles. ``He was
all emotional and said he watches the show with great nostalgia
because, he said, it captures the Petersburg where he was born and
brought up.''
</P>
<P>
   Where there are heroes, there are also myths. For all the
realism of ``Menty,'' there is also an element of make-believe in
the slightly rosy, good-humored picture of the life and times of a
big-city Russian police station.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cinema is the creator of myths,'' said Dmitri Svetozarov,
director of the ``Agent'' series. ``There were myths about the
Soviet policeman. And now there are these myths about the
contemporary policemen, showing them drinking vodka, dozing on the
job, all of which helps the viewers see themselves in these
characters. These myths may not be true either, but at least it is
a new myth.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, most Russian police officers are apt to be a bit more
bribable, and less successful at tracking down their prey, than
their TV counterparts. ``This is the police our viewers wish they
had but don't,'' admitted Kapitsa. ``And the police like it because
it makes them look good.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Petersburg's quiet streets and picturesque backdrops are one
reason this city is becoming, as some here now call it, Hollywood
on the Neva. ``The city itself is made for filming,'' explained
Nikolai Suslov, producer of ``Empire'' and before that the
technical producer of ``Killing Power.''
</P>
<P>
   But another motive is more prosaic. Although St. Petersburg is
Russia's second-largest city, it is significantly cheaper than
Moscow. According to Suslov, expenses here are, on the average, 20
to 40 percent less than in the capital and actors' wages _ which,
on average, equal $200 a day _ are literally half the going Moscow
rate.
</P>
<P>
   For St. Petersburg's hard-pressed theater world, the arrival of
the mini-series has proved to be a lifeline at a time when Russian
cinema is still languishing. ``I keep saying that these series play
a humanitarian role in St. Petersburg,'' said Svetozarov. ``We are
returning to viewers those actors who had disappeared from the big
screen. We are restoring those old contacts.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The birth of the series has also restored some life to the vast
inner-city studios at Lenfilm, once one of the powerhouses of
Soviet cinema and now a mournful shell of dilapidated buildings and
junked-up courtyards.
</P>
<P>
   But the industry here has a way to go before it reaches
Hollywood standards. Lacking equipment for synchronized sounds,
actors have to return to the studio to dub in their voices, and
scriptwriters are in a constant scramble to keep up with the pace
of production.
</P>
<P>
   All this is a particular strain for producers and directors
brought up in the Soviet school, when filmmaking was a leisurely,
labor-intensive process. Now filming that used to take months is
packed into a single week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still don't have the kind of industry they have in
America,'' Kapitsa said. ``But for the money that any American
director would think of as low budget, we can shoot something that
is very decent.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 2053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0352 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6011 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-OFFICEDEPOT19-COX     07-18 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OFFICEDEPOT19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With stock plunging, Office Depot replaces chief executive
officer
 &HT;    By Paul Owers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DELRAY BEACH, Fla. - With its stock price plummeting and
shareholder dissension soaring, Office Depot on Tuesday replaced
Chief Executive David Fuente with Bruce Nelson, the company's
international president.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson conceded the investment community has lost confidence in
the Delray Beach-based office supply giant and promised to take a
new look at all aspects of the business. Fuente will stay on as a
non-executive chairman of the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a candid guy, and the candid truth is that we've made some
mistakes,'' Nelson said. ``We have to fix them.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson questioned the company's recent decisions to enter
markets already dominated by competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the rest of the U.S. (stores) were doing as well as South
Florida, the company would be doing a lot better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Office Depot operates 855 stores in the United States and
Canada. It employs about 2,600 people at its Delray Beach
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson's appointment did nothing to hurt the company's stock
price. Office Depot shares (NYSE: ODP) closed Tuesday at $6.63, up
25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, 55, came to Office Depot when the company bought Viking
Office Products in 1998. The Utah native also was president and CEO
of Chicago-based BT Office Products USA and had more than 20 years
of senior management experience at Boise Cascade Office Products in
Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bruce brings a combination of strong leadership skills, solid
operating know-how, financial acumen and expertise in international
operations _ one of our key growth engines going forward,'' James
L. Heskett, chairman of Office Depot's Governance Committee, said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Fuente, 54, turned Office Depot into the largest U.S. retailer
of office supplies in his 13 years as CEO. Before that, the Chicago
native was president of the $1 billion-a-year Sherwin-Williams
Paint Stores.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, rival Staples announced plans to buy Office Depot in a
$3.4 billion stock deal before the Federal Trade Commission called
it off a year later. In July 1997, Fuente led a raucous party in
which relieved Office Depot employees threw away anything related
to the collapsed Staples deal.
</P>
<P>
   But the company's recent performance wasn't worthy of a
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Office Depot's sales have lagged, and the company announced last
week that its second-quarter profit fell by 20 percent.
Additionally, it said earnings for the year ending Dec. 31 could be
as much as 13 cents below analyst expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Office Depot shares have traded recently near its 52-week low of
$6 since trading in the mid-$20s early last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company today faces new challenges, and we agreed with
David that it was appropriate for him to take a more advisory
role,'' Heskett said.
</P>
<P>
   Fuente was not available for comment Tuesday. A source said
Fuente thought he would have been given more time to turn around
the company.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson earned $630,000 in base salary last year as chief
executive of Office Depot's Viking unit. Fuente's salary was $1
million, and he ranked fourth this year on a Bloomberg News list of
most overpaid and underperforming CEOs.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the company's move to change leadership looks
promising.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a good start,'' said Dan Binder, an analyst
with Buckingham Research Group in New York. ``In terms of a
restructuring the company, you have to start at the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Binder said Office Depot's slide is mostly attributable to
slumping sales in its retail stores. He expects the company to grow
more slowly and possibly close even more stores than the 27
announced last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nelson is an industry veteran and well-respected, and he'll be
extremely focused on fixing the problems,'' Binder said. ``I think
he'll be deliberate and analytical in his approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said Office Depot has enjoyed impressive growth in its
Internet and international businesses and intends to revitalize its
retail stores with a better product mix, customer service and
marketing. The company will continue to expand internationally
while cutting costs to lure back customers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson also expects to hire several senior-level managers,
including a marketing director. He did not rule out the possibility
of layoffs, but indicated that eliminating a large number of
positions was unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to take a look at everything we do and see if
there is a better, more efficient way to do it,'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
