<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6022 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-ART-NYT     07-18 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDEAST TALKS INTENSIFY AS NEGOTIATORS TACKLE ISSUE OF JERUSALEM
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JANE PERLEZ  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ The White House described the scene inside Camp
David on Tuesday as one of little sleep and unwavering intensity,
with President Clinton negotiating until dawn with Prime Minister
Ehud Barak of Israel and then, after just a few hours' sleep,
meeting with the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Informally, officials were suggesting that Clinton's artificial
deadline of Wednesday morning, when he is scheduled to leave for
Japan, could be stretched as much as 21 hours, an element of
information that added to a steadily building drama.
</P>
<P>
   At times on Tuesday, it seemed the impossible might be possible:
an agreement on all the issues, including Jerusalem. At other
times, the temperature receded back to the more sober expectation
of a rather modest agreement and a second summit meeting before
Arafat's Sept. 13 deadline for declaring a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   These polar extremes were fed by the pitch of diplomacy that
dribbled through the phone wires of the mountain retreat. Members
of the Israeli delegation have called home in the last 24 hours,
leaking news that the question of Jerusalem had been under
discussion since Monday and hinting at progress on this most
intractable issue.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Arafat was reported to have called his headquarters
in Gaza and told his aides to spread the word that he was
considering packing his bags and leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides were playing to their constituents, and preparing
public opinion for posssible outcomes. Arafat, presumably, was
showing that he was not going to give up on his long-held stance
that East Jerusalem must be the capital of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the same script, Barak was demonstrating that he was
a man of reason, and was prepared as Israel television reported
Tuesday night to make ``unprecedented steps'' toward the
Palestinian position on Jerusalem. If an agreement were not reached
on the future status of Jerusalem, Barak would be able to say that
he had tried his best and that the Palestinians were unmovable.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that Jerusalem was on the table was itself progress
over the seven-year time line of negotiations between the
Palestinians and Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was astonished by the degree of progress in the last few
hours,'' said an Israeli who was in contact with the delegation by
telephone and who was expressing the line of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Only several months ago, Jerusalem was a virtually taboo subject
in back-channel talks in Stockholm, where the top negotiators of
Arafat and Barak met and made progress on a variety of issues.
These included what might constitute the territorial boundaries of
a Palestinian state and what would be the fate of the three million
Palestinian refugees scattered across the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   But on Jerusalem, there was only generalized talk in Stockholm.
</P>
<P>
   According to reports attributed to Israeli officials, the
Israeli delegation at Camp David was presenting a plan that would
incorporate the Israeli bedroom communities that are now a de facto
part of the capital into the legal entity of Jerusalem. Among the
West Bank settlements near Jerusalem being mentioned are Maale
Advmim and Givat Zeev.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also calls for areas populated by Palestinians, such as
Beit Hanina and the Shuafat refugee camp, to be placed under
Palestinian control. The moves together would provide more
demographic balance in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   But this version of a solution for Jerusalem leaves unanswered
the top concerns of Arafat, who has insisted all along that East
Jerusalem, annexed by the Israelis in the 1967 war, should be the
capital of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   From the Palestinian point of view, the Israeli plan does not
deal with the heart of the matter: it leaves under Israeli
sovereignty the old city of Jerusalem, home of the main religious
sites of Judaism, Islam and Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   There have been some suggestions from outside the Camp David
negotiations in the last few days that the future of the Old City
could be set aside for future generations to decide. But there have
also been reports that Arafat has stood firm on Jerusalem,
insisting that no agreement can come out of these negotiations
without Palestinian control over the Al Aqsa Mosque and the Church
of the Holy Sepulcher.
</P>
<P>
   And from the Israeli side, Yitzhak Herzog, the Israeli cabinet
secretary, said in a speech before the Israeli Policy Forum in
Washington on Tuesday, that Israeli sovereignty over Jerusalem was
one of the sacrosanct ``red lines'' of the Barak government.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's spokesman, Joe Lockhart, stood studiously above the
fray on the issue of Jerusalem. He did not utter the word Jerusalem
or mention any of the other substantive matters, such as
Palestinian refugees or the boundaries of a new Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, through the release of bits of minutae on who was
meeting with whom or who was not meeting with whom, he depicted
Clinton as a president waiting to do some down-to-the-wire
persuasion with Barak and Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has confidently held to its belief that the
Palestinian and Israeli leaders see the value in forging an
agreement under the auspices of Clinton, recognizing that he is
steeped in the issues.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing Arafat for about an hour on Tuesday morning,
Clinton ``stands ready to talk to either leaders separately,
together, the negotiators, whatever we think is peaceful and
constructive,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   In their eighth day, the negotiations have produced a
roller-coaster of emotions, Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go through various emotions, ranging from moments where
you see promise, to moments where the only thing you see is
frustration,'' Lockhart said. ``Not only the president, the leaders
and all the delegations, have run the entire range over the last
eight days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
