<HEADLINE>
MATTHAEUS IN TROUBLE WITH METROSTARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If German legend Lothar Matthaeus thought he embarrassed himself
in the European Championships, think of the humorous reaction
overseas if the New York/New Jersey MetroStars cancel his contract
today.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of reporting to the MetroStars after Germany's
disastrous first-round exit in the Euro championships, Matthaeus
was pictured in a German magazine tanning on the beach in St.
Tropez in the south of France. This was after he told MetroStars
officials he was undergoing treatment for a back injury he suffered
during the championships.
</P>
<P>
   It's a slap in the face to his New York teammates, whom he
publicly criticized for not working hard enough. Matthaeus, 39, was
signed in the offseason to lure fans and improve the MetroStars,
who had the league's worst combined record the first four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But when Matthaeus left to join Germany's national team, the
MetroStars were 3-6-1 with him in the lineup. The team went 9-1-1
in his absence to tie Kansas City for the most points in the MLS
with 38, grabbing a big lead in the Eastern Division standings as
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good,'' midfielder Peter Villegas told the Newark Star- Ledger
when asked about the possibility of Matthaeus' release. ``Now maybe
we can get somebody who can help us.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears Matthaeus doesn't plan to return anyway. He told
Kicker Magazine he is expecting to be released. New York has said
it will make an announcement today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly looks as though we are heading for an amicable
separation,'' said Matthaeus. ``The club doesn't need me and I
don't need them. It's a shame it has not worked out, but I can live
without football.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's his prerogative,'' New York coach Octavio Zambrano
said. ``A player like him could take a lot of jobs. The ball is
really in his court, but if he returns we need to see a change in
Lothar's attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   New York/New Jersey general manager Nick Sakiewicz said he is
considering putting Matthaeus on the 15-day disabled list, but many
of the MetroStars players would rather remember the old Matthaeus,
not this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched him when I was younger and remember him from the
World Cup as an incredible player,'' said midfielder Mark Chung.
``I was looking forward to playing with him, but it has been
completely the opposite. It didn't match the hope.''
</P>
<P>
   The only reason Matthaeus may not be released is MLS has told
the MetroStars they will not receive another marquee foreigner as a
replacement. With depth an issue in the playoffs, Matthaeus'
experience could come in handy.
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano said he would welcome Matthaeus' return, but he's
concerned about his attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``The million dollar question is whether he's committed to this
team,'' Zambrano said. ``Lothar committed would be a great asset.
Anything else would be a disturbance.''
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano said the suggestion that New York only improved because
of Matthaeus' absence is not fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was coincidental,'' Zambrano said. ``When he left, we got
Steve Jolley, Daniel Hernandez, Roy Myers, Clint Mathis, and then
Tab Ramos was healthy again. That's the reason we've had this
recent success. Again, Lother com &QL;
</P>
<P>
   mitted would add to that success.''
</P>
<P>
   What an unfortunate ending for the U.S. men's national soccer
team in last weekend's opening game of Group E World Cup
qualification.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes away from a 1-0 victory over Guatemala in the heat
and humidity of Mazatenango, Carlos Ruiz tied the match with an
88th-minute goal and forced the U.S. to settle for a 1-1 draw.
</P>
<P>
   It was U.S. coach Bruce Arena's first Cup qualifying match. He
said a point on the road and wins at home are the keys to
advancing, but three points on the road would have helped
tremendously.
</P>
<P>
   Arena also could have made better substitutions. With a 1-0 lead
and 20 minutes to play, he still had three substitutions left.
Instead of bringing in defenders and removing forwards to fight off
a constant Guatemala attack, he sent in offensive-minded
midfielders Frankie Hejduk and Tab Ramos for forward Cobi Jones and
midfielder Earnie Stewart. He then traded defenders (Greg Vanney
for Eddie Pope).
</P>
<P>
   Why not leave in Pope, take out forward Ante Razov of Whittier
and bring in Vanney as a fifth defender? Oh well, it's easy to
second guess now. It's also easy to second guess the Mexican
official in charge.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz, who scored the tying goal, never should have been in the
match anyway. Ruiz, who received a yellow card in the 80th minute,
ran over American keeper Kasey Keller before his goal. The Mexican
referee amazingly did not even whistle a foul.
</P>
<P>
   Even referees need to get home safely. How do you think his
three-hour drive back to Guatemala City for a flight home would
have been if he had tossed Ruiz?
</P>
</TEXT>
