<SLUG> BC-PARIS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING OVER THE CREATIVE CONTROLS AT DIOR 
</HEADLINE>
   By CATHY HORYN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ To look at Hedi Slimane _ the Nouvelle Vague suits, the
crest of hair foaming down his angular head like two colliding
rogue waves _ is to imagine someone too cool for anyone over 40 to
identify with. Yet Slimane, who Monday was to begin his new job as
the men's wear designer at Christian Dior, turns out to be
something of a square. He often talks about character and
self-respect, two of the more negotiable virtues in the fashion
business, and has an affinity for the cultivated worlds of Yves
Saint Laurent and Karl Lagerfeld, whose long careers practically
make them geezers.
</P>
<P>
   Over breakfast one morning last week in Paris, Slimane, 32,
acknowledged that many fashion insiders were surprised by his
decision to go to Dior, which gets a lot of attention from John
Galliano's women's clothes but hardly causes a stir in men's wear.
Slimane made his name at Saint Laurent, where his sexually charged
men's clothes also found converts among women. Last spring he was
being courted by Gucci, which wanted to finance a Slimane label,
and by Patrizio Bertelli, the Prada chief executive, who wanted him
to design Jil Sander. If one knows Slimane, and the very French way
he thinks, his choice was not surprising. As he said of the move
from Saint Laurent to Dior, from one venerable French house to
another, ``It's just a walk across the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Saint Laurent, one may recall, began his career at Dior. So in a
sense, the look and culture that became Saint Laurent, and which
Slimane carefully grafted onto his men's style _ the sleek
``smoking'' pantsuits, the razor-sharp shoulders _ had its roots at
Dior. Slimane pointed out that although Saint Laurent made men's
wear fabrics popular in women's fashion, Dior was using fabrics
like glen plaid years before.
</P>
<P>
   Like Lagerfeld at Chanel, Slimane may be more at home working
with established references than inventing his own. So he wouldn't
have been automatically tempted by Gucci's offer to bankroll him.
There were also issues of creative control, which surfaced soon
after Gucci acquired Saint Laurent and Tom Ford assumed the title
of creative director for both houses. As hot as Slimane was at
Saint Laurent, Gucci made it clear that it wanted total control
over its acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   But as Slimane said, ``the No. 1 point for me was not the
control; it was the culture.'' Gucci, by contrast, has a very
quick, mobile culture _ one could almost call it a cellular phone
culture _ with decisions made by executives who may be in London,
Paris or Milan. That is not Slimane's style.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it should be said that Slimane will bring fresh buzz
to Dior, and that is something that Bernard Arnault, the chairman
of LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton, which owns the house,
understands well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
