<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ TUMBLES AMID PROFIT-TAKING; DOW AND S&AMP;P ALSO OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Nasdaq composite index fell sharply Tuesday as
investors chose to take profits after pushing the technology-laden
index higher in each of the previous four sessions.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq fell 97.50 points, or 2.3 percent, to 4,177.17. While
the decline in Nasdaq stocks was most pronounced, other major
market gauges also moved lower.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 64.35 points, or 0.6
percent, to 10,739.92, led lower by Intel, which fell 3 5/16, to
143. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 16.75 points, or
1.1 percent, to 1,493.74. General Electric, Pfizer and Lucent
Technologies were among the big losers. And the Russell 2000 index
of small company stocks fell 8.90, or 1.6 percent, to 536.28.
</P>
<P>
   Traders and analysts said the decline in prices, which came on
moderate volume, was warranted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market has had a very nice move up over the last month or
so, especially technology stocks, and the averages and individual
stocks are very overbought,'' said Kenneth M. Sheinberg, head of
listed trading at SG Cowen. ``It is time to consolidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Contributing to the slide in Nasdaq were Qualcomm, JDS Uniphase
and Cisco Systems, which all fell by more than 2 points. In the
previous four sessions, the Nasdaq had gained 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Although Intel fell during the day, it reported second-quarter
results that were better than expected after the market closed and
rallied as high as 147 after hours. It was not the only big company
to issue an earnings report after the close of trading.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft and Apple Computer, two other technology heavyweights,
also reported results that were better than expected.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings numbers led some analysts to suggest that Tuesday's
sell-off may be short lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is there will be a bounce on Wednesday,'' said Arthur
Hogan, chief market analyst at Jefferies &AMP; Co. in Boston. ``The
market has moved a lot in the last week, and there was room to take
profits. But when we start focusing on these great earnings
numbers, I think we will see buying again.''
</P>
<P>
   Three stocks fell for every two that rose on the New York Stock
Exchange on Tuesday. About 910 million shares changed hands on the
Big Board.
</P>
<P>
   Some stocks, which had advanced smartly in advance of earnings
reports that were expected to be good, retreated once the news was
announced.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch, which rose 10 percent last week, was hit hard
Tuesday even though it reported earnings that exceeded Wall Street
estimates. Merrill fell 3}, to 128\.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna was another big loser. The nation's biggest health insurer
fell 6 15/16, to 59 11/16, after it reported results that fell
short of estimates.
</P>
</TEXT>
