<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORCESTER-FIRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORCESTER OFFICIALS WEIGH LIABILITY IN WAREHOUSE FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ Walking through the Worcester Cold Storage
and Warehouse Co. building last October, Police K-9 Officer Daniel
Sullivan saw disturbing signs of life inside: mountains of trash,
piles of human waste, a stench so overwhelming that he feared for
the health of his dog.
</P>
<P>
   But while Sullivan apparently recorded his visit in a police
report, there is no sign that he reported the conditions to city
building inspectors, public health workers, or the warehouse owner.
A homeless couple, Tom Levesque and Julie Barnes, continued to
squat in the building for more than a month, until a candle that
fell over in their makeshift home last December sparked the fire
that killed six firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   Now, city officials are questioning whether Sullivan had a legal
obligation to report signs of the couple's presence to city
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something I'm looking into,'' Worcester Solicitor David
Moore said. City officials have become concerned about liability,
he said, since two fire-related lawsuits were filed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This type of incident has a way of ending up in a number of
lawsuits, so we're watching carefully,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   Three firefighters' widows sued Kwan and his wife in April,
saying they failed to keep the building secure from trespassers.
And last week, the owner of a diner next to the warehouse sued the
city, Kwan, and a demolition company, saying their negligence led
to the loss of his business.
</P>
<P>
   It was a complaint from a friend of Barnes and Levesque that
directed Sullivan to their cluttered corner of the massive
warehouse on Oct. 27, 1999. In his report, Sullivan described the
squalid conditions he found.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't take a step,'' he wrote, ``without walking on
rotting garbage and feces.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan's report was read to a Worcester grand jury in
February, before the panel voted to charge the homeless pair with
involuntary manslaughter. The grand jury minutes became public this
month, when the couple's attorneys filed them in Barnes' and
Levesque's defense.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's failure to report the warehouse fire underlies the
criminal charges they face. But the city solicitor said he's not
sure whether Sullivan or anyone else had a legal obligation to
report the couple's presence in the vacant building.
</P>
<P>
   If notified, the city would have sent an inspector to the
building, said Doug Scott, principal building inspector in
Worcester's Department of Public Health and Code Enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he had an obligation, but it would have been a
good thing to notify code enforcement,'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   Months earlier, city officials had ordered the building's owner,
Framingham developer Ding On ``Tony'' Kwan, to improve security at
the warehouse. Kwan complied with the order in July, and did not
know about Sullivan's October visit, said Richard Rafferty, Kwan's
attorney. In November Kwan inspected the site from the outside,
Rafferty said, and saw no signs that people could get inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it inconceivable that a police officer would see what
this police officer supposedly saw, and not notify the property
authorities or the building owner. He had a duty,'' Rafferty said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Worcester Police Department nor District Attorney
John Conte's Office would comment on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a Worcester Superior Court judge earlier this week
denied Levesque's request to reduce his bail from $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Judge Thomas Hillman reduced Barnes' bail from
$75,000 to $25,000, and allowed her to be released into the custody
of a Maine couple that adopted Barnes' younger sister. But Hillman
said that Levesque does not have the safety net that the Kings are
providing for Barnes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6034 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-COVERDELL-BAXTER19-CO     07-18 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COVERDELL-BAXTER19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Loss of Coverdell is hard hit
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As a final judgment on the effectiveness of Paul
Coverdell's public career, consider the several vacancies that have
to be filled due to his untimely demise.
</P>
<P>
   Of primary importance is Coverdell's seat in the U.S. Senate,
which will demand two important decisions for Georgia: the first
from Gov. Roy Barnes, who has the power to appoint someone to fill
the immediate vacancy, and the second from the voters, who will
have their say in November.
</P>
<P>
   With a Democratic governor and eight Republican congressmen, the
mind trips over all the possibilities for political drama in the
wake of this man, who went about politics in the most undramatic
way. But leave that speculation aside a moment.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of Coverdell also means Gov. George W. Bush will
have to find another Republican member of Congress he can trust as
much. That may not be easy. Coverdell's loyalty to Bush and his
father, who appointed him Peace Corps director, was unquestioned,
and he was well-known for keeping his mouth shut.
</P>
<P>
   The loss comes just a couple of weeks before the Republican
National Convention, which could be unfortunate timing. The
backroom wrangles and grudge matches with long genealogies that
cause problems at political conventions, were Coverdell's metier.
</P>
<P>
   We can be brief about his skills as a campaigner in his own
behalf. But anyone who was in that steaming hot hotel banquet room
at the 1984 New Orleans convention, when Coverdell pulled Pat
Swindall out of his hat like a rabbit, transforming the disgraced
congressmen into a compromise choice for chair of the bitterly
divided delegation, knows what a politician he was.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is going to have to find someone to act more like a
grownup. Not that there aren't those who do, but few would deny
that with the passage of Coverdell, the overall maturity level of
that body will decline considerably.
</P>
<P>
   This shy, sometimes awkward Iowa native served the state of
Georgia with a genuine respect for the institution, and never did
this shine through more clearly than in the impeachment trial of
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   An intense man with an active agenda, Coverdell might have
wished to be remembered for more active service. But it was the
essence of the man that when others were running to the
microphones, he conducted himself with the sobriety and decorum of
a judge.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate seemed to bring out something in him that was not so
obvious before his election in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   To have been deeply involved in Georgia Republican politics over
the past three decades, one almost inevitably has to have made a
lot of people mad at you. Coverdell was more deeply involved than
most. But many of those who have had their differences with him are
likely to feel the absence of one who took the interests of the
party so seriously.
</P>
<P>
   He was a power in the party before Newt Gingrich, and after. The
state's Republican establishment has now suffered two deep blows.
Whoever emerges as the GOP Senate candidate this fall will likely
also be running for the symbolic post of standard-bearer for the
state party.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia has never been unimportant to either of the presidential
campaigns, and a Senate election _ which could have a crucial
impact on the margin in the Senate a few years down the road - will
put the state at center stage for both national parties. It is the
sort of twist Paul Coverdell might have relished.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
