<HEADER>
A6041 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-GORE-FUNDRAISING-NYT &LR;      07-18 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-FUNDRAISING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS RAISED BY HOUSE PANEL ABOUT GORE REMARK AT FUND-RAISER 
</HEADLINE>
   By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Dan Burton urged Justice Department lawyers on
Tuesday to question Vice President Al Gore about a remark that he
makes on a videotape of a White House coffee in December 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The videotape is sensitive because it features both President
Clinton and Gore and contains two references to James Riady, an
Indonesian businessman who did not attend the coffee but whose
large contributions to the Democratic Party are the subject of a
federal investigation of campaign finance abuses.
</P>
<P>
   On the tape of the event, which took place on Dec. 15, 1995, in
the Roosevelt Room of the White House, Gore addresses Arief
Wiriadinata, an Indonesian gardener who illegally contributed
$455,000 to the Democratic Party earlier that year. The vice
president apparently mentions Riady.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is heard telling Wiriadinata that political issue
television advertisements, paid for by large contributors to the
Democratic Party, should be shown to Riady, Burton's investigators
said. Riady had not contributed any money to the Democrats in
either 1995 or 1996.
</P>
<P>
   On the tape, according to Burton, the vice president is heard
saying, ``We ought to, we ought to, we ought to show Riady the
tapes, some of the ad tapes.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is not seen on the tape saying those words, but Burton and
committee staff lawyers have concluded that it is the vice
president's voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the vice president's apparent location in the room, and
the apparent location of Wiriadinata, it is a reasonable assumption
that Vice President Gore was making this suggestion to
Wiriadinata,'' Burton wrote in a five-page letter to Attorney
General Janet Reno on Tuesday. ``It would indeed be extraordinary
for the vice president to suggest showing political issue
advertisements to an Indonesian billionaire who lives in Jakarta,
Indonesia.''
</P>
<P>
   During the same coffee, Wiriadinata tells President Clinton,
``James Riady sent me.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Kennedy, a spokesman for Gore, said, ``Wait until Dan Burton
finds out that when you play the tape backwards it says, `Paul is
dead.'''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Burton, R-Ind., is the chairman of the House Committee on
Government Reform, which has investigated campaign finance abuses
since 1997 and has had the videotape since late that year. It was
unclear why the committee is pursuing the issue of Gore's comment
now, but Burton intends to ask several witnesses about the matter
at a hearing scheduled for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the committee's investigators subpoenaed the original
coffee videotape from the White House and reviewed it on Monday at
the FBI laboratory in Quantico, Va., to ensure the accuracy of
Gore's words. Committee investigators say the vice president's
remark raises a question about what he may have known about any
relationship between Wiriadinata and Riady.
</P>
<P>
   The committee referred the videotape to the Justice Department
last December, but Gore was not asked about it during his interview
with federal investigators last April 19 or in four previous
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Burton said on Tuesday that this raised further questions about
the aggressiveness of the department's campaign finance inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a minimum, it is deeply disturbing that the Justice
Department has failed to take this piece of potential evidence
seriously,'' Burton wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Tuesday, James C. Wilson, the committee's
chief counsel, said: ``It would have been easy for the Justice
Department to have followed up on this information last year. I
don't understand why the attorney general failed to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiriadinata's contributions to the Democratic Party, totaling
$455,000, made headlines in late 1996 after it was reported that he
had little income working as a gardener in northern Virginia. His
father-in-law was a partner of Riady at the Lippo Group, the Riady
family conglomerate. The Democratic National Committee returned
Wiriadinata's contributions in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Wiriadinata is believed to be living in Indonesia, and has not
responded to the Burton committee's efforts to interview him.
</P>
<P>
   A White House official said that, after listening to the tape,
aides to Gore were not convinced that Riady's name was used by the
vice president. ``People say the V.P. is using a two-syllable name,
like Dotty or Godfrey, and not a five-syllable phrase like Riady,''
the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the official suggested more definitively that Gore had
used the name ``Godfrey'' during the remark. A Houston lawyer, Lee
Godfrey, had attended the same coffee.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Gore told investigators that he had seen Riady only
``twice in my life.'' The first time was during a trip to Malaysia,
and the second time was ``when he was in Betty Currie's office
preparing to go in to see the president with a couple of other
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton wrote in his letter, ``The vice president does not
describe the type of relationship with Riady that would lead him to
suggest a private screening of political advertisements in Jakarta,
Indonesia.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggests seven questions for Reno's investigators to ask Gore
about the incident. One of them is: ``If the vice president made a
suggestion about showing tapes to Riady, what did he know about
Riady that would lead him to make this suggestion in the presence
of Wiriadinata?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are interested,'' Burton writes in the conclusion of
his letter to Reno, ``the Committee on Government Reform has the
original Beta tape, and I would be willing to make arrangements to
furnish this evidence to you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
