<HEADER>
A6042 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-STOCKOPTIONS-MARKETPL     07-18 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKOPTIONS-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: SEC TO STUDY PAYMENT FOR ORDER FLOW IN STOCK
OPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Competition has come to the market for traded stock options, and
the customers may not be the winners.
</P>
<P>
   The four exchanges that trade stock options in this country
became more aggressive last fall in seeking to trade options that
had formerly been dominated by one exchange.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of that move, Arthur Levitt, the chairman of
the Securities and Exchange Commission, exulted that competition
was narrowing the spread between bid and asked prices for listed
options.
</P>
<P>
   ``In four of the five actively traded options we examined,
effective spreads have fallen between 22 and 44 percent since these
options went from single exchange trading to multiple listings,''
Levitt said in a speech last September.
</P>
<P>
   But those declines were temporary. Since then, competition for
options business has grown ever more steep _ but the competition
has taken the form of paying brokers for order flow. Spreads appear
to have widened, albeit not back to the previous levels. Wednesday
the SEC will announce a new study aimed at determining whether
payment for order flow is causing problems.
</P>
<P>
   For several months, the SEC has sat by as the payment for order
flow has intensified, to the irritation of many in the industry.
Some who are paying for order flow are furious that the SEC is not
stopping others from doing so.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are all saying, `We abhor this practice, and we wouldn't
do it if the SEC would just stop us,''' said one SEC staffer in
exasperation.
</P>
<P>
   Payment for order flow, long a practice in the stock market,
provides a way for brokerage firms to profit from sending their
orders to a particular place to be executed. Most of the electronic
brokerage firms now collect such payments in the options markets,
and other brokerage firms are beginning to look at getting such
payments.
</P>
<P>
   There were no such payments in the options market until last
fall in large part because there was little real competition in
that market. Even when options were listed on more than one
exchange, virtually all the business tended to be on one market.
Orders went where there was liquidity, which was where the orders
already were.
</P>
<P>
   That began to change last fall. The International Stock
Exchange, a new exchange, announced plans to begin trading many
options. (It did so in May, but so far has not had a very large
impact.) In addition, the Justice Department antitrust division
began showing interest in the options market. In short order, the
existing exchanges began to show more interest in competition.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom then was that the Chicago Board Options
Exchange, the leading market, would destroy the competition. In
fact, it has lost market share, in large part because a number of
specialist firms, which have operations on a number of exchanges,
began to offer to pay for order flow.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, the first to pay for order flow appears to have
been Susquehanna Partners, which had taken responsibility for
Microsoft options at the Chicago exchange. Microsoft options had
been dominated by the Pacific Coast Stock Exchange. Those payments
began last fall, and enabled Chicago to gain substantial market
share in those options.
</P>
<P>
   When Susquehanna began paying for order flow, it captured the
attention of other exchanges. Soon other exchanges began offering
major market makers, like Spear, Leeds &AMP; Kellogg and Knight, as
well as Susquehanna, the right to be the specialist on their
exchanges in options that had not previously been traded on those
exchanges. Some of those market makers were paying for order flow,
and they brought in business. At exchanges, the specialists are the
major players in any given option, but other local market makers
also participate in the trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``People thought multiple listing of options would be the death
knell for us,'' said Meyer Frucher, the chairman of the
Philadelphia Stock Exchange, on Tuesday. ``But it has proved to be
the salvation.'' Frucher said he came to realize that in the
changing options market it would be the specialist that would
become the brand name, not the options exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Brokerage firms that do business with Susquehanna route orders
to it to be traded at whichever market Susquehanna is the
specialist. It is a specialist in about 600 stocks, doing business
at all four markets. Susquehanna officials declined to speak on the
record about their business.
</P>
<P>
   As Chicago saw its market share begin to wither, it looked for
ways to get some of it back. On July 6, it stunned competitors with
its own plan. All market makers on the Chicago floor, whether the
specialists or those in the crowd, will pay a fee of 40 cents per
options contract, or 0.4 cents a share of stock covered by an
option contract. That fee will go to the exchange, which will give
it to specialists to use for marketing purposes, whether paying for
order flow or putting out glossy brochures.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to that, the CBOE had been among the harshest critics of
payment for order flow. But, said Edward J. Joyce, the exchange's
president, it had no choice. ``If payment for order flow is going
to be a factor, then we are going to compete on that front as
well,'' he said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago exchange was at a competitive disadvantage because
many of its specialists are local firms that handle relatively few
stocks and thus are less able to make deals with brokerage firms
that do not want to make dozens of deals to route order flow in
various stocks.
</P>
<P>
   To the amazement of other exchanges, the SEC allowed that
proposal to go into effect immediately, rather than suspending it
while seeking comment for 60 days. To the SEC, it appears to have
been a case of letting Chicago join the competition. To the other
exchanges, it amounted to a new and dangerous type of competition _
one that involves the exchange itself collecting the marketing fees
and that gets payments not just from the specialist but from all
market makers operating in a stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Purchase of order flow by an exchange is an untested concept
with uncertain ramifications,'' wrote Lanny A. Schwartz, the
Philadelphia exchange's general counsel, in a letter to the SEC.
``The commission should carefully consider all aspects of the
proposal before permitting its implementation.''
</P>
<P>
   Untested concept or not, Philadelphia announced last week that
it would mimic the Chicago plan, but would pay $1 a contract, or
two and a half times as much.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
