</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT EARNINGS EXCEED EXPECTATIONS, DRIVEN BY 10 PERCENT RISE
IN PROFIT 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE LOHR      
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. slightly beat Wall Street's expectations Tuesday
as its quarterly profits rose 10 percent, even though revenues were
flat.
</P>
<P>
   The leading software company got its biggest lift in the quarter
from a surge in the income from its swelling portfolio of cash and
equity investments. Microsoft executives cautioned that investment
income should drop in the current quarter. But they then delivered
an optimistic outlook for the current fiscal year, which begins
this month, saying the company expects revenues to rise 15 percent
over the next year with earnings rising roughly 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very, very good entering the next fiscal year,'' said
John Connors, the chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterly results, according to analysts, suggest that
Microsoft seems to be skillfully handling the uncertainties it
faces in its business and on the legal front. It is in the midst of
a transition in its product markets as its new Windows 2000
operating system is adopted gradually by corporate customers, at a
time when the business market for computers has been sluggish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a slow but steady transitionary quarter from Microsoft
sprinkled with some optimism for the future,'' said Richard
Sherlund, an analyst at Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has also just begun a longer-term shift in strategy as
more and more of its business will come from selling software as
Internet services _ an initiative the company announced last month,
called Microsoft.Net. That effort, analysts note, will require
significant investments by the company, though it will not yield
substantial revenues for at least another year.
</P>
<P>
   During a conference call with analysts Tuesday, Connors referred
only obliquely to the federal court ruling in April that Microsoft
was a monopolist that had repeatedly violated the nation's
antitrust laws. In listing the challenges the company had tackled
during the quarter, he mentioned the ``unprecedented level of news
on the legal front.''
</P>
<P>
   All sanctions against Microsoft _ including an order to split
the company in two _ have been stayed pending appeals, which could
take a year or more.
</P>
<P>
   In part because of the uncertainties raised by the antitrust
case, Microsoft stock fell by nearly 50 percent in the first five
months of this year, from a 52-week high of $119.09375 on Dec. 30
to $60.375 on May 26. Tuesday it closed at $78.50, up 31.25 cents.
The earnings announcement came after the market had closed.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter, Microsoft earnings rose nearly 10 percent to
$2.4 billion, or 44 cents a share. The consensus per-share estimate
among 24 analysts polled by First Call/Thomson Financial, was 42
cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   In the comparable quarter a year earlier, Microsoft reported
earnings of $2.2 billion, or 40 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's revenues for the most recent quarter were in line
with analysts' expectations at $5.80 billion, though up a mere $40
million from the year-earlier quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft continues to garner an increasing share of its
quarterly profits from gains on its sizable investment portfolio
rather than from current operations. In the June quarter, the
company reported investment income of more than $1.1 billion, or 31
percent of its pretax profits. In the year-ago quarter, Microsoft's
investment income added $485 million to its pretax income,
representing 14 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Microsoft pretax income from operations actually
declined in the most recent quarter to $2.5 billion, compared with
$2.9 billion in the quarter a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Connors said that the company's investment income will be
somewhat cyclical and that its contribution in the next quarter
will likely be ``significantly lower'' than in the June quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he told analysts, ``you should expect investment income
from Microsoft'' in the future generally.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the explanation is that Microsoft's business is a money
machine that piles up cash far faster than the company spends it.
And the added money in the company coffers earns dividends. At the
end of June, cash and marketable securities reached $23.8 billion,
up from $17.2 billion a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Microsoft has a $17.8 billion portfolio of equity
investments in technology companies, which are typically business
partners of Microsoft. In fiscal 2000 alone, Microsoft made 100
such investments totaling $5.4 billion. If those companies are
acquired, for example, Microsoft must sell its stake and report the
gain as portfolio income.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have been closely following the quarterly results for
signs of how Windows 2000, the new operating system introduced
earlier this year, is selling. Windows 2000 refers both to a new
version of Microsoft's desktop operating system for corporations
and new server software for running corporate networks and Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Connors declined to give much detail on Windows 2000 sales,
beyond saying the company is ``quite satisfied'' with early
deployments in big companies including General Motors, Royal
Dutch/Shell, Xerox and Motorola. Last month, the Defense Department
announced that Windows 2000 would be the technology platform for
its ``integrated warfare system'' on the Navy's next generation of
aircraft carriers, the CVN-77, known as the ``smart carrier.''
</P>
<P>
   The consumer market is carrying the personal computer market,
Connors noted, with year-to-year growth of roughly 15 percent.
Business demand is still sluggish in part because of the falloff in
spending following the widely anticipated Year 2000 problem.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts expect the September quarter, a traditionally slow
one for business purchases, to not be particularly significant as a
sign of whether corporate demand is picking up or how well Windows
2000 is doing. ``It looks like we'll have to wait until the
December quarter to get a really solid reading on where things
stand,'' said Sherlund of Goldman Sachs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
