<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR WEDNESDAY, JULY 19 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Wednesday, July 19. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-KOSOVO-HATE-NYT (moved on Sunday, July 16)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, July 16,
about Bernard Kouchner, the top United Nations official in Kosovo,
referred incorrectly to the military force there. As noted
elsewhere in the article, it is led by NATO. It is made up mainly
of NATO troops, with some from countries that are not NATO members.
It is not a United Nations force.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-MORGAN-NYT (moved on Saturday, July 15)
</P>
<P>
   An obituary on Sunday about John Morgan, a British etiquette
expert, misstated a recommendation of his that drew a columnist's
criticism in The Guardian. Mr. Morgan endorsed birth announcements
of heavy card stock cut from a sheet weighing 335 grams over all,
approximately 11.8 ounces; it was not the announcements that were
to weigh 335 grams.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT (moved on Monday, July 17)
</P>
<P>
   Because of an editing error, a report in the Campaign Briefing
column yesterday about a USA Today/CNN Gallup poll on the
presidential race misstated the results in some copies. In a
two-way competition, Gov. George W. Bush led Vice President Al Gore
48 percent to 46 percent. (The figures 45 percent and 43 percent
were their showings in a four-way competition that included Ralph
Nader and Pat Buchanan.)
</P>
<P>
   BC-NY-BLAST-NY (moved on Wednesday, July 12)
</P>
<P>
   A front-page article on Thursday about community spirit on the
Brooklyn block that was the scene of a fatal explosion referred
incorrectly to three neighbors of Leonard and Harriet Walit, the
couple who died. A baby whom the Walits had helped move into a car
was with Melanie Morton, not with a couple from the block. And the
couple's names are Andreas Killen and Marie Sacco, not Andreas and
Maria Sassos.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SKECHERS-LAGEAR-GREENBERGS-NYT (moved on Monday, July 17)
</P>
<P>
   Because of an editing error, an article in Business Day
yesterday about Skechers U.S.A. the shoe company, misstated its
financial performance for the third quarter of 1999. The company
had net income of $8.5 million, down $5 million from the quarter a
year earlier. It did not report a loss. The article and a picture
caption also misspelled the surname of the chief executive of
Element Holdings Inc., a marketing firm, who commented on the
popularity of the company's shoes. He is Kevin Umeh, not Ume.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
