<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE BILL ON CHINA TRADE FACES DELAY, LOTT PREDICTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate is unlikely to vote on a bill to grant
permanent normal trade relations to China before Congress adjourns
next week, meaning the vote would be delayed at least until
September, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very hard to get a final vote on PNTR before the
recess, if all of the options available to those that oppose the
bill exercised them, because there are several points where delay
could occur, filibusters could occur,'' Lott said, using the
shorthand for the trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   But Lott said senators still might begin debating the measure as
early as next Wednesday and wrap up when the Senate returned after
Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   Lott downplayed warnings by critics who say that delaying a
final vote is risky and insisted that the Senate would eventually
approve the trade measure by an overwhelming margin. The House
passed the measure, 237 to 197, on May 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe delay is dangerous, and certainly not fatal,''
Lott told reporters. ``The overwhelming majority of the Senate is
for China PNTR. The headline is going to read, sometime here in the
next month: `Senate Passes China Trade Bill.' And I don't think
there's going to be any significant change or any way to stop
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders, who are traditional Republican allies, have
been critical of Lott for putting one of their top legislative
priorities in jeopardy. They fear that postponing the final vote on
the measure could expose it to unforeseen impediments.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, though, the top priority for Senate Republicans has
been to pass two tax-cutting measures and as many of the 13 annual
spending bills to finance the government as possible before the
Republican National Convention, which begins at the end of this
month.
</P>
<P>
   With at least 70 senators prepared to vote for the trade
measure, associates of Lott say that he feels he has the luxury of
using the timing of the vote as leverage to win concessions from
Senate Democrats and the White House on the spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for the delay has been that supporters are trying
to pass a clean version of the House bill. If any amendments are
tacked on in the Senate, the whole measure would have to return to
the House for a second and potentially volatile vote.
</P>
<P>
   Senate and administration aides have worked fruitlessly over the
last week to work out a compromise on a measure offered sponsored
by Senators Fred Thompson (R-Tenn.) and Robert G. Torricelli
(D-N.J.).
</P>
<P>
   Their measure would require the administration to monitor
China's record on the spread of nuclear weapons. It would impose
automatic sanctions on China if there is ``credible evidence'' of
exports of certain types of prohibited weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton would have discretion to waive some penalties, but
others would be automatic. The administration and business leaders
have opposed the measure as unnecessary, even after Thompson agreed
to water down several provisions.
</P>
<P>
   Other senators, including Paul Wellstone (D-Minn.) and Jesse
Helms (R-N.C.) have said they want to offer amendments dealing with
China's record on human rights, labor standards and national
security.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Helms opened the first of two days of hearings by the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee, which he heads, to examine the
trade bill's impact. Helms opposes the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most disturbing are those who want to prevent Congress from
even addressing these national security questions during the PNTR
debate,'' Helms said, ``for fear that it will complicate what
amounts to a single-minded, dollar-driven crusade to make certain
this trade deal is approved in the Senate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
