<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6055 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TOURDEFRANCE-MARKETIN     07-18 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOURDEFRANCE-MARKETING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING AS FARCE ALONGSIDE THE TOUR DE FRANCE 
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: See also TOUR-DE-FRANCE, moved in ``s'' sports category.) 
 By SAMUEL ABT  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COURCHEVEL, France _ Christophe Benoit is spending three weeks
in July traveling around France on a four-wheel motorcycle inside a
huge pot of a pork-flavored pate. Mohamet, who declines to give any
last name, is making the same journey inside a can of butane gas.
Philippe Chapuis is going sometimes on roller skates, sometimes in
the back of a car in the white doughboy garb of Bibendum, the
Michelin man.
</P>
<P>
   The three, and 600 co-workers, are part of an enormous
advertising convoy that precedes the Tour de France, as the world's
greatest bicycle race takes three weeks to circumnavigate more than
2,200 miles of France and slices of Switzerland and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   All along the way, 40 European companies will spend millions of
dollars for the opportunity to acquaint a huge audience with their
products or, as detractors put it, litter the roads with junk.
There are lots of products: Each of 200 vehicles distributes at
least 5,000 objects a day or 20 million by the end of the race in
Paris on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies distribute many more gifts. ``We give away 20,000
bags a day, or 400,000 by the end of the race,'' said Daniel Isaac,
director of communications for Credit Lyonnais, the big French
bank. ``We've been a partner of the Tour for 20 years,'' he added.
``It's very important for our image.''
</P>
<P>
   The gifts are as varied as the givers. An off-track betting
system, the Pari Mutuel Urbain, distributes oversized green
cardboard hands. One of the country's trade union confederations,
Force Ouvriere, offers a yo-yo.
</P>
<P>
   Michelin and France Telecom give caps to many of the 15 million
spectators watching the race along the roads.
</P>
<P>
   The Champion supermarket chain is pleased to give a guide to
many sports, not including bicycle racing. Cochonou, a sausage
company, offers the obvious, as does Coeur de Lion, a cheese
company, and Haribo, a candy maker. La Redoute, a mail-order
department store chain, supplies shade screens for car windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can give just a piece of paper,'' said Jean-Pierre
Lachaud, who has directed the publicity caravan's operations since
1989. ``But an object of some value with a piece of paper, that's
OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Lachaud works with 10 assistants to run the caravan's
operations, using a radio-equipped plane to make sure the vehicles
are spaced correctly. ``Since 1989, we've made the caravan roll in
staggered formation so that journalists' cars can get through,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For safety, all objects are supposed to be handed to spectators,
not just dropped on the road. Nevertheless, many samples are flung
at the crowd and wind up in traffic, where young and old often dart
heedlessly to retrieve them. A 12-year-old boy died on Sunday, a
few days after he was hit by a vehicle as the caravan passed; it
was the first such death reported in a dozen years.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicles of the 40 advertisers, up from 36 last year, do not
include 35 more cars and trucks that sell magazines, newspapers and
T-shirts. Few salesmen follow the bicycle race itself, because most
spectators go home once the riders have passed.
</P>
<P>
   The caravan dates to 1930, when the Tour switched from teams
sponsored by companies, mainly bicycle manufacturers, to national
teams. While the teams that were commercially supported paid a fee
to enter, the national teams did not, and Tour de France officials
decided that income had to be increased. When commercially
supported teams were reintroduced in the 1960's, the caravan was
such a big part of the event that it was retained.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say the caravan helps entertain and enliven the crowd
when it passes an hour before the riders.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the gifts are very important, just little souvenirs,
but fun,'' said Isabelle Colombeau, a teacher, as she waited for
the caravan recently with her mother, father and brother. Nearby, a
small child cried, having been beaten by an adult to a leaflet from
Cofidis, a telephone credit service.
</P>
<P>
   The Colombeau family was especially pleased with its haul of key
rings from TotalFina Elf, the merged French oil company, and small
pots of rillettes, or pork pate from Bordeau Chesnel, the employer
of Benoit in his oversized mock pot.
</P>
<P>
   Each advertiser is charged a total of 130,000 French francs _
more than $18,000 _ for the first three vehicles and 30,000 francs
for each additional one, according to Florence Maire of the Tour's
marketing department. While most advertisers have three or four
vehicles, the insurer AGF reinforces its cars with a squadron of
young women on motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies employ young women to sit in the backs of open
cars all day, no matter what the weather, and wave to the fans or
swing their arms to the disco beat pulsing from an adjoining
loudspeaker as a young man pitches objects from the front seat.
That amounts to a lot of waving and swinging, since the average
daily stage of the race is 105 miles in four or five hours.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the workers appear to enjoy their jobs. Although their
pay by the advertisers is minimal, they say, they get free room and
board plus a chance to see the country and do a bit of partying
once the caravan is parked for the night.
</P>
<P>
   And, if they stay at it long enough, as Chapuis, the Michelin
man, has done, there is the ultimate honor: A week ago he was
awarded the medal of the Tour de France for 20 years' service and
devotion to the race. The millions at the sides of the many roads
simply thought he was waving at them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
