A6058 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-HOUSE-SPAM-HNS &LR;      07-18 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-SPAM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE APPROVES ANTI-SPAMMING MEASURE 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ E-mail users tired of wading through unsolicited
online advertisements would be able to compel companies to stop
sending the junk mail under legislation the House passed 427-1
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which now goes to the Senate, would permit computer
users to tell the Federal Trade Commission that they do not want to
receive the unwelcome e-mail ads, or ``spam'' in online lingo.
Direct marketers and other advertisers making wide use of the
Internet would be barred from e-mailing ads to any computer user
who has listed his online address with the agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``E-mail can be a useful advertising tool for business if used
properly and with the consumer's consent,'' said Rep. Gene Green,
D-Texas, the bill's chief sponsor. ``However, Internet users should
be given the opportunity to move out of the fast lane of the
information superhighway to better control the bulk e-mails
streaming across their computers.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ron Paul, R-Texas, was the only lawmaker to oppose the
legislation. He objected to the bill's provision that would have
federal law supplant state efforts to control unwanted e-mail
advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed Unsolicited Electronic Mail Act seeks to discourage
companies from sending unwanted ads by requiring them to include
their return e-mail address. Inclusion of the return address would
make it easier for recipients to reply and tell the companies to
stop sending ads, Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that fail to comply with the computer user's wishes
would be subject to a trade commission order to stop sending
advertisements. Defiance of the agency could leave the advertisers
subject to a court order that they stop.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that then fail to obey the order could be held in
contempt and fined, at the court's discretion.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney who represents direct marketers criticized what he
called ill-advised legislation that could hamper the ``free and
fair exchange'' of ideas on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would add another layer of complexity for an evolving
industry and hamper the ability of companies to get their messages
to consumers,`` said Andrew Lustigman of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Green, however, said the bill would not unduly interfere with
the right of companies to advertise.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the right to speak,'' he said, but they ``don't have
the right to make people listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the measure, the trade commission would be permitted to
charge computer users an as-yet-determined fee to defray the
agency's cost of compiling and maintaining the list and making it
available to companies.
</P>
<P>
   Internet providers would be able to sue for up to $25,000 those
online advertisers that fail to comply with a customer's request
not to receive their e-mail. Courts could increase the amount of
damages if they conclude that the companies ``willfully or
knowingly'' defied the request.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
