<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6060 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MICKEYMOUSE-ART-COX     07-18 0386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICKEYMOUSE-ART-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge: Museum can keep Mickey Mouse art, for now
 &HT;    By Bill Douthat
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH _Mickey Mouse will be hanging around Boca
Raton's International Museum of Cartoon Art for awhile longer.
</P>
<P>
   Circuit Judge Walter Colbath ruled Tuesday that, while a bank
can take possession of the earliest-known drawings of the famous
rodent in a mortgage foreclosure, there is no need for a
lickety-split seizure. With the extra time, the museum may be able
to keep one of its most-prized possessions.
</P>
<P>
   Colbath set a Aug. 1 hearing to allow the museum and SunTrust
Bank to recommend how the fragile, pencil drawings would be removed
from the museum in Mizner Park. Sometime after the hearing, the
judge will decide how the move would take place.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's exactly what we were hoping,'' said Nancy Colman, an
attorney for the museum, who asked for a three- to four-week delay
in the seizure of the drawings in a hearing last week. Colman said
the museum should be given enough time to refinance the mortgage,
allowing them to keep the drawings.
</P>
<P>
   SunTrust Bank wants the drawings because the museum is $170,000
in arrears on payments. The museum owes $1.1 million on a $3
million mortgage it took out in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The 36 drawings, valued by the museum at $3.2 to $3.7 million,
were pledged as collateral for the loan. The drawings were created
in 1927 for the animated film ``Plane Crazy,'' the first film
featuring Mickey Mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Beetle Bailey cartoonist Mort Walker, the museum's founder and
chairman, has called the drawings the museum's ``Mona Lisa.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker's wife, Catherine, said Tuesday that the judge's order
gives the museum some breathing room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand that (the judge) ruled for the bank, but
truthfully, we are very pleased that they are not going to be taken
out of the museum right now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At last week's hearing, museum curator Stephen Charla said the
drawings are historic artifacts and should not be moved without
great care.
</P>
<P>
   Museum employees suggested it could take three to four weeks to
plan and carry out a move of the framed drawings.
</P>
<P>
   That could give Mickey even more time for th museum to save his
home.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
