<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6063 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-GAPAC19-COX     07-18 0364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAPAC19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia-Pacific to spin off timber-growing division
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - Georgia-Pacific Corp. shored up its pledge to move
away from its commodity roots Tuesday, saying it will no longer own
the trees that feed its pulp, paper and building products business.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific said it plans to spin off its timber-growing
arm, the Timber Co., and merge it with Plum Creek Timber Co.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed $4 billion deal, Plum Creek would become the
second-largest private timberland owner in the country and retain
headquarters in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The Timber Co. manages 5 million acres, primarily in the
Southeast. After the merger, Plum Creek would own 8 million acres
concentrated in the South, the Northeast and the Rocky Mountain
regions.
</P>
<P>
   The $4 billion deal includes $1 billion in Timber Co. debt.
Timber shareholders will get 1.37 shares of Plum Creek for each
share of Timber held.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is the second strategic move by Georgia-Pacific in as
many days. On Monday, the Atlanta-based company announced plans to
buy rival Fort James for $11 billion to become the largest maker of
tissue products.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific also plans to sell mills that don't fit its new
consumer-oriented focus.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific Chairman and Chief Executive Pete Correll told
analysts in New York on Tuesday that the Timber Co. spinoff and
merger mark a departure from traditional philosophies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manufacturers don't have to own timberlands to be
competitive,'' Correll said.
</P>
<P>
   The companies said that Plum Creek would keep the Timber Co.'s
office and employees in Atlanta. Plum Creek's president and chief
executive, Rick Holley, will retain his position in the merged
company. Timber Co. President and Chief Executive Don Glass would
become chief operating officer and a director.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction must get approval from the companies'
shareholders. They also need a ruling from the Internal Revenue
Service allowing the transaction to be tax-free to Georgia-Pacific
and Plum Creek, and the shareholders of Timber Co.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
