<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6065 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-BLACK-VOTE-TEX     07-18 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-VOTE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACKS ALONE IN INCREASING VOTER TURNOUT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
 By BECHETTA JACKSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ It's no surprise to Ealy Boyd that
African-American voter participation in Texas and across the nation
increased from 1994 to 1998, even though it was a non-presidential
election year.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Boyd was working out of a cramped office in Town
Center Mall, helping run the Tarrant County Democratic Party's
get-out-the-vote effort.
</P>
<P>
   He handed out candidates' literature, worked the phones and
urged people in the mall to stop by the voter registration table.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good message, but the issues brought people to the
polls,'' said Boyd, 65, a retired suburban Fort Worth resident who
remains active with the Democratic party.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the things that we fought dearly for in the 60's and
70's had eroded away with the Republican Congress,'' Boyd said.
``People were just tired of that. They showed it by voting.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, African-Americans were the only ethnic group to
increase voter participation in Congressional elections from 1994
to 1998 _ improving from 37 percent to 40 percent _ an 8 percent
increase _ according to U.S. Census figures released on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, the black vote mirrored national figures. The
African-American vote in Texas increased from 33.1 percent in 1994
to 36.7 percent in 1998, said Census researcher Avalaura Gaither
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Anglo vote in Texas increased from 39.4 percent in
1994 to 42.4 percent in 1998, the nationwide number of white voters
decreased from 50 percent to 47 percent during that period, the
figures show.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic turnout in the Lone Star State decreased to 15.3
percent in 1998 from 18.9 percent in 1994. Nationally, the Hispanic
vote remained at 20 percent, Gaither said.
</P>
<P>
   The increase by black voters is a sign of things to come, said
Gary Bledsoe, president of the Texas State Conference of NAACP
Branches.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an even more serious push this year to increase the
African-American vote,'' Bledsoe said yesterday from his office in
Austin. ``We're working to see to it that those figures increase
further.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, African-Americans were frustrated with former House
Speaker Newt Gingrich's controversial Contract with America, as
well as the conservative leadership in Congress, said Roy Brooks,
precinct administrator for Tarrant County Commissioner Dionne
Bagsby.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lack of ability to get our issues addressed in
Congress,'' he said. ``We tend to vote most when our issues are
threatened.''
</P>
<P>
   African-Americans were also angered by President Clinton's
treatment during the height of the Monica Lewinsky scandal, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   At the local level, voters were concerned about county politics,
said Brooks, president of the National Association of Black County
Officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``People often perceive that the African-American voting block
is unsophisticated, but nothing could be further from the truth,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, overall turnout was down three percentage points,
from 45 percent in 1994 to 42 percent in 1998, a decline of about 3
million voters, the census data showed.
</P>
<P>
   While other ethnic groups stayed home in large numbers during
the off-year election, the NAACP and religious leaders mounted a
grassroots effort to get African-Americans to the polls, Bledsoe
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we couldn't slack off because Newt Gingrich was
speaker and there were escalated attacks on affirmative action,''
he said. ``People who thought that their vote did not make a
difference came to realize that Congress was much more important
than they had previously thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Black leaders made a concerted effort to mobilize black voters,
said J. Matthew Wilson, a professor of political science at
Southern Methodist University.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were the only major demographic group to do that,'' he
said. ``They wanted to help Democratic candidates in congressional
elections, and it worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks said he's delighted to know that the recent surge in
black voting has been documented.
</P>
<P>
   ``It lends credence to the fact that the black vote is still
vital and should be sought out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ealy, the Democratic Party worker, predicts that
African-Americans will increase the numbers further this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a critical election ahead of us,'' he said. ``I'll
certainly be out there trying to get people registered and to the
polls.''
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
