<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6066 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FASTFOOD-AD-COLUMN-NY     07-18 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASTFOOD-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: TACO BELL DROPS THE CREATOR OF ITS WISECRACKING
CHIHUAHUA 
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Taco Bell, the fast-food chain specializing in Mexican-style
meals, is suddenly saying adios to TBWA/Chiat/Day, the agency that
created the company's popular talking Chihuahua character.
</P>
<P>
   Taco Bell, based in Irvine, Calif., said Tuesday that it would
dismiss TBWA/Chiat/Day after three years of producing national
advertising campaigns and consolidate its account, for now, at FCB
Worldwide, an agency that has handled other duties. The billings
for the entire account were estimated at more than $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   The dismissal of the Playa del Rey, Calif., office of
TBWA/Chiat/Day came with the abrupt simultaneous departure of Peter
Waller, who as Taco Bell's president headed its marketing efforts.
The changes reflect the intensifying competition in the fast-food
industry as marketers jostle one another for what they call share
of stomach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's increasingly difficult for the `quick service' players to
show the kinds of gains they enjoyed in the past,'' said Ron Paul,
president of Technomic in Chicago, a restaurant consulting company,
``and somebody has to be blamed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not shoot the messenger,'' he added, ``it's shoot the
agency.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite widespread acclaim for the canine character, which
talked thanks to computer-generated effects, Taco Bell's sales had
stagnated recently. The dog's role was played down in current
commercials that played up the quality of the chain's food instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not what we wanted to do,'' said Tom Carroll, president
and chief executive at the TBWA/Chiat/Day office, adding that the
dog, which uttered expressions like ``Yo quiero (I want) Taco
Bell,'' has been ``one of the best advertising icons in recent
memory, which helped Taco Bell with the younger consumers who eat
fast food most.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When we did the advertising we felt we should do and had the
product, we sold product,'' Carroll said. ``The business isn't
doing well and we're one of the victims.''
</P>
<P>
   The dismissal of TBWA/Chiat/Day, part of the TBWA Worldwide unit
of the Omnicom Group, was not entirely unexpected. The trade
publications Advertising Age and Adweek reported this week that
Taco Bell had awarded an undisclosed national assignment to the FCB
unit known as FCB Southern California, based in Costa Mesa, which
handles assignments like media buying and field marketing.
</P>
<P>
   FCB Southern California had created national campaigns for Taco
Bell, carrying themes like ``Run for the border,'' until 1994, when
it lost that assignment to Bozell Worldwide in Costa Mesa and
Richards Group in Dallas. TBWA/Chiat/Day succeeded them in March
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``FCB is a creative powerhouse'' that ``understands our
business,'' said David Novak, chief executive at Tricon Global
Restaurants in Louisville, Ky., which owns Taco Bell along with KFC
and Pizza Hut.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Novak praised FCB, which created Taco Bell ads
during the chain's largest sustained sales gains in the 1980s and
early '90s, as ``committed to driving our same-store sales growth
with compelling advertising.'' He also outlined the ``immediate
challenge'' that faces FCB: to ``give us a fresh creative approach
to help improve sales trends.''
</P>
<P>
   FCB will handle all aspects of the Taco Bell account, Novak
said, until Waller's successor, Emil Brolick, determines whether
the agency will keep the creative duties or whether they will be
placed in review. Brolick is joining Taco Bell, with the title
president and chief concept officer, from Wendy's International in
Dublin, Ohio, where he had most recently been senior vice president
for new product marketing, research and strategic planning.
</P>
<P>
   Novak said in his statement that he and Waller had ``mutually
agreed it is an appropriate time at Taco Bell to bring in a new,
outside perspective, both in terms of new management leadership and
advertising support.''
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Ryan, chief executive in New York at FCB, part of True
North Communications, said he would disagree with an assessment
that FCB has a lock on the national creative assignment, as Brolick
considers his next moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great opportunity for us,'' Ryan said, ``but new
clients or old clients, if you don't come through and drive sales,
you're going to be in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to come through,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of the Taco Bell assignment is a blow to
TBWA/Chiat/Day, which is known for creating characters that
entertain consumers as they peddle products.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the agency, creations like the Taco Bell
Chihuahua and Mr. K, the smiling mascot for Nissan cars and trucks,
have been deemed more effective at generating smiles than at
selling burritos or sedans.
</P>
<P>
   But Carroll disagreed, saying: ``It's an old rap that just
doesn't hold water. It's product and promotion that drive frequency
and loyalty in fast food. It's advertising's job to create a
window, and we created a pretty big window.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when brands are struggling,'' he added, referring to
the recent period when the Chihuahua was de-emphasized in the
campaign, ``good things are dismantled.''
</P>
<P>
   The dog that talked with a sassy attitude and a Mexican accent
was introduced by TBWA/Chiat/Day in 1997 as an incidental character
in a single commercial. But the idea captured the public's fancy
and the the dog began appearing in more spots, then soon became a
popular culture phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   The dog appeared on the annual ``It List'' of hot trends
published by Entertainment Weekly magazine as well as on
merchandise like T-shirts and hats. Giveaways of talking Chihuahua
dolls were among the most successful Taco Bell promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what plans FCB might have for the dog, Ryan said, ``I
don't want to go into that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
