<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6067 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-ART-CALDER-SPI &LR;      07-18 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-CALDER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALDER`S 39-FOOT `EAGLE' HEADING FOR SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REGINA HACKETT  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A bright red colossus is headed for Seattle: Alexander Calder's
39-foot sculpture ``Eagle.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Art Museum announced Tuesday it had acquired the
1971 sculpture as the centerpiece of its planned Olympic Sculpture
Park with funds provided by former Microsoft president Jon Shirley
and his wife, Mary.
</P>
<P>
   Although the museum declined to say how much the sculpture cost,
dealers in the field estimated its value at roughly $7 million or
more. That's high for Calders but justified because of its size and
the fact that unique, monumental Calders rarely come on the market.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 10 years, the Shirleys have become two of the most
important art collectors and patrons in the region. Their interest
is modern and contemporary art, and they tend to buy in depth from
artists they admire, including New York painter Chuck Close. Once
they commit to an artist, they stay committed. For Close, they
helped fund his retrospective exhibit at New York's Museum of
Modern Art that appeared last year at the Seattle Art Museum,
thanks to the Shirleys' intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of art circles, Jon Shirley is best known as the third
president of Microsoft. In the 1980s, the long-time Tandy Corp.
executive brought business discipline to Bill Gates' young company
and steered it through the birth of the Windows operating system,
the move to the Redmond campus and the initial public stock
offering. He retired in 1990. Late last year, Forbes magazine
estimated his net worth at $653 million.
</P>
<P>
   Slated to open in 2003, the Sculpture Park has already been the
recipient of the Shirleys' generosity. They've given $10 million to
the creation of the park, the single largest donation and a hefty
portion of its $32 million overall cost: $17 million to purchase
the land, $15 for site development and $5 million for an endowment
fund to run it.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the museum had raised $29.3 million of the total,
leaving $7.7 million to go. Since then, the figure has grown only
by another $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the entire $32 million hits the museum's coffers,
there will be nothing left over for the purchase of art. Some
people have been wondering nervously if the seven and one-half acre
sculpture garden adjoining Myrtle Edwards Park on the Seattle
waterfront will turn out to be an empty shell, great for water and
mountain views and not so hot for artwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eagle'' proves such fears are groundless. The first piece
specifically earmarked for the park, ``Eagle'' will be its
keystone, creating what SAM director Mimi Gates called a ``lasting
legacy for generations to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates said acquiring the Calder was completely the Shirleys'
idea. ``They're committed to the park and to the power of outdoor
sculpture,'' she said. ``I love this piece, the fact that it's an
eagle, that there's tension between representation and abstraction.
It bursts upward with such graceful arches. I think it's the
perfect symbol for the city and for the museum.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there are a number of Calders in private collections in
the Northwest, this will be the only Calder sculpture in a public
collection in Seattle and the most important Calder in the region.
</P>
<P>
   The artist was still at the peak of his powers in 1971, the year
he was awarded the Gold Medal for Sculpture by the American Academy
of Arts and Letters and five years before his death at age 78.
</P>
<P>
   He was that rarity in modern art, a major figure who took
himself lightly. His made his substantial contribution by
celebrating the value of toys, circuses, free movement, abstract
form and lumpy, dumpy grace. He invented the idea of sculptural
mobiles, those masses of painted steel that hang in space and turn
freely, but even his stationary sculptures, such as ``Eagle,''
suggest movement in their motionless masses.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Philadelphia, the son of artist parents, Calder earned a
degree in mechanical engineering before turning his attention to
art in 1923, attending classes at the Art Students League in New
York and supporting himself with commercial illustrations.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris in 1926, he was first attracted to the
organically-shaped sculptures of Jean Arp and Joan Miro, as well as
the drawings of Paul Klee. Just as Klee said he wanted to take a
``line for a walk'' in his drawings,'' Calder decided he wanted to
take a line for a walk in his sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   He began making toys and circus figures out of wood, fabric and
metal, moving quickly to purely metal figures: drawings in space.
In 1930, he paid a decisive visit to Piet Mondrian's studio, where
the young sculptor was struck by the force of purely abstract art.
He told Mondrian he wanted to make the painter's sort of
abstractions move in space, which failed to create joy in the heart
of the older and more dogmatic artist.
</P>
<P>
   Calder wanted to sculpt volume without heavy mass, to entertain
space without filling it, to suggest instead of dictate. He thought
often of the music of the spheres and liked to think the universe
could hum. He wanted his sculptures to reflect that universal
tunefulness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eagle'' rests lightly on two feet with two abstracted wings in
the air, one bent informally forward, the bent wing breaking the
symmetry of the whole and giving a scruffy, devil-may-care grace.
</P>
<P>
   The sculpture will arrive early in the fall from its present
home in front of the Philadelphia Museum of Art, where it has been
on loan for nearly a year. The Seattle Art Museum has yet to
announce where ``Eagle'' will be placed until the Olympic Sculpture
Park opens.
</P>
<P>
   P-I business reporter Dan Richman contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
