</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR-TRAFFIC SYSTEM APPROACHED GRIDLOCK, WITH DELAYS OF UP TO 8
HOURS 
</HEADLINE>
  (duplication notice: also sent with `t' code) 
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Business travelers who go online for information might consider
bookmarking the new Federal Aviation Administration Web site that
gives real-time information on flight delays. It is
www.fly.faa.gov. The ``fly'' in the Web address is amusingly
optimistic. ``No fly'' would be more accurate these days.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, for example, delays began piling up on Friday,
when many flights from the Midwest to the East Coast were running
eight hours late. The national airspace became snarled again on
Sunday. On the FAA site, you could click on links to 40 major
airports and observe, from Denver to the Atlantic, a system
approaching gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you could also go to the airport, wade through the
crowd of long faces and find one that did not look ready to
explode. At Newark International Airport around 9:30 p.m. on
Friday, one of those calmer visages belonged to Derrick Canady, a
computer network executive from Denver who was having a long day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left home at 6:30 this morning for a business trip to Fort
Lauderdale,'' Canady said as fellow-travelers milled around, some
anxiously pressing cell phones to their ears and muttering darkly
when they could not get a line because the demand was overloading
the circuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wouldn't tell us what was going on, which really annoyed
me,'' Canady said. He was flying on Continental Airlines, but his
complaint about not being able to get adequate information was
echoed by other travelers on other carriers. Most scoffed when
asked if their airlines had kept them informed.
</P>
<P>
   Providing credible, timely information on delays is a major
component of a vaunted voluntary passengers-rights code that the
airlines drafted last year to head off the threat of federal
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we asked what was going on, the airline's people looked
at us like we were crazy,'' Canady said. ``We were like, `Hey,
we're just trying to find out when we're going to be where you're
supposed to take us.'''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Some people were getting in shouting matches with
the flight attendants, but what good does that do? You might as
well make the best of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Making the best of it is good advice for business travelers this
summer, as a three-year crisis of delayed domestic flights
threatens to grow in the heaviest travel months of July and August.
According to the FAA, June was the worst month ever for delays.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, last Friday afternoon, as serial delays were
once again staggering the traveling public, the FAA and the airline
industry were trying to spin some good news. The FAA said that an
agreement had been reached with airline pilots' groups in a recent
dispute involving a decades-old landing procedure that some pilots
believe can create potentially unsafe conditions as runway traffic
increases. New rules to address the pilots' concerns are expected
to be issued in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   In the procedure, called ``land and hold short,'' the tower asks
a pilot to land normally and then pause at an intersecting runway
to allow another plane to take off before continuing on to the
terminal. Pilots balking at these maneuvers were responsible for
about 10 percent of the recent delays at O'Hare International
Airport in Chicago and about a quarter of the delays at Logan
International Airport in Boston, according to industry estimates.
</P>
<P>
   But those numbers do not begin to account for the 49,000 flight
delays the airlines racked up in June or the ones piling up this
month. Pilots aren't causing this crisis. The great majority of
delays are attributed to bad weather; huge, growing volume; and the
inability of the air-traffic control system and the airlines to
keep pace.
</P>
<P>
   The number of domestic airline passengers has doubled since
1980. The airlines are putting more planes in the air each year _ a
trend that is aggravated by growing use of smaller-capacity,
fuel-efficient regional jets. More planes in the air means more
planes that can be affected by weather.
</P>
<P>
   Short of requiring people to stay on the ground, there are no
easy answers. As delays grow, FAA critics denounce the agency for
bureaucratic ineptitude, and some are even calling for
privatization of the air-traffic control system. But opponents of
this proposal question of the wisdom of effectively ceding control
of the nation's air space to the airline industry, which they say
already has a propensity for discouraging competition and
consolidating routes and airport gate slots into regional quasi
monopolies.
</P>
<P>
   At Newark last Friday night, though, all of this was somewhat
academic. There, and in airports all over the country, the concerns
were more narrowly focused on the simple challenge of reaching a
destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I have to pay for a hotel,'' Canady said, finally
acknowledging defeat as the tote boards blinked one cancellation
after another. ``And all the flights I checked for Fort Lauderdale
tomorrow are overbooked already. So tomorrow, I might just get a
plane get back home to Denver instead. I'll start out again after
the weekend. I ought to be able to get there eventually, right?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 2156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6074 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-CLINTON-VIETNAM-BOS &LR;      07-18 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VIETNAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON GOING TO VIETNAM AFTER THE ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton is planning to visit Vietnam this
autumn, capping a five-year period in which he normalized relations
and then negotiated a trade agreement with a nation whose very name
is a shorthand for geopolitical and emotional issues still
unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   A White House official confirmed Tuesday that Clinton hopes to
make the trip in mid-November, a week after Election Day. The trip
would be the first visit of a US president to Vietnam since 1969,
when Richard M. Nixon visited Saigon, then the capital of South
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   The journey of an American president to Vietnam, which now is
ruled by the Communist Party that two generations of French and US
military personnel tried but failed to defeat, would be an
unusually poignant event under any circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   But a trip undertaken by Clinton, the first president to come of
age in the Vietnam era, could provoke especially raw reactions. As
a college student in the Vietnam years, Clinton opposed US
involvement in the conflict and maneuvered to avoid the draft.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has not yet announced the president's intention
to visit Vietnam, but some preliminary arrangements have been made
and visas for the crew of Air Force One have been granted,
according to those familiar with planning the trip.
</P>
<P>
   The ostensible purpose for the visit is to mark a broad trade
agreement the United States and Vietnam reached last week. But
Vietnam occupies a special place in the American psyche, especially
for veterans and the baby-boom generation, and so the very footfall
of a president on Vietnamese soil automatically would be
transformed into an event of great significance.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials clearly hope the president's trip would be
a symbol of reconciliation with Vietnam and a signal of the good
faith of the United States after more than a quarter-century of
anxiety and ambiguity toward the Southeast Asian nation. But they
know the visit would also be a flashpoint for Clinton critics, who
almost certainly would contrast the president's eagerness to visit
Vietnam as a middle-aged man with his determination to avoid
service there as a young man.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton's trip would evoke a combination of reflection,
remembrance, bitterness, and anger in proportions difficult to
foresee, the significance of the visit goes far beyond any such
reactions.
</P>
<P>
   Important business and development issues would be involved.
Vietnam's gross domestic product, a conventional measure of a
nation's economic well-being, ranks 150th in the world. But already
many American and international businesses, including Caterpillar
and Nike, have made investments in Vietnam. And more companies are
expected to do so, taking advantage of a low-cost labor force eager
for work and of lower US tariffs growing out of the trade pact.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the political dynamics of Asia are changing swiftly,
and US officials are determined to take advantage of an opening in
the complex calculus of power politics.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomatically, the Clinton trip would be designed to offer
Hanoi some maneuvering room in Asia. Vietnam's closest ties are
with the communists in China. But Hanoi, which has painful memories
of its dependence upon the former Soviet Union in the waning days
of the Vietnam conflict, is eager to lessen its reliance on a
single ally. For that reason, Vietnam has developed an important
new relationship with China and is exploring a broader relationship
with France.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Defense Secretary William S. Cohen visited
Vietnam, arguing that while Washington and Hanoi were unlikely to
become allies, there was room for a warmer relationship between the
two nations. The visit of Cohen, a former Republican senator from
Maine, was an important precursor to the Clinton trip.
</P>
<P>
   Although more than half of Vietnam's 77 million people were born
after the hostilities ended in 1975, the war remains a great burden
there. The government of Vietnam says it lost 3 million people in
the conflict, with another 800,000 left wounded, and 300,000 still
missing. The government complains that millions of gallons of
American defoliant chemicals used during the war continue to affect
the nation's soil and hundreds of thousands of its people.
</P>
<P>
   The war also left scars in the United States, which lost 58,000
people in the war along with its sense of invulnerability and
invincibility. The war, along with the civil-rights movement,
triggered youth rebellion and an era of protest. One of those
caught up in the protests was Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's opposition to the war was passionate _ and, it turned
out, permanently recorded.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter he wrote to Colonel Eugene J. Holmes, the director
of the ROTC program at the University of Arkansas, Clinton spoke of
``working every day against a war I opposed and despised.'' Though
Clinton was not in the front ranks of antiwar activists, he worked
in the national headquarters of the Vietnam Moratorium and, as a
student at Oxford, promoted antiwar demonstrations in Great
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, which became public during Clinton's 1992
presidential campaign, speaks of Clinton's ``opposition to the
draft and the war,'' with Clinton saying, ``I am in great sympathy
with those who are not willing to fight, kill, and maybe die for
their country (i.e. the particular policy of a particular
government) right or wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the president, with the aid of Vietnam veterans such as
Senators John McCain, the Arizona Republican, and John F. Kerry,
the Massachusetts Democrat, pressed forward with establishing
normal diplomatic relations with Vietnam in 1995. The two nations
reached their trade agreement early this month, though Congress
still must approve the pact.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have full diplomatic relations with Vietnam,'' said
Thomas J. Vallely, a Marine Corps veteran who is director of the
Vietnam Program at Harvard's John F. Kennedy School of Government.
``We'll soon have full trade relationships. Clinton can go.
Remember: He's a better politician than we are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 2157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
