<HEADER>
A6076 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-EARNS-SPI &LR;      07-18 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-EARNS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTMENTS HELP MICROSOFT PROFITS DURING QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Microsoft Tuesday reported profits up 10 percent for
the just-completed quarter, but left some analysts worried that the
software maker's good results say more about investment strategy
than performance.
</P>
<P>
   The software giant posted net income of $2.41 billion, or 44
cents a share, for its fiscal fourth quarter ended June 30. That
compares to $2.2 billion, or 40 cents a share, in the same quarter
the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft was expected to earn 42 cents a share, according to
analysts' estimates compiled by First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Despite concerns about the rising share of profit derived from
investment, analysts also said the quarterly results suggest that
Microsoft seems to be skillfully handling the uncertainties it
faces in its business and on the legal front. It is in the midst of
a transition in its product markets as its new Windows 2000
operating system is adopted gradually by corporate customers, at a
time when the business market for computers has been sluggish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a slow but steady transitionary quarter from Microsoft
sprinkled with some optimism for the future,'' said Richard
Sherlund, an analyst at Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues met expectations at $5.8 billion, compared to $5.76
billion a year earlier. Most analysts had trimmed their revenue
forecasts after the company warned last quarter that business
demand for personal computers looked weak.
</P>
<P>
   For the fiscal year, the company announced net income of $9.42
billion, or $1.70 per share, a 20 percent increase over fiscal
1999. Revenue for the year totalled $22.96 billion, a 16 percent
increase over last year.
</P>
<P>
   But the company has been criticized for beating estimates
through high investment income rather than profits from its own
products. And that criticism continued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think they'd have that much investment income,'' said
Bill Epifanio, a financial analyst with J.P. Morgan. ``It was
expected that they'd take quite a bit from investments, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Fully $1.13 billion of the quarter's net income, or 47 percent,
came from investments, not from operating income, which includes
licensing fees, sales and other indicators of the company's own
health. Investment income has increased steadily at Microsoft over
at least the past five quarters.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of June, cash and marketable securities reached $23.8
billion, up from $17.2 billion a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Microsoft has a $17.8 billion portfolio of equity
investments in technology companies, which are typically business
partners of Microsoft. In fiscal 2000 alone, Microsoft made 100
such investments totaling $5.4 billion. If those companies are
acquired, for example, Microsoft must sell its stake and report the
gain as portfolio income.
</P>
<P>
   But operating income has actually been shrinking, dropping 14
percent since fourth-quarter 1999. Investment income made up only
22 percent of the company's net income that quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's chief financial officer John Connors acknowledged
how important investment income has become to Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the single biggest factor (in the investment gains)
was just the average size of our portfolio,'' Connors said. ``This
quarter was probably a little higher than we had planned.''
</P>
<P>
   But he defended the quarter's investment income, noting that
Microsoft's investment strategies involve companies that will help
Microsoft grow the overall computer industry. He added that the
lower pre-tax operating profit was due to an unusually high
year-ago quarter that saw revenues and profits lifted by special
items.
</P>
<P>
   Connors said highlights of the quarter included strong revenue
growth in Microsoft's consumer business, particularly its MSN unit,
which runs an Internet access service and operates a network of
increasingly popular Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, which competes in those markets against America
Online and Yahoo!, said MSN subscribers grew 20 percent to 3
million in the quarter, with traffic to the network's Web sites
expanding by 19 percent and average visit times rising 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As he did last quarter, Connors sounded a cautionary note on the
near-term growth of personal computer sales to businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw a mixed demand in the quarter for business PCs,''
Connors said, adding that the market was weak in May but seemed to
climb back somewhat in June. ``What we're really hoping to see is
really three months of sustained growth in the business PC
segment.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in line with guidance he gave last quarter, Connors told
analysts and reporters on a conference call he expects profits for
the current quarter to come in at 41 cents a share, up nearly 8
percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Connors said enthusiasm for Windows 2000, Microsoft's operating
system for corporate computers, was strong. But he gave no sales
figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel really good about the progress we're making in the
server business,'' Connors said without elaborating. ``We're on
track with Windows 2000 on the business side.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Microsoft.NET, the sweeping strategy Microsoft launched
in June, won't contribute to revenues until at least fiscal 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The results were announced after the market closed. Shares
climbed 38 cents in after-hours trading. The stock had gained 31
cents, to $78.50, before the market closed.
</P>
<P>
   Wire service material is included in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
