u a BC-ARK-GOVERNOR-RESIDENC     07-18 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARK-GOVERNOR-RESIDENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR'S MANSION IS A TRIPLE-WIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ Janet Huckabee would like it understood that
the first family of Arkansas is not moving into a trailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a trailer,'' she explained Tuesday, standing near
her husband, Gov. Mike Huckabee, in their backyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trailers are pulled behind a pickup truck,'' Huckabee said.
``We are not having a trailer on the mansion grounds.'' Nor is it,
she explained, a mobile home, since the Huckabees are not going
anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it a double-wide?'' she continued. ``The answer is no. It's
a triple-wide. So get it right, OK?''
</P>
<P>
   Very well _ to be precise, the Huckabees will be living for the
next year in what the industry calls ``manufactured housing,'' the
kind that is built in a factory and then trucked to a site in two
or three pieces. It will be in the backyard at the Governor's
Mansion, about to undergo a long-overdue renovation.
</P>
<P>
   This is, of course, a move fraught with risk for any governor,
let alone for one whose state already lacks a reputation as the
nation's most urbane. When J.D. Harper, the executive director of
the state's Manufactured Housing Association, praised the Huckabees
Tuesday for their ``courage,'' he was not referring to their
willingness to attract tornadoes, since the mansion has had no
trouble attracting them on its own. (The grounds were heavily
damaged by a twister last year.)
</P>
<P>
   No, Huckabee knew exactly what he was talking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know _ of all the states in the world, for Arkansas to be
the one with a governor living in manufactured housing _ well, you
can just hear the jokes already,'' she said in an interview. In
fact, the jokes have already begun. Last week, Jay Leno warned that
the move would not go over well with Arkansas voters, who might
think living in a double-wide would constitute putting on airs.
</P>
<P>
   But the Huckabees are determined to go through with this, and
not just because at least 12 percent of the state's population
lives in manufactured housing, according to the 1990 Census. The
fact is that the temporary home, when it arrives factory-fresh next
month, will be larger at 2,131 square feet than the residential
space in the mansion, where the Huckabees and their three
college-age children have had to live in about 1,200 square feet,
about the size of a modest New York apartment.
</P>
<P>
   The mansion, a brick Georgian built without much foresight in
1950, is small by gubernatorial standards, mostly formal parlors
that are heavily visited by tourists who want to see the home once
occupied by Bill and Hillary Clinton. (The Clintons tinkered with
the design but made no major structural changes.) Large receptions
are held in an outdoor tent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You open the door to your bedroom, and there's someone taking
a tour,'' said Huckabee, a Republican who has lived in the house
for four years. ``There's no privacy. We have to go in one of the
kids' bedrooms to watch TV.'' And, his wife added, the circuit
breakers trip if two people use hair dryers.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the temporary home, a high-end Eagle Point model
built by Champion Homes, will have a family room, a dining room, a
great room, a kitchen, a fireplace and three bedrooms, with
easy-to-clean vinyl siding, a washer and dryer, and amenities
considered the state of the art in manufactured housing.
</P>
<P>
   According to the company's brochure, the model is ``specifically
designed to appeal to the nation's largest and hottest new home
market segment _ the aging baby boomer.'' Huckabee is 44, his wife
just turned 45.
</P>
<P>
   When the industry heard that the family was planning to move out
of the mansion so that it could be expanded and renovated, several
manufacturers competed for the honor of donating the home, which is
worth about $110,000. After rejecting the security complications of
living in an apartment, the Huckabees accepted the offer as a
cost-saving measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of any other governors who have lived in our
products,'' Harper said. ``There is a certain stigma attached, and
we know all the jokes. But in fact this is a way for many people to
afford their own homes. So an opportunity like this gives us the
forum we need to show what our potential is.''
</P>
<P>
   The mansion is inside a fenced seven-acre compound in the Quapaw
section, a historic district near downtown filled with Queen Annes,
Greek revivals, and nothing that appeared to have arrived by truck.
Zoning rules do not even allow such dwellings. But the neighbors
don't seem to mind, as long as no one else tries to bring one in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad they're not leaving the neighborhood,'' said
Wendy Quaid, who was gardening this morning in front of her 1881
Colonial, a few doors down from the mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a governor here kind of helps the stability of the
neighborhood,'' Quaid said. ``Even if he's living in a trailer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
