u f BC-APPLE-EARNINGS-NYT     07-18 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLE REPORTS EARNINGS GAIN, BUT DISAPPOINTING SALES
</HEADLINE>
 By MATT RICHTEL  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ On the eve of its semiannual MacWorld trade
show, Apple Computer delivered mixed quarterly returns on Tuesday,
with earnings exceeding analyst expectations but sales falling
short of projections in light of disappointing sales of the iMac,
the company's staple consumer computer.
</P>
<P>
   But Apple executives promised to introduce new products on
Wednesday at MacWorld in New York that they suggested should spur
sales.
</P>
<P>
   For its third quarter, which ended July 1, Apple reported
earnings of $163 million, or 45 cents a share, a penny more a share
than analysts estimated. That figure compares with $114 million, or
35 cents a share, in the same quarter a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The figure does not include $37 million in capital gains the
company reported from the sale of some of its shares of ARM
Holdings during the quarter. Taking those returns into account, the
company reported earnings of $200 million, or 55 cents a share,
though analysts said the capital gain was a one-time return that
should not be included in an analysis of Apple's operating fiscal
health.
</P>
<P>
   But the good news on earnings was tempered by
lower-than-expected sales of $1.83 billion. That is 17 percent
higher than the $1.56 billion a year ago, but lower than the $1.9
billion many analysts had expected for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mixed quarter _ the revenue line was a tad
disappointing,'' said Charlie Wolf, executive director of UBS
Warburg, a New York-based investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   One reason revenues were below expectations was that sales of
the company's colorful iMac computers fell short of both company
and analyst projections. Fred Anderson, Apple's chief financial
officer, said 450,000 iMac's were sold in the quarter, not the
500,000 Apple had initially projected.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said he believed sales had fallen short because some
potential customers were waiting for a new version of the iMac.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that anticipation of a refresh of our product
family was the primary factor'' for the lower sales, Anderson said
during a conference call, though he declined to be specific about
the product announcements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been about nine months since we've made any major product
introductions, but we're going to change that tomorrow and we think
you will be impressed,'' Anderson said, apparently referring not
just to iMac but to other Apple products.
</P>
<P>
   Apple has long used the MacWorld stage as a forum for
introducing new products, typically keeping the announcements a
secret until the day of the show. Industry analysts speculated on
Tuesday that Apple would probably update the iMac but also announce
new products, including, perhaps, a low-cost device to connect to
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said that the announcements might obscure any clear
stock market response to the earnings report, since the products
will be introduced during the keynote address of Steven P. Jobs,
Apple's chief executive, shortly after the market opens. ``There is
not going to be any pure play on the earnings,'' Wolf said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the stock fell $1.0625, to $57.25, on the Nasdaq. It
fell as low as $53 in after-hours trading. The stock has more than
doubled in the last 12 months but is down about one quarter from
its high in March.
</P>
<P>
   The reason that earnings rose despite disappointing sales may be
explained by an increase in the company's gross margins, a measure
of how much the company's sales exceeded the cost of producing its
goods. In the quarter, the company reported gross margins of 29.8
percent, Anderson said, compared with 28.2 percent last quarter.
</P>
<P>
   David C. Bailey, a research analyst with Gerard Klauer Mattison
&AMP; Co., said the gross margin increase had exceeded his estimate of
28.7 percent for the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson attributed the increase in gross margins to three
factors: lower costs for components; growth in Internet sales,
which have higher margins; and a higher mix of sales being from its
professional line of products, the Power Book and Power Mac.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Anderson cautioned that the gross margin would
likely fall again in the coming months because of expected
increases in the costs of components, notably in memory and optical
devices. He said the company hoped to keep margins around 27
percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
