<HEADER>
A6081 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-COVERDELL-NYT &LR;      07-18 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-COVERDELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAUL COVERDELL, 61, DIES; INFLUENTIAL SENATOR FROM GEORGIA 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC SCHMITT and LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen &UR; . &LR;  Paul Coverdell of Georgia, a soft-spoken but
influential Republican leader, died Tuesday night in Atlanta, his
hometown, from a massive cerebral hemorrhage he suffered over the
weekend. He was 61.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell had undergone surgery on Monday after being
hospitalized for severe headaches.
</P>
<P>
   Rising rapidly, if almost invisibly, in the inner circles of
Senate power, Coverdell emerged as a close confidant of Majority
Leader Trent Lott, of Mississippi. Lott often turned to Coverdell,
a self-effacing former insurance executive, to handle some of the
most difficult and politically unrewarding jobs.
</P>
<P>
   An ally and longtime friend of former President George Bush,
Coverdell was the chief liaison in the Senate to the presidential
campaign of Bush's son, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul's death is a huge loss to his family, his friends, his
constituents in Georgia and our country,'' the governor said in a
statement released through his campaign office. ``Paul's
soft-spoken, hard-working ways will be sorely missed by all of us
who knew him and loved him.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Senate floor Tuesday night, Lott choked back tears in
praising his former colleague. ``Paul has been a close friend and
confidant, and an outstanding member of this body,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Tuesday night, President Clinton praised
Coverdell's contributions to the Senate and the country. ``He was a
tireless advocate who worked to ensure that all children have
access to quality education,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell's death, which follows the death last year of another
sitting Republican senator, John Chafee of Rhode Island, opens a
Republican seat at time when the party holds a 55-to-45 margin.
</P>
<P>
   Under Georgia law, the state's Democratic governor, Roy Barnes,
will appoint an interim replacement until a special election can be
held.
</P>
<P>
   The state's other senator, Max Cleland, a Democrat, said the two
possible candidates for the interim position would be Michael
Coles, the Democratic cookie magnate who lost to Coverdell in the
1998 election, and a former Democratic representative, Buddy
Darden. Barnes seemed unlikely to offer himself for the Senate
since he was elected only two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Cleland, who was sworn into the Georgia state Senate on the same
day as Coverdell 30 years ago, expressed his respect for his former
colleague. ``He never showed a trace of personal ego or
animosity,'' Cleland said Tuesday. ``He loved public service, he
loved politics and he loved to contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell was elected to the Senate in 1992, squeaking out a
victory over the liberal Democratic incumbent, Wyche Fowler Jr.,
and signaling a shift in Georgia politics. He was re-elected in
1998, despite concerns about his political vulnerability, much of
it fueled by his low-key, behind-the-scenes style of getting things
done.
</P>
<P>
   As the fourth-ranking Republican in the Senate, Coverdell held
the title of secretary of the conference. But he was expected to
move up the ladder to conference chairman with the retirement this
fall of Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   As secretary, Coverdell essentially ran the marketing department
for Senate Republicans, putting his organizational prowess to work
in shaping the party's message in five areas: education, taxes,
Social Security, defense and drug prevention.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Coverdell's interests and expertise ranged
broadly. He championed education savings accounts, a signature
Republican issue. He was a chief backer of a $1.3 billion aid
package to help Colombia combat drug traffickers protected by rebel
insurgents.
</P>
<P>
   And in a chamber defined by Washington Monument-sized egos,
Coverdell relished his image as a quiet insider. ``He was a humble
man who brought to the public discourse good ideas and common-sense
solutions,'' House Speaker Dennis Hastert said in a statement. ``He
didn't care who received the credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott affectionately called Coverdell ``Mikey,'' for the boy in
the Life cereal commercial who would ``eat anything.'' Coverdell,
Lott has said, would do anything that was asked of him, and do it
with enthusiasm. In fact, outside of work, he had few other
interests or hobbies.
</P>
<P>
   On the Senate floor, Coverdell was not a particularly eloquent
speaker and reporters sometimes struggled to find a single
straight-forward quote of his that they could use.
</P>
<P>
   But his timid demeanor belied his commitment to Republican
politics and his partisan drive. A conservative on most issues,
Coverdell did not hesitate to fight for tax cuts and a smaller
federal government, two favorite Republican themes.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell served in the Georgia state Senate from 1970 to 1989,
and was minority leader for 14 years. Coverdell often joked that he
knew too well what it was like being an underdog since, as minority
leader in the Senate, he represented all of five Republicans, as
opposed to 51 Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   It was during this time that he first met President Bush, who
was then U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, and the encounter
led to a lifelong friendship. Coverdell was a frequent visitor to
Bush's vacation home in Kennebunkport, Maine, despite his professed
incompetence on the golf course and aboard a fishing boat. ``I'm
not a golfer,'' he said during a recent interview. ``And I tangled
up his fishing reel.''
</P>
<P>
   He served as state chairman for the Georgia Republican Party
from 1985 to 1987. In 1989, Coverdell was named director of the
Peace Corps, a position which cemented his interest in foreign
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, his loyalty to the Bush family led to his selection
as Senate liaison to Governor Bush's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Des Moines on Jan. 29, 1939, Coverdell spent a large
part of his childhood in the Midwest. He earned a bachelor's degree
in journalism from the University of Missouri in 1961, and then
joined the Army in 1962, serving in Okinawa, among other places.
After leaving the Army, he helped his parents start the family's
Atlanta insurance and financial services business, Coverdell &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by wife, Nancy, a former flight attendant. They
had no children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 2209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
