u k BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-18 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: DECODING MALE DNA: WHASSUP? 
</HEADLINE>
   By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Desperate to catch up to the summer reality
phenomenon, NBC-TV executives are close to a deal for a show called
``Chains of Love,'' in which a young woman selects four men from a
pool of 100 prospects. The four men are then chained to the woman's
wrists and ankles, two on each side, for a week, while she
eliminates them one by one, until she gets to Mr. Right. Or perhaps
Mr. Left. (No ball and chain jokes.)
</P>
<P>
   Questioned at the press tour here Tuesday about the cheesiness
of this program, which was a hit in the Netherlands, NBC's
president of entertainment, Garth Ancier, protested ``It's a
relationship show.'' Once the laughter among the audience of TV
writers died down, a chagrined Ancier added, ``That wasn't supposed
to be funny.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a truth universally acknowledged that romance and reality
are mutually exclusive, but TV executives are obsessed with those
two topics at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   When they are not negotiating for reality programs that create
creepy Darwinian showdowns on a double-decker bus, in a prison, in
a boot camp, in a hair salon, in an apartment of five girls and one
houseboy who want to be celebrities, programmers are trying to come
up with the male version of ``Sex and the City.''
</P>
<P>
   One network executive said that this season every network had
three shows in development that aspired to be the male ``Sex and
the City,'' pulling back the curtain on how men really talk about
women, the same way the HBO hit lets men be privy to all that
female post-game analysis.
</P>
<P>
   The men I know think you cannot reverse the formula. ``Men don't
have any secrets,'' says one. ``And if they did, they wouldn't sit
around talking about them in groups at brunch over cosmopolitans.
It would not get much past `Wow! Look at her.' And `Whassup?'''
</P>
<P>
   Just try to switch genders for this week's episode of ``Sex and
the City,'' which is about the girls worrying about having too many
sex partners. No man has ever been consumed with fear about being a
slut.
</P>
<P>
   One attempt that will air this fall on ABC is ``Madigan Men,''
reteaming Broadway's ``Moon for the Misbegotten'' actors Gabriel
Byrne and Roy Dotrice as a father and son in New York. Byrne plays
a sensitive architect, the father of a teen-age son, whose wife has
left him for their nutritionist.
</P>
<P>
   The show's ridiculous premise is that Gabriel Byrne would find
it hard to make his way in the New York dating scene, and that
Irish men would talk to each other _ even for half an hour once a
week over Guinness _ about their emotions.
</P>
<P>
   Byrne, who came to NBC with the idea, said he had been inspired
by the covers of women's magazines and by ``Sex and the City.''
``What `Sex and the City' does so wonderfully is it opened that
secret world of women for examination by men,'' he says. ``It was
incredibly fascinating to men because it looked like a secret door
into a world that we knew nothing about.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Byrne, the only door likely to be opened by
this show is the one marked ``exit,'' since it focuses more on
father-son angst and Irish proverbs (``A windy day is not the day
for thatching'') than giving women tips on the male psyche and how
to tame it.
</P>
<P>
   Fox may have better luck since it went straight to the source,
Darren Star, the creator of ``Sex and the City,'' to design its new
series about single men and their tempestuous dating behavior.
``The Street'' is about carnivorous, libidinous young stockbrokers
working in a Wall Street firm, and their adventures with gorgeous
bankers, Russian strippers/day traders, hermaphrodites and
receptionists looking to climb by reading The Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   The secrets about men start spilling in the first show, when the
firm successfully launches an IPO for a company selling Ivy league
sperm. ``Yale sperm is worth more than Penn sperm,'' says one
partner, ``and anyone can tell you that.''
</P>
<P>
   Here at least we can learn some profound truths about men, what
they talk about when they get together for a beer, what kind of
women really appeal to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Xena?'' one guy asks another. ``Or Buffy?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
