<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6093 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-COLD-WAR-VETS-SPI &LR;      07-18 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLD-WAR-VETS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN LEGION SEEKS TO OPEN DOORS TO COLD WAR VETERANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE BARBER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For decades, nearly seven million veterans who kept
vigil during the uneasy peace of the Cold War have gotten the cold
shoulder from the nation's largest veterans lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Even after they braved atomic bomb tests, stood watch in missile
silos, flew bombers on patrol and risked a silent death under the
sea, they remain ineligible to join the 2.8 million-member ranks of
the congressionally chartered American Legion.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: Their hitches in the Army, Navy, Air Force or
Marines were during a time of official peace. Congress never
declared a Cold War with the Soviet Union and the Warsaw Pact.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday Harbor, Wash., though, the Legion's nearly 500-member
Hackett-Larson Post No. 163 voted unanimously last January to
change all that.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, its outgoing commander, former Marine Peter
DeLorenzi, will lead the charge at the Legion's state convention in
Yakima, Wash., introducing a resolution to allow Cold War vets to
join the Legion nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a beachstormer from way back,'' DeLorenzi said of his
mission in Yakima.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the preamble to the Legion constitution is to make
right the master of might, and this situation with Cold War
veterans is a great injustice,'' he said. ``This is the first
attempt at the state level to recognize them and have it presented
nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale Davis, who commands Washington state's 37,000 Legionnaires,
said if the measure is approved by the membership Saturday, it will
be taken to the national convention in Milwaukee in December.
</P>
<P>
   State leaders won't take a stance until the membership decides
on what he described as ``a well thought out resolution,'' he said.
``We're a grass roots organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said he's unsure how many of the state's estimated 300,000
veterans might be affected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like it would be a small number who are not eligible
because the U.S. government has managed to become involved in
conflicts almost constantly since World War II,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Legion is also looking out for its own interests. With World
War II vets nationwide dying at a rate of 1,000 per day, the
powerful lobby must keep up its strength.
</P>
<P>
   Post 163's resolution follows the action of Congress, which last
year officially acknowledged Sept. 2, 1945 to Dec. 26, 1991 as
``The Cold War,'' and authorized a certificate of recognition for
those who served, though not a campaign medal or ribbon.
</P>
<P>
   Congress pegged the start of the Cold War as the day Japan
surrendered at the end of World War II through the day the Soviet
Union officially dissolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that they are recognized as war veterans by Congress, we
hope it will be the final push to eligibility,'' DeLorenzi said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, some Legionnaires grumble, it's not like peacetime vets
can't out-flank the convoluted rules to join up. For example, a
male peacetime veteran can participate as a guest of his wife, even
if she has no military experience but joins the Legion's Women's
Auxiliary, which is open any woman whose father, uncle, stepfather
or a mother _ is or was in the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our prime motivating factors,'' DeLorenzi said, ``is
that we have a man who comes into the Legion with his wife, an
auxiliary member, and they have two children on active duty in the
military. But because he served in 1956-57, he is not eligible for
post membership.''
</P>
<P>
   The resolution urges the Legion to pressure its national
committeemen and members of Congress to change the charter. There's
some concern that Congress might not want to make vet's lobby even
stronger, DeLorenzi and other commanders say.
</P>
<P>
   The national leadership has taken no position on the issue
raised by Post 163, said Joe March, spokesman for the Legion's
national adjutant, Bob Spanogle, in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The number of veterans who served since W.W. II is about 26
million, March said. Of them, 19 million may join the Legion.
</P>
<P>
   The goal now is to sign up more of those 19 million, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things many people don't understand is that our
membership eligibility is set in stone by Congress,'' March said.
</P>
<P>
   While the Veterans of Foreign Wars is also charted by Congress,
it accepts only veterans who served served overseas in wartime.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, while peacetime veterans can't join, members of a
male component called Sons of the American Legion can participate
if they have a father who is an active Legion member, or a father,
grandfather or other direct family relative who served during
wartime.
</P>
<P>
   Women veterans can join the Legion, but DeLorenzi acknowledges
that the organization needs to straighten out its gender-based
components to reflect the modern military. But that's further down
the line.
</P>
<P>
   Around Puget Sound, some other commanders support Post 163's
initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be great to include the peacetime veterans,''
said Walt DeLong, a 24-year Navy veteran and commander of West
Seattle's American Legion Post 160. ``They served their time. Why
should they be cut out because their service was for three or four
years between wars?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
