u w BC-BAKALY-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      07-18 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAKALY-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTEMPT TRIAL CONCLUDES FOR STARR'S EX-SPOKESMAN
</HEADLINE>
  By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge said on Tuesday that she would
issue a verdict sometime next month in the criminal contempt case
against Charles G. Bakaly III, the former spokesman for the office
of independent counsel who is charged with lying to her about his
role as a source for an article in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   As the government and Bakaly's defense team made their final
arguments on Tuesday, Judge Norma Holloway Johnson, the chief judge
of the U.S. District Court here, asked both sides to provide
written summations by Aug. 11 that could serve as a foundation for
her verdict. She said she would probably deliver the verdict the
next week.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Bakaly could face up to six months in prison for
what government lawyers said was a series of lies about how much he
contributed to the article, which discussed whether President
Clinton could be indicted while in office.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Gershel, a Justice Department prosecutor, said in his
closing argument that Bakaly had misled Judge Johnson and
colleagues in his own office by trying to conceal some of the
information he had provided to the reporter who wrote the article,
Don Van Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Gershel said that a sworn declaration Bakaly filed with Judge
Johnson in February 1999 was false in its assertion that he had
never disclosed any ``nonpublic material'' to the reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He allowed his falsehoods and lies to be built into his
declaration,'' Gershel said. ``These were lies upon lies, and like
a house of cards they eventually came tumbling down.''
</P>
<P>
   Bakaly's defense lawyer, Michele A. Roberts, tried to narrow the
focus of the case in her closing argument. She said the prosecutors
had raised issues that had nothing to do with the case, like
Bakaly's appearance on the ABC television show ``Good Morning
America'' the day after the article was published. Prosecutors had
shown a videotape of that show in which Bakaly denied that the
office of independent counsel was the source of the information in
the article.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said it was irrelevant to the criminal case if Bakaly's
statements to the interviewer on the show were misleading or
accurate. The only thing that mattered, she said, was the signed
declaration, which she argued was not deceptive.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said that Bakaly had tried to modify the declaration,
which was drafted by lawyers in the independent counsel's office.
But she said that while some of his suggested changes were
included, several were not.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did not attempt to suggest that he provided no information
to Van Natta,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bakaly is charged not with leaking secret material but with
making false and misleading statements to the judge about his role
as a source for the article. By doing so, the government has
charged, he caused the court and investigators to waste their time,
which amounts to an obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   The Times article, published on Jan. 31, 1999, cited unnamed
associates of Kenneth W. Starr, the independent counsel, as saying
that he had concluded that he had the constitutional authority to
indict Clinton while he was in office. It also said that some
lawyers in Starr's office were in favor of indicting Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers complained to Judge Johnson that the story was
leaked by people in Starr's office to influence the impeachment
trial that was under way in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In response to that complaint, Starr's office filed a brief and
a declaration from Bakaly that asserted he had not provided any
nonpublic information to the reporter.
</P>
<P>
   After the declaration was filed, Bakaly gradually disclosed to
investigators from the Federal Bureau of Investigation that he had
provided the newspaper with some documents in connection with the
article. He also told investigators that he may have inadvertently
confirmed some information the reporter had told him he had learned
from sources outside the counsel's office.
</P>
<P>
   When the counsel's office learned of these later disclosures by
Bakaly about his dealings with the reporter, it informed Judge
Johnson that the original declaration was inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   At the trial, the FBI agents testified that Bakaly had told them
he wanted to send a message via the news article that the
investigation by the independent counsel would continue, despite
the impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The agents and Bakaly depicted a situation in which Bakaly
became more forthcoming about his role in contributing to the
article and only gradually began to realize that his comments were
making him a target of the agents' investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
