<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE SENATE: CANDIDATE RESTORED TO BALLOT
</P>
<P>
   Jack E. Robinson III, the Republican U.S. Senate candidate who
had been bounced from the Massachusetts ballot in his challenge to
Edward M. Kennedy, has suddenly stopped looking quite so
beleaguered. The state's highest court ruled Tuesday that Robinson
could appear on the November ballot because he did in fact have the
10,000 signatures he needed to qualify. The court said a few dozen
signature forms that were printed upside-down should still be
counted. Robinson said that the decision would let him finally get
his campaign into full gear. He plans to push ahead with
fund-raising and organization-building, and to seek a
reconciliation with state Republican leaders who had disavowed him
earlier in the campaign as he was parrying accusations about his
past. His chances against the most prominent member of one of
America's best known political families in an overwhelmingly
Democratic state are still seen as slim.
</P>
<P>
   THE STATES: GORE TRAILS BUSH IN ARKANSAS
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton and Al Gore carried Clinton's home state of
Arkansas by comfortable margins in 1992 and 1996. But a new
Mason-Dixon poll conducted for The Arkansas Democrat-Gazette raises
some doubts whether Gore can continue the streak. It has Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas ahead 46 percent to 40 percent, with 11
percent undecided. ``A very disconcerting poll for Democrats,''
crowed Bush's Arkansas chairman, Sen. Tim Hutchinson. Gore's
chairman, state Attorney General Mark Pryor, countered: ``It's
encouraging for Gore because most of the undecided voters will back
him.'' The poll, conducted July 13 through 15, covered 622 likely
voters and has a margin of sampling error of plus or minus four
percentage points. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE CONVENTIONS: CAROLINE KENNEDY TO SPEAK
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg, perhaps the most private of all
the Kennedys, has agreed to speak at the Democratic National
Convention in Los Angeles next month, 40 years after the party
nominated her father there. Her late brother, John F. Kennedy Jr.,
addressed the Democratic convention in 1988, and her uncle, Sen.
Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts, who will appear with her, is a
regular fixture at the conventions.
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH _ Austin, Texas
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE _ Memphis, Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
</TEXT>
