<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6100 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-REPUBS-NYT     07-18 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NONCANDIDATE MCCAIN IS STILL RUNNING HARD 
</HEADLINE>
  By JAMES BENNET   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain seems to be working harder at not
running for president than some guys _ we won't mention names _ do
in actually campaigning for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Since abandoning the race for the Republican nomination in
March, he has campaigned in so many states, for so many
congressional candidates and raised so much money, that his aides
have lost track of all three.
</P>
<P>
   And now, with a we're-puttin'-the-band-back-together mix of
nostalgia and anticipation, he is starting up his Straight Talk
Express to take himself, his old campaign team and about 60
journalists to the Republican National Convention in Philadelphia.
There, he plans to lead a town-hall meeting, hold a joint news
conference with MTV V-Js, make appearances on Comedy Central and
CBS News' ``Face the Nation,'' throw a party for 600 friends and so
on. To record the doings for ABC's ``Good Morning America,'' his
wife, Cindy, plans to carry the ``Cindy-cam.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying very hard not in any way to offend any of the Bush
people or overshadow what is clearly Governor Bush's event,''
McCain said in an interview Monday at his Senate office, where he
arrived illuminated by a CNN camera light.
</P>
<P>
   Advisers to Gov. George W. Bush profess not to be offended in
the slightest. They say that McCain's star power can now only
benefit them, by drawing the attention of independent voters.
</P>
<P>
   If there is to be any dissent at the convention, which begins on
July 31, it is not likely to come from the scrappy Arizonan who
used to say of Bush that ``if he's a reformer, I'm an astronaut.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said that even when he appeared in Philadelphia on July
30 at a planned ``shadow convention,'' which will also feature
antagonists of the right like the comedian Al Franken, he will
promote Bush as devoted to ``reform of education, of the military,
of our strategic posture nuclear-weapons-wise, health care, etc.''
</P>
<P>
   Though they have spoken a few times by telephone, Bush and
McCain have not appeared together since May 9, when McCain endorsed
his former opponent in Pittsburgh. But McCain said in the interview
that he intends to campaign alongside Bush after the convention and
again in September and October.
</P>
<P>
   Still, McCain seemed at times less than thrilled with his
bridesmaid's role. He looked down and spoke softly when asked to
describe his level of enthusiasm for Bush's candidacy. ``My
enthusiasm is very high,'' he said. In the interview, he became
animated only when discussing the high points of his campaign,
which he recalled with ``nostalgia and pleasure.''
</P>
<P>
   At the staff level, resentment, if not contempt, lingers on both
sides, but the two camps are learning to work together. Sniping
that used to take place in the open, then anonymously, is now done
strictly in secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the true backbiting now is limited to completely
off-the-record, which is progress,'' said John Weaver, a wry
adviser to McCain. But, he said, ``You'll never see the two staffs
go on vacation together.''
</P>
<P>
   In his subdued tones, McCain praised Bush as running ``an
increasingly centrist campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   From Bush's perspective, the benefits of comity are obvious.
According to public polls, McCain remains more popular than Bush or
Vice President Al Gore, as the senator's aides are quick to point
out. He is particularly beloved by the swing groups of independent
and undecided voters needed by both candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Thomas M. Davis III of Virginia, who is leading the
Republican drive to retain the House, said that even party regulars
clamor for McCain. ``Now that he's no longer a threat, they've kind
of embraced him,'' he said. ``He's everywhere from Florida to
Mississippi to New Hampshire. He's the man.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said that he wants comity because he is a loyal
Republican. ``I was very concerned about, and should be concerned
about, giving the appearance of being a bad loser,'' McCain said.
``I don't think that's helpful to me, to Governor Bush, or to the
party. And frankly, I didn't want to  &UR; be  &LR; a bad loser.''
</P>
<P>
   After dropping out of the race, McCain formed a political action
committee, Straight Talk America, to promote his agenda. He is
creating a Center for Conservative Reform to add some intellectual
heft to it. His aides acknowledge that the PAC could serve as the
basis for a future presidential bid, should Bush stumble. But while
McCain said, after a long pause, that he did not know if he would
ever run for president again, he called the prospect unlikely. He
said he did not want to be picked as vice president and did not
expect to be.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's aides studied how failed Republican nominees, including
Ronald Reagan in 1976, approached the party's conventions. But they
took more cues from the supportive role that Gen. Colin L. Powell
played in 1996. After first receiving the go-ahead from the Bush
camp, Andrew Card, the co-chairman of the convention, invited
McCain to speak at the convention during a meeting on June 20. He
said he told McCain that he was seeking ``political celebrities,''
not politicians.
</P>
<P>
   McCain does not plan to deliver anything like the jeremiad Pat
Buchanan delivered at the 1992 convention, when he rallied the
party to religious and cultural ``war'' and helped sink the
re-election bid of Bush's father. McCain's speech, scheduled for
10:30 on the convention's second night, will be devoted to Bush's
chosen theme, ``Strength and Security With a Purpose,'' and will
probably not even mention the senator's signature issue, campaign
finance reform, aides said. No one asked McCain to show his speech
to the convention organizers ahead of time, according to all
parties, but he plans to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Card said that, while McCain's bus trip was not part of the plan
for the convention, there was ``no danger'' of Bush being upstaged.
McCain will not even be in the audience when Bush accepts the
nomination. He plans to leave on the convention's third day,
Wednesday morning _ a sign not of pique, organizers and supporters
insist, but of self-abnegation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
