<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROKERS-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERRILL LYNCH TO CUT ABOUT 1,800 JOBS IN BROKERAGE BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grappling with slowing growth in its brokerage business, Merrill
Lynch &AMP; Co. officials said Tuesday that the firm would eliminate
about 1,800 jobs, mostly at its operations in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   An internal announcement of the cuts, most of which are expected
in the next few weeks, came after Merrill announced that its
second-quarter earnings rose 34 percent, despite a slim increase in
revenue from commissions and slower growth in the amount of money
customers invested at the firm. Merrill took in just $11 billion in
new money from customers in the United States, less than half the
$26 billion in net new assets reported by the rival brokerage firm
Charles Schwab.
</P>
<P>
   All told, Schwab took in $37 billion in assets last quarter, but
about $11 billion of that came through U.S. Trust Corp., a New
York-based money management firm that Schwab bought this year.
Excluding charges related to acquisitions, Schwab's operating
income rose 17 percent, to $198.8 million, or 14 cents a diluted
share, from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Like Schwab, Merrill recorded its second-biggest quarterly
profit, after an extraordinary first quarter. But Merrill's
earnings gain was driven by increases in stock trading and
underwriting and fees from advising on mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill earned $902 million, or $2.01 a diluted share, up from
$673 million, or $1.57 a share, in the second quarter of 1999.
Though down 15 percent from the first quarter of 2000, Merrill's
earnings easily exceeded analysts' expectation of $1.70 a share,
according to First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill also said that it would split its shares 2-for-1 next
month and the firm raised its quarterly dividend 7 percent, to 32
cents a share. Shares of Merrill Lynch, which have risen 53.9
percent this year, fell $3.75 on Tuesday, to $128.25.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Moszkowski, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney, said
Merrill's performance showed that ``the downturn has been more
shallow in the trading and investment banking business than you
might expect.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the brokerage business, he said, ``Schwab's inflows were
extremely strong compared to Merrill's.''
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the employees of Merrill's brokerage operations
Tuesday afternoon, E. Stanley O'Neal, who runs that unit, said
changes had to be made because brokerage expenses were rising 25
percent this year, while revenue was increasing at a 15-percent
clip.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal told the employees that 900 full-time jobs in the
brokerage unit would be eliminated beginning this week. Another 400
people who work for the firm as consultants and independent
contractors will also lose their jobs and about 500 jobs will be
eliminated through attrition. The job cuts amount to about 5
percent of the unit's 37,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   He said the cuts would affect all segments of the brokerage
operation, which is based in Plainsboro, N.J., but would have
little effect in the branch offices. None of Merrill's 15,200
brokers will be laid off.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill's chief financial officer, Thomas Patrick, said Merrill
hoped to reduce its costs by more than $150 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   While Merrill's employees were dealing with the firm's second
round of layoffs in less than two years, workers at Schwab were
cheering their firm's proven ability to attract assets even when
the stock market is in turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the sharp sell-off in technology stocks in April, Schwab
attracted 400,000 accounts and lost about 200,000. Its customers'
trading activity declined sharply, to 288,000 trades a day, from
386,600 trades a day in the first quarter. And the average
commission it received on each of those trades continued to slide,
to $36.65 from $46.44.
</P>
<P>
   Including the operations of U.S. Trust and Cybercorp, an online
trading unit it acquired this year, Schwab had total revenue of
$1.4 billion, up 26 percent from $1.12 billion a year ago. But its
net income dropped 20 percent to $137 million, or 9 cents a diluted
share, from $170 million, or 12 cents a share, a year ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
