<SLUG> BC-PHONE-PRICING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT STRIKES FEDERAL RULES FOR PHONE COMPANY PRICES  
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH SCHIESEL    
 c. 2000 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal appeals court Tuesday struck down Federal
Communications Commission pricing rules for telephone companies
intended to foster competition in local communications markets.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC could ask the Supreme Court to review the decision. But
if the ruling stands, it may mean long-distance giants and newer
companies will have to pay millions of dollars in additional
network-connection costs because it could increase the fees that
companies pay for connecting to the networks of local carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a nutshell, I think this means these rates will go up,''
William P. Barr, the former attorney general who is Verizon's
general counsel, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the Telecommunications Act of 1996, the government required
incumbent local phone companies _ not only the Bells but also
carriers like GTE and Southern New England Telecommunications _ to
open their networks to outside competitors. The FCC came up with a
system to determine what the incumbents could charge competitors
for using the necessary elements of their networks to provide local
service that requires the incumbents to charge as if they used the
most efficient, technically advanced communications equipment on
the market.
</P>
<P>
   But the incumbent phone giants protested that the rate system
was unfair and that the prices they were allowed to charge were in
some cases below their actual costs. The incumbents argued that
they should be able to charge fees based on their actual costs, not
the costs of a hypothetical network.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a three-judge panel for the 8th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals Appeals, in St. Louis, agreed with the local carriers,
saying that the FCC rules violated the communications act itself.
The decision would not take effect for 45 days. An FCC official
said a decision on whether to ask for a stay and whether to appeal
the ruling could come within weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
