<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SAYS GOVERNMENT SHOULD HELP FATHERS BE RESPONSIBLE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., Wis., Texas)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Gov. George W. Bush extolled the importance of
fatherhood Tuesday, lamenting the prevalence of children growing up
without the guidance of both parents and saying that he would
direct the federal government to spend more money to coax fathers
toward responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The amount he was talking about, $40 million a year, was small,
and the goal he was articulating was anything but controversial.
</P>
<P>
   But part of Bush's prescription, allowing the money to go to
groups that use religion in their efforts to unite fathers with
their families, illustrated a philosophy that has raised questions
about the separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   Bush talked about this approach during a panel discussion at a
private agency in Milwaukee, Faith Works, that incorporates
religion into its efforts to rehabilitate fathers with drug and
alcohol problems and guide them into schools and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faith does work,'' Bush said in Milwaukee Tuesday morning,
before he headed here for several campaign events. ``It's a
powerful concept. It's not a government concept, by the way. It
recognizes that there are powers greater than mankind.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also said that while the federal government should do its
part to help finance such efforts, it should recognize ``programs
that exist in spite of government, that help people who may be
coming out of prison, to help them find work, but also remind folks
of the importance of being a dad.''
</P>
<P>
   A description of Bush's proposed policy distributed by his
campaign aides said that most of the money would be directed by the
federal Department of Health and Human Services toward groups,
including those affiliated with churches, that help low-income
fathers find work and promote being responsible parents.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's proposal and the setting in which he unveiled it, an
inner-city agency that serves many African-Americans, were intended
to bolster his portrayal of himself as a ``different kind of
Republican'' with special concern for underprivileged people.
</P>
<P>
   The event also underscored the occasional exhortations by Bush,
who considers himself a devout Christian, for Americans to
rediscover the benefits of more traditional mores. So did the words
of one of the other panelists.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Joyce, who helps raise private money for faith-based
programs, said that Tuesday morning's event would have been
unimaginable a decade ago, when ``Murphy Brown,'' a television
comedy, ``taught elites that they could raise children without
having a dad in the house.'' The comment alluded to former Vice
President Dan Quayle's complaint at the time that the show exalted
single motherhood.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce hailed the progress that he said had been made since then,
and said that it certainly could not be attributed to ``the
example, say, of the leader of the free world, in terms of parental
virtue.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore has also advocated a role for religious
organizations in providing social services, with certain caveats.
But he has not pushed this approach as aggressively as Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush left Milwaukee and arrived here around midday to address
the National Conference of State Legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   He was introduced, at his campaign's request, by the Democratic
speaker of the Texas House, Pete Laney, an arrangement the Texas
governor said was an indication of the bipartisan spirit he had
brought to government in his state.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Bush attended a dinner here that was expected to raise
about $3 million for the Republican Party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 2240EDT &QL; 
