u f BC-INTEL-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      07-18 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL LOGS 80% RISE IN NET AND BIG REVENUE GROWTH  
</HEADLINE>
   By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Intel Corp., the world's largest semiconductor manufacturer,
reported record second-quarter earnings Tuesday, largely because of
gains on investments. But to Wall Street's relief, the company also
reported revenue growth that was stronger than expected and it
narrowly beat expectations for earnings from its products and
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a blowout like some of the other tech stocks have
had, but it's not bad,'' said Joseph Osha, who follows the sector
for Merrill Lynch Global Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Intel said it earned $3.14 billion, or 45 cents a diluted share,
in the quarter ended June 30, up almost 80 percent from $1.75
billion, or 25 cents a share, in the period a year earlier. But
after using the technology sector's increasingly common convention
of adjusting for accounting provisions connected to various
acquisitions, earnings were 50 cents a share for the quarter, a
penny more than the consensus of analysts, according to First
Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue jumped 23 percent, to $8.30 billion, from just under
$6.75 billion in the second quarter of 1999. The figures were
especially impressively, analysts said, because the second quarter
is normally slow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw strong demand in all business groups,'' said Craig R.
Barrett, president and chief executive of Intel, which is based in
Santa Clara, Calif. ``Looking forward, we expect to see strong
demand continue into the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts, Intel officials projected
that sales would be ``up'' and then, in case anyone missed the
optimism, noted that in the past they had often qualified such
projections with adjectives like ``slightly.''
</P>
<P>
   The results for the quarter and previous periods were restated
to reflect Intel's previously announced 2-for-1 stock split,
effective on July 30. The earnings were announced after the close
of trading on the New York Stock Exchange, in which Intel shares
fell $3.3125, to $143. In after-hours trading, the shares rose as
high as $147.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intel seems to be on a solid track going forward,'' said
Jonathan Joseph, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's performance this year has been hampered by its inability
to produce as much as customers want to buy. Those constraints are
expected to ease in the second half as new capacity comes on line
and Intel introduces its Pentium 4 chip, which has been developed
under the code name Willamette. But Intel said inventories were
still lower than it wanted and declined to assure analysts that
supplies would come into balance with demand before the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   The increased profits in the second quarter included $2.1
billion from Intel's sale of investments in Micron Technology and
other companies. Intel has contended that such gains should be
included in its regular earnings, since the practice of making
strategic investments in smaller companies has become just as
routine a feature of Intel's business as making microchips.
</P>
<P>
   Many other technology companies and a number of banks are also
deriving substantial contributions to earnings from their
investment activities. Intel said Tuesday that its Intel Capital
unit held stakes worth $7.5 billion in 450 companies at the end of
the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts are concerned, though, that investment earnings
can swing widely from quarter to quarter depending on when a
company sells investment shares and how the market is performing.
In fact, the earnings reported Tuesday were close to Wall Street's
projections only because analysts scrambled last month to adjust
their estimates after the company warned them that the investment
gains would be more than triple the $725 million it had previously
offered as guidance. Intel projected that such income would drop
back to about $800 million in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The second-quarter results were negatively affected by a
one-time charge of $200 million, or 2 cents a share, for the costs
of a program that began in the first quarter to replace defective
Pentium III circuit boards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
