question Tuesday, before pushing through a Republican plan to end the
marriage penalty tax. Lott was accompanied by an aide, Ryan Peebles,
right. The vote was 61-38, with eight Democrats joining Republicans
to approve the measure, which would reduce taxes for nearly all
married couples by $248 billion over the next 10 years. One
Republican voted against. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
