<P>
   (NYT13) TYRE, Lebanon -- July 18, 2000 -- HEZBOLLAH-TACTICS
-- Hezbollah, the Shiite Muslim  guerrillas who forced Israel from
the slice of southern Lebanon it had occupied for 22 years, grew from
a small band of amateurish gunmen to a highly sophisticated tactical
operation savvy enough to exploit a new weapon of modern warfare --
television. "The use of media as a weapon had an effect parallel to a
battle," says the top Hezbollah commander in southern Lebanon, Sheik
Nabil Quok. Quok, in a rare interview with a Western journalist
discussed not only how Hezbollah learned to improve its
effectiveness, strategy and weaponry, but also to videotape its
successes for distribution to the media. (Courtney Kealy/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- July 18, 2000 -- SOPRANOS-ACTOR --
Vincent Pastore, the cuddly cat burglar-hit man-mob informer known as
"Big Pussy" who came to a briny end this season, sent to sleep with
the fishes by his best friend, Tony, on the HBO cult hit "The
Sopranos." Regarding the Mafia, it's hedge time: he doesn't recommend
the lifestyle, but since it's an indirect provider of his lifestyle,
don't ask him to take potshots. Besides, he's kind of connected, and
says he can't go anyplace -- not even backstage at Springsteen --
without bumping into somebody from the five families. "They, uh,
always want to meet you if you've played somebody they know," says
Pastore outside the Westbank Cafe on 42nd Street in Manhattan.
(Librado Romero/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- July 18, 2000 -- NY-HARLEM-GALLERY-2 -- A
commercial renovation is changing the face of 125th Street in Harlem,
N.Y., bringing in Starbucks and Disney and with them presumably more
visitors, including tourists. "Untitled (Telephone/Butterfly)" by
Stephen Vitiello in the Project, a contemporary art gallery on West
126th Street. The Project presents an impressive lineup of artists
from the Americas, Europe, Africa  and Asia, many of them making
local solo gallery debuts. (The Project/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- July 18, 2000 -- NY-HARLEM-GALLERY-1 -- A
commercial renovation is changing the face of 125th Street in Harlem,
N.Y., bringing in Starbucks and Disney and with them presumably more
visitors, including tourists. The Project, a contemporary art gallery
on West 126th Street,in a former disco in Harlem, presents an
impressive lineup of artists from the Americas, Europe, Africa  and
Asia, many of them making local solo gallery debuts. Christian Haye,
founder of the Project with the gallery's director,  Jenny Liu,
inside  an installation by Camille Norment. (Chester Higgins Jr./The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- July 18, 2000 -- ADOPTED-MONKEY-2 --
Michelle Flikshtein, 13, and Cookie Flikshtein in front of their
house in Manhattan Beach's Russian community in Brooklyn, N.Y. The
saga of Cookie Flikshtein, a Cercopithecus diana, commonly known as a
diana monkey, has stirred tumultuous feelings on both sides of a
fight over her future. Backed by several experts, adamant New York
state officials have said the monkey does not belong in human society
and must be returned to her own. To the Flikshteins and an outraged
army of their neighbors, Cookie Flikshtein is a beloved -- albeit
rare simian -- member of the family. She may be a monkey, they say,
but she has adjusted enough to the human condition to spend most
evenings eating rocky road ice cream and watching the nightly news.
(G. Paul Burnett/The New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- July 18, 2000 -- ADOPTED-MONKEY-1 -- In
Manhattan Beach's Russian community in Brooklyn, N.Y., Roman and Inna
Flikshtein, 13-year-old daughter, Michelle, and their youngest,
Cookie. To the Flikshteins and an outraged army of their neighbors,
Cookie Flikshtein is a beloved -- albeit rare simian -- member of the
family.  The saga of Cookie Flikshtein has stirred tumultuous
feelings on both sides of a fight over her future. Backed by several
experts, adamant New York state officials have said the monkey does
not belong in human society and must be returned to her own. "So what
if Cookie is a monkey?" says Inna Flikshtein with tears in her eyes.
"She is part of this family. They want to take the baby from the
mother. But she will die without us, and we will die if we give her
up." (G. Paul Burnett/The New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) PHILADELPHIA -- July 18, 2000 -- PHILLY-CONVENTION --
Philadelphia is exuding the anxious headiness of a theater production
in the final throes of rehearsing a command performance for the
nation. This year's gathering of Republicans will be Philadelphia's
first national political convention since 1948, and many residents
are eager to show off the city's revival. Visitors to the rotunda at
the Liberty Place shopping center are dwarfed by a 60-ton sand
sculpture of Abraham Lincoln and The White House. (Ruth Fremson/The
New York Times) *Story moved 071500*
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- July 18, 2000 --
PROFILE-KAMARCK-BOS -- As one of only two high-powered women in a
thoroughly male-dominated presidential campaign, Vice President Al
Gore's campaign policy director, Elaine Kamarck, is frequently
described by her colleagues as having a potent personality that can
rub some the wrong way. Kamarck says she views her job as "protecting
the integrity of the policies that Gore adopts," which sometimes
means she has to be on the lookout for end-runs by advisers with
other priorities. Kamarck, on leave from the Kennedy School of
Government in Cambridge, Mass. (Wendy Maeda/The Boston Globe) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) PROVINCETOWN, Mass. -- July 18, 2000 -- NUDE-BEACH-BOS
--- Provincetown Selectman David Atkinson, a naturist who has
championed the cause for years, says he has paid more than $600 in
fines and admonishes those who think nudity bespeaks of vanity or
exhibitionist tendenies. Atkinson ran unsuccessfully on the
Libertarian ticket for secretary of state in 1998, and when the Globe
printed photographs of all the political candidates in suits,
Atkinson wore his birthday suit. "Nudity is natural and spiritual,"
he says, "and not the least bit sexy. (Barry Chin/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) CHICAGO -- July 18, 2000 -- BUSH-CAMPAIGN -- At the
National Council of State Legislatures in Chicago Tuesday, Gov.
George W. Bush extolled the importance of fatherhood today, lamenting
the prevalence of children growing up without the guidance of both
parents and saying that he would direct the federal government to
spend more money to coax fathers toward responsibility. Paul
Mannweiler, President of the National Council of State Legislatures,
Texas Lt. Gov. Rick Perry and Gov. George W. Bush on stage at the
NCSL convention in Chicago. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- July 18, 2000 -- BOLSHOI-DANCERS -- Maria
Alexandrova, 21, and Svetlana Lunkina, 20, two young Bolshoi Ballet
stars who are the darlings of ballet critics in Russia and Britain,
will appear in "Giselle" in the Lincoln Center Festival 2000 on
Sunday. Lunkina is the youngest Bolshoi ballerina ever to tackle the
demanding title role in "Giselle." Alexandrova, will dance Myrtha,
the queen of the ghostly, man-hating Wilis. (Sara Krulwich/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) PHILADELPHIA -- July 18, 2000 -- EMPLOYEE-ATTITUDE --
Increasingly, employees are testing the boundaries of the American
work ethic as employers, hammered by recruiting and training expenses
and fearful that they will be unable to fill job openings, make
allowances for just about every form of misconduct. The new
management rule of thumb, it seems, is that a warm body is better
than no body. "I think the attitude among workers right now is, 'I
could always go and get another job," says Kevin Meeker, owner of
Philadelphia Fish and Co., a restaurant and bar. (Salvatore C.
DiMarco/The New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- July 18, 2000 -- ONLINE-INVESTMENT-CLUBS
-- Offline or online, the intent of investment clubs now seems about
the same as it ever was: to learn. "People are craving ways to bring
other people into their investing experience, that's why the stock
discussion sites are so popular," says Ion Yadigaroglu, 30,
co-founder and chief executive of Bivio, a new Internet company based
in Boulder, Colo. Yadigaroglu in Times Square. (Ruby Washington/The
New York Times) *Story moved on 071700*
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
---------------------------
Steffen A. Kaplan
N.Y. Times News Service
212-556-4204
---------------------------
