<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of
tonight's New York Times Photo Package, moving Tuesday, 07/18/00.
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) ATLANTA -- July 18, 2000 -- OBIT-COVERDELL-3 -- Sen.
Paul Coverdell, a longtime Republican politician in Georgia who
became a congressional workhorse and quickly ascended to a leadership
post, died Tuesday of a stroke. He was 61. Coverdell had surgery
Monday to relieve pressure from a cerebral hemorrhage but died from
swelling in the brain, Piedmont Hospital said. Coverdell, who served
as Peace Corps director in the Bush administration, was first elected
to the Senate in 1992 by defeating incumbent Democrat Wyche Fowler
Jr. He also was the Senate liaison for George W. Bush's presidential
campaign and had been busy preparing for the Republican National
Convention in Philadelphia. Coverdell in his Capitol Hill office in
June. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- July 18, 2000 -- SENATE-MARRIAGE-TAX --
Trent Lott, the Senate majority leader, answering a reporter's
question Tuesday, before pushing through a Republican plan to end the
marriage penalty tax. Lott was accompanied by an aide, Ryan Peebles,
right. The vote was 61-38, with eight Democrats joining Republicans
to approve the measure, which would reduce taxes for nearly all
married couples by $248 billion over the next 10 years. One
Republican voted against. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- July 18, 2000 -- OBIT-COVERDELL-2 --
