<P>
   (NYT13) TYRE, Lebanon -- July 18, 2000 -- HEZBOLLAH-TACTICS
-- Hezbollah, the Shiite Muslim  guerrillas who forced Israel from
the slice of southern Lebanon it had occupied for 22 years, grew from
a small band of amateurish gunmen to a highly sophisticated tactical
operation savvy enough to exploit a new weapon of modern warfare --
television. "The use of media as a weapon had an effect parallel to a
battle," says the top Hezbollah commander in southern Lebanon, Sheik
Nabil Quok. Quok, in a rare interview with a Western journalist
discussed not only how Hezbollah learned to improve its
effectiveness, strategy and weaponry, but also to videotape its
successes for distribution to the media. (Courtney Kealy/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- July 18, 2000 -- SOPRANOS-ACTOR --
Vincent Pastore, the cuddly cat burglar-hit man-mob informer known as
"Big Pussy" who came to a briny end this season, sent to sleep with
the fishes by his best friend, Tony, on the HBO cult hit "The
Sopranos." Regarding the Mafia, it's hedge time: he doesn't recommend
the lifestyle, but since it's an indirect provider of his lifestyle,
don't ask him to take potshots. Besides, he's kind of connected, and
says he can't go anyplace -- not even backstage at Springsteen --
without bumping into somebody from the five families. "They, uh,
always want to meet you if you've played somebody they know," says
Pastore outside the Westbank Cafe on 42nd Street in Manhattan.
(Librado Romero/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- July 18, 2000 -- NY-HARLEM-GALLERY-2 -- A
