   (NYT7) PHILADELPHIA -- July 18, 2000 -- PHILLY-CONVENTION --
Philadelphia is exuding the anxious headiness of a theater production
in the final throes of rehearsing a command performance for the
nation. This year's gathering of Republicans will be Philadelphia's
first national political convention since 1948, and many residents
are eager to show off the city's revival. Visitors to the rotunda at
the Liberty Place shopping center are dwarfed by a 60-ton sand
sculpture of Abraham Lincoln and The White House. (Ruth Fremson/The
New York Times) *Story moved 071500*
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- July 18, 2000 --
PROFILE-KAMARCK-BOS -- As one of only two high-powered women in a
thoroughly male-dominated presidential campaign, Vice President Al
Gore's campaign policy director, Elaine Kamarck, is frequently
described by her colleagues as having a potent personality that can
rub some the wrong way. Kamarck says she views her job as "protecting
the integrity of the policies that Gore adopts," which sometimes
means she has to be on the lookout for end-runs by advisers with
other priorities. Kamarck, on leave from the Kennedy School of
Government in Cambridge, Mass. (Wendy Maeda/The Boston Globe) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) PROVINCETOWN, Mass. -- July 18, 2000 -- NUDE-BEACH-BOS
--- Provincetown Selectman David Atkinson, a naturist who has
championed the cause for years, says he has paid more than $600 in
fines and admonishes those who think nudity bespeaks of vanity or
exhibitionist tendenies. Atkinson ran unsuccessfully on the
Libertarian ticket for secretary of state in 1998, and when the Globe
printed photographs of all the political candidates in suits,
Atkinson wore his birthday suit. "Nudity is natural and spiritual,"
he says, "and not the least bit sexy. (Barry Chin/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) CHICAGO -- July 18, 2000 -- BUSH-CAMPAIGN -- At the
National Council of State Legislatures in Chicago Tuesday, Gov.
George W. Bush extolled the importance of fatherhood today, lamenting
the prevalence of children growing up without the guidance of both
parents and saying that he would direct the federal government to
spend more money to coax fathers toward responsibility. Paul
Mannweiler, President of the National Council of State Legislatures,
Texas Lt. Gov. Rick Perry and Gov. George W. Bush on stage at the
NCSL convention in Chicago. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- July 18, 2000 -- BOLSHOI-DANCERS -- Maria
Alexandrova, 21, and Svetlana Lunkina, 20, two young Bolshoi Ballet
stars who are the darlings of ballet critics in Russia and Britain,
will appear in "Giselle" in the Lincoln Center Festival 2000 on
Sunday. Lunkina is the youngest Bolshoi ballerina ever to tackle the
demanding title role in "Giselle." Alexandrova, will dance Myrtha,
the queen of the ghostly, man-hating Wilis. (Sara Krulwich/The New
York Times)
