<P>
   (NYT2) PHILADELPHIA -- July 18, 2000 -- EMPLOYEE-ATTITUDE --
Increasingly, employees are testing the boundaries of the American
work ethic as employers, hammered by recruiting and training expenses
and fearful that they will be unable to fill job openings, make
allowances for just about every form of misconduct. The new
management rule of thumb, it seems, is that a warm body is better
than no body. "I think the attitude among workers right now is, 'I
could always go and get another job," says Kevin Meeker, owner of
Philadelphia Fish and Co., a restaurant and bar. (Salvatore C.
DiMarco/The New York Times) *LITE
