<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Court Ruling Could Raise Costs for Phone Companies
</P>
<P>
   In a legal victory for local telephone companies, a federal
appeals court struck down pricing rules that federal regulators had
hoped would foster competition in local communications markets.
</P>
<P>
   If the ruling stands, it could lead to an increase in the fees
that companies pay for connecting to the networks of local
carriers, adding millions of dollars in costs for long-distance
giants like AT&AMP;T and WorldCom as well as for new companies that are
trying to break into the local telephone business. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Intel Reports Strong Sales Growth
</P>
<P>
   Intel posted record second-quarter earnings, largely because of
gains on investments. But the company also reported revenue growth
that was stronger than expected, and it narrowly beat expectations
for earnings from its products and services.
</P>
<P>
   Apple Results
</P>
<P>
   Apple Computer delivered mixed quarterly returns, with earnings
exceeding expectations but sales falling short of projections.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch to Cut 1,800 Jobs
</P>
<P>
   Grappling with slowing growth in its brokerage business, Merrill
Lynch officials said the firm would eliminate about 1,800 jobs,
mostly in New Jersey. An internal announcement of the cuts, most of
which are expected in the next few weeks, came after Merrill said
that its second-quarter earnings rose 34 percent despite a slim
increase in revenue from commissions and slower growth in the
amount of money customers invested at the firm. Shares of Merrill
fell $3.75, to $128.25.
</P>
<P>
   Taco Bell Dismisses Ad Agency
</P>
<P>
   Taco Bell is parting ways with TBWA/Chiat/Day, which created the
company's popular talking Chihuahua character, and will consolidate
its account for the time being at FCB Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Shopkorn to Join Druckenmiller
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Shopkorn, former chief equity trader at Salomon Brothers
and most recently top equity strategist at Moore Capital's hedge
funds, will join Duquesne Capital, where he will work with Stanley
Druckenmiller, former managing director of Soros Fund Management.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Declines in Profit Taking
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index fell sharply as investors chose to
take profits, sliding 97.50 points, or 2.3 percent, to 4,177.17.
The Dow Jones industrial average declined 64.35 points, or 0.6
percent, to 10,739.92, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
fell 16.75 points, or 1.1 percent, to 1,493.74. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GM Profit Beats Expectations
</P>
<P>
   General Motors revamped its sales discounts for the third
quarter and said that its profits inched up in the second quarter
instead of falling slightly, as had been expected.
</P>
<P>
   Air-Traffic System Nears Gridlock
</P>
<P>
   The air-traffic system approached gridlock over the weekend,
with delays of up to eight hours. And the crisis could grow in the
heaviest travel months of July and August.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
