<HEADLINE>
LAZIO BUYS $1.6 MILLION IN TV ADS IN RACE'S FIRST 6 WEEKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the first six weeks after he abruptly entered the
Senate race, Rep. Rick Lazio spent $1.58 million on television
advertising, and sought to bolster his candidacy by hiring several
political consultants who had worked on Sen. John McCain's failed
presidential bid, according to campaign records released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The records, which the Lazio campaign filed with the Federal
Election Commission and released to reporters, show that Lazio
collected $4.99 million in donations from April 1 through June 30,
nearly all of it after becoming a candidate after Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani withdrew in mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio spent a total of $2.32 million, and his campaign now has
$6.19 million in the bank, including money left over from his House
races.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign of Lazio's Democratic opponent, Hillary Rodham
Clinton, did not release her records Tuesday, saying it would do so
later in the week. This month, the Clinton campaign said it had
raised $5.1 million from April 1 through June 30, and spent $5.49
million, leaving her with $6.4 million on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Before April 1, Clinton had already spent $6.12 million, meaning
that so far in this campaign, she has raised $17.9 million and
spent $11.61 million. Even with the departure of Giuliani, who had
set a fund-raising record, the campaign is likely to be one of the
most expensive in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   In stepping in for Giuliani, who dropped out to focus on his
treatment for prostate cancer, Lazio did not adopt much of the
Giuliani campaign apparatus, the records suggest. The Lazio
campaign did spend $4,000 buying computer equipment and mailing
lists from the Giuliani campaign, but established its own office in
midtown Manhattan _ Giuliani's had been downtown _ paying $12,198
for rent and another $15,372 for furniture.
</P>
<P>
   And instead of keeping the Giuliani staff, Lazio turned to
veterans of the McCain campaign, the records indicate. Lazio spent
several thousand dollars hiring Campaign Services Group, a firm
headed by John Weaver, one of McCain's former strategists, as well
as two other McCain consultants, Amy Griffith and Keith Nahigian.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio also brought on another former McCain strategist, Michael
Murphy, and some of Murphy's associates. A Lazio campaign
spokesman, Dan McLagan, is another former McCain campaign aide.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the advertising expenditures, Lazio focused heavily on
direct mail fund-raising solicitations, hoping to emulate
Giuliani's extraordinary success in collecting donations from
people around the country who dislike Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio hired a prominent Republican fund-raising company, SCM
Associates of New Hampshire, spending $183,412, according to the
documents. The campaign also paid $20,156 to Econtributor.com,
which handles online fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   The filings also show that the Lazio campaign returned a $2,000
contribution from Christopher Quick, a former executive of Quick &AMP;
Reilly, the brokerage company. The Securities and Exchange
Commission is investigating whether Lazio had inside information
before he bought options in Quick &AMP; Reilly stock in 1997, which
yielded him roughly $13,500, a nearly 600 percent profit, in less
than seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Quick &AMP; Reilly, which is now a division of
FleetBoston Financial, have been among Lazio's biggest supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Quick donated $2,000 to the Lazio campaign on June 15, just as
he was being questioned by reporters about Lazio's option's trade.
(Quick said he had not discussed the company's stock with Lazio.)
</P>
<P>
   On June 30, the Lazio campaign returned the $2,000 because it
was over the limit. Quick had already donated $2,000, the maximum,
on June 28, 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
