<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MCCALL-FUNDRAISER-245&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK'S LABOR LEADERS BACK McCALL FOR GOVERNOR  
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In what labor leaders are calling a powerful
signal that they intend to support state Comptroller H. Carl McCall
for governor in 2002, nearly all of New York's top union officials
will hold a fund-raiser for him Thursday in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said it was far too soon for them or their unions to
make formal endorsements. But several of them, asking that their
names not be used, added that they expected, even intended,
Thursday's event to be taken as an early sign of e their
sympathies. ``We'd elect him tomorrow,'' one prominent union leader
said.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials said that it was highly unusual to hold an event
with so many big labor names so far from the election, adding that
they could not imagine doing so for the man who might be McCall's
top opponent in a Democratic primary, Andrew Cuomo, the federal
housing secretary.
</P>
<P>
   McCall has said he will not make a formal announcement of his
plans until after the November elections, but he has made an
unusually early start at laying the groundwork for a run for
governor and lining up the support of a large number of elected
officials, and his aides say he is clearly running.
</P>
<P>
   He could have a bruising primary against Cuomo and, should he
win, the comptroller could face a daunting challenge in taking on
Gov. George Pataki, a popular Republican incumbent with an
impressive political and fund-raising operation. The governor has
said he expects to seek a third term.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether Thursday's event marks the
beginning of a wholesale shift for the state's labor unions, which
have taken pains not to clash with Pataki. Most remained neutral in
the 1998 race, when it was clear throughout that Pataki would
easily win re-election, depriving the Democratic nominee, Peter F.
Vallone, of what is usually his party's most potent ally.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo's and Pataki's offices did not return calls Tuesday
seeking comment. Cuomo has said he might run for governor, though
there has been talk of his taking another high-level Washington job
if Vice President Al Gore wins the presidency. Cuomo has said that
plenty of time remains for him to decide about 2002 and that he is
perplexed by McCall's early start.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the lineup of sponsors for Thursday's even means that
he would have strong labor support in a run for governor, McCall
said, ``Somebody could certainly infer that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would send a signal to anybody that as far as labor
is concerned, that I seem to have a good head start in terms of
lining up labor support,'' he said. ``That means that support would
probably not be there for someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzy Ballantyne, political director of the state AFL-CIO, said,
``It's a little early for us to be making endorsements, but what I
think what you can read into it is Carl McCall has a great deal of
support in the labor movement for his current plans and future
plans.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall has long been a favorite of unions for his handling of
the state pension funds, including protecting them from attempted
raids by lawmakers. His stature within organized labor rose
significantly this year after the Legislature passed and Pataki
signed into law a bill giving automatic cost-of-living increases,
or COLAs, to retired state and local government workers for the
first time, a caus the comptroller championed for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The COLA has really solidified what was already very strong
labor appreciation for Carl McCall, and I don't think that Andrew
has a similar issue that is as transcendent that he can point to,''
said Randi Weingarten, president of the United Federation of
Teachers and one of the sponsors of the fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   The amount organizers expect to raise from Thursday's reception
at the carpenters' union hall, something over $100,000, is
relatively modest, as is the price of admission, $1,000. An
individual can contribute more than $30,000 to a gubernatorial
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Invitations to the event list 48 co-chairman, including top
officials of the state AFL-CIO; District Council 37, the New York
City employees' umbrella group; New York State United Teachers; the
Transport Workers Union; the Civil Service Employees Association;
the International Brotherhood of Teamsters; the Communications
Workers of America; and UNITE, the garment workers' union.
</P>
<P>
   The only notable absence from the list is that of Dennis Rivera,
president of 1199, the hospital workers' union, who is probably the
state's most politically potent labor official. Rivera is known for
hedging his bets politically and has worked hard at building good
relations with state Republicans. Last year, he played a central
role in negotiating with the governor on a new health care program
for the working poor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
