<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MINING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: LEAVING ENVIRONMENTAL LAW ALONE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: W. Va.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, July 19:
</P>
<P>
   Today is the final day for public comment on a proposed rule
change in the Clean Water Act that would allow the environmentally
destructive practice called mountaintop-removal mining, common in
the coal-bearing regions of the Southeast, to continue unimpeded.
In mountaintop-removal mining, the soil and rock above a coal seam
are dumped into hollows and streambeds.
</P>
<P>
   Last October a federal judge in West Virginia ruled that the
practice violated the Clean Water Act, which says that mining and
other wastes cannot be used as ``fill material'' in waterways.
Instead of defending the law, the Environmental Protection Agency
proposed to change the definition of ``fill material'' to eliminate
that part of the rule barring the use of waste. This in effect
gives the Army Corps of Engineers, which issues fill permits under
the Clean Water Act, the authority to bury streams and estuaries
with waste.
</P>
<P>
   The change is opposed by environmentalists and moderate
Republicans, including Rick Lazio, who are furious at the
administration for weakening its generally reliable support of the
Clean Water Act. Through an aide, Hillary Clinton, Lazio's opponent
in the New York Senate race, has said that she too opposes the
change in environmental rules. She and Lazio contest the change not
because they need to take a stand on mountaintop mining in West
Virginia, but because it would expose waters all across the United
States to the dumping of waste. The EPA argues that by altering the
definition of ``fill'' to include waste it is merely legalizing
current practice in the coal mining industry. But the better way to
make coal mining conform with the law is to leave the law alone and
end mountaintop removal, which has destroyed 1,000 miles of streams
in West Virginia alone.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's stand can be understood only in the
narrowest political sense. Mining that dumps waste into hollows and
valleys has expanded considerably during the past 10 years, and one
of the states in which it is most prevalent _ West Virginia _ is
represented by the powerful and agelessly influential Democratic
senator Robert Byrd. But by pursuing this rule change _ by
authorizing the dumping of waste into living waters _ the
administration has involved itself in a fatal contradiction,
claiming to support the Clean Water Act while also undercutting it.
What the act needs is not revision. It is enforcement. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
