A6227 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-VIRUS-NYT &LR;      07-18 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-VIRUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KERSHAW  
</HEADLINE>
  
 REGION BRACES FOR SPRAYING TO BATTLE THE WEST NILE VIRUS By SARAH c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As residents of Staten Island braced themselves on
Tuesday for spraying with the pesticide Anvil in response to signs
of West Nile virus, Westchester County officials announced that
they would also begin spraying the chemical on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very difficult decision personally for me to
make,'' Andrew J. Spano, the Westchester County executive, said at
a news conference on Tuesday after a pool of mosquitoes had tested
positive for the disease. ``We want to reduce the use of pesticides
in the county, and I have said over and over again it was our goal
to avoid having to use them.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement in Westchester, a suburban county north of New
York City, came a day after city officials announced that they
would begin spraying Staten Island starting Wednesday night because
two dead crows had tested positive for the virus, which the
authorities said sickened 62 people in the New York region last
year, killing 7.
</P>
<P>
   In the city, where the outbreak began last year in Queens, no
mosquitoes have tested positive for the virus, and there have been
no reports of illness in humans anywhere this summer.
</P>
<P>
   In Suffolk County on Long Island, where infected birds and
mosquitoes were found, spraying of Anvil and another pesticide,
Scourge, began Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City and in Westchester, officials will use trucks
to spray Anvil, part of a class of pesticides known as synthetic
pyrethroids, which mimic the natural pesticide produced by
chrysanthemum flowers. Scourge, a pesticide from the same family,
may also be used if more spraying is needed in other parts of the
city, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   For the residents of Staten Island, news that their
neighborhoods would be sprayed was greeted with a mixture of relief
and worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spray could hurt people, but it could also help people,''
said Angela Amari, 36. ``The virus is something a perfectly healthy
person could become extremely sick with. It's a double-edged
sword.''
</P>
<P>
   Several environmental experts said the pesticides being used
tended to have fewer health effects on humans than Malathion, the
pesticide that was used during an aerial spraying campaign last
year that drew vociferous opposition from environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   In April, city officials said they would no longer use
Malathion, which affects the central nervous system in mosquitoes
and, in large enough doses, in humans.
</P>
<P>
   The synthetic pyrethroids ``are generally not as potent or toxic
chemicals to humans,'' said Steven Johnson, the Environmental
Protection Agency's deputy administrator for the office of
prevention, pesticides and toxic substances.
</P>
<P>
   Still, health and environmental officials said the pesticides
could aggravate respiratory problems like asthma in people and
could also cause minor skin, throat and eye irritations.
</P>
<P>
   Officials encouraged residents to stay indoors and keep their
pets inside during the spraying hours, keep windows closed and
air-conditioners, which could allow the pesticide to enter their
homes, turned off. Residents are also urged to wash any toys or
equipment left outside before use.
</P>
<P>
   In Westchester, spraying of every road across half the county,
covering New Rochelle, Eastchester, Tuckahow, Bronxville,
Mamaroneck, Scarsdale, North Castle, Mount Pleasant, New Castle,
Pleasantville, Mount Kisco, Pound Ridge, Lewisboro and Bedford, was
scheduled for 11:30 p.m. Thursday to 4:30 a.m. Friday.
</P>
<P>
   On Staten Island, spraying is scheduled for 10 p.m. Wednesday to
5 a.m. Thursday in a two-mile radius of where the dead crows were
found, encompassing the Rossville and Westerleigh sections of the
borough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
