<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARNINGS AT COKE BOTTLER NARROWLY BEAT EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In results that narrowly beat analysts' expectations, Coca-Cola
Enterprises said Tuesday that its second-quarter profit rose 26
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Profit from operations at the company, Coca-Cola's largest
bottler, increased to $131 million, or 31 cents a share, compared
with $104 million, or 24 cents a share, in the quarter a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent period, a one-time charge of $12 million for
layoffs in Britain, where Coca-Cola Enterprises is struggling with
lower-priced Coke products in what has been one of its more
lucrative businesses, made net income $123 million, or 29 cents a
share. Results in the period a year earlier included a $103 million
charge for recalling products from France and Belgium, making net
income $34 million, or 8 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected the company to earn 28 cents a share,
according to First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue rose 8 percent, to $4.03 billion from $3.8 billion,
though sales volume declined in North America, its largest market,
and in Britain, another major market.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were slightly ahead because of higher pricing in North
America and higher sales costs, but it was nothing to write home
about,'' said Bill Pecoriello, a beverage analyst for Sanford C.
Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   Volume in North America, which accounts for most of the
bottler's sales, continues to be uncertain. While revenue per case
increased 5 percent, consumers seemed to be balking at higher
prices charged in supermarkets, where until recently Coke and Pepsi
were locked in a price war that kept the cost of six-packs and
two-liter bottles low.
</P>
<P>
   Coke and its archrival are betting that higher prices will
eventually be accepted by consumers, but so far consumers seem
reluctant. Sales of store-brand soda, which is cheaper, have
increased at double-digit rates this year, according to data
compiled by Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. The soft-drink category
is up 2.5 percent for the year, while store-brand soda has grown
9.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Volume growth is essential to Coca-Cola's earnings growth. The
company's chairman has said he expects volume to increase 5 percent
to 6 percent worldwide this year, and rise 7 percent to 8 percent
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to expect full-year volume in North America to be
flat to up 1 percent versus the prior year,'' said John R. Alm,
Coca-Cola Enterprises' president and chief operating officer.
Coca-Cola Enterprises, which is 40 percent owned by Coca-Cola,
accounts for 74 percent of Coke's North American sales in bottles
and cans.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts in May, Alm warned that
domestic volume would increase just 1 percent to 2 percent this
year, while estimates had been 2 percent to 3 percent. After he
made that announcement, his company's share price plummeted
$6.9375, to $15.625, a 52-week low. Shares of Coca-Cola were
dragged lower as well, losing $3, to $48.9375.
</P>
<P>
   The newly lowered volume estimates did not take a toll on the
stock Tuesday. Shares of Coca-Cola Enterprises rose Tuesday by just
less than $1, to close at $18.4375. Coca-Cola is holding a
conference call today to discuss its own second-quarter results,
which are being announced this morning.
</P>
<P>
   The bottler's sales were up 5 percent in the more lucrative
vending area, the company said. In Europe, sales rose 15.5 percent
in the quarter, although the second quarter of last year was a
particularly bleak one, in which Coke products were pulled from
store shelves and production halted in Belgium and France because
of contamination fears. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
