<HEADER>
A6235 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RUN-OLY-JOHNSON-2TAKE     07-18 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-OLY-JOHNSON-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH NOON FOR JOHNSON AND GREENE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Two months ago, Michael Johnson told a
small group of reporters that he would never borrow again from
professional wrestling to hype a race. He had learned his lesson
three years ago, he said, when he traded verbal half-nelsons with
Donovan Bailey of Canada to promote a manufactured 150-meter race.
Johnson ended up grabbing his leg in injury while Bailey grabbed
the title of world's fastest man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did the WWF thing,'' Johnson said, referring to the match
race in Toronto between the Olympic 100- and 200-meter champions.
``I'm not doing it anymore. I did it for the sake of the sport, and
it all worked well until the gun went off and I got injured. That's
not me. That's not what I'm about.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, facing an expected showdown at 200 meters on Sunday with
Maurice Greene, the current world record-holder at 100 meters, the
normally taciturn Johnson has again decided to hurl a few verbal
body slams. His words, both spoken and written, have provided a
riveting if uncharacteristic subtext to the most eagerly awaited
event of the Olympic track and field trials. And they reflect the
fact that, despite his gold medals and world records at 200 meters
(19.32 seconds) and 400 meters (43.18 seconds), Johnson has found
it necessary to repeatedly defend his stunning accomplishments
against what he considers disrespectful remarks about his speed,
character and integrity. ``I feel I need to defend myself,''
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I do dislike a lot of things Maurice Greene has said
about me and his attempt to elevate himself using my name.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, the 1996 Olympic champion at 100 meters, charged that
Johnson faked the injury to his left thigh once he realized he was
going to lose their 1997 match race. Greene's camp has accused
Johnson of ducking him on the international circuit. Greene has
also suggested that Johnson's world record at 200 meters was set in
Atlanta mainly because the track was built at the limit of
allowable hardness. Johnson bristles at these slights, which nag at
him like a pulled hamstring muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Donovan was a young guy who came into the sport and did not
show any consistency,'' Johnson said in a recent interview. ``He
won a gold medal that they were going to give to someone anyway. I
did something in Atlanta that no one had ever done. I put more
pressure on myself than anyone. Now all of a sudden I'm supposed to
be faking it? And I'm supposed to be afraid of Maurice, a guy who
has never run faster than 19.8? That's ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, Johnson has called Greene immature. Last Friday, in
a column written for USA Today, Johnson said that Greene was not
smart for scheduling a flurry of races in Europe during late June
and early July. He also criticized Greene's Los Angeles-based
training group, known as Hudson Smith International, saying the
members were unfocused and resting on past accomplishments. His
assessment of HSI was inaccurate _ the group's athletes have swept
all three Olympic spots in the men's 100 meters, taken a silver
medal in the women's 100 meters and won first place in the men's
pole vault and long jump _ but Johnson has hardly retracted his
words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people aren't used to being criticized,'' Johnson said.
``You either handle it or you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene has said he viewed the trials 200 as a semifinal match,
with the Olympics being the final, but he has also said, ``I'm
going to get Michael.'' Johnson said he would not settle for second
place at the trials because ``I'm better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think winning the race is going to silence any
critics,'' Johnson said. ``Once I beat him, Maurice will say, `My
goal is to win the Olympic Games.' Which is what he's supposed to
say. I'm not going to win to silence him, but because I can win and
I'm supposed to.''
</P>
<P>
   Trash-talking is an age-old custom in the sprints, where
athletes look for the slightest edge in races decided by hundredths
of a second. Johnson said he believed that Greene's bravado came
from insecurity not confidence. Greene said he laughed at Johnson's
public comments and just wants to put on a show. ``I like the
WWF,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But why the criticism of Johnson, who possesses a combination of
speed and endurance unmatched in the history of sprinting? ``I
think that's just the nature of the sport,'' said Ato Boldon of
Trinidad, who finished third to Johnson in the 200 at the Atlanta
Olympics and who trains daily with Greene in Los Angeles. ``Michael
Johnson could have 15 gold medals. He'd still be attacked by guys
like me and Maurice who want what he has. There is no respect in
this sport. You are only as good as your last race, and even then
you are going to be disrespected.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprinters are reluctant to speak respectfully of each other,
Johnson said, for fear of showing vulnerability. The quarter-milers
who have faced him, however, have been forced into deferential
submission by his dominance. Johnson has lost only 3 of 78 races
over 400 meters in the past 11 years. He won the Olympic trials on
Sunday by nearly a second.
</P>
<P>
   At the 200, injury has made Johnson more vulnerable in recent
years. He has run 16 200-meter races since breaking the world
record in Atlanta, but only four times has he dipped under 20
seconds. He owns the fastest time in the world this year, 19.71
seconds, but that was a race at altitude in South Africa. His
fastest time at sea level since Atlanta is 19.91 seconds, slower
than Greene's personal best of 19.86. The two sprinters have met
twice at 200 meters, and each has won once. Greene won the 200
meters at the 1999 world championships in Seville, Spain, while
Johnson did not enter the event, concentrating on the 400 meters.
</P>
<P>
   In Boldon's estimation, the first person off the curve on Sunday
will be the winner at the Olympic trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael knows he's not going to come off the turn behind
Maurice and run him down,'' Boldon said. ``Not now. Not unless he's
in 19.32 shape, which I don't think he is. If he is in 19.32 shape,
it doesn't matter what Maurice does. If Maurice comes off the turn
with a significant lead, that's it. Michael will not only not
challenge, Michael will appreciate the fact that every time he's
run a really fast 200, he's been hurt. He will settle for second
and bear the brunt of criticism to come and prepare for the
Olympics. On the other hand, if Maurice comes off even or behind,
he's going to floor it. He's going to try to get Michael. I don't
know if Michael can be run down.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In running his startling world record at Atlanta, Johnson
injured his left hamstring muscle. Against Bailey in 1997, he
injured the thigh muscle in his left leg. It was later determined
that the sacroiliac joint in his pelvis was slightly rotated, which
threw out of alignment the muscles in his left leg, making them
less efficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a cup of coffee in a saucer that's not quite sitting
in the groove, or a car with a front end that's out of alignment,''
said Dale Smith, who is Johnson's physical therapist. ``A tire that
gets 60,000 miles now will only get 15 or 20,000.''
</P>
<P>
   The greatest race of Johnson's career may not have been his
world records, but the 400-meter final at the 1997 world
championship in Athens, when he came from fifth in the final curve
to first at the finish on guts and experience. Tests later revealed
that his left leg had become slightly shorter, was still carrying
significant amounts of fluid from the injury against Bailey and was
30 percent weaker than his right leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the circumstances, that might have been his finest
race,'' said Clyde Hart, who coaches Johnson in Waco, Tex.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Smith travels to each race with Johnson, often
immersing him in ice baths and massaging him or helping him stretch
late into the evening after running rounds. Greene asserted that
Johnson would shut down if he was behind out of the curve Sunday,
saying Johnson ``doesn't want to put his body through that kind of
stress because every time something happens to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Johnson camp fumes at this, pointing out that he chased down
the 400 field in Athens on pure determination. There is nothing to
show that a sprinter is more susceptible to injury running from
behind than in front, Hart said. ``Besides that,'' he added, ``we
don't tend to be behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said: ``That's the difference between Maurice and me.
Maurice depends on me being afraid and shutting down or breaking
down to win races. I depend on Michael running great to win races.
It's obvious now that he feels the only way he can win this race is
to make me break down.''
</P>
<P>
   The brash but patient Greene, who holds the world record of 9.79
seconds at 100 meters, believes the two runners will come off the
curve together, or within one and a half steps of each other, and
that he will pull victory out at the end. ``My foot speed is
greater than his,'' Greene said. ``I believe I am a lot stronger
sprinter than he is.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I can't afford to let him come off the curve three
or four steps ahead. If he's that far ahead, I'll press too hard to
catch him and run out of gas.''
</P>
<P>
   Boldon, the 1997 world champion at 200 meters, said he would
give the nod to Johnson because of experience. ``It doesn't mean I
don't think Maurice can win,'' he said of his training partner.
``But I don't think Maurice understands that this is a race where
there are 10 ways to win it and 20 to lose it. Michael has probably
eliminated 19 ways to lose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 2319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
