<DOCNO> NYT20000718.0433 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-18 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6239 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-HEALTHC     07-18 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-HEALTHCARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON'S HEALTH PLAN EXPANDS ON A CURRENT LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hillary Rodham Clinton presented her plan Tuesday to
extend health insurance to millions of Americans, including 1.1
million New Yorkers. Her plan, which hews closely to the one
proposed by Vice President Al Gore, could not be further in details
and scope from the ill-fated program she helped to mastermind in
the early 1990's.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton outlined her initiative in a news conference at
Columbia-Presbyterian Center in Manhattan. Among other things, it
would, expand an existing government program to insure children.
``We will never be the kind of New York or America we should and
can be if we do not figure out a way to provide quality affordable
health care to every one of us,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, more than 19 percent of people under 65, or 3.1
million people, lack health insurance. A large number of them are
the working poor who make too much money to qualify for Medicaid
but do not receive benefits from their employer or cannot afford to
buy them. And despite a federal program that covers children, about
700,000 children in New York still lack insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion of insurance and health care to all Americans was
Clinton's goal in the early 90's. Her plan for universal coverage
was flattened by Congress in 1994 after determined lobbying by
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   That plan put much of the burden of covering the uninsured on
employers. But the plan presented Tuesday by Clinton, who is
running for the Senate, returns much of the burden to the
government and steers clear from visions of insuring the entire
nation in one blow.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may remember that seven years ago, I had a few ideas about
this topic,'' said Clinton, who has taken to joking about her
earlier failed effort and stressing that she has learned to take
small steps toward change in one of the most complex policy issues
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Her opponent in the Senate race, Representative Rick A. Lazio,
immediately criticized the plan, asserting that she did not reveal
where the money to pay for such expansions would come from. His
camp added that the federal government has shortchanged New York by
not providing a fair share of federal funds for existing programs,
and asserted that Clinton should have influenced her husband in
this area.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton suggested that federal budget surpluses could be used to
pay for her plan.
</P>
<P>
   The core of her proposal relied heavily on the Children's Health
Insurance Program, a 1997 federal-state effort. In this program,
the federal government gives states 65 percent of their costs to
insure children from families whose income is no more than about
$31,000 a year, for a family of four, or about 200 percent of the
federal poverty line.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton proposes expanding that program to children in families
living at an income level from 250 to 300 percent of the poverty
line, or about $51,000 for a family of four. That would cost an
additional $10 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   She would also like to see the program extended to parents of
children living within this income bracket. The New York State
Legislature recently passed a similar plan, known as Family Health
Plus.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said she also would make sure that all states use their
money under the federal program, or face losing the federal
matching funds.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, she proposes giving a 25 percent refundable tax
credit to people who are not insured through their jobs and need to
buy insurance as individuals, and giving families whose incomes are
above 300 percent of the poverty line a chance to buy Children's
Health Insurance Program insurance at a rate cheaper than the
market rates for individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has made similar proposals. His and Clinton's plans differ
mostly in their generosity. Her proposals for establishing
eligibility are a bit more lenient.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plan is far removed from her notions of universal
coverage in the early 1990's, which included a requirement that
employers pick up 80 percent of the cost of any health care plan
their workers chose.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has not yet released any specific proposal to deal with
those who do not have health insurance. Clinton's proposal came
after Lazio's wife, Patricia, a nurse, began appearing in a
television advertisement last week defending his record on health
care issues in Congress. ``He has not exactly been silent on these
issues,'' said a campaign spokesman, Michael Marr.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's advisers insisted that President Clinton has yet to make
sure that New York gets its fair share of federal money. New York
is indeed in danger of spending large amounts of state money on the
Children's Health Insurance Program next year. Under the law, New
York is to have 65 percent of the costs for its health insurance
program reimbursed by the federal government, up to $256 million.
The law sets a timetable, in the fall, for states either to use
their allocations or to relinquish what they haven't used to other
states.
</P>
<P>
   Because New York has by far the largest such program in the
country _ 522,000 New York children are enrolled _ it is well on
its way to surpassing its cap. That means that New York might have
to pick up the costs of additional enrollments.
</P>
<P>
   But many members of Congress would like to see states that have
failed to spend their money get another two years to work out their
programs before losing any funds. Health care experts say it is
unlikely that the Clinton administration could find a way to
release more money to New York for this program until these issues
are resolved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
