A6245 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-GORE-KAN &LR;      07-18 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Gore launches spirited Missouri campaign in KC  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ On a steam-bath of an afternoon in Kansas City, Al
Gore launched his Missouri comeback bid with a rousing call to arms
for the Democratic cause and a scathing attack on his rival
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing presumptive GOP presidential nominee George W. Bush by
11 points in a recent statewide poll, an energetic Gore tore into
the Texas governor, saying his tax-cut plan caters to special
interests and would send the national debt soaring again.
</P>
<P>
   ``You add up what they promise, and it's way bigger than the
surplus,'' Gore said at a rally at the Barney Allis Plaza, 12th and
Central streets downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Showing no ill effects from the sauna-like conditions, Gore
seemed in his element with a high-energy stump speech that at times
resembled a rapid-fire rebel yell.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I'm running for president _ to fight for you,''
Gore shouted at one point in his 25-minute address. ``To fight for
Kansas City. To fight for Missouri. To fight for working families.
To fight for those who don't have another champion. I want to fight
for your family and your future.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats estimated the crowd at 3,000 to 4,000, but Kansas City
Police later released a far more modest total. ``One thousand
tops,'' said Sgt. Randy Sims.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's downtown stump speech was the first of several events
during a rare, overnight visit by a presidential candidate to
Kansas City. Later Tuesday, he raised about $100,000 from 28
partisans at a sedate Democratic National Committee fund-raiser at
the Kansas City Club, 1228 Baltimore Ave.
</P>
<P>
   At a lobster dinner, Gore mocked the policies of the Republicans
as ``stale.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Their whole agenda is 20 years old,'' Gore said. ``We've been
there, done that, still paying the bills.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he left for the Park Place Hotel at Interstate 435
and Front Street in the East Bottoms. Visiting dignitaries usually
stay downtown or on the Country Club Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really random,'' Gore aide Alex Zaroulis said about the
hotel choice. ``They had enough rooms for the staff and the folks
traveling with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Gore is to begin his day with stops at one or two
locations around Kansas City. On Tuesday the campaign would not
disclose the locations.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a visit to Raytown, he is expected to unveil new
elements of his crime-fighting agenda. At a meeting with law
enforcement officials at Raytown City Hall, he is set to release a
plan calling for 10,000 more local prosecutors across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also is expected to renew his call for 50,000 new police
officers _ a plan styled after President Clinton's former call for
100,000 new officers.
</P>
<P>
   Crime also was the focus of the first part of Gore's day
Tuesday. In Memphis, Tenn., Gore proposed his own crime victims'
constitutional amendment. Under his plan, which is the focus of
television ads now airing in Kansas City, victims would be notified
when their attackers were released. And victims would have the
right to be heard at sentencing and be eligible for restitution
from a convict.
</P>
<P>
   ``The accused criminals have all kinds of rights, and we all
understand why it's part of our system,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But here's the point: When those rights are enshrined in the
Constitution and the rights of victims are not, whenever the two
are in conflict, it's not even a close contest. The victims are put
in the back seat and sometimes completely ignored.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, though, Republicans charged that the
Clinton-Gore administration had a chance to pass a bipartisan
amendment this year, but opted to kill the measure for political
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton-Gore withdrew their support for the victims-rights
bill in April of this year in order to preserve it as a campaign
issue this November,'' said Cass County Prosecutor Chris Koster. He
and other law enforcement officials and police held a press
conference in Kansas City before Gore arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's visit comes at a time of mixed signals about his standing
in the national race. Although a poll last week in /{The Kansas
City Star/} showed Gore trailing in Missouri, a national bellwether
state, by 48-37 percent, two new national polls out Tuesday showed
the race nearly dead even.
</P>
<P>
   Those standing in the crowd Tuesday night had more good news for
the vice president. Many were impressed with his vitality and a
sense that Gore was anything but the stiff, wooden caricature so
often joked about on late-night TV shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's gotten this image that's not correct,'' said
Angie Reuter of Kansas City. ``He was more dynamic than Clinton
was.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen him this fired up,'' said Ed Drake, a retired
local labor leader. ``He's getting into the swing of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanging from beams in the Barney Allis Plaza were a series of
posters proclaiming support from Kansas and Missouri labor
organizations: Pipefitters Local 533, Teamsters Local 541 and
Plumbers Local 8, among others. Gore's standing with labor has
suffered in recent months because of his support for free-trade
policies that many national labor groups oppose.
</P>
<P>
   Gore began his Kansas City appearance on a somber note by
calling for a moment of silence to honor the life of Republican
Sen. Paul Coverdell of Georgia, who death was announced shortly
before Gore took the stage. Coverdell had surgery Monday to relieve
pressure from a cerebral hemorrhage, but died from swelling in the
brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a partisan gathering, but we are all Americans,'' Gore
said. ``And when something like this happens, we join together in
thinking of the family...and honoring the service of an individual
who helped make our Constitution work.''
</P>
<P>
   Dressed casually in a polo and khakis, Gore covered a litany of
issues, from a patients' bill of rights to the need to raise the
minimum wage and teacher pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to treat teachers like the professionals they are,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he would balance the budget every year and work toward
paying off the national debt by 2012.
</P>
<P>
   On Social Security, Gore charged that Bush's plan to allow
individuals to invest a part of their retirement savings in the
stock market would be disastrous. Under the plan, money would have
to be borrowed to keep the system solvent, Gore said, because there
would not be enough money flowing into the program to meet ongoing
obligations.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans ``are proposing a plan that will cause it to run
dry,'' Gore said of Bush's plan. The system, he added, ``should not
be tampered with.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said individuals who lost money through the stock-market
option would be expected to be bailed out in the same way the
federal government aided savings and loan institutions that failed
in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, though, has said that allowing individuals to invest in
the stock market will increase their Social Security checks and
extend the program's life.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore said his plan would offer the best future for the
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will keep Social Security and Medicare in an iron-clad lock
box with a sign _ Politicians: Hands Off!'' Gore said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
