<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-TORRICELLI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POISED TO RUN FOR GOVERNOR, TORRICELLI SPLITS THE DEMOCRATS
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID M. HALBFINGER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Sen. Robert Torricelli has all but officially
declared his candidacy for the Democratic nomination for governor,
setting off a pitched battle with Mayor James E. McGreevey of
Woodbridge, the party's nominee in 1997, for the support of
officials across New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The showdown between two longtime allies has thrown the state's
Democratic Party into turmoil, just when it seemed to have been
recovering from a divisive Senate primary, and is raising concerns
that the distraction could hobble the party's performance in the
November elections.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday Jon Corzine, the Democratic nominee for Senate,
rescinded his endorsement of McGreevey, saying in an internal
campaign memo that he would remain neutral and acknowledging that
his campaign aides and advisers were caught in the middle of the
gubernatorial fight.
</P>
<P>
   In a replay of the jockeying for support that went on during the
Senate race between Corzine and Jim Florio, Torricelli and
McGreevey are carving up New Jersey county by county, racing to
lock up commitments from countless Democratic chairmen and
financiers, freeholders and mayors, union leaders and influential
ministers.
</P>
<P>
   It is still unclear who has the upper hand. Advisers to
Torricelli and McGreevey are both claiming broad-based support.
</P>
<P>
   But one side must be grossly exaggerating its support, or party
officials are telling each man what he wants to hear. For example,
in Essex County, a key battleground that has the state's most
enrolled Democrats, Torricelli and McGreevey are both claiming the
support of Mayor Sharpe James of Newark, State Sen. Richard Codey
and Thomas Giblin, the county and state Democratic chairman.
</P>
<P>
   James, who met with Torricelli on Monday, did not respond to
phone messages. Neither Codey nor Giblin would reveal whom he was
supporting. But two McGreevey supporters said Codey had told them
on Tuesday that he had reiterated his support for McGreevey in a
conversation with Torricelli that afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, Torricelli's camp is telling wavering Democrats that
he has the support of roughly two-thirds of the counties in the
state, including five of the seven counties in South Jersey. But
supporters of McGreevey say that in the south, only Camden and
Burlington Counties are backing Torricelli.
</P>
<P>
   Few of the state's Democratic leaders would clearly take sides
on Tuesday, or even speak for the record. But many were talking
plenty all the same.
</P>
<P>
   Those who favor Torricelli say he is simply the best-known, most
powerful and most electable Democrat in New Jersey. Next to
McGreevey, one senior party official said, ``it's like Mark McGwire
versus the home run king of the Pee Wee League.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brad Lawrence, a consultant to McGreevey whose firm is also
working for Corzine, said Torricelli, whose 1996 campaign
fund-raising operation has drawn the scrutiny of federal
prosecutors, would be more vulnerable to attack. ``We know the
microscopic scrutiny that Jim went under in 1997, and we know he
survived it rather well,'' Lawrence said. ``There are no dark
secrets out there. I think we can withstand the scrutiny of this
process better than the senator can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 2333EDT &QL; 
