<HEADLINE>
NEAGLE MAKES A WINNING FIRST IMPRESSION AS YANKS TOP PHILS, 3-1 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Denny Neagle warmed up in the bullpen in left-center
field at Yankee Stadium on Tuesday night, several paces from
Monument Park. A day earlier, he had become excited when he talked
about his debut with the Yankees and said that he merely had to
peer at the monuments to understand how special his first start
would be. Tuesday night, Neagle made sure it was special for more
than just the historic baseball setting.
</P>
<P>
   Tugging at his uniform pants or jersey, oddly blowing into his
left hand on a muggy night and working quickly, Neagle tamed the
Philadelphia Phillies and helped the Yankees roll to a 3-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The newest Yankee earned standing ovations after closing the
seventh and eighth innings with strikeouts, and he heard chants of
``Den-ny! Den-ny!'' His sturdy eight-inning performance allowed Joe
Torre to exhale and even smile on his 60th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   With Orlando Hernandez going on the 15-day disabled list Tuesday
because of a sprained right elbow and with David Cone going 12
starts without a victory, the Yankees were relieved to see Neagle
dominate Philadelphia. Torre repeatedly discusses how the Yankees
win because of solid starting pitching, and the acquisition of the
left-hander from the Cincinnati Reds last Wednesday should continue
to boost a sagging and inconsistent rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle allowed one run and five hits while striking out three
and walking two before turning the mound over to Mariano Rivera,
who retired the Phillies in order in the ninth for his 22nd save.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's Curt Schilling, an ace whose name pops up in
trade rumors several times a month, was superior to Neagle for a
good portion of the night. The Yankees did not collect a hit off
Schilling until there were two out in the fourth inning, but they
supplied the most important hits of the game in the fifth and
sixth.
</P>
<P>
   David Justice led off the fifth by lining a homer into the front
row of seats in right field. It was Justice's 24th home run of the
season, his third as a Yankee and his fourth homer in 27 career
at-bats against Schilling.
</P>
<P>
   After Chuck Knoblauch walked and Derek Jeter singled with one
out in the sixth, Bernie Williams rapped a triple to left-center to
drive in both and put the Yankees ahead, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   That gave Williams 87 runs batted in and helped the Yankees
finish interleague play with an 11-6 record this season.
</P>
<P>
   But this game was about pitching, not offense, and this game was
about the witty and talented Neagle. He has already endeared
himself to his teammates with his unusual imitations and his
eccentric personality, but his behavior would not be so funny if he
were a so-so pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees traded four prospects to get Neagle, and general
manager Brian Cashman is eager to begin negotiations with Neagle's
agent on a multiyear contract extension. Maybe he is a little more
eager after Tuesday night's stupendous effort.
</P>
<P>
   When Torre was asked what he liked about Neagle, he said: ``The
successes he has had in places and pitching in the postseason.
Obviously, he knows what he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, the Yankees were obviously happy that they had
snared Neagle. The left-hander was tested early when Doug Glanville
smacked a single under his glove to open the game. Glanville moved
to second on a wild pitch and took third on a groundout. But Neagle
retired Scott Rolen on a popout to strand Glanville.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle walked Pat Burrell to begin the second and allowed Alex
Arias' one-out single, but he came back to strike out Mickey
Morandini and retire Tom Prince on a fly ball.
</P>
</TEXT>
