<HEADER>
A6254 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-METS-BLUEJAYS-NYT     07-18 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-METS-BLUEJAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS DOWN TORONTO BLUE JAYS, 11-7 
 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Lenny Harris, the New York Mets' utility man, scored
two runs and added a run-scoring single on Tuesday night as the
Mets downed the Toronto Blue Jays, 11-7.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two games Harris has gotten a chance to play third
base and bat first, and he sparked the Mets again Tuesday night
with a leadoff home run. Harris, who is in his third stint as a
teammate of Mike Piazza's, said the trouble comes when the Mets
rely too heavily on their All-Star catcher. In the last two games,
Harris seems to have taken it upon himself to prove the point.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza had the game's most memorable hit, a grand slam in the
fifth inning that broke a 3-3 tie and made Bobby J. Jones the
winner despite an unsteady outing.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Harris who kept things lively Tuesday night, just as
he did on Monday, when his three hits and two stolen bases led to
an extra-inning victory. Derek Bell, who bats second, was Harris'
crony, going 3 for 4 with a homer and four runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   Harris drew a leadoff walk in the fifth, then stole second off
Chris Carpenter. Carpenter's pitches had movement, but they strayed
far from the strike zone, and he walked six Mets. He walked two in
the fourth inning, leading to a run, then walked two more after
Harris to load the bases in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   That would be fatal, because Piazza came up next. The Mets'
Robin Ventura gets considerable attention for his success with the
bases loaded (he has a .356 career average with 14 grand slams),
but Piazza may be even more dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   He went down in the strike zone and ripped a fastball into the
second deck in left center, 426 feet away. It gave the Mets a 7-3
lead and was Piazza's third grand slam of the season, tying a Mets
record. In his career, Piazza is batting .386 with the bases
loaded, and he has 12 slams.
</P>
<P>
   Harris has a chance to see significant playing time at third
base, with Ventura on the disabled list because of his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Franco was the first option at third base, but Harris
started there for the second game in a row Tuesday night, and
batted leadoff again. He had three hits and two stolen bases _
running on his own both times _ in a victory over the Jays on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he plays like that, you definitely want to see him
play,'' Manager Bobby Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Until Monday, Harris had only 2 hits in 21 at-bats since the
Mets acquired him from Arizona in early June. But Harris, who
batted .310 last year, was sure he would start producing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew sooner or later I'd get a chance to play a little
bit,'' Harris said. ``Stats are not important. People might look at
it and say he's struggling, his average is a buck-fifty or
something like that, but I'm a part-time player. It's not like I
can play everyday and come out of a slump. I'm a good hitter; I've
always been a good hitter. I wasn't worried about that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
