<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-DALY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
For '95 British Open champ, life remains a Daly struggle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ The ugliest rumor of all _ and doesn't that
cover more real estate than even his biggest corkscrew drive? _ was
that John Daly didn't have enough scratch to make the trip back to
the scene of the greatest moment in his life.
</P>
<P>
   What with his owing $20,000 a month in alimony and his being
another $1 million or so in debt, nobody was assuming anything
about the burning fuse with blond hair. Until somebody actually saw
Daly on the grounds of St. Andrews' Old Course, it was fair to
guess he might not show at all.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the sad state of affairs has come to regarding the
last man to walk out of St. Andrews with the Claret Jug.
</P>
<P>
   The line between rumor and fact has been blurred by so many
years of self-torment. And it's gotten so bad that Daly has used up
the sympathetic shoulders that once were there for him to lean
upon.
</P>
<P>
   There no longer is a pat on the back from observers and peers.
While many considered him a cult hero of sorts when he won the
British Open in 1995, the burly, chain-smoking, hard-living man has
now dug such a deep abyss for himself that even a return to St.
Andrews probably won't be enough to rejuvenate him.
</P>
<P>
   His bottle no longer is half-full. It now is just a matter of
waiting to see if he wants to return to what his fellow golfers
know is a terrific way to live _ as a productive member of the PGA
Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``John is his own worst enemy,'' says Jack Nicklaus. ``He's not
going to get better until he gets rid of those demons in his
head.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows how many holes Daly has left on this golf course of
life. Whatever the number, the demons have him dormie.
</P>
<P>
   The only hope, perhaps, is that a return to St. Andrews _ his
own personal Last Chance Saloon _ will roust Daly into better form
and a better attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like coming home,'' Daly says. ``I'd have walked over
broken glass to be here. Nothing was going to stop me.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are places in life you just want to be. This is one of
them for me.''
</P>
<P>
   It also might be characterized as the biggest gamble of all for
Daly. A huge loss here, and he might never recover. To see Daly go
off the handle and score a 12 on the Road Hole or spend an hour
trying to hack out of Hell Bunker would surprise nobody this week.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he has an exemption to play on the PGA Tour until
2005 because of his win here, Daly seems to know he now has nobody
who will pick him up except himself. And he's not sure he's
capable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be awesome if it was me and Tiger (Woods) coming down
the stretch on Sunday,'' Daly says. ``He's going to be there. And I
guess it's possible I could be on a flight home by then, though not
if I can help it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Daly hasn't been able to help two busted marriages. He
hasn't been able to help tossing away millions of dollars to
gambling. He hasn't been able to help the brain cells lost to binge
drinking for all those years.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are signs that all is not lost. Daly has lost a
few pounds (30, he claims), and his father, Jim, is certain his son
has his life ``back on track.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has always drawn strength from what happened here the last
time,'' Jim Daly says. ``I can tell you I haven't seen John so
happy and at peace with himself for a long time. All he wants now
is a couple of good performances on the golf course, and things
will be perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt the Old Course fits Daly just as well, and
maybe better, than it does Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can miss it left here all day,'' Daly says. ``You have the
whole of Scotland out there. And if me or Tiger mishit it, that's
usually where we end up (left).''
</P>
<P>
   Banking on Daly to make a turnaround this week is risky business
to be sure. In 2000, he's earned only $93,402. When you consider
his financial situation, it's barely enough to keep him in
Marlboros and greaseburgers.
</P>
<P>
   This is different, however. This is St. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I walk out on that course, I feel like it was made for
me,'' Daly says. ``Winning the Open at St. Andrews was a total
blast. I love everything about it, even the wind and the rain.
(There has been none of either this week.) I have so much
confidence here. It could be my comeback. It's what I do from here
on that matters, not the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Except nobody believes Daly can avoid the flippant tantrum. It
seems every tournament includes something new for him, and without
exception, it has been bad.
</P>
<P>
   It's been as consistent as the seasons since his win here in
'95, when he survived the sensational chip-in from Costantino Rocca
and won in a playoff. The routine since then has included a time of
sobriety, a couple of more trips to sobriety clinics, and finally,
an admission to himself and the public last year that he was
drinking again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made three trips (total) to rehab, and they cost me $30,000
a visit,'' he says. ``They were only in it to make money. The AA
(meetings) were much better. But I don't think I need them anymore.
Besides, I am not an alcoholic. I don't drink every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have four, maybe five beers if I go out to dinner, although
it's a 12-pack when I'm at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Specialists might argue the point of what constitutes
alcoholism. Regardless, Daly says he's feeling better than he has
in years, and his golf game is coming around as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching a replay of the '95 Open, when I putted
beautifully, and I noticed my left foot was a lot further back than
it is now,'' Daly says. ``I have been trying that again for the
last three days and have been holing everything. So I feel pretty
good about my chances.''
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be Daly's motto. He's not unlike a jump shooter in
basketball. The next shot is always going in, even if he's missed
every one up to that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still standing,'' he says. ``My heart is still pumping.
All I want to do now is play golf and leave the rest to others.''
</P>
<P>
   And maybe make his stop at Scotland's Last Chance Saloon a
fruitful one.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-18-00 2355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
